<HEADLINE>
ANTI-ENVIRONMENTAL AMENDMENTS ADDED TO DEFENSE MEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Military spending bills before Congress this week are being
loaded with unrelated environmental amendments that could block
formation of a new national park in Arizona and prevent enforcement
of the federal Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups said senators were using the must-pass
bills to carry language that otherwise would not pass. And House
GOP moderates circulated a letter saying the provisions ``would be
a serious procedural, political and policy mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the riders, proposed by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., would
give the Air Force permanent control of the Barry M. Goldwater
Gunnery Range in southwestern Arizona. Environmentalists recently
proposed that the 2.7 million-acre range be included in a proposed
Sonoran Desert National Park when the military no longer needs it.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ives, a McCain spokeswoman, said she couldn't comment
about the rider because of secrecy rules imposed by the Senate
Armed Services Committee about next year's defense authorization
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ives said she was unable to answer why McCain submitted the
amendment, or why it was not brought up in the Senate Energy and
Natural Resources Committee, which has handled similar legislation
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Another rider, proposed by Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., was
beaten back temporarily by environmentalists. It would have placed
a moratorium on creation of ``critical habitat'' for plants and
animals on the federal Endangered Species List.
</P>
<P>
   Critical habitat rules not only protect endangered species and
where they live, they protect lands where endangered species have
been driven out but could again repopulate. In Arizona, this could
affect protections for endangered owls in both the forests and
deserts.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Domenici withdrew his rider from an $11.6 billion
emergency spending bill providing military aid to Kosovo and
humanitarian aid to Central America. However, he said the proposal
would be resurrected as a separate bill in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said his plan would prevent creation of critical
habitat until recovery plans are completed for endangered species.
Environmentalists contend that federal officials have delayed
recovery plans because Congress fails to provide the money to
complete them, meaning there will be more delays in establishing
critical habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other riders are being piled onto the Kosovo/disaster
aid bill:
</P>
<P>
   An effort by Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., to block the listing
the Alabama sturgeon as an endangered species. He says such a
listing would restrict dredging in the state's waterways,
threatening the timber industry and other industries that ship
their products on barges.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., was trying to overturn a court
ruling that mining companies can't expand their milling operations
on public lands. Environmentalists complain those operations
pollute water. The ruling affects the Crown Jewel gold mine in
Gorton's state and other Western hard-rock mines.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, wants to prevent the National
Park Service from phasing out commercial fishing in the waters off
Glacier Bay National Park until courts decide the issue.
Environmentalists say that could take years.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's amendment helped prompt memos and letters to Sen. John
Warner, chairman of the Armed Services Committee:
</P>
<P>
   John Leshy, solicitor to Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, a
former Arizona governor, said new agreements between Interior and
the Air Force already are in progress that would govern management,
cleanup and the length of renewal of military uses of the range.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of eight national and Arizona-based environmental groups
signed a joint letter to Warner opposing McCain's move.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we recognize that the vast majority of these lands will
likely continue to serve as important training grounds for our
armed forces,'' the environmentalists' letter said, ``we believe
that the Department of Defense, working with the Interior
Department, can fulfill its training mission, while better
providing for the protection of the natural and cultural
resource(s).''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists questioned why McCain is trying to permanently
amend the status of the Goldwater range. &QL; 
This story included material from the Associated Press. Steve
Yozwiak can be reached at (602) 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
