<HEADLINE>
PATAKI DEFENDS TOUGHER GRADUATION TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki on Wednesday strongly defended
the stiffer graduation requirements that state education officials
are seeking to impose on nearly all public high school students,
and suggested that lawmakers should not try to water them down.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's comments could lead to a fight with members of the
Legislature, where there is growing bipartisan opposition to the
new standards. Lawmakers contend that the new requirements are
being phased in too quickly and do not provide an accurate measure
of students' overall academic abilities. The legislators also fear
that the failure and dropout rates in their own districts could be
high.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, in response to questions from reporters,
Pataki defended the new requirements. ``I think one of the most
important things we have to do is have high standards,'' the
governor said, ``and I think it's about time that we're finally
looking to elevate and raise standards in education.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he was concerned about the sentiment among lawmakers
to soften the new standards. ``Let me make it clear,'' he told
reporters at an impromptu news conference outside the State
Capitol. ``We should not back down one iota from our efforts to
raise students' performance standards in education.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's response drew immediate fire from lawmakers, many of
whom are under mounting pressure from parents, teachers and school
administrators in their districts to scale back the new
requirements, lest seniors fail in large numbers. Some lawmakers
say they fear that as many as 20 percent of seniors may be unable
to pass the new standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor is wrong, but it's a debate worth
having,'' said Richard L. Brodsky, a Democratic Assemblyman from
Westchester County who has proposed allowing school districts to
use alternative standards in place of the new exams being required
for graduation. ``Standardized testing should not be the sole
measure of whether a kid has met the academic standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Regents, the body charged with setting educational
policy for the state, and the state education commissioner have
announced that beginning next year, students will have to pass a
more rigorous English Regents exam to earn a high school diploma.
In later years, students will have to pass similar standardized
tests in four other subjects: math; American history and
government, global studies and science.
</P>
<P>
   The state first offered the Regents exam in 1879 as a standard
for colleges to use in evaluating high school graduates. But until
now, students needed only to pass a less rigorous competency test
to graduate, and only a minority have passed the more difficult
Regents exams; in New York City, fewer than 25 percent pass the
Regents.
</P>
<P>
   But the Board of Regents, under the leadership of the state's
education commissioner, Richard P. Mills, has argued that under the
old two-tiered testing system, some students have excelled
academically while others have graduated unprepared for college or
the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Mills and the Regents are not simply requiring students to pass
the Regents exams to graduate. They also say that they are making
the exams considerably harder.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers opposed to the new tests say that they generally
support the Regents' effort to raise academic performance. Their
main concern, they say, is that the tests do not fully measure the
academic ability of students, and that many school districts,
particularly poor ones, lack the resources to prepare low-achieving
students to take the new tests.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Democratic speaker of the State Assembly, Sheldon
Silver, who is the Republican governor's main rival in the
Legislature, used the debate over the graduation requirements to
make the case on Wednesday for one of his main legislative
priorities: providing more money to school districts to help them
prepare students better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we talking only about tests?'' asked Silver, a
Democrat from Manhattan, adding: ``Let's start debating the issues
of what standards we need them to meet and what resources we have
to provide to them. That's what's lost in the debate. Where are the
resources?''
</P>
<P>
   Silver, who has attacked the governor in the past for proposing
deep cuts for some education programs, also said: ``I don't have a
problem with having tests. What I am saying is that the debate
should not be whether the standards are too high or too low.''
</P>
</TEXT>
