<HEADLINE>
LPGA EVENT SEEMS HEADED FOR LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Legacy Golf Resort, a layout in south Phoenix that
won't open until mid-October, apparently is the new front-runner to
host the LPGA's Standard Register PING next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although tournament organizers said an agreement has not been
struck, ``The Arizona Republic'' confirmed through the Legacy's
architect and developer that only a few minor details are holding
up completion of the deal. The course would house the event in 2000
while its permanent site, Moon Valley Country Club, is recovering
from a renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The developer has made it real attractive for them, but I
guess they have to wait for some kind of approval from the LPGA,''
said architect Gary Panks, who has met with the Standard Register
PING tournament committee on three occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether that meant the tournament would get the course for
free, Panks said, ``That's the way I understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kerry Graham, who is chairing the site selection committee
for the Standard Register PING, said that the Legacy is one of
``three options, maybe more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Legacy) is definitely a consideration, but we absolutely
have not made a final decision,'' Graham said. ``We expect a member
of the LPGA field staff to be here next week, and we can review
that course along with several others.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legacy, which is located next to the Raven at South Mountain
just off Baseline Road, is a joint venture involving Arizona-based
Sunbelt Holdings and Carefree Partners, as well as Shell Vacations
of Chicago. Sunbelt Holdings President John Graham is the stepson
of Kerry Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that's a guarantee we'll get it,'' John Graham
said of the relationship. ``But at the same time, it might prove
helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Of more importance, the Legacy comes the closest to matching the
Standard Register PING's three criteria:
</P>
<P>
   A quality course with adequate facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Location that is geographically acceptable to volunteers and
fans.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament's charity, the Samaritan Foundation, will not be
jeopardized. The tournament raises between $350,000 and $800,000
annually for breast cancer research and education.
</P>
<P>
   The Legacy is a big surprise, as is another of the possible
sites, the Anthem Country Club course by Del Webb just north of
Phoenix. Both courses are still in the construction stage and came
into the search late.
</P>
<P>
   The other possible choice is the Karsten Course at Arizona
State, which was among the original three choices, including
Phoenix Country Club and the TPC of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   But Phoenix Country Club has turned down the LPGA event twice,
and the TPC never was in the running.
</P>
<P>
   John Graham said he hopes that the clincher will be that the
Legacy is offering a quality course with more than adequate
facilities for the right price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We very much want it, and at this point, that's very
meaningful to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Panks said the Legacy should be in ``perfect shape by the time
the tournament rolls around'' in March. Plus, he pointed out, there
will be on-site housing in the way of time-share condominiums, a
good-size clubhouse and an ``excellent practice facility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is well-suited for the ladies at a little over
6,000 yards, and visually the fairways are depressed, so it's good
for the fans' viewing, too,'' Panks said. ` &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
