u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     05-13 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)  
 SPORTS COLUMN: SPEECHES DON'T SCORE POINTSsco` (xx) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The boulder came rolling down on Tim Hardaway and the
Miami Heat on Wednesday night, from the top of the mountain on
which Pat Riley preaches. All the coaching axioms about force,
work, desire and playing with pain merged into this huge rock that
landed on Riley's team the way so many of their shots crashed into
the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two to 2. That's what the Knicks had to say about a Miami
playoff dream hinging on guts and will and one significantly shaky
knee. That was their riot of a run, from late in the second
quarter, into the third. Wednesday night's 97-73 Knicks victory at
Madison Square Garden made the score in this first-round series two
blowouts for the Knicks, one wrestling match for the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   These things can change, but Riley better have a couple of jump
shooters in his pocket along with Friday night's motivational
speech. Or he had better have a miracle cure for Hardaway's wounded
right knee.
</P>
<P>
   The hard way. That's how the Heat is trying to compete with a
team that is no longer a mirror image of itself, a team with
weapons. That's how the Heat is learning that their ticket to the
playoffs as the top-seeded team in the Eastern Conference is worth
as much as a typical Miami possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at the seedings _ I don't know about one versus
eight,'' Riley said. ``This isn't the typical-type season, as
you've had in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   He picked a fine time to realize this. People said the Knicks
were not a typical eighth-seeded team, but the real story here is
that the Heat isn't what you'd call your standard No. 1. Yet for
one extra home game, Riley drove his players, particularly
Hardaway, through 50 games in 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't he see his point guard, his one authentic perimeter
threat, dragging his knee through the second half of the season?
After so many playoff wars, didn't he know that the Knicks or any
other playoff team would match Miami's nightly effort come the
playoffs? Hardaway, a shell of his once explosive self, played in
every Heat game, except the last one in New York. He should've
taken a long rest, or at least a few games off, like Patrick Ewing.
Now Riley and the Heat are paying a price as stiff as Hardaway's
knee.
</P>
<P>
   The pint-sized shooting point guard took 8 shots on Wednesday
night, made 1. He is now 6 for 32 in the series. He walks away from
any questions about the right knee, but there is no first step, no
crossover dribble, none of the stop-on-a-dime elevation that has
tormented the Knicks so many times before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Timmy can play his game,'' said Alonzo Mourning, a
statement predicated on blind loyalty or wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway took 19 shots in Game 1, made 4. Riley sat him down and
suggested there had to be a better way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got on Tim about getting better shots after the first game,
about not always settling for the long jumper,'' said Bob McAdoo,
Riley's assistant, who hoisted a few jumpers in his own playing
days. ``We told him he had to trust the other guys, break the
defense down, create open looks for them.'' Hardaway collected 11
assists, the Heat won by 10.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck winning the series with the collection of castoffs,
much less the title. Good luck with the likes of the game but
broken down Dan Majerle, whose jersey was soaked with perspiration
from chasing Allan Houston five minutes into the game. Good luck
with Jamal Mashburn, who makes Marcus Camby look like Charles
Oakley. Good luck with Keith Askins and Clarence Weatherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   McAdoo said Hardaway didn't trust his Miami teammates when he
joined this team in 1996. As a Golden State Warrior, he once looked
around and saw the young Chris Mullin and Mitch Richmond and even
Latrell Sprewell. On Wednesday night, he passed the ball to
Mashburn, who launched tentative jumpers that grazed the rim. He
gave the ball to P.J. Brown, who dropped it under the basket. He
set Mourning up for a drive and the raging center charged face
first into the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The butchered possessions mounted and the Knicks ran away and
there was nothing Hardaway could do, so he got into it with Chris
Childs in the fourth quarter and suggested they meet outside the
Garden. That was frustration talking. Hardaway was ejected for that
and later in the locker room said, ``Man, I'm not talking.''
</P>
<P>
   He was always Miami's best hope against the Knicks and now all
he can do is pass the ball to Riley's castoffs and hope it somehow
goes in. Riley should have seen this coming, should have given this
man some rest. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
