<HEADLINE>
ASU CROSSING FINGERS  
 SUN DEVILS HOPING FOR BASEBALL REGIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Arizona State's desire to host an NCAA baseball
regional may not only hinge on its weekend series with Arizona, but
on a Pac-10 meeting 350 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California, which hosts Washington Friday through
Sunday, is one of three conference teams that submitted bids for
regional sites. With the NCAA expected to award just two of its 16
sites to Pac-10 teams, and Stanford a lock for one, USC and ASU
appear to be in a battle for the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decisions we make are always the target of criticism,''
said Le Moyne College Athletic Director Dick Rockwell, chairman of
the NCAA Tournament selection committee. ``It's always easy to
throw stones when you're on the outside. To put all this in
perspective, the ultimate goal would be to balance the regionals
geographically, have full houses at every game and to provide the
student-athletes with positive experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell wouldn't specifically address the Sun Devils' chances
but stressed the committee has not made up its mind.
</P>
<P>
   He will join the eight other committee members on a conference
call Monday morning to determine the first-round sites. Stanford,
which has won 10 straight and sits first in the Pac-10, is expected
to be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (31-22, 15-6 Pac-10), who took two of three from the
Sun Devils (38-19, 11-10) this season and are guaranteed to finish
higher in the conference, appear to have the edge. But if ASU
finishes strong this weekend and the Trojans struggle, the Sun
Devils might get a nod based on their overall record and their
ability to attract more fans.
</P>
<P>
   Teams that submitted bids were required to guaranteed $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be looking at a lot of factors,'' Rockwell
said. ``With the field expanded from 48 to 64 teams, there will be
new challenges. Are we going to make mistakes? Absolutely. Are we
going to make mistakes on purpose? Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU's chances to host would improve significantly if the
committee decided to give the conference three sites. Rockwell said
no decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   None of this matters if the Sun Devils struggle against the
Wildcats (31-20), who are in a three-way tie with ASU and
Washington for fourth place and also are hoping for a postseason
bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it will take (to earn a spot),'' Arizona
Coach Jerry Stitt said. ``Our guys just know how important this
series is and we hope they play the best they've played all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats have struggled recently, losing four of their past
six. The Sun Devils have rebounded from five straight losses with
victories in six of their past eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Pat Murphy came away with a good feeling about his
team after it took two of three from Washington in Seattle last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they showed tremendous resiliency in adverse
conditions,'' he said. ``They showed a lot of guts. To defeat the
defending Pac-10 champs two of three on the road helped us gain
some confidence.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
