<SLUG> BC-BBM-DBACKS-FARM-REPORT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON WORKING OFF THE RUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Brian Anderson, determined to be an asset for the
Diamondbacks, basically is making his two weeks with Triple-A
Tucson his spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can come down here and be mad and bitter, and two weeks go
by and I've not accomplished a thing,'' he said. ``Or I go down and
work hard, do what is asked of you, and be prepared when you come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander is taking the latter approach.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who was sent to the farm team Saturday after compiling
an 0-1 record and 9.58 ERA in eight appearances out of the bullpen,
is starting for Tucson and building stamina. He threw 40 pitches in
his first start Monday, gave up four hits and one earned run, and
struck out three and walked none in 2 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little rust,'' he said. ``I just need to get back
out there and pitch regularly. That's how I have to pitch to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson threw a personal-best 208 innings as a starter last
year, when he won 12 games and had a 4.33 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of free agents  &UR; Randy Johnson, Todd
Stottlemyre and  &UR; Armando Reynoso, Anderson moved into the bullpen,
where his workload was greatly reduced, even in spring training. He
pitched 10 innings in one month with the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throwing once a week, I was pretty useless,'' he said. ``I was
just taking an inning here and there in meaningless games. I was
not doing anybody any good in that role.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson isn't sure what role he'll assume when he returns.
</P>
<P>
   He has been assured by Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter that he'll have
two more starts, the next one Saturday in Omaha, then he'll rejoin
the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he'll throw about 65 pitches Saturday and up to 85
in his third start with Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said there is a good chance that I'll come back as a
reliever, doing the same thing,'' Anderson said. ``I'll at least
have some outings. I'll be sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I have to do to get well. I just wasn't getting it
done. I understand. I agree with them.'' &QL; 
Day by day &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sidewinders outfielder  &UR; Jason Conti, who earned Organizational
Player of the Year honors last year as a loan player to Double-A
Tulsa, took his 20-game hitting streak in stride. It was broken
Tuesday in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even think about it until I got to 15,'' Conti said.
``A couple of reporters asked me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Conti was selected Howe Sportsdata Player of the Week for May
3-9 for hitting .556 (10 for 18) with eight RBIs. The 24-year-old
is putting no timetable on reaching the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just work on what I have to do down here,'' he said.
``Whatever happens, happens. If somebody goes down, I'll be ready.
But I don't wish anybody to get hurt.'' &QL; 
Short hops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tucson pitcher  &UR; Nelson Figueroa was named the Organizational
Pitcher of the Month. He made four starts in April, winning three,
giving up 11 earned runs and striking out 20 in 23 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman  &UR; Jarrod Patterson of Double-A El Paso is the
Organizational Player of the Month for April, after hitting .380
with 10 double, 16 RBIs and a .648 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Jeff Andrews (0-3, 6.37 ERA in six starts) moved
from Class A High Desert to El Paso, replacing pitcher
 &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim, who is expected to make his first appearance with
Tucson on Friday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
