<HEADLINE>
OUT ON THE LEDGE  
 RUBBER MEETS ROCK ON 4X4 EXCURSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some casual four-wheel-drive trips turn nasty. They'll lull you
into contentment, then suddenly produce fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Road 677 is one of those roads. It's tame as can be a
good part of the drive, then grows horns and sharp teeth.
</P>
<P>
   I first heard about it from Tom Woods, a former Arizona Game and
Fish commissioner who four-wheels extensively with his wife, Sally,
in their built-up Ford Bronco.
</P>
<P>
   Woods told of a beautiful drive through rolling hills and upper
desert grasslands. He also told of a stretch going into Sycamore
Creek that was difficult for the average off-highway driver.
</P>
<P>
   The road can be reached at two places north of Phoenix off
Interstate 17. The first place is Bloody Basin Road, where you go
east about eight miles to the first major turnoff to the left,
which is marked as 677. The road comes out at Dugas Road to the
north. Sycamore Creek is just a few miles from Dugas Road.
</P>
<P>
   Both roads are clearly marked at I-17 exits.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said to start the trip off Bloody Basin Road and go north.
Going south off Dugas Road, he said, would be a real problem. That
statement was absolutely correct.
</P>
<P>
   I talked about 677 with Ed Fouts of Phoenix, who turned 83 on
Mother's Day. Fouts probably has covered more backcountry in
Arizona than any other man. He lives to do it.
</P>
<P>
   He remembered hunting deer off that road. His first trip over it
was almost 40 years ago. We agreed to go from the Bloody Basin
side, accepting that Woods was correct.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts took his Jeep, which has lockers on both axles and great
ground clearance. My stock S-10 Chevy Blazer was in for tough but
not destructive times.
</P>
<P>
   This was a beautiful drive through the grasslands with a great
view of the imposing Bradshaw Mountains to the west. Quail were
plentiful. The road was descent for high-clearance vehicles. Rock
outcroppings demanded some maneuvering along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The slopes leading into washes had eroded badly, leaving big
rock outcroppings that were rougher than heck. Some were a lot
worse than others. There was an occasional rub on the rear of the
Blazer when it passed through a bad spot, but nothing bad.
</P>
<P>
   We lost our way for a few minutes, and I managed to use the skid
plates twice on the same stupid rock while exploring. Bad judgment
on my part.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the 20-mile trip to Sycamore Creek, the road
became worse and worse. Fouts was fine. The Blazer struggled a
little. But no bad incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the descent to Sycamore Creek. This stretch REALLY was
eroded. It consisted of bedrock ledges and loose rock. Fouts'
companion, Bill Atherton of Phoenix, had to guide Fouts through
some spots. He spent a lot more time guiding the Blazer.
</P>
<P>
   Friend Steve Moorhouse, who was driving, gulped a few times but
got the Blazer over the ledges without a scrape on the bedrock. It
did get some desert pinstriping from an oak on one tight turn among
the ledges.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts didn't believe the Blazer would make it. It did, but is
making some strange noises now.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up that slope from the other side, especially with the
loose rock, would be even more challenging. My Blazer probably
would refuse to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was enhanced by Sycamore Creek with its huge sycamores
and running water. Great for wading and picnicking.
</P>
<P>
   This is a challenging trip for the average driver if he can beat
the ledges. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
