<HEADLINE>
E.P. ABRAHMA, 85, BIOCHEMIST WHO HELPED DEVELOP ANTIBIOTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sir Edward Penley Abraham, a British biochemist and Oxford
University professor who contributed greatly to the development of
today's medical arsenal of antibiotics, died on Sunday at his home
in Oxford. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   He left his mark on biology, chemistry and medicine. Worldwide
patents brought him wealth, some of which he used for trust funds
to support research and education, particularly at Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham came to international prominence while associated with
the William Dunn School of Pathology at Oxford in the late 1930s
and 40s. With Ernest Chain and Howard Florey, he investigated the
therapeutic potential of penicillin and played an important role in
purifying it and decoding its chemical structure.
</P>
<P>
   Although his interest in such matters was mostly academic, the
fruits of his work had important practical applications. The
penicillin research spawned a new generation of synthetic
penicillins.
</P>
<P>
   With his colleagues, he also discovered penicillinase, a
penicillin-destroying enzyme that disclosed much about resistance
to penicillin.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Abraham turned his attention to cephalosporins, a
category of broad-spectrum antibiotics derived from a fungus that
offered an alternative for people allergic to penicillin.
</P>
<P>
   Such medicines are in wide use today, treating respiratory
infections like bronchitis and pneumonia, infections of the urinary
tract and certain toxic blood disorders. They also heal wounds
infected after surgery and shield the patient on the operating
table from such infections in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham wrote ``Biochemistry of Some Peptide and Steroid
Antibiotics'' (1957) and ``Biosynthesis and Enzymic Hydrolysis of
Penicillins and Cephalosporins'' (1974), and contributed to the
textbook ``General Pathology'' and to scientific journals.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Southampton and educated at Queen's College,
Oxford, where he earned a Ph.D. in 1941. He also studied a year at
the University of Stockholm as a Rockefeller Foundation Traveling
Fellow in the late 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham held a chair in chemical pathology at Oxford
University's Lincoln College from 1964 to 1980, when he became a
professor emeritus. He had been a fellow at the college since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   He received many awards, including honors from Britain's Royal
Society and the Swedish Academy of Pharmaceutical Sciences. He was
knighted in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham's survivors include his wife of 60 years, Asbjorg Harung
Abraham, and their son, Michael.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
