<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5183 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AQUILA-KAN-KAN &LR;      05-13 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AQUILA-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILICORP SUBSIDIARY WANTS TO BUILD POWER PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ UtiliCorp United Inc. said Wednesday that a
subsidiary, Aquila Merchants Energy Partners, was seeking
regulatory approval to build a $250 million plant near Pleasant
Hill that could begin generating electricity by mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the gas-fired plant's 600-megawatt output
would be consumed by the estimated 180,000 western Missouri
customers of Missouri Public Service, another UtiliCorp subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Max Sherman, Aquila MEP project manager, said the rest of the
output, about 40 percent, would be marketed by Aquila Energy Corp.,
one of the country's largest energy-trading firms. Aquila Energy is
the parent of Aquila MEP and a wholly owned subsidiary of
UtiliCorp.
</P>
<P>
   Aquila MEP recently won a four-year contract to supply power to
MoPub.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said the corporate sisters' relationship spread economic
risk among the companies and offered a long-term benefit to utility
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Industry) deregulation is coming,'' he said. ``The problem
most utilities have in this country, and MoPub is no different, is
how can you invest in facilities when you don't know what's going
to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation will allow consumers to choose from competing
electric service providers, much like telephone service today.
</P>
<P>
   The plant will create about two dozen permanent jobs at the Cass
County site on 175th Street west of Pleasant Hill and just south of
a MoPub electric substation. The new plant is to be designed and
built by Kansas City-based Black &AMP; Veatch.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the Missouri Public Service Commission, the
facility will be one of only two independent power plants in the
state. The other one is being built in St. Francois County in
southeast Missouri, Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Aquila MEP owns interests in 17 other independent power plants
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Aquila Energy, now based in Omaha, Neb., later this year will
move its headquarters and more than 500 jobs to downtown Kansas
City at the Town Pavilion, 1111 Main St.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Land Clearance for Redevelopment Authority, the
Missouri Development Finance Board and the Kansas City Council
agreed to more than $16 million in tax breaks and other incentives
to lure Aquila from Nebraska.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-WARS-TICKETS-LAD     05-13 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-TICKETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS SCOOP UP `PHANTOM MENACE' TICKETS IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(With contributions from Daily News Staff Writers Lee Condon, Reed
Johnson, Marla Matzer and Dave McNary) 
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- ``Star Wars'' fans stood in long, long lines and
came from far, far away to get the first tickets a week before
George Lucas' much-anticipated prequel opens in theaters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Mann's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood, fans had camped in
line since early April and tested each other's knowledge of ``Star
Wars'' trivia.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Burbank, police braced for crowds downtown where two
theater complexes opened ticket sales at noon Wednesday for ``Star
Wars: Episode 1 -- The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the box office opened for pre-sales at the Pacific
Theatres' Winnetka 20 in Chatsworth, which boasts 70-foot-wide
screens, 350 people, some from as far away as Palmdale and Long
Beach, were ready to buy.
</P>
<P>
   All this for a movie?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's American mythology. It's part of American culture. This
is American history here,'' said Ryan Andolina, an 18-year-old
Marina del Rey resident who was first in line at the AMC 16 theater
in Burbank. ``I'm really not some geek, though.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Chinese Theatre, Lincoln Gasking, a 22-year-old from
Melbourne, Australia, and Tim Doyle, 27, from Toronto, Canada, were
the first to purchase tickets for the first screening at the
Chinese, ending a wait that began more than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are pure gold,'' Doyle said, showing off his handfuls of
tickets to the assembled TV cameras and gawking passers-by. ``Every
minute was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, lines snaked around theaters, callers jammed
ticket-sales phone lines and computer-users tied up online ticket
outlets. An accurate count of advance ticket sales won't be known
until next week, said Paul Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor
Relations Co., which tracks domestic box office receipts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have numbers until May 20 because theaters don't
report ticket sales until people actually use the ticket,'' he
said, ``but things are looking very good. There are lines around
the block all over country.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand didn't outstrip supply, however, at mutliplexes like the
Winnetka 20, where seats for the movie's opening day remained
available even after the hundreds of fans waiting in line when
ticket windows opened had been served.
</P>
<P>
   That's true at several area theaters despite the devotion of
fans, many of them twentysomethings like William Reyes and Gino
Sanchez, who were infants when the first ``Star Wars'' movie came
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sacrificed ourselves,'' said Reyes, 21, of North Hills, who
camped out to get a good place in line.
</P>
<P>
   With a limit of 12 per customer, most bought several tickets for
family members and friends -- or for themselves so they could see
the movie several times.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, 20, a Granada Hills resident, was the first to walk
away from the ticket window. He had 10 blue tickets, one of which
he plans to save as a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   A preordained blockbuster like ``The Phantom Menace'' lends
itself to galactic statistics. Winnetka, a special draw because of
its 70-foot-wide screens, put the first eight days of screenings on
sale Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' will be shown on three screens that can
collectively accommodate 1,822 people. The movie will be shown five
times per day in each. That comes out to nearly 73,000 tickets
available for the first eight days at Winnetka alone. The movie
will be shown on between 3,500 and 4,000 screens nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Winnetka assistant manager Mike Canzoneri guesses that only
opening day will be sold out by the time the first reel is ready to
roll.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. For most, it was worth waiting just to be able to say
they saw ``The Phantom Menace'' on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more to brag about,'' said Ivan Lawrence, 18, of
Chatsworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do what you gotta do,'' he said outside the Winnetka 20.
``It's `Star Wars.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The most carefully choreographed mob scene might have been
outside the Chinese, where several dozen ``Star Wars'' fans raising
money for charity have been camped out since early April.
</P>
<P>
   At Mann's Village in Westwood, Daniel Alter, 17, of Tarzana was
first in line five weeks ago. Since then, he'd been waiting in line
most of the time, with his mother bringing him food and other
friends relieving him for eight hours or so at a time.
</P>
<P>
   After he bought the 12 tickets he was allowed, Alter was
prepared for more waiting to get a good seat next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get right back in line for the ticket holders'
line.''
</P>
<P>
   At less-renowned local theaters, there were fewer fans waiting
in line but their `Star Wars' worship ran just as deep.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated mom Stella Palayan, a 51-year-old Glendale resident,
was first in a line of about 70 people at the Glendale Mann
Theaters to get tickets for the opening. She took over the spot at
8:30 a.m. from her 26-year-old son, Kirk, who had been camped out
since 6 p.m. Tuesday. ``He said `Mom, I owe you,' '' Palayan said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police reported no problems among the impatient
ticket-seekers, though some area police agencies set up barricades
to corral the hundreds of people who wanted to be part of history.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
