<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD INFERTILITY BE COVERED AS A DISABILITY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I chortled when I read the news item. The Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission ruled that an employer violated federal
disabilities laws by refusing to pay for infertility treatments
through its insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
   /{Oh brother,/} I thought. /{What will our litigious society
think of next?/}
</P>
<P>
   My knee jerk continued: /{Puhleeze. Inability to bear a child
doesn't affect one's ability to perform the essential functions of
a job _ which is what the Americans With Disabilities Act is
designed to protect./}
</P>
<P>
   Federal law says employers must provide reasonable
accommodations to help disabled workers do their jobs. /{But that's
for things like blindness and deafness, not infertility,/} I
reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Then I listened to a woman who desperately wants to have a baby
and _ so far _ has not become pregnant. She and her husband are
spending up to $20,000, considerable time and much emotional
anguish trying to conceive. There is no question in her mind that
she is a disabled worker who is ``not firing on all cylinders.''
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC decision drew on an earlier U.S. Supreme Court ruling
that called reproduction a ``major life activity.'' Bingo, the
woman said. Disability laws were written precisely to help those
who have impairments of major life activities.
</P>
<P>
   She views her inability to conceive as an impairment, just like
an inability to see or hear like ``normal'' people. ``Normal''
people, she said, bear children.
</P>
<P>
   She is not a sniveling basket case. Her co-workers see her as an
intelligent, productive worker. Meanwhile, she sought emotional
counseling through her employer's confidential counseling program.
</P>
<P>
   She came up empty. The program offered counseling for
alcoholism, drug abuse, depression and a host of other problems _
but no expert help for the pain of infertility. She found and pays
for counseling on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Look, she argued, if the ``best places to work'' provide
adoption benefits and maternity benefits, isn't it fair to help pay
for fertility treatments, which are just another way of having a
child? Isn't it discrimination for insurance companies or employers
to exclude coverage for infertility treatments?
</P>
<P>
   Those questions aren't answered easily. If, say, a woman elects
to remain childless during her most fertile 20s and 30s, is it fair
to expect her employers' health-care budget to subsidize $10,000 or
$20,000 _ or more _ worth of fertility treatments in her 40s? But
what if we're talking about an infertile couple in their 20s?
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a recent study by the consulting firm William
M. Mercer found that making infertility treatments a covered
benefit was not an unreasonable cost burden on employers. In fact,
such coverage may be cost-effective in terms of retaining
productive employees.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen states have some type of infertility insurance coverage
law, but there is no current federal mandate. More than 6 million
infertile Americans are hoping that changes.
</P>
<P>
   As many employers try to create ``family-friendly'' workplaces
in an effort to attract and keep workers, infertility sufferers say
it's discriminatory when the system is family-friendly only if the
family is easily made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0017 </DOCNO>
