u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-CHINA-SPI &LR;      05-13 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-CHINA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON TEACHER IN CHINA FINDS PROTECTIVE STUDENTS AMID
TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROSEMARY ADANG, SPECIAL TO THE P-I  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: Rosemary Adang, a faculty member at Highline
Community College in Des Moines, Wash., for nine years, is teaching
English this academic year at Shanghai Jiao Tong University in
China. As part of a faculty exchange program, she also is studying
Chinese culture. In the wake of NATO's accidental bombing of
China's Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, last Friday, Adang
described the tensions in Shanghai in e-mail messages to the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer. The time references are in Shanghai
time, which is 15 hours ahead of Seattle time. Here are excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ I taught two classes of first-year students
Wednesday. They, like students from all the major universities,
have been involved in the demonstrations (against NATO), and do
generally believe the bombing (of China's Embassy in Belgrade last
week) was intentional. It's a sad statement about our relations
with the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the English Department went into each class before
me to pave the way, but I don't know exactly what she said to them.
She had told me her intention was just to remind them to respect me
as an international guest.
</P>
<P>
   But the students did not direct any of their anger at me; in
fact, they were as protective as the faculty. One student even gave
me a hand-folded origami crane and told me it was a symbol of peace
and friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Another student asked me during a break if I had been scared.
When I said that I had (been fearful) to some extent, he said not
to worry because people know that individual Americans are not at
fault. But then he said, ``But there are radicals out there, so be
careful and stay at home as much as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   My third-year classes on Friday may be a bit rougher as they are
much more politically active, but I think they'll also hold the
distinction between the American government, which most of them see
as evil, and individual Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a sad week here in Shanghai. In an unrelated incident,
one of my graduate students committed suicide last weekend, and
that's been a big focus of my attention and feelings as well as the
bombing. (On Wednesday) after teaching for four hours, I attended
the funeral. There is no evidence that it was related to these
other events....
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night I attended the (meeting of the university's vice
president), where for over an hour he spoke about the bombing in
the most inflammatory terms possible, referring to the brutal,
vicious action; telling us we did not know the truth because we get
our information from the Western press; saying that the explanation
given by the United States and NATO was clearly false; and
referring to the eventual triumph of good over evil.
</P>
<P>
   He did say that the university guaranteed our safety on campus
and in our apartments and that we should be cautious elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   I think we're safe right now here in Shanghai, though the recent
events are very disturbing....
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the embassy happened just as I was going into an
unusual stretch of five days without classes to teach.... Being
away from my normal environment and my students (made) gauging the
tension somewhat more difficult, but at least here we have access
to CNN and some Chinese news in English....
</P>
<P>
   Our Chinese friends tell us that the American apology has not
been carried in the Chinese press, though apparently Tuesday
morning the Chinese government finally issued a public statement of
the apology.
</P>
<P>
   We're just a few blocks from the American Consulate, where there
have been protests since the bombing, and there are many more
police on the streets than usual, but the people in the hotel and
in a nearby restaurant have been very kind to us.
</P>
<P>
   One Chinese person told us that reasonable people here know that
(President) Clinton and NATO have not gone mad. Another said that
because of the upcoming 10th anniversary of the Tiananmen Square
protests, the government is eager to turn any unrest outward.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, as far as we know all the local universities
have bused students to the protests, and many of my own students
are suspicious enough of American foreign policy to be sincerely
angry and skeptical of the explanation of the bombing as an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, we've witnessed the presence of many police, a
convoy of about eight military trucks and one group of soldiers
that we saw running together toward the consulate. Police were
turning cars away from the intersection next to our hotel, which is
a route to the consulate.
</P>
<P>
   People on the streets, though, have not been noticeably hostile
to us. We've received some looks that I would call even more
searching than usual, but we've also received friendly looks and
nods that to me seem to be attempts to reassure us of their good
will.
</P>
<P>
   As I'm sure you know, Chinese people receive very little news of
the plight of the Kosovo people, hearing instead phrases like ``the
forced expulsion of the Albanians'' as the most negative reflection
of the situation. Many believe the stories on CNN are Western
propaganda and greatly exaggerated or possibly even fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   We're not very afraid for our personal safety, but it's
disturbing knowing that many Chinese people do hold America
responsible and believe that this could have been a purposeful
action....
</P>
<P>
   Again, we think we and Americans who happen to be in Shanghai
right now are probably safe as long as they stay away from the
protests and don't provoke reactions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOPT-CHINA-AZR &LR;      05-13 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPT-CHINA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESA COUPLE RETURN WITH ADOPTED CHINESE BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CLANCY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Mesa couple whose adoption of a Chinese baby came amid
ferocious anti-American protests returned to United States soil
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're home,'' said a relieved Tammy Jacobs, shortly after the
plane touched down at Los Angeles International Airport. ``We're
just happy to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs and and her husband, Loren, carried with them the
precious cargo they flew to China to get: 14-month-old Abigal Bei,
who rested in a cloth carrier slung over Loren Jacobs' shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   They were expected to arrive about 10 p.m. at Sky Harbor
International Airport in Phoenix amid the welcome greetings of
hundreds of well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   They were among 10 to 15 couples holed up in the White Swan
Hotel in Guangzhou, adjacent to the U.S. embassy, for several days
while angry mobs protested NATO's accidental bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Yugoslavia, which killed three journalists and injured
20 others.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations in Guangzhou began hours after the couple
arrived in the southern Chinese city, and ended shortly after
President Clinton's apology was aired on TV days after he issued
it. Officials warned the hotel guests to stay inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were afraid the protests would escalate,'' Loren Jacobs
said. ``They told us to stay away from windows and doors. We didn't
even know whether to make eye contact with hotel employes.''
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest fear was that there would be delays in getting
their visas processed. But immigration officials processed the
documents at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And by the fourth day, the couple ventured out to a market.
</P>
<P>
   Abigail is the couple's second Chinese baby. Their first is
4-year-old Kimmery, who stayed in Mesa with her grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Jacobses, John Carney and his wife also adopted a
second daughter in China. The St. Louis radio personality said he
was frightened the first day of the protests because he had never
seen such an angry crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But by the second day, he said, they realized they would not be
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy bombing prompted China to break contacts with the
United States on military relations, human rights, arms control and
other security issues. The country also allowed controlled
demonstrations, reportedly the largest and most widespread since
the Tiananmen Square uprising 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Adams of China's Children adoption agency in
Scottsdale, who worked with the Jacobses, said hotel workers
reported that the Chinese government hopes the protests will blunt
demonstrations on the Tiananmen Square uprising's 10th anniversary
on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   So far, she said, the adoption bureaucracy seems unharmed. She
said she received a letter from Chinese adoption officials on
Wednesday granting permission for six more local families to travel
to China for adoptions later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern, Adams said, was how China would react to the
news accounts of the demonstrations and of adoptions. She said that
on an ``NBC Nightly News'' account on Tuesday, anchor Tom Brokaw
made at least two references to adopted children as being
``unwanted'' in China.
</P>
<P>
   China has reacted negatively to such characterizations in the
past, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese laws restricting many couples to one child are behind
the high number of children in orphanages, estimated at 100,000 to
500,000, according to Adams. More than 95 percent of those children
are girls because in the Chinese culture, males dominate. Most of
them have been abandoned by families who want boys.
</P>
<P>
   China's Children has placed about 200 children with Arizona
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear couple Debbie and Ronald Whitler are pleased that their
upcoming trip to China to adopt a baby is scheduled to take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel threatened or worried about our safety,'' Debbie
Whitler said. ``I just don't want to be seen as the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   They have had a photograph of their daughter, who they have
named Lily Yan, since April 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's adorable,'' Whitler said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Jacobses, they took pleasure in satisfying their
American food craving after arriving at the Los Angeles airport.
They ate at an airport McDonald's. &QL; 
Michael Clancy can be reached at (602) 444-8550 or at
mike.clancy &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
