<SLUG> BC-CIG-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY'S LAWSUIT AGAINST TOBACCO COMPANY GOES TO JURY IN KC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did Charles Steele understand the risks of cigarettes and make a
rational choice to smoke, or was he hopelessly addicted to an
unreasonably dangerous product?
</P>
<P>
   Jurors faced that question Wednesday as lawyers representing
Steele's family and the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. made their
closing arguments in federal court in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The jury began its deliberations about 11:45 a.m. and quit for
the day about 5 p.m. They will resume this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Steele's son and daughter contend in their lawsuit that Brown &AMP;
Williamson's Kool Filter Kings were defective, ``unreasonably''
dangerous and directly responsible for his lung cancer. Steele died
in 1995 at age 56 while living in Vandalia, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Company lawyers, witnesses and officials have acknowledged that
smoking is risky, but they say Brown &AMP; Williamson has funded health
research on smoking and helped to disclose its hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Company experts also have argued that Steele never tried to quit
smoking and was exposed to a host of cancer-causing chemicals when
he worked at an aluminum foundry and at a brick-making plant.
</P>
<P>
   Steele's family isn't the only group watching the jury's
decision closely.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco analysts said Wednesday that the verdict could be a
bellwether for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   After years of consistently winning cases brought by sick
smokers, the industry has had a more mixed record recently.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris recently lost two cases on the West Coast, while
earlier this week the industry won three cases that had been
consolidated in a Memphis, Tenn., courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were the West Coast cases aberrations or were they the start
of a trend?'' asked Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst for Salomon
Smith Barney in New York. ``Only after a half dozen or more cases
go to juries will the pattern become obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors watch such cases closely, said Gary Black, with the
investment management firm of Sanford C. Bernstein in New York.
Stocks tend to move when tobacco companies lose lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors' psyches are very fragile here,'' Black said.
``Tobacco stocks have been on a downslide since January. People are
looking at this case to see if the industry is back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Arguing for Steele's son and daughter, lawyer J. Michael Cronan
said Steele was powerfully affected by nicotine, changing from an
affable family man to ``evil'' _ in the words of his sister _ when
deprived of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was greatly affected by smoking while others are not,''
Cronan said. ``In the context of his genetics and his environment,
he was addicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes by their very nature are defective, Cronan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The normal use of the product will cause serious injury or
death,'' he said. ``In the 1 1/2- to two-pack-a-day range (over 10
years) one in six smokers will get lung cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven McCormick, a lawyer representing Brown &AMP; Williamson,
argued that his client should not be held responsible for Steele's
decisions. Steele's daughter, he pointed out, testified that her
father read warning labels on his packs of Kool Filter Kings, which
he called ``cancer sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that an unreasonable risk?'' McCormick asked. ``Well, in
our country, that's a decision that adults get to make.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormick also threw a new wrinkle into the case he had been
arguing for eight days.
</P>
<P>
   How could the jury blame Brown &AMP; Williamson when some evidence
suggested that he smoked other companies' brands from time to time?
</P>
<P>
   McCormick observed that some of Steele's friends and family
members remember him smoking at least four other brands before he
was diagnosed with cancer in 1994. None of those brands was
manufactured by Brown &AMP; Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question he smoked Kool cigarettes sometime in the
later part of his smoking life,'' McCormick said. ``But this is not
the Steeles against smoking. It's the Steeles against our company
and our product.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning for rebuttal, Cronan reminded the jury of other
evidence that showed Steele smoking Kools from the late 1960s until
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Cronan closed argument in the case by telling jurors that about
9,500 Americans have died prematurely from smoking-related
illnesses since the trial opened on May 3. A verdict for Charles
Steele's children would send a powerful message to the company, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're here to stop the killing, to make smoking history and
to make Brown &AMP; Williamson deal with its problems,'' Cronan said.
</P>
<P>
   He asked jurors to award Steele's children about $1 million in
actual damages. But though he recently won permission from U.S.
District Judge Ortrie Smith to seek $25 million in punitive
damages, he did not suggest that figure to jurors Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
