<SLUG> BC-PAINT-POLLUTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINT RESTRICTIONS URGED TO KEEP AIR CLEAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX   AND MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hoping to brighten Southland skies, air quality
regulators on Friday will consider imposing tough restrictions for
the paint industry that could take some of the gloss off Los
Angeles and leave the city lusterless.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the plan by bureaucrats of the South Coast Air
Quality Management District will result in paints that are inferior
in almost every way, leaving consumers with fewer colors and higher
prices for a product that is harder to use and provides less
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney William M. Smiland, who with his brother Bob, owns
Smiland Paint Co. in Los Angeles, said the AQMD plan borders on
being draconian. ``We don't use words like `irrational' lightly but
I am going to use that word on Friday before the board.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy, this is nuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even air quality regulators acknowledge that their plan will
cost the paint industry tens of millions of dollars to implement,
impact a wide range of products on the market and could eventually
prove to be unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, to be voted on by the board Friday, are directed at
the solvents used in paint. They are designed to reduce the amount
of volatile organic compounds, or VOCs, released into the air by an
estimated 21.8 tons per day.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these kinds of compounds, measured in grams per liter,
react with other elements in the air to produce ozone, a component
of smog. They are found in such products as primers, sealers, rust
coatings, waterproofing, gloss and semi-gloss paint and quick-dry
enamels.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators are recommending a two-step reduction in the VOC
level. The first, gradual step would occur in 2002 with the steeper
and final cut coming in 2006, the AQMD said.
</P>
<P>
   The steepest cut, which would reduce VOCs down to 50 grams per
liter, will come in the kinds of products familiar to anyone who
has painted kitchen cabinets or the trim on their house. And by
2006 consumers will be paying about $6 more per gallon for their
glossy and semi-gloss paint, said AQMD spokesman Bill Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The board is scheduled to discuss the rules at its meeting at
9:30 a.m. Friday in AQMD headquarters, 21865 Copley Drive, Diamond
Bar.
</P>
<P>
   Some paints used in industrial applications such as smokestacks,
sewage treatment plants and industrial furnaces can have a higher
VOC content than paints used around the home. The limit for
quick-drying paint like that used on film sets will be 250 grams
per liter effective in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But the new formulas for paint used by government agencies for
items like bridges, roadways and water pipes will not be
implemented until 2006. Those limits will be higher than
residential users, the AQMD said, and are being implemented later
to give public agencies such as water plants enough time to find
paint that will pass muster of health agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Broadbent, the AQMD's deputy executive officer, estimated
that the plan will cost the industry about $58 million starting in
2002 as manufacturers develop new, cleaner paints.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations are based in part on a study by National
Technical Systems that was completed about a month ago, he said.
The work was overseen by a group that included representatives from
the painting industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final results have been coming out for the past few months
and shared by staff in public meetings, even though the final
report came out recently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has divided the paint industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Legislative and Regulatory Advocacy Program of
the Southern California Paint and Coatings Alliance, a lobby group
known by the acronym EL RAP that represents manufacturers,
distributors and retailers, claims the impact of the new rules will
be many times more severe than the district's estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The group claims that formulas for 7,000 paints, about 90
percent of those in use, will have to be reworked, an economic blow
of up to $1.75 billion.
</P>
<P>
   William Smiland estimates that his company has about $15 million
worth of formulas that will be wiped out if the new rule is passed.
</P>
<P>
   The products companies like his could make probably won't have
much consumer appeal because they will not last as long as today's
paints, hold vibrant colors or be very easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make low VOC paints but you can't get anybody to buy
them. It's very much like the electric car story. It is literally
this radical, outlawing Ford, GM and Toyota and just leaving the
electric car,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smiland also said that the regulations were drawn up before the
AQMD's study on the issue was complete.
</P>
<P>
   AQMD officials disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry representatives said that we were rushing to judgment
because the final report just came out. But we feel that while that
may be true, the information in that report has been out for some
time and has been shared for the industry for some time,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly acknowledged that quality might be an issue. ``To be
honest with you the results of that study were mixed. The zero
(low) VOC paints . . . often were not as good.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end the industry is being given some wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial standards are adopted in 2002, the district
will conduct feasibility studies on whether paints to meet the next
level of reduction can in fact be made.
</P>
<P>
   And manufacturers could still make some paints with a high VOC
content as long as the end result of all the paint they sold was
less VOCs, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   And Broadbent said that by 2006 some of the solvents being used
will not be as reactive as they are today because of other
pollution reduction methods being implemented. If that's the case,
a recommendation to modify the rules can be made.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some in the paint industry think the rules being
proposed by the district are all right.
</P>
<P>
   Ed &UR;  &LR; Laird, president of Coatings Resource Corp. in Huntington
Beach, which makes about 500 types of paint, thinks the industry
can adapt to the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the industry has negotiated very tough and I think the
AQMD has done a very thorough study. There are coatings that meet
the rules and we've had a fair shot. It's time to move on and make
paint. For the most part there is a price to pay for clean air and
it's passed onto the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Whittingham, the air quality staff member for Los Angeles
County Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich, said the new rules will
hurt the smallest manufacturers the most, but that the board will
consider giving them a year and a half after the compliance date to
meet the new limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the big companies put their stuff on the shelf, (the
small companies) can go out and get it and change their
formulations. That's a lot less expensive than the original
research and development,'' Whittingham said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
