<HEADLINE>
SPRINT RAISING CURTAIN LOCALLY ON ION TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Nearly a year after Sprint Corp. staged a
Broadway production to unveil its Integrated On-Demand Network, the
company is raising the curtain locally on technology that will
change the way its customers buy, use and pay for telecommunication
services.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sprint will open the ION Experience Center, an
interactive demonstration room where employees, customers and the
general public can schedule an appointment to scrutinize Sprint's
digital-age network and judge its seemingly awesome capabilities
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in the ground floor of a building at 9300 Metcalf Ave.,
the exhibit's purpose is twofold: to prove to skeptics, competitors
and potential customers that ION is real; and, more important, that
it works.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of that message to Sprint's future cannot be
overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ION is the new face of Sprint, the vehicle it will use to
deliver all of its services in coming years _ local or
long-distance telephone service, data transmission and Internet
connections, for residential customers or businesses alike.
</P>
<P>
   The company estimates that there are 40 million technology-savvy
households nationwide that could be potential buyers of the
service. And by the end of the year, when it begins delivering the
service to residential customers, it must convince them it is worth
between $100 and $175 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration center includes a working telephone switch
that provides futuristic phone services to a series of nearby stage
sets _ a kitchen, a home office, a small business and a large
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   To prove that no smoke and mirrors are involved, the floors of
the exhibit are transparent, so customers can see the wiring that
runs to each device. Even the refrigerator and stove work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer education is going to be a pretty long process,''
said Jeff Shafer, a Sprint spokesman. ``That's why we're getting
started now.''  &LR; brk:Race to market
</P>
<P>
   When Chairman William Esrey insists that Sprint has what it
takes to succeed without being bought by a larger company, he is
referring to ION.
</P>
<P>
   ION is Sprint's strategy to enter local phone markets around the
country, and grab a larger share of its customers' exploding
expenditures on communication services.
</P>
<P>
   It is a technology that Sprint says will eliminate the notion of
time and distance in telephone billing, enabling the company to
transform your plain vanilla phone service into an all-you-can-eat
smorgasbord of full-featured voice lines, lightning-fast Internet
access, videoconferencing, and video on demand.
</P>
<P>
   The question, observers say, is whether Sprint has what it takes
to successfully execute the ION game plan, and put its service into
homes and businesses around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In short, will customers buy it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that it's really neat,'' said Robert
Rosenberg, president of Insight Research Corp. ``But is it cheap?
Is is reliable? And how quickly is AT&AMP;T going to be there with a
comparable product?''
</P>
<P>
   When Esrey stepped into the theater footlights last July to
introduce ION, he told industry analysts and reporters that other
companies had bits and pieces of the technology, ``but only Sprint
has it all, and only Sprint has it now.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, however, observers are still puzzled over what
services ION will include, what it will cost, and when it will be
ready for more than the eight companies and 30 employees currently
beta-testing the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing still sounds like more of a billing system than
anything,'' said David Cooperstein, an analyst with Forrester
Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while AT&AMP;T has secured access to local consumers with
a megabuck spree of cable-television company acquisitions, Sprint's
strategy to make the final connections to consumers' homes remains
fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``ION sounds like a pretty compelling service, but they don't
seem to have a cohesive last-mile strategy,'' said Zia Daniell
Wigder, an analyst with Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Sprint has the opposite problem of AT&AMP;T. Ma Bell
has spent more than $90 billion to buy cable connections that will
allow it to compete with Baby Bells in local markets.
</P>
<P>
   Now AT&AMP;T must spend billions more to upgrade its cable systems
to provide services that they were never designed to handle, such
as two-way telephone service and high-speed Internet, with the same
near-perfect reliability of a phone network.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, on the other hand, has developed a service that embodies
the vision. Now it has to figure out how to get that service to
customers, and convince them that its worth as much as $175 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be easy. Around the country, cable and local
telephone companies are beating Sprint to market with one of the
most enticing ingredients in the ION package: high-speed Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two months, both Time Warner and Southwestern Bell
will offer their own flavors of high-speed Internet service in
Kansas City, priced at $40 to $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``First to market is major advantage,'' said Brian Adamik, an
industry analyst with the Yankee Group. ``Customers are less likely
to change once they're locked into a relationship. Sprint hasn't
even articulated what its offer is yet.''  &LR; brk:Wooing customers
</P>
<P>
   To hear Sprint tell it, ION is nothing less than a complete
reinvention of the traditional phone system, a technical voyage of
such mind-boggling complexity that you need an engineering degree
simply to understand the alphabet soup of technology acronyms
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Sprint will be deploying its ATM-based
service through an ISH connected to your home via ADSL, which
communicates with a DSLAM at the CO, which will be backhauled to
their POP via DS3...
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a telecom engineer's dream,'' said Fred Harris,
director of network planning and design at Sprint. ``I finally got
the opportunity to do this the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sprint engineers, ION represents the great leap forward to
what analysts call Converged Network Services, a world where local,
long distance, video and data travel over the same, fantastically
efficient network.
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, Sprint's network promises to facilitate
telecommuting, distance-learning, desktop collaboration and
electronic commerce. It could also alleviate the pressure on
businesses to maintain dedicated technical staff to deal with
problems on their own networks.
</P>
<P>
   To the consumer, what it means is that a technician will come to
your home and wire up an electronic magic box to which your
computer, telephones, fax machine and other communication devices
will be linked.
</P>
<P>
   Once the service is installed, users in different rooms of that
house could simultaneously talk on the phone, access the Internet
at warp speeds, download a video, and video conference with work _
all over the same connection.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, Sprint plans to put the power of its network
directly in each user's hands. Using computers, customers could add
new phone lines with the calling features of their choice, or
request huge amounts of bandwidth for a high-quality video
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ION also erases the notion of a phone bill based on time and
distance. Instead, users will pay a flat fee, which will include
virtually unlimited long distance, all calling features and huge
bandwidth use.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, Sprint's prices sound steep, particularly
because the service doesn't include cable TV programming or the
equipment needed to video conference. But company officials think
that about 40 million technology-intensive households in the United
States will consider it a bargain when they see what's included.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these households are already spending $100 to $175 a
month,'' Joan Jarrett, director of emerging markets for Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still weighing different pricing options for the
service, whether it will require a service contract, and how much
to charge for the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it is grappling with the bigger issue that puzzles
most analysts: how to get the service into consumers' homes.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, most observers have assumed that Sprint would
reach residential customers with souped-up copper phone lines _
known as asymmetric digital subscriber lines _ leased from the
regional Bell companies.
</P>
<P>
   The company does intend to do that in some markets. During the
past month, however, Sprint has spent more than $1 billion to
acquire the stock of three little-known wireless cable companies.
Collectively, those companies own wireless broadcast licenses with
the potential to reach 24.2 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a risky move. Using wireless to carry data is a fairly new
use of the technology, and Sprint will have to spend millions to
upgrade that technology to handle data.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sprint's marketers are doing everything they
can to build hype, with a national advertising campaign, regular
news releases and moves like the ION experience center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest risk here is the schedule,'' Harris said. ``Come a
year from now, when the number of customers starts skyrocketing,
it's got to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0055EDT &QL; 
