<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5192 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEEF-KAN-KAN &LR;      05-13 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEEF-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINER THINGS IN LIFE _ IMPORTED _ AT RISK IN BEEF WARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like to shop in the gourmet aisle of your local
supermarket?
</P>
<P>
   Then start stocking up on Dijon mustard, Swiss chocolate and
mineral water from France. Their prices may be about to double _
because Europeans aren't buying our hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Better get that pate, those sun-dried tomatoes and Roquefort
cheese, too. And if you've been intending to buy a moped or another
type of European motorcycle, do it soon.
</P>
<P>
   They're all part of a long list of imports from 15 European
countries that Washington may slap with a 100 percent punitive
tariff because their governments refuse to accept hormone-treated
beef from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest skirmish in a trade war with the European Union
that the beef industry estimates has cost American farmers about
$500 million in lost revenue in the last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has said it will not meet a World Trade
Organization-imposed deadline set for today for it to comply with
the organization's ruling that it lift the beef ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like to see a trade war, but you've got to have a
level playing field,'' said Larry Oltjen, a fourth-generation
cattle rancher in Robinson, Kan., and president of the Kansas
Livestock Association.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle is crucial to the Kansas economy. It accounts for nearly
$17 billion, almost a quarter, of the state's total economic
output. The state exported $471 million in beef and veal all over
the world in 1997. Missouri exported more than $64 million in beef
products that same year.
</P>
<P>
   The tension with the European Union is over the use of
artificial growth hormones, present in more than 90 percent of U.S.
beef production. The beef industry says the hormones produce cattle
with less fat than animals not fed with the hormones.
</P>
<P>
   But the mad-cow disease scare in Great Britain increased
concerns in Europe about the safety of its food supply, and the
union banned all imports of hormone-treated beef.
</P>
<P>
   For years, both sides of the Atlantic have waged a war of words,
sanctions and scientific studies. But in three instances, the World
Trade Organization has ruled against the European Union and ordered
it to lift the beef ban.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Ziegler, a spokesman for the Office of the U.S. Trade
Representative, said the European Union had engaged in a ``cynical
political manipulation'' of legitimate concerns over food safety to
engage in protectionism. Washington countered with a threat to
raise prices on $900 million in European Union goods if the ban is
not lifted by today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming weight of the scientific evidence is that
there is no human health threat posed by the proper use of growth
hormones,'' Ziegler said.
</P>
<P>
   Maeve O'Beirne, a spokeswoman for the European Union, said the
union was conducting its own studies and had asked for a longer
delay instead of today's deadline. She said the union had offered
to award the United States compensation in return for the
continuation of the ban on hormone-treated beef, such as dropping
the tariffs on the non-hormone-treated American beef.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
