<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUPLE-DIE-SPI &LR;      05-13 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUPLE-DIE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE DEVOTED TO ONE ANOTHER DIE AN HOUR WITHIN EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Gladys and Pete Saccomanno died the way any of us who
ever swore undying love to someone else would want to: at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Pete died at Seattle's Virginia Mason Medical Center Friday
night of complications from lymphoma. Gladys died in an ambulance
on the way to the hospital, apparently of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour separated the Seattle couple's deaths. Pete's
heart stopped in the hospital almost the moment Gladys died, but
medical technology got it started again; he passed away shortly
after she did.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was a fairy tale marriage with a Shakespearean end.
</P>
<P>
   Pete and Gladys Saccomanno were buried Wednesday morning at
Seattle's Evergreen-Washelli Cemetery. She was 78, he was 76. A
cold mist fell on their burial sprays and left dark splotches on
the jackets of their friends, some who knew them from 35 years of
horse racing at Longacres race track in Seattle and later Emerald
Downs in Auburn, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end, when Gladys was in a nursing home with heart
trouble and Pete was undergoing chemotherapy, Gladys stopped
eating, and told friends she didn't want to go on living. But a
friend persuaded her to start eating, leave the nursing home, take
care of Pete, and wait for the birth of her great-grandson.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Gladys agreed, but if Pete passes on, she said, then she
didn't want to live, either.
</P>
<P>
   Their lifelong love began at first sight. They met in a
Harley-Davidson store in Trinidad, Colo., in 1939, when Pete
whistled at Gladys in the store, earning a rebuke and a glare from
her brother. They were married in 1942, and Pete went off to war,
the last time they would be apart.
</P>
<P>
   Pete came back and worked as a longshoreman on the Seattle
docks. She taught him how to handicap horses, he taught her how to
smoke. They rode their motorcycles together, Pete speeding along on
a black Harley, Gladys next to him on her white Indian with black
trim.
</P>
<P>
   Pete called her ``Princess.'' She called him ``Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Their only fight _ in 57 years of marriage, the only thing
anyone can ever remember them ever arguing about _ was whether
Gladys should tour as a professional bowler.
</P>
<P>
   A scratch bowler in Seattle's co-ed leagues, Gladys bowled an
average 243, and often rolled 260. In the basement of their Seattle
home are 47 bowling trophies Gladys won.
</P>
<P>
   She always was lucky. Her friends called her psychic. She was
uncanny at picking winning horses, using numbers she got off the
1-900 horoscope lines, numbers she saw on newspaper comics pages,
even phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   They never missed a day at Long-acres Racetrack, and came home
winners enough times that they bought new cars for their only
child, Linda.
</P>
<P>
   When Gladys' eyesight failed 12 years ago, when macular
degeneration made the world dim and fuzzy and narrow, she and Pete
kept going to the races. Pete would study the racing forms,
transcribing them onto white pieces of paper using big, black
numbers for her to see.
</P>
<P>
   Few people could tell she was blind, because she was agile. She
moved through the racetrack in a smock, with a couple hundred
dollars of fives in her left pocket and a couple hundred dollars of
singles in her right.
</P>
<P>
   She smiled a lot at her table in Longacres' wine cellar, the
same one they sat at all the time, toward the back corner, near the
buffet table. She'd smile when her picks were going well, when Pete
told her what was going on. She'd curse when her picks didn't win,
place or show.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at their funeral, a trumpeter played the traditional
horse racing theme ``A Call to the Post.''
</P>
<P>
   What was recalled were the little things: She was always his
princess, he at her beck and call. They cooked and despite her
failing eyesight they worked together, Pete doing the measuring and
Gladys the mixing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be blind but I can still feel,'' Gladys told friends
when they learned how their Christmas cookies were made.
</P>
<P>
   After the blindness set in, Pete would put makeup on Gladys
every morning, and she'd sit still, smiling at him. He sewed her
pants suits, made her purses.
</P>
<P>
   Even the hospital nurses cried when they heard what happened.
Maybe it was coincidence they died when they did, maybe not,
because no one has ever proved, empirically, that you can die of a
broken heart.
</P>
<P>
   But Gladys and Pete Saccomanno died within an hour of each
other, the last chapter in a real American love story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
