<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-CANSECO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUES' POWER PLAYS SHORT OF HIGH VOLTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The power is still on in the St. Louis Blues' power
play, but the light is definitely flickering.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Blues scored a power-play goal Wednesday night. It was
their second in this series. The only problem? They've had 21
chances, including seven Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues couldn't score with almost 90 seconds of five players
against three Wednesday night. Their one power-play goal was a
fluke, a centering pass from Geoff Courtnall that bounced in off
Dallas Stars center Mike Modano.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two or three games I thought our power play has been
effective,'' Blues coach Joel Quenneville said. ``We get a fluke
power-play goal by Courtnall. Sometimes things like that turn
around a power play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues have scored with a man advantage 10 percent of the
time in this series. It's not ``that'' bad, but it certainly isn't
anything like the 27 percent clip they were scoring at on the power
play in the first round against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis was 9-of-33 with a man advantage in the first round.
SPEAKING OF DEPTH
</P>
<P>
   Depth has been a Stars' strength all season. Coach Ken Hitchcock
has been rolling four lines since training camp, a luxury opposing
teams usually do without.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except for St. Louis in postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues have had 15 players score goals in the playoffs, best
among the eight remaining teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all year long we've had a number of guys able to
score,'' coach Joel Quenneville said. ``The nice thing is you don't
have to rely on one guy to do your scoring. If it's not (Pierre)
Turgeon scoring, hopefully, it's maybe Al (MacInnis) or Pavol
(Demitra), and now all of a sudden you have some secondary guys to
count on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice knowing you don't have to look to one guy to
contribute goals.'' BECOMING FANS
</P>
<P>
   Joel Quenneville watched Tuesday's game between Colorado and
Detroit, and he admitted to rooting for the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   No, he doesn't care who wins. But the Red Wings were up 2-0 in
the series and looking well on their way to a sweep, a bad sign for
the Blues and the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are rooting for the other series to be a long series. It's
only human nature,'' Quenneville said. ``You don't want to see them
have a sweep and have an easy time of it, knowing that they are
going to be fresh and have time to get rested for the next series.
That's the last thing you want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no sweep. Colorado won 5-3. RUNNING ON EMPTY?
</P>
<P>
   Blues defensemen Al MacInnis and Chris Pronger sit at No. 1 and
No. 2 in minutes per game in the playoffs. Pronger leads all NHL
players with 35.82 minutes per playoff game while MacInnis averages
35.61.
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis says he feels fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``And obviously, Prongs is a lot younger than I am,'' MacInnis
said. ``Joel (Quenneville) has given us a lot of time off. We feel
fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Quenneville said Pronger and MacInnis were logging just as much
ice time during regular-season play. Pronger ranked first among NHL
players, averaging 30.61 minutes per game, while MacInnis' 29.12
average had him fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a new thing for them,'' Quenneville said. ``They have
grown accustomed to managing their ice, knowing they are going to
be out there a lot. They are very astute as far as their
positioning goes, which can conserve energy.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
