<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5203 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GALLOWAYCOLUMN-TE     05-13 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GAGGING NOW, BUT WILL THEY CHOKE?
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ First came misfortune Wednesday night, which
eventually resulted in misery, which left the Dallas Stars with a
nagging question to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   Are they gagging in this series?
</P>
<P>
   Gagging, of course, is defined as the first sign of choking.
</P>
<P>
   Open wide, fellows. Let's check those throats.
</P>
<P>
   Staggered again at Kiel Center by a another overtime disaster,
the Stars no longer qualify as the best team in the NHL, no longer
have Detroit in their conference finals cross hairs, and, please,
don't even mention the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there is a much greater concern.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Stars better than even the St. Louis Blues?
</P>
<P>
   When the Blues' Pierre Turgeon, taking a beautiful feed from
Sergei Zubov, ripped home an overtime goal Wednesday night,
second-round survival for Dallas became an immediate issue.
</P>
<P>
   Since Zubov was wearing a visitor's jersey, an assist won't show
up in the official scoring. ``But it was the best pass (Turgeon)
got all night,'' said St. Louis' Geoff Courtnall, celebrating the
3-2 victory with a one-liner.
</P>
<P>
   This second-round series became tied at two wins apiece,
guaranteeing a trip back here after Game 5 at Reunion Arena on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   But a more critical issue for coach Ken Hitchcock is the
heavily-favored Stars have not demonstrated any signs of
superiority in the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 was actually their best overall performance of the
series, starting with Eddie Belfour in goal and Mike Modano getting
unleashed again. Yet, the Stars still lost.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov had one of those major blunders that haunts postseason
participants, sliding a mindless pass across his blue line, right
on to the stick of Turgeon. Where was Pat Verbeek with a slash to
the back of the knee when you really need him?
</P>
<P>
   Turgeon took the gift, skated in unchecked on Belfour, and
buried the puck above Belfour's right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have that _ he knows it, we all know it,'' said
Hitchcock, describing the Zubov brainlock.
</P>
<P>
   But while that one misplay ended the game, the Stars had spent
the regulation 60 minutes cursing the hockey gods.
</P>
<P>
   There was certainly no Cup luck on this evening. Misfortune
nailed them repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Most deflating was when Verbeek poked home what could have been
the game-winner with five and a half minutes remaining in the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   Except Jamie Langenbrunner was also cruising the crease area
with Verbeek, and as the replays would show, yes, he had a half a
skate in the blue. Not when the puck went in the net, but as the
puck entered the blue-colored crease
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner was just lifting his skate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the rule,'' Hitchcock said. ``I guess that evens out
the Edmonton series.''
</P>
<P>
   That one was the killer, but there was also more.
</P>
<P>
   After a strong first period resulted in a 1-0 Stars lead, the
Blues scored twice in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The first came after Brad Lukowich broke his stick and was
trying to defend Pavol Demitra with just gloves and skates. That
allowed Demitra to slide a feed to Jochen Hecht, who had shaken
Craig Ludwig, and was alone in front of Belfour. Hecht connected
for the tie, and ignited what had been a docile crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But the go-ahead goal for St. Louis involved even worse luck for
the Stars. Courtnall fired a seemingly harmless pass from the
corner that crossed in front of Belfour. But the puck connected
perfectly with Modano's stick, and deflected past Belfour into the
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fluky,'' said St. Louis coach Joel Quenneville. Fluky,
however, still counts.
</P>
<P>
   Playing well enough all evening for a shutout, Belfour instead
was shaking his head over two coulda, woulda, shoulda goals. And
that was before Zubov made his mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock shook up his lines for Game 4, and even made the major
move of separating Brett Hull from Modano. He was hoping for a
``jump-start'' for Modano, who had been no factor in two straight
games. That part worked. Modano was a dominant force, scoring less
than a minute into the game, and assisting on Jere Lehtinen's goal
to open the third period.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, he also ``assisted'' on the Courtnall goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of evening for the Stars. A gagging kind of
evening. And now they have to prove that a gag won't lead to a
massive choke. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
