A5206 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES_sport     05-13 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES </SLUG>
 _ sports 
Overtime Blues hit Stars again 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mike Heika 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ST. LOUIS _ The mirror cracked on the Stars last night, and the
image afterward wasn't pretty. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Victimized by two bad breaks and one bad play, the Stars lost a
3-2 overtime game to the St. Louis Blues at the Kiel Center and saw
their best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals series tied at
two games apiece. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the third consecutive overtime game in the series and the
second consecutive overtime loss for the Stars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All three \RBlues\S goals were lucky goals,'' said Stars
center Mike Modano, who had a goal and an assist. ``It was bad
breaks on our side and good luck on their side, but you have to
work hard for your breaks and your luck. They force us to play a
mistake-free game, and, if we don't, we end up paying for it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars paid heaviest in overtime, when they were dominating
the extra period and lost because of a single mistake. With the
Stars trying to push the puck out of their defensive zone,
defenseman Sergei Zubov made a careless cross-ice pass that was
picked off by Pierre Turgeon in the neutral zone. Turgeon then
walked into the offensive zone and threaded a 40-foot shot past
goalie Ed Belfour and into the upper left corner of the net for the
game-winner 5:52 into overtime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turgeon's goal was almost a perfect snapshot of the series as
the Blues have been continually working to force Stars' mistakes,
and continually working to make the Stars panic. Once again, the
Blues lived off a neutral-zone turnover. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a mistake,'' Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk said.
``If nobody made mistakes, you'd have a lot of scoreless hockey
games.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Blues, the Stars aren't allowing that to
happen. On the Blues' first goal, defenseman Brad Lukowich broke
his stick and forced defensive partner Craig Ludwig to try to
over-cover behind the net against both Jochen Hecht and Pavol
Demitra of the Blues. Hecht played a perfect shell game on Ludwig,
bouncing a pass to himself off the back of the net and taking a
hustling Ludwig completely out of the play. Hecht then passed to
Demitra and moved to the front of the net, where Demitra fed him
for a 10-footer from right in front of Belfour 5:02 into the second
period. It was the second goal of the series for the rookie from
Germany. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, who was again solid with 27 saves, had even worse luck
later in the second period. While Blues winger Geoff Courtnall was
rushing into the offensive zone, he was forced into the left corner
and wheeled to throw what he thought was a pass into the slot.
While no Blues player was close to the puck, Modano tried to stop
the pass and accidentally tipped it past Belfour and into his own
net for a 2-1 Blues' lead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really looking for it, and I just had my stick on the
ice,'' Modano said. ``When it rains, it pours. It just seems
everything is going against us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, however, hadn't seen the worst of their luck. After
Modano worked a play to tie the game on Jere Lehtinen's goal 40
seconds into the third period, the Stars appeared to have victory
in hand. With about 5 1/2 minutes remaining in the game, Pat
Verbeek slipped a wrister through the pads of Blues goalie Grant
Fuhr. However, Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner had skated hard to
the edge of the goal crease and had his skates inside the crease
before the puck entered the crease. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The play was overturned on replay; an NHL rule designed to
protect goalies prohibits any player from preceding the puck into
the crease on a scoring play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A rule's a rule,'' Matvichuk said. ``It went our way in the
Edmonton series \Rdenying an Oilers goal\S. It went against us
tonight.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek said he didn't blame Langenbrunner, who was charging
hard to the net and had his skate in the crease for only a second
or two. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't cry over spilt milk,'' Verbeek said. ``It's over, so
let it go.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Modano scored 59 seconds into the game to give the Stars an
early lead and had a strong game on a new line that included gritty
winger Grant Marshall and was minus Modano's yearlong linemate,
Brett Hull. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best I've felt all series,'' Modano said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Modano said he would need to feel even better when the
series returns to Texas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We handled the play for the most part tonight, we made good
decisions with the puck, Eddie made some great saves and we had a
lot of things going,'' Modano said. ``We just have to dig down even
deeper now. The breaks are going against us, so you've got to
really work hard.'' &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
