<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S WHAT HIT THE HEAT: A 32-2 RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was as unforeseeable as the harmony on the court
between Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston. With about four and a
half minutes left in the second quarter on Wednesday night,
something struck the Miami Heat. Its execution became shabby, its
shooting stroke went cold and its hopes of taking control of this
series vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The next 12 minutes 26 seconds of Game 3 of this
three-of-five-game series were a nightmare for the Heat. It was
outscored, 32-2. Knicks 97, Heat 73. Game over. Circle the wagons.
</P>
<P>
   Even Pat Riley, that master motivator, admitted to being
shellshocked by the sudden death of his offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was alarming to me was how quick it happened,'' Riley
said after his team shot 34 percent from the floor. ``About seven
minutes into the second quarter it began to go and we just could
not get it back. They had this run that was just overwhelming. But,
as I know in this game, I know we have one more left in us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room, in the gloomy aftermath of their whipping,
the Heat players drummed up cliches about bouncing back and never
saying die. They talked about having fought through adversity
before, and Alonzo Mourning even reminded members of the news media
that the Heat led last year's first-round series, two games to one,
before losing in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never doubt this team,'' said Dan Majerle, who missed all
five of his shots and played with a severely bruised right
shoulder. ``This team's always been real resilient. We've got no
choice on Friday but to come out and play hard. Everything's on the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   But Majerle appeared battered as he mouthed those words, not
just physically, but mentally. He sounded defeated, a man trying to
convince himself to believe. And he was not alone. The entire Heat
locker room was a dismal collage of bowed heads, stunned
expressions and sullen comments. It was hard for the Heat players
to be the big, bad, bold men they are reputed to be when they knew
they had given up halfway through their most important game of the
year. For when it began going badly, when the Knicks began
expanding their lead, Riley's warriors threw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just took a hit and quit on the game,'' Majerle said. ``We
didn't stay the course and keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Brown, who had all 9 of his points and 5 of his 8 rebounds
in the first quarter, could not deny the truth in Majerle's words.
``It looked like our confidence went,'' he said. ``When it didn't
look good, we lost our fire. Instead of stepping up and coming
together like we should have, we just relaxed and didn't fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Heat's problem during that crucial stretch was the
absence of Mourning. After picking up his fourth foul two minutes
into the third quarter, he sat for nearly seven minutes. Mourning,
who led the Heat with 18 points, was one of Miami's few sources of
scoring in the first half, finishing with 13 of its 37 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Mourning's removal does not completely explain the team's
fruitlessness. After all, he played for all but 1:10 of its nearly
five-minute scoreless stretch just before the half, and after he
returned for the final 3:23 of the third, the Heat scored 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   This collapse was bigger than Mourning's having a subpar game.
It was Tim Hardaway looking like a shadow of himself on a sore
knee. It was Jamal Mashburn playing soft and not getting to the
free-throw line. It was the Heat being outrebounded by 37-19 and
grabbing just two offensive rebounds over the final three quarters.
It was a Heat bench that produced practically nothing before
garbage time.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks certainly deserve credit for their defense, but it
was not as if they were smothering the Heat. Majerle and his
teammates missed numerous open shots when the Knicks were slow on
their rotations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shots were there,'' Mourning said. ``We were so wide open
that we passed up the drive. Those same shots that we missed this
evening, we made them in Game 2. But when you miss them on a
regular basis, you have to start driving, taking it to the hole.
That's what we didn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, like hardheads, they continued to hoist 3-pointers,
despite missing their first 17 and finishing 4 for 23 (17.4
percent). Balls clanged off the front of the rim, bounced high and
wide off the back, and one attempt by Keith Askins missed the rim
altogether.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0032 </DOCNO>
