<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5211 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     05-13 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
There has been nothing during the first six weeks of the season to
suggest the Astros are not the team to beat in the National League
Central. Likewise, nothing occurred over the past three days to
indicate the Pittsburgh Pirates have what it takes to do anything
about it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros delivered the knockout punch Wednesday behind another
strong effort from Jose Lima, who held the Pirates to one run in
eight innings to key a 6-2 Astros victory at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Championship fights have been stopped with less bloodshed than
the Astros forced on the Pirates, who were outscored 31-10 in the
three-game series. The Astros completed their third series sweep of
the year and their first at home. They have won 12 of their last 14
games against the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' run total for the last three games matches the
Pirates' run total against the two-time defending division champs
since the start of the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some problems with this team,'' Pirates manager Gene
Lamont said. ``We came up against a team with hot bats, and their
pitching was outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have come to expect that from Lima, who evened his
career record at 31-31 and won for the sixth consecutive start. He
has pitched at least eight innings in three of his last four
outings.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates scored a run off Scott Elarton in the ninth and had
the potential tying run in the on-deck circle, but Elarton was able
to avoid disaster despite issuing three walks in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was completely out of rhythm,'' Elarton said. ``I'm glad it
wasn't a 2-1 ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   He could thank the Astros' explosive offense for that. The
Astros overcame a 1-0 deficit by scoring four runs in the sixth
inning. Carl Everett led the attack with three hits, but Richard
Hidalgo delivered the game-winner with a two-run triple.
</P>
<P>
   Big hits are becoming second nature for Hidalgo, who has driven
in 15 runs in his last 18 games while compiling a .317 batting
average during that stretch. Seventeen of Hidalgo's 31 hits have
been for extra bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard has come up with some huge hits for us,'' Astros
second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``He's a hell of a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima moved into some good company Wednesday, joining
Philadelphia's Curt Schilling as the only six-game winners in the
NL. Three of Lima's wins have come at home and three on the road,
but the Astrodome has been particularly good to him. Wednesday's
effort lowered his ERA to 1.97 at home, compared to 4.67 on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love pitching in the Astrodome,'' Lima said. ``I love
hearing those people cheering for me. No one thought I'd be at this
point (6-1), but I am. I want to be the No. 1 guy someday.''
</P>
<P>
   He's well on his way. Lima's only stumbling block Wednesday
occurred in the first inning when Pirates left fielder Al Martin
led off with a triple and scored on Mike Benjamin's single. Lima,
who struck out a career-high nine batters, didn't allow another
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That triple didn't bother me,'' Lima said. ``After that, I
kept the ball down and pitched well inside. If you leave the ball
up, they're going to hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first five innings, it appeared the Astros had
exhausted their offensive resources the previous night when they
tied a club record with 19 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates starter Jason Schmidt, whose career record fell to 0-7
against the Astros, retired five of the first six batters he faced
and skirted trouble in the third, fourth and fifth innings when the
Astros had runners in scoring position but failed to cross the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like he was going to cruise,'' said Bill Spiers, who
started at shortstop for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed in the sixth when the first five Astros reached
base. Ken Caminiti drew a leadoff walk, and Everett followed with
the second of his three singles. Both scored on Hidalgo's second
triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a good pitch to hit,'' Hidalgo said. ``It was a
fastball. As soon as I hit the ball, I had third base on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Pirates center fielder Brant Brown must have felt like the
Astros were picking on him. Hidalgo's triple got under his glove,
Spiers' subsequent RBI triple flew over his head, and Paul Bako's
broken-bat single landed in front of him. By the time reliever Brad
Clontz could put out the fire, the Pirates' one-run lead had turned
into a three-run deficit.
</P>
<P>
   After pitching at least six innings in each of his first five
starts, Schmidt has been knocked out after five innings in his last
two trips to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mystery to me,'' said Schmidt when asked about his
record against the Astros. ``I'm frustrated with myself and
wondering why I can't beat these stinking guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
