r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     05-13 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN, THEN HEAR BAD NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Their 1-0 victory over the New York Yankees on
Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium might have seemed too good to be
true for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, it was.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering the clubhouse after Chuck Finley (eight innings)
and Troy Percival (one inning) outdueled Yankees pitcher David
Cone, it was announced that Angels right fielder Tim Salmon will
miss at least five more weeks with a sprained left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, examined by hand specialist Dr. Norman Zemel, had an
arthrogram performed Wednesday, a procedure in which dye is
injected into the affected area to enhance X-rays. It showed the
sprain is worse than initially thought and he was fitted with a
short cast he'll wear for three weeks. After the cast is removed,
Salmon will need a minimum of two weeks for rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen it ever,'' the Angels' Mo Vaughn said when
asked about the team's injuries this season. ``It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon has already missed eight games since spraining the wrist
trying to make a sliding catch on a sinking liner by the White
Sox's Paul Konerko at Edison Field on May 3.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of being able to enjoy being the first team to shut
out the defending World Series champions this season, Angels
manager Terry Collins had to contemplate a lineup without another
of his top players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You beat the best team in baseball in a tremendous ballgame...
talk about getting a sock in the gut. We got one tonight,'' Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of Sunday we're watching him swing the bat and he feels
good. Then Monday it doesn't feel so good and he's out a week to 10
days. The next thing you know it's six weeks. We have to suck it up
again. We'll take a look and see what our options are, what we got
lineup-wise. Let's just hope he doesn't need surgery after six
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels didn't need Salmon on Wednesday, the way Finley
pitched. He struck out a season-high 11 and allowed three hits _
all singles _ in his eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees only threatened once _ in the third inning _ when
they used a single by Shane Spencer, a throwing error by third
baseman Troy Glaus and a wild pitch to put runners on second and
third with one out.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley got four strikeouts in the inning to escape. That's
right, four, tying a major-league record.
</P>
<P>
   After having already struck out Scott Brosius, Finley struck out
Chuck Knoblauch with runners on second and third for strikeout
No.2. Then he struck out Derek Jeter with a a forkball in the dirt,
but catcher Charlie O'Brien couldn't find the ball, which sat on
the dirt just behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The base runners stayed, but Jeter reached first to load the
bases for Paul O'Neill, who struck out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 33rd time in major-league history a pitcher has
struck out four in an inning, the 14th time in AL history and the
second time by an Angel (Ryne Duren, May 18, 1961 for the L.A.
Angels).
</P>
<P>
   Finley (2-3) came out after the eighth inning because he had
made 131 pitches, and Percival slammed the door in the ninth for
his seventh save. Percival struck out two in a 1-2-3 ninth,
including getting a curveball past Tino Martinez to end it.
</P>
<P>
   American League hitters were batting .133 against Cone (4-1)
going into the game Wednesday, the best by any pitcher in the
majors. The Angels managed five hits off him in seven innings, the
big hit coming from No.9 hitter Andy Sheets. Sheets' hit-and-run
double to right field in the seventh scored Orlando Palmeiro with
the only run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew David was throwing the ball great, he was pretty much
matching me pitch for pitch, inning for inning,'' Finley said.
``Combine pitching like that with their lineup, you figure you got
a tough night ahead of you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't nibble, nibble, nibble. You've got to go after them
because you can't let them get in a hitter's count where they can
kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, though, appeared stunned when told of the news on
Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This `it's early in the season' (nonsense) ain't there
anymore,'' he said. ``That's bad news, especially facing teams that
are at full strength. The same kind of thing seems to follow us.
The sunshine never can break through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
