<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES MICROSOFT TEMP WORKERS ENTITLED TO STOCK PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At least 10,000 former temporary workers at Microsoft
Corp. must be allowed to purchase the valuable shares of Microsoft
stock they were denied during their stints there, a U.S. Appellate
Court panel ruled late Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, in a case called In Re Vizcaino, in its narrowest
reading means that a large class of temporary workers at Microsoft
must be permitted to participate in the Redmond, Wash. company's
Employee Stock Purchase Plan, which gives discounts of 15 percent
or more on Microsoft stock.
</P>
<P>
   Interpreted more broadly, the Vizcaino decision may mean that
Microsoft _ and all employers in the Western states covered by the
9th Circuit Court of Appeals _ must give the same benefits to past,
present and future temporary workers that conventional employees
receive, including employer-matching 401(k) plans and
employer-funded health insurance, said David Stobaugh, one of the
attorneys who brought the class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter, Microsoft will have a hard time saying
people who are employees for the purpose of stock-plan eligibility,
as the court here has said they are, are not employees for other
purposes,'' said Stephen Strong, a colleague of Stobaugh in the
Seattle law firm of Bendich, Stobaugh &AMP; Strong, P.C.
</P>
<P>
   And the ruling _ unless overturned by the full appellate court
or the U.S. Supreme Court _ poses much broader concerns for
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a significant ruling because it cuts across the industry
and cuts across business,'' said Rob Enderle, an analyst with Giga
Group of Santa Clara, Calif. ``Employers are going to have to
rethink how they classify employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft hadn't received the opinion Wednesday and spokesman
Dan Leach said he couldn't comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   But Enderle estimated that the financial damages to Microsoft
from the decision might be between $15 million and $20 million. He
also said the ruling, which came down after the stock market closed
Wednesday, might also dent Microsoft's stock price today. Microsoft
stock rose five-eighths on Wednesday to close at 80 and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Punishing as a $20 million hit might sound, Microsoft likely can
absorb it. The mammoth software maker has $22 billion in cash on
hand and $2 billion more flows into its coffers every three months.
</P>
<P>
   The class of workers covered in the decision includes temporary
workers and independent contractors who worked 20 hours per week or
more for at least five months over the course of a year, any time
after the end of 1986, Stobaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Former temporary workers at Microsoft who think they're members
of the eligible class can print out forms from a Web site,
www.bs-s.com, to submit a claim.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft currently has 5,500 to 6,500 temporary workers. It
says contingent workers help it affordably expand and contract its
work force when starting and finishing large software projects.
These workers are employees of temporary agencies, not Microsoft,
so they don't receive all the benefits Microsoft employees do,
though they frequently earn higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what remedy former workers will receive hasn't been
determined. The federal court said they should receive the value of
the stock as if they had bought it at the time they first could
have and then held it for one year. Stobaugh and Strong have argued
that the proper holding duration is the average holding period of
people in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Temp workers on Wednesday expressed jubilation over the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding! Oh, wow! I think it's wonderful _ but I bet
temporary agencies will cut back on their wages now,'' said
Charlotte Quinn of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a great victory'' said Marcus Courtney, a
co-founder of WashTech, a union representing computer-industry
technical workers, ``It's not everything we wanted, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
