A5218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-     05-13 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)  
 TENTATIVE ACCORD REACHED ON EMERGENCY MILITARY SPENDING BILL  (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ignoring their leaders' wishes to hold the spending
down, congressional negotiators tentatively agreed on Wednesday to
spend $11.7 billion in emergency money to finance the fighting in
Yugoslavia and a host of Pentagon programs.
</P>
<P>
   A House-Senate conference committee cut deals past midnight in a
game of political poker that began with President Clinton's bid for
$6 billion for the bombing in the Balkans. After two days of
intense haggling, they had not begun to fight over how to pay for
the emergency bill. Nor had they rid it of a myriad of
multimillion-dollar Senate amendments and riders favoring special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Senators sought hundreds of millions for mining, gas, oil,
fishing and other business interests, not everyone's definition of
an emergency, as some Democrats pointed out. Political
conservatives remained furious that most of the money would come
out of the social security surplus. Democrats trying to add
billions for farm aid and school safety programs were voted down as
midnight neared.
</P>
<P>
   Other emergency spending measures for Central American and
Caribbean countries struck last year by hurricanes seemed likely to
grow to include close to $1 billion for the victims of last week's
Midwest tornadoes and American farmers crippled by falling food
prices. That would bring the emergency package to more than $13
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The chief negotiators, Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska and Rep. C.W.
(Bill) Young of Florida, both Appropriations Committee chairmen,
rejected pleas from the majority leader, Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, and the House speaker, Rep. Dennis Hastert of
Illinois, to hold the military spending down to $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and Rep. Jerry Lewis, the head of the House Defense
Appropriations Subcommittee, disagreed on the meaning of the $11
billion figure sought by the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven billion is a ceiling, not a floor,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis responded: ``It was a floor.''
</P>
<P>
   That set the tone for the conference, which veered on Wednesday
from deadly serious to nearly madcap.
</P>
<P>
   Proceedings halted for nearly an hour as Stevens and his fellow
Alaska Republican, Sen. Frank Murkowski, argued for a measure aimed
at helping commercial fishermen ply the wilderness of Glacier Bay
National Park. Conference members stared into space and up to the
heavens as that debate ground on. The measure was opposed by the
House members.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens succeeded in inserting $3 million for commercial
reindeer herders, ``my Santa Claus amendment,'' he called it.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments ground on over another amendment, which would let
natural-gas producers avoid repaying $235 million in penalties and
interest they owe to overcharged consumers in 23 states, ``a
straight special-interests versus public-interest issue,'' said
Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The conferees were working on a deal to kill the natural gas
amendment if House negotiators agreed to restore $150 million they
planned to cut from a program to store 50 tons of Russian
weapons-grade plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   Some members wondered allowed what such provisions were doing in
an emergency spending bill aimed at financing NATO's air war. ``The
question of whether it's a emergency or not is in the eye of the
beholder,'' sighed Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Well after midnight, Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., sought $175
million to provide up to $1 billion in loan guarantees for steel
and iron-ore industies.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and Young, the chief appropriators, agreed on $11.7
billion, about $5.7 billion more than Clinton requested for NATO
operations in Kosovo. They added $2.25 billion for military
operations and maintenance, $1.84 billion for a military pay
increase, $300 million for aircraft, $475 million for conbstruction
at overseas bases, $250 million for missiles and munitions, $200
million for the Coast Guard and $100 million for military
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   They also agreed to spend $819 million for war refugees from
Kosovo, far more than the White House sought.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest stumbling blocks lay ahead. Moderates still
must convince converatives that they should pay for the package
with money from the Social Security surplus, rather than cutting
domestic programs. House members had to keep twisting senators'
arms to convince them that they should drop the amendments and
riders benefitting home states and pet interests.
</P>
<P>
   Unless that happened, Obey said, the bill would resemble ``not a
Christmas tree, but a Christmas tree farm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
