<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ WOWS MARINERS WITH 15-K OUTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ken Griffey Jr. thought back to Randy Johnson. David
Segui couldn't make any comparisons. Edgar Martinez remembered last
April 11 ... the last time the Mariners faced the best pitcher on
the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez humbled some of baseball's best hitters Wednesday
night, striking out 15 Mariners over eight innings in a 9-2 win for
the Boston Red Sox. The Fenway Park crowd of 28,177 chanted
``Pe-DRO! Pe-DRO!'' throughout the night, and hung as many ``K''
cards as they had the last time Martinez pitched.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander is now 7-1, with an earned-run average of 1.81,
and he's making a fine case to start the All-Star Game in his home
park. He has at least 10 strikeouts in six straight starts, the
first pitcher to do that since ... the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to go back to Randy,'' said Griffey, when asked of
the last time he'd seen such dominance. ``He's just got everything
out there. You just go up there swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   And often, you go down swinging. Griffey struck out three times,
as did Jay Buhner. Every starting Mariner but John Mabry struck out
at least once. David Bell hit his career-high 11th home run, but
only three others got hits.
</P>
<P>
   No Mariner had more experience against Martinez than leadoff man
Brian Hunter. But familiarity didn't help him; Hunter fanned twice
and now is 5 for 28 lifetime off Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pumped up at the start of a game, and he's throwing
hard,'' said Hunter. ``It felt like he was throwing about 100 miles
per hour early in the game. He's a real smart pitcher, because
he'll use his fastball more early in the game, then later, when
you're gearing up for it, he'll throw his breaking ball for a
strike. He just keeps you guessing. After one strike, you almost
have to go into the two-strike (approach), and it shouldn't have to
be like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez was most concerned with Edgar Martinez, whom he
retired on a strikeout and fly out after walking him his first
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Junior, I just make my pitches and I hope I get away
with them,'' Martinez said. ``You have to respect him. But you know
what? To be honest, you have to be more careful with Edgar
Martinez, even more than Griffey. Griffey's going to get you,
there's no doubt, but Martinez is going to get two hits. And if
not, you have to thank God 30-hundred times.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar welcomed the challenge, even if he's still seeking his
first hit off Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to face him, because he's one of the best,'' said the
Mariners' designated hitter. ``And the way he's pitching right now,
he is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui was undaunted. Before the game, he told Martinez, a former
Montreal teammate, that he was going to get some hits off him.
Segui did double, but Martinez struck him out twice. Never shy
about displaying his frustrations after strikeouts, Segui was tame
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, he said, is the best pitcher he's ever seen. And his
``Bugs Bunny'' change-up, he added, is the ``filthiest'' change-up
he's ever tried to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never laughed after striking out before, but he made me
laugh,'' Segui said. ``I struck out on a pitch that was closer to
Jay in the on-deck circle than it was to me. I looked out, and
Pedro was laughing. Usually I would throw a bat at the pitcher if
he did that, but he's one of those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of my best friends in baseball, but it would be nice
to see him let me get a hit once in a while. Cory (Segui's son)
needs to eat, too. But he's worth every nickel.''
</P>
<P>
   With a contract that averages $12.5 million annually, Martinez
makes about as much as the entire healthy Mariner staff. Two
rookies, Mac Suzuki (0-2) and John Halama, walked seven Red Sox
last night, and hit another.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners return home having walked 55 over eight games on a
3-5 road trip. Twice Wednesday night, they walked little-known
Brian Daubach to load the bases for Nomar Garciaparra. It was
hauntingly familiar to Monday's game, when Garciaparra hit one
grand slam after a hit-by-pitch and another after a walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox shortstop had four hits and drove in three runs last
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Garciaparra wants to keep us in town,'' said M's
manager Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't mind pitchers giving up runs,'' he said. ``You don't
mind it. It's going to happen. But, boy, get hit doing it. I can
live with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their careers, it's not mine. I can tell you that. Their
careers, not mine.''
</P>
<P>
   When Halama walked two in the ninth, leading to three Boston
runs, it pushed his ERA to 5.14. In perhaps the most telling
statistic on the staff-wide struggles, only one Mariners pitcher,
reliever Jose Paniagua, has an ERA below 5.00.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
