<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-RIDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S COURAGE, GRIT RIDE HIGH ATOP HORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDI HUNT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ For many people, mounting a 1,000-pound show
horse would not be easy under the best of circumstances. Imagine
trying to do it paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Margo O'Callaghan, who faithfully climbs aboard a horse
three times a week without the use of the right side of her body,
paralyzed from a series of debilitating strokes more than 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'd sort of like to refine my scramble into the
saddle,'' she jokes.
</P>
<P>
   She climbs a kitchen stepladder, then sort of hurls her 90-pound
frame across the back of the horse. Once there, her grin turns into
an infectious laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``But since I can't use my right arm or leg, this will have to
do for the time being,'' she says. ``At least I'm up and ready to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed she is, trainer Joanna Fowler of Redmond, Wash., says.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than ready, all the time,'' Fowler says. ``She's a real
pro who takes very seriously the work we've been doing to get her
ready for a national competition next month.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan, who lives in Seattle with her sister, is training
for the U.S. Equestrian Team's Gladstone Festival of Champions in
New Jersey June 23-27. She'll compete in the Bradshaw Challenge, a
four-day competition involving four teams made up of six
able-bodied and one disabled rider.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said the prestigious event showcases some of the
country's top riders in seven equestrian events and serves as a
qualifier for national and world championships.
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan was invited based on past competitions, including
the CALNET (California Network for Therapeutic Riding) National
Championship. She was the 1998 Champion of that event.
</P>
<P>
   Her ultimate goal: to qualify for the U.S. Paralympic Equestrian
team, which will compete in Sydney, Australia, next year.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler has no doubt O'Callaghan can qualify, even though she's
classified as the most severely disabled competitor among those
invited to participate at next month's Gladstone Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know Margo,'' Fowler says. ``She's an incredibly
determined competitor and demanding rider who doesn't like to lose.
Look at how focused she is right now on what she's doing. She never
breaks that focus; she always gives every ride her all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Margo wants something and she wants to win a place on the
team very, very much, I don't believe anything can stop her, not
even on a borrowed horse, which is what all the disabled riders
have to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandi Fukumoto, O'Callaghan's close friend and riding partner,
said O'Callaghan is a great inspiration to everyone who sees her
riding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say `I can't do that' when you have Margo there,
showing you she can do it even with disabilities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler agrees. She has about 50 young people taking lessons at
her stable, and they worship O'Callaghan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rush to help her out if they see she needs it. But she
helps them, too. Being around her shows them people with
disabilities can do anything an able-bodied rider can do,'' Fowler
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her courage is another lesson they won't forget. They see her
fall off a horse, bounce right back up and continue her training as
if nothing has happened. She doesn't baby herself one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fukumoto wonders if she would have O'Callaghan's determination
and courage under similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope if anything happens to me physically, Margo will
be around to kick my behind and help me get my life back like she
has hers,'' she says. ``It hasn't been easy for her, but you'd
never know it sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fowler had to use one word to describe O'Callaghan, it would
be intrepid. ``She's amazing, fun to train, but most of all,
intrepid.''
</P>
<P>
   The skies open up, drenching horse and rider. Fowler nods toward
them. ``See what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan, 53, wasn't always the happy, upbeat woman who
laughs joyously as she completes her workout.
</P>
<P>
   When she had her strokes at age 29, she withdrew from the world
around her, sister Liz O'Callaghan recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't interested in going anywhere or doing anything,''
her sister remembers. ``She just sat around or went to her physical
therapy. It wasn't much of a life.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan might still be stuck inside, doing nothing, if it
hadn't been for her physician, Dr. Jean Nokes, who persuaded her to
try the Little Bit Therapeutic Riding Center in Woodinville, Wash.
The non-profit organization teaches people with disabilities to
ride horses.
</P>
<P>
   That was 20 years ago, and O'Callaghan hasn't slowed down since.
She still rides at Little Bit once a week, and added dressage
training with Fowler two times weekly five years ago, Fukumoto
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was and still am in awe of Margo and what she can do on a
horse, '' Fukumoto says. ``Her riding is incredible, considering
that riders usually control their horses with their legs. I just
don't know how she does it with one leg and one arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``And her balance is superb.... I don't know how she did that,
considering her condition at first. All I know is she's in complete
control all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan competes in dressage, an event that requires the
rider and horse to complete certain moves in perfect harmony. If it
were compared to ice skating, dressage would be the compulsory
figures, Fowler explains. The second phase of dressage is a
free-style routine set to music, called the Musical Kur.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where we choreograph moves that fit music chosen by
the rider,'' Fowler says. ``Margo picked `Can-Can' and `Fiddler on
the Roof,''' really delightful music, but requiring a lot of
intricate moves. She's already performing the whole routine without
missing any of the moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Fukumoto is so committed to her friend's success she is
collecting donations to cover O'Callaghan's expenses in the 1999
show season. An account has been set up in O'Callaghan's name at
ACORD, a non-profit organization; Fukumoto said people can call her
at 206-932-1112 for information.
</P>
<P>
   Fukumoto will pay her own expenses to New Jersey so she can
serve as support staff for O'Callaghan and the trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't miss it for the world,'' Fukumoto said. ``She's my
hero.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
