<SLUG> BC-NY-BOMB-THREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB THREAT AT UPSTATE SCHOOL FORCES OUT LIEUTENANT GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue was escorted out of an upstate high school
on Wednesday afternoon after a bomb threat interrupted a discussion
that she was having with students about the issue of school
violence. The 1,900 students at Schenectady High School, however,
were not evacuated while the building was searched.
</P>
<P>
   The Schenectady schools superintendent, Raymond Colucciello,
said security procedures have been changed in the wake of incidents
like the 1998 shooting in Jonesboro, Ark., in which false alarms
were used to lure students outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't always leave,'' he said, explaining the decision not
to evacuate the students. ``The recent guidelines say if you go
outside, you may be putting them in harm's way.'
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor's chief of staff, Eileen Long, said
school officials decided to call off the visit, and they escorted
Ms. Donohue and another member of the task force, Mayor Jerry
Jennings of Albany, from the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety concerns for the students and the faculty members
that were in that school were the most important,'' Ms. Long said.
``We did not want to hamper their ability to implement their
procedures regarding school security.''
</P>
<P>
   Colucciello said school officials did not want Ms. Donohue in
the way. ``Collectively, the governor's staff and our staff decided
to end the interview,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Colucciello said a search by school and law enforcement
officials quickly determined that the threat was a hoax. He said
the caller seemed to be an older woman, not a student, who did not
know the school well.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Donohue is the chairwoman of a state task force on school
violence and had been meeting with about 25 students in the school
library to discuss the issue. In recent weeks, she has been
visiting schools across the state. She was about midway through the
conversation, which included a discussion of bomb-scare procedures,
when the threat came in by telephone shortly before 1 p.m.,
Colucciello said.
</P>
<P>
   The task force was formed several weeks before the Littleton,
Colo., killings pushed school violence issues to the forefront of
national attention. Ms. Donohue's visit to Schenectady was widely
publicized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
