<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS CRUSH HEAT, 97-73 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was as if Latrell Sprewell had thrown a match down
on the court just before the half and a flame quickly spread
throughout the building. By the middle of the third quarter, the
crowd looked on fire as they twirled their orange towels over their
heads like helicopter blades and nearly lifted Madison Square
Garden off its foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Elephants could fly on Wednesday night during the New
York Knicks' inconceivable 32-2 run that was stoked by Sprewell in
the second quarter, carried on by an assortment of his teammates
into a wild third and left a crestfallen Pat Riley staring into the
stands long before the final buzzer sounded to end his team's
misery.
</P>
<P>
   His Heat, the top-seeded team in the Eastern Conference, is one
game from elimination after the Knicks grabbed a 2-1 lead in this
three-of-five-game series with an emphatic 97-73 victory in Game 3.
The Knicks can advance to the second round by winning Game 4 on
Friday night at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   An inspired Sprewell helped put them in their enviable position
by stepping onto the floor in the middle of a somewhat flat start
by the Knicks and swiping a pass by the Heat's Tim Hardaway 12
seconds into his appearance. By the time he released a silky
3-pointer to give the Knicks a lead with 3 minutes second left in
the second quarter _ a lead they would not relinquish _ Sprewell
had the place jumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a way of getting you pumped up,'' said Sprewell, who
scored a game-high 20 points and fed off the crowd's fever. ``The
energy was as high as I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   This night was not just about Sprewell's love affair with the
crowd. It was about the pained Patrick Ewing pushing forward on his
aching left Achilles' tendon to grab 8 rebounds and score 15 points
on the night. It was about a Allan Houston fighting off flu
symptoms that left him alternating a diet of Advil and bottled
water and coming up with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think emotion carried me,'' Houston said. ``I feel
great. We won. So I feel tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of reason. This nearly seamless production by
the Knicks struck an uncanny resemblance to the way the Knicks
dominated the Heat in Game 1. Once again, Houston and Sprewell
found a groove together. Once again, the Knicks led by as many as
30 points in the game. Once again, Miami was unthinkably out of
sync from the perimeter, missing its first 17 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just sort of settled for those, you know,'' Riley said.
``The shot was there, but it wasn't going in for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The more they missed, the more long rebounds ended up in the
hands of players like Chris Childs, who pushed the Knicks toward
easy baskets in transition. Childs was at the root of Hardaway's
meltdown, too. Once again, Hardaway was lost in territory that used
to be his. He was 0 for 5 from 3-point range and was so frustrated
he didn't stick around to see the end. With 8:45 left in a game
that had been put away, Hardaway felt he was fouled by Childs. He
argued, cursed and ranted some more at the official Mike Mathis.
And for that, he was mercifully ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to pull him away from there because we needed him
in the game,'' said Alonzo Mourning, who scored a team-high 18
points for Miami. ``I thought Mike was wrong. He was kind of quick
to do that. But I mean, it's over with.''
</P>
<P>
   The afterglow has a 48-hour limit for the Knicks. They know what
it's like to hit the Heat with a blowout, just as they did in Game
1, and have the favor returned the next time, as in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go back and watch Game 2,'' Houston said. ``And I
want to see what we did wrong in that game and learn from it.
Hopefully, we can learn from it. I know the next one is going to be
a war.''
</P>
<P>
   That word ``war'' keeps getting bandied about when these two
teams are involved. But through three games, the finishes have not
been tense, not even close. In each game, there has been a big run
to decide the game. This one was no different.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' 32-2 run began with a jumper by Ewing with 3:34 left
in the first half and ended when Jamal Mashburn hit only the second
field goal in a 12-minute span on a jumper with 4:15 left in the
third. In between, the Knicks dived for every loose ball and
harassed the Heat with their defense.
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing to see a rabid Marcus Camby defying his spindly
frame by beating the rugged P.J. Brown to rebounds. It was another
to watch Ewing, playing with every joint of his 36-year-old body in
need of ice, flying on the floor for a loose ball in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of effort was the opposite of the lethargic start that
left the well-oiled Heat up, 11-4, in the opening four minutes of
the game. A couple of minutes later, Sprewell arrived to strike a
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I attribute a lot of this to the crowd,'' Sprewell said.
``They had me pumped. It was just great, just a lot of fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
