<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5235 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-13 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Astros can't lose anybody else. Otherwise, Jose Lima will have
to find a bigger cap.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the level of his pitching acumen, he may have to
anyhow. His head swells a little bit every fifth day. Could you
picture Lima clutching the Cy Young Award?
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, try. Lima, the Astros' resident oddfellow _ even in a
clubhouse that includes Derek Bell _ is having a year that should
distinguish him from the pack, as if that were necessary. On
quirks, silly faces and animated gestures, he stands apart. A
greater eccentric you will be hard-pressed to find.
</P>
<P>
   Or, at present, a tougher pitcher to hit. He beat the Pirates
6-2 Wednesday night for his sixth consecutive victory after taking
the mound wearing a hat upon which he had scrawled the numbers of
all his fallen comrades. There was an 18 for countryman Moises
Alou, a 12 for Ricky Gutierrez, a 21 for Mitch Meluskey, a 19 for
Doug Henry and a 25 for Jose Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Tom McCraw's 16 will be there, too, when Lima makes his next
start Tuesday in Los Angeles. The Astros' hitting coach will be
taking a leave of absence after Sunday's game to begin treatments
for his recently diagnosed prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' Lima said. ``Tom's my boy. But his situation is
different, more serious. He has cancer. I pray for him. I hope God
takes care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers serve to remind Lima that, because his ballclub is
playing short-handed, he ``must work that much harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima wears his knickers high and his heart on his sleeve. The
stronger he pitches, it seems, the more animated he gets. And he's
pitching beautifully right now, good enough at the puzzled Pirates'
expense to have joined the Phillies' Curt Schilling as the National
League's first six-game winners.
</P>
<P>
   He earned the same distinction a year ago. That's right. He was
also 6-1 at the outset last season en route to the breakthrough
16-8 finish that forewarned of his potential to be a serious,
reliable, every-fifth-day starter. There will be no more comical
(bullpen) relief in Jose's foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   This guy is good. Funny, too.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe his reaction to Ed Sprague's left-field foul
ball in the sixth inning that missed becoming a monster three-run
homer by mere feet, Lima said: ``I go AHHHHHH! I blow it (foul). I
say, `God, God, please, please.' No way I hang a pitch like that
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima's evolution from erratic thrower to polished pitcher has to
do with a change in his animal instincts, suggests manager Larry
Dierker. Two years ago, when Lima was in the process of going 1-6
doing mostly garbage-time middle relief, Dierker sat him down and
spoke to him of ``the way of the dog and the way of the cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Lima was a dog _ in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dog challenges every hitter, strength against strength,''
Dierker said, ``and you're going to lose a lot of those
dogfights.''
</P>
<P>
   Re: Lima vs. Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   The cat, of course, is stealthier and sneakier. He ambushes the
hitter, which is what Lima has learned to do, although he said of
Dierker's dog/cat parable: ``I remember he said that to me, but I
don't understand it. Tell it to me again, so I can comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, never mind, Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a more sophisticated pitcher now,'' Dierker said.
``He's very good at challenging hitters but also at being careful
when he needs to be. He knows when it's OK to come after a guy and
when to throw the ball out of the zone. He's finally figuring
things out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker called Lima's walking Jason Kendall earlier in the sixth
after Kevin Young's double ``semi-intentional, a sign of his new
maturity. He's no longer afraid to put a man on.''
</P>
<P>
   Maturity? One Pirate begged to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``That jumping-around (stuff) gets to you,'' Pittsburgh's Al
Martin said. But Martin added: ``He's definitely a tough pitcher.
His changeup is one of the best in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima hasn't had a truly bad outing yet. His lone loss, in his
first start April 8, still saw him go eight innings, giving up just
two earned runs and striking out seven. At Chicago on April 20, he
lasted only five innings but earned a win anyway because the Astros
scored 10 runs behind him.
</P>
<P>
   This night, his mates got him four in the sixth and two more in
the seventh, making moot the quick run he gave up in the first when
Martin led off with a first-pitch triple and the second hitter,
Mike Benjamin, singled Martin home.
</P>
<P>
   Lima would go eight innings, losing his chance for a second
consecutive complete game only because, with a day off today,
Dierker thought Scott Elarton needed some action. The Astros' thin
pen is actually overrested at present.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, in part, to Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal,'' he said, ``is to be No. 1. With more hard work,
someday I can be No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he'll paint it on his cap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
