<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BASS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASS TOURNAMENT TO BENEFIT ABUSED CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB WHEAT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CASTAIC, Calif. _ Joan Flynn knows how much of a difference fishing
can make in a child's life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Flynn adopted an 8-year-old boy she met two years
earlier at Royal Family Kids Camp, a Costa Mesa summer retreat for
abused, abandoned and neglected children. Today the camp is one of
two charities that benefit from her work in bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to camp is one of the few happy moments for these kids
(age 7 to 11) in their young lives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn is helping coordinate the seventh annual Bassing for
Abused Kids team-fishing tournament Saturday at Castaic Lagoon.
Proceeds benefit the camp and Santa Clarita's First Nurturing
Touch, which assists in the training of foster families. To
encourage family participation, a free trout derby for children is
also staged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many top pros who fish the tournament, but we also
have a lot of great `buddy teams' made up of father-son,
mother-daughter, even mother-in-law and son-in-law combinations,''
Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Manifold, Royal Family Kids Camp director, said the money
raised from Bassing for Abused Kids is crucial to his budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at least a third of our budget, and it comes down
literally to how many kids can go,'' Manifold said. ``We were
founded nationally here, but this tournament has allowed us to have
58 camps in 24 states going this summer. So think of the dramatic
impact anglers can have on (helping) hurting kids, just by doing
what they love doing best _ fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many campers don't have even bare essentials _ socks, shoes,
toothbrush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide that for them,'' Flynn said, ``as well as a
`birthday party' day for all 110 kids because a lot of times
they've never had anyone to even acknowledge it in the past. Can
you imagine being a kid and never having a birthday party? Or even
(not) getting a card, much less a present?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never more than two campers to one counselor because
these children need special attention. Sometimes people think
abused kids are somebody else's problem.... We provide love and
change to break the cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Tournament director Ron Cervenka donates his time and the time
of his staff; he figures it's the least they can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only tournament me and my staff does for nothing
each year, and that's because we know the money really goes to
directly help these kids,'' said Cervenka, a Burbank homicide and
robbery detective from Saugus who also directs the Southern
California division of the Western Outdoors News Bass
team-tournament circuit. ``Bass fishing has been really good to me,
so it's only right that I can give something back.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn notes that every year the event has grown, with 78 teams
vying for the $1,000 top prize and some 650 children enjoying the
derby last April, when $20,000 was raised for Southland children.
The event was moved to May this year _ even though April is
National Child Abuse Month _ because of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU'RE GOING . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Bassing for Abused Kids charity event is Saturday at Castaic
Lake Recreational Area. Take the Golden State Freeway (5) north,
exit at Lake Hughes Road and turn right. Turn left on Ridge Route
Road and right into the park.
</P>
<P>
   Parking is $6 per vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   A free trout derby for those 15 and younger is from 9 a.m. to 4
p.m. at the lower lake _ Castaic Lagoon. Other activities include
face-painting, games for children and a charity raffle ($2 per
ticket). The grand prize a 1999 Ford Ranger pickup. Raffle tickets
can be purchased in advance at the Magic Ford dealership at the
Valencia Auto Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The bass-fishing team tournament begins at sunup at the upper
lake's west ramp. Entry is $120 a team; registration is from 6 p.m.
to 10 p.m. Friday and again from 4 a.m. to 5:30 a.m. Saturday at
the launch site.
</P>
<P>
   Trophies are awarded to the top three placers, to the big-fish
winner (a $20 optional entry) and to the top man/woman and
child/adult combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Event information: (805) 521-1319 or (714) 540-6690. Park
information: (805) 257-4050. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
