<HEADER>
A5240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      05-13 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FIREWORKS AS ANGELS SHUT OUT YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hostilities were expected at Yankee Stadium Wednesday
night, one night after some nastiness between the New York Yankees'
Derek Jeter and Anaheim's Troy Percival. Instead, there was nothing
but brilliant pitching, and ultimately, frustration for David Cone
and the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley, the Angels' ace, carried a 5.92 earned run average
into the game, but pitching against the Yankees brings out the best
in him. He struck out 11 in eight innings and allowed just three
hits in a 1-0 decision over Cone, before a crowd of 23,540.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim run came in the seventh inning, and it was the
bottom of the Angels' order that finally got to Cone. Orlando
Palmeiro, the No. 7 hitter, worked a leadoff walk. Charlie O'Brien
tried and failed three times to bunt, a strikeout, but then the
right-handed hitting Andy Sheets leaned over the plate to stroke a
line drive into the right-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro got a terrific jump off first base and by the time Paul
O'Neill recovered the ball and relayed it back to the infield,
Palmeiro was across the plate and Sheets was standing on third.
Jeter, standing near first base, dropped his head in disgust, and
Cone, backing up home, kicked at the dirt slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Cone kept the Angels from scoring any more runs, lobbying loudly
to the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre to remain in the game before
retiring Mo Vaughn on an inning-ending pop out. But one run was one
too many and Cone (4-1) suffered his first loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Finley improved his season record to 2-3 and went to 16-8
against the Yankees for his career. Percival earned the save for
the second straight night, striking out Chili Davis and Tino
Martinez in a quiet ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   After Percival hit Jeter with a fastball in the ninth inning of
Tuesday's game, an overnight of reflection did nothing to change
opinions. Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager, was still
convinced Wednesday that Percival nailed Jeter on purpose, and
Percival maintained that the Yankees were ridiculous to think he
would intentionally create a situation in which O'Neill and Bernie
Williams would get to bat with a chance to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   The ill feelings were there before Wednesday night's game, and
the umpires did not attempt any pre-emptive actions to curtail a
possible brushback battle. When Terry Collins, the Anaheim manager,
strolled to the plate to exchange lineup cards with the Yankees
coach Chris Chambliss, the plate umpire, Dan Morrison, quietly
sorted out the copies and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Only Cone knows if he went to the mound intending to retaliate.
Only Cone knows if he was waiting for the proper circumstances to
plunk somebody: two out and no one on base and some noteworthy
Angel at the plate, whether it be Darrin Erstad or Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone and Finley quickly locked into a duel and there really
was no margin for error or retaliation. Every runner represented
the potential lead run; the outcome could have turned with any
batter.
</P>
<P>
   Most American League umpires are calling a narrowed version of
the strike zone, without fringe benefits: You must throw it over
the plate to get a strike. But Morrison was giving both pitchers a
bit extra off the corners, and Finley and Cone seized on this
spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, armed with a live fastball and reacting jauntily on close
pitches, threw strikes consistently and only reached two-ball,
no-strike counts once in the first 19 batters he faced. The
left-handed Finley was both predictable and unhittable. He threw
fastballs to get ahead in the count, and then, almost without
exception, he finished off the Yankee batters with his
split-fingered fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had their chances against Finley. Shane Spencer led
off the third inning with a single to left. Scott Brosius struck
out, but Troy Glaus, the third baseman, threw the ball away on Joe
Girardi's grounder, and the Yankees had first and second and one
out. Finley threw a wild pitch to advance the runners before
striking out Chuck Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   With Jeter due to bat, O'Brien went to the mound to mull over
the situation. Jeter is among the game's hottest hitters, first
base was open, and the slumping and discouraged O'Neill was on
deck.
</P>
<P>
   Finley pitched to Jeter carefully, but once he got two strikes,
Finley threw a splitter that Jeter chased unsuccessfully; the ball
went in the dirt near home plate, O'Brien lost sight of it and
Jeter hustled to first. Bases loaded for O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neill struck out, Finley's fourth strikeout of the inning,
tying a major league record. O'Neill is 0 for 14 with runners in
scoring position since May 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
