<HEADLINE>
DON'T BLAME DAFOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ It was not his fault. The Bruins Wednesday night lost
a playoff game that they should have won, but no one was blaming
goalie Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   The B's thoroughly outplayed the Sabres for two periods. Dafoe
faced only seven shots in the first 40 minutes, and Boston led,
2-1. But the Sabres outshot the Bruins, 18-7, in the third and won,
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   It was not right. This is upstate New York. You do not expect to
get your wallet picked in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about not staying back,'' Dafoe said. ``But we
didn't practice what we preached. A one-goal lead in the Stanley
Cup playoffs after two periods has got to be enough. But we sat
back and totally let them come at us. Why it happened, I don't
know. They outshot us, 14-1, at the start of the third, and that's
not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey guys don't point fingers. An NHL locker room has no Wade
Boggs saying, ``Hey, I got my three hits.'' In a league largely
populated by Canadian farm boys, Eastern Europeans, Scandinavians,
and snow-belt Americans, there is no room for the blame game. Dafoe
knew he outplayed the great Dominik Hasek in Game 3, but there was
no need for excuses or chest-thumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in pretty good shape,'' said the polite, sad-eyed
goalie. ``But for one reason or another . . . I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the Bruins felt there was reason for confidence after two
periods. The B's had the Sabres back on their heels (do skates have
heels?). Fans at Marine Midland Arena were booing the locals. The
game belonged to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly thought that,'' said Dafoe. ``We're a very good
team when we have a lead. Those first two periods were the best
periods we've played in the series. I was very confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe has carried the B's quite a few times this season, but he
was little more than an interested bystander when the Bruins
humbled the Sabres in periods one and two. Seven shots. Six saves.
One softie goal after a Ray Bourque penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the dreaded third. The B's went to the Patrick
Buchanan (conservative) game plan, and it backfired. Teams that
play to win usually win. Teams that play not to lose usually lose.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's Rhett Warrener tied it in the seventh minute of the
third period, and Dixon Ward put the hometown team ahead a couple
of minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seemed to lose one or two assignments, and they
capitalized,'' reasoned Boston coach Pat Burns. ``That second goal
changed everything. I knew when they got that second goal that the
whole momentum changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrener's goal was a second-chance effort. Dafoe saved the
defenseman's first shot but was unable to control the puck. ``I
made the save with my stick, but it went straight back out to
him,'' said Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   These Bruins are young. Most of them had never won a playoff
series before beating Carolina in the first round of these
playoffs. Dafoe had never won a series before he beat the
Hurricanes, and he remembers that Boston trailed, 2-1, before
winning the final three games of that series. The experience serves
them well now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking at this as a panic situation,'' said the
goalie. ``If we win Friday, we've accomplished what we set out to
do here.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be important to put Game 3 in the rear view mirror. All
the B's went to bed Wednesday night knowing that they gave one
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``A one-goal lead after two periods in the Stanley Cup playoffs
has got to be enough,'' said Dafoe. ``But for one reason or another
_ I really don't know _ we sat back and they totally came at us. We
shouldn't be doing that at this point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stop the puck, that's all. It's the one thing I do. But
this is not the way this should have gone.''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have more experience than some of our younger players,''
said Burns. ``What we have to do is convince the younger guys that
it'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe may need a little convincing. He knows he played well
enough to win Wednesday night. He made more saves and more
difficult saves than the indomitable Dominik. But his team lost the
game, a game it should have won.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
