<HEADLINE>
SONICS COULD BE SEEKING SWEETER ARENA DEAL THROUGH WNBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ One thing you hate to hear is that maybe the
SuperSonics would use Seattle's love of women's basketball as a way
of gaining more control of KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   A theory of that sort was floated in city hall this week _ after
the mayor got a letter from the Sonics ownership arm, The Ackerley
Group, asking for, among other things, dates for WNBA games and the
ability to book more events at the Seattle Center venue.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the mayor's office released a letter it sent back to
the Sonics outlining lease concessions the city would grant the
Sonics for WNBA games, should the Sonics be awarded one of four
expansion franchises for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Mayor Paul Schell told public radio listeners he and
city council members were not comfortable giving the Sonics extra
dates, as requested.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet the Sonics, through their operating and ownership
groups, Full House and The Ackerley Group, were not amused that the
city had given the appearance of taking the offensive in these
negotiations over WNBA arena dates.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a city deal, per se. Bringing a WNBA team to Seattle
is the Sonics' call. The whole point of the WNBA was for NBA teams
to have summertime sports entertainment to help fill vacant arenas
during the NBA's offseason.
</P>
<P>
   It is a far cry from the grass-roots, girls-need-role-models-too
business model used by the now defunct American Basketball League,
which brought the Reign to play in front of a loyal and
not-so-small circle of fans in a more community-oriented fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But with the ABL gone, the only hope for pro women's hoops rests
with the NBA and its mega-corporate franchises. For women's hoops
fans, it is sort of like little sister meets Big Brother _ and
watch out.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lesson in how quickly the good feelings surrounding
women's pro basketball can be shredded in the corporate world of
big bucks sports entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   All but four of the existing 12 WNBA teams now own or control
their arenas. So the Sonics have been told by the league that it
would be good to find out exactly what kind of deal the Sonics can
get from the city, since a model for success in the WNBA is based
on arena control and revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics asked for the moon, according to city hall insiders.
</P>
<P>
   The city responded by offering the Sonics the stars.
</P>
<P>
   So now the city and the Sonics are dancing a dance that both
sides hope ends with a WNBA expansion team and no toes stepped
upon.
</P>
<P>
   However, the good-faith partnership was tested last week by a
newspaper editorial in which John Dresel, president of Full House
outlined ``an extraordinarily generous offer to the Seattle Center
and the city of Seattle'' by ``taking on the debt service ($7.5
million) and event-management responsibility for the building.''
</P>
<P>
   The city was not amused. Apparently, no one in City Hall or at
Seattle Center had at that time received a copy of this
``extraordinarily generous offer,'' and were offended when Full
House made a public plea for understanding and support on an issue
that had never reached formal negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Dresel said the mayor and city council had
``misunderstood'' Full House's latest proposal for extra KeyArena
dates. Dresel said Full House has abandoned any notion of obtaining
sweeping control of KeyArena and instead is seeking the ability to
``cross-promote WNBA dates using open dates'' that would give the
city added revenue, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (enhanced management of KeyArena) was an old deal. What
we are looking for is a win/win solution and getting on with the
business of getting a WNBA team here,'' Dresel said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the public posturing by Full House as late as last week
did leave city officials wondering what exactly the Sonics want in
their KeyArena arrangements _ and how far they will go to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Dresel's adamant disclaimer that Full House is no longer
seeking widespread control of KeyArena, a little paranoia on the
city's part is justified.
</P>
<P>
   In these days of big business sports, things like this happen
when governments partner up with sports teams. The local
authorities want control and taxpayer protection. The teams,
however _ which often control volatile emotional strings of their
sports-loving public _ often get the upper hand, since at any time
they can make threats, including packing up and moving.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Mariners have a new stadium that they will run.
It is why billionaire Paul Allen has a new football stadium ordered
for his Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone would like to think negotiations for a WNBA team
between Full House and the city can be done without a hitch. But
don't think for a minute these sweetheart deals for the M's and
Hawks _ completed after the Sonics signed their KeyArena deal with
the city five years ago _ did not make the Sonics guess this might
be the right time to go back to the well. It doesn't hurt that they
could use as collateral for concessions such a welcome thing as a
women's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
