<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINSSABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES BEAT BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Bruins are in this morning. They will downplay
it, talk about how it was only Game 3, that there is lots of time
left in this series that there are many chances, that they are only
down by one game. The fact is, it's very likely the Bruins will
look back on Wednesday night, a 3-2 defeat at Marine Midland Arena,
as the turning point in this Eastern Conference semifinal series,
as the one that got away, as, dare we say it, the one that was the
beginning of the end.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the Bruins were the better team for 40 minutes.
They employed a nearly perfect (and ultra-boring) game plan. They
suffocated the Sabres. Then, in the third, they allowed the Sabres
to come up for air and not only did they take a breath, they blew
the Bruins away.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Boston trails, 2-1, in the best-of-seven series
with Game 4 Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on us,'' said wing Steve Heinze. ``We can't have third
periods like that and expect to win. It was two different games.
Unfortunately we played three periods and not two because we were
the better team for two periods but they were just way better in
the third. We didn't put them away or have the killer instinct or
the eye of the tiger to put them away. When it slips away like
that, shame on us. You've got to have the killer instinct in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had a 2-1 lead heading into the final period but in a
span of less than three minutes, the Sabres closed the gap and took
the lead for good. Right wing Dixon Ward tallied the winner at 9:38
of the third. Center Michael Peca dished a pass to Vaclav Varada,
who centered the puck out in the slot for Ward. Ward one-timed it
past goalie Byron Dafoe and the Bruins couldn't recover.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins came out with a strong game plan, though it nearly
derailed before it got started. Just 10 seconds into the game, Ray
Bourque was whistled off for hooking, giving the Sabres a power
play that defenseman Jason Woolley converted at 1:37. The Sabres
were up, 1-0, and no one had even worked up a sweat for the Bruins
except coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like a hiccup, though, because the Bruins came
charging back on the power play. With Wayne Primeau serving a
holding-the-stick call against Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek, center
Joe Thornton dished a pass from below the right circle through the
crease. It caromed off Anson Carter and went right onto the stick
of Heinze, who banged in a quick shot at 8:47 for his third goal of
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' second goal came as a result of a fortuitous
long-range slapper by defenseman Dave Ellett that went off the left
knee of Hasek, momentarily stunning the goalie. Hasek went right
down to the ice and couldn't move. The Sabres tried to clear the
puck but Thornton corralled it and flung it down to Carter, who was
heading for the net. Carter tapped it into the empty net at 12:48.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was all Boston as the Bruins managed the most
boring, but convincing 20 minutes of defensive hockey they've
played in the series. They trapped, they clogged the neutral zone,
they kept the Buffalo forwards to the perimeter. They managed to
hold the Sabres to a measly four shots in the period and seven
through the first 40 minutes while generating 14 themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Then the wheels fell off. The momentum shifted dramatically in
the third, with the Sabres leaving the Bruins in the dust. At the
7:35 mark, Buffalo had more shots (10) than it had in the first two
periods combined and Boston had none. The Bruins' first shot on net
in the period came from Don Sweeney at 7:57.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't start working until the third period,'' said Buffalo
coach Lindy Ruff. ``They played a pretty smart game in the first
two periods and our lack of hustle allowed them to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rhett Warrener tied the game, 2-2, at 6:44 when he
swatted in his own rebound from the right circle. The Sabres gained
enormous energy from the score and kept coming like a tidal wave.
When Ward scored it was lights out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't finish,'' said Burns.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins hope this game won't be the one that finishes them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
