<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     05-13 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY'S HOMER SPARKS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Before the series began with the Chicago Cubs, the
Dodgers held a players-only meeting in which the message was to
watch each other's back.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi had everyone's back for most of the season. Todd
Hundley had Mondesi's back Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After Mondesi struck out in a crucial eighth-inning at-bat,
Hundley led off the ninth with a homer to tie the score.
Pinch-runner Tripp Cromer then scored on Rod Beck's wild pitch with
one out as the Dodgers rallied to stun the Cubs 3-2 in front of
40,007 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was the type of jolt the Dodgers needed heading into today's
day off and into their three-game series in St. Louis. Instead of
limping in after another abysmal homestand, the Dodgers have
momentum and have won their fourth series in five attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it had to do with Hundley's swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the key guys in this lineup, we need his power,''
Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield said of Hundley. ``Hopefully,
he can get in a rhythm, and so can some other guys, including
myself, and we can get something going.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time it appears the Dodgers have the makings of a streak,
something goes awry. Their eighth comeback win of the season was
also the first time since April 6 the Dodgers won a game in their
final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   About the only one who hasn't gone through a dry spell is
Mondesi. In the first two games of the series he hit four homers,
and the pieces were in place in the eighth for another momentous
occasion. However, with two runners on, one run already in and the
Cubs leading 2-1, Cubs reliever Scott Sanders struck out Mondesi to
preserve the lead, albeit momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   It was also another infamous undoing of Beck, the Cubs closer.
He's blown four of 11 save chances and dropped to 2-4. Dodgers
right-hander Jamie Arnold (2-0) pitched one scoreless inning of
relief for the win.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to protect a 2-1 lead for starter Kevin Tapani, who
pitched 72/3 innings, Beck's fourth pitch was a fastball Hundley
hit into the right-field seats to tie the score 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for my teammates, most for the guys in here, to
prove to them that I can hit and contribute offensively,'' Hundley
said. ``Mondesi's been carrying us basically all year. It's nice to
sneak on them (the Cubs). That's the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros followed Hundley's homer with a double down the
left-field line. Cromer pinch-ran, Beck intentionally walked Todd
Hollandsworth and Adrian Beltre moved the runners over a base with
a bunt.
</P>
<P>
   Beck was ahead of pinch-hitter Mark Grudzielanek 1-2, which
meant little when catcher Sandy Martinez couldn't handle a pitch
low and far outside. It allowed Cromer to score and give the
Dodgers the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a (very poor) fastball (to Hundley),'' said Beck, a
Grant High product. ``Right now I (really) suck. I'm angry and I'm
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's ninth-inning homer was a long-overdue moment for the
switch-hitting catcher who finally has his timing at the plate
after missing spring training and hitting a miserable .158 with two
homers and four RBI in April. This month Hundley is hitting .378
(14 for 37) with three homers and eight RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's maybe not doing the things you want to see him do (all
the time), but he's my guy,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``I feel real good for him. He wants it, and he'll get it. It's
going to be fun going to war with him this season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
