<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 03:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5266 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBRARY-BOY-SFCHRON &LR;      05-13 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBRARY-BOY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO LIBRARY DOES ABOUT-FACE ON `READING WIZARD' BOY  &HT;     By YUMI WILSON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An 11-year-old boy who wanted to dress up as the
Reading Wizard and introduce preschoolers to the joy of books at
his local San Francisco library soon will get his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown ordered library officials Wednesday to end a
``bureaucratic runaround'' and told them to ``immediately implement
a program'' in which John O'Connor can dress up, in a jester's hat
and black cape, and read to preschoolers at the Presidio library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our libraries are supposed to turn kids on, not turn them
off,'' said Brown, who took action on an official trip to
Washington, D.C., after learning in The Chronicle that library
bosses had brushed off John's idea. ``We should be rewarding young
people with creative ideas, not discouraging them.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the mayor has invited John to give his first reading at
City Hall for children from the nearby Tenderloin neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome all entrepreneurial volunteers in our city,
regardless of their age,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's cause was taken up by schools, community groups and
the media across the country Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the article in the paper, and I just thought the kid
was unique,'' said Steve Ridgeway, segment producer for the
``Tonight Show,'' who called a reporter in hopes of reaching
O'Connor. ``It's not every day when you find an 11-year-old doing
something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, staffers at the San Bernardino Sun
newspaper started a collection drive so they could buy books for
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, an ambitious and articulate sixth-grader at St.
Vincent de Paul School, said he was happy that his dream is coming
true. He was, however, a little surprised by the uproar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect this kind of attention,'' he said. ``It got on
the front page, and then this happened. It's just shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Michael O'Connor, applauded the city for helping his
son fulfill a dream to help others through reading. The elder
O'Connor gave special thanks to Supervisor Gavin Newsom and his
aide Michael Farrah, who agreed to help John make his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really appreciate the courtesy and respect that they've
shown my son,'' O'Connor said. ``They treated him like an
intelligent person, which he is. I think it's a great introduction
to the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   John came up with the idea to be a Reading Wizard two months ago
while talking to his mother, Shannon Bracht, about how he could
perform community service. Introducing kids to reading, he figured,
beat having them watching TV or playing video games all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But a staffer at the library told him, ``We don't do that kind
of thing.'' Other appeals were similarly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, he contacted Newsom's office, then wrote a
letter to the library.
</P>
<P>
   Library officials had planned to send letters to John to explain
that trained staffers were given the task of reading to
preschoolers and preparing ``an entire program for the event.''
</P>
<P>
   But before they could get the missives in the mail, the mayor
was preparing his press release.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was ``appalled that this has been going on for two months
and, a) it has not been brought to a resolution, or, b) to his
attention,'' said his spokeswoman, Kandace Bender.
</P>
<P>
   City Librarian Regina Minudri said Wednesday that the library
would, indeed, launch a program to give O'Connor and other youths
an opportunity to read to preschoolers. It will be called ``Kids
Read to Kids at the Library'' and become part of the summer reading
program for youths 10 to 16. Librarians will train John and others.
</P>
<P>
   At the steps outside Presidio library Wednesday, Minudri
explained that she never got a copy of John's letter until reading
about it in the paper. She also apologized to John if he ``felt he
was rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   But she stood by Sadako Kashiwagi, the children's librarian at
Presidio, who ``did what she was supposed to do when she declined
John's offer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a librarian who has been with the San Francisco
library for 10 years and has never received a complaint from the
public,'` Minudri said. ``In fact, she hosts a very popular
children's reading hour at the Presidio branch.''
</P>
<P>
   With that said, however, Minudri said it was time to take
O'Connor's idea to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good ideas often come from unexpected places, and we want to
thank John for his great idea to start a reading program for
children by children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John may be reading at a lot more places besides the library.
Since the story broke, he has gotten offers from local schools, the
Boys and Girls Club, Internet companies and others _ all asking him
to come read to youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Other readers just called to applaud John for standing up to
what they view as bad rules and too much bureaucracy, which they
say makes it tough for anyone to volunteer for good causes.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom said one caller had invoked the recent high school
killings in Colorado as a reason to look favorably upon ideas like
John's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prevention is better than a cure,'' the caller told Newsom.
``Things like this are a solution to Littleton-type massacres.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
