<P>
   &UR; WHO WAS THE GREATEST JOCK?: JORDAN, GRETZKY OR ELWAY &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW MARSHALL, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a game that you play in bars across America now, after
a few beers, and it takes a few beers for it to make much sense.
The game goes like this: who was the best, John Elway, Michael
Jordan or Wayne Gretzky?
</P>
<P>
   It is not a very smart game, and the conclusion usually depends
on whether you are an American football, basketball or hockey fan.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is pretty obvious, actually... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (1,050 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-GRETZKY-JORDAN-ELWAY-COMMENTARY-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AND THESE STORIES, MOVED TUESDAY (MAY 11)... &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `OF ALL THE EMBASSIES IN ALL THE CITIES...WE HAD TO HIT THAT
ONE' &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RUPERT CORNWELL, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ To misquote Humphrey Bogart: ``Of all the embassies in
all the cities in all the world, we had to hit that one'' _ the
mission in Belgrade of China, the country, after Russia, whose
consent is most vital if a United Nations resolution imposing a
Kosovo settlement is to succeed... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: This article can stand in 725; total uncut is 950
words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-BOGART-BOMB-BEIJING-725&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF ONLY SOMEONE HAD BOUGHT A `FODOR'S YUGOSLAVIA 1999' &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RUPERT CORNWELL, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ The bonehead air strike against the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade confirms the first law of those who adhere to the screw-up
theory in life: the more sophisticated the means at hand (in this
case the intelligence-gathering capability of the CIA), the more
elementary is likely to be the inevitable mistake (in this case, it
would appear, relying on an out-of-date map).
</P>
<P>
   Alas, if only someone had bought a Fodor's guide... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: Two helpful optional trims _ totaling 575 _ at 600 and
1,000. Total uncut version is 1,300 words.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-NATO-MURPHY'S-LAW-600&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ENEMY WITHIN: NATO TURNS TO SELF-CRITICISM &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By STEPHEN CASTLE, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ The question was serious, but the answer came back
with a full, shoulder-heaving laugh.
</P>
<P>
   No, replied the senior NATO diplomat, the alliance had not made
contact with dissident elements in Belgrade: ``Quite frankly,'' he
said, ``we are not that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost seven weeks into the Balkans bombing campaign a sudden
outburst of frankness _ and soul-searching _ has struck NATO's
headquarters in Brussels... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: Article can stand in 725; total uncut version is 1,050
words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-NATO-FLOGS-ITSELF-725&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WAS SECOND WORLD WAR WORTH 56 MILLION LIVES? &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By AN WILSON, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ We British had grown used to having a prime minister
who was ignorant, but now a far more worrying thought occurs. Has
he gone mad?
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair's recent self-justifying speeches, delivered with
laryngitic, manic jerkiness, persuade me that war is almost always
an act of madness.
</P>
<P>
   And the rhetoric that he uses, with its pseudo-Churchillian
echoes and its allusions to the Second World War, provoke
disturbing, unwelcome thoughts _ not merely about the current
conflict in Kosovo, but about the whole of 20th-century history,
and the brave sorrows which our parents' generation underwent... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (1,000 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WAS-WWII-WORTH-IT?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BOMB TOO FAR &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Editorial) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT, London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Minister Robin Cook said Saturday that it was
one of the tragic accidents of war, but the NATO bombing of the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade was more than that.
</P>
<P>
   It was an act of monumental incompetence in a war that has been
characterized from the start by military bungling and political
cowardice... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (950 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-NATO-FOLLY-EDITORIAL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
