<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 09:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX     05-13 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: That burning issue again
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like one of those ever-reviving creatures in a cheap monster
movie, the push to whittle down the free-speech guarantee in the
Bill of Rights is back among us. Did you ever notice how much
harder it is to kill a damn fool idea than a good one?
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee has voted 11-7 to approve a
constitutional amendment that would create the first-ever exception
to the First Amendment so that show-offs who burn American flags
could be prosecuted as criminals.
</P>
<P>
   This cheap political hustle remains, as in its earlier outings,
not just a solution in search of a problem but a solution that
would provoke the very problem it pretends to oppose. Flag-burnings
are rare and little-noticed when they do occur, but criminalize
them and you raise their value. Every two-bit cause monger would be
assured a courtroom forum.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington handicapping on this latest effort is all over
the tote board. House approval is a given. The Senate is, as they
say, too close to call. Many Congress watchers figure this year's
push has a good shot at the necessary two-thirds vote.
</P>
<P>
   Others figure legislation Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., has
introduced will provide political cover for a crucial two or three
senators to hide in by way of ducking the amendment. His bills
would punish the burning or desecration of a flag to incite riot
and the destruction of a flag stolen from the U.S. government or
removed from federal property.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court routinely discards attempts to dodge its
ruling that flag-burning is constitutionally protected speech and
the court is unlikely to be worn down by this one. Even so, a vote
for McConnell's legislation would be a talisman against the tawdry
political trick of charging that members who oppose chipping at the
First Amendment are thus supporting flag-burning and maybe even
hoping for it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, flag-burning is a noxious act, but it is precisely because
the act is so heinous to most that it also carries such big
political magic. And because it carries that mojo, it is exactly
the sort of powerful political speech, however symbolic, that the
justices have consistently judged must be constitutionally
sheltered. No protection is required for unexceptionable utterance.
</P>
<P>
   If one theatrically unpatriotic act can be constitutionally
anathematized, the push will be on to banish others, for the same
petty political advantage that can be wrought of defaming
principled opponents as unpatriotic. That way lies, at the far end,
a sort of democratic lese-majeste that could punish indignities to
elected officials as totems of the nation. No more heckling
presidents or members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment has served us brilliantly. The odd
flag-burnings that occur under its indulgence inevitably, by their
excess, discredit the very point they are intended to make.
Flag-burning is its own worst enemy, overwhelmed by the contrary
free speech it energizes.
</P>
<P>
   How foolish, if we begin to erode our actual freedoms in order
to sanctify their symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
