<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5376 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV16-C     05-13 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE McCAIN FACTOR
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 16.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On this fine spring day, early in the presidential
culling process, John McCain's campaign travels had left him bone
tired. A quiet-spoken and fiercely disciplined man, McCain has
never fully regained his strength, which was sapped when he spent
five years in a North Vietnamese prison.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, politics consumes much of McCain's life. His quest for
the White House usually puts him on the road for all but the three
days in midweek that the Senate meets.
</P>
<P>
   It also keeps him apart for long periods from his second wife,
Cindy, whom he married in 1980 and who lives in the same gated
Phoenix house where she grew up. It was Cindy who brought Bridget,
at 7 the youngest of their four children, home from Mother Teresa's
orphanage in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was down in Atlanta this weekend, giving a speech, some
guy asked me how does my position on Kosovo effect my presidential
chances?'' McCain recalled as we sat in his sunlit Senate office.
``I told him, I don't know and I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Should McCain's long-odds presidential quest prevail, it will be
neither as a result of his ordeal in Hanoi, nor his impressive
intellect, but because a consensus emerges that it's time to put a
truth-teller in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   McCain knows that his reply to the Kosovo question in Atlanta is
the practice of politics at its best. And he knows that his
reputation as a maverick, while politically useful, is false. On
issues that count, he's in sync with most Republican primary
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is now the one challenging George Bush for the
nomination,'' Mary Anne March, a political consultant in New
Hampshire, told a CNN reporter the other day. ``The more people
know about him, the more they like him. John McCain could pull an
upset in New Hampshire, and if he does that, then all bets are
off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like George Bush,'' McCain told me. While McCain clearly
wants to be president, it's also clear that he would have no
regrets if the young Texas governor, whom he views as his only real
rival for the nomination, beats him.
</P>
<P>
   Being president ``would put my family through an ordeal,''
McCain said. ``Anyway, one way or another, we'll know 10 months
from now how it turns out. And, whatever happens, I'll still have a
life.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain respects Bush and his advisers. He doesn't respect
Clinton and his advisers. As he puts it:
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States is prepared to lose a war,
rather than do the hard work, the politically risky work of
fighting it as the leader of the greatest nation on Earth should
fight when our interests and our values are imperiled. Shame on the
president if he persists in abdicating his responsibilities, but
shame on us if we let him.''
</P>
<P>
   I suggested to McCain that electoral appeal of Bush the Younger
might be a dynastic one _ much as the English in 1660 embraced
Charles II, whose father had been beheaded by the Puritans and who,
after years in exile, was restored to the British throne on his
30th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he agreed. ``And I suspect that some Republicans feel
quite ashamed these days for having abandoned Bush to back
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
