u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUPONTCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-13 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUPONTCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BRUINS HAVE LESSONS TO LEARN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Kevin Paul Dupont  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Young teams have nights like these, growing pains, and
there was pain aplenty for the Bruins to wallow in Wednesday night
after they watched their 2-1 lead disappear into the western New
York night.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes from taking a 2-1 series lead over the Sabres,
the Bruins spent too much time standing around, looking around,
looking like out-of-place teenagers in the executive board room.
Suddenly, everyone was wearing pinstripes and wingtips, and they
were still in highcut sneakers and cutoff jeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried, we were still in the game,'' said Boston defenseman
Kyle McLaren, reflecting on Rhett Warrener's goal that pulled the
Sabres into a 2-2 tie with 13:16 to play. ``We wanted to get back
on track, but it never happened. I think we hung our head too
low.''
</P>
<P>
   One minute they were there, the next minute they were the
hang-down-your-head Tom Dooleys.
</P>
<P>
   It's just what you have to live with when you back an evolving
team, a work in progress. Should the Bruins have won Wednesday
night? Absolutely. The Sabres played somewhere between poorly and
OK for the better part of 40 minutes, and the Bruins came out for
Period 3 hoping to nurse a one-goal lead to the winner's circle _ a
sure ticket to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   It took Boston nearly eight minutes to land its first shot on
net in the final period. By then, the Sabres already had Warrener's
tying goal, just one of 10 shots they had on Byron Dafoe before Don
Sweeney landed the first on Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't be doing that at this point in the season, but we
did,'' said Dafoe, who once again outplayed the great Hasek,
something he now has done twice in this series. ``We have to
correct that.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the Bruins did was correct. In Game 2 at the Vault,
the Sabres came storming out of the gate and landed 17 shots on
Dafoe in the first period. The Bruins were pinned in their own end,
unable to get out from under the Sabres' forechecking blanket.
</P>
<P>
   They came into Game 3 needing to be much quicker behind their
own blue line, and they were, not allowing the Sabres to mount any
kind of offensive pressure. Buffalo's one goal came when Dafoe
errantly pushed a puck into the slot, only to see it wash back in
his crease when it deflected off Michal Grosek and Sweeney. Jason
Woolley potted it from a bad angle with only 1:37 gone. An awful
goal. But, the Bruins didn't give up another shot for the rest of
the period. It was symptomatic of the entire night: small mistakes
and huge consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they know more than some of our younger
players,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``I thought Joe Thornton responded
well, after having a so-so game on Sunday. Now, if we could get
everyone to respond like that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal was another one of those, shall we say,
maturity issues. Dixon Ward swatted in a one-timer from the top of
the crease to put it away with 10:22 to play. Rarely do you see
someone left so wide open so low, especially in Burns's
defensive-minded scheme. Ward had slipped his coverage, just by
inches, with Landon Wilson just a step out of synch in his
man-to-man coverage. Across came Vaclav Varada's feed and Dafoe had
no chance at blocking the Ward rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost one or two assignments,'' said Burns. ``That Ward goal
was a perfect example.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins fell into a 2-1 deficit in their first-round series
against the Hurricanes and turned it around dramatically by smart,
controlled play, withstanding some intense forechecking. They were
patient, smart, and confident enough with their game and maintained
their poise. They found a way out.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't the same margin for recovery with the Sabres. They
hop on mistakes and bury them (translation: they don't have a
Martin Gelinas to double hit the puck in front of a wide-open net).
Don't be misled. Buffalo isn't quite an NHL powerhouse. But there's
enough here, especially with Hasek in net, for them to play poorly
for two periods and know, if the score remains close, they've got
enough talent and energy to knock off a team that just isn't quite
as mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to be close games,'' said Boston
captain Ray Bourque. ``We knew most likely they'd be one-goal
games. And most of the game, we did the right things. It's just
that it got away from us in the third period. We felt pretty good
about our game, but we sat back a little and we can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque called Friday's Game 4 here a ``must win'' for the
Bruins. The accompanying truth to that is they must not lapse into
what has become their young man's twilight zone. They could
eliminate all the prolonged hiccups and still lose. But failing to
eliminate them virtually guarantees defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Under Burns's knowing watch, they have chalked up two dreadful
periods in this series. That's a concern. The coach can see it
playing out in front of him, but he doesn't have the fix.
</P>
<P>
   The cure in this case is experience, knowledge, coming of age.
None of that can be accomplished with a 30-second timeout, some
chest beating and an X-and-O diagram scribbled on the top of the
dasher.
</P>
<P>
   It takes more bodies, more talented bodies, and most of all it
takes time _ the shortest commodity of all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
