<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, May 13, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DNA-MURDER (San Francisco) _ DNA tests hae linked an imprisoned
killer to the unsolved knife slayings of an Albany, Calif., couple
in 1981, according to police. Police Lt. Bill Palmini said DNA
tests that hadn't been invented at the time of the murder have
``conclusively'' linked Jackson to the murders. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-SMOKING-ADS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Starting this weekend,
tobacco executives get skewered as liars and hypocrites with a
series of anti-smoking TV ads recently approved by California Gov.
Gray Davis. Former Gov. Pete Wilson had vetoed the ads because he
didn't think taxpayers should pay for personal attacks on a legal
business. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ Lawyers suing Ford Motor Co. will
be allowed to present evidence that the automaker allegedly hid
problems with an ignition part to avoid environmental fines that
could have totaled $50 billion. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-LOWE-PROFILE (Undated) _ Actor Rob Lowe talks about
fatherhood, his upcoming role as No. 2 in the new Austin Powers
film and ``Atomic Train,'' an NBC miniseries that begins Sunday. By
MIKE McDANIEL
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STARWARS-CHARACTERS (Undated) _ You know all about Luke,
Leia, Han, Lando and Chewbacca. You know all about Death Stars, the
Millenium Falcon, X-Wing fighters and the Force. Yet none of those
``Star Wars'' trilogy characters or elements arise in ``Star Wars:
Episode One _ The Phantom Menace.'' Though some familiar faces will
reappear, George Lucas' universe is expanding. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STARWARS-PORTMAN (New York) _ She was offered a role in one
of the biggest movies ever _ and hesitated. When asked to play
Queen Amidala, young ruler of the embattled planet Naboo in ``Star
Wars: Episode One _ The Phantom Menace,'' Natalie Portman wasn't so
sure. said. ``I'd be signing not only for three films, but pretty
much 10 years of my life,'' said Portman, 17. ``It's a huge deal at
any age, and when you're that young, it's really scary.'' By BRUCE
WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   BURT-BACHARACH (Albany, N.Y.) _ Bacharach is back, in a big way.
In fact, popmeister Burt Bacharach seems to be bigger than ever,
and that's really saying something considering the way his songs
dominated the pop charts back in the '60s. By GREG HAYMES.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (San Francisco) _ Women with a localized breast
tumor may need only to have it cut out _ and not also undergo
expensive and potentially harmful radiation treatments _ to keep
the cancer from recurring, according to a new study. By ULYSSES
TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CONTAINERS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Recycling and reusing are good
for the environment, but federal food safety officials say those
old margarine tubs you keep using to reheat leftovers may be bad
for your health. So are plastic bowls and polystyrene boxes from
take-out joints. By LISA STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
is going to be re-elected but he's still running scared. He may not
prove as popular with voters as he is with himself. Sometimes it's
hell having an ego as big as the Ritz. Especially when most voters
want to check out. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-ADS (San Francisco) _ A new Anheuser-Busch ad urges gay beer
drinkers to ``Be yourself and make it a Bud Light.'' The print ad
is intended to sell beer to gay men. Gays should be skeptical about
this ad campaign. By DAVE FORD.
</P>
</TEXT>
