<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JULIA-ROBERTS-IN-NOTTING-HILL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ISN'T JULIA ROBERTS' LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Julia Roberts
with Hugh Grant in ``Notting Hill.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Look in the dictionary under ``type-casting,'' and you might
find a picture of Julia Roberts.
 &HT;    No, she's not a prostitute, a conspiracy-busting law student or
a wedding-sabotaging food critic. But look at her next couple of
films.
 &HT;    In ``Notting Hill,'' opening May 28, the $20-million-a-movie
superstar plays the world's most famous movie star, a tabloid
fixture whose scandal-ridden personal life is common knowledge the
world over.
 &HT;    Then there's ``Runaway Bride,'' which will open in August.
Working with Richard Gere and Garry Marshall, her co-star and
director in her breakout film, ``Pretty Woman'' (l990), Roberts
plays a woman who has a habit of changing her mind just as she's
about to walk down the aisle.
 &HT;    If that reminds you of Roberts' notorious vanishing act just
before her scheduled 1991 wedding to Kiefer Sutherland, you're not
the only one.
 &HT;    Roberts herself denies any connection between the actress and
the role. Settling in for an interview at London's posh Dorchester
Hotel, she says with a straight face that she doesn't see any
similarities between ``Notting Hill's'' superstar actress and
Hollywood's real-life Julia Roberts.
 &HT;    ``In almost every way she's different from me, a different
person coming from a different place,'' Roberts says. ``I'm not
having fun at the expense of my own life _ but I am getting a kick
at the expense of her life.''
 &HT;    Co-star Hugh Grant, who plays a mild-mannered bookseller who
captivates the celebrity, scoffs at her denials.
 &HT;    ``She's either deluding herself or lying,'' he says. ``There
were times in this movie that she'd deliver a speech I felt was
coming from somewhere deep in her soul.''
 &HT;    Writer/producer Richard Curtis, who also directed Grant in
``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' (l994), admits that the
resemblances aren't coincidental.
 &HT;    ``I wrote the script with Julia in mind,'' he says, ``and
frankly I never expected her to say she'd do it. But she said it
was the best romantic comedy she'd ever read.
 &HT;    ``Still,'' he adds, ``we were very surprised by her reaction. We
thought she was going to be able to give us so many more insights
into what it was like to live under the harsh glare of fame and
celebrity. But she's not playing Julia Roberts _ she's playing
another person entirely.''
 &HT;    As for ``Runaway Bride,'' Roberts has left more than a few
suitors in her wake. In years gone by she's been linked to Liam
Neeson and Jason Patric, engaged to marry Sutherland and, in 1993,
married to and divorced from singer Lyle Lovett.
 &HT;    She's currently hot and heavy with Benjamin Bratt, the New
York-based actor who stars in NBC's long-running television drama
series ``Law and Order.'' Roberts recently accepted a fraction of
her normal salary to do a guest spot on the series, playing a
seductive New York executive whose one-night stand with a prominent
investment banker results in his ``death by Viagra.''
 &HT;    The May 5 episode revolved around Roberts' attempts to seduce
Bratt's Det. Reynaldo Curtis, who hangs onto his virtue and his
marriage by his fingernails.
 &HT;    ``I begged for the part,'' Roberts says with a laugh.
 &HT;    The 31-year-old star, her dark hair pulled back severely, looks
waif-thin in the current Hollywood fashion, in form-fitting black
slacks and jacket. The whole effect is very movie-star, which of
course is what ``Notting Hill'' is all about.
 &HT;    ``Fame is not a big deal,'' she insists. ``It's a myth. People's
perception of my life or an actor's life is a lot more hectic and
outrageous and pressure-filled and glamorous than I have ever known
my life to be, or the life of any of my actor friends.
 &HT;    ``People will just assume that, because I'm playing an actor in
this movie, she is me or I understand everything about her life,''
she adds. ``I don't. All actors are different _ we're not an
assembly-line breed.''
 &HT;    Despite all appearances to the contrary _ including past
complaints about the agonies of life in a celebrity fishbowl _
Roberts insists that she isn't unusually stressed by her Hollywood
lifestyle.
 &HT;    ``I don't feel any pressure in my life,'' she says. ``Pressure
is a choice ... As my celebrity and power in Hollywood has
increased, I have become more relaxed. Being famous brings with it
an understanding of how to deal with all that comes with fame.
 &HT;    ``I possess a knowledge of who I am and what I want and why I
want it,'' she says. ``And that makes me a very centered person.
I've always had a certain amount of perspective. I came into this
business with my eyes wide open.''
 &HT;    Grant has had his own brushes with the down side of fame _
including media fascination with his long-lived relationship with
supermodel-turned-actress Elizabeth Hurley and his arrest for
soliciting a prostitute _ but Roberts says that the film was hardly
an act of retaliation. In fact, she says, at times it was downright
silly.
 &HT;    ``Hugh would tease me relentlessly,'' Roberts recalls. ``But he
learned quickly that I could give as good as I get.''
 &HT;    Grant confirms her report.
 &HT;    ``Sure,'' he says. ``I'd tease her about her hair, clothes and
her entourage and everything that she cares a lot about.
 &HT;    ``We'd end our debates by having food fights,'' he says. ``She'd
throw food at me and I'd throw it back _ and then I'd see her
enormous bodyguard closing in and I'd be intimidated. So I lost
most of the food battles.''
 &HT;    Roberts laughs.
 &HT;    ``This is classic Hugh Grant material and what he does so
well,'' she says. ``It's been really fun to watch him be this
clever, fumbling, sweet guy he plays in the movie.''
 &HT;    Even fame has its limits, Roberts adds. There are some
celebrities who are dismayed when they are not recognized, but she
says that she welcomes it.
 &HT;    And, yes, there are indeed people who don't recognize Julia
Roberts.
 &HT;    ``At a party a woman turned to me and said, `Well, what do you
do for a living?''' she recalls. ``When I said I was an actress,
she replied, `Would I have seen you in any particular film?'
 &HT;    ``Then another woman came over and began screaming `Oh my God,
it's Julia Roberts!'''
 &HT;    The actress rolls her eyes.
 &HT;    ``I envy that woman who didn't know me,'' she says. ``She has a
full and fulfilling life to not know who I am.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Notting Hill,'' consult the
official Website at www.notting-hill.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
