A5437 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-RECORD-COX     05-13 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RECORD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush wants to go `off the record' at public event
 &HT;    By Mike Elswick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush was talking presidential
Wednesday _ but in a private way _ even though he was in one of the
state's most public buildings and talking to a crowd that included
public officials.
</P>
<P>
   About halfway through a 10-minute stand-up briefing to Longview
Partnership representatives in Austin for a two-day visit, Bush
abruptly stopped talking when he saw a reporter from the Longview
News-Journal taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the state's top elected public official standing in a
public office in the Texas State Capital on the taxpayer's payroll,
said all of his comments were ``off the record.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, pointing a finger, and with what one Longview
visitor called ``a laser beam look,'' threatened to leave the room
if a note pad was not put away and a tape recorder not turned off.
</P>
<P>
   He continued his presentation but reiterated two more times that
his comments were ``off the record.'' Although he has not yet
declared his candidacy for president, Bush is considered a
front-runner for the Republican Party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Longview News-Journal publisher Glenn McCutchen, who was part of
the Longview Partnership group meeting with state officials, said
he was incensed over the idea of the state's highest elected
official not being willing to stand behind comments he was making
on public issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 35 years in journalism I've never seen anything like
this,'' McCutchen said. ``It raises the question of whether Gov.
Bush is telling one story in private and another in public.''
</P>
<P>
   In general terms, Bush discussed his feelings on a variety of
issues from the end of the current Texas Legislative session, the
morale of United States military troops, national leadership and
world issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry in a separate briefing to about 20 Longview
Partnership representatives, was not so reluctant to be quoted as
he praised the leadership Texas is receiving from Sen. Bill
Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant. As chairman of the Texas Senate Finance
committee and as a senior senator, Perry said Ratliff is a key
player in helping shape the future of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an extraordinary job Bill Ratliff is doing representing
you and all of Texas,'' Perry said. ``The appropriation process is
so vitally important. He listens to requests judiciously and is
very fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry called Ratliff's job as chairman of the finance committee
``one of the toughest in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   He said as the Texas Legislature moves into the final weeks of
the session the intensity level is increasing dramatically. But he
said Texas continues to be a model of bi-partisan politics with
both Democrats and Republicans
</P>
<P>
   working together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children's education has been one of the major focuses,''
Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Elswick is the business editor of the Longview News-Journal
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
