<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Friday,
May 14. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   SAM _ Kansas Sen. Sam Brownback has found himself well-placed
for a publicity coup. As a critic of violent song lyrics, the
conservative Republican is now the talking head in demand when talk
turns to culture. A Senate hearing and White House meeting are
helping him gather steam. David Goldstein. 25.
</P>
<P>
   KEN: Trial of Kenneth Demarrias provides look at youth violence
and what's being planned to stop it. He is charged with two counts
of first-degree murder for killing a 17-year-old and a 15-year-old
over a basketball game at Winner Park. The murders last year
outraged a city trying to come to grips with rising juvenile
homicides. In response to last year's murders, the Partnership for
Children and 25 other agencies will soon release a series of
recommendations to curtail youth violence in Kansas City. An
official with the partnership says it's necessary to intervene
earlier in children's lives. Demarrias was 18 at the time of the
killings and faces life without parole if convicted. Joe Lambe. 20.
Photos, graphics.
</P>
<P>
   CIG: Another victory for tobacco as federal jury in KC finds in
favor of cigarette company and gives no money to the Charles Steele
family, who'd claimed years of smoking killed him. Mark Morris. 15.
</P>
<P>
   KIP: Kansas City police conduct a search of the Smithville Lake
area Thursday for Crystal Kipper's body. The search stems from a
map mailed anonymously to The Star purporting to show where Kipper
can be found. Obviously, it could be a cruel hoax. B. Williams. 15.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH: The Mid-America Regional Council of greater Kansas City
says list of future federal highway projects affected by the U.S.
Dept. of Transportation ruling this week will be released on
Friday. Mike Mansur. 15.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH: A new program offers protection and peace of mind for
elderly or disabled Kansas City residents. The Senior Watch Program
started in January in the police department's East Patrol Division,
but could spread to the rest of the city. Program members provide
police with their phone number, medical history, family contacts
and the name of someone nearby who can let police into their home
in an emergency. The information is entered into a computer, and
accessed only by the police. Since January, 280 people have joined
the program. Malcolm Garcia. 16. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ADOPT: Scott and Kim Tucker of Leawood return to KCI from China
with their newly adopted daughter, Lillie Gwynne Tucker, at 3:50
p.m. Thursday. We quiz them on their tumultuous last few days holed
up in a Chinese hotel above streets filled with rock-throwing mobs.
Photo. Phil O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   CRISIS: In the wake of the Littleton, Colo., shooting, Swope
Parkway Health Center and TMC Behavioral Health Network form a
school-based crisis team. The team will begin a pilot project at
Central High School and Central Middle School. Eventually, the
program will expand to as many as 12 KC School District schools.
Tanika White.
</P>
<P>
   DIAL (Business) _ Ready or not, local dialers will have to add
913 or 816 to millions of calls when they're dialing across the
state line. Eric Palmer
</P>
<P>
   VANGUARD (Business) _ The Justice Department charged Thursday
that American Airlines monopolized airline passenger service to and
from DFW International Airport, trying to force Kansas City-based
low-cost carrier Vanguard Airlines out of business. By Randolph
Heaster
</P>
