<HEADER>
A5453 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-CHILDREN-$ADV1     05-13 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-CHILDREN-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PLIGHT OF KOSOVO ALBANIAN CHILDREN, RUNS PARALLEL TO THOSE OF
BOSNIAN WAR
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ They joke and laugh and draw
pictures, just like so many children the world over. For a moment,
it's easy to imagine the eight- and nine-year-olds in Hamdija
Pasic's art class are just like other children.
</P>
<P>
   But these children have seen the worst the adult world has to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after the bloody civil war ended here, many of
Bosnia's youngest victims are still reeling from the horrors they
lived through. Horrors that aid officials worry are now being
repeated on a new wave of innocents from the war-torn Serb province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As Pasic and scores of psychologists, psychiatrists, social
workers and teachers struggle to undo the damage the war did to
Bosnia's children, they hope that their work here sheds some light
on the problems sure to arise with Kosovar Albanian refugee
children.
</P>
<P>
   Pasic, a counselor with the Christian aid organization World
Vision, particularly worries
</P>
<P>
   about one little boy. There's one like him in every class, a
withdrawn, troubled child who won't talk about the memories that
haunt him. When he draws a picture of himself, he scribbles over
the face, obliterating the eyes and nose, scratching out the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he's a refugee, but we're not sure what else happened
to him,'' Pasic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got some pretty serious problems, self-esteem issues. We
think there are family problems, but we're not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   So how will the children of Kosovo fare? What ongoing effects
will they feel years from now?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say, experts in Bosnia say. Nationwide statistics
aren't available, though counselors say they're seeing some very
serious problems, including an increase in juvenile crime and
suicide. A few months ago, a Sarajevo 13-year-old committed suicide
with a hand grenade, a method that's become increasingly common
since the war here ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid the world will never understand what these children
have suffered,'' said
</P>
<P>
   sociologist Milanka Mikovic. ``Hundreds of thousands lost their
homes, their friends, their
</P>
<P>
   schools, their pets, and all the things that make the lives of
kids what it's supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mikovic studied a group of 500 schoolchildren between the ages
of six and ten in Sarajevo. Twenty-three percent had seen a
relative wounded; 38 percent had seen dead bodies in the street; 46
percent were refugees within the city. Among those children, she
found an unusually high incidence of insomnia, aggressive behavior,
panic attacks, depression and problems in school.
</P>
<P>
   According to UNICEF, 45,000 children lost a parent. More than
3,000 lost both parents. And tens of thousands lost relatives or
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors like Pasic do what they can for the children. The
World Vision program includes music therapy and group discussions
about things like conflicts and how to resolve them, fears and how
to cope with them, memories and how to understand them. At
HealthNet, another humanitarian aid group working here, counselors
work one-on-one with the more seriously disturbed children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to make a prognosis,'' said psychologist
Amira Gradincic. ``What we're
</P>
<P>
   seeing, is it going to be a damaged generation in two years?
It's hard to know. In 15 years, yeah, maybe. They did suffer a lot
and they are still carrying those experiences with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia's children are also struggling with the physical
consequences of the war. More
</P>
<P>
   than 35,000 were wounded and approximately 4,000 of those
suffered disfiguring injuries,
</P>
<P>
   according to UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've noticed a lot of eye problems and more leukemia than we
used to,'' said pediatrician Mira Ademovic. ``But we don't have the
funds to do any kind of systematic analysis to be able to say for
sure, this child's problem is because of the war or we have more of
this type of problem because of the war. We don't even have the
equipment to do analyses to determine nutritional deficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ademovic said she has seen many children who's growth was
stunted by poor diet and health care during the war and even three
years later; they're shorter and smaller than
</P>
<P>
   their ages would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, counselors at Moj Prijatelj, which means ``My
Friend'' in Serbo-Croatian,
</P>
<P>
   work with another group of children struggling just to be kids.
</P>
<P>
   The girls in the seven- to 12-year-olds group idolize the Spice
Girls and worship the
</P>
<P>
   Back Street Boys. They come to the center every afternoon to
practice dances they'll do
</P>
<P>
   in a play they're planning.
</P>
<P>
   A video-tape of last year's play, which the children wrote
themselves, seems to start like any other school play. The princess
complains she's bored and one of her friends suggests she have a
new dress made. No, the princess says, she has too many dresses.
Another friend suggests she start another war.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. We've already fought everyone. I'm bored with war,'' the
princess says, almost hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
