<HEADER>
A5454 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-CANDIDATES-$AD     05-13 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CANDIDATES-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI ELECTION'S TWO FRONTRUNNERS: DIFFERENCES IN STYLE OVER
SUBSTANCE
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-ELECTION-$ADV16.
 &HT;    For Sun., May 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israelis go to the polls Monday to choose their next
prime minister. Though they could face a run-off on June 1, the two
clear frontrunners are incumbent Prime Minister Benjamin ``Bibi''
Netanyahu and challenger Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   THE INCUMBENT UNDER FIRE: BENJAMIN ``BIBI'' NETANYAHU
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS: Elected in 1996, heads the right-wing Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE: The American-educated 49-year-old is smooth and
telegenic. First Israeli prime minister to really resemble American
politicians. Fluent in English.
</P>
<P>
   BRAINS: Went to high school in the United States, got a master's
degree in business from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   BRAWN: Commando captain in the Israeli army. Was shot in the
hand by friendly fire during the rescue of a hijacked Sabena
airliner.
</P>
<P>
   VIEWS: Fierce opponent of slain Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and
Oslo peace process. Since being elected, he has slowed the process
down.
</P>
<P>
   BACKING: Support from Jewish settlers living in the disputed
West Bank territories, ultra-religious Jews and the blue-collar
Jews whose families immigrated to Israel from other Middle Eastern
countries.
</P>
<P>
   THE UNTESTED CHALLENGER: EHUD BARAK
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS: Barak heads the left-wing Labor Party, but spent most
of his career in the Israeli military.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE: The 57-year-old is short and stocky, and speaks with
heavily accented English.
</P>
<P>
   BRAINS: Master's in engineering systems from Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
   BRAWN: Israeli army's most decorated soldier. Was Netanyahu's
commander. Once sneaked into Beirut, disguised as a woman, and
assassinated terrorists in a PLO headquarters. His campaign
commercials call him ``soldier number 1.''
</P>
<P>
   VIEWS: Would accelerate Oslo peace process but says he will give
up little more than Netanyahu. He has stressed economic and social
issues in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   BACKING: His support mostly comes from secular Jews of European
descent and Israel's large Arab population.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5455 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-$ADV     05-13 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS WORLD WATCHES, ISRAELI VOTE WILL HINGE ON PERSONALITIES
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-CANDIDATES-$ADV16.
 &HT;    For Sun., May 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As Israelis prepare to vote in elections Monday, the
question of how their country will co-exist with its neighbors is
being pushed slowly aside by the question of how Israelis will live
with each other.
</P>
<P>
   They will be voting according to their disparate views on
whether Israel should be a Western-styled democracy or a Jewish
fundamentalist state. They will be expressing their frustration
over a recession and looking for candidates that sympathize with
their particular ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   And, while they revel in the politics of the region's only
democracy -- voter turnout is sure to be over 80 percent -- the
divisions between what many call Israel's ``tribes,'' are in plain
view.
</P>
<P>
   On major intersections across the country, religious Israeli
youth -- boys in yamulkas and girls in long skirts -- carry signs
for the several right-wing and religious parties. Opposing them are
left-wing secular youth, in halter tops and jeans -- touting their
favorite pols.
</P>
<P>
   Five candidates vie for prime minister. The clear front-runners
are incumbent right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin ``Bibi'' Netanyahu
and former general, left-winger Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The minor candidates -- former defense minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, extreme right-winger Benjamin ``Benny'' Begin and Arab
candidate Azmi Bishara -- could likely drop out before Monday's
vote. If not, Netanyahu and Barak will probably face each other in
a June 1 run-off. Polls currently show Barak with a small lead.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, 57, and Netanyahu, 49, used to be in the same elite
commando unit, but they battle each other now under the guidance of
their American political consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu tells Israelis that even the Arabs want Barak because
he's weak. Barak, on the other hand, seems to appeal on a wider
range of issues. He tells Israelis that Netanyahu has left the
country ``stuck'' on all fronts, from economic development to
religious tolerance to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, far from world peace, the race could hinge on the
personality of Netanyahu, who seems to both inflame and personify
the country's divisions.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters are the ultra-religious and ethnic groups that
proudly call themselves ``the rabble.'' They feel Netanyahu fights
for them against Israel's elites just as he does against the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's opponents are fed up with that confrontational
nature. They call him a liar who is exploiting Israel's divisions
and pushing it toward war its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Even many of Netanyahu's cabinet ministers have abandoned and
bad-mouthed him. The distrust seems to trickle down to his voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stay loyal to who is with the right wing,'' says reluctant
Netanyahu supporter Eliyahu Mordechai, 33. ``But, as far as the
personal aspect goes, there have been changes. He's not so
popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai sells nuts in Jerusalem's Mehaneh Yehudah produce
market, long a Netanyahu stronghold. The market is filled with
blue-collar Jews descended from other Middle Eastern countries who
feel alienated by Israel's Jews of European descent.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai removed the prime minister's picture from his stall
after Netanyahu fired a popular defense minister. Striding out of
his shop toward the crowded market, Mordechai sums up the changing
mood: ``Barak is going to win big.''
</P>
<P>
   Other former Netanyahu supporters have been repelled by the
power he has granted to the ultra-religious parties in his
government.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the 1 million immigrants from the former Soviet
Union voted heavily for Netanyahu in 1996, tipping the election his
way. They were hawks on security and felt ignored by the Labor
Party elites.
</P>
<P>
   But they are largely secular, and Netanyahu's religious allies
have challenged their Judaism, making it difficult for them to get
married or bring other relatives to the country. Polls show many
Russians are looking toward Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Last week(CQ), as he plunged in public opinion polls, the brash
Netanyahu turned to contrition. Telegenic as always, the
American-educated politician called his Likud Party loyalists home,
trying to remind them of the issue that has usually mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching a moment of truth in these elections,''
Netanyahu stated. ``I never said I was free of errors, but there is
one thing I can say, with my hand on my heart: That I have lead the
state of Israeli on the only road that can bring security and
peace. . . . I implore you to put aside all other concerns. I
implore you to come home to the Likud.''
</P>
<P>
   But, security is a tougher sell this year than in the past.
Barak's stance toward the Arabs differs little from Netanyahu's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sting of the campaign, the Arabs, has been neutralized,''
said pollster Hanoch Smith. ``It's very hard to differentiate among
any one of the candidates as to what they're saying about the main
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, Netanyahu may be tough, but Barak was Netanyahu's
former army commander. He is also Israel's most decorated soldier.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, he would likely move quicker than Netanyahu on small
issues in the peace process, but stay firm on the major principles.
He refuses to share Jerusalem with the Palestinians, insists on
keeping most of the West Bank settlements in place and says he'll
be stingy with West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference is one of attitude. While Netanyahu reminds
Israelis of their fear of Arabs, Barak tells them they have nothing
to fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more powerful than any neighbor. We can afford to
pursue peace from a position of strength,'' says Barak, whose short
and stocky physique belies his commando past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to fight terrorism. I will not let anybody strain
our security,'' Barak says.
</P>
<P>
   The tough talk has helped Barak bring the Labor Party toward the
political center, just as U.S. President Bill Clinton and British
Prime Minister Tony Blair did when their parties were viewed as too
far left of the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   As Barak has taken cues from the outside world, world leaders
seem to be pulling for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Clinton administration appeared to back Netanyahu's
losing opponent, Shimon Peres. Now, it has been careful to remain
neutral. But it's clear that Netanyahu has frequently upset Clinton
by stalling the peace process and encouraging settlements on
disputed West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   Several Arab leaders, through appeals to his opponents, indicate
they also want Netanyahu out.
</P>
<P>
   That's a fact Netanyahu is quick to publicize. But, it doesn't
matter to people like Galit Natan, a 30-year-old architect who
brought her daughter to a ``Just not Netanyahu'' rally recently.
</P>
<P>
   She said Barak and Netanyahu will make similar concessions in
the peace process but, ``the process to get there with Netanyahu
will be horrible. It's the person. We are voting for a person, not
a party.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
