<HEADER>
A5461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-COLUMN14-COX     05-13 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With his pen in his hand
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The memories are distant, so distant that the
words come back only in bits and snatches. Sentence fragments.
Sparks off a campfire, scattered wide by the wind.
</P>
<P>
   But I can see clearly in my mind's eye the two old men sitting
outside on whatever was handy, smoking and passing a quart of beer
while they told each other stories.
</P>
<P>
   Stories of brave souls and treacherous ones. Stories of lost
love and lost treasure. Stories about white horses with magic
powers and the men who rode them. Stories that bedazzled a boy of
3.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing I like better than a good story. It is the
inheritance my grandfather Crecencio Garcia left me and one shared
with most of his children and their children.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather was through being a janitor every day at 3 p.m.
On his way home, he would pick up a canteloupe or watermelon to
bring to my mother. He would get me in the trade and down the dirt
street we'd go to the corner grocery for beer, a pouch of tobacco,
rolling papers and a soda for me.
</P>
<P>
   Properly supplied, we would arrive at the home of his
story-swapping buddy and the tales would commence. I see them
still, my Papa Cencho and his friend Ramos, two old men rolling
cigarettes, sharing beer and talking of other days.
</P>
<P>
   The memory comes and goes but rode a fast horse last week when I
heard that Americo Paredes had died. He was the storyteller's
storyteller. He knew my grandfather without ever having met him and
he knew him well.
</P>
<P>
   The transmissions of culture, values and folk history are the
storyteller's crops. You'll find the soul of a people in their
stories and that is the field in which Paredes labored long and
labored well.
</P>
<P>
   He was a journalist at his roots, beginning as a reporter for
the Brownsville Herald and in the military. A compendium of
outstanding ``Stars and Stripes'' stories carries one about the
Japanese war crimes trial under Americo Paredes' byline.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of us, and he never really quit being one of us,
although he left the daily business to pursue a higher education
and university teaching career.
</P>
<P>
   He never quit listening, though. And we all know that the
absolute best storytellers and journalists are the best listeners.
</P>
<P>
   He listened while the old men told their stories. He tape
recorded their music. If he hadn't been around to do that, those
stories and songs would have scattered like those sparks that glow
brightly but die quickly in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   And we would be the poorer because we would have lost a part of
our heritage, a piece of the culture that molds us into who we are.
</P>
<P>
   The good doctor expresses that thought well in the
acknowledgments (even that was poetic) in his famous ``With His
Pistol in His Hand: A Border Ballad and Its Hero'':
</P>
<P>
   ``To the memory of my father,
</P>
<P>
   who rode a raid or two with
</P>
<P>
   Catarino Garza;
</P>
<P>
   and to all those old men
</P>
<P>
   who sat around on summer nights,
</P>
<P>
   in the days when there was
</P>
<P>
   a chaparral, smoking their
</P>
<P>
   cornhusk cigarettes and talking
</P>
<P>
   in low, gentle voices about
</P>
<P>
   violent things;
</P>
<P>
   while I listened''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican American journalists in particular owe Dr. Paredes a
great deal. He was in this racket long before we were welcome in
it. Even in the late '60s when we started to enter the field in any
kind of numbers, it wasn't easy for us. I can only imagine what it
was like for a Chicano reporter in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of the love for storytelling my grandfather left
me and the inspiration of Dr. Paredes keeps me in this business.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard about Dr. Paredes' death, I thought about what
Miles Davis once said about Duke Ellington: ``I think all musicians
should get together on a certain day and get down on their knees
and thank Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, today's crop of Mexican American journalists should
get down on their knees and thank Dr. Paredes.
</P>
<P>
   My deepest sympathy to the family. Their loss is profound, and
one shared by anyone who loves words.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at agarcia(at)statesman.com
or at 445-3667.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
