<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN14-COX     05-13 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hate-crimes bill could hurt Bush either way
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Would Gov. George W. Bush push the Texas Senate
to pass a hate-crimes bill if President Clinton called and asked?
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of James Byrd Jr., the black man who was dragged to
death behind a pickup truck near Jasper, says Clinton told her
Friday during an Austin visit that he would call ``if he thought it
would help.''
</P>
<P>
   Not likely the president will make that call _ since it probably
would have zero effect on the governor if he did.
</P>
<P>
   First, Clinton was the guy who removed George W.'s dad from the
White House _ albeit with Ross Perot's help.
</P>
<P>
   Second, and probably more important, is the widespread
presumption that the governor-who-would-be-president would prefer
the bill stay stalled so he isn't faced with having to declare
himself for or against.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he thinks Texas already punishes hate crimes
enough. And indeed, critics of the hate-crimes legislation point
out that the first of the three men tried for Byrd's murder got the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill passed the House, by a surprisingly large 83-61
margin, after some impassioned speeches and with some Republicans
co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Wolens (D-Dallas), who has carried the bill for
years, used words like ``spic'' and ``nigger'' to an
uncharacteristically hushed House chamber as a reminder of the
venomous epithets used against people simply because of their skin
color.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul Moreno, a lawyer from El Paso who uses a wheelchair,
told of housing discrimination in Austin while he was a law
student.
</P>
<P>
   Behind many of the votes against the bill in the House, and
opposition in the Senate, is conservative fear that it gives new
standing to homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Glen Maxey (D-Austin), the Legislature's only openly gay
member, said he was gratified when several rural, conservative
Democrats who had said they would vote against the bill wound up
supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the toughest vote I've cast this session,'' said one of
them, Rep. David Counts (D-Knox City). Counts said it became clear
``that the hate had escalated. As I listened to the debate, it
occurred to me that it was time to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, where a bill must have a two-thirds majority to
be brought up for consideration, the bill is stuck. Even though all
15 of the Democrats are for it, its sponsors need six of the 16
Republicans to get it to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Democrats, with newfound political fervor now that
former Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock isn't there to keep them in
check, have made the hate-crimes bill their defining cause this
session. Some have said they'll start killing other bills,
including the appropriations bill, if hate crimes remains stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Several opponents back the party line broadcast by Texas GOP
Chairman Susan Weddington, that Texas has tough criminal penalties
already and shouldn't make it a bigger crime to hurt one group of
people than another.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Texas already has a hate-crimes law, which stiffens
penalties for crimes involving hate or bias but does not specify
which groups are covered.
</P>
<P>
   But others _ including some who have voted for the bill in the
past _ simply don't want to vote this time and put themselves or
Bush on the spot. Sen. Florence Shapiro (R-Plano), who co-sponsored
the current hate-crimes law, says she can't see what the new one
would add. ``I haven't made a decision one way or the other,'' she
said Wednesday. ``I'm still looking for answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The thinking is that if it passed and Bush doesn't veto it, that
could hurt him with conservatives in Republican presidential
primaries. If he did veto it, or even let it become law without his
signature, that could cost him in the general election with
minority group members, homosexuals and civil-rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Armbrister of Victoria, probably the most conservative
Democrat in the Senate, says even though he's for the bill, and
even though some Republicans might vote yes were it to come up,
most of his Republican colleagues will be against it _ no matter
what.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that are going to vote no are like the people that
are going to vote yes,'' Armbrister said. ``There ain't nothing you
can do to scare 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com or 445-3644.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
