A5464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN14-COX     05-13 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When hammering doesn't work, this campus does
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ After the Columbine shootings, amid the stories of
the campus loners who killed, Chris Hanks felt chilled. In the
school where he works, Hanks sees many students who'd be seen as
likely candidates for the Trenchcoat Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   They may not dress that particular way. They may not have death
wishes plastered all over them and posted on the Internet. But,
said Hanks, they fit the media profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dress oddly, listen to strange music, and for the most
part are on the fringes of their high school community.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks' chill? It wasn't from fear that those students would turn
violent. Hanks likes them, trusts them. The chill comes when he
wonders what those young people must think about all of this.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Hanks sees them every day means they're not headed
in the direction of violent oblivion. They know the direction to
that, which is out the door.
</P>
<P>
   They attend OPTIONS, an alternative high school at McLennan
Community College. It is fed by districts throughout McLennan
County. OPTIONS is an acronym representing more words than you need
to know. What you should know is this: It's a place for students
who've decided the traditional high school is no place for them.
Hanks is its coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS is voluntary and structured much like a workplace.
</P>
<P>
   It's designed for students who otherwise would drop out or zone
out. It is self-paced. Scheduling is flexible, in some cases to
allow a student to hold a job and stay in school. The students may
have family problems, may have their own children, may have medical
or emotional problems that caused them to fall behind, or simply
were bad fits in their high schools.
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary aspect is pivotal. Students who are disruptive or
belligerent are gone from OPTIONS. When the bell sounds, you work _
just like on the job. You set goals and you are there to meet them.
</P>
<P>
   Some students will return to their home campuses when they catch
up on their academic goals. Many will earn their diplomas at
OPTIONS. Some are there to get their GED.
</P>
<P>
   The program, serving ages 15 to 20, has been successful enough
in its five years that Hanks is hoping to expand the program to
14-year-olds who might be spinning their wheels trying to advance
to high school and also to students who are older but who don't
have the requisite sixth-grade-level academic skills that OPTIONS
requires.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing exotic about OPTIONS. Essentially it's a
one-room school tucked into the former Waco High School building.
</P>
<P>
   Though in its infancy it relied heavily on computer software for
self-paced learning, today it relies most heavily on textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Success in getting underachievers to succeed often hinges on
finding exactly where they stand academically and proceeding from
there.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are students who have high intelligence but lack
the motivation, or who simply can't stand to be in the traditional
high school.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks had a long talk with some of his students about the
Columbine incident and school violence in general. ``They want to
talk and they have opinions,'' he said. He said his students saw
some of themselves in the depictions of the two boys now seen as
evil's archetype.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS is a place where students who felt marginalized on their
home campuses feel more mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the issue is social promotion, whether it's social
alienation, school districts that want to do the right thing will
offer options. Or they'll simply let those at the margins drift off
the edge.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
