<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDSUMMER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS `NIGHT'S DREAM' LACKING MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Midsummer Night's Dream'' is Shakespeare in love,
but don't let that fool you. While the exuberance and goofiness and
lyrical eloquence of the text remains, director Michael Hoffman's
plodding adaptation suffers from an incoherent vision and a fatal
lack of magic. There are still some wonderful moments and an array
of fine performances, but those elements don't coalesce in a manner
that is meaningful or enchanting.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, who also wrote the screenplay, puts this ``Dream'' in
turn-of-the-century Tuscany, where, as the prologue relates, the
good news is that high collars and bustles are disappearing. The
new sensation is the bicycle, which Hoffman uses at every
opportunity to symbolize both the psychological freedoms and
obstacles the film's lovers face. Given the number of antique
bicycle sightings here, you half expect to see Paul Newman's Butch
Cassidy ride through town to the strains of ``Raindrops Keep
Fallin' on My Head.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the golden Tuscany landscapes (Frances Mayes
would be delighted), we meet the four star-crossed lovers, Hermia
(Anna Friel) and Lysander (Dominic West) and Demetrius (Christian
Bale) and Helena (Calista Flockhart). Hermia loves Lysander, but
her father has promised her to Demetrius, much to the chagrin of
Helena, who is passionately devoted to Demetrius. (Shakespeare
would have been a natural ``Melrose Place'' scribe.)
</P>
<P>
   The four find their way to a forest ruled by the fairy king
Oberon (Rupert Everett) and his queen, Titania (a radiant Michelle
Pfeiffer), who are having their own problems with love. Soon Oberon
dispatches his impish prankster, Puck (Stanley Tucci), to deliver
potions that will throw the mortals' world into chaos and
eventually make Titania fall in love with the actor-jackass, Bottom
(Kevin Kline).
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' is a narratively
complex work that requires a director skilled enough to weave all
the elements together. Hoffman only partially succeeds. Much of the
problem comes from the pedestrian use of the setting. The dark
forest looks like an outgrowth of Disneyland's jungle safari ride.
Kitschy, yes; enchanting, no. And the fairies sadly call to mind
another Disney creation _ Tinkerbell.
</P>
<P>
   When the squabbling lovers stumble into the woods, the pace
turns leaden. By the time they re-emerge for the concluding
play-within-a-play from Bottom and his talentless troupe, so much
ground has been lost that the movie never quite recovers.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Brits fare best with the Bard. Friel and
West make a convincing romantic couple, and Everett's Oberon
registers well. Flockhart and Kline give engaging, broader
performances that at times seem at odds with the film's overall
tone, a fault of the director, not their own. Tucci, though a bit
long in the tooth for Puck, plays the spirit with a winning charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' has been adapted for film twice
before _ Mickey Rooney played Puck in Max Reinhardt's 1935 version,
and the Royal Shakespeare Company (with Judi Dench) weighed in in
1968. It's a tough play to film with all its surreal and
fantastical elements, a challenge Hoffman undoubtedly discovered
when he tackled the project. His ``Dream'' is a credible effort.
Maybe another filmmaker will capture Shakespeare's magic someday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
