<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5467 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASCARA-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-13 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASCARA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICK FLICK COVERS FAMILIAR GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:   1 1/2 stars  
BY MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Mascara'' is a nicely made, well-acted
independent film that unfortunately just doesn't have much to say.
Writer-director Linda Kandel, a native Angeleno, has made a
good-looking movie that supports stereotypes about L.A. and about
``chick flicks'' in general.
</P>
<P>
   The film centers around three pretty, upper-middle-class women
living in Los Angeles _ Ione Skye, Lumi Cavazos and Amanda de
Cadenet _ who are all facing problems and transitions in their
lives as they near age 30. One is getting married; one is unhappily
married; one is in a dead-end relationship with an older but
immature man, played quite well by former Sex Pistols guitarist
Steve Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Stereotype No. 1: In chick flicks, men are mostly hateful
losers; women define themselves by their relationships with men,
then kvetch about it. One husband is a philanderer. One is a
philanderer AND a compulsive spender. The boyfriend is a boozy
lecher who lustfully eyes his teen-age daughter's rear end.
</P>
<P>
   The young women talk and obsess about all this for an hour and a
half. The best solution in the end appears to be leaving the men
behind. Pretty depressing, and nothing's really learned.
</P>
<P>
   Stereotype No. 2: Los Angeles is full of navel-gazing,
insulated, beautiful people who lead such cushy lives that they
have to invent problems for themselves. It's not really clear why
the character played by Cavazos (of ``Like Water for Chocolate'')
walks out on her husband of seven months early in the film.
</P>
<P>
   It seems justified later when we find out what a loser he is,
but the excuse she seems to have at the time is that her
``traditional'' parents pressured her to get married. Young, indie
filmmakers should just have a single actress play the social
climbing/pressuring/insensitive mother in all these films, so we'd
get the idea immediately, instead of having to sit through the
tedious, obligatory scene establishing this character. It still
wouldn't solve the problem of the child's character being
spineless.
</P>
<P>
   Cavazos' character announces she's pregnant about three-quarters
of the way through the film. We've known this for a while, since
she keeps throwing up. The final scene has her giving birth,
flanked by her two girlfriends and no men. Yes, sisterhood is
powerful _ but it's hard to feel joyous about another life being
brought into the middle of this messed-up, self-centered trio.
</P>
<P>
   In her ``director's statement,'' second-time director (Kandel's
first feature, ``Naked Jane,'' was _ run for the hills _
``acclaimed at the Sundance Film Festival'') says she wanted to
make a film about ``friends who at times have led empty bourgeois
lives, but don't or can't do it any longer.'' If only that
transformation had been more apparent on the screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
