<P>
   HAIRCOLOR-MEN _ The number of men who color their hair, and the
range of products targeted toward them, increases yearly. Downpager
focuses on products, methodology and men's motivation to dye.
(Hill, Atlanta Journal-Coinstitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs _ EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MAY 16.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-KANI-Q&AMP;A _ At the ripe age of 29, Karl Kani could
rightfully be called the Granddaddy of urban sportswear. His baggy,
bright clothes revolutionized street looks a decade ago, but the
brand's lost its shimmer to the Fubus and Hilfigers of the world
since. In Q&AMP;A form, we catch up with comeback-minded Kani as he
celebrates 10 years in business and collects honors from
AmericasMart. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MATERNITY-CLOTHES _ WACO, Texas _ Comfort. Comfort. Comfort.
That one small word means the world to mothers-to-be when it comes
to surviving the warm-weather months of their pregnancy. (Mays,
Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HAIR _ ATLANTA _ For 53 years, Irene McCoy has gotten up before
dawn to work at a cinderblock beauty salon across from Georgia
Tech. She says she's 62, admits to 84, looks somewhere in between
and is still hard at work at a business that's aging as rapidly as
its customers. A few years ago she gave the shop to Mozelle
Collins, 57, who started out there as a shampoo girl 40 years ago.
Regulars still keep the phone ringing, wanting to run in for a $10
weekly shampoo and set. But times are changing. Many customers have
died or moved to retirement communities, and Mozelle supplements
her income by doing hair at nursing homes. (Lee, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A gardening column by Lee May. This week: Lee
muses on the contradictions involved in growing roses. ``The rose,
that deeply-loved, highly-prized queen of the garden, has its own
contradictions, lessons. It is at once elegant and prickly, silky
and rough, inviting and repelling, bringing those qualities
together like no other flower.'' (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   FURNITURE-HOLLYWOOD _ HIGH POINT, N.C. _ High Point spring
furniture show wrapup. Furniture designers take a page from Tinsel
Town's Golden Age of glamour by designing lines that are glamorous,
clean and sleek. More than a half-dozen design houses ``went
retro;'' and companies are banking on consumers wanting to cull the
best of modern design for homes they will decorate in the new
century. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   HOME-FURNISHINGS _ If you're wondering where furnishings, like
fashions, are headed as the calendar turns to a new century, think
east _ as in France and beyond to Asia. Not French as in ornate,
heavily gilded pieces, or Oriental as in high-laquered, exotic
ones. And while you're traveling, think back to the curvy modern
lines 1920s, '30s and '40s, when the glamour of Art Deco ruled.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WORKSHOP-PONDS _ A weekly series giving step-by-step guidelines
for an inexpensive weekend project for the home or garden. This
week: Installing a pond. (Shifrin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS
