</P>
<P>
   BUZZME-LOGAN _ Interview with Winder songwriter Jack Logan,
whose new album ``Buzz Me In'' marks his debut for Capricorn
Records, and active return to a musical career that's been stuck in
idle. (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-YANKEES _ Yankees! In Atlanta! As it turns out, Miss
Pittypat's shocked words in ``Gone With The Wind'' were an
understatement. Union troops were closing in on the city, and her
words suggest Atlanta was a united city. Not so, says UGA professor
Thomas Dyer in a new book, ``Secret Yankees,'' just published by
Johns Hopkins University and getting some national attention.
Yanks'd been here for years, and actively helped the Union. It's
taken two decades of research, starting with an old diary in the
UGA archives, but Dyer's found that Atlanta was crawling with Union
sympathizers and spies. Historians praise the scholarship because
it took a dogged investigation to find out that Atlanta's
population wasn't as unified as Gone With The Wind has led most
folks to believe. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
ILLUSTRATION. 47. MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   YANKEES-EXCERPTS _ Excerpts from the ``Secret Yankees'' diary.
(Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10. MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week. This
layout is now available
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0515 FATHERHOOD _ In his new book, Leonard Pitts
Jr. recounts the struggle to cope with his anger toward his father
and become a better parent himself. Interspersed with his memories
are stories of other African-American men facing the same
difficulties. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
3-column color photo of Pitts and a 1-column color photo of the
book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PITTS TIPS _ Advice on how to be a better father.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK NEWS _ It's something of a relief to pick up the first four
volumes in a new series of books, biographies of 150 pages or so,
well written by people who know. The series is called Penguin
Lives, and at first glance it might be seen as a kind of
biographical literature for the age of the sound bite. (Bernstein,
N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW CRYPTONOMICON _ Neal Stephenson's ``Cryptonomicon'' is
filled with technical information about the minutiae of
code-writing and breaking, statistics and probability theory and
encryption within various computer programs. There's a plot mixed
in there, too. (Beach, Austin American-Statesman) Art includes
1-column B&AMP;W pic of author as a child and a 6-pica color photo of
book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW CLOSE RANGE _ If there is any blood left in our romance
with the West, Annie Proulx wrings it dry in her powerful new
collection, ``Close Range: Wyoming Stories.'' (Lehmann-Haupt, N.Y.
Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-FLORIDA _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ ``Beyond the Theme Parks:
Exploring Central Florida'' by Benjamin D. Brotemarkle, an expert
on Florida history, culture and the arts, serves as a useful guide
for both locals and tourists interested in enjoying something
different than the larger tourist destinations in Central Florida.
(Shashoua, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   EVEREST _ It's Everest climbing season. We profile Hugh Morton,
one of the few Southeasterners to summit the peak, and recap the
books, films and websties devoted to the ongoing fascination with
the mountain. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ADVENTURES _ A list of new and forthcoming books about
real-life adventures, to accompany the story about books on
climbing Mount Everest. (Weaver, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ALTAR _ A visit with Charles Price, author of ``Freedom's
Altar,'' a book about the period immediately after the Civil War
when former slaves and masters attempt to get along. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WHYBUY _ Paco Underhill, whose has been studying the
science of shopping for two decades, explains Why We Buy in a new
book about retail anthropology. For a close-up view of the
psychology of shopping, we follow Underhill through several Atlanta
stores and report on his observations. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Georgia native Frances Mayes figured her book,
``Under the Tuscan Sun,'' would do well, but even she was surprised
when her epicurean travelogue sold 900,000 copies. Now she's back
in town with a follow-up tome, ``Bella Tuscany,'' and at work on a
novel; publishing group to choose 100 best gay and lesbian books of
the century; Oprah's new book club selection is ``White Oleander,''
a stunning first novel reminiscent of Joan Didion's writing.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 21.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WOMAN _ Review of Natalie Angier's book ``Woman: A
Geography,'' getting all sorts of press. (Morris, Austin
American-Statresman).
</P>
