<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CONTAINERS-HNS &LR;      05-13 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CONTAINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE-OUT CONTAINERS POSE DANGER WHEN REHEATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA STEVENS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Recycling and reusing are good for the
environment, but those old margarine tubs you keep using to reheat
leftovers are bad for your health. So are the plastic bowls from
the take-out won-ton soup, and the polystyrene box that held the
chicken wings from yesterday's lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Those containers are fine for the food that was originally
packaged in them, but shouldn't be used for any other purpose,
according to the USDA Food Safety and Inspection Service.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic wrap, foam meat trays, convenience food dishes and egg
cartons have been approved for one-time use and one-time use only,
Bessie Berry of the USDA Meat and Poultry Hotline says. They have
not been tested or approved for any other use, including cooking,
Berry says.
</P>
<P>
   They can't take the heat, so get them out of the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Berry says consumers misuse containers and wraps, which can
contaminate food when heated. Worse yet, the food doesn't have to
come in direct contact with the material to be contaminated. For
example, plastic wrap used to cover a dish for reheating in the
microwave can melt onto the food. Also, excessive heat applied to a
closed container can cause chemical gases to contaminate the food,
according to the Food Safety and Inspection Service.
</P>
<P>
   Microwave food in the package it came in only if the package
says it's microwave safe, and then only use it once, advises the
Food Safety and Inspection Service. Don't let the plastic wrap
touch the food, and do not reuse the wrap. Foam meat trays and
other plastics should not be used in the microwave oven because
they are not heat-stable. To be safe, remove the meat from its
packaging before cooking or defrosting in the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic packaging materials also should not be used in
conventional ovens. They can catch on fire or melt, causing
chemical contamination of the food. Sometimes these plastics are
inadvertently cooked with a product. For instance, giblets might
accidently get cooked inside a turkey or the absorbent pad from a
pork roast might end up in the oven. If this happens and the
packaging materials do not melt or come apart, the cooked meat will
not pose an imminent health hazard, the Food Safety and Inspection
Service says. But if the packaging does become altered, either
melted or changes shape in any way, do not eat the food.
</P>
<P>
   So what kind of wraps and containers can you use in on your
stove, in your microwave and conventional oven? _ Boil-in-bags: A
sealed container made of heat-resistant material that holds food
and allows the bag to reach boiling temperature. Rice, frozen
entrees and some vegetables are packaged in these bags.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oven cooking bags: Both the bags and their closure ties are
made from heat-resistant nylon. They can be used in a microwave or
conventional oven set no higher than 400.
</P>
<P>
   _ Parchment paper: An odorless, tasteless paper made from cotton
fiber and pure chemical wood pulps. The parchment may be waxed or
coated and is greaseproof or grease-resistant. Parchment paper is
primarily used in baking and as a pan liner or to wrap foods in for
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wax paper: A triple-waxed tissue paper; made with a food-safe
paraffin wax that is forced into the pores of the paper and spread
over the outside as a coating.
</P>
<P>
   _ Microwavable containers: Make sure the plasticware says
microwave-safe or microwave heat-resistant. If you're not sure, do
not use it to microwave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
