<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE'S OWNER IS CHARISMATIC, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ At first, it appears he's just too nice. Too
charming, too gracious, too humble. This is the 1990s, and it seems
anyone who acts overly friendly turns out to be a fraud running
some sort of scam. But the more you talk to Bob Lewis, who, along
with his wife, Beverly, owns Kentucky Derby winner Charismatic, the
more you believe he is genuine. It is simply impossible to dislike
the man.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, on Lewis's 75th birthday, he stood near the stakes
barn at Pimlico, where the 124th Preakness will be run Saturday,
and accepted congratulations, while revealing that he knows a
little more about horse racing than most, and a lot more about
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine being this age and having this much fun?''
said Lewis, who survived a heart attack in 1972 and recovered from
subsequent bypass surgery. ``It's just been bubbling over, and it's
really incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob met Beverly when both were students at the University of
Oregon, and they were married in 1947. Their horses run in the
green and yellow of the Oregon Ducks. Bob, whose parents took him
to the races at Santa Anita as a tyke in 1934, made his money as a
beer distributor. The Lewises have been successful almost from the
time they started investing in thoroughbreds in 1990, and last year
their horses, who are trained primarily by D. Wayne Lukas and Bob
Baffert, earned $5.7 million in purses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Wayne and I put Charismatic in that $62,500 claimer (at
Santa Anita Feb. 11), I would have been delighted if he had been
claimed,'' said Lewis. ``I never told Wayne that, but I make no
bones about it. I'd have salvaged $62,500 from the $200,000 I paid
for him. I know that's poor business economics, but Charismatic
loves to eat. He's a glutton and he was eating me out of house and
home. We have 90-plus horses, with 55-60 in training, and finishing
third and fourth doesn't pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in thoroughbred racing could this happen. It just
happened overnight. All of a sudden, a claimer can blossom, and
here we are on hand for another Preakness.'' Silver Charm, owned by
the Lewises and trained by Baffert, won the Derby and Preakness in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The collective egos of Baffert and Lukas wouldn't fit in the
Grand Canyon, yet Lewis deftly manages the two highest profile
trainers in the game. ``My approach was developed by lifelong
experience with business,'' said Lewis. ``You employ people. If
they prove they can do the job, you give them the ball and let them
run with it. We don't interface between the two trainers. We don't
carry communications from one to the other. If you don't honor
their confidences, you hurt your chances. One of the problems
owners have in this business is that they get on a winning streak,
and, all of a sudden, they know more than the trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let the trainers call the shots, and we run along behind
them and spend the money. We've had good counsel, and it's just
come together for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious Lewis knows how to delegate authority. But Lukas
will tell you there's much more to him as a horse owner than that.
``There aren't many Lewises in this sport,'' said Lukas. ``He's a
higher echelon owner. You don't often find people of this caliber
in racing. The way they handle themselves, accepting the ups and
downs, they represent the game so well. They represent me and Bob
well. They're very understanding, win or lose. They are
appreciative of their trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've stepped up to the plate. They didn't get here by
winning the lottery. Bob started as a beer salesman and he's worked
hard. I'll tell you, he's got guts. He's big in the sales ring.
He'll go for $1 million, $1.2 million, $1.5 million. He doesn't
lack the courage of his convictions and he really backs you up. If
I say there's one I want, he won't stop until we get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who is also very active in charity work, is racing's
greatest goodwill ambassador, greeting everyone on a first-name
basis, with a warm smile and a firm handshake. But it's also
obvious he comes to play. Charismatic beat Cat Thief, who is
trained by Lukas but owned by W.T. Young of Overbrook Farm, by less
than a length in the Derby, and Lukas is sending Cat Thief out in
the Preakness. It is possible Cat Thief could cost Charismatic not
only the Preakness but the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cat Thief is a meaningful threat, and Baffert has the two
fillies (Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting),'' said Lewis.
``It's just like the beer business, it's competitive as all get
out. But it's part of this great sport we participate in. I'm
confident, I think we have a hell of a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lewis could probably sell just about anything to just about
anybody. And you'd be happy to buy it.
</P>
</TEXT>
