<HEADLINE>
RETHINKING RADIATION AFTER A BREAST SURGERY  
 OF DIET AND FOLATE LEVELS: FORTIFICATION IS PAYING OFF  
 GAINS IN ANXIETY BATTLE, TESTING FOR COLON CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 Rethinking radiation after a breast surgery
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women who undergo localized breast surgery for the removal of a
common early-stage cancer condition can have their need for
follow-up radiation eliminated if surgeons remove an extra
centimeter of tissue around the lumps, a new study indicates.
</P>
<P>
   The study involves ductal carcinoma in situ, abnormal cell
growths inside milk ducts. DCIS comprises a quarter to a third of
the 180,000 new US breast cancer cases detected each year. Medical
authorities long have debated the health and lifestyle merits of
wider tissue removal versus breast conservation. About half of
later breast cancers in women who have had DCIS removed are
invasive, metastatic forms.
</P>
<P>
   In the current New England Journal of Medicine, Dr. Melvin J.
Silverstein of the University of Southern California School of
Medicine and colleagues (including Dr. Bernard S. Lewinsky,
Monica's father, who is an oncologist) report on 469 women with the
cancer who were treated at two California facilities between 1972
and February 1998. Just under half of them had no follow-up
radiation therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Among women whose lumps were removed with a one-centimeter
margin of tissue (10 millimeters or just over a third of an inch),
more than 97 percent had no recurrence of cancer, and radiation
therapy did not lower recurrence rates. Silverstein's study found
radiation therapy benefited only women who had one millimeter or
less of extra tissue removed around the DCIS.
</P>
<P>
   For women facing a DCIS removal surgery, the findings suggest a
trade-off: Having more tissue removed might alter or disfigure the
breast but eliminate or delay the need for what is normally 30 days
of fatiguing, follow-up radiation treatment. Deferring radiation
has another benefit. Standard US practice is to resort to
mastectomy if a first round of radiation fails to keep cancer away,
but women who had DCIS removal and then got breast cancer could try
radiation before needing a mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dr. Carolyn Kaelin, director of the Comprehensive
Breast Health Center at Boston's Brigham and Women's Hospital,
noted that Silverstein's pathologists used a meticulous way of
measuring how much tissue was removed around the DCIS lump. Their
approach may be too expensive for health plans or hospitals to
support its wide use in advising women whether enough tissue was
removed to justify no radiation. Kaelin said she would encourage
women who choose extra tissue removal in DCIS operations to decline
later radiation only if they were being ``closely followed'' with
semiannual breast examinations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Of diet and folate levels: fortification is paying off
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US government's two-year-old program to require grain-based
products to be enriched with folate, a form of folic acid, is
showing ``substantial improvements'' in people's levels of the
substance, according to another study in the current New England
Journal of Medicine. For women of childbearing age, consuming
adequate folate from food or supplements sharply reduces the risk
of having a baby with spina bifida or a neural tube birth defect,
and it may reduce all people's risk of stroke and heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Tufts University, the Framingham Heart Study,
and Memorial Hospital of Rhode Island followed 1,100 children of
participants in the heart study, comparing blood folate levels from
groups of people seen before grain fortification was required and
after. Overall, average blood folate levels more than doubled after
the change. The percentage of people with low folate concentrations
plunged from 22 percent before to 1.7 percent later. The age of
study participants averaged 55, but the researchers have ``no
reason to believe'' folate fortification is not yielding the same
benefits for women of childbearing age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Gains in anxiety battle, testing for colon cancer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators this week have approved use of Paxil, a
common treatment for depression and panic disorder, for social
anxiety disorder, a debilitating condition. . . . Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center researchers led by Dr. Martina Morrin
report promising results testing a new kind of colon exam that uses
injections of air followed by a CT scan to find possibly cancerous
polyps. Traditional exams use enemas or endoscope insertions. . . .
Eating a Mediterranean-style diet rich in monounsaturated fatty
acids can help prevent memory loss and cognitive slippage in later
life, according to a study in this month's journal Neurology. It
followed 278 Italians who got on average 15 percent of their daily
calories from olive oil, a prime source of the fatty acids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
