<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-FIRES-$ADV16-C     05-13 1891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FIRES-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A YEAR AFTER FIRES, MEXICO'S LAST VIRGIN JUNGLE FACES MORE
DANGER
 &HT;    1200&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: Locator map at end of story file.
 &HT;    For Sun., May 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENITO JUAREZ, Mexico _ Scorched pines appear to scream against
the sky here, the victims of devastating fires that swept through
Mexico last year and sent plumes of smoke wafting into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican forestry experts say parts of the Chimalapas wilderness
in southern Oaxaca and Chiapas states -- which includes Mexico's
last virgin jungle and cloud forest -- were left in ashes and will
need a century or two to grow back.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than forest fires that threaten one of the world's
most biologically diverse landscapes, where pine-studded mountains
blend into lowland jungle and misty cloud forest so rugged it has
never been fully explored.
</P>
<P>
   Although attempts to teach other ways of farming have begun,
many peasants in the Chimalapas this spring are continuing to use
slash-and-burn farming to prepare fields for planting and make way
for cattle.
</P>
<P>
   The centuries-old practice of setting fire to land is killing
off life in once lush valleys and slopes of the Chimalapas. Because
Mexico's National Ecological Institute estimates that more than 95
percent of the country's original tropical and rain forests(CQ)
have been decimated since the Spanish nearly 500 years ago, the
Chimalapas is a precious survivor dear to conservationists.
</P>
<P>
   The forest, which occupies much of Mexico's Isthmus of
Tehuantepec, is home to plants that grow nowhere else on the planet
and endangered animals like jaguars and the green-plumed quetzal
bird.
</P>
<P>
   Slash-and-burn farming was blamed for sparking many of last
year's fires, along with fires set by squatters clearing land for
cattle pastures and narcotics traffickers carving out space to
plant marijuana or opium poppies.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal logging continues to claim threatened cedar and mahogany
in the Chimalapas. And squatters continue to encroach on lands
belonging to the native Zoque (pronounced, ``So-kay'') Indians
sparking violent clashes over land ownership the government has so
far failed to address.
</P>
<P>
   After the fires last year, a presidential decree was issued to
prevent charred forest from being colonized. But the World Wildlife
Fund and Zoque natives here fear the decree is being ignored --
easy enough in a region so remote and wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man's only limits to moving in are his own,'' said Domingo
Jimenez, a Zoque Indian with a third-grade education who fought
fires last year and is a passionate environmentalist, organic
farmer and foe of slash-and-burn agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Casteneda of the World Wildlife Fund in Oaxaca said the
organization has already received reports of people moving into
fire-damaged areas.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF collaborated with the Mexican government on a post-fire
study that estimated that at least 35 percent of the vast
Chimalapas forest -- which is more than 1.4 million acres -- was
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated four percent of the damaged area was completely
incinerated.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the WWF and the government agree that most remote
sections of the jungle terrain are too sensitive to be reforested
by humans.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of acres of jungle teems with as many as 400 species of
flora or fauna and reforestation would probably upset that delicate
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the diversity is so great that if people don't enter
the forest to use the land or raise cattle on it then it has a
greater chance of recovering,'' Casteneda said. ``But in no less
than 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wendt, a University of Texas at Austin botanist who began
exploring the Chimalapas in the late 1970s, said keeping people out
is key.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fires were devastating,'' he said. ``But the real problem
is what happens next.''
</P>
<P>
   Squatters have been picking at the edges of the Chimalapas for
decades, eroding pines by repeated burnings and moving further into
the heart of the forest, where only a handful of communities are
legally entitled to own land.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists are worried that a highway under construction
on the forest's northern border with Veracruz will cut through the
jungle and create more pressure to open up it up for exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   Oaxacan government officials are considering making the
Chimalapas a protected biological reserve. But they've run into
resistance from the Zoque, who fear outsiders will end up
exploiting the forest, not protecting it.
</P>
<P>
   Homero Aridjis, a writer and one of Mexico's most outspoken
environmentalists, says the Zoque have a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in Mexico is that laws protecting biological
reserves are constantly being violated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez agrees, and believes the Zoque should be made stewards
of a reserve. ``We know the valuable resource we have and we know
we're capable of taking care of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old farmer lives in Benito Juarez, a hamlet of
wooden huts with no electricity that's three hours into the
Chimalapas by car and 40 miles from the nearest paved road.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bone-crunching drive with rivers to ford and narrow
twists that drop off into mist-filled canyons.
</P>
<P>
   Peaks topped by cloud forest soar above pines covered in
epiphytes and flocks of parrots circle in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez knows the Chimalapas as well as anyone, and last year he
walked through smoke and flames into the jungle to cut landing
zones for firefighters dropped in by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   The carbonized remains of pines and other trees disturb the
beauty of the landscape along the road to Benito Juarez. But the
most devastated areas -- where 200- and 300-year-old trees were
killed -- are at least a six-hour hike into the jungle, Jimenez
said.
</P>
<P>
   When smoke from the Chimalapas fires and others in Mexico wafted
across the Gulf of Mexico in May 1998, communities in Texas were
forced to declare environmental alerts. After diplomatic haggling,
Mexico finally asked for help and a team of U.S. firefighting
experts arrived in the Chimalapas to offer technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The United States spent $7.6 million in aid, especially for the
rental of special airplanes to help douse flames that hop-scotched
through the jungle. Never before, natives said, had the moist cloud
forest been consumed by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mexico's spring rains were late last year, the jungle
was drier and vulnerable to sparks from controlled fires that
leaped out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez and other farmers who harbor a deep distrust for the
government also believe arsonists set fires to help open the way
for the government's large highway project.
</P>
<P>
   This year rain has already moistened the Chimalapas, squelching
fear of a similar catastrophe, said Oscar Sedeno, director of
forestry for Mexico's environmental ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Although slash-and-burn farming has not been prohibited, Sedeno
said, federal officials are offering workshops on how farmers can
turn the remains of corn stalks and other crops into mulch rather
than burning their fields.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez, who belongs to an environmental group in Oaxaca called
Maderas del Pueblo, or Forests for the People, is way ahead of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Trained by Maderas del Pueblo, he's been leading a revolution
among villagers by teaching organic farming methods.
</P>
<P>
   He's been slashing and plowing under crop remains for five
years, fertilizing his land with compost he makes instead of
relying on ash from burnings. He mixes insecticides from the same
herbs he uses as medicinal teas and poultices.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 80 families in Benito Juarez have been converted to
organic farming, especially after they saw Jimenez's crop yields
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to just strike a match and walk away,''
Jimenez said. ``It's almost double the work to plow the field
under. But it pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The village of Benito Juarez and neighboring villages of outside
colonizers live in an uneasy truce. But Jimenez says many outsiders
aren't interested in protecting the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Fights over control of the Chimalapas go back to colonial times,
when Jimenez's ancestors were forced to buy back their land from
the Spanish, giving birth to the name, ``Chimalapas,'' which means
``gourd full of gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the road to Benito Juarez, Jimenez surveys fresh ash
covering a hillside that a colonizer has burned for several years
each spring so new grass will grow as pasture land.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day nothing will grow here, not grass, not trees,''
Jimenez said. ``There are alternatives to this, but it's hard to
break with tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Fires set by other farmers were crackling along the road, some
smoldering unattended -- a violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Benito Juarez resident Miguel Maya turned over the names of two
offenders of the law to authorities this month and is waiting to
hear the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should get jail,'' he said. ``The people who burn the
forest endanger the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Maya joined one of the new fire brigades Mexico's environmental
ministry established this year to patrol Mexican forests at risk.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Chimalapas still doesn't have sufficient look-out
towers, but at least the brigades are better equipped than last
year, when kerchief-clad peasants tried to fight fires by swatting
at flames with branches.
</P>
<P>
   Sedeno said the country has tried to improve its firefighting
capability over the last year with more training, radio
communication systems and public information campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   This month U.S. Forest Service employees paid a follow-up visit
to talk about safety in areas where firefighter fatalities
occurred, Sedeno said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has established a system for offering quick
financial and technical support again if Mexico requests it, said a
spokesperson at the United States Agency for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mexico was severely criticized at home and in the
United States for not requesting aid sooner from the United States
to extinguish the fires, some of the worst this century.
</P>
<P>
   ....................................................................
....................................................................
.......
</P>
<P>
   MAP INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Benito Juarez, Oaxaca is a village inside the Chimalapas forest,
which occupies half of Mexico's Isthmus of Tehuantepec.
</P>
<P>
   For big picture purposes, Benito Juarez is about 254 miles
southeast of the capital city of Oaxaca and about 40 miles north of
the small city of Zanatepec, which is on Highway 190 on the
southern half of the Isthmus. Zanatepec is 53 miles east of the
city of Juchitan, a relatively large city also on Mexico's Highway
190.
</P>
<P>
   The Chimalapas forest is a massive area of some 1,467,180 acres.
Its western border is, roughly, Mexico's Highway 185 and its
southern border is Highway 190. To the west, the forest extends
into Chiapas almost to the city of Cintalapa and north to the
reservoir Netzahualcoyotl. The northern border of the forest is the
state of Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
   ....................................................................
....................................................................
