<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISPLAY OF EXCESS IN `PHANTOM MENACE' COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time magazine has already devoted a cover story to ``Episode I _
The Phantom Menace,'' replete with ``exclusive pictures'' and an
interview with filmmaker George Lucas. Entertainment Weekly
produced its own cover treatment, hyping ``ten pages of exclusive
photos.'' It's been celebrated on the pages of Vanity Fair, Wired,
and even Popular Mechanics. A computer search _ just for the period
from May 3 to May 11 _ unearthed almost 600 stories on the ``Star
Wars'' phenomenon. Variety film reporter Oliver Jones calls it
``the most hyped movie in the history of movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this mind-boggling, stage-managed, pre-event
publicity, the decision of three newspapers to publish reviews last
weekend before the film's May 19 opening has provoked cries of
jounalistic skulduggery from 20th Century-Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all lived for the last 20 years with trust in each
other,'' says Fox Domestic Film Group chairman Tom Sherak,
referring to the unwritten agreement between studios and newspapers
that films will not be reviewed until they open. ``These people
have broken that trust. . . . What do we teach our kids about our
words, our ethics, our morals?''
</P>
<P>
   If Sherak's sense of deep moral betrayal seems to strain
credulity, that's because it does. Cynics noted that Fox's response
may have something to do with the fact that two of the early
reviews _ in The New York Daily News and The Toronto Star _ were
less than enthusiastic. (The third scofflaw, the Los Angeles Daily
News, handed out three and-a-half stars. And USA Today chimed in
with a three-star review Wednesday.) Jones thinks the studio
doesn't ``honestly care'' about early reviews, but that the protest
may be intended ``to engender sympathy because the advance word on
the movie has not been great.''
</P>
<P>
   The gentleman's agreement on reviews has loopholes big enough to
drive an 18-wheeler through. Newsweeklies, for example, are exempt
from the embargo foisted on newspapers. Early Internet reviews now
sprout like weeds. And then there is the laughable hairsplitting.
Detroit Free Press film critic Terry Lawson went to a screening
last Friday and wrote a Sunday piece cataloging the impressions of
his colleagues (``the instant reviews were decidedly mixed.'')
Doesn't that qualify as a review? Not according to Sherak, who gave
Lawson a clean bill of health.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the embargo breakers are not exactly contrite. ``We
thought the hype and orchestrated leaks about the film really took
it into another category,'' said Jim Travers, managing editor of
The Toronto Star. ``What they are trying to do is use us as the
hype mechanism.'' Los Angeles Daily News entertainment editor Rob
Lowman was also unmoved by criticism from the ``Star Wars''
spinmasters, noting that they tried to ``control and create the
media buzz at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment Weekly film critic Owen Gleiberman sees a rough
justice in all this. ``The grand irony (is that) the early negative
buzz has basically been the hype of the movie coming back to bite
the studio,'' he said. ``It's a bit disingenuous for them to be
complaining about this when they've basically been counting on
weeks and weeks of publicity. I think the whole media crossed the
line with this movie. Too much, too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the marketer, a ``disappointed'' Sherak, manages to mix one
final ``Star Wars'' plug with his media scolding, characterizing
those embargo-breaking papers as ``the true side of the dark side
of the force.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like the Vietnam War itself, the bitter residue of CNN's
``Valley of Death'' story refuses to fade into history. That
program _ on June 7, 1998, alleging US use of nerve gas in a covert
mission during the Vietnam War _ left a bloody trail of
professional casualties. (The most recent was Peter Arnett, the
``Valley of Death'' narrator who departed CNN last month and just
signed on with www.foreigntv.com, a new Internet global news
outlet.)
</P>
<P>
   Of all the parties to this fiasco, no one has battled harder to
regain her reputation than April Oliver, the fired CNN producer who
has insisted that ``Valley of Death'' was solid journalism and that
CNN buckled under pressure to disavow it.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN has served us up to the military with great fanfare,''
Oliver said after filing a May 7 lawsuit against CNN and a
countersuit against retired Major General John Singlaub.
</P>
<P>
   Singlaub, who sued Oliver and CNN for defamation last year, has
been a vocal critic of ``Valley of Death.'' What raised eyebrows
was Oliver's decision to identify him in her suit as a confidential
source who confirmed crucial aspects of ``Valley of Death'' in six
conversations with her. Singlaub's attorney, Philip O'Neil, said
Singlaub ``does not deny talking to'' Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's identification of Singlaub invited comparisons to Mike
Gallagher, the former Cincinnati Enquirer reporter who identified a
confidential source to minimize his criminal liability for stolen
voice mail messageshe used in an investigative report on Chiquita
Brands International.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did make the promise to go to jail to protect him,'' said
Oliver of her confidentiality agreement with Singlaub. ``Once he
sued me, I was released. . . . He thrust it on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the circumstances, journalistic ethics experts tend to
agree with Oliver. ``I think all bets are off when your source sues
you,'' said Paul McMasters, the Freedom Forum's First Amendment
ombudsman. ``If there's ever an occasion where (naming a
confidential source) is justifiable, this is it,'' added Jane
Kirtley, executive director of the Reporters Committee for Freedom
of the Press. ``Essentially, you're talking about a complete
breakdown between source and journalist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
