<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW FOR NEW MOTHERS: EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the first session of every new mother support group she
leads, parent educator Margaret Hannah drops what amounts to a
bombshell: You need to grieve the person you were before you became
a mother, because you will never be her again.
</P>
<P>
   For women struggling to know ``Who am I now that I'm a mom?''
this is not exactly a comforting thought.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah is undeterred. She approaches the topic almost like
castor oil for the psyche: Even if the who-am-I question is not
causing anxiety, even if you have not yet articulated it to
yourself, getting it out in the open makes you feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming a mother is a huge psychological event. It takes
adjusting to,'' agrees developmental psychologist Brenda Hunter of
Vienna, Va., who has studied the subject for decades and is author
of ``The Power of Mother Love'' (Water Brook).
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, women overdo preparation for the logistics of
motherhood _ stocking a nursery, reading baby-care books,
interviewing a pediatrician _ and underdo coping with what Hunter
calls the psychic earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   That lapse can have profound ramifications years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your kids are grown when you wonder for the first time,
`Who am I?' it's scarier and harder to figure out,'' says social
psychologist and researcher Carin Rubenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why this is a starting point for Hannah, who leads
groups for WarmLines, a parent resource center in Newton. Amy
Hummel of Brookline, whose son Conor is 12 weeks old, can already
see changes in herself. ``I always thought of myself as a fearless
person, but suddenly I'm fearful of all sorts of things,'' she
says. ``It's very nerve-racking.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear that something might happen to the baby and,
concurrently, that you are responsible for its survival, is
probably the most awesome of emotions new mothers feel. Even women
who have worked for years in powerful and important jobs say this
is the line in the sand that makes them feel truly grown-up, says
Rubinstein. She is author of ``The Sacrificial Mother: Escaping the
Trap of Self-Denial'' (Hyperion).
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make any woman feel inadequate _ ``How can I do
this?'' ``Will I ever get it right?'' _ and vulnerable. That, in
turn, affects her sense of herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many ways in which we have to relinquish control,
because things are out of our control,'' says Hannah. ``To many
women, this feels like they are making mistakes. That makes them
feel bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Hummel wasn't necessarily a risk-taker, but she wasn't a
worrier, either, and as a dedicated runner she knows what it means
to be passionate about something. Nonetheless, the love she feels
for Conor is far more intense than she expected, and so is the fear
and worry. When it threatens to overtake her, she looks for joy in
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I focus on the here and now, like that he's smiling today.
Then I feel emboldened instead of vulnerable,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Not all woman are able to do that; indeed, many become
immobilized. When she was a new mother, psychologist Harriet
Lerner, author of ``The Mother Dance: How Children Change Your
Life'' (HarperCollins), remembers being unprepared for how
frightened and emotional she felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You discover you're open to a wider range of emotions,'' she
says, ``including that you aren't the clear-thinking, highly
evolved person you fancied yourself to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, she says, ``You wrap feelings of guilt and
inadequacy around you like a familiar blanket, even if they are
feelings you never had before.'' She felt guilty even before the
birth of her first child. A difficult pregnancy led to a premature
labor, and she remembers being sad: If she couldn't even get
pregnancy right, what kind of mother would she be?
</P>
<P>
   A more humble person, for starters. One of the first changes she
noticed was a newfound sense of humility. ``Before I had
children,'' says Lerner, ``I was amazed at the `improper' behavior
of other mothers. I knew I would never yell at my kids, fight with
my husband in their earshot, or feed them at McDonald's. Of course,
I've done all of those things and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about motherhood,'' she says, ``is that we don't
have a clue what it will evoke in us until it's our turn.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some research, however, that predicts how we will
react. Studies bear out the idea known as attachment theory: A
child's early ``attachment'' to her mother will affect that child's
ability to form other relationships throughout her life. Thus a
woman whose own mother was warm and caring will be less anxious,
less vulnerable, and more nurturing than a woman whose mother was
emotionally unavailable to her. The woman who wasn't nurtured
herself tends to be more fearful, because she feels less capable;
in order to compensate for her higher sense of vulnerability, she
tends to be more rigid _ keeping a strict schedule, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman who had a lot of nurturing has a stronger sense of
herself and brings more confidence to her mothering,'' says Hunter.
``It's as if there's a deeper well of her own mother love to draw
upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Maura Wayman, also in Hannah's group, may be a good example. The
oldest of five children, she was raised in a nurturing family where
she began baby-sitting at 8. She says she and her sisters are calm,
confident mothers who rarely second-guess themselves. The
responsibility of motherhood ``doesn't feel scary to me,'' she
says, ``but it does surprise me that, no matter how tired you are,
you are able to do what you have to do and do it with love.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter says that's because women with a nurturing history are
more able to ``surrender to motherhood: to go with the flow as
opposed to saying, `This baby isn't going to change my life.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, women who don't have the well of nurturance to draw
from aren't doomed. Two things can make a difference for them:
</P>
<P>
   --A supportive husband who nurtures her while she nurtures the
baby;
</P>
<P>
   --A community. Whether it's a mothers' group, an extended
family, or an informal network of women, ``knowing you're not alone
gives you perspective and strength,'' says Rubenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the question of ``Who am I?'' is most vivid
around questions of work. The woman with a strong personal history
of nurturing, studies show, has an easier time making decisions
about whether to go part time, leave temporarily, or change to a
position with less status. ``It's less of a crisis,'' Hunter says,
``because she has a stronger sense of self.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayman had an easy time making the decision to work only part
time as a corporate video producer, but she felt split between her
roles as professional and mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was odd my first day back. Everyone treated me the same,
which was good in one way but weird in another,'' she says. ``I
wanted to say, `Do you know how different I am? I'm a mom!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hannah tells women that they often become more efficient and
more compassionate as workers. ``When you see you are competent
enough to have life-and-death responsibility for a baby, it changes
your perspective. Office politics may seem petty.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman Rubenstein worries about most is the one who buries
her identity when she becomes a mother. ``You still need to do the
things you love, the things that make you you,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months after giving birth, she says, mothers need
to reengage to some degree in activities they enjoy, from running
to reading. Otherwise, they become sacrificial, not even seeing
themselves as a separate person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like that,'' she says. ``I didn't buy clothes for myself
for years. But it's not healthy for yourself or your children.''
For every woman, the balance of being a person versus being a
mother is different and sometimes a struggle to achieve, ``but you
need to at least work at it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Wayman thinks of herself as a pie whose slices are thinner than
before. ``I can still do things I like to do, just with a lot less
intensity,'' she says. ``I used to go mountain biking three times a
week, now I go only once. If we see friends, it's for two hours,
not four.'' Amy Hummel, who did an ultra-marathon before she
conceived, no longer runs every day but still runs ``when I need
to,'' albeit at 5 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   As much as she enjoys it, however, there's also something
different about it that reflects what Hannah says about never being
the same. ``Before, my head was always into the run,'' says Hummel.
``Now my head is back home, with Conor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AFTERTHOUGHT: Newly published: ``Creating Ceremonies: Innovative
Ways to Meet Adoption Challenges'' by Cheryl A. Lieberman and Rhea
K. Bufferd (Zeig, Tucker &AMP; Co., Phoenix).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Accept that you will have irrational fears and worries about
safety and health. Make a deal with your pediatrician so you can
say, ``I'm having an irrational worry right now . . .''
</P>
<P>
   --Women who struggled to conceive tend to struggle most with
questions of self-identity, coming down harder on themselves for
any ambivalent thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   --Emotions in the first few weeks or month are often due to
hormonal surges, not necessarily part of the identity struggle.
</P>
<P>
   --When you make time for yourself, don't do it when no one in
your family sees it happening but rather when they can notice, so
that it registers that you think enough of yourself to take time
for yourself. It's not only good modeling, but also sends a
message: ``I count, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz is author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell). She
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
