<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT DRUG TRADE: LUXURY CARS ARE CURRENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Mass. _ After more than 10 years tracking the deadly
commerce of street drug crime, Hartford Police Sergeant Christopher
Lyons thought he had seen every exchange imaginable: Drugs for
cash. Drugs for guns. Drugs for jewelry. Drugs for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lyons and others say, Hartford's drug dealers and buyers
have found something new to trade: Cars for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the aftermath of the crack '90s, they have come to be
known in Hartford and other areas of the state as ``half-g'' cars _
cars rented by the hour or day to drug dealers, typically in return
for a half-gram of cocaine. In some cases, strung-out addicts short
on cash loan the cars indefinitely to pay back deep debts to
unforgiving suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the phenomenon drew widespread attention and fueled
community-wide anger in Hartford after a black teenager was shot by
police following a chase. The teen, Aquan Salmon, was riding with
friends in a car later identified as a half-g car, registered to a
white female from an outlying suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have tracked the emergence of half-g's in Connecticut
say the trend has mushroomed with deadly potential, arming young
dealers with new mobility and a new sense of power. Once a code
word among street gangs, they say, half-g's have become familiar
shorthand in narcotics units from Hartford to Bridgeport to New
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big problem, and I don't see an end to it,'' said
Lyons, who headed the Hartford Police Department's gang task force
in the early 1990s and watched the trend emerge. ``The people
buying the crack come in with their cars, and they smoke for as
long as they can. And then the kids use the car for all kinds of
other crimes _ drive-bys, delivering drugs to other locations,
robberies, reckless driving, you name it.''
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about how widely the trend has spread
nationally. Police and researchers who track drug and gang activity
in Massachusetts say the phenomenon has not crossed the border.
Even Connecticut law enforcement officials are divided about
whether the trend might be occurring in other cities, and known by
another name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see people selling drugs for cars, for weapons, for lots of
things,'' said Bridgeport Police Sergeant Rafael Villegas, who is
assigned to the FBI's gang task force for the city. ``We've even
seen junkies who lease their cars out all the time, going from one
high to the next. It's the enterprise system.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hartford, police say it would be nearly impossible to
document or prove every half-g transaction.
</P>
<P>
   But Lyons said he knew something was up when he began seeing
street kids _ kids he had always seen walking or riding the buses _
riding in legally registered cars, many of them high-end Hondas,
Acuras, or even Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were coming across case after case where kids in the city
were driving around in these cars,'' Lyons said. ``These were 14-
and 15 year-olds. We'd stop some of them and ask where they got the
car from, and they'd say, `Oh, it's my friend from Stratford or New
Haven or Berlin.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, owners of cars began reporting them stolen
after dealers refused to return them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, you have these owners saying their cars were
stolen, then the car turns up with the keys in the engine, and the
ignition isn't even popped,'' said retired Hartford Deputy Police
Chief Gerry Pleasent. ``You look at that and you know something is
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally used in cocaine deals, the phenomenon now involves
trades of almost any drug, in varying amounts, for anywhere from a
few hours to a few days' use of a car.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the new-fangled street leases, officials say, is
a symbiosis between suburban addicts and young urban street dealers
who live worlds apart but share a common craving: anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   For suburbanites hiding crippling habits, the exchange offers
hours-long binges three or four highway exits from home, without
having to give up hard cash. For the teenage lookouts, runners, and
small-time dealers who make up the core of the industry, a half-g
is a ``clean'' ride, a new opportunity to commit crimes without
being traced.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the whole war on drugs, cars were the weak link for a lot
of these kids,'' said Sergeant Maura Hammick, spokeswoman for the
Hartford Police Department. ``It has a plate that can be traced. It
has a distinction to it. If a kid drove it all the time, neighbors
would know, and if someone witnessed the car in a crime, they could
say `Oh, that's so-and-so's car.'
</P>
<P>
   Following a national push to crack down on street-level drug
dealing by seizing cars involved in drug crimes, Hammick said, ``it
became very appealing to some of these kids to use a complete
stranger's car, because nothing they did could be traced back to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the shooting of Aquan Salmon, community
activists have called for new statutes targeting drug users who
loan cars to urban teenagers in exchange for drugs. While a
polarized community in Hartford waits for state investigators to
conclude their probe into the case, some say the consequences for
buying drugs must be handed down equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in from the suburbs, score their drugs and get on
out of town, and those people who are living here end up getting
all the (jail) time,'' said the Rev. Nora Wyatt, Jr., president of
The Greater Hartford African American Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt said the half-g trend preys on young teens who have known
only poverty. Many of them have never seen a Mercedes-Benz or a
Lexus, much less driven one, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have laws so that people contributing to kids
committing crimes are held as responsible as the kids themselves,''
he said. ``They're part of the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1321EDT &QL; 
