<SLUG> BC-AUTO-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODEL DIVERSITY STARTS ON THE `PLATFORM' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the early 1990s and General Motors was a wounded
automotive giant. The company's product line was stagnant, its
reputation tarnished, its bottom line suffering.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point was the company's Cadillac division, longtime
top American producer of luxury automobiles, which suddenly found
itself lacking as other companies, notably foreign manufacturers,
flooded the market with cheaper luxurious cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we needed an entry-level luxury car,'' recalls
Jan-Willem Vester, assistant director of communications at
Cadillac. But the problem, with cash tight, was how to develop a
new car from scratch. The answer, and one which is playing a
significant role in auto development today, was simple: Don't.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cadillac looked to Germany where GM's Opel branch was
already manufacturing an entry-level luxury car, the Omega. Today,
using the platform on which the Omega is based, Cadillac builds its
entry-level Catera and sells it anywhere in the world the Omega is
not sold.
</P>
<P>
   Platform-sharing, long practiced effectively as body-on-frame
construction in the world of trucks, is today a significant player
in the ability of auto manufacturers to enter and compete in the
myriad of niche markets that have sprung up on auto lots across the
land.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking plain old ``badge swapping'' as practiced by
GM in the 1980s, when it fooled no one that a Chevy was really a
Caddy or that a simple change in hood ornamentation meant different
handling and performance.
</P>
<P>
   We are talking sedans that become small SUVs; four-seaters that
become whistling two-seat coupes; trucks that become behemoth SUVs;
trucks that become SUTs _ as in Sport/Utility Trucks. And it's all
done on identical or similar platforms with common attachment
points for engines, suspension systems and the sheetmetal that
forms the widely different bodies of the various models.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about cost-effectiveness in a world where a good niche
might mean 25,000 annual sales of a particular model _ good numbers
but hardly enough to warrant from-scratch development. Instead,
using about 20 percent shared components, manufacturers are
building truly different cars on similar platforms and building
some cars that might otherwise never have been developed.
</P>
<P>
   Seen the New Beetle, that zippy little commuter vehicle from
Volkswagen? It's built on the same platform as the VW Golf. And
when you spot your first Audi TT Coupe, note that it, too, is built
on the same platform.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is doing the same with its SUT (essentially, an SUV with
its back cut off to allow for some semblance of a pickup truck bed)
and its new SUV, the Xterra.
</P>
<P>
   Ford rolled out a Thunderbird prototype earlier this year. It
will share platform characteristics with the Lincoln LS and the
Jaguar S-type.
</P>
<P>
   And when you see one of the behemoth, four-door Ford F-Series
pickup trucks, with an 8-foot bed roll by, picture that enclosed as
the company's giant new SUV, the Excursion, which will be nearly a
foot longer than the Chevrolet Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   There can be ``great, massive difference between models,'' says
Ford spokesman Mike Vaughn, ``but why not gain the efficiency of
sharing platforms?''
</P>
<P>
   If there has been a star on the stage of shared platforms, it
would have to be the Toyota Camry. You'll find its platform on the
Lexus ES300 sedan and in stretched or altered versions on the
Sienna minivan, the swank Avalon, and even the Lexus RX300 SUV.
</P>
<P>
   It was through alteration of the Camry platform that Lexus was
able to quickly enter the SUV field. The big Lexus LX470 and the
Toyota Land Cruiser also share a platform. Further, Toyota plans to
put its 2000 Celica atop the Corolla platform, making the Celica
``lighter and peppier'' with as much as 180 horspower, according to
Wade Hoyt, a Toyota spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect example of how shared platforms can let a company roll
out a fairly specialized auto can be found at DaimlerChrysler,
itself a recent hybrid. They've developed the new Neon, a year 2000
model that will be sold under both the Dodge and Plymouth badges.
This is a pretty standard move and at that level of auto, consumers
don't seem to mind even if they know badge-swapping is going on.
</P>
<P>
   But what is intriguing is that DaimlerChrysler used the
development of this platform to launch a radically different car,
the Chyrsler PT Cruiser. Jan Zzerina, the company's senior manager
for car and truck platforms, likens this development process to
getting two cars for the price of one. At just over $1 billion in
development costs, he's right on the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, shared platforms make it easier from many
aspects when you talk about an overall program investment,''
Zzerina says.
</P>
<P>
   ``By getting all these shared efficiencies up front we end up
with a common framework, a common process'' yet when the two cars
roll off the assembly line ``we have very distinct products
visually'' with different wheel bases, different engines, different
performance characteristics and, most important, widely different
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   As consumers stalk the auto landscape looking for the latest
trend, swapping the van for the truck for the SUV for the SUT for
the sports car, what Zzerina calls ``flexible architecture'' will
be a key in any company's meeting our needs at prices we can
afford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
