<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADCLIFFE-DONATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADCLIFFE DONATIONS RISE IN RESPONSE TO CHANGE IN ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Heartened by the recent announcement that it would
reshape itself into a Harvard institute for the study of women,
Radcliffe College donors have been contributing in record numbers,
with $6.5 million given in the three weeks since the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of pledges, compared with $4 million in the nine
months before the announcement, came as a relief to officials at
both Harvard and Radcliffe, who feared that alumnae would be so
angry that the college had ceded the education of undergraduate
women to Harvard that they would refuse, even rescind, donations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, donors and alumnae appear to be championing the new
role for the 105-year old women's college, hailed as a major
addition to a university still struggling to shake a longstanding
``women problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The new pledges range from $150,000 to $2 million, and come from
non-alumnae as well as alumnae, men as well as women. One alumna
changed her will the week after the announcement of the Harvard
merger, leaving the new Radcliffe $1.5 million when she died two
weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Some donations were unexpected, other donors had been long
expected to make some kind of gift. But what sealed the deal, the
college's fund-raisers say, was the announcement on April 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their way of saying, `I really believe this is going to
be a significant piece of the future with Harvard and Radcliffe,'
'' said Joanna Brode, Radcliffe's director of development. ``The
future looks terrific. People are giving to what there is at
Radcliffe already and what they expect the future will be, based on
Harvard's new commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe was originally founded to educate a gender that as
late as 1969 a Harvard dean said would not make ``any significant
contributions to society.'' An agreement in the mid-1970s allowed
women to be jointly admitted to Harvard and Radcliffe, but
Radcliffe retained its independence and functions as the college
for undergraduate women at Harvard, granting degrees and
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   That undergraduate role ended with the agreement approved by the
boards of trustees of both institutions and announced in April.
Harvard is to absorb Radcliffe's $450 million in real estate and
endowment into its own $13 billion portfolio, and contribute $350
million to endow the new Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study,
which is to be primarily focused on women, gender, and society.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe trustees fought with Harvard in nearly two years of
merger negotiations to prevent the women's college from being
demoted to an affiliate, which would have put it on par with the
Arnold Arboretum or Memorial Church within the Harvard universe.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that Radcliffe would become a so-called ``tub''
_ on par with the law school, or the Kennedy School _ was seen as a
victory for Radcliffe and for women at Harvard. It was even more of
a victory to those who had watched Harvard's public battles over
the relatively small number of tenured women professors, which
remains about half the national average. A report done by Harvard
administrators two years ago acknowledged that women do not feel
invested in the university, either as students or as alumnae.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe alumnae had resisted relinquishing the undergraduate
role, saying Harvard needed Radcliffe to prod it on tenure, the
mentoring of new graduates, and issues of particular interest to
undergraduate women, like sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honestly surprised that there hasn't been more
negativity,'' Brode said. ``There's sadness, as there is with
anything that changes or passes, or comes to an end and starts a
new beginning. But everyone feels very good that Harvard has . . .
validated Radcliffe and its program.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement to create the new Institute, Radcliffe
President Linda S. Wilson said, would do more to promote women's
interests _ at Harvard and beyond. While the institute will not
grant degrees, it will hire faculty for the first time in its
history. (Classes at the original Radcliffe were taught by Harvard
professors in their off hours.)
</P>
<P>
   The burst of support from the Radcliffe community, Harvard
president Neil L. Rudenstine said, ``reinforces what we all
believe, that the Radcliffe Institute will be an enormously
important resource for Harvard and for the scholarly world at
large. These early signs of support help to ensure that the
Institute will be well-launched and well-supported from the
outset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
