<HEADER>
A5528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-SUMMER-BOS &LR;      05-13 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICKLY BOY-WONDER FACES TEST OF POLITICAL SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Larry Summers mastered macroeconomics. He chewed
through problems in finance, in taxation, in labor economics,
writing papers so numerous and insightful that Harvard made him a
tenured professor at age 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are fields that people specialize in and try to carve
out careers in,'' said Dale Jorgenson, a Harvard economics
professor. ``Larry took them all on at the same time. There are a
lot of geniuses around here, but there's no doubt that Larry always
stood out by comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy-wonder economist has been slower to grasp the subtle art
of politics, however, where a soft touch is important and those
with less nimble minds, when they hold high office, must be
respected. Now, nine years after leaving Harvard for Washington,
Summers's political and intellectual skills will face their
greatest test if he becomes the next US Treasury Secretary,
replacing Robert Rubin, who resigned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Currently the No. 2 Treasury official, Summers was nominated by
President Clinton for the top job. Senate confirmation is
considered likely.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old Summers will be the first Treasury chief in
memory who is also a ``technical'' economist _ a man who thrives on
the fractions and equations in textbooks. Economics is in his
blood: He is the son of two economists and the nephew of two Nobel
prize-winning economic thinkers, Paul Samuelson and Kenneth Arrow.
</P>
<P>
   But Summers will also have to massage egos on Capital Hill and
on Wall Street to do his job well. Although he has apparently
worked in recent years to smooth his notoriously prickly edges,
many people in Washington still remember demeaning lectures from a
man commonly called abrasive and arrogant -- a huge contrast to the
genteel and smiling Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is more political and partisan than Rubin,'' said
Representative Jim Saxton, a New Jersey Republican who deals often
with the Treasury as chairman of Congress's Joint Economic
Committee. ``I hope he will grow into this new role.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As the day-to-day face of the Treasury Department on Capitol
Hill, he has been abrasive and rude,'' said a Republican aide who
works often with Treasury officials. ``He's super-bright, but not
modest about it,'' said Gary Hufbauer, a scholar at the Institute
for International Economics. Rather than using gentle persuasion,
he said, Summers has a ``tendency to try to educate you in a way
that's moderately or severely humiliating.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics are still quick to mention that Summers, while chief
economist at the World Bank in the early 1990s, signed on to a memo
that suggested that developing countries were ``under-polluted''
and could make money by accepting more toxic waste. The incident
left Summers looking like an indifferent academic, with no heart --
and no ear for politics. He later described the memo as a mistake
and said it did not reflect his views.
</P>
<P>
   As the Treasury's top deputy for international affairs, Summers
took heat from Congress over a 1995 loan package to Mexico during
its peso crisis, an incident during which many lawmakers complained
that the Clinton administration kept them in the dark and ignored
their authority.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, business lobbyists still smart at a comment Summers
made while a Treasury official that the only argument in favor of
lower estate taxes was ``selfishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few doubt that the Senate will confirm his nomination.
Summers has been a key part of the team that has won wide credit
for the nation's long-running prosperity, at a time when Asia and
much of the rest of the world sank into recession. Time magazine
put him on its cover as part of the ``Committee to Save the
World,'' along with Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Summers's reach has been as vast as his academic
exploits. He has been a central player on issues ranging from
Social Security, to reforming the International Revenue Service to
the global warming debate, in which he helped persuade President
Clinton to reduce its commitment to an international effort to
lower certain pollutant emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Summers has also been the administration's point man behind the
international rescue-loan packages for troubled Asian nations. He
has shuttled at times from Indonesia, to South Korea and China,
earning him a comparison to former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   While has the Asian crisis has subsided, some critics have
charged that US policy needlessly forced troubled Asian nations to
raise taxes and interest rates, which threw millions of people into
joblessness and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   As he became an international diplomat, Summers also has
apparently worked to become more diplomatic in his dealings in
Washington. ``I think a lot of the rough edges have come off,''
said Robert Litan, a scholar at the Brookings Institute. ``Larry's
become a statesman. He's learned the lingo and how to stroke egos.
That's a skill you learn in Washington. It's not a skill you have
to practice in academia.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence H. Summers was born in 1954 in New Haven. The father of
twin daughters and a son, he is married to Victoria Summers, a tax
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, the family owned a home in Newton. Summers's latest
government financial disclosure statement, for 1997, shows assets
of at least $900,000 _ far less than Rubin, who made tens of
millions of dollars on Wall Street. It also shows liabilities of
more than $500,000, primarily from a mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Summers earned his undergraduate degree at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology in 1975. As a sophomore, a recommendation
from his father won him a coveted job as a researcher to Martin
Feldstein, the high-profile Harvard economist. Over the next few
years, the two became partners, and they eventually wrote
pioneering papers on the effects of taxation on capital formation.
Some credit their work with helping to convince Congress to cut tax
rates in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Summers won a job on the MIT faculty before he finished his
doctoral work at Harvard. He was named a tenured Harvard professor
in 1983, and is widely believed to have been the youngest person
with that distinction at the time.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard spokesman Wednesday could not confirm that honor, but
said a 26-year-old mathematician, Noam Elkies, became the youngest
tenured professor in university history in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   With scores of academic papers to his credit, Summers is best
known as a leading writer on the factors that determine how and
where people invest. He also helped deflate a popular economic
theory that claimed that people would respond to higher tax rates
and other changes in fiscal policy in a way that nullified the
effect of the new policy. His research showed that fiscal policy
can have a direct effect on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   He also gathered data to poke holes in another popular theory,
which held that markets always quickly adjust prices to reflect new
information.
</P>
<P>
   Summers first went to Washington in 1982 as a staff economist
for the Council of Economic Advisers, then headed by Feldstein.
Another entre to politics came when he met Rubin and other
Democratic insiders while working on Michael Dukakis's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Summers was chief economist at the World Bank but fell short in
a bid for its presidency. Looking for a role after Clinton's
election in 1992, he was bypassed as head of the National Economic
Council but landed as Under Secretary of Treasury for International
Affairs. He won the No. 2 spot at Treasury in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a far different resume than Rubin's, Summers is unlikely
to set a new direction at Treasury this late in the Clinton
presidency. The biggest change? ``Now, you've just got to practice
saying `Secretary Summers' instead of `Secretary Rubin,' '' said
Martin Regalia, chief economist for the US Chamber of Commerce.
``Is the administration likely to change its position on tax cuts
or Social Security? I don't think so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
