u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-CABARET-BOS &LR;      05-13 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-CABARET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VERSION OF `CABARET' LOSES THE MUSICAL'S SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CABARET 
Musical in two acts. Music by John Kander. Lyrics by Fred Ebb. Book
by Joe Masteroff. Based on the play ``I Am a Camera,'' by John Van
Druten and on ``Berlin Stories,'' by Christopher Isherwood. 
Directed by Sam Mendes. Codirected and choreographed by Rob
Marshall. Set, Robert Brill. Lighting, Peggy Eisenhauer and Mike
Baldassari. Costumes, William Ivey Long. Produced by the Roundabout
Theatre Company. Presented by Broadway in Boston. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``Cabaret'' began life in 1966 it was far too timid in
exploring the psychosexual politics of life in Berlin at the dawn
of the Nazis' rise to power. By the time Bob Fosse, Liza Minnelli,
Joel Grey, and Louis Armstrong got through with it you could be
excused if you thought the cabaret was a healthy haven of hedonism,
a Cheers bar where everybody knew your name.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mendes, director of the new ``Cabaret'' that took New York
by storm last year and has now set up shop at the Colonial Theatre,
can be given some credit then for turning the musical on its head
and serving up a clearer view of what the cabaret represented _ a
decidedly decadent place that symbolized the amorality, and
ultimately immorality, of political indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in giving ``Cabaret'' such an attitude adjustment
Mendes discarded the heart and soul that made the musical special
in the first place. If Fosse and Minnelli gave the original,
somewhat stilted musical an amphetamine rush of showstoppers, then
Mendes is overly satisfied with the heroin chic of fashion ads. For
all the radical rethinking and restaging that goes on here, the new
``Cabaret'' is, like Mendes's ``Blue Room,'' a soullessly dark look
into a world where the pursuit of happiness, particularly sexual,
obscures any hope of achieving a higher humanity.
</P>
<P>
   This, I admit, is a minority view. Most, though not all, of the
New York critics hailed the new version, and the Tonys beamed on
Mendes, Natasha Richardson as Sally Bowles, and Alan Cumming as the
Emcee. Be that as it shouldn't, the touring version here isn't the
same production that played New York. Teri Hatcher and Norbert Leo
Butz are serviceable, but nowhere near the dominating presences of
Richardson and Cumming. It was also decided not to transform the
Colonial into the Kit Kat Klub setting that Henry Miller's Theatre
and Studio 54 became. That isn't all to the bad, as the cabaret
setting of ``Cabaret'' _ making the audience into complicit Germans
_ was as glib as most everything else about Mendes's staging.
</P>
<P>
   Boston audiences, though, are not spared Mendes's bleak chic. We
still have Butz and various Kit Kat Boys and Girls prowling the
borders of Robert Brill's black-and-silver set, peering through the
large off-center frame above the action, and casting scowls on the
attempts of the two couples to transcend the travails of their time
and place. Even the sweetest song in the score, ``Married,'' is
snatched from Herr Schultz and Fraulein Schneider, and turned into
a Dietrich-like turn, complete with strobe light. Butz plays the
Emcee like a vampiric, lascivious bisexual cross between Sting and
Billy Idol, which is along the lines of Cumming's slightly gayer
portrayal.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't quite have the menace he should, but the problem
isn't with him, or that Hatcher seems to have based her portrayal
of Bowles on watching Joanna Lumley in ``Absolutely Fabulous.'' It
isn't even with the darkness of Mendes's vision. Julianne Boyd's
version that played at the Hasty Pudding and Foxborough a couple of
years ago was such a shining success because it did darken the
original's hues, but it also made us care about the content of the
characters and the politics of the cabaret in a way that Mendes
seems utterly unconcerned about.
</P>
<P>
   That's the important failing of this ``Cabaret.'' The music by
John Kander and lyrics by Fred Ebb still make up one of the last
great scores the American musical produced, and if some of the
numbers get lost in less than melodious deliveries, at least the
band hits its targets with distinction. (Joe Masteroff, who wrote
the book, was in attendance.) Some of Rob Marshall's choreography
is impressive. Dick Latessa as Schultz complements a Topo Gigio
persona with an Ezio Pinza vocal style. Hatcher's singing wouldn't
make you run out to buy her CD, but it wouldn't make you run out of
the theater, either. It's competent if not distinctive, and if she
shouts too much in the title song, so does Richardson. At least she
doesn't pervert it into the song of personal liberation that
Minnelli did. (Would that we could be as generous to her acting.)
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher is not the show's main virtue or flaw. When Mendes has
the Emcee change into his final costume of the evening _ one that
flies in the face of everything that comes before _ it's the final
insult to the audience's intelligence. But then this is a
production that seems to be aiming at the audience's head when,
like the cabaret itself, it's really aiming much lower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1332EDT &QL; 
