<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PARENTS NEED ANSWERS, THEY TURN TO NETMOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other night, I found myself in a chat room on America
Online, waiting for Tom Morello of Rage Against the Machine to get
to the point. Along with Hillary Rosen, president of the Recording
Industry Association of America, Morello was on-line to discuss
violent music in the aftermath of the shootings in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of addressing the subject, Morello began with a
screed about the war in the Balkans and got on a soap box about
politicians decrying violent lyrics while NATO engages in a bloody
bombing campaign. Morello certainly wasn't the first to make that
connection, but the thing was, nobody in the chat room was there to
discuss it. Most of the teen-agers just wanted to type love letters
to Morello, but some of the parents on-line had genuine concerns.
What, if anything, should they be doing to monitor their kids'
exposure to pop culture? And what about the Internet? How do you
ensure kids' safety on-line without hindering their exposure to its
enormous potential?
</P>
<P>
   Forget the chat room: All you got there was ``Blah, blah, blah,
Yugoslavia,'' ``Blah, blah, blah, President Clinton,'' and ``Blah,
blah, blah, Tom Morello is God.'' I gave up and zapped off an
e-mail to NetMom, an expert in youth culture on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are concerned, NetMom replied. She's seen a dramatic
increase in hits to her informative site (www.NetMom.com) since the
Littleton tragedy. ``Kids are more savvy about the Internet than
their parents are,'' says NetMom, aka Jean Armour Polly, a former
librarian and author of ``The Internet Kids and Family Yellow
Pages.'' ``But that doesn't mean parents should go off the deep end
and pull the plug. They should investigate it. If you don't have it
at home, go to a cyber cafe or the public library. See what's out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Polly is an Internet pioneer and something of a Net evangelist
(she coined the term ``surfing the Net''), and she's not about to
offer alarmist views about cyberspace. ``There are dangers out
there, but outweighing those dangers is the wonder of the Internet
and the fabulous sites created for and by kids. The educational
benefits are so rich, and I'd hate to see parents scared off
because of stories saying that the Internet is evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. Polly urges parents to allow the Internet into their
homes on their own terms. And she offers some sensible advice on
how to do just that. The first thing, of course, involves
old-fashioned, non-technical communication. ``People don't talk to
their kids,'' she says. ``You can have someone on-line talking in a
chat room about how to be a better parent while their own kid is on
the floor behind them. It's so funny. You can reach across the
globe in a chat room, but why can't you reach out to your own
kids?''
</P>
<P>
   That's lesson number one. But what about that eerie feeling that
your kids are one click ahead of you out there in cyberspace? Here
are NetMom's suggestions. Some parents opt to filter the Internet
in a variety of ways. First, some Internet service providers filter
certain content for children; these providers can be found by
checking out http://thelist.internet.com; do a search on
``filtered.'' AOL, for instance, offers its members a parental
control option.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the filtering software packages, which have been
controversial since they came on the market. First Amendment
activists are against them as a general rule, especially in public
libraries. But even the staunchest free speech advocates would
admit that people can make their own choices about what content
comes into their homes. These packages, which include products like
CyberSitter and SmartFilter, allow parents to block pages that
contain pornography and hate speech. When they were first
introduced, they were creaky, blocking sites that might have a
chicken breast recipe or a discussion of breast cancer. They've
gotten better, though, and the question ``To filter or not to
filter'' is a personal choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have filters in our house,'' Polly says. ``Son of
NetMom (Stephen) is almost 13, and we do a lot of talking about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Son of NetMom, of course, is pretty adept on-line. And his
mother can tell you about plenty of places where kids can learn
on-line in a safe environment. She raves about some of the search
engines designed specifically for children. The popular Ask Jeeves
site, for instance, has a site designed for youngsters called Ask
Jeeves for Kids (www.ajkids.com). Polly also recommends
www.yahooligans.com and Kids Click, a site created by librarians
(http://sunsite.berkeley.edu/kidsclick!/).
</P>
<P>
   The point is, you don't have to be powerless and you don't have
to turn to chats with rock stars to figure out what to do. Danger
may be only one click away in cyberspace, but so is a wealth of
educational experiences. Just ask NetMom. She knows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Liesl Clark didn't expect to be deluged with media requests when
she ascended Mount Everest to film a PBS Nova documentary. But
early this week, the team of climbers discovered the body of George
Mallory, the British adventurer who disappeared on Everest back in
1924. Word travels fast in these days of instant communication,
especially when you're chronicling your adventures on a Web site
(www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/everest/).
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were waiting at Base Camp, the climbers used their
satellite phone and laptop to announce the news to the world,''
Clark wrote in an e-mail to this column. ``Instantly, the whole
world knew... Somehow, Web-casting has taken the world by storm,
and anyone can post news, without understanding the repercussions.
While the outside world feasted on the breaking news, we were
holding on at Base Camp for the team to return, still very much in
the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we deluged with media requests? Just about every major
magazine and newspaper has been in touch with us, asking for photos
of Mallory and doing interviews. I just got off the satellite phone
with the Sunday Times in London. I'm not so sure the media would be
quite so anxious to speak with us if we were in Boston. I can only
tell you that when I call a reporter and say, `This is Liesl Clark
calling from Everest Base Camp,' they, amazingly, don't put me on
hold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVITT14-COX     05-13 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVITT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEVITT'S STRATEGY AT SEC IS SPELLED D-I-S-C-L-O-S-U-R-E
 &HT;    740&AMP;add.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Expect to hear more from the Securities and
Exchange Commission in the coming months about the need for
additional disclosure by mutual funds on the cost of investing and
the impact of taxes. Ditto for plain English documents.
</P>
<P>
   Those are among the issues SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt _ one year
into his second five-year term _ has on his mind. In an interview
with David McNaughton of Cox News Service, the 68-year-old Levitt
also addressed other questions about the agency's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The SEC has a number of issues on its plate, in addition to
the much-publicized Internet fraud. Does the agency have enough
resources to do its job?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think any law enforcement agency has sufficient
resources to assure the public that all misdeeds will be
anticipated, or addressed. But I think a focused enforcement arm
can try to address those areas which we feel represent the greatest
threat to the American investor or to the financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we could use additional resources. ... But I don't think
there is a law enforcement agency in this country which wouldn't
say the same.
</P>
<P>
   Do I think the public is being violated because we're so
understaffed? Not really. We still have good people coming to us
for amounts of money that is much less than what they could make in
the private sector because they believe in what we are doing,
because they're really patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the subject of Internet fraud, there have been suggestions
that the SEC conduct undercover stings to combat it. Is that
something the agency would consider?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think it's a good idea. I think you have to approach
that very carefully. It involves privacy issues. I suppose if you
allowed every law enforcement agency the ability to do anything
they want, you'd probably have less crime. But at what price? It's
a price that I don't think I would be prepared to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about investment-related Internet chat rooms? Should
they fall under investment advisory regulations?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think as long as people know that chat rooms can be
unreliable, and as long as we are prepared to go after people who
make fraudulent use of chat rooms, by being paid to promote certain
securities _ as long as we can go after that kind of miscreant, I
think our role is to educate people as to the dangers of believing
everything they hear in the chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are penalties for securities law violations sufficient,
particularly in regard to repeat offenders?
</P>
<P>
   A: Boiling in oil would be suitable in some cases, I suppose,
but I wouldn't ask for that remedy. I think we have at our disposal
what I think is certainly more than any other regulator any place
in the world (has), and I think probably adequate to our needs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In terms of priorities, what would your selection be?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would say seeing to it that the numbers available to
investors are as comprehensive and accurate as possible, consistent
with our mandate of full disclosure. That means America's
accounting must keep pace with our markets and our financial
system. So seeing to it that our numbers are accurate and reliable,
stamping out accounting fraud, coming down hard on those companies
that abuse the system by trying to make numbers that will satisfy
short-term-oriented analysts, is a major target of this commission.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing structural issues in our market by seeing to it that
the explosive changes occurring in our markets create a system
where competition is both fierce and fair. I mean adjusting to
electronic markets and deciding which new entrants will be treated
as an exchange or dealer, what the level of oversight will be, how
to deal with the rules and regulations submitted by the various
self-regulating agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing to it there's no compromise in the kinds of protections
investors have in U.S. markets in terms of the new formulation of
international accounting standards.
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening the role of the audit committee, a protection for
the public investor. I appointed a blue ribbon committee to
evaluate the role of the audit committee and now we intend to
implement those recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to diminish the influence of pay-to-play, both in the
municipal market and in the corporate market, and to extend that to
the role of investment advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Greater disclosure on the part of mutual funds in terms of what
it's costing investors to invest in those funds, and the risks that
those investors endure in those funds.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: The SEC has several options to produce its desired results.
Among those, how effective has jawboning been?
</P>
<P>
   A. I've been amazed at how important the bully pulpit is. When I
give a speech on a serious subject, the lawyers and accountants of
America write to their clients and say, ``This is what the SEC is
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's been a far more reliable device than either rule-making
or seeking legislation. Legislation is my last alternative because
it's so unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You raised objections in congressional testimony about the
House version of proposed financial services deregulation. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: The most serious problem, which makes this bill in my
judgment very, very bad for investors, is that the banking
exemptions are so arcane and ill-suited to today's environment that
in effect they permit and encourage banking regulators to oversee
securities activities that are conducted within the bank. And
that's just wrong. And dangerous to investor interests to allow
that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do you feel it's dangerous?
</P>
<P>
   A: The way the system works best is when banking regulators
watch the bank and securities regulators watch securities
activities. If banking regulators are concerned about the safety
and soundness of the bank, and they have as a subsidiary a
brokerage operation, and the banking part of the bank is undergoing
some financial trauma, it's all too easy to suck up the resources
of the brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   If the brokerage firm is guilty of some fraudulent activity, how
would the bank deal with that in terms of its overall reputation?
The culture of the brokerage industry is to publicize misdeeds.
That is not the culture of the banking industry, which fears (for)
safety and soundness. They want to handle it themselves in their
own way and keep it quiet. The brokerage industry has remedies. The
banking industry does not. We can kick someone out of the brokerage
field and keep them out of financial services. You can't do that in
banks.
</P>
<P>
   We also have a whole mechanism of enforcement and surveillance.
Banking examiners don't do that. Different culture. Different
levels of protection. And I'm interested in one level, and that's
investor protection. It's kind of the mantra that guides every
decision we make.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
