<HEADLINE>
RUBIN'S EXPERTISE IN TIME OF CRISIS WILL BE MISSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Financial types typically don't have much use for government.
</P>
<P>
   To Wall Street, government is a big, clumsy player that is more
likely to make things worse rather than better. Investors prefer to
place their trust in the collective wisdom of free markets.
</P>
<P>
   Except for those times when markets stop working, when fear is
in the air, and financial problems look as if they will snowball
into full-scale disasters. At times like those, investors dump
their laissez-faire attitudes, along with their stocks, and turn to
government for help.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican crisis in late 1994 was one of those times. So was
the Asian crisis in 1997 and the Russian crisis in the summer of
1998. ``We are living in a period that has demonstrated both the
strengths and the limitations of markets,'' says Fred Breimyer,
chief economist at State Street Bank.
</P>
<P>
   It was in those times of crisis that Robert Rubin made his mark
and why he will be so sorely missed on Wall Street. As Treasury
secretary, Rubin was the fireman who kept the fire from spreading,
the cop on the corner who prevented the fight from spiraling into a
full-blown riot.
</P>
<P>
   Working with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and his
designated successor, Lawrence Summers, Rubin kept the US market
and the US economy insulated from the worst of the damage. Along
the way he became so valuable to President Clinton and so highly
regarded on Wall Street that he couldn't leave his job, even though
he clearly wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he is resigning now means the worst of the
global crisis is over,'' says Mark Zandi, chief economist at
Regional Financial Associates, a Pennsylvania forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost more than 200 points
Wednesday morning when news of Rubin's resignation first became
public. The market later came back, closing for the day with a loss
of just 25.78. Investors may have been reassured when Greenspan
spoke favorably about Summers.
</P>
<P>
   All three men have had plenty of experience on the international
front. When the Mexican peso collapsed, Rubin and company backed an
emergency loan to Mexico over the strong objections of the
Republican Congress. Mexico went into a painful recession, but its
economy and market bounced back quickly. Just as important, the
rest of Latin America and the rest of the world avoided disaster.
</P>
<P>
   In the cases of Asia and Russia, the Rubin team worked through
the International Monetary Fund to stabilize markets and rebuild
investor confidence. Asia remains a work in progress. Some
countries, including Korea and Thailand, have bounced back; others,
most notably Japan, have not. Russia is still a mess.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a sense that those in charge knew what they were
doing _ that the fate of the financial world was in good hands.
``Rubin is just an incredibly competent man,'' says Nancy Kimelman,
chief economist at Technical Data in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On the domestic front, Rubin steered Clinton toward deficit
reduction and impressed upon his boss the importance of keeping the
bond market happy. He also made sure the administration avoided
criticizing the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Neither policy initially went over well with the liberals, but
they were hard put to complain in the face of a strong economy and
a bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin earned the enmity of Republicans in 1995 when he juggled
funds to keep the government running when Congressional Republicans
tried to shut it down. They were no more pleased with his efforts
to block a variety of proposed tax cuts. More often than not, he
got his way.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin visited Boston a number of times over the years. He was
always a terrible interview. He never had anything of interest to
say _ at least on the record. If he ever gave a major speech, no
one can remember it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for an important public official he was remarkably
closed-mouthed. He rarely said anything about financial markets,
even though he spent 26 years at Goldman Sachs. When he was asked
about the dollar, he said he favored a strong US dollar and that
was it. He seemed to know when it was useful to speak up and when
silence could be more effective.
</P>
<P>
   In person Rubin cut an impressive figure. He came across as
bright and in charge. He never looked rattled. In the financial
community, he inspired confidence, a precious commodity. In
Washington he sometimes seemed like one of the only grown-ups in a
town full of out-of-control teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is a mensch,'' says Kimleman, using a Yiddish word
that literally means man but actually refers to a solid, decent
person in whom you can place your trust.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, Rubin's heir apparent, is brilliant, experienced, and
knows as much as anyone about the US and world economies. His
challenge will be proving to the markets and to Washington that he,
too, is a mensch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
