<HEADLINE>
CAN NEW SIDING GO OVER OLD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Two contractors have bid to re-side my house, which now has
aluminum siding on the front and cedar shingles on the sides and
back. The shingles are over original clapboards. One contractor
said to take off the cedar shingles; another said there is no need
to remove them. Who's right?
</P>
<P>
   P. M., Ashland, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. They both are, although the one who said there is no need is
lazy, or not willing to take them off and charge more money. Most
new siding (vinyl, clapboards, or shingles) can be applied over old
siding, but since your sides and back already have two layers, a
third layer would bring out the wall much too far, requiring some
treatment to the window and door casings so that the new siding
would not end in midair where it meets the casings. If the windows
are treated to prevent this midair meeting, the windows and doors
would look indented _ pretty silly on a house. So, while it may be
more expensive to remove the old shingles, I would do so.
</P>
<P>
   As for the aluminum, it definitely should come off no matter
what kind of siding you apply to the front.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am getting a distinct smell of cigarette smoke in the
living room of my apartment since a smoker moved in below me, and
it migrates to the bedroom as well. I have been in the 25-story
building since it opened in 1963. The maintenance people caulked
along the baseboard, and I think around a pipe coming out of the
floor, which helped a little. The baseboard heater is several
inches above the floor. Is there anything else that I can do?
</P>
<P>
   J. W., Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. Physical blocking is the best thing you can do to keep out
the smoke, and caulking is physical blocking. Have any and all
joints caulked; it may not look so hot but it may help. The joints
that can be caulked are at the top of the baseboard (which I assume
is what was already caulked), between the baseboard and the floor,
around pipes coming through the floor or wall, and possibly around
window casings because the smoke may be coming up through the wall
and into your unit around the window casing. Do this on inside
walls as well as outside ones.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a shoe mold (a quarter-round molding) between the
baseboard and floor. If you have hardwood flooring, there may be a
half-inch open joint under that shoe mold; that is an expansion
joint to allow the wood floor to expand and contract, which is good
because it prevents the floor from warping. But that open joint may
be a perfect conduit for the smoke from below. The best way to
caulk that joint is to remove the shoe mold, caulk the joint
heavily, fill the open joint, and put the shoe mold back on. This
will make a good closure, and be invisible. The caulking is
flexible enough that it will not interfere with the expansion and
contraction of the floorboards.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing to try is to have your neighbor have his unit
caulked between wall and ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Caulking has to be complete and thorough; a lick and a promise
will not do. The more seams and joints and cracks you caulk, the
better off you will be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Could I douse the weeds that grow in the cracks in my
driveway with bleach to keep them away? Would that pose an
environmental risk?
</P>
<P>
   ED BOOTH, Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, that would work, and the environment is not compromised
because bleach converts to a less toxic, less caustic material when
it contacts the ground. But I think that vinegar will be more
effective, and will prevent new weeds from growing for nearly the
whole summer. Vinegar is concentrated acid rain, and we all know
what acid rain does. One caveat: Whether you use vinegar or bleach,
don't put it on any area where you don't want the plants killed.
</P>
<P>
   This all will work on weeds that grow between bricks and other
paving materials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can I power-wash my house? It is 70 years old and the siding
is shingles.
</P>
<P>
   KIRSTEN LEWIS, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the shingles are painted, or stained with a solid color
stain, you can power-wash, which will take off loose paint or
stain. If you plan to repaint or restain, let the shingles dry out
for four or five dry days. If the shingles have a semitransparent
stain, you can also power-wash, but it may fade the stain
considerably, requiring restaining.
</P>
<P>
   Shingles that are intact and lying flat on the wall can be
power-washed; so can clapboards that are well nailed. If the
shingles are curling a bit, or the clapboards are lifting, I
suggest not power-washing because the strong stream of water can
get too far under the shingles, causing delays in drying out.
</P>
<P>
   I would not suggest power-washing vinyl or aluminum siding
because if water gets into the seams and behind the siding, it
would take a long time to dry out _ not a good idea or a good thing
for the sheathing or whatever wood is under the siding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
