<HEADLINE>
CLMBING THE LADDER TO SUCCESS SAFELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone has a ladder story, so with the ladder season upon us,
it's time to make sure that we do all the chores that require
ladders safely and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those chores are painting, washing and reglazing
windows, putting up shingles, taking down shingles, repointing the
chimney, reroofing or repairing a roof, cleaning gutters. Chances
are that this summer you will be doing one or more of these chores.
</P>
<P>
   Working on ladders carries an inherent hazard; after all, you
are not working on the ground (the safest and most comfortable
place to be, usually); you may be just a few feet above ground, or
up to 20.
</P>
<P>
   Any work above 20 feet high is best left to the pros. And, if
you don't like heights, then don't even bother. The better part of
valor is to stay on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Most accidents on ladders are due to operator error or
carelessness. The operator may have leaned too far to one side
trying to reach a distant area without moving the ladder. Or, he
stood on a step too high up the ladder, losing his balance. Or, he
positioned the ladder too steep or too shallow, inviting a fall.
</P>
<P>
   Other causes are defective equipment or using a ladder not
designed for the job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The handyman has his own ladder mishaps; you can decide if it
was his own fault or not.
</P>
<P>
   This one he couldn't blame on anyone else. The handyman had a
wood ladder, which he stored outdoors for some years. But he took
good care of it, keeping it well oiled, and not painting it,
because painting could cover defects.
</P>
<P>
   So he set up the ladder carefully, stepped on the bottom rung,
and foomp! The decayed rung broke at each end, sending the handyman
down suddenly. The fall was only 12 inches, but it was enough to
get rid of the ladder in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but what if the rung that broke was the top rung?
</P>
<P>
   Another intrepid ladderman (whose name we will not mention to
protect the guilty) set up a scaffold board suspended from two
ladders, safe when done rigfht.
</P>
<P>
   Our friend did do it right, but from then on didn't do anything
right. He couldn't reach part of his project, so he put a few
plastic milk cartons on the scaffold board to get just a little
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Lo, the jury-rigged cartons tottered and fell, sending our
friend down the wall for 12 feet, feet first. He landed on his
feet, bounced back, and ended up on his back. He was unhurt, but
you should have seen the fingernail marks on the wall, where he
clawed and clawed to save his life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All these stories are simply to stress the need for good
equipment, proper use of it, and the usual safety precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Ladder Co. of Greenville, Pa., has been making ladders
and accessories for 75 years now, and is well aware of the need for
quality in its products, but also the need for safety, proper use,
and intelligent behavior while sky high.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Ladder &AMP; Scaffolding Co. of West Lynn, Mass. is a
manufacturer of all kinds of ladders, scaffolds, and accessories,
and has branches in Orwigsburg, Pa., Washington, D.C., and West
Springfield, Mass. It, too, has plenty of tips on safety and proper
use of ladders.
</P>
<P>
   In the market to buy a ladder? Consider what you will use a
ladder for. Extension ladders come in four weight-carrying
categories, extra heavy (300 pounds); heavy duty, 250 pounds;
medium duty, 225 pounds, and light duty, 200 pounds. Remember, the
pound rating includes the weight of the climber as well as
everything he is carrying. For most residential uses, the medium
duty is a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   What material?
</P>
<P>
   What material? Wood is economical, electrically non-conductive
when clean and dry, and heavy. While aluminum and fiberglass
ladders are generally lighter than wood, they still are not
featherweight.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum is strong, lightweight, and corrosion resistant.
Fiberglass is electrically non-conductive and strong.
</P>
<P>
   The choice is yours and may depend on the cost of the ladders.
But don't expect any cheapies from either Werner or Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   A most important part of operating a ladder safely is how far
the base should be from the house. If it is too close to the house,
the climber could tip over backwards as he gained height. Too far,
and the ladder should skitter down the wall, carrying the climber
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Werner says the right angle for an extension ladder is 75 1/2
degrees between the base and upper support point. That makes the
ratio of setback and height 1 to 4. In other words, the setback
(distance of the base from the house) should be one foot for each
four feet of height from base to upper support point. For a 20-foot
ladder, the setback would be 5 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Read the rules
</P>
<P>
   Before you start, think safety. Read all ladder labels, pay
attention to them.
</P>
<P>
   Inspect the ladder for defects, damage, or loose or missing
components.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure working parts move properly and connections are
secure.
</P>
<P>
   Keep ladders in good condition. Clean spills or drips, and keep
the ladder free from oil, paint, and other slippery materials.
Lubricate moving parts.
</P>
<P>
   Use a fiberglass or a dry, clean wood ladder when working near
power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Open stepladders completely and lock into position. Make sure
all ladder feet are on a firm base, and both rails of an extension
ladder are firmly against the house.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now, finally, you can start climbing. Well, not before a few
rules are dunned into you head:
</P>
<P>
   Get help if the ladder is too heavy to lug around. Avoid
carrying an extension ladder in the vertical position; it's too
easy to lose balance and break the ladder, yourself, and anyone in
your way.
</P>
<P>
   Climb facing the ladder. Center your body between rails.
</P>
<P>
   And a few don'ts: Don't stand above the highest safe-standing
level. Don't stand above the second step from the top of a
stepladder and the fourth rung from the top of an extension ladder.
Don't exceed the duty rating of a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the dos and don'ts are based on common sense and
logic. Let's hope we all have some.
</P>
<P>
   And, one piece of logic you can apply if you don't like heights
and don't like ladders: Have someone else do these strange things.
Paying him is worth it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
