r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTI-SMOKING-ADS-HNS &LR;      05-13 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-SMOKING-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR LAUNCHES ADS ATTACKING TOBACCO INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Starting this weekend, tobacco executives get
skewered as liars and hypocrites with a series of anti-smoking TV
ads recently approved by California Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Pete Wilson shelved the ads because he didn't think
taxpayers should pay for personal attacks on a legal business but
should concentrate on the harmful health effects of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The ads approved by Davis also include a new campaign featuring
emotional testimony from children who lost their parents to cancer.
Another black-and-white piece features a plea from the brother of
the rugged-looking actor who played the ``Marlboro Man'' and later
died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Still another features a woman with a weathered face who says
she started smoking at age 10. ``I started smoking to look older,
and I'm sorry to say it works,'' the woman adds regretfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ads will tell the truth in plain, unvarnished fashion,''
Davis says.
</P>
<P>
   Although California has the second-lowest smoking rate in the
nation, behind Utah, the teenage smoking rate has begun to climb.
Anti-smoking groups claim teenagers respond better when authority
figures like the tobacco industry are ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   Under Davis, ridicule is again state policy.
</P>
<P>
   A TV ad produced for $350,000 in 1995 and never used, dubbed
``Insurance,'' shows shadowy-looking tobacco executives smoking
cigarettes and laughing over their money, then switches to the
front door of an insurance company that gives lower rates for
people who don't smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Although the companies are not named, the ad is referring to
British American Tobacco and Lorillard, cigarette makers owned by
conglomerates that also include life insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco industry. They profit, you lose,'' says the ending
voice-over.
</P>
<P>
   The next Wilson-era ad approved by Davis appeared briefly before
Wilson pulled it in the mid- 1990s. Dubbed ``Boardroom,'' the
30-second piece shows video footage from an April 1994
congressional committee where tobacco executives testified that
nicotine is not addictive.
</P>
<P>
   It ends with the tagline: ``Do they think we're stupid?''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Philip Morris said the company has no problem
with state-sponsored TV ads and campaigns that target teenage
smoking, but it objects to the ``essence'' of the ads that directly
attack tobacco executives.
</P>
<P>
   Under the recent mega-settlement with tobacco companies, about
$1.5 billion has been set aside for anti-smoking ads throughout the
country. Many of those ads are under development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope the state devotes a significant portion of their
settlement funds to youth smoking-prevention programs,'' said
Philip Morris spokeswoman Mary Carnovale. ``As far as these
(Davis-approved) ads are concerned, we just don't feel they are
accurate depictions of Philip Morris and our people.''
</P>
<P>
   California has one of the most well-financed anti-tobacco
campaigns in the nation. Since voters raised the cigarette tax by
25 cents a pack a decade ago, about $634 million has been spent
fighting smoking under Proposition 99.
</P>
<P>
   This year's TV ad campaign costs about $25 million, and will
include an increased presence on networks that teenagers tend to
watch more, like MTV and Fox. Most of the new ads will be on the
air this weekend, then briefly trail off during the summer when
fewer people watch TV.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-tobacco forces had been frustrated with Davis for not
quickly approving the Wilson-era ads and about 19 new ads produced
by Asher &AMP; Partners, the state's Los Angeles-based agency. Several
of those new ads remain in the pipeline, Davis said Wednesday, and
should be approved within a few months.
</P>
<P>
   The recent settlement with the tobacco industry also gave
California health officials control last month of 366 billboards
that were being used to advertise cigarettes. Anti-smoking groups
praised Davis for moving quickly to seize that $10 million windfall
and approve ads for them.
</P>
<P>
   The new billboard campaign includes a more aggressive use of ads
linking cigarettes to impotence. One billboard shows a mock
Marlboro Man with a droopy cigarette in his mouth and the word
``IMPOTENT'' behind him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
