<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5543 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-13 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL VICTORY FOR COMMON SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much power should fear have over your life? That's a
question each of us has to confront.
</P>
<P>
   A friend told me this story last week. She'd run errands with
her two children, Suzie, 8, and Greg, 4. She had to return a video
and pick up Greg's bike from the repair shop, but luckily, the two
stores were within sight of each other. When she arrived at the
video store, however, Suzie wanted to look at the children's videos
without anyone rushing her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can return the tape by myself,'' she'd said confidently,
stepping out of the car. ``I'll meet you at the bike store.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of leaving Suzie on her own took her mother's breath
away. ``I have one nightmare that chills me to the bone, the
thought that something might happen to either of my children
because of poor judgment on my part,'' Karen said to me. ``Did I
want to let Suzie out of my sight for even one minute? Absolutely
not, but this wasn't only about what would make me comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to understand that Karen's daughter had been the most
outgoing of kindergartners until the school showed a video warning
her and her classmates about the danger of being abducted by
``friendly strangers.'' Looking back, Karen believes Suzie's
innocence was shattered when she was told to beware of people who
were nice to her and to view even their neighbors as a possible
threat. Suddenly the place where her child had formerly felt
completely safe became populated with potential kidnappers,
fiendishly disguised as friends, who might steal her if she let
down her defenses.
</P>
<P>
   What other defense does a 5-year-old have except to stay afraid?
</P>
<P>
   How else can you explain that Suzie was afraid to go upstairs in
her own home? Why else would kidnappers have haunted her dreams,
waking her several times a night for over a year? Why else would
she panic at the sight of a strange man on her street? All her
family's reassurances were useless against her terror. She remained
hyperalert, having lost faith in the power of adults to protect
her, for isn't that what we're confessing when we place so much
responsibility for her own safety upon a child's small shoulders?
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, her family has been encouraging Suzie
to reclaim her fearless self, to look up and see blue sky instead
of dark clouds, to regain her confidence in herself and the world
around her. Recently her parents transferred Suzie to a private
school, which operates on the philosophy that it is crucially
important to awaken and preserve a child's innate sense of wonder,
awe, and reverence, in part by providing positive experiences while
limiting unmediated access to violence in the media.
</P>
<P>
   So here was Suzie, apparently in recovery, and how did her mom
react? She was tempted to say she was too scared to leave Suzie
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Karen believes we are eroding the sense of security necessary
for learning and growing and loving life by giving children
frightening information beyond their conceptual and geographical
scope. She has seen her child haunted, and hindered, by her
overwhelming preoccupation with possible hidden dangers in her
immediate environment.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety can do that. It drains life of pleasure. It makes us
flee from stressful situations rather than cope with them. It
adversely affects our ability to be curious, to think clearly, to
respond appropriately, to focus on the challenges we actually do
face rather than those we fear. Anxiety is, above all, irrational.
It blinds you to the subtle signs you really should be heeding by
making you see danger everywhere all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Karen knew that. After all, she was fighting her own anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   This is what she did.
</P>
<P>
   She looked up the street. She looked down it. Whatever evil was
happening elsewhere, all the strangers she could see looked
extremely friendly. They looked like folks who vote at town meeting
and recycle their newspapers and walk for AIDS. They looked like
people who volunteer to walk abandoned pets and coach soccer teams
in their free time. They looked exactly like all the decent, kind,
and trustworthy people Karen and her family had lived happily among
for the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   She walked Suzie into the store. She said to Stan, the very nice
guy who owns the place, ``Keep an eye on her, will you?'' Then she
walked out the door.
</P>
<P>
   You'd better believe she gave Suzie an enormous hug when the
child, all smiles, was safely back in her arms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
