<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY CAN, IT SEEMS, BUY HAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; want to make the journey to financial wholeness.
</P>
<P>
   I want to release the energy of money.
</P>
<P>
   I want to set out on the hero's path toward money power. For, as
the mythologist and philosopher Joseph Campbell once said, ``Money
is congealed energy, and releasing it releases life's
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   I think I sense something congealing here, although I'm not
entirely sure it's the energy of money. It could be a publishing
trend. But it may be something else.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently I never knew money could be so spiritually
enriching. Then I discovered two new books, Suze Orman's ``The
Courage to be Rich'' and Maria Nemeth's ``The Energy of Money.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the two books are different in many ways, they share a
common goal, to make readers one with their money, in a holistic,
New Age sense.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, both Orman and Nemeth are already one with my money,
since I parted with $24.95 for each book. That's a total of $49.90,
plus tax.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters.
</P>
<P>
   Because money isn't money as we remember it from the booming
'80s _ you know, the old
let's-buy-everything-we-can-lay-our-hands-on kind of money. Here in
the booming '90s, the new money is a metaphor for self-esteem,
self-empowerment, and spiritual enrichment. It's a vehicle for
self-actualization, a path to inner peace.
</P>
<P>
   The basic message of both books is simple: Quit spending money,
save it instead. This isn't exactly a new idea, but tarted up with
a lot of New Age concepts and psychobabble it seems different,
somehow. More marketable.
</P>
<P>
   With consumer debt heading toward the stratosphere, both Orman
and Nemeth would seem to be fighting an uphill battle. But
precisely because so many people are deeply in debt, both have
found eager audiences. Orman, particularly, is wildly popular, with
her PBS special ``The Courage to be Rich,'' her regular appearances
on the Oprah Winfrey program, her own show on QVC. Her first book,
``The 9 Steps to Financial Freedom'' sold 2 million copies; the new
book has been on the New York Times bestseller list since it was
published eight weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Orman writes, ``unbelievable as it may seem, it takes courage to
be rich. Why? Because choosing wealth as a goal requires facing
everything about your money bravely, honestly, with courage _ which
is a very, very hard thing for most of us to do. But it can be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   If you face up bravely to your finances, Orman promises you'll
feel ``rich in every way, both in the way your bottom-line numbers
read and in your heart, your soul and the way you live each day.''
You can find your bliss in your bank balance. Isn't that nice?
</P>
<P>
   Nemeth's book is even more New Age-y than Orman's. It grew out
of her ``You and Money'' course, a series of seminars for the
financially bewildered. Nemeth, a clinical psychologist, is
inspired by Joseph Campbell's ``The Hero With a Thousand Faces''
and applies his ideas to mastering ``the energy of money.'' She
also invokes a host of sages _ Jung, Shakti Gawain, Sogyal
Rinpoche, Marianne Williamson, among others _ and tosses around a
lot of New Age terms and concepts _ Metaphysical Reality, Facing
the Shadow, Conquering the Dragon, Dancing With the Monkey.
</P>
<P>
   It all boils down to one thing: Stop squandering your money.
Which is good advice, no matter how you say it. You could start
your hero's journey toward mastering the energy of money by
borrowing these books from your public library, instead of buying
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
