<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5549 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-GIBSON-ART-BOS &LR;      05-13 1751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-GIBSON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S VICTORIAN SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Victorian Age would not be fully understood or
appreciated till the year 2000, Charles Hammond Gibson Jr. wrote in
1939, his crystal ball no cloudier than most. To help things along,
he took a step that has helped us visualize life a century ago: He
made arrangements for his family's residence at 137 Beacon St., in
the heart of Boston's Back Bay, to become a historic house museum.
Gibson House, as it's called, opened to the public in 1957; now, it
is attracting some long-overdue attention and undergoing needed
restoration work. Refreshment of the wallpapers alone will bring
back some idea of the Gilded Age.
</P>
<P>
   But the real charm of the house is the hodgepodge of its
decorations. Three generations of Gibsons and their many servants
lived in this narrow, five-story row house, and it's the task of
Edward W. Gordon, museum director, to figure out the waves of
Gibsonian acquisition and redecoration.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the stuff belonged to the Gibsons. When the house got
under way as a museum, it attracted many a donation of the unloved
and the unwanted. ``For a while, we were a drop-off center,'' says
Gordon, who is also president of the New England Chapter of the
Victorian Society in America, as he eyes a sentimental ``Rogers
Group'' sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   The house itself is good-goods: the Victorian view of the French
and Italian Renaissance. Built in 1859-60 for Charles Gibson's
grandmother, Katherine Hammond Gibson, the house is a sort of
architectural equivalent of that Victorian-Renaissance favorite,
Longfellow's verse translation of Dante's ``Divine Comedy.'' In
decor, however, it's more complicated; the house we see today is
less Katherine Gibson's than her daughter-in-law Rosamond Gibson's,
and her taste did swerve once or twice. Just because she loved all
things French did not mean that Rosamond, Charles's mother, would
not find a place for Colonial Revival, which was American, or Art
Nouveau via Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Our story begins with the great landfill that transformed tidal,
smelly Back Bay into the modern grid of streets that became
Boston's newest swell neighborhood. Katherine Gibson had lived on
Beacon Hill till her husband, who imported rum from Havana,
perished in a steamboat accident. What impelled her move to Beacon
Street can't now be known, but move she did, into a brick and
brownstone house designed in the Italianate mansard style by Edward
Clarke Cabot, architect of the Boston Athenaeum. While the widowed
Katherine was one of the first women to own a Back Bay house, she
had comfort and company right next door (at 135 Beacon), in an
almost identical house built for her nephew. Cabot, by the way,
probably designed more than just the house: In the mid-1800s,
interior decoration was still largely the province of architects.
It would not surprise Ed Gordon to discover that Cabot furnished
the upstairs music room with the heavy French Renaissance Revival
cabinets and chairs that now crowd the downstairs front hall.
</P>
<P>
   When Katherine died in 1888, the house went to her son and his
wife, the former Rosamond Warren. Boston owes its position in
medicine to the doctors Warren. A smallpox vaccine was developed by
Rosamond's great-uncle, General Joseph Warren, who died at Bunker
Hill in 1775; John Collins Warren would help found Massachusetts
General Hospital and pioneer in the use of ether as an anesthetic.
Gibson House has other historic links as well, though visitors
hoping to find a connection with Charles Dana Gibson will be
disappointed, Gordon says, for the illustrator who gave us the
all-American ``Gibson Girl'' was a New Yorker. But Charles Hammond
Gibson Sr. played in the first known lawn tennis game in America,
at the family's summer place on Nahant in 1874, the year of Charles
Jr.'s birth.
</P>
<P>
   With the Beacon Street house hers, Rosamond set about imposing
her taste. She was ``a huge fan of French culture,'' Gordon says;
she traveled to France often and hired a French governess for young
Charles and his two sisters. She did over the music room in what,
for the time, passed for 18th-century French, a LouisSomething
homage of striped wallpaper and furniture painted white. Edith
Wharton and Ogden Codman were doing it, too; none of this was
``period'' or ``authentic,'' but that wasn't the point. Big, comfy
sofas, meanwhile, assured Boston that Rosamond hadn't gone native.
She observed the usual pieties, continuing to display the Warren
family's China Trade dinner service and the Gibson family's
Limoges. She also continued to hang the Old Masters. That the
paintings were mostly copies _ a good Guido Remi but a bad Raphael
_ was no cause for shame but proof of travel and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Then it gets interesting. We don't know the circumstances, but
Rosamond swerved into the kind of Art Nouveau called ``Aesthetic.''
This was not really a detour but the natural progression of the
French taste for the exotic. In the 18th century it had been
Chinoiserie, concocted of Chinese plus Persian plus Indian, and all
of it made in Europe for Europeans. Then, in 1854, America pried
Japan open for Western trade, and Japonisme was the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Rosamond's bedroom suite, all 15 pieces of it, may look like
bamboo, but it was made of bird's-eye maple in 1871 by John Vaughn
near Boston's Union (North) Station. The ``Shinto gate'' curtain
rods and the ``Japanese gate cresting'' headboard tell you it's
Japanese. The bedroom fireplace looks backward and forward in time.
The Gibson house was a modern residence when built, with central
heating and indoor plumbing, and its many fireplaces burned coal.
Gordon points out that Rosamond had her fireplace deepened so she
could have a proper log fire under her Colonial Revival
mantelpiece. The unglazed tile fireplace surround is ``after
William Morris,'' making Arts &AMP; Crafts another link to the
aesthetic movement. Altogether a room rich in competing
19th-century styles.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosamond's gift to Boston (and Victorian studies) is the
astonishing wallpaper she hung in the front hall and staircase
hall. This is called ``Japanese leather.'' It was indeed made in
Japan, but of molded paper with the raised pattern gilded. ``Meiji,
19th century,'' Gordon says of the Japanese origin for the swirls
of pomegranates, roses, and vines. He smiles and adds: ``It really
gives you an idea of what was meant by the `Gilded Age' in
America.'' Americans who traveled in Europe would have come across
walls covered in the similar ``Spanish leather,'' which was
sometimes real and sometimes pretend. Victorians liked figuring out
how to produce the pretend, such as pinchbeck, an affordable metal
that passed for gold. Victorians patented wallcoverings that
mimicked wood paneling, such as lincrusta and anaglypta; Gordon
relishes showing off American-made lincrusta, a sort of linoleum,
used for the dressy wainscoting in Rosamond's bedroom and Charles's
red study.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, keeping up with the Gibsons must have taken some
doing, and later on Charles played the eccentric for all it was
worth. He wore spats, well after they'd gone out of vogue. For a
costume party in Newport, he donned Chinese silk pajamas with
matching yellow slippers. He was always writing to the kings and
queens of England, and back would come, on red-crested paper, a
typed acknowledgment signed by a courtier. These he framed and
displayed in his dressing room, along with a pinup of Joe Louis in
boxing trunks. Long before he died in 1954, he tried the house out
as a museum. Chairs were roped off, museum style, with gold cord.
People sat on the stairs drinking Charles's martinis, which, during
Prohibition, he made with his own bathtub gin. The world, he knew,
would not look on his like again, and Gibson House would be his
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Charles wrote descriptions of some of the reception rooms and
attempted a catalog. But the only known interior photograph is a
picture in Life magazine for March 24, 1941, of novelist John P.
Marquand interviewing Charles, all starch collar, in the library.
Gordon speculates that something of Charles's nostalgia for the
past went into the eponymous hero of ``The Late George Apley,''
which won Marquand the Pulitzer Prize in 1937 for its satiric view
of Beacon Street in genteel decline.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Hammond Gibson Jr. may have been as stuffy as his photo
portraits made him look; in any case, people back then didn't grin
into the camera. He spent a year studying architecture at MIT and
was interested in architectural history; he was a poet, as the
English royals well knew, and his good works included service on
the Boston Parks Commission. He also did the family genealogies. He
inherited the house in 1934, and in 1939 he wrote his prophetic
letter on understanding the Victorian Age. The recipient was
William Sumner Appleton, founder of the Society for the
Preservation of New England Antiquities; Charles was pitching his
family home as a historic house museum. Alas for Charles, SPNEA's
mission was Colonial and Federal. Nor did the Massachusetts
Historical Society care to buy the house.
</P>
<P>
   So the Gibson House as a public museum slumbered on, till the
world discovered the Victorians. As a tourist destination, Gordon
admits, the house has a long way to go. ``The best-kept secret in
Boston,'' he says. There are guided tours; they run Wednesday
through Sunday all summer. (Telephone 617-267-6338 for further
information.) A friends organization raises money and puts on house
parties for people interested in architecture, antiques, and
literature. Film companies use the house; scenes from the
Merchant-Ivory production of ``The Bostonians'' were done here in
1983. A commercial for Victoria's Secret was shot in Rosamond's
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   And now restoration has started, under Gary Wolf Architects of
Boston and contractor Tom Cooney of South Boston. There are 27
windows to restore or repair, as well as the roof to mend, and this
will take all (and more) of the initial matching grant of $35,000
from the Massachusetts Historical Commission. Only when the
envelope is secure can Gordon push on to restore and refresh the
interiors. She who gave her name to the Victorian Age died in 1901.
That centennial is an anniversary to shoot for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
