<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5550 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-HISTORY-BOS &LR;      05-13 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE APPLES BLOSSOM, A BITE OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's apple blossom time: romantic, nostalgic, wonderful days in
May when all the world is fragrant, blooming, and beautiful. No
flowering tree so symbolizes spring in America as the apple.
</P>
<P>
   Brought by the first European settlers, apple trees were
necessary for survival in Colonial times and in settling the West
as well. As soon as land was cleared and a cabin built, an apple
orchard was planted. Fresh apples and apple butter were staples in
the settlers' diets. Boiled apple cider and vinegar were used to
preserve food, and alcoholic applejack, always in demand, could be
used to barter for flour, sugar and livestock.
</P>
<P>
   The legend of Johnny Appleseed sowing apple seeds all over the
country is well known, but American Forests, an old, nonprofit
organization devoted to greener cities, ecosystem restoration, and
helping people plant and care for trees, has researched his real
story.
</P>
<P>
   Born John Chapman in Leominster, Mass., he left home after
serving in the Revolutionary War to start apple tree nurseries, and
then sold the trees to settlers for about 6 cents a piece. As the
settlers began moving to western Pennsylvania, then to Ohio and
beyond, he would precede them by some years going by canoe or on
horseback. In a yet unpopulated area, he would purchase a tract of
land, surround it with a rough brush fence and sow more than 1
million apple seeds on the land. When the settlers finally came, he
would return to his nursery and sell his apple trees to make their
lives more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   A frontiersman of intense religious passion, he believed that
all things existed simultaneously in the physical and spiritual
worlds, and as he planted, he preached as well. Many legends arose
about him, hiding underwater and breathing through a reed to escape
hostile Indians or walking barefoot across a frozen lake. He died
in 1845 in Fort Wayne, Ind., at the age of 70.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his trees are long gone, but a few years ago, an
original 140-year survivor was found by Jeff Meyer, American
Forests' horticulturist, who took cuttings and has propagated this
original tree. A very large, vigorous fast-growing tree, it
produces winter apples, called Rambo. If the idea of growing Johnny
Appleseed's historic tree appeals to you, a 3-foot sapling, which
comes with a certificate and a planting tube to protect it from
deer and weather, can be ordered ($35, plus $8 shipping).
</P>
<P>
   American Forests Historic and Famous Trees Program has other
fascinating trees. How about progeny of the tulip poplar originally
planted by George Washington at Mount Vernon in 1785? Or a white
oak from Franklin Roosevelt's Hyde Park home? You might consider
offspring of the crab apple shading John Kennedy's gravesite in
Arlington National Cemetery. On a lighter note, American Forests
has descendants of trees from Graceland, Elvis Presley's estate. To
learn more about this planting program, check out American Forests'
Web site at www.amfor.org/fht, or call 1-800-320-8733.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to grow apple trees as ornamentals, they are lovely
and produce more than enough fruit for applesauce, apple butter,
pies and such. Excess fallen fruit on a lawn needs to be raked up.
To grow apples as a serious crop requires pruning, using resistant
varieties, spraying for diseases and insects, and usually growing
dwarf varieties so one does not have to harvest with a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Since we're waxing romantic about apple blossoms, why not a
little sentimentality for moms on Mother's Day? I just picked a
small bouquet of violets, actually weeded them out of the perennial
bed, to be honest. But it brought back memories of days long gone
when, in our woods, I would pick little bouquets of violets for my
mother. There were always wild violets along the path.
</P>
<P>
   Violets are reliable as the return of spring. I grow lots of
them, purple, white, pinkish, speckled and every hue in between. Or
rather, I let them grow, for they volunteer everywhere, their seeds
carried by ants and other critters.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers grow in the lawn, where they are a considered a weed
by the green carpet crowd. In the perennial bed, they have to be
kept from surrounding weaker plants. In the vegetable garden,
despite being edible, they get plowed under. By summer's end their
tired leaves wear brown-splashed fatigues. But in May, they are
fresh and young, ready to be picked for a nostalgic nosegay for
someone special.
</P>
<P>
   Because violets can become intrusive, where to plant them and
let them run is a challenge. Some spots to consider are under
shrubs, behind the mulch pile, around the play equipment, beside
the garage, edging the vegetable plot, along the property line.
Like all wildflowers, they will move slowly southward to follow the
sun. Good soil, moisture and fertilizer will help them grow strong.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone should have some sprigs of violets to pick, for like
the ever-returning spring, their cheerful faces add grace to the
month of May. And someday, they may stir a memory for your family
of days long gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ruth S. Foster has been a landscape consultant in the Boston area
for many years.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
