<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION'S ROLE TO SELF-DISCOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The adventurer's life is determined by destiny. And
fate surely will be involved in Walter Zenga's arrival Saturday in
Columbus, Ohio, some 500 years after the city's namesake Genovese
explorer sailed to the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga also has discovered a new world, one in which
soccer-specific stadia are rare. Now Zenga will lead the Revolution
into their eighth game of the season, the first in Columbus Crew
Stadium, which has been constructed as a model for MLS teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe my team will become a part of history,'' Zenga said
Sunday. ``But my team must not think about the inauguration and the
party, it must think only about Columbus.''
</P>
<P>
   The team, not Christopher, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga believes the scale of the Crew Stadium, with 22,500
capacity expandable to 40,000, is ideal for the MLS. Zenga has
regularly performed in much larger stadia in grander cities, but he
concluded his Serie A career in Italy in a perfectly acceptable
43,000-capacity stadium in Genoa with Sampdoria, a club presided
over by a Boston University graduate, Enrico Mantovani.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should have been done before the first season, not in the
fourth season,'' Revolution midfielder John Harkes said. ``But it's
exciting that this is being done and that someone had the vision
and the dedication to put this kind of money into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution again will be shorthanded. Zenga (right groin
strain) and Mike Burns (hamstring) are probable. Harkes (right knee
ligament sprain) is questionable. Imad Baba (groin), Richard
Goulooze (calf strain), and Paul Keegan (right knee ligament
sprain) are doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution are facing three successive road games,
they seem optimistic. They have earned only 1 point in four home
matches, but have won twice and tied in regulation time in three
away games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to play the same soccer in Foxborough,'' Zenga said.
``But it isn't any different playing home or away.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, road trips to Eastern Conference sites can be relatively
stress-free, with little distracting or negative influence from
opposing fans.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, expectations could be unrealistically high for the
Crew, who are in first place in the Eastern Conference after
playing their first seven matches on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the experienced players, this is another fairly big
game,'' Burns said. ``But you never know how the younger players
will react.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is this is a conference game for us and we are
a win away from being in first or last place. We are going to have
to at least match (Columbus's) intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara, an Azorean club in Portugal's Second Division, will
meet the Revolution in an exhibition at Foxboro Stadium 7:30 p.m.
June 10 . . . The Midnight Riders supporters group will travel by
bus to Columbus and to East Rutherford for the MetroStars game May
29.
</P>
</TEXT>
