<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PROM-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET 16 AND ABOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mount St. Joseph Academy announced it was having a spring
freshman prom, Robin Carney was wicked excited. After all, she had
a date and money for all the trappings (limo, tickets, photographs,
hairdresser, and makeup artist).
</P>
<P>
   But like a twisted Cinderella story, Carney _ a plus-size
clothes wearer _ discovered over the months that there was no way
she could go to the ball. Unfortunately for her, most retailers
don't carry prom dresses larger than a juniors's size 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on my hands and knees begging stores,'' says Carney, 14,
whose dad, Bob, drove her all over Boston. ``Every store that had
my size (22) had old-lady clothes. And it was way too expensive to
have a dress made.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the ugly side of prom season. While many high school
girls are tanning and cruising malls to prepare for one of the most
anticipated events of the teenage years, plenty of plus-size girls
are sitting at home in tears. (Girl magazine reports that millions
of US teenagers fall in the plus-size range.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to find dresses,'' says Jessica Boyle, 17, a
size 22 junior at Saugus (Mass.) High School who has shopped all
over the area. While she can find formals that fit, they aren't the
stylish ``must-have'' gowns featured in magazines like Prom and
Seventeen. They're mature-looking gowns designed for older women _
a big ``no'' for a student in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think society has this idea of the perfect gal: the skinnier
the better,'' complains Boyle. ``I understand that I'm a teenager
and that most people my age are not my size. Still, it's unfair
that larger-size clothes are ugly. They're lime green and orange.
They say `Look at me. I could be nuclear waste.' ''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the plus-size teen market _ size 16 and up _ has
come a long way from the past. Young, rail-thin celebrities like
Calista Flockhart are under attack for sending the wrong message to
13- to 18-year-old Americans, who number 11.3 million, according to
the US Census Bureau. The new magazine Girl meticulously places
teenagers of all shapes and sizes on its pages. Stores like Sizes
Unlimited, The Avenue, Lane Bryant and 14/16 Plus cater to the need
for fashionable casual clothes ranging from women's size 14 to 32
(Lane Bryant stops at size 28). A junior's size 18 is the
equivalent of a women's size 14, while a junior's size 32 compares
to a women's size 28.
</P>
<P>
   The persistence of eating disorders and miracle diets, however,
still stands as testimony to the fact that many in society can't
shake the notion that ``thin is in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been really slow to catch on that 50 percent of
teenage girls are size 11 or above,'' says Susannah Cahn, fashion
director at Girl, which conducted its own research. ``It's time
people accepted that. Retailers need to carry cool clothes in all
different sizes. That's reality.''
</P>
<P>
   But many store owners say they won't carry junior gowns over
size 18 because manufacturers charge them extra fees. ``I fight
with manufacturers every day,'' says Yolanda Cellucci, owner of
Yolanda's boutique in Waltham, Mass. ``When I say I need a 20 or
22, they tell me I have to pay $50 more. . .They think their
dresses look unattractive that large and they don't want to ship
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda's will special order dresses for girls. The store also
custom makes plus-size prom dresses but the price tags are a
shocker: $400 to $500 each.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be flip and suggest that plus-size teens who are
frustrated with their shopping options should just lose weight.
Well, Robin Carney has tried that. ``I've tried so many times to be
a size 0,'' she says. ``I tried Slim Fast, dieting, and exercise. I
couldn't do it. I've always gone back to being Robin, not being
skinny.''
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, she says, it wouldn't matter. ``I think if
you're not going to be a size 2 it's not a big deal,'' she says.
``Not everyone has to be perfect in a bathing suit.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but try explaining that to the kids at school. Stephanie
Patalano, 17, says she used to come home bawling everyday after
school. ``I grew up my whole life with people making fun of me. .
.Now that I look back on it, it's terrible...the mean jokes. You
can't tell an overweight person not to care. Of course I care.''
</P>
<P>
   Her freshman year in high school in Medford, Mass., Patalano
remembers people snickering as she walked down the hall. ``Someone
threw paper in my hair once,'' says the size 22-24 senior. ``There
there was a big fight . . . someone said something. I said
something back. A fist flew and that's all I needed.'' (Patalano
won the fight.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Society thinks everyone should be a small size. It's what
we're brought up to think. It's a crock . . . I think size 2 is
disgusting. Calista Flockhart? I don't think she's beautiful at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the plus-size prom set, there's a new fairy
godmother of sorts in the Boston area. Jody Abrams, a plus-size
social worker who missed her prom, has opened Bodacious Babes in
Saugus, Mass., a contemporary clothing store dedicated to sizes 14
to 36. She carries everything from lingerie to business suits for
women to hip prom dresses for teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what it's like to have a choice of not just
one thing, but many things,'' Abrams says. ``It's really affirming
when a customer comes in your store and starts screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   For Robin Carney, who was ready to tell her date that she
couldn't go to the prom, discovering Bodacious Babes was a dream
come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the car, my Mom was like `Don't get your hopes up,' ''
recalls Carney. ``She was doubtful because we had been to so many
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the Carneys crossed their fingers and walked in. ``It was
glorious,'' says Robin's mother, Susan. ``It was like walking into
heaven. There were five beautiful dresses to choose from . . . it
was the first time we've ever had that kind of selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother and daughter broke down in tears when Robin tried on the
gowns and Robin recalls her mother said, ``You're going! You're
definitely going!''
</P>
<P>
   What a change from the days when Robin _ looking for dresses for
school dances _ would stand outside plus-size stores while her
mother brought career-looking adult dresses to the door for her to
discreetly approve. ``I get wicked self-conscious,'' Robin
concedes. ``Who's going to see me there?''
</P>
<P>
   Says Susan, ``A trip to the mall turned into something very sad.
. .I would get her something. She hated it. She would get in a bad
mood and ruin the dance. . .It's so important for teenage girls to
dress right.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin's silver prom gown was certainly a hit at school but
sadly, five of her close friends (all plus-size) couldn't afford
Bodacious Babes' prices (prom gowns average $189). Rather than go
to the prom, the friends (who told Robin they were too
self-conscious to be interviewed) came to Robin's house and sat on
her bed to watch her get ready. ``They were all crying when I put
on my makeup,'' says Carney. ``They said, `I want to go so bad! I
should have gotten a dress!' They were all so surprised. They'd
never seen a plus-size dress so beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carney walked into the dance hall, she says, ``I felt like
a princess. . .My dress was awesome.'' Still, she felt somewhat
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some skinny friends there. But most of my friends are my
size. I wanted my close friends there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1348EDT &QL; 
