<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-MURDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA LINKS KILLER TO UNSOLVED CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An imprisoned killer long suspected of a string
of horrific rape-murders in the San Francisco area has been linked
to the unsolved knife slayings of an Albany couple in 1981, DNA
tests show.
</P>
<P>
   Charles ``Junior'' Jackson, 62, a onetime Oakland handyman
serving a life term for a 1982 Oakland murder, is the prime suspect
in the Nov. 22, 1981, killings of contractor Henry Vila and his
wife, Edith, during a nighttime burglary of their Albany hill home,
police officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Police Lt. Bill Palmini said DNA tests that hadn't been invented
when the Vilas were killed ``conclusively'' linked Jackson to the
murders, which had baffled a generation of detectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never forgot this case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmini said police had reopened their probe of the Vila murders
with the aid of Alameda County prosecutor Rockne Harmon, a
nationally known DNA expert who has been helping homicide
investigators use state-of-the-art DNA tests to break unsolved
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon said Jackson may not be charged with murdering the Vilas
until scientists complete DNA tests on evidence from a string of
other killings in which he may be implicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't make a charging decision until we address all the
cases we think he's committed,'' the prosecutor said. ``I can't
tell you if we've even scratched the surface with this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is serving a life term in Folsom prison for the January
1982 murder of Joan Stewart, a San Francisco City College biology
professor who was raped, strangled and stabbed along a wooded road
in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators declined to disclose the other cases in which
Jackson is emerging as an uncharged suspect. But according to court
records from his 1982 trial, Harmon, who prosecuted the case, told
the judge at the time that he believed _ but could not prove _ that
Jackson had committed these crimes:
</P>
<P>
   _ The rape and stabbing murder of Ann Johnson, 27, the wife of a
Highland Hospital physician, in her home in Oakland's Montclair
District in August 1975.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rape and stabbing murder of Marian Kiteas, 42, in her home
in the El Cerrito hills, eight days after Johnson died.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rape and stabbing murder of Gladys Fielding, whose age was
not specified, in her Castro Valley home in May 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is described in court records as an illiterate high
school dropout who first was convicted of a felony _ burglary _ in
1953. Over the next 30 years he repeatedly was imprisoned on
convictions for burglary, rape, assault and child molesting.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, he was paroled from prison after serving three years on
a rape conviction and returned to Oakland, where he began working
odd jobs, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Nov. 22, 1981, police believe Jackson broke into
the home of Henry Vila, 62, who was asleep in an upstairs bedroom
with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Vila, roused by the noise, is thought to have confronted the
intruder, and was knifed to death in the bedroom after a struggle.
Edith Vila, 59, was sexually assaulted and stabbed to death in her
bed. The house was ransacked and the phone was ripped out of the
wall, suggesting to investigators that Edith Vila may have been
trying to call for help.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, after Jackson was arrested for Stewart's
murder. Investigators targeted him for the Vila killings, but
police could not find sufficient evidence to charge him, Palmini
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, investigators decided to try DNA testing on a
sample of genetic material that had been collected at the murder
scene and preserved. Two scientific labs compared the material with
a sample of Jackson's DNA, and both concluded the samples matched
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``With today's technology, the DNA can uniquely identify the
person,'' said Harmon, who began using DNA science as a trial
prosecutor and later served as a DNA expert in the O.J. Simpson
trial.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is encouraging police departments to use DNA to
re-investigate unsolved murders and rapes. He said that if DNA
evidence has been preserved, it's relatively simple to compare it
with the DNA of a suspect _ or, in cases in which no suspect has
emerged, to compare it with a state database of criminals' DNA that
is being compiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
