r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-13 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS PUT SQUEEZE ON VENDOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For Scott Fader, competing head-to-head with the
Arizona Diamondbacks has been like a Little Leaguer going up
against Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But, since opening day of last season, Fader has stood his
ground, not backing away from inside pitches, not striking out.
He's even slapped a single or two.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has irritated the suits with the big offices in
Bank One Ballpark. So much so, they recently decided to play (begin
ital) real (end ital) hard ball with Fader, making his life like
facing Randy Johnson _ blindfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a 10-pound bat.
</P>
<P>
   With one arm tied behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have money and power, no doubt about it,'' Fader says.
``The best I can do is talk to guys like you.''
</P>
<P>
   At every Diamondbacks home game, Fader and his small squad of
vendors sell an alternative program called ``Beat on Baseball''
outside Bank One Ballpark. The cost is $1.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of last season, the Diamondbacks' official
program sold for $5. As time went on and Fader thrived, the
Diamondbacks lowered their program price to $3.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, it was dropped to $1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to put me out of business,'' Fader says. ``It's
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Not according to Diamondbacks President Rich Dozer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to put him out of business,'' Dozer says.
``We're just trying to increase our circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, would eventually have the same result. &QL; 
STRIKE 2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing new. At the beginning of last season, team
officials sent a squad of security goons to roust Fader and his
vendors from the street outside the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't want ``Beat on Baseball'' sold near the ballpark,
claiming it was illegal. The team even got the city of Phoenix to
go along with it for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we prevailed on that one,'' Fader says. ``And I eventually
got a check for $10,000 from the city for my troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just the beginning, though, like scoring a run in the top
half of the first inning, before the opposition sends up its heavy
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's become a vendetta by people at the
Diamondbacks,'' says Joseph Kreamer, Fader's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Kreamer sent a letter to the team's attorney threatening to sue
over what he calls a predatory attempt to bankrupt Fader. ``If you
try to deprive someone of their business, you can be liable for
those acts,'' Kreamer said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozer says the Diamondbacks aren't trying to create a monopoly,
but only responding to economic pressures. He also says management
is upset because Fader prints an advertisement for a topless
nightclub on the back of his program.
</P>
<P>
   ``What got us in a tizzy was the family-entertainment thing,''
Dozer says. ``We say baseball is family entertainment and they're
selling a publication that has strip-bar ads in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a smoke screen,'' Fader says. ``They allow `The
(Arizona) Republic' to be sold at the ballpark, and they run ads
from all kinds of strip clubs.'' &QL; 
CURVE BALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, a local television station produced a news
segment taking Fader to task for the risque advertising in his
publication.
</P>
<P>
   The report was done by a station that has a contract to
broadcast Diamondbacks games. The same station that broadcasts the
``Jerry Springer Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hypocrisy here,'' says the attorney Joseph
Kreamer. ``Scott's really getting hurt by this, and it's sad in
light of (Diamondbacks managing general partner) Jerry Colangelo's
new book. Here's Jerry offering advice for small-business men (in
the book), then turning around and smashing one for doing something
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Fader says he has no plans to back off. ``If I started selling
beer, do you think Jerry would lower his price to a buck?'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   But, Fader's a little guy in the big leagues. It's tough enough
to make solid contact when the opposition's hurling high hard
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   He's got no chance against spitballs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
