   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-BALLET-MEN (New York) _ Attention must be paid this
season to the male dancers at American Ballet Theater. Rarely has
so much talent at the top come together at one time: like planets
converging in the night sky to symbolize an auspicious future, this
cluster of men, with their virtuosity and diversity of style, has
changed the look of the company. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   MET-TUTTLE (New York) _ Richard Tuttle, the artist, walks the
galleries of the Metropolitan Museum and talks about art. By
Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SALEM-TRAVEL (Salem, Mass.) _ Stand by the second-story window
of the nearly two-century-old Custom House here and you will find
yourself gazing over a waterfront that once linked the young United
States with the world's farthest corners. All's quiet now. But the
place once saw ships in such numbers _ en route to or from China,
Europe, the West Indies, the South Seas _ as to rank Salem among
the nation's most cosmopolitan and wealthy cities. Salem is
probably most closely linked in the public imagination with the
1692 witchcraft trials, but it contains much more of interest. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ART-AUCTION (New York) _ Christie's 20th-century sale. By Carol
Vogel.
