<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MIDSUMMER-TEX     05-13 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MIDSUMMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ALL IT HAS GOING FOR IT, THIS `DREAM' IS NO GREAT SHAKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Michael Hoffman's idea-stuffed production of ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' spins vigorously. Setting the film in
turn-of-the-century Tuscany, he uses Shakespeare's material for
Freudian implications, as a way to shake off the binding clothes of
the Victorian era _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, we see the quartet of young lovers (Calista
Flockhart, Christian Bale, Anna Friel and Dominic West) passed out
in a field, blissfully stripped of their clothing. It feels,
though, as if it took a long time and lot of work to get them
there.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman put together a dream cast for this film. It includes
Flockhart (in the first film she has done since ``Ally McBeal''),
Michelle Pfeiffer, Kevin Kline, Rupert Everett, Stanley Tucci and
David Strathairn. Everett, speaking his lines with magisterial
slowness, plays Oberon, the fairy king who sets the romantic farce
into motion when he spies the young lovers _ some of whom are
chasing the wrong person _ and decides to meddle in human affairs.
He sends his emissary, Puck (Tucci), to cast spells that will bring
the right couples together. Puck fails miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Oberon's beloved Titania (Pfeiffer) falls for Bottom
(Kline), a strutting blowhard and no-talent actor who has been
transformed into a donkey. The makeup choice here is smart. It
exaggerates Kline's features instead of putting a donkey mask on
his head, so that we can still see his shining, cocky eyes _
although from certain angles, his floppy ears and big teeth make
him look more like a live-action version of Bugs Bunny.
</P>
<P>
   The director's use of actors parodying themselves in an unreal
world can be overwhelming. His 1991 comedy ``Soapdish'' is a
delirious farce of entrances and exits, with Kline as _ again _ a
vain, minimally talented egomaniac actor. ``Soapdish'' also
featured Robert Downey Jr. as a furiously ambitious network
executive who, in the movie climax, staggers off shattered by the
truth and wrings his hands in such a freakish and unique gesture
that you'll be hitting the rewind button to watch several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dream'' could've used Downey's ethereal quick-wittedness.
Hoffman was asked if he considered Downey for Puck _ a role he was
born to play _ and the director replied that he wanted Downey, but
that the actor was having legal troubles and could get no
dispensation to leave the country. (Tucci doesn't do a bad job. His
Puck is closer to the ground, more lizardlike than you imagine.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Midsummer'' features peculiar staging, in which once again the
American actors seem not up to what's asked of them, Flockhart in
particular. She's tantrum-y _ as if she's losing an argument with
McBeal's Fish _ and races through her lines, seemingly in an effort
to finish as quickly as possible. Pfeiffer, shot through the
soft-focus Fairy-cam, is wistful and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's heavy-lidded emphasis seems strange at first, but he
at least shows some command. The movie itself, as oddly deft as it
is sometimes, does not. Coming after ``Shakespeare in Love,''
movies using the Bard now have a huge obstacle to surmount, and ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' isn't up to the race. It feels more like
one of love's labors lost.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``A Midsummer Night's Dream''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Michael Hoffman
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Calista Flockhart, Kevin Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ mild sexuality
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
