<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, May 14:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing Kosovo crisis:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton addresses a
veterans group in what a National Security Council spokesman says
is ``an opportunity to give a larger explanation to the American
people about the U.S. interest in Kosovo.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Bielefeld, Germany) _ Foreign Minister Fischer
is hit by a paint bomb on Thursday as the Green Party holds a wild
congress with Kosovo as its main topic. Unlikely as it may be, a
party vote against Germany's Kosovo policy could lead to fall of
the government. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Diplomatic developments. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-PRESS (Beijing) _ On the role the Chinese media
played in reaction to embassy bombing. Its language was very
reminiscent of old days and many papers printed identical pages of
coverage. But how well and how long and on what issues can this
control really work in a society with access to the Internet and
other communication tools? For instance, at a Foreign Ministry
briefing today, the first question, from a Chinese reporter, was
why officials never mention Serbian ethnic cleansing. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ The Chinese Foreign Ministry criticizes
the U.S. for suggesting that the Chinese government was involved in
protests at the U.S. embassy and elsewhere. A public service is
held with leaders in an apparent effort settle the matter. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RIGHTS (Belgrade ) _ The U.N. human rights commissioner
arrives in the Yugoslav capital and is snubbed by President
Milosevic. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMPEACH (Moscow) _ The Russian Parliament starts its
impeachment hearings against President Boris Yeltsin; other
political developments.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VOICES (Moscow) _ What ordinary Russians have to say
about the political turmoil and the impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LEGAL (Moscow) _ The constitutional ins and outs of
impeachment and how it affects Yeltsin's ability to dismiss
Parliament if it doesn't confirm his latest prime minister. By
Celestine Bohlen. (short)
</P>
<P>
   Eds, see also RUSSIA-ECON, listed below under FINANCIAL.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Israel's prime minister, Benjamin
Netanyahu, with his back to the Western Wall as poll numbers get
grimmer, lashes out at the press, the left, some on the right and
celebrates a bittersweet Jerusalem Day holiday. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-JERUSALEM (Jerusalem) _ The Israelis talk about Jerusalem
as their undivided capital, but the reality is that East Jerusalem
and West Jerusalem are increasingly two separate worlds. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-SPY (London) _ The British government says a former spy
is the person who posted spies' names on a World Wide Web site. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-PRESIDENT (Rome) _ Italy's Treasury minister, Carlo
Ciampi, who belongs to no political party, is elected president by
Parliament, partly for that reason. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ It began as a disaster relief
bill. It's beginning to look like a disaster. The emergency
spending bill for Kosovo and the victims of Hurricane Mitch is
ballooning toward $15 billion, a grab-bag filled with goodies for
senators' favorite causes, dismaying conservatives and liberals
alike and conceivably headed for defeat or a veto. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   JUVENILE-CRIME (Washington) _ The Senate continues working on
the juvenile crime bill, and may take up gun-control amendments. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JUVENILE-CRIME-ASSESS (Washington) _ From Arkansas to Colorado,
most shootings produce much more sound and fury than and political
or legislative action. A look at the political power of the NRA,
and the attempts by Republicans to turn the focus elsewhere. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-GREENFIELD (Undated) _ Meg Greenfield, the editor of The
Washington Post's editorial page, who brought a combination of
gimlet-eyed, sometimes discomfiting analysis and wry wit to bear on
a generation of the nation's policy-makers and politicians, has
died at 69. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GAMES (Los Angeles) _ In the aftermath of the shootings at
Columbine and schools elsewhere, video game makers, whose products
are increasingly coming under fire for excessive violence, have
their annual meeting in Los Angeles. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   HISS-TESTIMONY (New York) _ A judge orders the disclosure of
some grand jury testimony in the Alger Hiss case, saying it will
clear up some important historical questions. Ruling may set
precedent by allowing for release of such testimony in cases of
historical import. By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The political briefs column. By B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Testimony continues in the police
brutality case. By Joseph B. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DUKE-RESEARCH (Durham, N.C.) _ More and more patients are
getting care through participation in research experiments or
clinical trials. What happens to them, and the researchers, when
the government steps in and halts the program, as it did this week
at Duke University? By Philip J. Hilts. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHROMOSOME-LOOPS (Undated) _ Researchers have long wondered
why a cell's ``suicide mechanism,'' triggered by breaks in DNA, is
not activated by the endings of chromosomes. Now they know: the
ends of chromosomes are tied up in a elegant little loop. By
Nicholas Wade. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The peddling of ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' has already reached a frenzied
state _ even though the movie does not open until Wednesday. Behind
the groundswell of excitement is a huge marketing machine
supervised by George Lucas. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   AMR-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The Justice Department files an
antitrust lawsuit against American Airlines, accusing the airline
of predatory pricing. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING-REBOUND (Undated) _ Manufacturing has survived
slowdowns in Asia and elsewhere. That would not be surprising if
not for the fact that export growth has fallen sharply. While
services often get credit for the robust American economy,
manufacturing is clearly holding its own, government statistics
show. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:25 a.m., stocks were higher. The Dow
Jones industrial average was up 112 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 9 points
and the Nasdaq composite was up 22 points. Stocks in Europe were
higher, although a number of markets, including Frankfurt, are
closed for Ascension Day. In Asia, the Japanese and Hong Kong
markets were little changed. In the credit markets at midday, the
long bond was priced to yield 5.77 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   FORD (Detroit) _ Developments at Ford Motor Co.'s annual
meeting. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ President Boris Yeltsin's decision to
fire his Cabinet may deepen Russia's economic troubles by
jeopardizing a badly needed loan reform program with the
International Monetary Fund and other negotiations with foreign
creditors. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ The Brazilian central bank cuts rates
for the sixth time in two months, bringing them to levels last seen
in early September when Russia's financial crisis was beginning to
unnerve foreign investors in Latin America's biggest economy. The
latest rate cut reinforced a view of increased confidence and
unexpectedly strong financial resilience in Brazil. By Simon
Romero.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-POWER-ADS (Washington) _ An affiliate of the Better
Business Bureau that arbitrates complaints about advertising refers
the nuclear industry's ads to the Federal Trade Commission and
state Attorneys General for possible prosecution. The industry had
persisted in running ads about the benefits of nuclear power even
though the ads had been ruled deceptive. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   A.M. Rosenthal's ``On My Mind'' and Thomas L. Friedman's
``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
