<HEADER>
A5608 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     05-13 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TELLS HOW SOME DOWN-TO-EARTH GUYS MADE IT BIG IN HARDWARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The names Bernie Marcus and Arthur Blank may not be familiar,
but if you're a homeowner, you sure know their store.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about the suburbanite's main supplier. The place new
homeowners go and drop a hundred bucks every week for what seems
like years.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   If you ever wondered how such a great concept developed, or how
much a retailer could influence American life, read ``Built from
Scratch: How A Couple of Regular Guys Grew The Home Depot From
Nothing to $30 Billion'' (Times, 332 pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Marcus and Blank, who founded Home Depot, wrote the book with
Bob Andelman.
</P>
<P>
   They offer great stories about starting and running a successful
business.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take many numbers to show how well these guys are
doing. In 20 years, the chain has gone from four stores in Atlanta
to 775 stores with 160,000 employees, or associates. The chain's
combined sales total, as the title suggests, $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   This book is an open, no-holes-barred look at two brilliant yet
down-to-earth men. Their honesty shines through. They even reveal
their secret to success _ in the first paragraph:
</P>
<P>
   ``Take two Jews who have just been fired, add an Irishman who
just walked away from a bankruptcy and an Italian running a no-name
investment banking firm. Add _ then subtract _ Ross Perot. Lease
space from a shrinking discount chain, fill a space the size of a
football field full of hardware (and a few hundred empty boxes,)
and you've got a company.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus and Blank were fired after successfully running Handy
Dan, a subsidiary of Daylin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Without financing, the two embarked on a new type of hardware
retail store that had been in the back of Marcus' mind for years.
By 1979, he was ready to test that concept with the first Home
Depot.
</P>
<P>
   But they still needed money, and that is where Dallas
billionaire Ross Perot entered the picture, although only briefly.
Perot, Marcus and Blank, along with investment banker Ken Langone,
had put together a deal in which Perot would put up $2 million in
exchange for 70 percent ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But after several meetings _ and Perot's veto of Marcus owning a
used Cadillac as a company car _ Marcus knew that the relationship
would not work. He later notes that Perot's original investment of
$2 million would be worth about $58 billion today.
</P>
<P>
   But an investment group came forth with the money, and Marcus
and Blank had their company.
</P>
<P>
   There authors provide many other interesting vignettes and many
sound managerial concepts that you've read in other books, but, in
this case, also see in practice.
</P>
<P>
   They talk about building customer loyalty, employee incentives,
building relationships with vendors, giving back to the community
and providing shareholder return. Ultimately, they show how doing
all of these things right can not only make a lot of money but can
also profoundly affect a culture.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus likes to tell of speaking before the Rotary Club in
Atlanta in 1981 and asking how many people considered themselves
real do-it-yourselfers. At that time, about 20 people raised their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when he made the same speech to the same club and asked
the same question, only 15 of the 450 people did not raise their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had changed America,'' they write.
</P>
<P>
   This book will tell you how.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Leader to Leader: Enduring Insights on Leadership from the
Drucker''
</P>
<P>
   Foundation's Award-Winning Journal
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Frances Hesselbein and Paul M. Cohen
</P>
<P>
   Jossey-Bass, $27
</P>
<P>
   This collection of essays written by top management gurus and
managers is pulled from ``Leader to Leader,'' a quarterly started
three years ago by the Drucker Foundation. The publication has no
set agenda, but it opens the floodgate for what is on the minds of
managers, such as Drucker, and those in the thick of the work, such
as Southwest Airlines Chairman Herb Kelleher. Leadership, teams,
the global economy and the information economy are some of the
topics of these interesting essays.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``What Every Manager Needs to Know About Sexual Harassment''
</P>
<P>
   By Darlene Orlov and Michael T. Roumell
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1997, the number of sex discrimination claims rose
42 percent, according to the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission. Of those claims, the number involving sexual harassment
more than doubled. Darlene Orlov, a human resources consultant, and
Michael Roumell, an attorney specializing in labor and employment
law, have written a good and practical overview, complete with
concrete ideas on how to write and implement policies.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart Guide to Starting a Small Business''
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Rogak
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $10.95
</P>
<P>
   At any given moment, about 7 million adults in this country are
contemplating starting their own businesses. This book focuses on
how to plan, start and operate a business during its first year. It
covers topics such as finding the best business to fit your
personality and skills, finding the financing and how to market
your venture. The author owns a publishing company and has written
more than 25 books.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
