<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing Kosovo crisis:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton addresses a
veterans group in what a National Security Council spokesman says
is ``an opportunity to give a larger explanation to the American
people about the U.S. interest in Kosovo.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Bielefeld, Germany) _ Foreign Minister Fischer
is hit by a paint bomb on Thursday as the Green Party holds a wild
congress with Kosovo as its main topic. Unlikely as it may be, a
party vote against Germany's Kosovo policy could lead to fall of
the government. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Diplomatic developments. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-PRESS (Beijing) _ On the role the Chinese media
played in reaction to embassy bombing. Its language was very
reminiscent of old days and many papers printed identical pages of
coverage. But how well and how long and on what issues can this
control really work in a society with access to the Internet and
other communication tools? For instance, at a Foreign Ministry
briefing today, the first question, from a Chinese reporter, was
why officials never mention Serbian ethnic cleansing. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ The Chinese Foreign Ministry criticizes
the U.S. for suggesting that the Chinese government was involved in
protests at the U.S. embassy and elsewhere. A public service is
held with leaders in an apparent effort settle the matter. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RIGHTS (Belgrade ) _ The U.N. human rights commissioner
arrives in the Yugoslav capital and is snubbed by President
Milosevic. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
