   And
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LEGAL (Moscow) _ The constitutional ins and outs of
impeachment and how it affects Yeltsin's ability to dismiss
Parliament if it doesn't confirm his latest prime minister. By
Celestine Bohlen. (short)
</P>
<P>
   Eds, see also RUSSIA-ECON, listed below under FINANCIAL.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Israel's prime minister, Benjamin
Netanyahu, with his back to the Western Wall as poll numbers get
grimmer, lashes out at the press, the left, some on the right and
celebrates a bittersweet Jerusalem Day holiday. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-JERUSALEM (Jerusalem) _ The Israelis talk about Jerusalem
as their undivided capital, but the reality is that East Jerusalem
and West Jerusalem are increasingly two separate worlds. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-SPY (London) _ The British government says a former spy
is the person who posted spies' names on a World Wide Web site. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-PRESIDENT (Rome) _ Italy's Treasury minister, Carlo
Ciampi, who belongs to no political party, is elected president by
Parliament, partly for that reason. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ It began as a disaster relief
bill. It's beginning to look like a disaster. The emergency
spending bill for Kosovo and the victims of Hurricane Mitch is
ballooning toward $15 billion, a grab-bag filled with goodies for
senators' favorite causes, dismaying conservatives and liberals
alike and conceivably headed for defeat or a veto. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   JUVENILE-CRIME (Washington) _ The Senate continues working on
the juvenile crime bill, and may take up gun-control amendments. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JUVENILE-CRIME-ASSESS (Washington) _ From Arkansas to Colorado,
most shootings produce much more sound and fury than and political
or legislative action. A look at the political power of the NRA,
and the attempts by Republicans to turn the focus elsewhere. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-GREENFIELD (Undated) _ Meg Greenfield, the editor of The
Washington Post's editorial page, who brought a combination of
gimlet-eyed, sometimes discomfiting analysis and wry wit to bear on
a generation of the nation's policy-makers and politicians, has
died at 69. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GAMES (Los Angeles) _ In the aftermath of the shootings at
Columbine and schools elsewhere, video game makers, whose products
are increasingly coming under fire for excessive violence, have
their annual meeting in Los Angeles. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   HISS-TESTIMONY (New York) _ A judge orders the disclosure of
some grand jury testimony in the Alger Hiss case, saying it will
clear up some important historical questions. Ruling may set
precedent by allowing for release of such testimony in cases of
historical import. By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The political briefs column. By B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
