   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DUKE-RESEARCH (Durham, N.C.) _ More and more patients are
getting care through participation in research experiments or
clinical trials. What happens to them, and the researchers, when
the government steps in and halts the program, as it did this week
at Duke University? By Philip J. Hilts. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHROMOSOME-LOOPS (Undated) _ Researchers have long wondered
why a cell's ``suicide mechanism,'' triggered by breaks in DNA, is
not activated by the endings of chromosomes. Now they know: the
ends of chromosomes are tied up in a elegant little loop. By
Nicholas Wade. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The peddling of ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' has already reached a frenzied
state _ even though the movie does not open until Wednesday. Behind
the groundswell of excitement is a huge marketing machine
supervised by George Lucas. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   AMR-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The Justice Department files an
antitrust lawsuit against American Airlines, accusing the airline
of predatory pricing. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING-REBOUND (Undated) _ Manufacturing has survived
slowdowns in Asia and elsewhere. That would not be surprising if
not for the fact that export growth has fallen sharply. While
services often get credit for the robust American economy,
manufacturing is clearly holding its own, government statistics
show. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:25 a.m., stocks were higher. The Dow
Jones industrial average was up 112 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 9 points
and the Nasdaq composite was up 22 points. Stocks in Europe were
higher, although a number of markets, including Frankfurt, are
closed for Ascension Day. In Asia, the Japanese and Hong Kong
markets were little changed. In the credit markets at midday, the
long bond was priced to yield 5.77 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   FORD (Detroit) _ Developments at Ford Motor Co.'s annual
meeting. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ President Boris Yeltsin's decision to
fire his Cabinet may deepen Russia's economic troubles by
jeopardizing a badly needed loan reform program with the
International Monetary Fund and other negotiations with foreign
creditors. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ The Brazilian central bank cuts rates
for the sixth time in two months, bringing them to levels last seen
in early September when Russia's financial crisis was beginning to
unnerve foreign investors in Latin America's biggest economy. The
latest rate cut reinforced a view of increased confidence and
unexpectedly strong financial resilience in Brazil. By Simon
Romero.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-POWER-ADS (Washington) _ An affiliate of the Better
Business Bureau that arbitrates complaints about advertising refers
the nuclear industry's ads to the Federal Trade Commission and
state Attorneys General for possible prosecution. The industry had
persisted in running ads about the benefits of nuclear power even
though the ads had been ruled deceptive. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
