<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-CANDIDATES-$ADV16     05-13 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-CANDIDATES-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CANDIDATES SEEK TO CLICK WITH VOTERS ON THE INTERNET
 &HT;    730&AMP;adds. With WEB-SITES. Moving in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories for release Sunday, May 16.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a million potential voters discovering the
Internet every month, the presidential candidates have rushed to
hang their campaign banners in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike 1996, when the World Wide Web was less pervasive, about a
dozen slickly packaged campaign 2000 sites have sprung up in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   To voters, they offer a wealth of information on the candidates
and their families, speech texts, position papers and travel
schedules. As Internet bandwidth expands, the sites may offer full
audio and video services.
</P>
<P>
   What they do not offer is a critical look at their own campaigns
nor, for that matter, any others. For political comparison
shopping, Web users must look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   To candidates, the Internet is a way to reach wealthier and
better-educated citizens, who are more likely to vote, and younger
ones who are politically uncommitted. It is a new way to recruit
volunteers, correspond with the public and sample their opinions,
and _ if regulators can be persuaded to go along _ even collect
campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The Web's appeal to presidential contenders is further
heightened because it's much cheaper to reach voters on line than
with such traditional methods as TV ads, direct mail or
door-to-door visits. Some experts predict the Internet could do
much to level a political playing field long tilted in favor of the
best-financed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But a site's best value to a candidate may lie in the ability to
easily create databases of thousands of loyal supporters. It takes
only a few taps on a keyboard to send highly targeted messages to
large groups via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 2000 campaign is going to be the first election cycle when
there'll be some real campaigning done on the Internet,'' said
Craig Crawford, an analyst for the Hotline, an online political
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who learn how to ``successfully inform, persuade,
enlighten, and even confuse voters'' on line will win votes, said
Gary Selnow, a professor of computing systems at San Francisco
State University and a leading scholar on the advent of political
activity on the Internet. To do so, he said, they need to sponsor
state-of-the-art ``home pages'' while also offering extensive
electronic bulletin boards and access to their data libraries.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual tour of the Web sites uploaded by the current crop of
presidential hopefuls reveals that nearly all of them are doing
just that. Perhaps predictably, the well-financed front runners _
Democratic Vice President Al Gore and Republican Texas Gov. George
W. Bush _ have also mounted the most extensive Internet efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Updated nearly every day, the Gore and Bush sites feature
interactive polling on such issues as the Colorado school killings
and video and audio clips of their campaign appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain's site features a ``2000 Campaign Store'' where
for $25, fans can buy a videotape on line that tells the Arizona
Republican's life story.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish such tasks, presidential hopefuls have hired a
host of Internet advisers. Campaign finance records show that up to
half of the top-paid 20 presidential consultants in the first three
months of 1999 did all or some of their work on their candidates'
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   And yet just how this process will evolve remains uncertain.
Some cyber-gurus doubt whether the Web can reach undecided voters
in significant numbers, a vital element in close races. ``I don't
think we're going to see that yet in 2000,'' the Hotline's Crawford
says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, compared to traditional campaign methods, the Internet
remains a bargain. ``For what you put into it, you get a real good
return on the dollar,'' noted Roger Salazar, Gore's political
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Pat Buchanan pays his webmaster a hefty $50,000 annual
salary, Bush compensates his top political consultant, Karl Rove,
at the far heftier rate of $2,400 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, yet another Republican contender with deep pockets
and a richly textured Web site, spent $200,000 on video production
costs in the first quarter of 1999, plus hundreds of thousands more
in direct mail appeals. The elaborate Forbes site, which he opened
to formally announce his candidacy in March, costs less than
$10,000 a month to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The 21st century is about to begin, and nobody can afford to
look like they belong to the previous century,'' says Michael
Cornfield, a political scientist who teaches a course at George
Washington University on the impact of the new media on U.S.
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Internet is going to change American politics and
American campaigning, but it's not going to do it the way
television did it with one dramatic event like the Kennedy-Nixon
debates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like the telephone or electricity. There are going
to be small changes by the hundreds of millions. And we're going to
look back in five years and say oh, the late 1990s and the year
2000, that's when it began.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same factor that's feeding the use of the Internet
for commerce, for E-mail. There are millions upon millions of
people who are going on line to do everything and politicians go
where the people are,'' Cornfield adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other great attraction for politicians is (they) like to
go on at length on their views, and in contrast to television,
radio, even newspapers, you can go on as long as you want on your
own Web site and nobody's going to cut you off,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   While some presidential Web sites invite visitors to make
on-line contributions with their credit cards, the Federal
Elections Commission bars such donations from counting toward
much-prized federal matching funds in the hope that it will deter
donors seeking to skirt campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Says Sharon Snyder, a spokeswoman for the commission: ``A credit
card is only a promise of payment, not the actual payment. There's
not the required documentation as you get with a check.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the candidates can only ask would-be donors to follow
up their on-line pledges by sending along their checks. But the
contenders want the commission to reverse its ruling, which has
stood since 1983, before the Internet played a role in politics. A
decision is due in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is clearly a much more significant part of life
than it has been in previous election cycles. It's really an
opportunity for more people to get involved in the matching
process,'' argues Eric Hauser, press secretary to former Sen. Bill
Bradley, who is challenging both Gore for the Democratic nomination
and the FCC for its ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
