   Gary Bauer _ Standard fare oriented to campaign theme of
``Advancing America's Values.'' Interns can volunteer their
services on line. (http://www.bauer2k.com/).
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan _ Finely tuned online menus link to in-depth
position papers, upcoming campaign events and instructions on how
to join Buchanan's ``Internet Brigade.'' (http://gopatgo2000.com/).
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush _ Front-runner's cyber-castle features video and
audio clips plus more family lore than most rivals offer. There's a
direct appeal for Hispanic support. (http://www.georgewbush.com/).
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole _ Stark ``Welcome Page'' opens to a fully
featured site, including links to charities providing aid in Kosovo
crisis (Dole recently visited the war zone) and an on-line version
of the campaign's 129-page quarterly report to the Federal Election
Commission. (http://www.edole2000.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes _ One of the most extensive of the presidential Web
sites and one of the few that faithfully provide daily updates.
Visitors can easily click on hot links to virtually the entire
Republican political online world, plus a host of conservative
organizations and most mainstream news outlets. Press-friendly
stance extends to online sign-up for campaign coverage credentials.
(http://www.forbes2000.com/).
</P>
<P>
   John Kasich _ With short and snappy domain name, Ohio
congressman urges supporters to get involved and shows them how.
(http://k2k.com/).
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes _ Packed with speech texts and schedules.
</P>
<P>
   (http://www.keyes2000.org/).
</P>
<P>
   John McCain _ Slick site highlights toll-free number and ``get
involved'' page to process volunteers and would-be donors online.
Campaign items can be bought through an on-line store.
(http://www.mccainforpresident.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle _ No misspelled words here: Yet another highly
polished site, replete with thumbnails of Quayle's
vice-presidential years. (http://www.quayle.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Bob Smith _ Visitors are bidden to buy Smith's $50 ``share'' in
America's future but aren't shown how. While there's a tab for
``media appearances,'' there were none in the offing in mid-May.
(http://www.smithforpresident.org/).
</P>
<P>
   For an independent view:
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics1'' offers strong Web starting point to examine
would-be presidential players.
(http://www.politics1.com/p2000.htm/).
</P>
<P>
   For basic up-to-date politics news, political junkies also often
turn to ``All Politics'' (http://cnn.com/allpolitics/).
</P>
<P>
   For links to potential presidential candidates in 2000,
including third party hopefuls, you can try
http://www.politicsonline.com/ or ``Elections U.S.A.''
(http://www.geocities.com/CapitolHill/6228/).
