<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEA WITH MUSSOLINI'` MUNCHING SCENERY LIKE CRUMPETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it ``Divas Live, 1935-1945.'' Or to be more accurate,
``Divas on Film.'' The grandes dames on parade in Franco
Zeffirelli's sudsy, picturesque World War II drama, ``Tea With
Mussolini,'' include Cher, Judi Dench, Joan Plowright, Maggie Smith
and Lily Tomlin. With the exception of Ms. Tomlin, playing the
relatively thankless role of a butch, heavily suntanned
archeologist stomping around northern Italy 60 years ago, these
estimable actresses have been encouraged to chew up the scenery
every chance they get. And oh do they grab at it!
</P>
<P>
   Once you accept the notion that ``Tea With Mussolini'' aspires
to be little more than a kind of British-Italian ``Steel
Magnolias,'' with a patina of World War II-movie uplift, it becomes
a pleasure to watch its stars shamelessly hamming it up. Their
thespian antics go a long way toward concealing the weaknesses of a
makeshift screenplay (by John Mortimer and Zeffirelli, based on a
chapter from the director's autobiography) that has many more
characters and events than it can comfortably handle.
</P>
<P>
   The runaway winner of the acting diva derby in terms of
attention-getting lines and haughty attitudinizing is Ms. Smith, as
Lady Hester Random, widow of the British ambassador to Italy and
quintessential British snob. Lady Hester is the de-facto leader of
a small colony of English women living comfortably in Florence in
the late 1930s. Anything that doesn't conform to her refined code
of English aristocratic propriety becomes an object of withering
scorn. Take desserts. Observing a sundae being served, she sniffs
that Americans, whom she despises, have even found a way to
``vulgarize ice cream.'' Craning her long neck, her saucer eyes
bulging with indignation, Ms. Smith suggests a rare, high-strung
shore bird crankily peering down its beak at the more common
species on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Hester, and her circle, known in Florence as the
``Scorpioni,'' who have tea together every afternoon at 4,
ostentatiously worship art and poetry, and lead a charmed
expatriate life. When that existence is imperiled by the rise of
Italian fascism and some smashing of windows, Lady Hester, who
admires Benito Mussolini, arranges for herself and a pushy young
British journalist to meet with Il Duce and receive his personal
assurance that no harm will come to them. With her illusions of
self-importance, she is completely taken in by his propagandistic
flimflam and promise of protection.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Judi plays Arabella Delancey, a flighty, weepy art lover
and would-be painter who flutters around Florence with a mongrel
pooch named Billyboy to whom she is passionately attached. Ms.
Plowright's character, Mary Wallace, is a bit more hard-headed than
Arabella, but still quite dithery. Until Italy aligns itself with
Germany, and English culture suddenly becomes unfashionable, she is
the tutor and surrogate mother to Luca (Charlie Lucas), an
artistically inclined Italian boy whose businessman father wants
her to instill him with English genteel manners.
</P>
<P>
   But once the political tides have shifted, Luca is abruptly
whisked off to Austria for training to become a good little Nazi.
When he re-appears late in the film to execute some improbable
heroics, he is 17 and played (badly) by a different actor (Baird
Wallace).
</P>
<P>
   Flitting in and out of the film is Elsa Morganthal (Cher), a
former Ziegfeld showgirl whose marriages to much-older men who die
have left her swimming in money. A free-spending, free-loving art
collector whose dream in life is to possess Picasso's ``Les
Demoiselles d'Avignon'' (even if it is a fake), Elsa appoints
herself Luca's patron and later entrusts her fortune to a
suspiciously handsome and helpful young Italian lawyer who also
becomes her lover. Flouncing around in garish period fashions, Cher
is as likable as ever, dispensing her special blend of gawky true
grit and zany regality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea With Mussolini,'' which spans 10 years, beginning in 1935,
follows the declining fortunes of these women, who are eventually
rounded up, bused to another city and forced to share crude
barracks-like quarters. When they are transferred to a hotel, Lady
Hester believes that her supposed friend Il Duce has intervened.
She is sadly mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea With Mussolini'' belongs to an old-fashioned tradition of
escapist moviemaking in which star turns, romance and melodrama are
swirled together with pretty scenery and a dash of camp into a
confection that used to be called ``a woman's picture.'' If ``Tea
With Mussolini'' isn't believable for a second, on its own
glamorous terms it isn't half-bad.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `TEA WITH MUSSOLINI'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Tea With Mussolini'' is rated PG (Parental guidance
suggested). It has one discreet bedroom scene.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Franco Zeffirelli; written by John Mortimer and
Zeffirelli, based on ``The Autobiography of Franco Zeffirelli'';
director of photography, David Watkin; edited by Tariq Anwar; music
by Alessio Vlad and Stefano Arnaldi; art directors, Carlo
Centolavigna and Gioia Fiorella Mariani; produced by Riccardo
Tozzi, Giovannella Zannoni and Clive Parsons; released by G2 Films,
an MGM company. Running time: 117 minutes. This film is rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Cher (Elsa), Judi Dench (Arabella), Joan Plowright (Mary),
Maggie Smith (Lady Hester), Lily Tomlin (Georgie), Charlie Lucas
(Luca as a child) and Baird Wallace (Luca).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
