<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING SAIL FOR THE WHITE HOUSE WITH JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You read it here first, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson will not seek the Democratic Party presidential
nomination in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   However, you don't need to call up Dionne Warwick's psychic hot
line to divine Jackson's intentions for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this paradoxical Jacksonian utterance to the Democratic
National Committee last fall:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not decided to run the race in 2000, but I will set the
pace in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that meant he intended to raise certain kinds of issues,
particularly those relating to low-income and minority persons,
whether he was actually running or on the sidelines coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the portrayal of himself as the pacer suggested in
a Freudian way that he was leaning more toward making the race
again than just kibitzing.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing speculation about his 2000 intentions could not help
but make the possibility of a fourth bid for the White House more
tantalizing for him. The clincher, of course, is the spurt of
favorable publicity he has received from his free-lance diplomatic
coup in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   That almost certainly elevated the thought of giving it another
shot from the tempting to the irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   As sure as tides flow in and out, Jackson has decided to run. He
knows about that tide in the affairs that Shakespeare referred to _
how it must be taken at the flood. And his poll numbers now are
flood-level. He must take the plunge now or wonder evermore about
what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he's gotten too long in the tooth to envision a
better opportunity after the century turns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jackson cannot make his announcement at this time.
That wouldn't look right. It would seem too opportunistic, coming
so soon after the release of the three American soldiers who were
kidnapped and held by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Jackson must wait until either a Kosovo peace
agreement is reached or there is indisputable progress toward one.
He will then be able to portray his negotiations with Milosevic as
a breakthrough that helped get the negotiations on track.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson can't wait too long. If he does, he won't be able to
attract the funding and support to mount a credible race. Jackson
knows that; therefore, he is likely to get off the dime before
summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   And that would be exceedingly good for the Democratic Party,
although many of the party's movers and shakers view that prospect
with some trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who shudder at the thought of another Jackson
presidential campaign think that his previous campaigns have
divided the party and diluted its strength.
</P>
<P>
   They can see him raising exalted expectations among
African-Americans, only to have them dashed again when Jackson
doesn't win the nomination. And he won't, again. And thousands of
disillusioned African-Americans will stay home again on Election
Day, they say.
</P>
<P>
   There are Democrats who maintain that in his three bids for the
presidency, Jackson inadvertently has been the best asset the
Republicans had going for them. And they have a point.
</P>
<P>
   But even if that was the case, this is another day. The dynamics
of the 2000 race suggest that a Jackson candidacy would boost the
Democrats' chances of retaining the White House and of regaining
control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's running will indeed be pace-setting. His direct
involvement will assure that meaningful issues are addressed and
that the eventual winner will be toughened sufficiently in the
process to take on George W. Bush and the public relations
illusionists who have made him out to be the leader and thinker
that he is not.
</P>
<P>
   The operating assumption here is that the Republicans will not
be smart enough to nominate Elizabeth Dole, who really does possess
charisma, political skill and the vision thing.
</P>
<P>
   All of the good that Jackson could do for the Democrats in the
end game of the 2000 campaign, however, could go for nothing if
they don't have enough political courage to nominate him for vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Jackson must face reality and accept the
opportunity to become vice president as the only road to the
presidency that is open to him.
</P>
<P>
   With Jackson on the ticket as the vice presidential nominee, the
Democrats would mobilize millions of African-American, Hispanic,
female and low-income voters who otherwise would sit out the
election. They could provide the margins of victory in both the
presidential and congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   As Shakespeare said: ``There is a tide in the affairs of men
...'' Jackson's star is on the rise. The Democrats would be
well-advised to ride it with him.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
