<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5728 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JOANOFARC-TEX     05-13 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JOANOFARC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS' MINISERIES IS A SEXY, COMPLEX TAKE ON FRANCE'S VISIONARY
HEROINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the risk of sounding like a Neanderthal, I must admit that
the Joan of Arc put forth in Sunday's CBS miniseries is the
15th-century equivalent of Britney Spears' see-but-don't-touch
sensuality and ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer's'' kick-butt persona.
Either way, it's a turn-on for at least half the population.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other half, the feminine angle of Joan as a
strong-willed independent woman kicking up dust within a man's
domain more than suffices, particularly once she emerges as a
different kind of leader: one able to handle a sword and move
people with equal skill.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions, however, are beside the point. ``Joan of Arc,''
which airs at 8 p.m. CDT Sunday and Tuesday on CBS, is a powerful,
sensitively made movie that's as refreshing as it is surprising.
Refreshing, since heavily promoted made-for-TV movies are usually
hollow cinematic contraptions. Surprising, since it's airing during
May ``sweeps,'' when such bloated silliness (like the recent
``Noah's Ark'') is the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Director Christian Duguay has coaxed one mighty fine performance
from 16-year-old Leelee Sobieski, who successfully embodies Joan of
Arc's most amazing contradictions _ a girl who becomes a country's
heroic, headstrong savior even though she can neither read nor
write.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne d'Arc, as she was known in France, was a simple peasant
girl who rescued France from defeat in one of the darkest periods
of the Hundred Years' War with England. Her first great triumph was
to lead a French army against the English who had laid siege to the
city of Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, her first triumph was getting past her stern father,
Jacques (Powers Boothe), a well-intentioned provider who, like
pretty much everyone else, didn't quite know what to make of Joan's
deep desire for her country to be unified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your daughter is very outspoken,'' a visitor tells Jacques.
``She is young,'' is his response. ``She'll outgrow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cracks Joan: ``I'll never outgrow simple decency.''
</P>
<P>
   She was a different kind of child early on: good-hearted and
spirited. As she's written here, she often battled her father over
her generosity to others. Some historians believe that Joan may
have been clairvoyant _ that she could hear everyone's thoughts.
But ``Joan of Arc'' doesn't mess around with such matters. It's
made clear that as early as age 10, Joan was having religious
visions and hearing what she believed were the voices of saints.
</P>
<P>
   Telling others that the voices were persuading her to help King
Charles VII of France drive the English from French soil was met
with skepticism, to say the least. Rather quickly, Joan is
perceived as either a young girl clearly devoted to and driven by
God, or a mad woman who needs to cleansed.
</P>
<P>
   Joan first travels to the town of Vaucouleurs and persuades one
of the king's representatives, Sir Robert de Baudricourt (Maury
Chaykin), to provide an escort to see the king, played by Neil
Patrick Harris of ``Doogie Howser'' fame. (Don't worry, he'll grow
on you.) Much of southern France had recognized the young king as
ruler _ but his enemies, the English and the Burgundians (French
citizens who supported the English), controlled Paris and the
northern part of France.
</P>
<P>
   Seems Charles had never been crowned because the city of Reims,
where French kings were crowned, lay in enemy territory. His
situation hopeless, Charles figured it would be harmless to at
least listen to Joan, who might or might not be the fabled savior.
</P>
<P>
   Joan is victorious in battles (there are bloody fight scenes,
but none involving Joan, who was used mostly as a figurehead) and
in bringing a unified front. The English come to see Joan as an
agent of the devil, and eventually imprison her for witchcraft and
heresy.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Sobieski shines, displaying different layers of
emotion, wit and intelligence. Despite the abuse of her English
captors _ including rape and torture _ she continues to insist that
her visions and voices come from God. The exchanges between Joan
and Bishop Cauchon (Peter O'Toole), Charles' spiritual adviser, are
priceless. The bishop eventually believes her, but it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   The scene of Joan burning at the stake is an emotional one, shot
with restraint and earnestness.
</P>
<P>
   This brief synopsis cannot contain all the characters and their
plot-skewing connections to Joan, but Duguay introduces each
character with much-needed clarity.
</P>
<P>
   The director uses his four hours to paint full portraits of the
key players, particularly the obsequious-but-devious bishop, who
fought his own internal demons in deciding whether to believe
Joan's claims of talking to saints. He's like a jealous crybaby,
wanting to remove her if only to mask his own failings as a
clergyman who has never heard anything resembling a higher power.
</P>
<P>
   And Peter Strauss is surprisingly effective as La Hire, a
war-weary mercenary who takes one look at Joan on the battlefield
and asks, ``Shouldn't you be in bed, child?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the only time ``Joan of Arc'' kowtows to Hollywood
caricature, making La Hire the rough military man softened by a
young girl's innocent devotion. Unless, of course, you count the
hint of sexual attraction between Joan and Jean de Metz (Chad
Willett), described in press materials as ``the handsome young
nobleman'' who becomes a trusted ally. He always seems to be
available for intimate fireside chats.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Joan of Arc'' is dramatically enticing and, dare I
say, educational. Many authors have dealt with her life, so you can
imagine the various interpretations. George Bernard Shaw, in fact,
portrayed Joan as a woman with Protestant beliefs who opposed the
Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   Here Joan is a girl who makes choices, who understands her
context in history, who is a natural leader, and whose experiences
shape and expand her actions.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Joan of Arc'' succeeds because it uses Joan to ask other
penetrating questions: Does God talk to you literally or does he
speak to you through inspiration, ideas and bursts of creativity?
Was Joan hearing her own intuition, or was she actually hearing
voices and being guided?
</P>
<P>
   No wonder she remains a mysterious figure. This didn't make it
into the movie, but some historians claim another person was burned
at the stake in her place. Just something else to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
