<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRIS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IRIS BLOND': WHERE TO GO IN DESPAIR? TO A PSYCHIC, OF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Iris Blond'' is a bittersweet romantic comedy that serves as a
reminder of a time when frequent film imports from Italy and France
constantly enriched what has come to be known as the quality of
life in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Not every film was a ``400 Blows,'' ``Breathless'' or ``Claire's
Knee,'' or even ``Cinema Paradiso'' or ``Il Postino,'' nor did it
herald the arrival of a new wave or a new auteur.
</P>
<P>
   But even the modest among these films enlightened audiences
about new directors, new actors, other cultures, other landscapes
and other attitudes and customs.
</P>
<P>
   So in its skilled, commercially entertaining way, ``Iris
Blond,'' imported from Italy and filmed in Belgium, can be
appreciated for its window on other worlds and its grown-up
attitude toward love.
</P>
<P>
   For those who cherish the hallmarks of European style, let it be
said that ``Iris Blond'' reaches its denoument in classic fashion
in a Brussels railroad station and on a stage before an ecstatic
young audience.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing well-acted comedy, stylish pop music and an informed eye
for the promises and perils of romance, ``Iris Blond'' stars Carlo
Verdone, its director and co-author, as Romeo Spera.
</P>
<P>
   Like his namesake, Romeo, a composer, keyboardist and band
leader, is not lucky in love. Closing in on 50 when the film opens
in Italy, he is being informed that his latest love has been
betraying him with a married member of the band, which means that
both Romeo's relationship with the woman and the band are finished.
</P>
<P>
   Like any sane person whose life has collapsed around him, Romeo
heads for a popular fortuneteller (Nuccia Fumo), known as the
Saint, and in a richly comic scene played from a wheelchair and
behind smoked glasses, she tells him of his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   It resides with a woman named for a flower who is a singer to
boot. Well, in a twinkling, Romeo has a gig playing piano aboard a
cruise ship, and he and a woman of a certain age named Marguerite
(Andrea Ferreol) are exchanging goo-goo eyes across a crowded room.
</P>
<P>
   In the terrestrial realm, Romeo and Marguerite (a flower of the
chrysanthemum family) are soon sharing her digs in Brussels with
her pampered white poodle, Corneille, and Romeo is accompanying
Marguerite in her Jacques Brel nightclub act, playing ``Ne Me
Quitte Pas'' ad nauseam.
</P>
<P>
   So late one night Romeo uses a walk for Corneille as a pretext
to escape Marguerite's company and her diet to gorge himself in a
fast food outlet. And there he meets Iris (Claudia Gerini), a
waitress who is not only named for a flower but also Italian,
beautiful, half his age and possessed of legs that seem to stretch
from Taormina to Milan. What's more, she can sing like an angel, as
he discovers on a visit to church.
</P>
<P>
   A few drawbacks: Iris drops men as fast as she attracts them,
and although she is willing to let Romeo live with her while he
composes for her and readies her for a career as a pop artist,
there is to be no sex _ at least not with him.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, everyone will achieve success, but in European films
as in real life, success and a happy ending are two different
things.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``Iris Blond'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It involves uninhibited language, simulated sex
and partial nudity.
</P>
<P>
   `IRIS BLOND'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Carlo Verdone; written (in French and Italian, with
English subtitles) by Francesca Marciano, Pasquale Plastino and
Verdone; director of photography, Giuseppe Di Biase; produced by
Vittorio Cecchi Gori and Rita Cecchi Gori; released by Miramax
Films. At the Angelika Film Center, Mercer and Houston Streets,
Greenwich Village. Running time: 100 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Carlo Verdone (Romeo Spera), Claudia Gerini (Iris Blond),
Andrea Ferreol (Marguerite), and Nuccia Fumo (Fortuneteller).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
