r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DANCEMAKER-TEX     05-13 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DANCEMAKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART _ AND THE PAIN _ BEHIND A GREAT DANCE COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dancemaker,'' the Oscar-nominated documentary about
choreographer Paul Taylor, starts with a camera watching from the
wings as his company bounds onto the stage.
</P>
<P>
   As we hear the dancers sliding across the floor and their
footfalls slapping onto the boards, ``Dancemaker's'' uniqueness is
evident. Never before has a movie on dancers given such a sense of
their physcial presence. And we also get a sense of the man who
created the company, and whose talent and ego have made it such a
singular artistic triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Diamond shows all the abrasions and scar tissue
behind keeping such a company running. A former dancer himself, he
imbues ``Dancemaker'' with the sense of Olympian physical
sacrifice. The performers, after a glorious performance, talk about
the aftermath and the toll the dancing exacts _ you can hear the
muscles rip and the bones creak.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor initially comes off as kindly and a little distracted _ a
slow-motion charmer who tosses off gentle anecdotes between hissing
plumes of smoke from a cigarette. (And the cigarette becomes a
motif _ the nicotine is the calmative that links almost everyone.)
</P>
<P>
   But the more time the camera spends interviewing him as he tells
stories of his successes and failures, the clearer it is that he
makes every single decision. His high-strung obstinacy _ a contrast
to his laid-back manner _ is also reflected in the interviews with
the dancers from his troupe, both current and former, who discuss
surviving their tenure. (One of the dancers, an enthusiastic young
woman, is fired by Taylor, who says he just didn't want her around
anymore.) This is a powerful portrait of the rewards of art, and
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Dancemaker''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 5 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Matthew Diamond
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Paul Taylor
</P>
<P>
   Length: 98 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Not rated _ includes nudity and adult subject matter
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
