<SLUG> BC-FILM-STARWARS-CHARACTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHARACTER GUIDE TO `THE PHANTOM MENACE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've seen the first ``Star Wars'' trilogy so many times you
can recite the dialogue in your sleep.
</P>
<P>
   You know all about Luke, Leia, Han, Lando and Chewbacca.
</P>
<P>
   You know all about Death Stars and X-Wing fighters.
</P>
<P>
   You know it all.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those characters or elements are to be found in
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' which opens
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although some familiar faces will reappear, George Lucas'
universe is expanding along with his special-effects artistry, and
the new film offers an awesome amount to absorb.
</P>
<P>
   Another adjustment is the fact that it's the first part of a
prequel trilogy. ``The Phantom Menace'' begins a generation before
Darth Vader chased Princess Leia toward Tatooine at the start of
1977's ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   But take heart. There's still time to cram _ and without
spoiling too much of the story.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see the film ``cold,'' read no further.
Otherwise, here's a roundup of major characters to watch for in
``The Phantom Menace,'' and how the prequel trilogy will tie into
the original.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHERE IT ALL BEGINS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' story starts about 30 years before ``Star
Wars.'' The greedy Trade Federation threatens the balance of the
peaceful Galactic Republic, placing a blockade around the planet
Naboo. Jedi Knights intervene on behalf of Naboo. Yet the true
threat _ ``the phantom menace'' _ is the elusive Darth Sidious.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile on the desert planet Tatooine, a small boy named
Anakin Skywalker and his mother live as slaves. But the empowering
Force is strong in Anakin, and his destiny lies in the stars _ as
Darth Vader, military commander of a dark Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come in the prequel trilogy are the ``Clone Wars''
referred to briefly by Princess Leia in ``Star Wars,'' and the
near-extermination of the Jedis that's apparent in ``Star Wars,''
with the evil Empire taking over the galaxy and Obi-Wan and Yoda
living as hermits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Episode II'' is expected to be set about a decade later than
The Phantom Menace, with a romance between the grown Anakin and
Queen Amidala of Naboo. They will wed, and Amidala will give birth
to Luke and Leia.
</P>
<P>
   The siblings, strong in the Force, will face desperate times
during ``Episode III.'' Though separated as infants, their rescue
and survival will provide ``A New Hope'' (the subtitle of ``Episode
IV,'' which was the original ``Star Wars'' film), when the Rebel
Alliance defies the Empire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THEY'RE BACK _ BUT YOUNGER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Obi-Wan Kenobi: The Jedi Master played by Sir Alec Guinness as
an old man and mentor to Luke Skywalker in 1977's ``Star Wars''
appears here as an eager young Jedi apprentice played by Ewan
McGregor.
</P>
<P>
   _ R2-D2: The squat little astromech droid of the first trilogy
appears here in all his cute, beeping glory, looking just the same.
</P>
<P>
   _ C-3PO: The prissy gold protocol droid of the first trilogy
appears in ``Phantom Menace,'' but in unfinished, skeletal form.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anakin Skywalker: Before he became father of Luke Skywalker
and Princess Leia and then a mass murderer, Darth Vader was an
innocent, mop-topped, 9-year-old slave played by Jake Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yoda: The tiny Jedi Master voiced by Frank Oz is a bit younger
here, but still ancient. (Yoda was 900 years old in ``The Empire
Strikes Back.'') He's also less isolated as a member of the Jedi
Council.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jabba the Hutt: The huge, sluglike gangster from ``Return of
the Jedi'' appears here as gambling boss of the planet Tatooine,
Anakin's home world.
</P>
<P>
   _ Palpatine: In ``Return of the Jedi,'' Palpatine, played by Ian
McDiarmid, is the self-anointed emperor of the Empire, imposing
martial law on the galaxy and ruling with the dark side of the
Force. ``Episode I'' has Senator Palpatine, a scheming politician
representing Naboo, home world of Queen Amidala, and also played by
Ian McDiarmid. Are the senator and emperor the same? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEW FACES, NEW PLACES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Queen Amidala: Played by Natalie Portman, 17, she's the
14-year-old monarch of the planet Naboo who faces an invasion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Padme Naberrie: She's one of Queen Amidala's handmaidens and a
near-twin. In fact, at times Padme looks exactly like Amidala.
</P>
<P>
   _ Qui-Gon Jinn: Played by Liam Neeson, he's a veteran Jedi
Master who goes with Obi-Wan to Naboo, then to Tatooine, in the
service of Queen Amidala. Though ``The Phantom Menace'' is an
ensemble film, he is its central character.
</P>
<P>
   _ Darth Maul: A red-faced, horned, devil-looking dude, he's a
Sith Lord, as Darth Vader will become. (The Sith are worshipers of
the Force's dark side.) Played by Ray Parker, Maul wields a
lightsaber that's held in the middle and kills from both ends. Stay
away from this guy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Darth Sidious: Also played by McDiarmid, he's a Sith meanie
and the new film's title character. As the title hints, you won't
see him much, but you'll feel his presence throughout as he pulls
his evil strings. Maul is his apprentice, just as Obi-Wan is
Qui-Gon's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mace Windu: Played by big-time ``Star Wars'' fan Samuel L.
Jackson, he's a Jedi Master who's a senior member of the Jedi
Council. Expect a bigger role for him in ``Episode II.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chancellor Valorum: Played by Terence Stamp, he's a bureaucrat
with good intentions but no match for Palpatine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jar Jar Binks: A computer-generated character voiced by Ahmed
Best, he's an amusing, big-eared member of the Gungans, an
amphibious, froglike species of the planet Naboo. The clumsy,
hapless Jar Jar tags along with Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boss Nass: Played by Brian Blessed, he's leader of the
Gungans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shmi Skywalker: Played by Pernilla August, she's Anakin's
doting mom and Luke's grandmom. She's in slavery with her son on
Tatooine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Battle Droids: Depicted via computer images, they're
mechanized soldiers of the Trade Federation. In the original
trilogy, they're supplanted by Imperial Stormtroopers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
