A5748 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-THECASTLE-TEX     05-13 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THECASTLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A MAN'S `CASTLE' ISN'T HIS TO KEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the hype for the gently satirical comedy ``The Castle''
is trying to cast director/co-writer Rob Sitch as an Australian
Roberto Benigni. It's true that they do have things in common, such
as each being christened with a variation on the same first name
(and a fine first name it is). Otherwise, the comparison is mostly
specious: Sitch's dry, deadpan approach couldn't be more different
from Benigni's manic romanticism. Both styles do have the potential
to divide audiences, but not in the same ways.
</P>
<P>
   Like Benigni with ``Life Is Beautiful,'' Sitch uses comedy in an
attempt to explore some serious subjects. And like Benigni, he's
concocted a very likable family with an eccentric patriarch.
</P>
<P>
   The dad here is Darryl Kerrigan, an affable bloke who's content
to live in his humble home, where he can praise his wife's cooking,
raise his greyhounds and express heartfelt interest in the lives of
his four quirky children, even the son who's in prison. Darryl
doesn't mind that his house has power lines in the yard and is so
close to an airport that he feels like a plane could land on top of
him. In fact, he thinks it's kind of neat.
</P>
<P>
   For Darryl, ignorance is bliss, so it's no wonder that at first
he thinks it's a good thing when representatives of an airline come
knocking at his door, offering him money for his home. He politely
declines the offer only to find out that the law compels him to
give up the place he loves to make room for expansion of the
airport. No way is Darryl going down without a fight, and with the
aid of an inexperienced lawyer mate, Darryl takes on the system.
</P>
<P>
   Sitch's handling of this material is almost too droll and
laid-back for the movie's own good. Even the multiwriter screenplay
seems to be reminding itself what the movie's about, and it gives
Darryl a brief speech about aborigines that seems out of character
for such a naive guy. The movie is laced with sly wit, but it's so
leisurely that some of the jokes walk by you before you know
they're being made. It often seems to be a step behind itself.
</P>
<P>
   Sitch and his co-writers have created a great character in
Darryl, though (you could call him one of the best of 1999, except
that the film was made in 1997), and Michael Caton plays him with
amiable, unpretentious dignity. As Darryl's wife says, he's a man
of principle, and Caton latches on to him in ways you might not
even be aware of until the movie's had time to settle in your mind.
Tiriel Mora, who looks like an Australian Oliver Platt, is amusing
as Darryl's befuddled lawyer, and Costas Kilias earns the movie's
biggest _ albeit easiest _ laughs as Darryl's Lebanese neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The audience at this particular preview screening seemed to be a
bit baffled by the movie's unhurried style, which says more about
the bombastic methods employed by most U.S. comedies than it does
about ``The Castle,'' which has the calm humor of ``Local Hero''
and a bit of an angry core, like ``The Full Monty.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's entry on the Internet Movie Database features
several laudatory comments from Australian viewers, who praise the
perceptive way the movie encapsulates Aussie eccentricities into
one close-knit family. But you don't need to be Australian to get
the message that maybe, just maybe, love and honor can triumph over
misguided progress.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Castle''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Rob Sitch
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Michael Caton, Tiriel Mora
</P>
<P>
   Length: 87 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ apparently for strong language that could just as
easily have received a PG-13
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
