<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REBELS AND OUTLAWS' CD TOUGH TO BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You don't hear us put the words ``sheer'' and
``genius'' together about too many compilations, particularly
country samplers.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Rebels &AMP; Outlaws: Music From the Wild Side of Life''
(EMI), due Tuesday, is quite simply a fantastic idea fully
realized.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is easy to grasp: 14 tough-talking tracks from the
likes of Merle Haggard, Wanda Jackson, Faron Young and Hank
Thompson stemming from a time when ``politically correct'' was
still decades away and songs about murder, livin' fast, doing time,
cheating and causing trouble were standard fare.
</P>
<P>
   Call it ``blacklisted country.'' This isn't Garth Brooks, kids.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best of a fine lot are Jackson's ``Riot in Cell Block
Number Nine,'' the Louvin Brothers' ``Knoxville Girl'' and Tex
Ritter's ``Blood on the Saddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Also taking honors are Thompson's ``Cocaine Blues,'' Johnny
Cash's ``Folsom Prison Blues'' and Young's ``Live Fast, Love Hard,
Die Young.''
</P>
<P>
   We wish ``Rebels &AMP; Outlaws'' covered multiple CDs. Maybe it will
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the disc's cover shot probably won't make many new friends,
either. It shows a nasty Cash giving his famous one-finger salute
to a photographer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1604EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0156 </DOCNO>
