A5760 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITOR-OVERHOLSER-TEX     05-13 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITOR-OVERHOLSER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITOR WHO PUSHED TO NAME NAMES FEELS STING OF BLAME GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Geneva Overholser, one of the most successful women in
American journalism, knows all too well about the weaknesses of
newspaper reporting, having weathered a bout of headlines herself.
</P>
<P>
   Overholser made her name as an editor by saying that society is
better when newspapers report on the private lives of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Then newspapers reported on her own private life. Her love life.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't entirely pleased.
</P>
<P>
   She saw a press that was too quick to jump to conclusions, too
willing to oversimplify issues. Add that to her list of complaints
about newspaper reporters and editors.
</P>
<P>
   Overholzer was in Dallas for a speech Thursday night to the
Association for Women Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Overholser made her name in 1990, when she, then-editor of The
Des Moines Register, wrote an editorial that challenged
conventional newsroom wisdom concerning coverage of rape victims.
Traditionally, newspapers have not published the name of rape
victims to ensure their privacy. Overholser wrote that adult rape
victims should be named, just as adult victims of all violent
crimes are named. Naming victims would remove rape from the
category of ``sex'' and more properly place it in the category of
``violence,'' Overholser contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rape is an American shame,'' she wrote. ``Our society needs to
... attend to it, not hide it or hush it up.'' The editorial gave
courage to one Iowa reader, Nancy Ziegenmeyer, who lived with the
frustration of delays in the prosecution of the man who had raped
her. Ziegenmeyer decided to come forward, and she allowed the
Register to use her name in a five-part series published in 1990
that won journalism's highest prize, the Pulitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Overholser received a good share of ink in journalism trade
publications for her willingness to take a fresh look at old
journalism practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspapers aren't worth a damn if they don't invade people's
privacy,'' she was quoted as saying in 1990 in American Journalism
Review, then known as the Washington Journalism Review.
</P>
<P>
   Overholser resigned from the Register in 1995, without another
job, saying the business of journalism was so commercially driven
that newspapers were no longer operating in the public interest.
The move was widely regarded in journalism as a brave step taken
for ethical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The upper ranks of Gannett Co., owner of the Register, bristled
when they heard Overholser's negative assessment of their corporate
style, according to news accounts. Months later, on the back page
of a local news section in the Register, a story appeared about
Overholser. The former editor had purchased a house in Washington,
D.C., with the Register's former managing editor, David Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Overholser had not used her famous
forthrightness when she gave her reasons for her resignation. She
and Westphal had worked closely together at the Register, both were
married to other people, both resigned on the same day, and both
filed for divorces shortly after leaving Iowa. Overholser and
Westphal now are married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can repeat that I genuinely left the job for professional
reasons,'' Overholser wrote in a Washington Post column in 1995.
``I can say that I couldn't have added then the truth about the
course my personal life would take, because I didn't know. None of
that holds the kind of power for people that this one fact holds:
Eight months later, the two of us are together here in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she reluctantly talks about her conversion from
newsgatherer to newsmaker. ``All journalists would learn from
having a story written about themselves and placed on the front
page,'' Overholser told the Star-Telegram. ``I felt it was reported
on without much awareness of how complex the issue was. Once people
heard I was in love, they thought, well, this can't really be about
distress about her newspaper's profit pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Overholser is still outspoken about her profession.
She recently completed a term as ombudsman for The Washington Post
and now is a syndicated political and social issue columnist at the
Post. Among her complaints about journalists are: They too often
write as if they have a permanent sneer on their faces; they lean
too heavily on anonymous sources; they are suckers for ``leaks'';
and they forget that their job is not to increase corporate profits
or boost their own careers but to be part of a free press that
makes democracy work.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
