<SLUG> BC-EDGE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EDGE OF 17': A MANY GENDERED THING, THE TRUE NATURE OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The insecurities and turbulent desires of adolescence have
rarely been portrayed more faithfully on screen than in ``Edge of
17,'' the latest and most poignant in a recent spate of teen-age
male coming-out-of-the-closet dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its nationality, one thing that sets this American
independent film apart from two likable British forerunners,
``Beautiful Thing'' and ``Get Real,'' is its sexual candor.
</P>
<P>
   When Eric (Chris Stafford), a sensitive high school boy about to
enter his senior year, has his first encounters with Rod (Andersen
Gabrych), a slightly older college student he meets at a summer job
in an Ohio amusement park, Eric is the picture of fumbling
awkwardness and vulnerable, dewy-eyed romanticism.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being the Prince Charming of a gay teen-age boy's
fantasies, Rod, a hotel-management student at Ohio State
University, is a suave gay Don Juan who takes an amused pleasure in
seducing younger boys.
</P>
<P>
   In giving himself to Rod, Eric falls naively and desperately in
love, only to find himself treated with a supercilious
condescension.
</P>
<P>
   Eric's second encounter, a man he meets in a disco who drags him
into the parking lot for quickie sex, is much worse. These two
encounters leave the starry-eyed Eric with such a bleak outlook on
his romantic future that he panics, decides to turn straight and
convinces Maggie (Tina Holmes), his former girlfriend in whom he
has already confided his homosexual desires, to have sex with him.
</P>
<P>
   The scene in which poor, virginal Maggie, who really loves Eric,
fools herself and is wooed into giving him a heterosexual
initiation that proves horribly empty, is so truthful it almost
hurts to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the movie's strengths is its acutely remembered sense
of time and place. Written by Todd Stephens and directed by David
Moreton, ``Edge of 17'' is set in Sandusky, Ohio ( Stephens'
hometown), in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, British pop stars like Boy George and Annie Lennox
were at their peak of popularity, and groups like the Bronski Beat
were popularizing disco-oriented pop songs with explicitly gay
content. The movie gets the music, the clothes and the tone of the
teen-age culture of that era exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   As Eric, whom Stafford plays with a winning mixture of avid
sincerity and ingenuous narcissism, metamorphoses from a skinny,
ordinary-looking high-school boy into a preening distillation of
period British pop fashion, with flaming two-toned hair, eyeliner
and Culture Club-inspired clothes, you fear for him.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing all dolled up at a teen-age party where he does a
spaced-out solo dance, Eric endures the first slings and arrows of
peer-group homophobia and flees in tears.
</P>
<P>
   What the movie also gets right are Eric's rapidly escalating
fear and sense of being different and the confusion and
befuddlement of his nice but conventional girlfriend and loving but
uncomprehending parents.
</P>
<P>
   Eric, the oldest of three boys, has a Moog synthesizer in his
bedroom and has begun composing electronic pop ditties. He dreams
of moving to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the movie we learn that his down-to-earth mother
(played with a wonderful solidity by Stephanie McVay) gave up her
dreams of being a concert pianist to rear a family. She is so
devoted to her children's future that she has even gone back to
work to support the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edge of 17,'' which opens in New York City on Friday, has its
sentimental touches. It gives Eric a kindly godmother in Angie (Lea
DeLaria, as incandescently feisty as ever), a raucous tough-talking
lesbian with a heart of gold who manages the local gay bar.
</P>
<P>
   The campy denizens of that bar, who take Eric under their wing,
also emerge as gay caricatures. And the film's ending in that disco
is a bit too patly upbeat. But these are minor flaws in a movie
that captures a small slice of 1980s middle-class Middle-American
life just about perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `EDGE OF 17'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Moreton; written by Todd Stephens; director of
photography, Gina DeGirolamo; edited by Tal Ben-David; music by Tom
Bailey; production designer, Ivor Stilin; produced by Moreton and
Stephens; released by Strand Releasing. Running time: 100 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Chris Stafford (Eric), Tina Holmes (Maggie), Andersen
Gabrych (Rod), Stephanie McVay (Mom) and Lea DeLaria (Angie).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
