</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALEM-TRAVEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALEM BEYOND WITCHES: LEGACY OF A LIVELY SEA TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, Mass. _ Stand by the second-story window of the nearly
two-century-old Custom House here and you will find yourself gazing
over a waterfront that once linked the young United States with the
world's farthest corners.
</P>
<P>
   All's quiet now. But the place once saw ships in such numbers _
en route to or from China, Europe, the West Indies, the South Seas
_ as to rank Salem among the nation's most cosmopolitan and wealthy
cities.
</P>
<P>
   One who would have occasionally stood here was Nathaniel
Hawthorne, who worked in an office downstairs as surveyor of
Salem's port in the late 1840s, when he also began writing ``The
Scarlet Letter.'' A few blocks away stands one of his subjects in
another of his novels, the House of Seven Gables.
</P>
<P>
   Salem is probably most closely linked in the public imagination
with the 1692 witchcraft trials, but it contains much more of
interest. Nearly 400 years old, it long thrived on maritime
commerce, a legacy you can discover downtown in an area designated
as a National Historic Site (which includes the Custom House),
inside a terrific museum and on some elegant residential streets.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there is easy. A commuter train connects Salem with
Boston, 15 miles to the southwest. Or you can do what my wife,
Margaret, and I did recently and drive up Route 1A from Logan
Airport. The trip takes just half an hour, which is just as well,
since the scenery tends toward car dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Salem has a workaday appearance. It does not feel
prettified, a circumstance that ends its finer neighborhoods an
authenticity that would be suspect in a place scrubbed and buffed
for tourists. Nothing really prepares you for the pleasing sight of
Federal-style buildings beside the nine-acre Common or the
impressive collections in the Peabody Essex Museum.
</P>
<P>
   We chose the Hawthorne Hotel as our base; it's a 70-year-old
brick building, recently restored and as centrally located as one
could hope. From the moment we arrived and asked for a bigger room
to accommodate a crib for our baby, we found the staff consistently
courteous and helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, facing the Common, stands a statue of Salem's founder,
Roger Conant, in conical hat and swirling cape, with a plaque
telling how, ``by grace,'' he persuaded English settlers not to run
off to Virginia. That was in 1626.
</P>
<P>
   The statue can be glimpsed from the Tavern on the Green, one of
the hotel's two restaurants. When we settled in for lunch, we also
got a view into the distinctive brand of religious pluralism here,
seated as we were near a jovial group of middle-age patrons, most
wearing silver pentangles, a symbol of Wicca, or modern-day
witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do want a closer look at Wicca, whose
practitioners describe it as Earth-centered, peaceful and devoid of
belief in a devil, Salem offers small shops stocked with books,
jewelry and more. A few can be found on Pickering Wharf, like the
store run by Laurie Cabot, once dubbed the city's ``official
witch'' in a proclamation by former Gov. Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1692 trials remain before the public eye, in one form or
another, thanks to well-advertised commercial ventures. We skipped
the Witch Village, Witch Dungeon, Mayhem Manor and something called
Dracula's Castle.
</P>
<P>
   We did go to the Salem Witch Museum, where visitors are ushered
into a dark, spooky room to listen to a 20-minute taped narration
as lights illuminate life-sized figures dressed to represent people
in the trials. We emerged disappointed, thinking it low on
historical context.
</P>
<P>
   But the attached shop has a good selection of books, like
``Witchcraft at Salem'' by Chadwick Hansen. Rejecting conventional
views of the trials, it argues that in 17th-century New England, as
in Europe, some people did practice what they understood to be
witchcraft, and that two of the 19 people hanged in 1692 were
probably practicing black magic.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone looking for a physical link to that era ought to walk
over to the Old Burying Point on Charter Street, which contains the
grave of John Hathorne, one of three judges in the trials and an
ancestor of Nathaniel Hawthorne, who added the ``w'' to the family
name.
</P>
<P>
   The graveyard also holds the remains of Nathanael Mather, a son
of the famous Boston Puritan leader Increase Mather. The father
wrote an influential book critical of the methods of inquiry used
by the Salem trial court. Many gravestones are adorned with
carvings of the death's heads and hourglasses found in
pre-Revolutionary War burying grounds.
</P>
<P>
   From there it's a few minutes' walk to the Salem Maritime
Historic Site, where the National Park Service runs tours led by
rangers.
</P>
<P>
   One tour takes in the Custom House, its exterior adorned with a
gold-painted eagle clutching a shield emblazoned with the stars and
stripes. Inside the building are artifacts from Hawthorne's days as
port surveyor. His was a political appointment served during a
period when the port was in decline. He found the duties dull. A
display case shows off what he left behind: quill pens, an inkwell,
a walking stick and other items. The tour, by the way, makes note
of another famous native, Nathaniel Bowditch, a self-taught
mathematician and astronomer and, like Hawthorne, a sea captain's
son. Bowditch's extensive corrections of British navigational
tables led to his 1802 book, ``The New American Practical
Navigator,'' the foundation of modern navigation.
</P>
<P>
   I returned to tour two historic houses at the site. Most
impressive is Salem's oldest brick home, the Derby House, on Derby
Street, overlooking Derby Wharf. The house belonged to Elias
Haskett Derby, identified by the Park Service as ``probably
America's first millionaire,'' another Salem distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Derby owned 33 ships and began trading with China in the 1780s.
He might now be hailed as an early exponent of globalization. He
was unquestionably a dominant figure at the height of Salem's
trading importance in the 1790s. At Derby's funeral, his minister
eulogized him by saying, ``Many gathered around him, many imitated
his enterprises and many shared in their success.''
</P>
<P>
   The guide, standing near a portrait of the merchant inside the
house, said that Derby's eyes were of different colors, one iris
blue, the other brown, and that he was a dedicated landsman who
shunned sea travel.
</P>
<P>
   From his parlor, Derby could keep an eye on doings at his wharf.
The room still possesses a convivial charm, with family portraits
on the walls and a diamond-patterned sailcloth rug on the floor. On
a landing on the hall stairway there is a grandfather clock with a
gold-on-black Oriental design.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably for the Derbys, the family lost its ascendancy after
Elias died in 1799. He and his wife had built a 60-room mansion in
Salem's center, but both died shortly after its completion. The
house was torn down in 1815.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I walked toward the site, but only to see some of the cultural
legacy of Salem's trade, the Peabody-Essex Museum, founded in 1799
by sea captains dedicated to collecting ``artificial and natural
curiosities'' from around the world. Exhibits range from maritime
paintings and ship models to art objects from the Far East, the
South Pacific and elsewhere. The museum is planning an expansion
that will increase gallery space by more than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret and I never got much beyond the first rooms, near the
entrance, except to visit the museum's pleasant cafe, where we
found a table in a glass-fronted nook overlooking a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Among the exhibits we saw ere the rooms dealing with New
England's bond with the sea. There is good information on whaling,
although in that trade Salem ranked well behind ports like New
Bedford and Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Display cases contain scrimshaw, the whale's teeth incised by
sailors passing idle time on deck. And there are whale bones carved
as walking sticks, dominoes, even a clock, as well as the lower jaw
of a sperm whale.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings portray the explosive action of the whale hunt. One,
titled ``Attacking the Right Whale,'' became the model for the 19th
century's most popular whaling print. It shows a six-man boat
alongside a wounded whale, the hunt at its climax.
</P>
<P>
   Killing a whale was a drama in two parts, beginning with
harpooning the animal and letting it drag the whaleboat until
exhausted, after which the boat's officer dispatched the whale by
puncturing its lungs with a lance.
</P>
<P>
   It was cruel, dangerous and exciting. For those who want to know
more, Herman Melville gives a memorable description of the process
in the chapter titled ``Stubb Kills a Whale'' in ``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Open the book and you'll also find a Salem connection right up
front. It is dedicated to Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Park Your Broom in Salem &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting Salem, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   HAWTHORNE HOTEL, 18 Washington Square, at Hawthorne Boulevard,
(978) 744-4080. Daily room rates: $125 for a single; $154 to $172
for a double; $285 for a suite.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   TAVERN ON THE GREEN AND NATHANIEL'S, both inside the Hawthorne
Hotel, 18 Washington Square, at Hawthorne Boulevard, (978)
744-4080.
</P>
<P>
   BELLA VERONA, 107 Essex Street, (978) 825-9911.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM CAFE, Peabody Essex Museum, Essex and Liberty Streets,
(978) 740-4551.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   OLD BURYING POINT CEMETERY, entrance on Charter Street, between
Central and Liberty Streets.
</P>
<P>
   PEABODY ESSEX MUSEUM, East India Square, at the corner of Essex
and Liberty Streets, (978) 745-1876 or (800) 745-4054. Open Mondays
through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.
Admission, which also includes admission to the Phillips Library,
$8.50; $7.50 for students and the elderly; $5 for children 6 to 16
years old; free for children under 16. On view through Jan. 31,
``Gold Coast Treasures,'' an exhibition of American decorative
arts. From May 28 through Oct. 31, ``Timeless Visions; Contemporary
Art of India.''
</P>
<P>
   PHILLIPS LIBRARY, 132 Essex Street, (978) 745-9500, extension
3053; the library is part of the museum, although it is on Essex
Street, half a block east. Open Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays,
10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Thursdays, 1 to 8 p.m. From Memorial through
Labor Days, also open Mondays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission, which
also includes admission to the Peabody Essex Museum, $8.50; $7.50
for students and the elderly; $5 for children 6 to 16 years old;
free for children under 6. Ongoing exhibitions: ``The Real
Witchcraft Papers'' and the Saltonstall Family Portrait Collection.
</P>
<P>
   SALEM REGIONAL VISITORS CENTER, part of National Parks Service,
2 New Liberty Street, (978) 740-1650. The Salem Maritime National
Historic Site offers tours of historic houses; information at 174
Derby Street, (978) 740-1660; Orientation Center at the National
Historic site, with a videotape on maritime history and ranger-led
tours, 193 Derby Street. Tours of historic houses are given daily
by appointment, from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; fee, $3; $2 for students,
children and the elderly; $10 per family.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOM HOUSE, Derby Street, part of the National Historic Site.
</P>
<P>
   DERBY HOUSE, Derby Street, overlooking Derby Wharf, part of the
National Historic Site.
</P>
<P>
   NARBONNE HOUSE, Derby Street, part of the National Historic
Site.
</P>
<P>
   SALEM WITCH MUSEUM, 19{ Washington Square North, (978) 744-1692.
Daily, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., till 7 p.m. in July and August.
Admission, $5; $4.50 for the elderly; $3 for children 6 to 14; free
for those 5 and younger.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas for Reading
</P>
<P>
   ``WITCHCRAFT AT SALEM,'' by Chadwick Hansen (George Braziller);
paperback, $11.95; hardcover, $22.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``SALEM: MARITIME SALEM IN THE AGE OF SAIL'' (National Park
Service, Division of Publications); $6.50, available at the Salem
Regional Visitors Center.
</P>
