<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5768 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LOWE-PROFILE-HNS &LR;      05-13 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOWE-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH LOWE: FUTURE BRIGHT FOR BRAT PACKER TURNED DAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday and Monday, we'll see him as John Seger, dangling from a
helicopter and scurrying atop train cars, trying to prevent a
nuclear accident.
</P>
<P>
   In June, he'll be the 1969 version of No. 2, doing what evil men
do to stop that masterful superagent, Austin Powers.
</P>
<P>
   By fall, we may see him as a White House employee with an
overactive libido.
</P>
<P>
   But all around and in between, Rob Lowe's favorite role these
days is playing Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recently had the weird experience of being elated that my
kid got into the kindergarten he wanted,'' the 35-year-old father
of two confided. ``I thought, `It's not like it's Stanford, for
God's sake. Rob, get a grip.'''
</P>
<P>
   Parenthood agrees with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that visceral connection that's completely unique to you
and your child, and yet utterly common to every child and their
parent,'' he said in a recent phone conversation. ``When your kid
snags his first ground ball in T-ball, throws it to the first
baseman and turns around to look to find you to see if you've seen
it, it doesn't get any better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing responsible parent is an about-face from the indelible
impression he left in 1988, when a video surfaced of him and an
under-age girl having sex. Before that, he was the impossibly
pretty member of the so-called Brat Pack, which included such
members as Emilio Estevez, Ally Sheedy and Anthony Michael Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The video shook him up and nearly tanked his career. ``There's
no way you can know how embarrassing it was,'' he told People
magazine in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1991 he married an ex-girlfriend of Estevez _ Sheryl
Berkoff, now 37 _ and became a family man. He and Sheryl are
parents to Matthew, 5, and John Owen, 3.
</P>
<P>
   And though his career stalled, it never derailed. He's made more
than two dozen films since the video incident, a couple of his
roles memorable (including Nick in the 1994 miniseries ``The
Stand'').
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back on TV. In ``Atomic Train'' (9 p.m. EST Sunday and
Monday, NBC), Lowe plays John Seger, an investigator with the
National Transportation Safety Board. It falls on John to do what
he can to stop a runaway train bound for Denver. The train carries
hazardous material and, uh-oh, one stolen nuclear bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The slender actor with the soft face relished the idea of
playing a physical role. The part called for him to jump onto a
moving train from a hovering helicopter, walk/run/crawl atop the
boxcars, and assorted other stunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stunts that look the most dangerous are actually
the safest, and others that look innocuous scare the hell out of
you,'' he said. ``I think the scariest was the one where I'm
hanging from the ladder of a helicopter and they lower me to the
top of the train and I jump/fall off onto the train.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chopper pilot says, `Look, when I'm coming down toward the
train, if you hear any difference in the rotors, just lie down. I'm
going to try to ditch it over here. And oh, by the way, make sure
you don't touch the ladder until I've grounded it by touching it on
top of the train, because it carries an electronic charge that
could shock you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't tell you that when you're signing up. Then, you
know, I'm on top of this thing. You can't hear anything. Of course,
the weather's coming in, we're losing the light, we've got about 15
minutes to get this, it's the end of the day _ it (the nature of
the business) never changes. I got up there and thought, `What have
I got myself into?' I've got a helicopter hovering over my head; I
mean, literally the skid is touching my shoulder. I thought, `This
is crazy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But that said, it's really gratifying because when you see the
movie, you'll go, `That's really him.'''
</P>
<P>
   He's had other action roles before _ he recently made two
made-for-cable films playing a Jack Higgins hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a physical person,'' Lowe said. ``I really enjoy it. There
were days where, honestly, all I did was hang upside down, hang by
one arm, jump, swing, fall on the ground, get beat. I would come
home and sit in the tub with Epsom salts and go, ``Oh, my aching
...' I felt like a little boy, playing in the yard. It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Lowe does not succeed in preventing the
train from unleashing its explosive cargo. Poor Denver is
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The miniseries was filmed last fall, months before the high
school shootings in the Denver suburb of Littleton. NBC
investigated changing the location in the miniseries, then opted
not to.
</P>
<P>
   What went through Daddy's mind when he heard about Littleton?
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue is that, at 5 and 3, it's not appropriate for
them to know about this,'' Lowe said. ``I don't want their
innocence compromised. My son and I read the paper every day, and
we took a little sabbatical from that. To me, the incident
reinforces what I think I already intuitively knew, which was that
you have to be involved in your kids' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this action film was one he made for his boys, he said,
``You know what? A lot of it was. They have `Atomic Train' hats
they wore to school.''
</P>
<P>
   The tape of the show had just arrived, and Lowe was planning to
watch it with his sons _ at least the action scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe does not believe violence in movies _ even the destruction
of a city _ necessarily breeds violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people drink from the same cesspool and don't run
amok,'' he said. ``They play the same hideous games. I don't want
them in my house, but at the end of the day, if they did come into
my house, I have every confidence they're not going to send anybody
off to the deep end because we're constantly trying to cover the
other bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Lowe has the lucky fate of being in two more
high-profile projects. In ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me,'' he plays the 1969 version of the Robert Wagner character from
the first film, No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say it without sounding like a shill because it's really
Mike (Myers') baby: It is one of the funniest movies ever made,''
said Lowe. ``It's like seeing ''Airplane!,`` ''Young Frankenstein``
or ''Caddyshack`` for the first time. I'm playing a young Robert
Wagner with frosted hair and the R.J. Wagner voice, I mean, come
on. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall, we may see him in a new TV series from what Lowe
calls a ``teaming of the titans,'' Aaron Sorkin (``Sports Night'')
and John Wells (``ER''). In the hourlong drama ``The West Wing,''
Lowe plays a bed-hopping White House deputy communications
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people interested in me doing an hour show for many
years, and I just didn't want to commit to the time,'' Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   This is too good to pass up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a drama, but like all of Aaron's work, it's funny. It
turned out fantastic. Everybody's really positive (that a network
will pick it up), but nothing's for sure in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC has first option on the series, which also stars Moira
Kelly, Brad Whitford, Richard Schiff and Martin Sheen as the
president.
</P>
<P>
   If it's sold, it will mean more time for Lowe to spend with
family, since the show will shoot at the same set every day and
will feature a share-the-load, ensemble cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I don't have to go to Sri Lanka, and with four or five
leads, I'll have some time off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
