<SLUG> BC-TREK-DEEP-SPACE-NINE-FINALE-ART-ADV10-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 ATTN: KENTUCKY 
 DEEP SPACE NINE BEAMS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MAY 24, 1999) 
 Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of the cast of
``Star Trek: Deep Space Nine.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It hit Nana Visitor like a photon torpedo.
 &HT;    ``I was taking a walk around the Promenade set as they were
disassembling it, and I realized that `Deep Space Nine' was really
ending, possibly forever,'' says Visitor, who has played Col. Kira
Nerys for all of the ``Star Trek'' spinoff's seven-year run and
even married one of her co-stars, Alexander Siddig.
 &HT;    ``I'd never before allowed myself to feel so profoundly sad
about something,'' she says. ``When I'd done stage shows and the
closing notice went up, I'd just leave after the last performance.
But I can't do that with `DS9.'
 &HT;    ``Too many bits of my life are interwoven into this show, these
sets, these people,'' she concludes. ``I want a long, long
goodbye.''
 &HT;    Trekkers will have their own chance to bid farewell to ``DS9''
when its two-hour finale, ``What You Leave Behind,'' airs in
syndication the week of May 31.
 &HT;    On a rainy April day in Hollywood, the end can barely be seen
looming on Stage 18 at Paramount Pictures. Everyone's too busy
making ``What You Leave Behind.''
 &HT;    Veteran ``Trek'' director Allan Kroeker peers into a monitor,
setting up Scene 63H, which finds the enigmatic Cardassian, Garak
(Andrew J. Robinson), looking at the corpse of a Cardassian female
_ could she be his mother? _ and dashing from a claustrophobic
cellar after Kira implores him to run.
 &HT;    Crewmen blow billows of thick smoke onto the cramped set,
Robinson taps his foot impatiently and, finally, Kroeker calls
``Action!'' The actors play out the scene several times, until
Kroeker signals his satisfaction and asks the crew to reverse
camera angles.
 &HT;    As a contingent of grips, boom operators, assistant directors,
stunt doubles, stand-ins, makeup artists and extras swarms in,
Kroeker steps outside to smoke a cigarette and talk.
 &HT;    ``In a sense we're winging it because we got the script so
late,'' he says, ``and that's OK to a degree. In television, if you
get too much time to think about something you can get paralyzed.
 &HT;    ``This show has been, `Let's jump into the fray blind, and hope
for the best,''' he adds. ``But it's a good group of people I'm
working with and, knowing that, knowing that they work well under
tremendous pressure, I don't mind improvising.
 &HT;    ``And we've been doing a lot of that.''
 &HT;    Over in his office, Ira Steven Behr sheds some light on the
ambitious episode's top-secret plot. Behr has been ``DS9's''
day-to-day producer for several years now and he, with Hans
Beimler, wrote the finale.
 &HT;    ``We're going to see the culmination of the Dominion war,'' he
says. ``We're going to see the culmination of the relationships
we've been following for seven years, and we're going to give every
character _ the regulars and almost all of our recurring characters
_ at least a moment.
 &HT;    ``I think we're trying to bring a tear to people's eyes and
maybe also a smile to their faces,'' he adds. ``We're trying to do
a hell of a lot in two freakin' hours, and it's going to be
jampacked with action and fun-filled.
 &HT;    ``When it's over, I hope people will say, `Yep, that was the
final episode of a seven-year series, and they didn't punk out on
us. They threw in everything but the kitchen sink.'''
 &HT;    Behr chuckles.
 &HT;    ``And,'' he says, ``if we'd had a little more time we probably
would've thrown in the kitchen sink.''
 &HT;    Across the way in his own office, ``DS9'' co-creator and
co-executive producer Rick Berman offers his view of ``DS9's''
impending departure.
 &HT;    ``It's like having children,'' he says. ``They eventually grow
up and move out of the house. You're sad, but it's a rite of
passage.
 &HT;    ``Everyone asks if there will be `DS9' features or television
movies,'' Berman adds, ``and the truth is I don't know. I've had no
such discussions yet with Paramount.
 &HT;    ``I will say this,'' he says. ``I certainly hope that we've not
seen the last of Odo (Rene Auberjonois), Kira, Sisko (Avery Brooks)
and the others. That would be a shame.''
 &HT;    In the final analysis, ``DS9'' remains the dark and gritty
``Trek,'' the Enterprise-less saga that polarized fans, the show
that dared to push people's buttons, kill off popular characters
and spend two-plus years on a complex war story line. If ``DS9''
failed to be embraced by the masses, if it emerged as the
franchise's neglected stepchild, Behr says, so be it.
 &HT;    ``It's not a kid's show and it's not toy-friendly,
necessarily,'' the producer says. ``It's a show that makes you
think.
 &HT;    ``The franchise will never be the same because of `DS9,''' he
adds. ``The wonderful thing about `DS9' is that we've got 176
episodes that are not going to go away.
 &HT;    ``The episodes will be on video, on laserdisk and on DVD, and
they'll be syndicated. Whoever wants to discover, rediscover or
continue to discover the show will have that opportunity ... ad
nauseam.'' 
 -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    Liam Neeson offers an inside look at ``Star Wars: The Phantom
Menace.''
 SIDEBAR: CONVENTION CALENDAR  
 June 5-6: Wonderfest at the Executive West Hotel in Louisville,
Ken., featuring Chris Walas and D.C. Fontana. For information,
consult the official Website at http://www.wonderfest.com.
 -0- 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
