<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5791 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICKYMARTIN-CD-TEX     05-13 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICKYMARTIN-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICKY MARTIN'S HOT STUFF _ IN ANY LANGUAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You will not hear a catchier song than Ricky Martin's ``Livin'
La Vida Loca'' _ not this year, not next, not _ maybe _ ever.
</P>
<P>
   Relentlessly up-tempo, featuring a smattering of rock guitar and
an insistent chorus, it is the vehicle that former Menudo member
Martin _ he of the pretty face and the boffo appearance on this
year's Grammy awards _ is riding to be the first truly huge male
Latino crossover star.
</P>
<P>
   You will listen. You will sing along. You will, now and in the
coming weeks, have no choice. Not that you want one.
</P>
<P>
   It should go without saying that ``Livin''' is the best thing on
Martin's eponymous English-language debut CD, which hit the stores
this week after being bumped up by two weeks to capitalize on the
nearly out-of-control craze for Martin product that ``Livin'''
sparked.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody should be surprised by this, and it's not necessarily a
bad thing: ``Ricky Martin'' is not a bad CD _ buffed and polished
to within an inch of its life, yes, and full of ballads that sound
suspiciously similar, definitely, but not bad.
</P>
<P>
   What it is, however, is pure pop product, produced and written
by committee: Eric Bazilian and Rob Hyman of the Hooters (remember
them?) and hugely successful songwriter Diane Warren _ who penned
Aerosmith's Oscar-nominated ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing'' _ all
wrote for the CD. As did Cuban-born Latin-pop-semi-star Jon Secada
and pop-hits-to-order songwriter Desmond Child. As did Madonna and
``Ray of Light'' producer William Orbit. Martin did not write one
word that he sings on the CD.
</P>
<P>
   The result is exactly what you'd expect: catchy, glossy, frothy,
tuneful, built for radio play. And also fairly bloodless and
undistinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the songs are in English, but there is a second version
of ``Livin''' and the ballad ``Bella (She's All I Ever Had)'' for
his longtime Latin-American fans. All of the above makes ``Ricky
Martin'' just right for capitalizing on the currently exploding
Latin-crossover craze and giving Martin more than enough material
to drive the little girls crazy in concert.
</P>
<P>
   They'll fill the sheds and arenas this summer and fall, dancing
to ``Livin', Spanish Eyes, Shake Your Bon-Bon'' and ``Love You For
a Day,'' and then hold their collective breath as Ricky gets all
sensitive on us with ballads such as ``I Am Made of You'' and
``Maria.'' Lighters will be held aloft. There will be much
swooning. Large amounts of money will be made.
</P>
<P>
   And the reality that Martin's voice is only fair (or maybe even
a notch below that) and his music is cut out of several
well-established molds (Secada, Gloria Estefan) will not matter to
anyone. The point is to make music that sells, and that is what
``Ricky Martin'' is doing and will do. For a good long time.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Martin
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky Martin''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Records
</P>
<P>
   3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
