<HEADLINE>
THE GIRL WITH COLITIS GOES BY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I've searched high and low on the Internet trying to find the
official lyrics to the sitcom ``Good Times'' so I can figure out
the line that begins ``Hanging and a ...'' What is that line?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.C.T., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: It's ``Hangin' in a jury,'' according to the Good Times
Online Scrapbook.
</P>
<P>
   The song, also titled ``Good Times,'' was written by Dave
Grusin, Alan Bergman and Marilyn Bergman. It is one of 50 themes
from CBS television shows included on ``CBS: The First 50 Years''
by TVT Records.
</P>
<P>
   For ordering information, call (888) 488-8237 or visit the World
Wide Web site www.tvtrecords.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Times Online Scrapbook is published at
www.geocities.com/TelevisionCity/7916/times02.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I went to school at L.D. Bell (High School) in the late '70s
with a guy named David Savage, who later had a son named Fred. Are
the actors Fred and Ben Savage the sons of my former classmate?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.N.C., Hurst, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The performing Savages _ Fred, Ben and a sister named Kala _
are the sons of Lew and Joanne Savage.
</P>
<P>
   Lew Savage runs an industrial real estate development business
in Chicago. The family was living in Glencoe, Ill., in the early
'80s when Fred landed his first TV job _ a Pac-Man vitamin
commercial. They moved to Tarzana, Calif., five years later, as all
three children pursued acting careers.
</P>
<P>
   Savage fans can write to Fred in care of Creative Artists
Agency, 9830 Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90212; and Ben in
care of William Morris, 151 El Camino Drive, Beverly Hills, CA
90212.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Sebastian Junger, the author of ``The
Perfect Storm''?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.B., Billerica, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Junger in care of Author Mail, 7th Floor,
HarperCollins Publishers, 10 E. 53rd St., New York, NY 10022.
</P>
<P>
   Junger's first book, ``The Perfect Storm'' was an unexpected
hit, spending 50 weeks on The New York Times' bestseller list. The
nonfiction book describes a 1991 storm that sank the Andrea Gail, a
72-foot fishing boat headed home to Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, Junger established the Perfect Storm Foundation in
Gloucester to provide cultural and educational grants to children
whose parents work in commercial fishing.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the World Wide Web site
www.perfectstorm.org or write to Perfect Storm Foundation, Box
1941, Gloucester, MA 01931-1941.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
