<SLUG> BC-ENDURANCE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ENDURANCE': THE DISNEYFICATION OF A LONG-DISTANCE RUNNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Endurance,'' a docu-drama based on the life of the Ethiopian
long-distance runner Haile Gebrselassie, has the lofty goal of
investing rural Ethiopian life with the primal dignity evoked by
Robert Flaherty in his groundbreaking documentary studies of
Eskimos and Polynesians. But its mixture of biographical hype and
social studies quickly curdles.
</P>
<P>
   Among other problems, ``Endurance'' is excruciatingly dull.
Several scenes of Gebrselassie trotting happily through the African
fields are interminable, and so are videotaped sequences of actual
races. The promiscuous application of John Powell's poundingly
bombastic score of East African folk music in ``The Lion King''
mode only makes matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the movie, Gebrselassie, filmed near his
birthplace in Ethiopia, speaks a few words in broken English. After
that, we never get to know much about him, partly because most of
the dialogue is not subtitled.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Endurance'' is a fictionalized re-creation of the
runner's youth, with a child actor (Yonas Zergaw) playing the
rebellious boy who carries a portable radio into the field to
listen to the broadcast of a race at the 1980 Olympic Games in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Leslie Woodhead, a British documentary
maker, the film has many panoramic shots of the arid Ethiopian
landscape and of villagers laboring in the fields. We observe bread
baking, livestock herding and milking, hay pitching and water being
fetched from the only available source, three miles from the
village.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic scene shows the boy's mother collapsing on her
way back from the spring with a sack of water. Two short scenes
later, she is dead, of undisclosed causes.
</P>
<P>
   Later scenes find Gebrselassie playing himself. In one, he says
goodbye to his father to go live in Addis Ababa and train for the
Olympics. In another, he has an early conversation with his future
wife. Both are painfully stiff, labored re-enactments of events
that surely must have had emotional charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Endurance'' undoubtedly means well. But watching it is a
little like leafing through a 1950's National Geographic photo
spread depicting the mores of a ``primitive'' tribe.
</P>
<P>
   As depicted here, with the ersatz ``Lion King'' music behind
them, Gebrselassie and his fellow Ethiopians come awfully close to
fitting a false, condescending stereotype of the noble savage.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `ENDURANCE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Leslie Woodhead; director of
photography, Ivan Strasburg; edited by Saar Klien and Oral Norrie
Ottey; music by John Powell; produced by Edward R. Pressman,
Terrence Malick and Max Palevsky; a Walt Disney Pictures production
released by Buena Vista Pictures. Running time: 83 minutes. This
film is rated G.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Haile Gebrselassie (himself), Yonas Zergaw (young Haile),
Shawanness Gebrselassie (Haile's mother), Gebrselassie Bekele
(Haile's father), Tedesse Haile (young Haile's father), Assefa
Gebrselassie (Haile's brother), Alem Tallahun (Haile's wife) and
Tizazu Mashresha (Haile's trainer).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
