<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEAR-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     05-13 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEAR-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLEAR SPRINGS': MEMORIES OF HER OLD KENTUCKY HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her novels and short stories, Bobbie Ann Mason limned a New
South reeling from the dislocations of modern life, a place where
the old certainties of family and religion are slipping away and
small towns and family farms have been replaced by malls and
subdivisions and fast-food joints. In her new memoir, ``Clear
Springs,'' she returns to the region of western Kentucky she has
depicted so many times before, but she gives us her own memories of
the area, before it was flung so precipitously into the 20th
century by World War II and the incursion of radio and television
and film.
</P>
<P>
   She gives us a portrait of a time when ``farm ways had not
changed much since pioneer times'' as well as a portrait of her own
extended family, whose ancestors first settled in the region nearly
two centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Clear Springs'' is powerful in its depiction of the
lives of the author's relatives _ in particular, the lives of her
mother and grandmother _ it quickly becomes clear that Ms. Mason is
not a natural memoirist.
</P>
<P>
   In her stories and novels she has skillfully employed the
present tense and a dispassionate third person voice: a clipped,
uninflected voice, vigorous in its immediacy but not given to
rumination. It is not a voice that lends itself easily to the
introspective form of the memoir, and Ms. Mason's reminiscences
often feel perfunctory and forced. There are listlike recitations
of things and people she remembers, as though she could not be
bothered with dramatizing them or bringing them to life. The
sections of the book dealing with her journeys beyond Kentucky _
namely, her post-college sojourns in New York and New England _
feel especially generic and flat.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Mason's fans, the primary interest of this memoir may
lie in its revelation of just how rooted the themes of her fiction
remain in the facts of her own life. The pull felt by so many of
the people in ``Shiloh and Other Stories,'' ``Love Life'' and
``Spence and Lila,'' between home and rootlessness, between what
Ms. Mason calls ``the call of the hearth or the call of the wild,''
appears to have been experienced to acute degree by the young Ms.
Mason herself, while the sense of loss her characters feel, their
regret over missed opportunities and misplaced dreams, seems to
have shadowed her mother's entire life.
</P>
<P>
   As in Ms. Mason's fiction, the women in this memoir are
practiced at the arts of coping; they are more practical, more
inclined toward self-improvement than their menfolk, who tend to be
dreamy, passive, often feckless.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mason's fiction (frequently hailed or dismissed as ``Kmart
realism'') has delineated the alienation and loss of authenticity
that social change has brought to the South. But in this volume she
does not romanticize the vanishing farm life she knew as a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mason's family did not have an indoor bathroom until she was
8, and she went to sleep with a pan to catch the water that dripped
from the ceiling above her bed. Vacations were unknown to farmers _
there were always cows to milk, chickens to feed _ and daily life
was defined by a numbing round of chores. In the 1940s and '50s men
still plowed the fields with a team of mules, and women churned
their own butter and made their own clothes. When someone died and
neighbors came to pay their respects, most would bring prepared
dishes from the supermarket. ``Store-bought costs more,'' Ms. Mason
explains, ``so it has higher status.''
</P>
<P>
   From an early age Ms. Mason rebelled against the circumscribed
life of the farm. She says she hated the fact that farmers were at
the mercy of nature (dependent on good weather for crops and ever
fearful of tornadoes, fires and droughts), and she learned through
such unlikely books as the Bobbsey Twins adventures that a wider
world existed beyond the Kentucky hills. ``Granny didn't question a
woman's duties, but I did,'' she writes. ``I didn't want to be
hulling beans in a hot kitchen when I was 50 years old. I wanted to
be somebody, maybe an airline stewardess.''
</P>
<P>
   In time Ms. Mason did escape: she went away to college and
graduate school, got a writing job in New York and married a
Yankee. Her mother, who had had similar yearnings for independence,
was never able to act on them. Orphaned at an early age _ her
father left before she was born, her mother died when she was four
_ Christy Lee married Wilburn Arnett Mason when she was 17 and
promptly moved in with him and his parents. For the next four and a
half decades she would live in the shadow of her redoubtable
mother-in-law, Ethel, who made her ``feel worthless, out of
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethel herself was given to serious depressions; over the years
she would undergo a series of shock treatments that would leave her
increasingly debilitated. Ms. Mason later learns that Ethel had
spent her own youth caring for her father, who was dying from
syphilis. The shame of his sin ``must have been stark and heavy,''
Ms. Mason speculates. In Ethel's time, ``a simple human error _
like an unwed pregnancy, or a son who `turned out wild' _ could
cause a trauma that colored a lifetime,'' she writes. ``It was
disgrace, shame, the sense that everything one worked for and
believed in and hoped for was ruined by a single misstep.''
</P>
<P>
   With the death of her grandmother, and later her father, Ms.
Mason realized the future of their family farm looked bleak. Though
her mother refused to sell it, she soon moved to a house in town
and leased the fields to a neighbor. ``I'm aware that something
larger than myself, larger than our family, is ending here,'' Ms.
Mason writes. ``A way of life with a long continuity, tracing back
to the beginnings of this country, is coming to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CLEAR SPRINGS
</P>
<P>
   A Memoir'
</P>
<P>
   By Bobbie Ann Mason
</P>
<P>
   298 pages. Random House. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
