<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT     05-13 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON HOME VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Quirky Tour By a Poet-Guide &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not the sort of information one expects from a tour guide,
even in New York City. ``Greenwich Village is one of those rare
districts that occurs once in a while in human history,'' Timothy
(Speed) Levitch says into a microphone from his perch atop a
double-decker bus on the streets of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear, a basic theme in all our lives, constantly afraid along
the streets of Greenwich, under threat of assassination and the
assassins are our dreams triumphant.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists are left to make of that what they will in ``The
Cruise,'' Bennett Miller's probing and acclaimed documentary about
a man who could be described, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York
Times, as ``a representative New Yorker; there is probably no one
in the world remotely like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitch, 28, has a high nasal voice and scraggly looks
reminiscent of Tiny Tim. In tone he resembles Woody Allen, though
his observations are often oblique and run to streams of
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me he was compelling in a way that I tried not to explain
to myself too much,'' Miller said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists on the buses usually just sit dumbfounded. ``My
attitude at first was `I'm going to kick these people until they
wake up,''' Levitch said in an interview. ``Then I was reading some
Eastern mysticism and it was pointed out that most of the human
population is asleep. Don't wake them. They're asleep for reasons
you're not meant to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller took pains to present someone much deeper than a
smart-mouthed New Yorker who deliberately bewilders his audience.
His film, which is to be released on tape Tuesday by Artisan, gets
Levitch off the bus for extended reflections that remain steeped in
the city but venture into a strange and intriguing psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very obscure personality when I found him, living on
life's margins,'' Miller said. ``What interested me is that he
expresses a very open appreciation of life, love and beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   In front of the camera, Levitch shows certain exhibitionistic
tendencies, but they ameliorate gradually. ``He emerges as a
thinking, feeling person,'' the director said. ``Otherwise he'd
remain a cartoonish character, a happy-go-lucky, Walt Whitmanish,
Willie Wonka type.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitch occasionally guides walking tours, but he no longer
rides the double-deckers with, as he puts it, the ``international
flesh congregation.'' To him the bus was a structure orbiting in a
circle and facts were pieces of history subject to mood and
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``History would often change according to my emotionalism,'' he
said. ``The height of the Empire State Building would go up or down
according to my mood.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film he says that his ideal tour group would be the 11
people who have survived a leap off the Brooklyn Bridge, a
structure he likens to an all-powerful being who doesn't attack us
for our fears and distractions.
</P>
<P>
   For these people, he added, directions and facts wouldn't mean
as much as they would to the average tour taker. ``Those who are
enjoying our lives in the city are healthy associates of chaos,''
he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Holy Man &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two shopping network executives, Ricky (Jeff Goldblum) and Kate
(Kelly Preston) hit a man with their sports car. Oddly, though, the
victim, a beatifically smiling fellow who calls himself G (Eddie
Murphy, isn't hurt. Because he seems to have no earthly
connections, Ricky takes G under his wing and into his cocktail
parties. Before long, G emerges as a spiritual guru of mysterious
origin and dewy-eyed sincerity who, despite a professed aversion to
all things material, can sell things like crazy on television. That
works out well for Ricky and the network, both of which are
floundering, but the contradiction in values remains a puzzler in a
film that, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``hasn't a
prayer making sense of this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Touchstone. $104.16. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
Release date: May 18. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Very Bad Things &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Acting unwisely during a bachelor party in Las Vegas, five
friends respond to the violent death of a stripper by cutting up
her body and distributing the parts in the desert. From then on,
matters really get out of hand for those most intimately connected
with the impending nuptials of Kyle (Jon Favreau) and Laura
(Cameron Diaz). A boastful loose canon (Christian Slater) takes
charge of the cover-up to the distress of his nervous cohorts
(Daniel Stern, Jeremy Piven and Leland Orser), who feel sorry for
themselves and get into other fatal mishaps. Viewers may share the
script's eagerness to see all these witless characters dead, but
the film has so little point of view it's hard to care. ``There's
not even much shock value to the story itself, a kind of
Dockers-clad `Lord of the Flies''' (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $108.01. 100 minutes. R. Release date: May 18. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Imposters &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two starving actors in the 1930s, Arthur (Stanley Tucci) and
Maurice (Oliver Platt), evoke everyone from Laurel and Hardy to the
Marx Brothers as they race around New York performing melodramatic
skits in public places (like getting into a staged knife fight in a
Central Park cafe). Then they make the mistake of insulting a
famous actor and notorious drunk (Alfred Molina), who picks a fight
of his own and then claims to be seriously injured. In a panic,
Arthur and Maurice stow away on a cruise ship, eventually emerging
as stewards. But who should also be aboard but their enraged
nemesis, touching off a wild dash from stateroom to stateroom in
many disguises. Though Tucci's film crams too many stock '30s movie
caricatures onto a ship of fools, there is such unrestrained glee
that ``it hardly matters if this swirl of cotton candy disappears
even before it touches the tip of your tongue'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $100.96. 101 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: May 18. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NIGHT WATCH (LE TROU). Five convicts try to tunnel their way
out of the big house in Jacques Becker's final film. That may not
sound like the most original screen concept, but Becker worked for
Jean Renoir, inspired the likes of Jean-Luc Godard and Francois
Truffaut, and made movies noted for their detail and character
portrayal. In ``Le Trou,'' Bosley Crowther wrote in The New York
Times, he turned out a ``cliff hanger that throbs with excitement
and suspense and, at the same time, offers some stabbing insights
into the anxieties and energies of imprisoned men.'' 1960. Home
Vision. $29.95. 123 minutes. French with English subtitles. No
rating. Release date: May 18.
</P>
<P>
   AS TIME GOES BY. In the BBC romantic comedy, Judi Dench stars as
a widow who rekindles a romance with a retired British Army officer
with whom she had a brief romance 38 years before. (And perhaps her
beautiful, twice-divorced daughter can get fixed up in the
bargain.) 1999. BBC Video/Fox. Two cassettes, $19.98. 85 minutes
each.
</P>
<P>
   THE GIRL GETTERS and THE LEATHER BOYS. Mods and motorcycles get
surprisingly fine treatment in two British films from Kino. In
Michael Winner's ``The Girl Getters'' (1966, 79 minutes), Oliver
Reed stars as a slick, womanizing beach photographer who gets cut
down to size by a fashion model. Generally regarded as one of the
better films about the '60s youth scene, Sidney J. Furie's briskly
paced ``Leather Boys'' (1963, 105 minutes), stars Rita Tushingham
as the dissatisfied wife of a biker-mechanic (Colin Campbell).
$24.95 each. Information: (800) 562-3330.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
