<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-13 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: THINGS RARE, BEAUTIFUL AND VERY FRENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The small, refined world of fine French antiques
dealers here has just shrunk: Tony Victoria has sold his family's
five-floor gallery on East 55th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery, Frederick Victoria &AMP; Son, was established by
Victoria's father in 1941. Tony Victoria went to work there in 1972
and inherited the firm on his father's death in 1980. The gallery
sells an unusual mix of 18th-century French and Continental
furniture, porcelains and objets d'art with a sub-speciality of
items in the chinoiserie style.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never wanted anything that was run of the mill, only crazy
things,'' Victoria said. ``We always liked things that had
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   As Herve Aaron, another second-generation dealer who works with
his father at Didier Aaron, the renowned Paris and New York
gallery, put it: ``Not only does Tony have the same broad and
eclectic taste as his father, with a vision for design which is out
of the classical, but he also has a real human quality rare in a
dealer. He likes to share his knowledge. If we dealers lose clients
today, it's because we don't know how to interest them enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria said he had sold the gallery because he ``had an offer
for the building that was too tempting to refuse.'' Now he is
selling its contents in two auctions at Christie's in New York in
May: 126 lots in the sale of ``Important French and Continental
Furniture, Ceramics, Tapestries and Carpets,'' to be held May 27 at
Rockefeller Center, and 176 lots in the sale of ``European
Furniture and Decorative Arts,'' to be held on May 26 at Christie's
East, at 219 E. 67th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick P. Victoria &AMP; Son Inc. has been a New York
institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its closing makes me sad,'' said Stephanie Stokes, a Manhattan
interior designer who spent two hours in a Christie's basement last
week studying the collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, the sale offers the opportunity of a lifetime,'' she
said. ``Tony has an unfailing, extraordinary eye. There is simply
nothing ugly there. The painted pieces are particularly strong and
we don't have a lot of good painted furniture in New York. It's a
truly spectacular collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Her thoughts are echoed in the preface to the sale's catalog,
which was written by Hubert de Givenchy, the Paris couturier who is
now president of Christie's France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always made a point of visiting Freddy and Tony Victoria at
their gallery whenever I was in New York,'' Givenchy wrote. ``I was
constantly struck by the wonderfully eclectic range of treasures on
display there, all chosen with a distinctive eye for striking and
unusual shapes and forms.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing for the sale is good. Christie's sold the French
furniture in the Martin and Pauline Alexander collection April 30
for $10 million above the high estimate, for a total of $27.5
million. Leon Dalva, a proprietor of Dalva Brothers, a fine French
antiques gallery on East 57th Street, said, ``There has been a
steady increase in the demand for French furniture, and Tony's
taste is wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-story Victoria gallery resembled a great French country
house, with tall ceilings, creaking wood floors, ceramic stoves and
antique French paneled walls. It was so comfortable, and the
conversation was so good, that people often spent the afternoon in
the shop. Clients included Brooke Astor, Rachel (Bunny) Mellon,
Barbara (Babe) Paley, Grace Kelly and Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   For decades the gallery sold 18th-century French furniture,
clocks, porcelains, chandeliers, mirrors and paintings to
collectors through legendary designers like Elsie de Wolfe, Sister
Parish of Parish-Hadley, Eleanor Brown, founder of the decorating
firm McMillen Inc.; Billy Baldwin, Mark Hampton and Michael Taylor
of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the gallery was a source for designers as varied
as David Anthony Easton, Mario Buatta, Stephen Sills of Huniford
Sills, Bunny Williams, Howard Slatkin, Albert Hadley and Edward
Perrault of Houston, all looking for antiques with style and
personality.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the sale pieces have universal appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always liked things that were easy to live with, both
visually and in terms of maintenance,'' Victoria said. ``We have a
lot of painted furniture, not a lot of ormolu, and everything is in
its original state.''
</P>
<P>
   The lot pictured on the catalog's cover is my favorite; it's one
of a pair of extraordinary Italian polychrome mirrors in the
Chinese taste. Each has a scene showing Chinese men hauling framed
mirrors up a hill next to a Chinese pavilion and an elaborate
fretwork surround inlaid with mirror, with an exotic canopy at the
top shading a gilded face of a man with a long mustache. The
estimate for the pair is $250,000 to $350,000, but the pieces are
bound to fetch more. They are unique.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 84 will also turn heads. It is a Louis XV chaise longue
known as a ``chaise d'amour.'' It has caned sides, a silk velvet
headrest, palm rests and a long narrow seat. A celebrated French
dealer, Gaston Bensimon, told Victoria in 1984 that its purpose was
``to make love.''
</P>
<P>
   Most charming perhaps are a pair of circa 1770 Italian
papier-mache chinoiserie figures seated crosslegged on cushions.
Brightly painted, each is 18 inches tall and has a lively,
expressive face. The man wears a long droopy mustache, a
pagoda-shaped hat and a flowing gold-decorated green robe over his
pantaloons. The woman wears a bright red jacket and a Mona Lisa
smile. They nod their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinoiserie taste is something I inherited, and it became
second nature,'' Victoria said. ``These two are unusual because
such figures were delicate and didn't survive as well as other
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese nodding-head figures were popular in England in the 18th
century, Victoria said. The Boulay 300 magazine says the ones in
the sale are probably Venetian. The estimate is $30,000 to $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some pieces in the sale are very rare. ``In 18th-century
France,'' Victoria said, ``if you had a lot of taste and money you
could commission individual pieces of furniture for specific tasks
like hairdressing, games, even lovemaking.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, there is a Louis XV caned beechwood chair with a
heart-shaped back known as a ``fauteuil a coiffer.'' It once
belonged to Michel David-Weill. Designed as a chair for a woman
having her hair dressed, it is one of only two known in this style;
the other is in the Musee des Arts Decoratifs in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's father once owned that chair, but he donated it to
the museum in memory of his eldest son, Frederick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chair my father always coveted,'' Victoria said.
``When he bought it in 1962, it was the highest-priced chair that
had ever sold, at 90,000 French francs.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he bought his chair in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Will the sale be a success? Dalva said: ``Business is good.
Merchandise is hard to find. And the estimates are very
reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Your move.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
