<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can the Fall Be Far Behind?
</P>
<P>
   With next month's Tonys prompting more than a few yawns from
Broadway's cognoscenti, some gazes are already drifting toward the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   There already appears to be a candidate for a musical
blockbuster, ``Saturday Night Fever.'' The musical, based on the
movie, has had brisk sales. Although the cast offers no major stars
thus far, the show sold $1.6 million in single-ticket sales in the
first weeks, and its total advance stands at $6.2 million. It is to
open on Oct. 21 at the Minskoff Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Other entries confirmed include the play ``Voices in the Dark,''
at the Longacre Theater (to open on Aug. 12); ``Kat and the
Kings,'' a musical about a South African singing group at the Cort
(Aug. 19); a drag (as in queen) show, ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour''
at the Booth (Oct. 17) and ``Putting It Together,'' a Sondheim
sampler, at the Barrymore (Oct. 28).
</P>
<P>
   Now, three more fall entries have confirmed dates. ``Epic
Proportions,'' a comedy by Larry Coen and David Crane about the
making of a biblical epic, will open on Sept. 16. Kristin Chenoweth
(``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'') has been mentioned as a
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Swing,'' a musical paean to the retro-dance fad,
which has set a tentative Nov. 18 opening at a Nederlander house.
Lynne-Taylor Corbett (``Titanic'') will direct.
</P>
<P>
   Also confirmed is the revival of Peter Shaffer's ``Amadeus,''
which is to play in Los Angeles before landing at a Shubert house
for a Dec. 16 opening. David Suchet, who starred as the narrator
and villain Salieri, will reprise the role here. Sir Peter Hall
directs.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the autumn landscape gets murkier, with producers
still looking to settle such minor details as theaters, dates and
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss Me, Kate'' looks solid for a November opening, in a
theater to be named later. A member of the production staff said a
midsize Broadway house had already been offered but could not be
identified because a show was currently running there. Casting is
not complete, but Marin Mazzie and Brian Stokes Mitchell are strong
possibilities, the staff member said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vivian Beaumont Theater, at Lincoln Center, has long had
``Marie Christine,'' Michael John LaChiusa's musical with Audra
McDonald, scheduled for November, but look also for the Beaumont's
current resident, ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' to transfer
to a smaller Broadway house if its sales keep up. Another possible
fall entry comes from Matthew Bourne, director of ``Swan Lake.''
Katharine Dore, the producer of Bourne's latest ballet,
``Cinderella,'' which is just completing a run in Los Angeles,
inquired this week about bringing the show to Broadway for a
limited run in the late fall.
</P>
<P>
   Of the possible straight plays, an early autumn entry may be a
revival of ``The Rainmaker'' by N. Richard Nash. The production,
directed by Scott Ellis, drew strong reviews at the Williamstown
Theater Festival last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Harrelson has been approached about playing Starbuck, the
male lead, and the Brooks Atkinson is a possible home if the right
cast can be assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Another production hunting for the right man is a revival of
Eugene O'Neill's ``Moon for the Misbegotten.'' Cherry Jones has
long been attached to the project, and people connected with it say
Stephen Rea is a candidate to play opposite her.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-December will bring a trip to ``Wrong Mountain,'' a surreal
comedy by David Hirson involving a giant worm, theatrical mind
games and a crazed director. Alan Cumming (``Cabaret'') was
involved in early readings.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel, Superstar
</P>
<P>
   The producers Anita Waxman and Elizabeth P. Williams, an
ambitious new team, said this week they were forming a commercial
production company, Orpheus Productions, devoted to staging the
work of the British director David Leveaux, most recently of
``Electra.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet on people,'' said Ms. Waxman, ``and David seems like a
good bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Haimes, the artistic director of both the Roundabout
Theater Company and Livent, will be an adviser to the new company.
Its first production is likely to be Eugene O'Neill's ``Desire
Under the Elms'' next spring, followed by a revival of the musical
``Nine,'' both directed by Leveaux.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most fascinating project is still several years
from fruition: a Kevin Costner musical. Ms. Waxman said Costner had
begun development work on ``My Cuba,'' a musical about the Cuban
revolution and the rise of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Costner would star in the musical and help produce it with
Orpheus. The show may be performed in workshop sometime after 2000.
Representatives at Costner's production company, Tig Productions,
confirmed the project.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Cho's Return
</P>
<P>
   It's been four years since Margaret Cho, then the country's
hottest comedienne, watched as her big break broke down.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Ms. Cho's sitcom ``All-American Girl'' was canceled by
ABC amid slipping ratings and a controversy surrounding the show's
portrayal of Asian-American life. It was an experience that Ms.
Cho, 30, now variously likens to ``a descent into hell,'' a
``Jacobean tragedy'' or the story of ``the Trojan Margaret.'' More
seriously, Ms. Cho says she, too, was slipping, into alcohol and
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't talked about it,'' she said in a telephone
interview from Los Angeles. ``And I certainly haven't been able to
laugh about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting June 22, however, Ms. Cho will be exploring her
Hollywood days _ and daze _ in New York in a one-woman show she has
written. It is her theatrical debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories I have been telling have changed so much and
expanded so much that they became too big to tell in a comedy
club,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which is still untitled, is to play at the Westbeth
Theater Center, which has been home to successful one-person acts
by the likes of Eddie Izzard and Sandra Bernhard. Ms. Cho, who is
Korean-American, says that while her days in Hollywood were
``harsh,'' her show is less so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say that comedy comes from coping with painful
experiences,'' she said. ``And I've had some practice with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
