<HEADER>
A5847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      05-13 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Museum Lays In Vintage Kellys &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art's permanent collection
continues its rapid growth, some of this country's best-known
artists are choosing to give and sell the museum works from their
own collections. This week the museum announced that it had bought
22 works, paintings, wall reliefs and sculptures, by Ellsworth
Kelly. They have been valued at more than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   The works range from the artist's student days in Boston, just
after World War II, to his large-scale sculptures of the last 10
years. They are to be exhibited at the museum in the summer of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approached the artist,'' said David A. Ross, the museum's
director. ``It's part of our overall strategy to tell the complete
story of modern art.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year ago the museum bought 14 works by Robert
Rauschenberg, many from the artist's own collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be able to go in depth with the work of certain
artists when warranted,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's trustees match the director and curators as fans of
Kelly. (One, Donald Fisher, founder of the Gap, owns one of the
largest private collections of Kelly's work.) An anonymous group of
trustees paid for the 22 works.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, 75, is considered one of the nation's pre-eminent postwar
artists. His relationship with the San Francisco museum dates back
to 1988, when an exhibition of his works on paper was shown there.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly later donated a sculpture, ``Diagonal With Curve XI''
(1982), to the museum in memory of John Caldwell, the former chief
curator, who died in 1993. The gift was also timed to coincide with
the opening of the museum's new building in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Among the earliest of the new acquisitions is ``Self-Portrait
With Thorn,'' a 1947 Picassoesque painting. Another painting,
``Shuan-Shu'' (1948), is an abstract play on Chinese characters.
There are several of Kelly's large-scale sculptures as well as some
of his earlier ``Chance'' compositions. The sculptures include
pieces in steel, aluminum and wood. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unearthed &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery of Art in Washington, like its counterpart
in London, has begun producing small, tightly edited exhibitions
that focus on a specific work of art.
</P>
<P>
   From May 30 through June 18, ``The Taking of Christ,'' a 1602
painting by Caravaggio, will hang in a room in the museum's West
Building as the centerpiece of the show ``Caravaggio's `The Taking
of Christ': Saints and Sinners in Baroque Painting.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting had fallen out of the art world's sight for almost
two centuries when it was rediscovered in Ireland in 1990. It was
recognized by scholars in the dining room of the Dublin residence
of the Society of Jesus. The painting was labeled as the work of
Gerard van Honthorst, a Dutch painter who was influenced by
Caravaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painted for Ciriaco Mattei, a Roman nobleman and
remained in the family until 1802, when it was sold to a Scotsman
named William Hamilton Nisbet,'' said Philip Conisbee, senior
curator of European paintings at the National Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was then that the attribution was changed. In 1921,
Nisbet's family sold it.'' By the end of the 1920s the painting had
been given to the Jesuits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, theJesuits invited Sergio Benedetti, the senior
conservator for the National Gallery of Ireland in Dublin, to see
the painting. He recognized it as the long-lost Caravaggio. Ten
other experts traveled to Dublin and confirmed his discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery's exhibition draws on ``Saints and Sinners:
Caravaggio and the Baroque Image,'' a show in the McMullen Museum
of Art at Boston College through May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we couldn't take the entire exhibition, I thought we
could reinstall the Caravaggio with eight of our own works, some
that have been recently cleaned and others that are recent
acquisitions,'' Conisbee said.
</P>
<P>
   The other works are by artists influenced by Caravaggio.
Included are ``Soldiers Playing Cards and Dice (The Cheats)''
(circa 1620-22) by a French follower, Valentin de Boullogne, and
two restored works, ``St. Jerome and the Angel'' (1625) by Simon
Vouet and ``St. Sebastian'' (circa 1620-30), by Tanzio da Varallo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Manet Reunion &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery of Art in Washington and the Frick
Collection in New York are uniting two parts of a large painting by
Manet that was displayed at the 1864 Paris Salon as ``Incident in a
Bullfight.'' The painting became two independent canvases when
Manet cut two sections out of it soon after its return from the
Salon.
</P>
<P>
   Art scholars have suggested that Manet was reacting to criticism
that the toreador in the foreground was too large for the figures
in the background or that the artist was seeking to make two
stronger works. He is thought to have discarded the rest of the
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   One work, ``The Dead Toreador,'' is in the permanent collection
of the National Gallery of Art. The other, ``The Bullfight,'' was
acquired by the industrialist Henry Clay Frick in 1914. The two
paintings will be displayed together for the first time from May 25
through Aug. 22 in the Frick's East Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades art historians and conservators have tried to
reconstruct the original work. ``It's been a puzzle to try to see
what the original composition looked like,'' said Susan Grace
Galassi, the Frick Collection's associate curator, who organized
the show. ``Our only record has been three caricatures from
satirical publications of the period and verbal descriptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1982, she said, people have studied the works with X-rays
and determined that the artist altered the painting before showing
it at the Salon. Putting together the two works was an obvious
idea, she added. ``Hopefully, this will be the beginning of more
research.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Curator at the Modern &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art has announced that Paulo Herkenhoff, an
art historian, critic and director of the Sao Paulo biennial show,
will serve as an adjunct curator in the painting and sculpture
department for three years beginning in September. He will work on
exhibitions and acquisitions, particularly of Latin American and
contemporary art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
