<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      05-13 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ATOMIC TRAIN': LOCOMOTIVE HURTLING INTO DARK REAL-LIFE ISSUES  
 `DOUBLE PLATINUM': DULL PROMOTIONAL VEHICLE FOR DIANA ROSS AND
BRANDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes for `Atomic Train' are at end of review.
Time, channel are for New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Atomic Train'' was not produced by that amorphous bogeyman
that some people in Washington have blithely named the ``toxic
culture.'' This is a silly two-part mini-series that works
surprisingly well on the level of formulaic action. It is ``Speed''
on a train with Rob Lowe in the Sandra Bullock role, playing a hero
who has to stop a runaway train hurtling toward Denver carrying a
nuclear bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Happenstance also caused that train to collide with actual news
events. After the shootings at Columbine High School, the Denver
setting acquired an unintended chill. Understandably, NBC did not
change the setting of its film. Would it have been kinder to have
targeted Salt Lake City, which has had shooting sprees of its own?
Just as understandably, the NBC station in Denver has chosen not to
carry the mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   But while ``Atomic Train'' was not made by the devil, it is the
very definition of a cheap thrill. Even before the train heads
toward Denver, there is something creepy, callous and
self-defeating about the way the mini-series uses realistic
allusions to lend credence to its inane story. At the last minute,
NBC substituted the words ``hazardous material'' for ``nuclear
waste'' and tacked on a disclaimer saying the mini-series is ``not
based on fact.'' The network denied it was responding to pressure
from the nuclear power industry. Those changes are ludicrously at
odds with the mini-series' tone.
</P>
<P>
   In a prelude to the main plot, the drama begins with lifelike
news reports of fictional railroad accidents. ``As night falls in
Omaha, the rescue teams have nearly completed the grim task of
sifting through the wreckage,'' one newsman says, in a
pitch-perfect imitation of the typical anchor's melodramatic
delivery and overwritten script.
</P>
<P>
   Even more jarring is language that brings to mind the crisis in
Kosovo. As residents begin evacuating Denver, just in case the Rob
Lowe character fails, the president addresses the nation. He is
played by Edward Herrmann as a man who is sincerely concerned but
hasn't a clue what to do. We see him on the Times Square Jumbotron,
the NBC logo prominently displayed, saying, ``I ask that you open
your hearts and your homes to any refugees from Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Some characters are already heading toward what is called ``a
refugee camp on the Kansas border.'' You would think the world has
enough refugees without NBC adding some from Colorado. Instead of
adding realism such language jolts viewers out of the story,
emphasizing the distance between this glib action movie and harsh
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics prevent ``Atomic Train'' from being as purely
escapist as it could and should have been. Most of the time it has
the action formula down. ``We're a rolling Chernobyl,'' the train's
engineer says of the nuclear waste he is hauling (whatever he calls
it), and that is before anyone realizes that an unstable Russian
nuclear bomb has been hidden on board by the corrupt owner of a
waste disposal company hoping to save shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   The train loses its brakes. John Seger (Lowe), an investigator
for the National Transportation Safety Board, happens to be in the
neighborhood. Before long, he is leaping onto a freight train from
a helicopter, jumping from that freight train to the atomic train,
and dangling upside down between cars trying to fix the brakes. So
much for believable action. But then ``Speed'' wasn't exactly a
study in realism. ``Atomic Train'' maintains a swift pace and
enough suspense to carry it over the story's obvious trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe keeps a straight face, though it will be hard for viewers
to do the same when watching what is supposedly the atomic train
speeding along twisty mountain tracks. It is conspicuously a
miniature, with cute little toy cars in front of a tiny fake
mountain. The special effects are more convincing when they get
around to fiery explosions.
</P>
<P>
   As in most action movies, the emotional part of the plot is both
de rigueur and completely dispensable. John Seger is a caring
family man, with a belligerent teen-age daughter, a new wife and a
small stepson. What better way for a family to blend than to face
nuclear holocaust?
</P>
<P>
   ``Atomic Train'' takes an exceptionally dark turn in the second
episode and becomes a different sort of disaster movie. The plot
shouldn't be given away, though anyone with an eye on the clock in
Part One can make a safe guess. The evacuation leads to panic,
looting and general social chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Watching ``Atomic Train'' will not lead to anything like that,
though it does raise lingering questions about how real tragedies
are put to tacky fictional use.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ATOMIC TRAIN'
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Sunday and Monday nights at 9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 4 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   First of a two-part mini-series, written by Dick Lowry and David
Jackson; Dennis Hammer, Armand Speca and Jeff Fazio, executive
producers; Mike Joyce, producer; Barbara Kelly, co-producer.
Produced by Dennis Hammer Productions in association with NBC
Studios Inc.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Rob Lowe (John Seger), Esai Morales (Noris ``Mac''
MacKenzie), Edward Herrmann (President) and Kristin Davis (Megan
Seger). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `DOUBLE PLATINUM'
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Sunday night
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 7, New York, at 9)
</P>
<P>
   The only question raised by ``Double Platinum'' has to do with
money. How many CDs will be sold as a result of this joint
promotion for Diana Ross and Brandy? Disguised as a soap opera, the
film is really a two-hour music video so lacking in style it makes
the dullest VH-1 video seem like cutting-edge art. Ms. Ross plays
Olivia, who leaves her husband and baby daughter, Kayla, to pursue
her dream of becoming a star. Eighteen years later, about 10
minutes in television time, she looks up Kayla (Brandy), and helps
 &UR; her &LR;  pursue her dream of becoming a star.
</P>
<P>
   They fight, they make up, but all of it is an excuse for the mom
and daughter divas to sing in hackneyed poses: onstage in front of
an adoring crowd, in a recording studio. Brandy's songs include
``Almost Doesn't Count'' and Ms. Ross' ``Every Day Is a New Day.''
With the exception of a duet at the end, all are available on their
latest CDs.
</P>
<P>
   There is not a surprising or believable moment anywhere, though
there is talent squandered everywhere. The most conspicuous waste:
Brian Stokes Mitchell plays Kayla's dad. Though his rich voice
provided the most powerful moments in ``Ragtime'' on Broadway, here
he doesn't sing a note.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
