<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     05-13 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: GEOFFREY RUSH; SODERBERGH'S LATEST; ICE CUBE IN
`NEXT FRIDAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geoffrey Rush: Bouncing Boy Sees Busy Days
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Perhaps the best word to describe the way Geoffrey
Rush chooses his movie roles is ``bouncing.'' He played a painfully
unbalanced piano prodigy in ``Shine,'' a deadly serious Inspector
Javert in ``Les Miserables'' and a hilariously bumbling theater
owner in ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   And now more bouncing: he will appear this summer as the wacky
Casanova Frankenstein in ``Mystery Men,'' a delirious comic book
comedy, and as a murderous theme park creator in the earnest horror
film ``House on Haunted Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of bouncing, and Rush, taking stock of those shifts
at home in his native Australia, said in a telephone interview that
more were in store.
</P>
<P>
   This summer he plans to begin shooting ``Quills,'' in which he
will play the aging Marquis de Sade, famous for his literary
descriptions of sexual sadism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just done two American genre pieces, and I thought this
was something I wanted to bounce back toward,'' said Rush, who has
become one of Hollywood's most respected character actors. ``It's a
great argument about libertarianism versus repression. I would
probably describe this as a sophisticated, cerebral event.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie will be directed for Fox Searchlight by Philip
Kaufman, director of ``Rising Sun,'' ``Henry and June'' and ``The
Unbearable Lightness of Being,'' among other films, and it also
stars Kate Winslet.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the Marquis de Sade is old and imprisoned, Rush
said, and suffers when a fairly progressive prison warden is
replaced with a stricter and more repressive warden. That is the
platform for a dramatization of the debate over what can be
expressed and what should be repressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees himself as an irreverent peddler of pornography,''
Rush said. ``The question is whether someone like this should
remain locked up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're coming out of this slight puritanical phase now
and it's time to ask if writers can write what they want to write.
This movie is starting to scratch that old wound.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush said that in a sense the movie was almost like a period
drama depicting a debate like that posed in ``The People vs. Larry
Flynt,'' the Milos Forman film that explored the contemporary
debate over pornography and the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Rush said he was attracted not to the debate but to the script,
which he found extremely powerful.
</P>
<P>
   And next? Another bounce for Rush, who said he was planning to
do a play in Australia called ``The Small Poppies,'' in which he
will play a 5-year-old on his first day of school.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh's Newest
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his breakthrough movie, ``Sex, Lies and Videotape,''
in 1989, Steven Soderbergh has tended to make films that explore
nervous characters with an psychologically probing style. From
``Kafka'' in 1992 to ``Out of Sight,'' last year's noirish
thriller, the movies he has directed have gotten under the skin of
their characters, if not the audiences.
</P>
<P>
   His newest movie, ``The Limey,'' a $9 million drama about an
Englishman who gets out of prison only to come to Los Angeles to
try to learn how his daughter died, is a character study. The film
is to play in Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   But in two weeks Soderbergh is to begin work on a film that will
move into a slightly new direction. For starters, the movie, ``Erin
Brockovich,'' has a $55 million budget, the biggest he has worked
with. For another, it stars one of Hollywood's most expensive
actresses, Julia Roberts. The drama, based on real events, involves
a town whose water is poisoned by a local company, which Ms.
Roberts' character successfully sues.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh said he was drawn to the project by how different it
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really isn't a method to what I do other than being
engaged by the material and wanting an experience different than
the one I just came out of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh acknowledged that Jersey Films had urged him to
consider the project for some time and that he had initially
rejected it because it was so unlike his usual material. But after
he finished shooting ``The Limey,'' he said, he finally read the
script and found it more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``The Limey,'' an impressionistic film whose chronology
jumps around, ``Erin Brockovich'' has a linear plot. ``I said,
`Let's do the opposite for a change,''' Soderbergh said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roberts plays a divorced woman with three small children who
discovers while working as a clerk at a law firm that a company has
been covering up how its contamination of the water supply is
causing serious illnesses. She and her boss, played by Albert
Finney, take on the polluter and win a $400 million suit.
</P>
<P>
   The studio behind the project, Universal Studios, evidently sees
the film as a potential Oscar contender because it hopes to release
the movie just before year's end, when serious dramas tend to get
the most visibility.
</P>
<P>
   The movie may be a potential award vehicle for Ms. Roberts, who
has received two Oscar nominations but no statues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never made a movie in which a female character had that
much time on the screen,'' Soderbergh said. ``She's in virtually
every scene in this film.''
</P>
<P>
   What he ultimately found engaging about the movie, he said, was
the struggle faced by Ms. Roberts' character, who is torn between
her strong views and the fact that nearly everyone around her views
the pollution situation differently than she does and feels she is
going off half cocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what I liked is that this is a high-wire act for
her,'' Soderbergh said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ice Cube in Cult Sequel
</P>
<P>
   The business of building movie franchises has become fairly
clear-cut in Hollywood: take a blockbuster, focus on the lead
character, put him (it's never a her) in new and different
settings, and then start counting your money.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's never quite that simple. But even by the basic
rules of this business, ``Next Friday,'' which began shooting in
Hollywood this week with rapper Ice Cube and Michael Epps in the
leading roles, is an unusual kind of sequel. It is the follow-up to
``Friday,'' a so-called urban comedy _ meaning a movie with a
nearly all-black cast _ that was released in 1995 to generally
scathing reviews and earned a fairly meager $28 million or so at
the box office. It starred Ice Cube and Chris Tucker, at the time a
relatively unknown comedian.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Friday'' got a second wind. The video of the movie sold
and sold and then sold some more: it was on the video best-seller
list for about 100 weeks, with more than 600,000 tapes sold to
date. What's more, more than 2.2 million copies of the movie's
hip-hop soundtrack have been sold. And the film cost a fairly
modest $4 million to produce and distribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday'' was, in short, a cult hit, and New Line Cinema, which
produced the film and now the sequel, is banking that the success
can be reproduced in ``Next Friday,'' a film that for a while
anyway nobody wanted to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had vowed never to make a sequel to `Friday' because I
thought it was a classic and that we couldn't repeat it,'' Ice Cube
said. ``I didn't want to be one of these guys regurgitating the
same old jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the original movie's remarkable life in video and
the prospect of remaking the film in a different setting _ in this
case, a suburb rather than the inner city _ led him to give it a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   The movie will cost $11 million, which is still modest, and New
Line expects to release it in December. The director is Steve Carr,
who will be handling his first feature film. Ice Cube is a producer
as well as the screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a classic franchise, and Ice Cube didn't want to
do it,'' said Michael De Luca, president of production at New Line.
``But there was a real crossover in video that nobody expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Ice Cube said that for him, the original film's video life
proved one theory about films with largely black casts.
</P>
<P>
   Because of some violent incidents at rap movies, some whites
avoid seeing such films at theaters, but the appeal of black
culture makes them avid viewers of the videos, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are few movie theaters in black neighborhoods, he added,
and young blacks often feel uncomfortable going to largely white
neighborhoods to watch movies steeped in their culture. So they
also tend to rent or buy the videos instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I just try to make a movie true to myself and my
culture,'' Ice Cube said. ``White audiences want something that's
authentic, and if you do that, you also attract the black
audience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
