<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AIMS TO STOP AFFLUENT FROM DODGING THEIR DEBTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 16)   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ School administrator Elfreda Massie and her
husband, Leonard, couldn't make ends meet despite their $180,000
combined annual salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Massies filed for bankruptcy twice in the past 18 years but
they still lived a life style that allowed them to take vacation
trips to Cancun, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The Massie's most recent bankruptcy _ filed last June _ showed
the couple had amassed more than $140,000 in debt on 23 credit
cards as well as a loan of almost $10,000 from a teachers' credit
union.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of their bankruptcy plea, the Massies will be able
to walk away from much of that debt, even though Mrs. Massie, a
deputy school superintendent in Baltimore, earns $108,000 and her
husband earns about $72,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of case we are trying to eliminate,'' said
George Wallace, a member of the Consumer Bankruptcy Reform
Coalition, a group of banks, credit unions, retailers and mortgage
companies that are pushing for bankruptcy reform. Wallace also
practices bankruptcy law in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition is urging the Senate to approve legislation in the
next two weeks that would require most people earning more than
$50,000 annually to pay a portion of their debts. The House
approved similar legislation earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to tighten the federal bankruptcy law comes as more
and more consumers seek to shed their debts by filing for
bankruptcy. A record 1.4 million Americans sought bankruptcy last
year, according to the Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts.
Bankruptcy filings have climbed by nearly 20 percent a year since
the early 1990s, prompting creditors to ask Congress for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the need for bankruptcy reform is fairly obvious,''
said Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa., citing those bankruptcy
figures. Grassley is the author of the Senate bankruptcy bill.
</P>
<P>
   The means test in the legislation would be adjusted on a
regional basis. The Senate bill, unlike the House bill, gives
bankruptcy judges some leeway to stray from using the means-test.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 study by the tax firm, Ernst &AMP; Young, showed that as many
as 10 percent of bankruptcy filers were financially able to pay a
significant portion of their debts, which is what they would be
required to do if they meet the means-test in the pending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace acknowledges that many people who file for bankruptcy
protection aren't abusing the system and got into trouble with the
loss of a job or hit with thousands of dollars of unexpected
medical bills. Indeed, Mrs. Massie told a local newspaper that she
got into financial trouble when she had to pay a portion of nursing
home care for a relative.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and supporters of the reform legislation say that, even
with the changes they want, the bankruptcy law would still give
people a ``fresh start'' when they run into unforeseen financial
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a family is making $30,000, $40,000 or $50,000, that fresh
start is guaranteed,'' said Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., and author of
the House bill. ``But if you are earning $60,000, $80,000, $100,000
or beyond, then that set of circumstances has to be looked at more
closely.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, consumer groups, and a handful of
Republicans say the means-test is too rigid.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., complains that the
IRS living standards are not adjusted for regional differences and
could hurt people living in high-cost areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems to me a little humanity, a little flexibility, a
little reasonableness in working out the living standards...is
appropriate,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the measure ``is a great bill for the creditors,''
noting the ``awesome'' power of creditor lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde was unsuccessful in his attempt to amend the bill to use a
calculation other than the IRS version to determine living
standards, but ultimately voted for the bankruptcy overhaul bill.
</P>
<P>
   While the credit industry has pushed for bankruptcy reform,
consumer groups argue that creditors helped contribute to the
increase in bankruptcies by encouraging people to take on more debt
by, for example, sending out millions of credit card solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Torres, legislative counsel for Consumers Union, said many
credit card firms attract people by offering low interest rates but
then raise the rates to as much as 19 percent later on. He said
many people don't understand the impact of high interest rates and
only making a minimum payment on a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it would take a person with a $2,000 credit card
bill more than 10 years to retire the debt only paying the minimum
amount of $10 or $15 a month _ and that's without ever adding to
the debt.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill was amended to require credit card issuers to
give consumers more information about the effect of only paying the
minimum amount per month and other financial information. The
Senate bill is likely to amended in the same manner as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
