u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MET-TUTTLE-3RDTAKE-AR     05-13 0190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-TUTTLE-3RDTAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: at his pictures.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still on this subject, he cites the Met's van Eyck, a diptych of
the Crucifixion and Last Judgment. ``With van Eyck's works
generally there's another plane of consciousness because of the
words on the frames of the pictures, which mean that the illusion
in his paintings is brought together with another kind of
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Tuttle made ``Monkey's Recovery for a Darkened Room
(Bluebird),'' a wall relief of branches, wire, cloth, string and
wood scraps, which he says formally relates to the Met's diptych.
``The link is in terms of the organization of bottom, middle and
top, the fact that the panels of the van Eyck are divided
horizontally into three parts, and in a sense so is `Monkey's
Recovery' _ and maybe also in terms of having two vertical parts,
the branches of `Monkey's Recovery' being on one side and the wood
on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle cites the art historian Erwin Panofsky, who said that
once you have van Eyck in your eye, Rubens is just another painter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to live every day of my life with van Eyck in my
eye,'' Tuttle adds.
</P>
</TEXT>
