<SLUG> BC-CAR-WALLACE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACE NOT LETTING SOME BAD LUCK AFFECT HIS PREPARATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace is perhaps a pit stop, a bad shock and a wreck
away from being a major player in the Winston Cup points
championship, which is not to say he is out of it.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran driver who has won at least one race in each of the
last 14 years, Wallace is noted for his determination and attention
to detail. Right now he's at seventh place in the standings and
he's had one win _ the Food City 500 in Bristol, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Because he understands cars, is often demanding and is never
afraid to express his opinion, Wallace can be a difficult boss.
That can be especially true when he isn't running as well as he
feels he should.
</P>
<P>
   At 42, his competitive edge remains sharp.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he will tell you that, with this season about a third
over, he is disappointed with his overall performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had three bad problems with finishing below 30th _ that
was at Atlanta and Darlington and Talladega _ so I'm worse off than
I thought I'd be right now,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   If Wallace is behind, it's not because his Ford isn't ready to
race. He strongly believes that the teams that prepare the best do
the best, and he is normally ready to run when he gets to the
track.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some things you just can't prepare for.
</P>
<P>
   Like the California 500 two weekends ago in Fontana, where he
got caught in the pits by a caution flag that caused him to fall a
lap behind the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Or in March in Atlanta, where he felt fairly confident going
into the Cracker Barrel 500 only to have trouble with a bad shock
that dropped him to 35th.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Diehard 500 in April at Talladega, Ala., where while
running third he was taken out by a wreck that was not of his
making. He had expected to do well in the race since he had the
dominant car at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the eighth-place finish in Daytona ... well, you
get the point, even if Wallace hasn't gotten as many as he would
like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to be the lap leader, but that doesn't win
races,'' said Wallace, who has led more laps than anybody in three
of the 10 races so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to do that, but unforeseen circumstances sometimes
happen, like at Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a restrictor-plate wreck in a long, long time,
and it seemed like for a long time there I was involved in every
one of them, and then it happened again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe the guy I ended up running into was Jeff
Gordon. I hit him dead in the door at 180 mph and we both walked
away from it, but you can't dwell on that. You've just gotta keep
running,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while the points may not show it, when he is right,
Wallace can be about as tough as anyone to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, he has shown strength on the restrictor plate
tracks _ Daytona and Talladega _ and the short tracks, those less
than a mile in length, places where he traditionally runs well.
</P>
<P>
   And if he can avoid the bad luck that befell him at Atlanta,
Darlington and California, he could still be a factor in the points
chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really like to talk about frustration because there is
a lot of stuff you can't do anything about,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That deal at Fontana, I went in there with high hopes of
winning the race and running good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon was running at warp speed again and I made a scheduled
pit stop running fifth. When I left pit road, the caution flag flew
and I'm down a lap. That's bad luck right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not gonna change my feeling on preparation,'' Wallace
said. ``I still feel like we've prepared great and we're gonna stay
that way throughout the year,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is a firm believer that hard work pays off.
</P>
<P>
   His team has worked feverishly to build a new fleet of more
aerodynamic cars, and they are coming on line now.
</P>
<P>
   With a little luck, that may enable him to keep some of the
other leaders in line behind him.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
