<SLUG> BC-BURT-BACHARACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACHARACH IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREG HAYMES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Bacharach is back . . . in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, popmeister Burt Bacharach seems to be bigger than ever,
and that's really saying something considering the way his songs
dominated the pop charts back in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   The Bacharach comeback seems to have ignited a couple of years
ago with the show-stopping sing-along of his hit ``I Say a Little
Prayer'' in the film ``My Best Friend's Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's soundtrack also included everyone from Ani DiFranco
to Mary Chapin Carpenter offering their interpretations of his
classic tunes. Then there was Bacharach's cameo in the film
``Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, hipsters like the Ben Folds Five, Sheryl Crow and
Chrissie Hynde paid tribute to the songmaster in a New York City
concert that was broadcast on TNT and PBS. And just a few months
ago, Rhino Records gave him the deluxe treatment with a smashing
3-CD box set of his works, ``The Look of Love: The Burt Bacharach
Collection.''
</P>
<P>
   But proving that he's not merely living off his considerable
past glories, Bacharach teamed up with Elvis Costello to write and
produce the Grammy-winning album ``Painted From Memory,'' one of
the most sophisticated pop albums of last year.
</P>
<P>
   This week, People magazine named the 70-year-old Bacharach as
one of the 50 most beautiful people in the world, featuring him
alongside folks like Sandra Bullock and Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   And Bacharach is back on the road again, including a tour stop
at Proctor's Theatre in Schenectady on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing more touring now than I've ever done in life,''
Bacharach admitted during a telephone interview last week from
Texas, where he was performing with the Houston Symphony Orchestra.
``It's kind of funny, but that's just the way things have turned
out for me.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're hot, you're hot, and Bacharach has a busy schedule
leading up to the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be doing a lot of touring for the rest of this
year,'' he says. ``And the new `Austin Powers' movie comes out next
month, and Elvis and I are in that as well as on the soundtrack.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another upcoming project finds Bacharach reunited with
lyricist Hal David and vocalist Dionne Warwick _ the magic
triumvirate of talent that forged a long string of smash hits back
in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote the score for the upcoming Bette Midler movie, `Isn't
She Great,' which is the life story of novelist Jacqueline Susann.
It comes out at the end of the year, I do believe. I wrote two
songs as well as the background score, and both songs were written
with Hal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacharach and David, a Midas-touched combination, haven't worked
together in more than 25 years. A rift in their long relationship
followed their collaboration on the disastrous '73 film ``Lost
Horizon,'' and bridges weren't mended until they teamed up again
for ``Isn't She Great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the filmmakers just liked the association,'' Bacharach
says matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Hal is a great lyric writer, but right now I'm
really happy just writing with a lot of different people. Of
course, there was the project with Elvis, and I've also just
written a new instrumental with Dave Koz, that he's about to
record. I like working this way. It's like dating, you know?''
Bacharach _ who was previously married to actress Angie Dickinson
and his former songwriting partner, Carole Bayer Sager _ currently
lives in Pacific Palasades, Calif., with his wife, Jane, and their
children, 6-year-old Oliver and 3-year-old Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   While Bacharach once ruled the pop charts, he realizes that
contemporary radio is a whole different ball game today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees anymore. It's a very different
youth-driven market today, very singles-oriented. I think it's just
difficult today for Top 40 radio to accept not just me, but Elvis
as well, to a certain extent, so we didn't even try with `Painted
From Memory,''' he explains. ``We tried to market the album in a
different way, rather than promoting it through radio. It was very,
very hard.
</P>
<P>
   Bacharach _ who names Babyface as one of the contemporary
songwriters whose work he admires _ realizes that most of today's
hits are about lust, not love, although he insists that romance
hasn't completely gone out of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there room for a romantic song to get on the radio today?
Yes, and I think there always will be,'' he declares. ``I just
think that the opportunities are narrower today. But I really can't
be bothered with that, because it's all out of my control. I just
try to write the best songs that I can write, and go from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
