<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STARWARS-PORTMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROYAL ROLE: ACTRESS HAD TO THINK TWICE BEFORE TAKING PART AS
QUEEN AMIDALA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She was offered a role in one of the biggest movies
ever _ and hesitated.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to play Queen Amidala, young ruler of the embattled
planet Naboo in ``Star Wars: Episode One _ The Phantom Menace,''
Natalie Portman wasn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment was huge,'' Portman, 17, said after a press
screening of the film last weekend. ``I'd be signing not only for
three films, but pretty much 10 years of my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge deal at any age, and when you're that young, it's
really scary.''
</P>
<P>
   She also was concerned about how much the prequel trilogy
``would put the cast in the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out there already, and when it comes out, it's gonna be
even crazier. It obviously takes away from your private life.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to mention the Carrie Fisher syndrome. Fisher has
long felt that the first ``Star Wars'' trilogy stunted her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some concern about being identified with a role
forever,'' Portman said.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, creator George Lucas gave her time to think. Portman
was one of the first people cast in ``The Phantom Menace,'' and
filming was still a year away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't pressuring me at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After pondering for a few weeks, she finally gave Lucas a go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided, `Let's have a fun summer and a great,
memorable experience.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now the confessed chocoholic is ``really proud of this film.''
</P>
<P>
   As for earlier concerns, she said, ``I think we (the actors) are
all different from the previous stars of ''Star Wars.``
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us are known for other works, especially people like
Liam (Neeson), Ewan (McGregor) and Sam (Samuel L. Jackson). I don't
think the (film) industry will recognize us now only for this
work.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if it does, she said ``I wouldn't be upset to be
remembered most for this role.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's doubtful that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Portman made a big impact with ``The Professional,'' playing a
girl teaming with a hitman after her parents are murdered. She also
received raves for her work in the film ``Beautiful Girls'' and for
the title role of the Broadway play ``The Diary of Anne Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   Her other film credits include ``Mars Attacks!,'' ``Heat'' and
Woody Allen's ``Everyone Says I Love You.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Lucas cast her, Portman never had seen a ``Star Wars''
film. She was born and raised in Israel, ``and I just missed it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   After her family moved to Long Island, she got the acting bug.
But she's not sure she wants to act forever.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Portman is attending college this fall (``I'm not
saying where right now''), and she'll do film work _ including her
second ``Star Wars'' movie in 2000 _ only during summers.
</P>
<P>
   A boyfriend? She's mum on that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did (have a boyfriend), it'd be unfair to him to place
him in a limelight he didn't choose,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But many male fans have written to Portman, whose beauty once
earned her modeling offers, which she declined to pursue acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's because I've been in some guy movies,'' she said
with an easy laugh, referring to ``The Professional'' and ``Heat.''
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't think ``The Phantom Menace'' is one such film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a lot more female-oriented. The costumes, scenery
and images are so beautiful, and there's a strong female character.
Plus, you have the heartthrob value of Ewan McGregor.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman's Amidala is a 14-year-old ruler who, in the later
films, will wed Anakin Skywalker, the future Darth Vader. They'll
then have two kids: the original trilogy's Luke and Leia.
</P>
<P>
   Anakin was played by Jake Lloyd, then 8, in ``The Phantom
Menace.'' His part will be recast with an older actor for ``Episode
II,'' to be shot, like ``Phantom Menace,'' in Tunisia and England,
as well as Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``My character will be in her early 20s then, and Anakin will be
about 16,'' Portman said. ``Then, in the third film, we'll be a
little older.''
</P>
<P>
   Amidala must act older to be taken seriously as a young ruler.
So the queen wears elaborate makeup, clothes and wigs and speaks in
a regal voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're some of the most beautiful costumes ever made for a
film,'' Portman said. ``They really helped me with the character,
because you carry yourself differently when you're wearing that
kind of gear.''
</P>
<P>
   Hair and makeup took 2 to 2 1/2 hours, but the costumes were a
snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were made for snap on, snap off, so if you had to go to
the bathroom you wouldn't ruin a day (of shooting),'' Portman said.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't think Amidala's white lipstick with a red stripe
down the middle will start a trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks really cool, but it's so difficult to keep up,''
Portman said. ``The white and red soon turn pink. I had people
reapplying it all day.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows some female fans will try it, anyway, but that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great how passionate these people are,'' she
said. ``I haven't met them, but they seem like fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
