<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD CUT TAXES FOR SMALL INVESTORS
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Millions of taxpayers who invest would receive tax
relief under a bill introduced Thursday in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Savers Act would raise the threshold on the 15 percent
personal income bracket by $10,000 and make tax-free the first $500
in interest and dividend income for families and $250 for single
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would cut taxes by $135 billion over five years and
$345 billion over 10 years. It would provide tax relief to 110
million taxpayers over all. Of these, 30 million low- and
middle-income would be able to invest tax-free, and 10 million low-
and middle-income taxpayers would not have to pay capital gains
tax, Wexler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am comfortable with this tax cut because it doesn't touch
Social Security money and it reaches people who don't often get a
break from the federal government,'' said Rep. Robert Wexler,
D-Fla., who sponsored the bill along with Rep. Lindsey Graham,
R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill was introduced in the Senate by Sens. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., and Paul Coverdell, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
