A5920 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-ADS-HNS &LR;      05-13 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTOXICATED BY BUD LIGHT'S GAY-THEMED ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE FORD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gay media activists used to excoriate television
news shows for illustrating gay-themed stories with footage
showing, from behind, two anonymous men holding hands on a city
street.
</P>
<P>
   The activists believed such depersonalizing imagery reduced gay
men to negative component parts: held hands, rear ends,
facelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Now, similar imagery _ two muscled arms, one man's hand clasping
another's, all shown from behind _ is gracing print advertisements
intended to sell beer to gay men.
</P>
<P>
   The new Anheuser-Busch ad urges gay beer drinkers to ``Be
yourself and make it a Bud Light.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole idea sounds ground- breaking: Big corporation features
gay men in ads goes against prevailing wisdom that ``queer doesn't
sell.'' Indeed, the ads are controversial. Rev. Jerry Falwell has
called for an Anheuser-Busch boycott.
</P>
<P>
   In the gay community, a flurry of forwarded e-mails the past few
weeks has exhorted gay-friendly folks to phone Anheuser-Busch to
``support'' the ads.
</P>
<P>
   But gays risk looking like chumps. The e-mails hinted the ads
would appear on TV. Wrong. They said the ads would run in
mainstream magazines. Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will appear only in the lesbian and gay print press, and
in specific gay pride parade programs (including San Francisco's).
</P>
<P>
   Armed with misinformation and clouded thinking, gays are
unthinkingly supporting a profit-motivated corporation as it seeks
an improved bottom line. These ads signal nothing more than
clear-eyed corporate calculation. Advertising imagery does not
change peoples' minds; it changes peoples' buying habits. That's
exactly what Anheuser-Busch intends to do.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported a net income of $319 million in the first
quarter of 1999, a 20.3 percent increase over the same period last
year. The company further reported that, as the nation's
top-selling light beer, Bud Light showed double-digit 1998 sales
growth for the seventh straight year. Anheuser-Busch long ago
determined that it is ``safe'' _ read: profitable _ to market Bud
Light to gays.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to the evaporation of social and fiscal pressures
against including gays in ads, the company is stroking gay men by
portraying us _ or at least our hands. After all, we're a coveted
target demographic, one that repays gay-positive advertising
imagery with fierce fealty.
</P>
<P>
   That's no doubt why Anheuser-Busch is one of the principal
sponsors (more than $75,000 in donations) of this June's gay pride
parade in San Francisco. The company is building on previously
established brand loyalty and, in the process, enjoying community
support generated by ad ``controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   But gays pay a price for such loyalty. In the past decade,
several studies have shown that gay men have a disproportionately
higher rate of drug and alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Studies also continue to show a strong correlation between
substance use and HIV infection rates among gay and bisexual men of
all ages and ethnicities. Adherence to HIV therapies can be
affected by substances used as well.
</P>
<P>
   Any company making a profit from alcohol sales in the gay
community _ ``responsible drinking'' exhortations notwithstanding _
is on shaky ground.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, gays are still so starved for positive
representation in the dominant culture that we run the risk of
mistaking consumerist assimilation for respect, advertising imagery
for rights.
</P>
<P>
   We fervently fire off e-mails in support of a consumerist
vehicle designed to vacuum dollars from our community, but where
are we when hot-button gay legislation is up for grabs?
</P>
<P>
   We are taxpaying citizens who can neither marry, serve openly in
the military nor, in some states, legally adopt children. We enjoy
few protections from job and housing discrimination. ``Faggot'' is
still an acceptable epithet on some school playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Gay-themed beer ads running in the gay press are not going to
change that; nor are they going to convince non-gay people to join
us in achieving societal equality.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll save my flag-waving until Anheuser-Busch is willing to
do more than throw a few dollars at a few gay pride parades, and
when company ads show gay men as more than disembodied parts.
</P>
<P>
   When the company finances grassroots gay rights legislative
drives, corporate gays-in-the- workplace seminars and substance
abuse treatment for gay addicts, for example, I'll be impressed.
But as long as the company hijacks gay imagery in the rush to
increase beer sales, it is no more ``progressive'' than any other
multi-billion dollar multinational corporation seeking to enhance
its bottom line. And a gay community that blindly supports the
company implicitly signals that it is willing to settle for second
best.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Examiner contributor Dave Ford lives in San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
