<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-OFFDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Perez, daily grind is a dream
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Braves catcher Eddie Perez has spent the last week
living out his dream of playing every day. Perez has started a
personal high of six consecutive games behind the plate while Javy
Lopez has been home in Puerto Rico because of the death of his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old dream for Perez, one that carried him through nine
years as a backup catcher in the Braves minor league system, when
people around him wondered why he continued to put himself through
the work, only to be disappointed repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was never the hitter that Lopez is. He wasn't the
investment that first-round pick Tyler Houston was. But he found
his own reasons to keep going back to the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd say, `Why do you keep doing this if they don't give you
the chance?' '' said Perez, who will return to the bench when the
Braves open a three-game series with the Cubs today. ``But I always
had it in my mind I wanted to play every day. I never gave up. I
never thought, `I'm tired of this,' not even when I was having
those bad, bad days.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez's first season in Class AA in 1992 he backed up Lopez for
the Greenville Braves team that made the Southern League playoffs.
The next year, Lopez was sent on to AAA Richmond and Perez was back
in AA Greenville. But he had the chance to play every day.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in Greenville, however, Perez learned that
Houston was going to do that, and Perez was asked to play first
base. To make matters worse, Houston got hurt, and the Braves put
another catcher behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I was real down,'' Perez said. ``I said, `That's
it.' I talked to my wife, and she said, `Slow down. Think about
it.' I said OK. I took it easy and kept working out like always.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment passed. And Perez started hitting the ball like he
never had. But then more bad news. He broke his tailbone on a play
at the plate and was out for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He picked himself back up again by playing winter ball in his
native Venezuela and was assigned to AAA Richmond in 1994. He spent
two seasons as a backup there before getting his first call to
Atlanta in September 1995. He was put on the postseason roster for
the 1995 World Series team and has been playing for the Braves ever
since as Lopez's backup, primarily as the catcher for Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I'd make it,'' Perez said. ``I didn't know how. . . .
It was tough. We went through some bad times. But I like the way it
was. In this life, nothing is easy. I don't like to get chances
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez is coming off a career-year when he hit .336 although he
started only 39 games. He's hitting .280 this year and continuing
to do the good defensive work he's known for behind the plate. In
the offseason, he signed a two-year $1.2 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people tell me I need to go somewhere else,'' Perez
said. ``I'm not thinking about that. I'm thinking about here and
playing the best I can. I (still) want to play every day. I've got
to wait like I waited to get here. My chance is going to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez is more grounded in reality lately, given what two of his
closest friends on the team have been through _ Lopez losing his
mother and Andres Galarraga battling cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me realize how important people on this team are, my
life, their lives,'' Perez said. ``I never thought about that.
You'd worry that someone might get traded, but that's nothing like
what we've been through this year. Baseball is not the whole thing.
That's one of the things I really see this year.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
