<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-FEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thompson attempts to take team from ARCA to Winston Cup
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Only five NASCAR owners _ Bill Davis, Rick Hendrick,
Larry McClure, Butch Mock and Jack Roush _ have won races on both
the Busch Grand National and Winston Cup circuits.
</P>
<P>
   So making the jump to Winston Cup from ARCA racing, a notch
below Busch in NASCAR's pecking order, seems nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Mark Thompson of Cartersville, Ga., who hopes
to debut his Phoenix Air Racing team on June 27 in the Winston Cup
race at Sears Point Raceway in Sonoma, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who owns Phoenix Air, a Cartersville company that
specializes in aircraft services, has heard doubts before. In 1992,
the U.S. Navy decided to abandon its naval station on Midway
Islands, two tiny islands about 1,200 miles northwest of Honolulu
and the site of the historic World War II battle.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a test pilot who used the islands' airport to refuel
his planes during military-contract missions, persuaded the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service to let his company manage the islands,
which were turned into a wildlife refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson spent millions of dollars updating the islands'
infrastructure, restoring the old naval barracks and installing
plumbing and a cellular communications systems. Now, Thompson has
140 full-time employees on the islands, which host no more than 100
tourists at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could run quite a few Winston Cup races with what it costs
to run that island,'' Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   Air Phoenix will run only five Cup races this year. After Sears
Point, the team will attempt to qualify at Pocono in July,
Indianapolis and Watkins Glen in August and Homestead in November.
Thompson hopes to run a full schedule next year.
</P>
<P>
   David Murry, 42, a road-course specialist from Lilburn, was
hired as Air Phoenix's driver. Thompson met Murry in 1988 at the
Skip Barber Racing School at Road Atlanta. Murry was one of the
school's instructors; Thompson was a student.
</P>
<P>
   Murry, who earned his reputation driving Porsches, narrowly
missed the field for the Winston Cup race at Watkins Glen in 1995.
He finished two-thousandths of a second behind Rusty Wallace, who
used a provisional to make the race.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson recently purchased three Ford stock cars driven by
Winston Cup veteran Geoffrey Bodine last year, and two ARCA cars
are being converted. They'll shake down the cars at Road Atlanta on
Tuesday, and then test at Watkins Glen June 15-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be just a road-race driver,'' Murry said. ``I
want to be a full-time Cup driver. Obviously, that also entails
driving on ovals. I've done road-racing for so long, it's going to
be a fresh start and a challenge. I want to be in Winston Cup,
because that's where the competition is and that's the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was one of ARCA's top superspeedway drivers before a
crash involving a slower car at Atlanta Motor Speedway in March
1998. He broke an ankle and missed six months of work because of a
head injury. Thompson says owning a team allows him to stay
involved in racing but doesn't put his companies at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
