A5923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SARAZEN-OBIT-COX     05-13 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SARAZEN-OBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sarazen remembered as 'an icon' for golf
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While the golf world mourns Gene Sarazen today after
his death Thursday at age 97 in Naples, Fla., it also celebrates
his life, his accomplishments and the people he touched.
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen, who died from complications with pneumonia, was the
first to win golf's professional Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   He hit ``the shot heard 'round the world'' with the double eagle
at the Masters in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   As the host of ``Shell's Wonderful World of Golf'' in the 1960s,
he took golf all over the globe and into living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   He invented the sand wedge in 1932, allowing people an escape
from golf's deepest bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in golf presume he also invented class.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``The Squire'' and always neatly attired in his
traditional cap and knickers, Sarazen had an impact on golf from
age 20, when he became the youngest player to win the U.S. Open in
1922, to last month, when he made his traditional appearance at the
Masters, hitting a ceremonial first shot with Sam Snead and Byron
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   After helping put Augusta, Ga. and the Masters on the map in the
1930s, he brought his stylish personality and historical presence
from his Marco Island, Fla., home to Chateau Elan, north of
Atlanta, as the namesake of the Sarazen World Open, from 1994
through 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to miss him,'' said Don Panoz, who founded the
tournament to honor Sarazen. ``The world will miss him. The golf
world will miss him. He was an icon for this game. He was the
transition from the old game, which was reserved for a few, to the
new game. . . . I think anybody whose path has been fortunate to
cross his is always better for the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Harrison, N.Y., in 1902, Sarazen won seven major
championships and was the first to win all four Grand Slam
tournaments _ the Masters, the U.S. Open, the British Open and the
PGA Championship. He was the oldest living Ryder Cup player. When
the PGA Tour inaugurated its Lifetime Achievement Award in 1996,
Sarazen was the first recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has lost one of its great heroes,'' PGA Tour
commissioner Tim Finchem said. ``Gene Sarazen dedicated his life to
golf and became one of the game's legendary figures. In addition to
being a Hall of Fame player, he was a wonderful ambassador to the
game throughout his life.''
</P>
<P>
   With Sarazen's passing Thursday, his close friend Ken Venturi
called it ``the end of the hickory-shaft era.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most charming Gene Sarazen stories was first heard a
few years ago from Jim Riddle, an Atlanta golf-course developer
whose father met ``The Squire'' in the 1960s during a corporate
outing at Pinehurst, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks after returning home from the trip, Riddle's
father received a postcard from Japan, where Sarazen was playing in
a tournament. Jim remembered the glow on his father's face when
reading the words from the legendary Sarazen, who expressed his
enjoyment of their meeting.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sarazen World Open came to Chateau Elan in Braselton in
1994, Jim introduced himself to Sarazen and related his father's
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell your father I said hello,'' Sarazen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Jim told Sarazen that his father had died several years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Showing that warm grin and those kind, twinkling eyes, Sarazen,
then 93, said to the son, ``Well, then I'll tell him hello for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen outlived all of his contemporaries and even outlived his
own tournament, which was played for the last time in November.
Despite an attempt by Panoz to continue the event on the European
Tour, the tournament officially completed its run.
</P>
<P>
   At his final Masters appearance on April 8, the crowd around the
first tee at the Augusta National Golf Club was abnormally large,
pushing toward the large oak tree in front of the clubhouse.
Sarazen struck the ball solidly, hitting a drive slightly off to
the right. While hitting the ball often entailed a cortisone shot
to his shoulder two weeks before the Masters, Sarazen never
disappointed the crowd. But, then again, great shots from Sarazen
became expected after the 4-wood that sailed 220 yards into the
hole at Augusta's 15th in 1935 for a double-eagle 2. At age 72,
Sarazen made a hole in one at the 1973 British Open at Royal Troon.
</P>
<P>
   Lon Fellenz, the Sarazen World Open's tournament director,
remembered ``The Squire'' at his happiest in 1994, when he was
riding around in a cart before the first day's play of the
inaugural event. Sarazen had helped design the course with Sam
Snead and Kathy Whitworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a little kid when he saw it the first day, when it
was all set up for the tournament,'' Fellenz said. ``He said,
``Don, you've done all this for me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Sarazen World Open brought ``The Squire'' huge
satisfaction in his later years. And the tournament in turn brought
a new generation of golfers a knowledge of Sarazen _ the player and
the man _ that otherwise might have been hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Fellenz recalled introducing the late Jeff ``Squeeky'' Medlen,
Nick Price's caddie who would die of leukemia the next year, to
Sarazen in 1996. It was Medlen's last event. Fellenz also
remembered once sitting upstairs on the porch of the Augusta
National clubhouse with Sarazen and Herbert Warren Wind, the famous
golf author, and hanging on each word of their many stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, I contributed nothing to the conversation,''
Fellenz said, ``but I damn sure listened. I had breakfast with him
before he hit the first ball, and then I flew back with him on
Don's plane. I guarantee you, if they put that (experience) in an
auction, it would get a pretty big ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Panoz spoke Wednesday with Sarazen in the hospital, describing
him as ``lucid'' and in ``good color.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene knows where he is all the time,'' Panoz said, ``but we
kind of knew the antibiotics weren't working. He told everybody
they were talking too much and that he needed some rest. I figured
it wasn't going to be very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Panoz was returning to Naples on Thursday with Sarazen's
grandson, Geoff, the head professional at Chateau Elan, but they
arrived too late to speak with him again. He died at 9 a.m. at
Naples Community Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lived a full life,'' Panoz said. ``I think in a way we
helped make the last years of his life a lot richer.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
