<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     05-13 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT REVIEWS ON MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in
New York City. (Star) denotes a highly recommended film or series.
Ratings and running times are in parentheses.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``AFTER LIFE,'' starring Arata, Taketoshi Naito and Erika
Oda. Written, directed and edited by Hirokazu Kore-eda (not rated,
118 minutes). Much of this transcendently compassionate, gently
humorous Japanese film is set in a drab office building where
courteous caseworkers welcome the week's new clients.
</P>
<P>
   The place turns out not to be a social service agency but a
metaphysical way station where the newcomers are people of all ages
and types who have just died and have three days to select one
memory to take with them into eternity. Before they depart, those
memories will be filmed. As they tell their stories and make their
choices (those who can't choose remain at the processing center as
caseworkers), the movie becomes a profound meditation on life's
meaning and value and the relationship of movies, memories and
dreams (Stephen Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``ANALYZE THIS,'' starring Robert De Niro, Billy Crystal,
Lisa Kudrow and Chazz Palminteri. Directed by Harold Ramis (R, 110
minutes). The title, concept and teaming of these co-stars are all
funny before the lights go down, so think of this comedy as an
offer you can't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   Cast as a mobster whose confidence is shaken, De Niro is
hilarious simply by playing his role halfway straight, in classic
goodfella style. His mobster finds just the right comic foil in
Crystal as the psychiatrist who utters the immortal, ``When I got
into family therapy, this wasn't the family I had in mind.''
There's a lot more where that came from in this breezy comedy
(Janet Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``COOKIE'S FORTUNE,'' starring Charles S. Dutton, Glenn
Close, Patricia Neal, Julianne Moore and Liv Tyler. Directed by
Robert Altman (PG-13, 118 minutes). What a treat. The sweet
assurance and guerrilla wit of Altman's vintage ensemble films make
a copacetic return with a Southern small-town black comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Seamlessly made and completely enveloping, it tells of the
machinations set off when a wealthy old woman (Ms. Neal) outrages
her diabolically genteel niece (Ms. Close) by committing suicide.
As the old woman's dearest friend and the niece's unwitting
nemesis, Dutton is rock solid and appealing. The entire cast works
on a single wavelength as Altman makes the most of a well-woven
screenplay by Anne Rapp (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE DREAMLIFE OF ANGELS,'' starring Elodie Bouchez and
Natacha Regnier. Directed by Erick Zonca (R, 113 minutes; in French
with English subtitles).
</P>
<P>
   In this very special French film about two freewheeling young
women, their turbulent friendship is frayed by sexual passion and
economic realities. The weaker and more head-turning of the women
(Ms. Regnier) falls for the advances of a rich nightclub owner,
while her fiery friend, played with unforgettable immediacy by Ms.
Bouchez, rages against what she views as imminent disaster.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Zonca shows astonishing acuity in observing how
the women's diverging values affect every aspect of their lives. A
rare and wrenching drama (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``ELECTION,'' starring Matthew Broderick and Reese
Witherspoon. Directed by Alexander Payne (R, 105 minutes). From the
acerbically funny director of ``Citizen Ruth'' comes this caustic
satire of the American electoral process in a high school setting.
</P>
<P>
   Its leading candidate, Tracy Flick, played tartly by Ms.
Witherspoon, has a mother who sought tactical advice for Tracy from
Connie Chung and Elizabeth Dole. Broderick plays the hapless
good-guy teacher who thinks this wicked little front-runner needs
to be stopped. And the hunky newcomer Chris Klein plays Tracy's
reluctant opponent in a style best described as early Keanu.
</P>
<P>
   With a lovely ear for hypocritical conversation, the screenplay
specializes in keeping all the characters a few beats off of what
they actually mean (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``ENTRAPMENT,'' starring Sean Connery and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
Directed by Jon Amiel (PG-13, 105 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This glossy caper film summons the days when being a thief was
the profession of choice among debonair movie heroes. And heroines:
as the great-looking insurance investigator who is supposedly
investigating Connery's glamorous super-burglar, Ms. Zeta-Jones
makes a smashing gymnast and heist expert in her own right.
</P>
<P>
   No need to believe the outlandish details of the story; there's
enough verve and charisma to the stars to make the escapade easy on
the eyes. The action sequence, in which the stars hang off the side
of the world's largest skyscraper, is a vertiginous show stopper.
And here's a nice bonus: nobody gets killed (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``EXISTENZ,'' starring Jennifer Jason Leigh and Jude Law.
Directed by David Cronenberg (R, 90 minutes). Not for Cronenberg
the sleek futuristic look of other films that play virtual reality
games.
</P>
<P>
   This one has the insinuatingly ghoulish hallmarks of other
Cronenberg fever dreams (like ``The Fly,'' ``Crash'' and ``Naked
Lunch''). And it uses them to weirdly enveloping effect as a
renowned game designer (Ms. Leigh) and her wary companion ( Law)
try to play the most dangerous game she has yet created.
</P>
<P>
   This sci-fi scheme is disturbingly effective as it plays its own
mind games with the viewer, complete with a sharp final twist. The
title is pronounced ``eggs-is-tense'' (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``GO,'' starring Sarah Polley, Katie Holmes, Timothy Olyphant,
Taye Diggs, William Fichtner, Scott Wolf and Jay Mohr. Directed by
Doug Liman (R, 100 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This three-episode demimondaine comedy borrows truckloads of
inspiration from ``Pulp Fiction'' but still has some flash and
personality of its own. Liman, who shot the film as well as
directed it, uses a supermarket as ground zero and sends a sullen
cashier (Ms. Polley) out to make a drug deal.
</P>
<P>
   He embellishes this situation fully enough to send his film down
the rabbit hole into neo-Tarantino adventures, some of which (guys
go to Las Vegas, then get into trouble with strippers, gunplay, car
theft and a brake-screeching chase) are a lot more tired than
others. The ensemble cast shows cool comic flair (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``HIDEOUS KINKY,'' starring Kate Winslet. Directed by
Gillies MacKinnon (R, 99 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Winslet knew best when she took on this offbeat, richly
atmospheric adventure in the wake of ``Titanic.'' The leading role
in MacKinnon's vividly colorful film offers her a field day. She
plays a young hippie mother who brings her reluctant British
daughters to Marrakesh, circa 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The film, about the mother's willfulness, the girls' reaction
and the sheer headiness of their surroundings, belongs to the
striking subgenre in which it is baby-boom adults, not their
children, who most need to come of age (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MATRIX,'' starring Keanu Reeves, Laurence Fishburne and
Carrie-Anne Moss. Directed by Andy and Larry Wachowski (R, 120
minutes). The time-traveling story steeped in virtual reality will
be all but incomprehensible to nontechnofreaks. And the film
borrows unapologetically from other sci-fi extravaganzas, with a
big debt to ``The X-Files'' in the paranoia department.
</P>
<P>
   But the storytelling is intricately bizarre and the special
effects are indeed special, notably when it comes to midair martial
arts with a gravity-defying gusto. And Reeves shows that you can
look like a Prada model while behaving like an action hero.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main stars here is Bill Pope, an inventive
cinematographer. He and the Wachowskis provide a couch-potato
epiphany: while the characters seem to be performing marvelous
feats, they're often lying stock-still in the grip of virtual
reality (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MUMMY,'' starring Brendan Fraser Rachel Weisz, Arnold
Vosloo and John Hannah. Directed by Stephen Sommers (PG-13, 134
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   More like a video game than a movie, this incoherent spoof (very
loosely based on the 1932 Boris Karloff horror classic), overloaded
with cheesy special effects, suggests an unwieldy hybrid of
``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' and ``Abbott and Costello Meet the
Mummy'' via ``Night of the Living Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The intrepid adventurers who disturb an ancient Egyptian crypt
that carries a fearful curse are Fraser (playing a swashbuckling
American in the Foreign Legion), Ms. Weisz (as a plucky wide-eyed
English librarian) and John Hannah (as her twitty older brother).
</P>
<P>
   It's all played for laughs. The only scary moments involve
swarming scarabs who burrow under the skin and do awful
``Alien''-like things (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE'' (the Oscar winner for best film,
best original screenplay, best art direction, best costumes and
best comedy score).
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth Paltrow (the best-actress
winner), Geoffrey Rush, Ben Affleck and Judi Dench (best supporting
actress). Directed by John Madden (R, 113 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   A witty, sexy and merrily literate delight, with an
exhilaratingly clever premise that only gets better as the film
unfolds. The screenplay, originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm
and turned by Tom Stoppard into razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of
his ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine
whatever it likes about the link between Shakespeare's artistic
passions and his mad yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, this tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an
Elizabethan theater fraught with the same backbiting and conniving
we enjoy today and has great fun presenting the creation of ``Romeo
and Juliet,'' glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a
fine, tempestuous duo, and she gives the first great, fully
realized starring performance of her career (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THIS IS MY FATHER,'' starring Aidan Quinn, Moya Farrelly and
James Caan. Directed by Paul Quinn (R, 120 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Made with obvious sincerity, this story of a glum Chicago
schoolteacher ( Caan) in search of his more interesting Irish
forebears (Quinn) involves a third Quinn brother as well. And
Declan Quinn's cinematography adds warmth to an atmospheric,
sentimental tale featuring stellar Irish actors (Stephen Rea,
Brendan Gleeson, Colm Meaney) in cameo roles.
</P>
<P>
   Aidan Quinn's sturdy performance, as a lonely farmer in love
with a fiery young lass from a prosperous family, does a lot to
help the film override its hackneyed elements and keep it moving
(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``A WALK ON THE MOON,'' starring Diane Lane, Viggo
Mortensen, Liev Schreiber, Tovah Feldshuh and Anna Paquin. Directed
by Tony Goldwyn (R, 107 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This evocative 1969 period piece, set on the brink of Woodstock
in a Catskills holiday camp, is as seductive as the handsome,
itinerant hippie who turns its heroine's life upside down.
Thoughtfully conceived and movingly acted, it sweeps a housewife
and mother named Pearl Kantrowitz (Ms. Lane) into a torrid
extramarital romance and then weighs the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   With a tenderness that is unusual for a contemporary American
film, it tells an enveloping tale enhanced by artfully selected
Woodstock-era music. Mortensen may strain credulity as the foxiest
blouse salesman in the Catskills, but he certainly does wonders for
the movie (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE WINSLOW BOY,'' starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca
Pidgeon and Jeremy Northam. Written and directed by David Mamet (G,
110 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Terence Rattigan's play, about the 1910 schoolboy's trial that
created a furor in England, has been artfully pared down to its
essentials in this stately and deliberate adaptation. Played with
unusually effective restraint by a fine, meticulous cast, it works
as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the family of a
cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the consequences of
that accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Delhomme's cinematography is beautifully lucid and
painterly. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch acting style sets the
film's tone and gives her suffragist character a sharp edge
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   ``THE SHARPEST GIRL IN TOWN: ANN SOTHERN.'' Long before
``Working Girl,'' Ann Sothern was a feminist icon in the 10 MGM
Maisie films in which she portrayed a working woman getting ahead
in the years of the Depression and World War II. The versatile
actress won wide popularity playing street-smart, wisecracking
characters in musicals, comedies and melodramas.
</P>
<P>
   And now she is being celebrated in a retrospective at the Museum
of Modern Art. At 6 p.m. Friday, she will be seen in one of her
most brilliant dramatic roles, as a career woman, wife and wise
friend in ``A Letter to Three Wives,'' directed by Joseph L.
Mankiewicz, who won an Oscar for his screenplay about three women
who receive a letter from a friend saying she has run off with one
of their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Crain, Linda Darnell, Kirk Douglas and Thelma Ritter play
leading roles. Continuing through Sunday at the Museum of Modern
Art, in Manhattan, the series is free with museum admission: $9.50
for adults; $6.50 for students and people 65 or older; free for
visitors under 16 accompanied by an adult. Pay what you wish on
Fridays from 4:30 to 8:30 p.m. Information and screening times:
(212) 708-9400 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
