<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5944 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     05-13 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY I HATE `SUNSHINE STATE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the final graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lots of people criticized the Florida Legislature for wasting
taxpayers' money debating whether the mockingbird or the scrub jay
should be the official state bird.
</P>
<P>
   I agree. It would have been much better if the Legislature had
wasted taxpayers' money debating whether ``Sunshine State'' should
continue to be Florida's official nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. Sunshine State is not the stupidest nickname
among the 50 states. That distinction would have to go to Rhode
Island, the nickname for which is ``Little Rhody.'' I don't know
who came up with this gem but he or she must have given it all of
three seconds of thought. Presumably, whoever came up with ``Little
Rhody'' found it preferable to ``Insignificant Pip-squeak State
That No One Can Remember'' or ``Lots of Crime for Its Size.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons why Florida should not be called the
Sunshine State. For one thing, it could be construed as false
advertising. There are lots of times when the sun does not shine in
Florida. Nighttime, for example, and during hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a little bit of sunshine can go a long way, as anyone who
has lived through a Florida summer can testify. Come August, many
Floridians would favor renaming their state the ``Please, God, No
More Sunshine State (And While You're at It, See If You Can Do
Something About the Humidity, Too).''
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine causes sunburn and skin cancer, so if we want to be
truthful, we should probably rename Florida the ``Melanoma State,''
though the Chamber of Commerce would probably argue against it on
the grounds that it is not a positive enough image.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine can also lead to cataracts, so we might consider
renaming Florida the ``Eyeball Disease State,'' though the Chamber
of Commerce probably wouldn't go for this one, either.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine is linked to thunderstorms, hurricanes and tornadoes.
It also promotes the growth of plants like ragweed and crabgrass,
not to mention poison ivy.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive sunshine forces us inside to air-conditioned rooms,
requiring us to burn precious fossil fuels that contribute to air
pollution and global warming. (As if it weren't hot enough
already.)
</P>
<P>
   I could go on, but I think we've established that sunshine is
evil and not something we should be crowing about on our license
plates.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part is selecting an alternative nickname because there
are so many good ones to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   We can rule out the ``Show-Me State'' as Missouri has already
claimed that one. (It has never been made clear to me what it is,
exactly, that people from Missouri want us to show them. The money,
perhaps, or maybe something they can't see from there, like the
ocean.)
</P>
<P>
   Also spoken for is the ``Tarheel State,'' the ``Sooner State''
and the ``Hoosier State,'' which is fine with me. (I'll leave it to
columnists in North Carolina, Oklahoma and Indiana to deal with
these ridiculous nicknames; I've got problems of my own.)
</P>
<P>
   Some states use animals in their nicknames (Oregon is the
``Beaver State,'' Wisconsin is the ``Badger State'' and Utah is the
``Beehive State'') and that is a possibility for Florida, too. We
could be the ``Fire Ant State,'' the ``Cockroach State'' or, my
personal favorite, the ``Lovebug State.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas calls itself the ``Natural State,'' though judging by
Bill Clinton's antics it might want to rename itself the ``Au
Natural State.'' Florida might want to start calling itself the
``Naturally Hot and Humid State,'' then again it might not.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois calls itself the ``Prairie State'' for some reason. We
could be the ``Swampy State'' except during times of drought when
we could rename ourselves the ``Up in Smoke State'' or the ``Do You
Smell Something Burning?'' state.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have the space here to examine all the ways that we can
improve on ``Sunshine State'' as Florida's official nickname.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have any suggestions of your own, feel free to send
them to me by one of the means suggested below and I'll use them in
a future column.
</P>
<P>
   Send to: I Hate the Sunshine State
</P>
<P>
   c/o David Grimes
</P>
<P>
   Herald-Tribune
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Drawer 1719, Sarasota, Fla. 34230
</P>
<P>
   Or send a fax to (941) 957-5276. Or send an email to
david.grimes(AT)herald-trib.com
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAD-COMPANY-NYTR &LR;      05-13 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-COMPANY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE AND CHEMISTRY BRINGS BAD COMPANY TOGETHER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BILL DEAN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first performance by the original Bad Company in 18 years
came from a sad note but begins on a high one.
</P>
<P>
   A full-blown reunion tour _ which starts Saturday with a
sold-out concert in Clearwater, Fla. _ was the last thing on
members' minds when they assembled two years ago for the funeral of
their old manager, Peter Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a strange twist of fate, really,'' said guitarist Mick
Ralphs, who formed Bad Company in 1973 with singer Paul Rodgers,
drummer Simon Kirke and bassist Boz Burrell.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Peter, who used to manage Led Zeppelin, passed away, we
all went to pay our respects, and then we met up again,'' Ralphs
said in a telephone interview from his home in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when we all got back together, I could feel the chemistry
was still there between the four of us.''
</P>
<P>
   That same chemistry was evident from the start in the group's
self-titled, 1974 debut album. ``Bad Company'' sold more than 5
million copies and introduced American audiences to the group's
no-frills hard-rock sound.
</P>
<P>
   Revved by Rodgers' gritty vocals and fueled by Ralph's power
chords, the band scored with singles ``Can't Get Enough'' and
``Movin' On.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's 1975 follow-up, ``Straight Shooter'' also hit big in
the United States, unleashing radio staples ``Feel Like Makin'
Love,'' ``Shooting Star'' and ``Good Lovin' Gone Bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad Company's straight-ahead rock approach was the group's
answer to the glitter, glam-rock music by such bands as Mott the
Hoople _ the English group Ralphs left to start Bad Company.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as a British ``supergroup'' from the start, since Rodgers
and Kirke had been in the popular group Free (``All Right Now''),
and Burrell had played with King Crimson, the original Bad Company
recorded four more albums before breaking up in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   While Rodgers formed The Firm with Zeppelin guitarist Jimmy
Page, Ralphs and Kirke joined American vocalist Brian Howe and
others to continue on as revamped ``Bad Company'' through the 1980s
and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Ralphs said the later configurations never captured the magic
like the original. ``It's a strange thing, because I can work with
Simon, I've worked with Boz, like two or three of us at a time, but
when you get all of us together, something just happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even have to be playing. If we're just all in the
same room, I can feel the energy. After all this time, it was still
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Grant's funeral, the four continued to meet to discuss
what tracks would be included in an anthology of the original group
that Elektra Records wanted to release.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, there were still no plans to reunite, Ralphs
said. Then Elektra asked if they could find unreleased songs to
include in the two-disc set.
</P>
<P>
   But with members spread across two continents _ Ralphs in
England, Burrell in Scotland, Rodgers in Canada and Kirke in New
York City _ communication would have taken forever, Ralphs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Paul said, `Well, why don't we just record some new
songs? It would be simpler and quicker,' '' Ralphs said.
</P>
<P>
   The four holed up late last year in a small studio in the
village of Ripley, England (Eric Clapton's hometown) to record four
new songs.
</P>
<P>
   Those songs, including the first single ``Hey, Hey,'' and two
previously unreleased songs from the 1970s, have been packaged with
the group's best-known material in ``The Original Bad Company
Anthology,'' released in March.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Ralphs said, the record company wanted the
original members to tour to support the album. And that's exactly
what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Paul was initially not sure,'' Ralphs said. ``Then he
agreed to do some dates. And then, it blossomed into what is now a
30-date national tour, all over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond that, I don't know. The whole thing with this group is
that nothing is planned,'' Ralphs said. ``In a way, it's
dangerously exciting, because we never planned to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And in a way, it's only fair that we do this, because the
people in America have been so loyal,'' he said. ``It's been
heartwarming.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
