<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, May 14, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Very pleasant weather is expected from the Northeast to the
upper Great Lakes. High pressure crested over eastern Ontario will
circulate very dry air into New England on brisk breezes from the
north. A few clouds will linger over northern Maine; otherwise,
abundant sunshine is likely. The leading edge of drier air should
stretch from Delaware to Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and scattered showers will make it a dull day from
Virginia to South Carolina. Low pressure near Myrtle Beach will
direct much cooler air from the Atlantic into the Southeast. An
active sea breeze in coastal Georgia and western Florida will
promote afternoon thunderstorms inland.
</P>
<P>
   A ribbon of moisture will link the East Coast disturbance with a
developing storm over the northwest Plains. Skies will stay mostly
cloudy from West Virginia across the Ohio Valley and into the upper
Mississippi Valley. Sunshine and seasonably warm conditions will
dominate the central Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
   Humid air streaming northward across Texas will be lifted by a
jet stream disturbance over the Red River Valley. This will trigger
a few strong thunderstorms later in the day. Showers and a few
storms will moisten the Dakotas ahead of a complex cold front. It
will become windy and rather cool in the northern Rockies with some
snow showers.
</P>
<P>
   Brisk onshore winds will direct very cool, moist air into the
Pacific Northwest. Coastal showers are expected with lowering snow
levels in the Cascades. The Southwest will stay sunny and warm, but
some fog will linger at the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Status of Stratus
</P>
<P>
   Low stratus clouds dulled the southern California coast Thursday
as Pacific moisture condensed over chilly coastal waters. Water
temperatures average in the 50s and 60s along the California Coast,
even in summer. Coastal waters owe their chill to prevailing winds
from the northwest, which blow around high pressure over the
Pacific. In turn, winds cause coastal waters to initially move
south. Water then gradually turns west out to sea, deflected by the
effects of the rotating earth. To compensate for water flowing
seaward, chilly water from below ``upwells'' to take its place.
</P>
</TEXT>
