<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-BALLET-MEN-A     05-13 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-BALLET-MEN-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN BALLET THEATER'S MALE DANCERS: RARE CONVERGENCE OF
TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attention must be paid this season to the male
dancers at American Ballet Theater. Rarely has so much talent at
the top come together at one time: like planets converging in the
night sky to symbolize an auspicious future, this cluster of men,
with their virtuosity and diversity of style, has changed the look
of the company.
</P>
<P>
   From Angel Corella, 23, to Julio Bocca, 32, these performers
have given classical dancing, especially in the 19th-century
repertory, a new image. Powerhouse technique has come to the fore
with Bocca, Corella, Ethan Stiefel, 26, Jose Manuel Carreno, 30,
and Joaquin De Luz, 23.
</P>
<P>
   But so has purity of classical style, which receives an extra
dimension from Vladimir Malakhov, 31, whose elegance is echoed by
Maxim Belotserkovsky, 27, and more flamboyantly by Giuseppe Picone,
23. Add the versatility of Keith Roberts, 29, and it all comes down
to sheer dance power.
</P>
<P>
   The effect these days at the Metropolitan Opera House is not
subtle. Multiple pirouettes beyond expectation have become the
norm, frequently topped by the gasp-producing bravura step spliced
suddenly into the air. Academic niceties are nonetheless not
forgotten. The polish and precision that Ballet Theater made its
trademark in the past have been enhanced by this virtuosity. The
new emphasis is on projection, not only in dramatic
characterization but also in movement. Classical technique is
extended, expanded and given its full value.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe in progress will find this development as
natural as achieving the once-daunting four-minute mile. But the
course of male dancing in ballet has hardly followed a straight
line. The Paris Opera Ballet, cradle of professional ballet, had so
little use for its men by 1891 that a member of the National
Assembly, in a budget debate, proposed eliminating the entire male
corps. Bus drivers could do the job when needed, he contended.
</P>
<P>
   What a far cry from the beginning of professional dancing at the
same Paris Opera. During its first decade as a ballet company
(1671-1681), men were the only dancers onstage. Women had taken
part in the court ballets favored by Louis XIV. But when ballet was
transferred to the stage and theatricalized with professionals,
women had to bide their time. In the 19th century, the Age of the
Ballerina, they took their revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ballet Theater, which made its debut in 1940, was for many
years identified with its ballerinas. For many, Ballet Theater will
always be the company that produced Nora Kaye and Alicia Alonso in
the 1940's when it also presented international stars like Alicia
Markova and assorted guest ballerinas. Diana Adams, Melissa Hayden,
Violette Verdy and Janet Reed were at Ballet Theater before they
became principals at the New York City Ballet and in reverse, a
leading Balanchine dancer like Mary Ellen Moylan joined Ballet
Theater in 1950. Major names like Rosella Hightower and Sono Osato
also found a home there.
</P>
<P>
   To think of Ballet Theater in later years is to think of Carla
Fracci, Natalia Makarova, Toni Lander, Cynthia Gregory, Gelsey
Kirkland and Martine van Hamel, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The company's male classical tradition could look back to Anton
Dolin, Igor Youskevitch, Erik Bruhn, Royes Fernandez and later
Fernando Bujones, Kevin McKenzie and, of course, Mikhail
Baryshnikov. Anthony Dowell danced a few seasons, and Bruce Marks
moved easily between classical and contemporary works in which John
Kriza and Hugh Laing, not strictly classical dancers, had fierce
impact.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Baryshnikov in the current top ranks. A dancer of
his caliber and, especially, consistency is hors concours, and the
20th century has seen very few like him. But when Ballet Theater's
dancers perform the leading male role of ``La Bayadere'' this
weekend through May 20, or in a group in ``Le Corsaire'' (May
24-27), their cumulative artistry and technique are felt to
breathtaking effect.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, the company's artistic director and himself a model of
the noble classical style, has accomplished something unusual. No
other company has as many first-rank male dancers in leading roles
at the same time. ``There are more better men; that has to do with
volume,'' McKenzie has said in the past, explaining that he does
not feel women dance less well than men or that great male dancers
have not existed previously. In 1973, for instance, the paragons of
male classical style in the west were certainly Peter Martins and
Helgi Tomasson of City Ballet as well as Rudolf Nureyev and Dowell
at the Royal Ballet. Baryshnikov, who had appeared in London in
1970, was still with the Kirov Ballet in the Soviet Union; he
defected in 1974 and joined Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Today, City Ballet has outstanding dancers, and their training
enables them to dance a Balanchine repertory that Ballet Theater
cannot always master stylistically. Nor are the women at Ballet
Theater to be considered slouches. Too many of the works depend
upon a ballerina. Yet even so, much of the company's repertory
today gives equal time, if not more, to the male dancer.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, he can be a seasoned principal like Gil Boggs
(now in his final season), Guillaume Graffin and Robert Hill; at
this stage, their artistry prevails over pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Angel Corella
</P>
<P>
   But the excitement at Ballet Theater is over young dancers like
Corella, the embodiment of bravura used to artistic purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very strange,'' Corella said, recalling how he began
ballet lessons at 8 in Spain with his older sisters in Colmenar
Viejo, an hour's drive from his native Madrid. ``I had never seen
any kind of dancing, but I knew I wanted to be a dancer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw Corella in his first Ballet Theater season in
1995 could see his sensational potential and talent. The technique
was there but raw. Nonetheless, he could already channel his
exuberance into the precision of Balanchine's ``Theme and
Variations.'' More than anyone, he personifies the joy of dance.
</P>
<P>
   Like virtually all the younger stars, he has worked to refine
and polish his style. He and Stiefel, who made a visible and
overwhelming breakthrough in technique shortly after joining Ballet
Theater in 1997, both rein in their explosiveness to offer deeply
Romantic portrayals as Albrecht in ``Giselle'' (May 28-June 2).
This is normal for Corella.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think dance is in your head,'' he said. ``You have to
visualize what you will go for and then do it.''
</P>
<P>
   After studying in Madrid from age 11 to 15 with Victor Ullate, a
former star of Maurice Bejart's company, and joining Ullate's
company, he acquired an understanding of technique. His trademark
multiple turns come from a straight back and strong stomach
muscles. Yet if Ullate ``told me what dancing was like, he did not
let me use it,'' Corella said. The major influence on him at the
Ullate school was Karemia Moreno, a Cuban teacher who had taught
Carreno. ``She gave me freedom,'' Corella said. ``She pushed me and
believed in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Makarova was on the jury that awarded him the grand prize
and gold medal of the 1994 Paris International Dance Competition.
Corella said she suggested he join Ballet Theater, where he has
since defied conventional thinking about typecasting. Contemporary
choreographers, beginning with Twyla Tharp, have used his dazzling
energy for seemingly superhuman feats, and he has also appeared in
roles that range from the comic to the heroic.
</P>
<P>
   The extra virtuosic dimension comes to him on the moment: ``The
music pushes you up, and when I get that excited I go for it. It's
nice to surprise the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Before performing the very difficult butterfly jumps as a skater
in Frederick Ashton's ``Patineurs,'' he watched skaters on
television. ``I saw that I had to throw the body forward and kick
the legs back afterward. It's a little bit scary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Corella's line is more elegant than when he first arrived,
the credit goes in part to the classes he took for two years with
Stanley Williams and Andrei Kramarevsky at the School of American
Ballet. ``Their classes made me work my legs so that they are more
straight,'' he said. ``I think a lot of it also comes from being at
Ballet Theater. It takes a lot of dancing to become comfortable
onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Corella did a tango with the letter R from a
computer-generated alphabet on ``Sesame Street.'' But at Ballet
Theater he does not feel restricted to one partner or one kind of
role. ``I'm only 23 years old,'' he said. ``If I start seeing
myself in only one way, it's very limiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Stiefel
</P>
<P>
   If most of Ballet Theater's male stars come from abroad (Spain,
Latin America and the former Soviet Union), Stiefel is virtually
the hometown boy who was already too good to make good. He has
become better.
</P>
<P>
   At 16, he joined City Ballet, where he became the all-American
prince. He flashed through the air with rocketlike sleekness, his
perfectly pointed feet elongating a taut line. Cool and
steely-eyed, he could also show the winning boyishness that
emanates now with such grace in his own virtuoso display in ``Les
Patineurs'' and the Romeo he showed off last week. Soviet-style
bravura seemed beyond him: that is, until he molded and willed
himself into the extraordinary dancer he is today.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Bocca
</P>
<P>
   Cult worship in dance is not new. Bocca was its natural target
when he stepped into princely roles as a teen-ager upon joining
Ballet Theater as a principal in 1986. That so young a dancer could
understand ``The Sleeping Beauty'' so well was exceptional. But
then this young Argentine had already won the gold medal at the
1985 International Ballet Competition in Moscow and knew how to use
technique not for its own sake but to define every role.
</P>
<P>
   More than once, he has shown this dancing with a difference. In
``The Merry Widow'' two years ago, the sheer force of his first
eruption onstage brought the ballet up to a higher level of comic
artistry. He knows how to suffer with Alessandra Ferri in
``Giselle,'' too.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Manuel Carreno
</P>
<P>
   Carreno is, like Stiefel and Corella, a dancer who has
transformed himself. When seen previously with the Royal Ballet, he
seemed more a demicaractere dancer than a danseur noble. Yet noble
is what he has become, especially as the prince to Susan Jaffe's
princess in a variety of 19th-century works. He does not need to
act to convey his sensuality; it comes through his pantherine
quality in ``Le Corsaire'' and the soft landings and fluency of his
muscular and classical style.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Malakhov
</P>
<P>
   Malakhov is in a class by himself. No category defines him. What
some might see as eccentricity is a superindividuality.
Shakespeare's Ariel would find him a soul mate, not only because he
has a remarkable gift for staying suspended in space but also
because his mix of purity and mischief leads to surprises. His
amazing classical line and body placement come from the Bolshoi
School in Moscow. He parachuted into Ballet Theater in 1995 and
showed how ``Bayadere'' should be danced. You can see him in it
Saturday afternoon and Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Maxim Belotserkovsky
</P>
<P>
   Belotserkovsky, Malakhov's fellow Ukrainian, was trained at the
Kiev Ballet School, a close runner-up to the Bolshoi School.
McKenzie spotted his potential as a first-class classical dancer in
1994. Along the way, Belotserkovsky has surprised us, notably as a
muscular bare-legged dancer in Nacho Duato's contemporary
``Remanso.'' Tall and Byronic, he radiates good breeding and has
recently improved in his virtuosity, as his wonderful ``Don
Quixote'' shows this season.
</P>
<P>
   Giuseppe Picone
</P>
<P>
   Picone needed only to step onstage as the prince in
``Cinderella'' in 1997 to give Ballet Theater its first genuine
heartthrob in years. Trained initially in his native Naples, he
left Italy to dance in France and with the English National Ballet.
Picone knows that a handsome face is not enough. The matinee idol
appeal works best when his classical technique is in top form,
bursting with flair and flourish in ``Le Corsaire.'' He is sexy and
has a sense of humor onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Roberts
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, with Ballet Theater since 1987, is classed as a
contemporary dancer, but like many graduates of the North Carolina
School of the Arts, he excels in a variety of styles. Lar Lubovitch
and Ms. Tharp have used his outstanding fluency, and he moonlighted
as the main swan in Matthew Bourne's ``Swan Lake'' on Broadway. The
angelic looks help the purity and innocence that Roberts brings to
his questing heroes in ballets like ``The Sleeping Beauty'' and
this season's ``Snow Maiden.''
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin De Luz
</P>
<P>
   De Luz is Spanish, short and a dynamo. Since joining the company
in 1997, he has been concentrating on the precise finishes that
will make his powerful solos even more impressive. Technique
reaches new heights in his dancing.
</P>
<P>
   And as none other than Balanchine once said, ``Technique is
art.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
