<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The latest developments in the
NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia, and the diplomatic efforts to
halt the bombing. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ As Congress continued work on a
pork-laden bill to pay for the Kosovo war, President Clinton on
Thursday welcomed the prospect of having the $11.7 billion measure,
even if it was twice the amount he sought. House-Senate negotiators
were expected to resume work Thursday afternoon. (Malone, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-CAMP _ TIRANA, Albania _ The first American camp opens
in Albania to house 20,000 refugees. First lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton is expected to visit on Friday. Developing. (Roughton, Cox
News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHE _ RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ How Johnny Ringo
decided on the spot that although he, too, could smell gasoline
coming from one of the refueling tankers for Apache attack
helicopters here minutes before a mission, he'd go for it. There
literally wasn't time to check with superiors. And how he got there
in time, with 10 seconds to spare, to refuel the roughly 10 Apaches
as they floated in like black ghosts to meet the Chinook.
(Albright, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-RELOCATE _ ATLANTA _ Iranians, Bosnians and now
Kosovars _ refugees from various conflics keep coming to Atlanta in
significant numbers. Why? Relief agencies send refugees to Atlanta
for much the same reasons that other people move here _ the place
has a lot of jobs available, moderate living expenses, and offers
refugees good hospitality (churches and individuals more willing to
help than in other places). (Oglesby, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/REFUGEES-PROFILES _ ATLANTA _ Six short profiles of recent
refugees who settled here: (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BARRGUNS _ Bob Barr submits legislation to amend the federal
Individuals with Disabilities Education Act so that local school
boards are allowed to expell disabled students who come to school
with guns, weapons, etc. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LEVITT _ WASHINGTON _ Interview with SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt.
(McNaughton, Cox News Service). 25. Also moving in the financial
(f) category
</P>
<P>
   JUDICIARY _ Coverage of House Judiciary committee's hearings on
teen violence following the Littleton shootings. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE _ Results are released of first definitive study of how
many people have lost health insurance as a result of welfare
reform. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RECORD _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush was talking
presidential Wednesday _ but in a private way _ even though he was
in one of the state's most public buildings and talking to a crowd
that included public officials. About halfway through a 10-minute
stand-up briefing to Longview Partnership representatives in Austin
for a two-day visit, Bush abruptly stopped talking when he saw a
reporter from the Longview News-Journal taking notes. Bush, the
state's top elected public official standing in a public office in
the Texas State Capital on the taxpayer's payroll, said all of his
comments were ``off the record.'' (Elswick, Longview News Journal)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LBJ-SYMPOSIUM _ Coverage of the symposium. Today's featured
guests are Julian Bond and Peter Scheslinger. (McLeese, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NRA-FLAP _ ATLANTA _More fallout from NRA's Wayne LaPierre being
invited to state GOP convention next weekend. U.S. Rep. Charlie
Norwood plans to talk to state chair Rustl Paul today about why the
GOP is inviting LaPierre when for the last couple of cycles the NRA
has endorsed top Democrats. Norwood's also demanding answers to
rumors Rusty is going to sign on as an NRA lobbyist when he
finishes his term as state chair. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OLYBRIBES _ Sydney Olympic Committee president Michael Knight
has released personal notes on International Olympic Committee
members made by Australian IOC member Phil Coles that mirror notes
Atlanta bidders made about some of the same members. Both bid
cities noted personal details, relatives and suggested gifts.
Personal details such as marital problems, perceived honesty, even
matters such as smoking, eating and shopping habits, were
documented by Coles, a member of the Sydney bid team. Atlanta
bidders concentrated on relatives, possible gifts and how to issue
multiple invitations to the city. (Turner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UT-PROJECT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ In a meeting in South Texas, the
University of Texas Regents approve $90 million in construction
projects, including a dorm at the UT campus and fire safety
equipment at Jester Dorm that will require a $100 room fee increase
to pay for installment. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW-INTERVIEWS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The state parole board on
Thursday endorsed a plan to personally interview death row inmates
before deciding whether their lives should be spared. The vote,
which came in a meeting of the board's policy panel, is in response
to criticism that the board has not thoughtfully considered
clemency requests and has done most of its work in private. (Ward,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
