<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5965 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-WEXLER-GRAHAM-     05-13 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-WEXLER-GRAHAM-TAXES-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      WEXLER WORKS WITH IMPEACHMENT FOE ON TAX CUTS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ron Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 13 -- Eager to move beyond the partisan rancor
which defined the impeachment saga, U.S. Rep. Lindsey Graham,
R-S.C., has joined a former foe to sponsor a bipartisan tax-cut
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican member of the House Judiciary Committee, Mr. Graham
was one of the 13 trial managers who prosecuted President Clinton
in his trial before the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., also a member of the House
Judiciary Committee but perhaps the most outspoken critic of the
impeachment process, is Mr. Graham's unlikely partner as lead
advocates for the Small Savers Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good signal that we are working together for the
good of the country,'' Mr. Graham said. ``That other stuff is
behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Small Savings Act was originally written by U.S. Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga., and U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who
introduced the bill in the Senate. The bill's goal is to make it
easier for Americans to save money by reducing taxes on savings.
Specifically, it would:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Expand the 15-percent tax bracket to include some people
</P>
<P>
   &UR; currently in the 28- and 31-percent tax brackets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Exclude up to $500 in dividend and interest income from taxes,
</P>
<P>
   &UR; which would, in effect, make the first $10,000 in a savings
</P>
<P>
   &UR; account tax free.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Exempt the first $5,000 in long-term capital gains from taxes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Increase the contribution limits on deductible IRA's from
</P>
<P>
   &UR; $2,000 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Simplify the tax-paying process by allowing more taxpayers to
</P>
<P>
   &UR; file using Form 1040EZ.
</P>
<P>
   ``One third of Americans have no savings and another one third
have less than $3,000. With such a low rate of savings, many people
are not equipped to deal with financial trouble or plan for
retirement,'' Mr. Graham said. ``We're cutting taxes to increase
savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue the Small Savings Act would do nothing to help
those in the working class, or even the lower-middle class. Only
those who had been in a higher tax bracket and those already with
substantial savings accounts would benefit, they claim.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wexler disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Small Savers Act will ensure that 10 million low and
middle class Americans will no longer have to pay capital gains
taxes,'' he said. ``A substantial number of those who will benefit
from this provision are senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a common story from my district: a couple in their
seventies work their whole lives, educate their children, make some
modest investments and then they retire to sunny Florida. After a
few laps in the pool and a couple of games of mahjong, the reality
of life sets in. Now they need the money from their investments for
doctors, prescription drugs and long-term healthcare. Uncle Sam
shouldn't consume the benefit of their modest savings. We're not
talking about millionaires here. We're talking about people to whom
$5,000 means a great deal,'' Mr. Wexler said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Coverdell and Mr. Torricelli have gotten support for their
bill from Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., making it
likely to pass the Senate this year. Mr. Graham and Mr. Wexler have
not yet lobbied leaders in the House, but they plan to use support
in the Senate for leverage. The White House has not yet been
approached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1748EDT &QL; 
