<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5967 &Cx1f; ttj-z
R L &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAST-CABC-HNS &LR;      05-13 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CABC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY RECOMMENDS NEW BREAST CANCER PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Women with a localized breast tumor may need
only to have it cut out _ and not also undergo expensive and
potentially harmful radiation treatments _ to keep the cancer from
recurring, according to a study by National Surgical Adjubant
Breast Project.
</P>
<P>
   The results could prompt doctors to rethink the way they treat
so-called duct carcinomas in situ (DCIS), a noninvasive cancer that
is usually curable. The study was published in the New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnoses of DCIS have grown from fewer than 2 percent of all
breast cancers to nearly 20 percent because of the widespread use
of mammography, which catch the tumors before they become invasive.
Once that happens, radiation and other advanced therapies are
almost always needed.
</P>
<P>
   But prior to that, if surgeons cut away enough of the tumor so
that there is at least a 10 millimeter (two-fifths of an inch)
margin of healthy tissue around it, chances are women won't also
need radiation to keep it from coming back, the study finds. With
smaller margins (between 1 and 9 millimeters), there was only a
slight advantage to radiation treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, standard care is for patients to receive five to six
weeks of radiation treatments, which costs roughly $10,000. A
single course of radiation treatment hasn't been linked to serious
side effects or deaths, but radiation is known to cause some
cancers, and there is concern that exposing women to too much
radiation over their lifetime will harm them. As a result, doctors
will only give a woman one course of radiation therapy; if her
cancer recurs, they switch to other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, which followed 469 patients for eight years, just
3 percent of the women whose tumors had a clear margin of at least
10 millimeters had a recurrence _ whether or not they had radiation
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The current standard for treatment is based partly on
government-funded research done by the National Surgical Adjubant
Breast Project, which found that radiation does help patients with
DCIS.
</P>
<P>
   However, Michael Lagios of St. Mary's Medical Center and
co-author of the latest study said the previous work probably
included many tumors that had become invasive. In those cases,
radiation does help give a better outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the project were unavailable for comment. But in
an editorial in the same issue of the Journal, two doctors at
Vanderbilt University wrote that the study will generate excitement
about the possibility of curing the localized tumors with surgery
alone.
</P>
<P>
   The key to knowing when to forgo radiation is to carefully
examine the excised tissue to make sure the margins are clear all
the way around, Lagios said. For women with low-grade cancers that
show fewer mutations, a margin of less than 10 millimeters _ but at
least 1 millimeter _ is usually good enough, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The process is something like slicing a loaf of bread and
looking for raisins or nuts. By taking more and thinner slices of
the cancer specimen, pathologists can be sure they aren't missing
tiny amounts of invasive cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able with much higher confidence to exclude patients
with invasive carcinoma,'' Lagios said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
