<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NBC-HOMICIDE-NYT &LR;      05-13 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-HOMICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC, CITING ECONOMICS, CANCELS `HOMICIDE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC has canceled its critically celebrated police drama
``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' after seven seasons, the show's
creator, Tom Fontana, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The network, which is to announce its new lineup of programs for
next fall Monday, called Fontana with the news Wednesday night.
``They said it came down to the economics,'' Fontana said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicide,'' never a hit, has slipped further in the ratings
this season, losing about 2 percent of its viewers. It ranked 60th
among all the network shows in prime time this season.
</P>
<P>
   It was, however, among the most critically praised shows of the
past decade, routinely selected as the favorite show by newspaper
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Hollywood executives have said in recent weeks
that ``Homicide'' was a likely target for cancellation because NBC
is enthusiastic about at least four hourlong pilots for shows for
the coming season. The cancellation of ``Homicide'' means at least
one of these shows is likely to inherit its time slot of Friday at
10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Fontana said he received the call from Scott Sassa and Garth
Ancier, the two top executives in NBC's entertainment division.
``They couldn't have neen nicer.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But they pointed out that ``Homicide'' had already completed 122
episodes, more than enough to sell in syndication. ``They weren't
sure how making it 144 would add to its value,'' Fontana said. He
said NBC executives had pointed out that keeping ``Homicide'' going
would cost about $200,000 more per episode than a new drama series.
</P>
<P>
   The show's repeats have already been sold to the Court TV
channel. NBC has an ownership interest in the show, which is
produced by Fontana's company in partnership with Barry Levinson's
Baltimore Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had seven seasons; that's a respectable run,'' Fontana
said. Still, he said, some of the other staff members on the show
were devastated by the news. ``I've been through cancellation
before, when I worked on `St. Elsewhere.' It's like a death in the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the cancellation would have its greatest
impact on the production crew in Baltimore. It was the only
television show produced there.
</P>
<P>
   Fontana said the producers had anticipated the possibility of
cancellation and so he had written a final episode, ``which kind of
ties a lot of things up.'' That will be broadcast Friday, May 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
