<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT A FIGHT, APOLITICAL CANDIDATE IS ELECTED PRESIDENT OF
ITALY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Seeking consensus and political stability, Italy's
Parliament Thursday chose Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi as
the country's new president.
</P>
<P>
   Ciampi, 78, a former prime minister, was chosen by secret ballot
on the first round of voting, only the third presidential candidate
elected so quickly since World war II.
</P>
<P>
   Ciampi's smooth election was a tribute to his unblemished
reputation as a technocrat and senior statesman. But it also
signaled that Italy, eager to hold its own within the European
Monetary Union and anxious about the war in Kosovo nearby, has lost
some of its appetite for back-room politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply moved,'' said Ciampi (pronounced CHAHM-pee) after
his victory was announced. ``I hope I am worthy of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Italians were mostly relieved. For months, the country had been
immersed in speculation about the political intrigue and
horse-trading leading up to the election. On the eve of the voting,
Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema negotiated a consensus candidate in
a flurry of meetings with political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The fiercest last-minute lobbying against Ciampi came not from
the opposition but from D'Alema's own governing coalition _ another
reflection of the fragility of Italian governments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, in what is now seen as the last gasp of the old, deeply
corrupt political elite, it took Parliament nearly two weeks of
tactical feints and oblique lobbying to select Oscar Luigi Scalfaro
as president.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, prime ministers, not presidents, make policy. But
presidents do have the power to dissolve parliament or appoint a
new prime minister when a government collapses.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, politicians of every stripe raced before television
cameras to congratulate themselves on their somewhat novel display
of responsibility and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ciampi is the icon of the establishment,'' Giuliano Ferrara,
editor of a maverick conservative newspaper, Il Foglio, explained.
``There was a great desire at this time to not inflict an ugly
battle on the public, but there was also the fact that the
alternative candidates to Ciampi were so unconvincing and small.''
</P>
<P>
   Ciampi, who served as governor of Italy's Central Bank between
1979 and 1993, earned international respect for his efforts to free
the bank from political control and set its own course on interest
and exchange rate policy. In 1993, Ciampi, who did not belong to
any political party and was untainted by scandal, was pressed to
serve as a caretaker prime minister for eight months. Two
successors recruited him to run Italy's treasury. When Italy
qualified to use the new European currency, the euro, in 1998,
Ciampi was also widely credited with the feat.
</P>
<P>
   His successor at the treasury will be Giuliano Amato, a
respected former prime minister who is now minister of
Institutional Reform.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
