<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FEAR-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA GETS NO CHEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ The Kosovo war has uncapped an eruption of anti-American
sentiments, going far beyond the ideological antagonisms of the
Cold War. It is true, as NATO and U.S. officials keep saying, that
Slobodan Milosevic's villainous treatment of ethnic Albanian
Kosovars has isolated Serbia in much of world opinion. But,
paradoxically, it hasn't made a hero of America.
 &HT;    Conspiracy theories are mushrooming in a bewildering mixture of
supposedly dark American motives, many contradictory, but that
doesn't seem to matter. For some, the United States is supporting
Moslem Kosovars because it wants to destroy Orthodox Christianity
in Europe. And for others, including Middle Easterners, that is
merely a trick to fool Arabs into thinking the United States has no
quarrel with Islam.
 &HT;    Greek Cypriot students attack the U.S. Embassy not only for
bombing Serbia but for having failed to bomb Turkey when its 1974
invasion of northern Cyprus sent Greek-speaking refugees fleeing
south. Not only Chinese students, but people in Belgrade too are
convinced the Chinese embassy was deliberately bombed to show
Beijing how little Washington thought of it.
 &HT;    A French former ambassador, too well-informed for that kind of
coffee-shop nonsense, nonetheless bewailed what he considered the
great new menace of the U.S. ``hyper-power,'' much more dangerous
for the world than the Cold War, he argued, because then the two
giants restrained each other. It is a curious nostalgia for the
frightening nuclear confrontation, imagining that what didn't
happen couldn't have happened whereas now, he said, ``the U.S. can
do anything it wants.''
 &HT;    In Thailand, there are angry demonstrations before the U.S.
embassy, not for Serbia but to show resentment that America prefers
a New Zealander to Supachai Panitchpakdi, the Thai candidate to
take over as director of the World Trade Organization. Many
Russians are convinced that the secret U.S. plan is to take over
the whole world and make satellites of everybody else,
Stalin-style, although elsewhere America's failure to protect human
rights in Africa and Asia shows that it is racist and doesn't care
about others.
 &HT;    Oddly, you don't much hear that, on the contrary, the
protracted, unsuccessful war shows how effective are the limits on
American power, how little the U.S. achieves with its vast means.
Except for some Americans, the assessment of evidence so far is not
what seems obvious incompetence, bad planning, poor judgment and
obsession with high-tech weapons, but proof of rapacious ambition.
 &HT;    There is plenty to criticize, from the peculiar, self-awed
conviction that Milosevic could only be terror-stricken by NATO
threats and therefore cave gracefully as the chorus sang the
finale, to the ridiculous mistake about the perfectly well-known
Belgrade buildings. But leave aside the logic. The illusion, the
perception of power seems to have taken over here.
 &HT;    And it needs to be understood. It isn't so much about the
bombing, the war, the failure to accommodate decently the sudden,
incredible mass of homeless people, as it is a release of feelings,
suspicions, discomforts that were already there.
 &HT;    Partly, the sense of an American threat is an inevitable
reflection of the unique accumulation of strengths at a time of
world transition, when nobody feels sure of their role and their
future. America just looks too overwhelming to be trusted. Every
country uses claws to defend its national interest, but there's a
difference between a pussy cat's scratch and a tiger paw.
 &HT;    Partly, also however, there is an inflated, extravagant fear of
American omnipotence due to the American habit of boasting,
self-promotion, trying to keep up morale with dubious claims of
superiority. ``We are number one,'' was the intoxicating refrain
the late President Ronald Reagan taught Americans to get over the
Vietnam blues. Whether they really believe it or not, others feel
there's a risk that it might prove unpleasantly true.
 &HT;    But the show of force is a charade, destructive but mindless.
B-52 bombers, and even worse $2 billion B-2s, fly 30-hour missions
from the American Midwest with several aerial refuelings to bomb a
Danube bridge or a Belgrade TV station. Washington has forgotten
the B-52s couldn't even stop the bicycle supply train down the Ho
Chi Minh trail. This isn't quite what is needed to keep peace
against thugs.
 &HT;    There will need to be rather some modesty, some willingness to
forego reminding the world of America's might and even a little
extra courtesy if this unpleasant reaction to America is to be
countered. Even American prosperity is something of an insult to
those falling behind. They can't be expected to offer sympathy,
they need it.
 &HT;    Unfair, you say? Well, there is a price for being on top and
trying to make everybody admit it, perhaps worthwhile but still to
be paid.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1999 Flora Lewis 
