<HEADLINE>
NO LABELS FOR BEVERLY HILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This columnist recently wronged the sophisticated
denizens of Beverly Hills by suggesting they might have more money
than brains and therefore fall for a silly stunt proposed by animal
rights extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, common sense and the love of luxe prevailed as the
elite enclave's voters this week overwhelmingly rejected a
so-called truth-in-slaughtering initiative meant to discourage the
purchase of fur coats.
</P>
<P>
   My apologies, beautiful people. You did well. Patricia Nixon may
have scored political points by wearing a cloth coat in the 1950s,
but there's little glory in it these days for anyone who can afford
a nice warm hairy alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would have required fur coats to carry tags
describing the murderous methods by which the pelts might have been
violently separated from their original owners. The labels were to
be symbolic and scary rather than informative. They would not have
specified the actual way the animal was killed _ no retailer or
wholesaler is likely to know that _ but merely would have listed
the most grisly possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The splashy Rodeo Drive social set defeated this nutty idea by
63 percent to 36 percent, even though some well-known Hollywood
stars like Jack Lemmon crusaded on its behalf. Despite the fact
that the fur labeling act was the only measure on the ballot, voter
turnout was unusually high, roughly a quarter of the city's 20,473
registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   It got nearly everybody's attention, all right, inside Beverly
Hills and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   That was the point of the exercise. The animal rights radicals
tried to create a national stir in a city renowned for glamour and
wealth that despite its sunny climate is one of the largest fur
retail markets in the country. If Beverly Hills would fall for this
nonsense, maybe other places would.
</P>
<P>
   A new gimmick was needed. The old tactic of throwing paint on
women bundled in fur coats is wearing thin, to say the least. The
models who had posed for advertisements in the nude pledging never
to wear fur are being seen again on the runways in fur-trimmed
outfits. Setting fires in fur salons produced a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed tags would have warned: ``This product is made with
fur from animals that may have been killed by electrocution,
gassing, neck breaking, poisoning, clubbing, stomping or drowning
and may have been trapped in steel-jaw leg-hold traps.'' As a guilt
trip, it was powerful. As a helpful label, it was useless.
</P>
<P>
   Furriers insist that minks and other fur-bearing animals raised
on farms for their skins are killed humanely with a lethal dose of
painless sodium pentobarbital. The animal rights crowd refuses to
believe the industry and did not bother to include that method on
its proposed labels.
</P>
<P>
   There are some unregulated trappers who capture and perhaps
mutilate animals in the wild to sell their pelts. Nobody really kno
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
