u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BUDGETTHISISTH     05-13 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR MAY
13, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-CABLE. (For the Hollywood Reporter.) The Federal
Communications Commission agreed to exempt analog cable boxes from
rules to make cable boxes available in commercial outlets (300
words). By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-CUSTOMS. U.S. Customs Service Commissioner Raymond W.
Kelly, told a Senate panel today that the agency has had problems
from the start. (350 words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-GRAHAM-COVERDELL-TAX. U.S. Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.,
announced today he is sponsoring a $350 million tax cut proposal.
The Senate version of the plan was sponsored by Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga., and has bipartisan support. (400 words) By Ron
Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA-GUN. Sen. Dick Lugar was one of five Republicans to
support a Democrat proposal to require people who buy guns at gun
shows to undergo background checks. (400 words) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- GUN-ADD. Maine Sens. Susan Collins and Olympia J. Snowe
supported the gun lobby on Wednesday by rejecting a Democratic
proposal to require background checks at gun shows, citing language
in the amendment that would have created a national registry of
people who buy firearms at shows. But because they were unhappy
with a GOP replacement measure that would not have required any new
checks, Snowe, Collins and other moderate Republicans joined forces
with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. today in backing a compromise
measure. By Charles Davant.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- DEFENSE-SPENDING. The Senate Armed Services Committee
today rejected the Clinton administration's request for another
round of military base closures and authorized billions of dollars
of spending in Maine. (300 words). By Charles Davant.
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS-CAMPAIGN-MONEY. House Democrats will not use
President Clinton's impeachment trial as a rallying cry for next
year's elections, choosing instead to highlight a campaign platform
built on issues such as improving health care and saving Social
Security. (400 words). By Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYVANIA-JAIL. Four Kosovo refugees who made it to Fort Dix,
N.J., wound up in Pennsylvania county jails only days later after
being charged with faking their identities to enter the country,
immigration officials said. (500 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-FEINGOLD-TEETH. Citing an extreme shortage of
dentists, Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., introduced legislation
Thursday that would make it easier for people in rural areas to get
access to dental care. (350 words) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-RYAN-LOCKBOX. Janesville Republican Paul Ryan teamed
up with Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, today to introduce legislation
that would make it harder for Congress to use the projected Social
Security and Medicare surplus for other government programs. (350
words) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-SENATE-GUNS. Democratic Sen. Herb Kohl's legislation
requiring every hand gun to be sold with a child safety lock is
scheduled to be voted on today as part of the juvenile crime
package. Will also include comments from Kohl and Sen. Russ
Feingold, D-Wis., on other aspects of bill. (Possible--contingent
on vote) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
