<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPRECIATE-STEINBERG-     05-13 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATE-STEINBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINBERG BROUGHT IMMIGRANT'S VIEW OF AMERICA TO CARTOONING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saul Steinberg, an immigrant penman whose whimsical, dystopian
view of America helped elevate him to the top echelon of
contemporary artists, drawing comparisons to such giants as
Picasso, Miro, and Klee, died Wednesday at his home in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He was 84. The cause of death was not revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Steinberg once commented that ``the doodle is the brooding
of the hand,'' and among 20th-century artist-illustrators there was
no more gifted, prolific doodler than he. Mr. Steinberg created a
galaxy of surrealistic images _ a wholly original visual
vocabulary, in effect _ that embraced everything from modern
architecture to punctuation marks, Mickey Mouse to metaphysics, in
bridging the supposedly unbridgeable chasm between popular culture
and Serious Art.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Steinberg was closely associated with New York City and The
New Yorker throughout his career. Beginning in 1941, he produced 85
covers and more than 640 illustrations for the weekly magazine that
came to define urban sophistication and intellectual panache.
</P>
<P>
   His most celebrated New Yorker cover, an image that was often
parodied, perverted, or transposed to other venues and other
contexts, appeared in March 1976. It depicted the world from a
terminally provincial Manhattanite's perspective, with 9th Avenue
looming in the foreground, the Hudson River flowing by in mid-range
and the rest of the planet _ stretching from New Jersey to China _
squeezed into a space not much bigger than the magazine's logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked it up and thought, oh, how wonderful _ and how
beautiful and, yes, funny,'' author John Updike, another longtime
New Yorker contributor, recalled Thursday. ``The joke wasn't
overstated, it was just there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Steinberg, said Updike, ``created a niche between the world
of cartooning and the world of high art that did not exist before.
You could see the seriousness of his cartooning, the gravitas
behind it, from the very beginning. He was also lucky to have
William Shawn as (the magazine's) editor, because another editor
might have balked at running work of such intellectual
complexity.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like film director Milos Forman, Mr. Steinberg brought a
foreigner's curiosity and a European's formidable intellect to bear
on a postwar America that sometimes seemed designed for, if not by,
his pen and the satirical genius with which he wielded it. Born in
Romania in 1914, the son of a printer and box maker, Mr. Steinberg
studied at the University of Bucharest before moving to Italy,
where he received a doctoral degree in architecture in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Emigrating to the United States in 1942, he gained a
professional foothold at The New Yorker, where his spare, elegantly
linear drawings reflected his deep personal concerns, including
political fascism, overbearing bureaucracy, and brooding questions
of identity. He married in 1943 (Mr. Steinberg is survived by his
wife, the painter Hedda Lindenberg Sterne, from whom he separated
in the 1970s), became a US citizen and joined the Navy during World
War II, where he served in part as an anti-Hitler propagandist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he was included in a show at the Museum of Modern Art,
the first major public recognition of his talent. Among published
collections of Mr. Steinberg's work are ``All in Line'' (1943),
``The Art of Living'' (1949), ``The Passport'' (1954), ``The
Inspector'' (1973), and ``The Discovery of America'' (1993). He
also painted, worked in three-dimensional media, amassed an
impressive collection of works by contemporaries like Picasso, de
Kooning, and Guston, and, in 1973, was himself the subject of a
major Whitney Museum retrospective.
</P>
<P>
   As Mr. Steinberg's cartooning style evolved _ from abstract,
philosophical musings to sendups of government documents and later
to paranoia-fueled snapshots of urban life in which Mickey Mouse
toted an Uzi and hookers wore hot pants cut clear up to their
necklines _ his fame also grew, even if the art world didn't always
know how to categorize him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His drawings are, in a sense, anthologies of art history,''
the critic Hilton Kramer once wrote, citing cubism, expressionism,
pointillism, and primitivism as being only some of the more obvious
influences. Mr. Steinberg, Kramer added, ``sees experience itself
as a parody of experience, with `style' the only reliable clue to
its mysterious gyrations.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been no accident that the most famous Steinberg
drawing appeared in 1976, the year of the American bicentennial.
With the country swept up in a yearlong orgy of
self-congratulation, Mr. Steinberg burst forth with some of his
most wickedly on-target commentary about contemporary society.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that no icon of Americana was immune from his
amusement, from the Easter Bunny to the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
Updike remembers one New Yorker cover from that era that cast Uncle
Sam as matador and a Thanksgiving turkey as the bull. Not exactly
Norman Rockwell holiday sentiment, but then conventional
sentimentality was seldom Mr. Steinberg's calling card. More
typical is a cartoon showing nine fish swimming in a circle, trying
to swallow one another. The fish are labeled ``Facts,'' ``Time,''
``Space,'' ``Noise,'' ``Truth,'' ``Chauvinism,'' ``Taxes,''
``Ambition,'' and ``Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept up with the times,'' Updike noted in paying tribute to
Mr. Steinberg. ``As the urban scene darkened in the '70s and '80s,
you got those crime-ridden, drug-ridden landscapes with the cop
cars blaring and the preflattened pedestrians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``View of the World from 9th Avenue,'' the New Yorker cover that
launched a thousand imitators, was another product of these fecund
times. By 1984, Mr. Steinberg had grown so weary of the copycats
that he sued Columbia Pictures for using the image in an ad
campaign for the film ``Moscow on the Hudson.'' A federal court
agreed with Mr. Steinberg, but by then it was hard to find a city
with a downtown bigger than four square blocks that did not inspire
some bastardized version of Mr. Steinberg's matchless original.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have retired on this painting,'' the artist himself
once mused, sarcastically or painfully it is not clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saul Steinberg was our Picasso, our great original,'' said
current New Yorker editor David Remnick. ``We'll miss his eye, his
line, his language, his wit, and his friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   William Steig, who lives in Boston, has been a New Yorker
mainstay since 1930. Thursday he recalled a trip to France some 50
years ago, where he met up with Mr. Steinberg, his obliging tour
guide. The two artists who opened up the pages of The New Yorker to
what Updike calls ``meditative, introspective cartooning'' had
their own Parisian fling together. They went out sketching, toured
art galleries and museums, and even gambled in the casinos of Monte
Carlo, recalled Steig.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very great artist, tremendously talented. An absolute
original,'' said Steig in a telephone conversation from his Back
Bay apartment. ``Did he influence younger artists? I don't think
so, because Saul is not really imitable. I really can't think of
anyone quite like him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
