<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; tab-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEPTUAGENARIANS'-SPRE     05-13 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEPTUAGENARIANS'-SPREE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEPTUAGENARIANS' SPREE: DRIVING COLORADO'S SAN JUAN LOOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Sales Executive DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Colorado's San Juan Skyway is one of six All-American highways
cited for their superior and stunning scenic beauty.
 &HT;    A pair of septuagenarian friends _ Joan Dunlop and Vesta Foster
_ from Fort Collins, Colo., had a hankering to tour the renowned
mountain loop traversing the state's southwestern corner, and
recently did just that.
 &HT;    The preferred months for seniors traveling to this alpine region
are during the cooler months of June, September and October. For
wildflower buffs, July is prime, while June boasts lovely green
aspens which peak golden come September.
 &HT;    Since weather is always iffy in the mountains, Dunlop and Foster
packed clothes for cool nights and hot days, with layers suitable
for any situation short of a sudden _ and highly unlikely _
blizzard. They brought plenty of high-altitude gear: brimmed hats,
sun screen _ SPF No. 30 _ and water bottles to keep well-hydrated
in the dry air. To avoid altitude sickness (headaches are a common
symptom), Dunlop and Foster limited themselves to one glass of wine
with dinner and advise lowlanders to minimize activities for the
first few days to acclimate to the thin air.
 &HT;    
 ON THE ROAD AGAIN  
 &HT;    Although both Dunlop and Foster normally drive manual sticks,
they rented an automatic for that extra kick, and were happy with
the results when it came to passing lumbering RVs and trucks on
steep inclines. Lucky for agoraphobic Dunlop, her pal Foster is an
experienced mountain driver who didn't mind navigating narrow,
twisty roads with sheer drop-offs.
 &HT;    
 FINE B &AMP; Bs  
 &HT;    The duo found a number of fine bed-and-breakfast inns along the
Skyway. None with elevators, but if stairs pose a problem, they
suggest asking for a first floor room.
 &HT;    To ensure a nightly room, they referenced ''Bed &AMP; Breakfast
Innkeepers of Colorado'' and ''Inns of the San Juan Skyway.'' After
selecting a mutually satisfying accommodation, they called the
inn's 800 number, bypassing the central reservations number
(800/962-2493), preferring the personal touch of speaking with the
innkeepers directly.
 &HT;    The ''Bed &AMP; Breakfast Innkeepers of Colorado'' can be obtained
by calling 800/636-2242. For ''Inns of the San Juan Skyway,'' call
800/962-2493. For maps or tour books, call the San Juan National
Forest at 970/247-4874 or the Uncompahgre National Forest at
970/874-6600. Or visit the website at http://sanjuanskyway.com.
 &HT;    
 DAY ONE  
 &HT;    Ouray, located in a red-walled canyon, was the first stop. It
was late afternoon, and the pair's home for the night was the China
Clipper (800/315-0561), a new Victorian-style house on a hill. Many
steps led to the house, but they parked in back and entered on
ground level where their room was located.
 &HT;    Morning found them hiking to Box Canyon Falls, on the edge of
town. There, they enjoyed a breath-taking of Ouray and its majestic
surrounding peaks. Later, they took a jeep tour of nearby back
roads.
 &HT;    
 DAY TWO  
 &HT;    The Million Dollar Highway _ a continuation of U.S. 550 on the
Skyway _ led them to Silverton which lies at 9,318 feet in a
caldera of a dormant volcano. This former mining town boasts a
summer-population of 550, and a stalwart winter population of less
than 225. Nearby, Old 100 Mine and Mayflower Gold Mill are
worthwhile tours.
 &HT;    On the National Register of Historic Places, the Wyman Hotel
(800/609-7845) has been lovingly restored. However, Dunlop and
Foster discovered the building's pipes and plumbing were less than
silent and highly recommend ear plugs, unless you like the sound of
people showering at 5 a.m.
 &HT;    To take the historic narrow-gauge train between Silverton and
Durango, Dunlop and Foster rode a 7:30 a.m. bus to Durango, then
hopped the 9 o'clock train back t Silverton, arriving at 12:30. By
buying a ticket well in advance, riders can get a seat in a
restored, enclosed, turn-of-the-century car. But if the weather is
good, consider the open gondolas with their unobstructed views of
the Animas River and the bracing perfume of evergreens dotting the
nearby hills.
 &HT;    The Skyway between the Silverton and Durango offers more alpine
vistas. Red cliffs herald Durango on the edge of mountains, the
largest city in the San Juans, with its intriguing mix of
cosmopolitan and cowboy ambiance. South of town is Lightner Creek
Inn (800/268-9804), the movie City Slickers was filmed nearby.
North is Apple Orchard Inn (800/426-0751), with gardens and trout
ponds, and near Trimble Hot Springs for a relaxing soak.
 &HT;    
 TRIP TO TELLURIDE  
 &HT;    Dunlop and Foster elected to visit Mesa Verde en route to
Telluride, taking U.S. 160 to the entrance to the park, where,
rather than worry about parking, they joined a tour of the kivas
and cliff dwellings, lunching at Farview Lodge.
 &HT;    Colorado Route 145 carried them through flat sage lands, slowly
climbing along the Dolores River to the short road into 8,745-foot
high Telluride, another box canyon, with only one way in or out.
Snow peaks rise above the end of Colorado Avenue, the main street.
A sky-blue Victorian, the Alpine Inn (800/707-3344), was their home
that night, where the breakfast sun room looks out on the new
gondola.
 &HT;    The gondola, absolutely free, takes passengers to a corral of
picnic tables and a noontime barbecue, then goes over the mountain
to the posh ski resort, Mountain Village.
 &HT;    On a history tour of town, Dunlop and Foster learned there are
350 miles of mountain tunnels. It was here that Butch Cassidy
robbed his first bank with such successful results, he made bank
robbery his full-time career.
 &HT;    Continuing northwest from Telluride, at Sawpit they tooled up a
steep gravel road to a broad valley for some smashing views of the
San Juan peaks across a meadow of lupines. The road came out onto
CO 62, where they followed the designer fence of Ralph Lauren's
ranch to Ridgway, the site of beautiful Chipeta Sun Lodge, a spa.
 &HT;    Dunlop and Foster's adventurous excursion shows just how easy it
is to discover travel treasures _ right in our own backyards.
 ----- 
 &HT;    For mature travelers it's the best time of life to get up and
go! The aim of this column is to help make it happen. While many of
the bargains and special trips that will be reported on are for
49ers-plus, the information can help younger travelers spot values
too.
 &HT;    Mature travelers should remember that wherever they go, whatever
they do, they should always ask for the senior-citizen discount,
even if one isn't posted. That's one of the main privileges of
being among the ''chronologically gifted'' who are 50 or over. 
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 ----- 
 &HT;     ( The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
 &HT;     c.1999 The Mature Traveler Newsletter  
