<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADBURY-COKE-COX     05-13 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADBURY-COKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Political football' hurdles keep Coke from pushing scrum of
Cadbury-Schweppes buy through
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Coca-Cola's $1.85 billion agreement to purchase
Cadbury Schweppes' brands outside the United States is turning into
an unanticipated game of ``political football,'' a high-ranking
Cadbury official said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the regulatory hurdles preventing the deal from winning
approval in certain countries have been caused by the intensifying
trade disputes between the United States and Europe, said John
Brock, managing director of global beverages for Cadbury Schweppes.
He spoke to reporters about the issue Thursday at the Beverage
Forum/99 conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola wants to buy Cadbury brands in 120 countries,
excluding the United States, France and South Africa. Those brands
include Dr Pepper and Canada Dry, as well as Schweppes' mixers. But
the initial deal has been rejected by antitrust regulators in
Mexico, Australia and Belgium. The companies have submitted a
revised agreement in Australia and hope to do the same in Mexico
and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   On deck are regulators in Germany, Spain, United Kingdom and
Italy. What's more, the European Union is scrutinizing the deal,
even though Coca-Cola and Cadbury question its jurisdiction in the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   While Brock said Cadbury and Coca-Cola expected regulatory
problems, he acknowledged there have been ``more questions than
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is turning into a political football, not just a
regulatory situation,'' Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Randal Donaldson, however, did not agree.
``We would be surprised to know that the Coca-Cola-Cadbury
Schweppes deal is part of any political debate between the European
Union and the U.S. government,'' Donaldson said later in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Several industry analysts attending the conference blamed
Coca-Cola for fumbling its relationships with regulators in some
countries.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, the deal, which was announced last December, is
taking longer to consummate than expected. In fact, it could close
in stages, with Coca-Cola acquiring Cadbury brands in some
geographic areas with others to follow later, said John Sicher,
editor and publisher of Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   Brock said he still expected the deal to ultimately win
regulatory approval. So does Coca-Cola. Five of about 20 nations
that require such approval have given it so far.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, however, expect the deal to have a rough time in about
10 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement must be approved by regulators in ``key markets''
for the overall deal to be completed, Brock said. He would not
identify those markets. But, for example, out of 600 million cases
sold annually by Cadbury outside the United States, 91 million are
sold in Mexico, Sicher said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current obstacles, Brock remained optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll do a mega-deal with Coke,'' he said. But if the
regulators sink the agreement, ``there are plenty of other deals to
do,'' he said. ``The cash that would come from it isn't necessary
for us to go out and do the transactions down the road we'd like to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock said Cadbury agreed to the deal with Coca-Cola because of
the ``significant premium'' the Atlanta-based company was willing
to pay. The premium amounts to 20 times cash flow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Brock said, the brands will get increased
exposure because of Coca-Cola's vast distribution network around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great deal for Coke,'' he said. ``The brands will
certainly fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
