<HEADER>
A6051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BISHER-SARAZEN-CO     05-13 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BISHER-SARAZEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gene Sarazen: 97 years of a wonderful habit
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Somehow or another, I guess I'd never thought of the
world without Gene Sarazen in it. But, after 97 years, we're going
to have to try to get used to being without him. He died in a
hospital in Florida yesterday morning, and this old planet is all
the poorer for it. Not that any of us should be surprised at the
loss of a man nearly a century old, but a 97-year habit isn't easy
to break.
</P>
<P>
   This is the column you've dreaded writing. Inevitable, yes, but
there was something about ``The Squire'' that bespoke permanence.
You never felt age when you were around him. His good humor, his
ready smile, his love affair with golf took care of that. He stood
on the first tee at Augusta National on a dampish Thursday morning
last month and took probably his last swing at a golf ball. There
was no surrender in him.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for the perfect word to describe him, try
``gentleman.'' There was never a more genteel player in the game.
Oh, I'm certain he could turn a fiery phrase or two when he was of
whippersnapper age, but let me tell you, he had a tough row to hoe,
this little Italian kid trying to muscle in on Walter Hagen, Jim
Barnes, Tommy Armour and the big guns of the time. Barnes was the
only player I never heard him speak well of. Barnes had chased him
off the tee in a practice round before the U.S. Open in 1922, a
tournament that Gene would win later that week at the age of 20.
</P>
<P>
   He also won the PGA Championship that year, and again in 1923
and 10 years later. He won the U.S. Open again in 1932, the British
Open the same year, and in 1935 the Masters, first player to win
the four professional majors. It was in the Masters that he struck
what probably is still the most famous golf shot in history, the
double eagle on the 15th hole that forced a playoff he won the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 71, he made his last appearance in competition,
the British Open at Troon, and he still had one more glorious shot
left in his bag. He aced the Postage Stamp hole the first day, the
next day holed out from a bunker for a birdie. That was four
strokes better than Arnold Palmer on the same hole the same two
days.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all history stuff. What Sarazen brought to golf could
not always be measured by the score. As his dear friend Don Panoz
said, ``Sportsmanship, integrity, high standards, strong will and
determination.'' Panoz had just visited his bedside in Florida,
held his hand _ ``his grip was still strong'' _ but he knew the end
was near.
</P>
<P>
   Panoz created the Sarazen World Open to call attention to a man
professional golf seemed to have forgotten. He beat the World Tour
to the draw. He turned The Legends at Chateau Elan into a virtual
shrine to Sarazen. Unfortunately, the PGA Tour didn't share Panoz's
high regard for this pioneer who stood for all the good in golf,
and the Sarazen was wiped out in the new World Tour upheaval. In
February, a letter arrived announcing that the Sarazen World Open
office was officially closed. Within a few months, the tournament
and the man both died.
</P>
<P>
   He was the son of a carpenter named Federico Saraceni, and
changed his name because, he said, ``It sounded more like a
violinist than a golfer.'' He had high times with movie stars,
statesmen, tycoons and mugs, and on the other extreme, found time
to farm and make money at it. And as for the wealth the present-day
professionals enjoy, Sarazen has never uttered an envious word.
</P>
<P>
   He did say a couple of years ago, ``I was checking down the list
of money-winners on the tour last year. The player who ranked 169th
made more than I did in my whole career.'' He never snarled or
sobbed, he laughed. His kind of wealth could not be measured in
money.
</P>
<P>
   No column can properly do justice to Gene Sarazen. Just say
this: The man is dead, but the legend and his legacy shall never
die.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the Sports Editor of The Atlanta Journal,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
