<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSTOMED TO TURMOIL, RUSSIANS TAKE LATEST CRISIS IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ There was a lot of smoke but little debate Thursday in
the employees lounge at the Master and Margarita Hair Salon on
Moscow's busy Garden Ring Road, as two women hairdressers
reluctantly discussed Moscow's latest political crisis during a
cigarette break.
</P>
<P>
   ``What news?'' said Violetta Alekseyevna, a dark-haired
50-year-old, pausing between puffs to consider her views on the
sudden dismissal of former Prime Minister Yevgeni Primakov. ``We
have crises all the time. The government changes all the time. What
leader has ever given me anything, anyway? I live in a village
outside of Moscow, where we don't have gas, or running water.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door in the women's salon, Lena Kovalyova, a 29-year old
client who was having her long blond hair blow dried, shrugged off
talk of a pending vote to impeach President Boris Yeltsin. As far
as she was concerned, none of this week's turbulent events could
hold a handle to the financial collapse of Last August.
</P>
<P>
   Now that, she said, was a real crisis. ``In August, I was upset,
now I'm not,'' she said. ``Then we were all jumping, now we are
not. This doesn't affect common people. If prices go up, it is
unpleasant, but nothing depends on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting used to political crises is now part of the
post-Communist Russian experience. After the attempted coup of
1991, the shelling of the parliament in 1993, the three turnovers
in government in the last 14 months seems tame by comparison. And
Yeltsin's epic battles with his Communist opposition in parliament
have become background noise for many citizens who are still trying
to figure what role they have in Russia's imperfect democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an unclear situation for seven years now,''
said Kirill Kaminsky, 24. ``What can I say? I don't think there
will be a big collapse this time, but even if there is one, people
won't go out onto the streets. People don't pay attention to such
things anymore. They go on with their business.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last several months, poll after poll have shown Primakov
to be Russia's most trusted politician and most people interviewed
after his dismissal Wednesday, agreed that he was worthy of
respect. ``He was decent,'' said Nadezhda, a 29-year-old
hairdresser at another Moscow hair salon. ``That is why they got
rid of him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been shocked by the situation we have been seeing for
some time,'' noted Vitaly Tretyakov, editor of Nezavisimaya Gazeta,
a Moscow daily, interviewed on a radio talk show. ``There is no
confidence in anyone, first of all Yeltsin. Only the government and
Primakov had the people's confidence. Let us wait and see if the
people come out on the streets in support of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Echo Mosky, the same radio station, asked listeners to
call in to say whether they were ready to protest Primakov's
ouster, only 26 percent of 3,4000 callers said they would. ``Not
under any circumstances will I go out on the street,'' said one
elderly woman. ``What's the point?''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that people are indifferent, or that they aren't
worried. Several people talked about their uncertainties, even
fears for the future, about their uneasy feeling that this kind of
political instability can not continue indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is that things not get worse, but my opinion is
that something bad will happen,'' said Sveltana Makutdinova, who
sells bread at the Victor Market, a popular neighborhood grocery
store. ``The ruble will go down again, and price will go up. I
think people's patience is almost exhausted. Everyone is on edge.''
</P>
<P>
   For Tatyan Norkina, a 52-year-old employee at the state
Committee for Land Resources, the worst is never knowing what to
expect. ``Whenever a new minister has to be appointed, we don't
work for a time,'' she said. ``Our ministries keep being united,
then divided. First our committee belongs to one ministry, then
another. We move from one building to another. Right now is sowing
season, but we won't be able to work. We don't have the laws in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Some blame Yeltsin, others blame his advisers. ``I think all
this is the result of Yeltsin's inability to rule the country and
of his fear of competition,'' said Sergei, a 34-year old banker.
``A great deal is done not by him, but by his circle which is
looking for its own dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   All these are disturbing thoughts for people trying to get by on
meager salaries, holding down prices _ a haircut at the Master and
Margarita costs the equivalent of $2.50 _ in order not to lose
customers. ``We don't talk about politics with our clients,'' said
Ms. Alekseyeva. ``We exchange anecdotes or funny situations. People
have so many burdens. They come to the salon to relax, not to solve
global problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
