A6062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SARAZEN-MASTERS-C     05-13 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SARAZEN-MASTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sarazen, Masters had 44-year love affair
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gene Sarazen's ``shot heard 'round the world'' in 1935
put the Masters on the map and ``The Squire'' into the history
books. Sarazen didn't see the ball drop into the hole on his double
eagle at No. 15, but he heard the cheers.
</P>
<P>
   The applause continued for the next 44 years each time Sarazen
set foot on Augusta National Golf Course, where he served as an
honorary starter since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen, who died of pneumonia Thursday at age 97, made his
final appearance at the Masters last month, teeing off with fellow
legends Sam Snead and Byron Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene was a pioneer participant in the Masters tournament and
held a special relationship with Augusta National Golf Club,'' club
chairman Hootie Johnson said in a statement. ``We will miss him
very much next year on the first tee. He was a great champion and
ambassador for golf.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sarazen Bridge, a footbridge across the 15th-hole pond
dedicated in his honor in 1955, serves as a tangible reminder of
the shot Grantland Rice called the greatest in golf.
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen staged the first comeback in Augusta history _ it was
only the second year of the tournament, then known simply as an
invitational for Bobby Jones' friends.
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen was on the 14th green when Craig Wood birdied 18 to take
a three-shot lead. Jones already had drawn up a winner's check for
Wood. According to golf lore, Sarazen's playing partner, Walter
Hagen, turned to him and said, ``Well, I guess that's it, isn't
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sarazen replied, ``I'm not so sure. Some magic can drop from
anywhere.'' Sarazen hit a 4-wood 220 yards _ and got a 2. The ball
flew over the pond, bounced once, rolled to the pin and disappeared
before about two dozen people, including Jones. Sarazen parred the
final three holes, forcing a 36-hole playoff. On a cold, wet
Monday, he beat Wood by five strokes to earn $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a spectacular shot, the one everybody talks about,''
Sarazen later recalled, ``but I take my greatest pride in having
won the U.S. and British Opens in the same year, 1932.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, wherever I go, people say, 'That's the man who got
the double eagle. Actually, it was just a piece of luck. They
forget the championships I won.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen became the first golfer to win all four majors. To his
colleagues, he was not only a great champion, but a treasured
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Venturi lived near Sarazen on Marco Island, Fla., and they
played golf and socialized together.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, Venturi hosted a tournament that was a tribute to
his late wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Sarazen said, 'I'll be there,' and he sat on the first tee
under an umbrella for four hours,'' Venturi said. ``He said he
wouldn't leave because he thought the world of my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after the Masters, Sarazen asked Venturi if he was thinking
of holding another tournament. ``I said, 'No, I couldn't make an
encore, I couldn't duplicate it,''' Venturi said. ``And he said,
'Well I probably won't be here next year anyway.'''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
