<HEADER>
A6063 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEETONIONS-FOOD-AZR &LR;      05-13 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEETONIONS-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET VIDALIA _ GRAND CANYON ONIONS ARE SWEET AND TASTY  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO HAS BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS)  
 (ADV: WITH SWEETSIDE-FOOD) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Have you ever wondered why you never heard of Arizona
sweet onions before there was a festival to promote them? Well,
here's the deal: Arizona sweet onions are not new. Onions grown in
Arizona (begin ital) always (end ital) have been sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural sources say the alkaline soil abundant in Arizona
minimizes production of sulfur, the component that gives rise to
the sting of onions, the reason eyes tear as you chop into onion
cells.
</P>
<P>
   So, how come Arizona onions aren't as famous as their
counterparts from Vidalia, Walla Walla and Maui, to name three
locations whose names are associated with sweet onions?
</P>
<P>
   If Ken Gablin and a large host of volunteer onion enthusiasts
have their way, Grand Canyon Sweet Onions someday may be known as
well as the Texas 1015s and other premium sweet-onion brand names.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Arizona Sweet Onions will be sold in 10-pound bags
for $5 at the 11th annual Sweet Onion Festival at the Rock Springs
Cafe near New River.
</P>
<P>
   Gablin's homemade onion ice cream, made from slowly caramelized
sweet onions and lots of real cream, is a revelation he serves to
curious visitors at his home in Sun City, Ariz. So, how did a
retired entrepreneur get to call himself the King of Sweet Onions?
</P>
<P>
   ``I held my hand up and volunteered one day,'' Gablin said.
</P>
<P>
   An herb enthusiast whose dad's Victory Garden in World War II
was as big as a city block, Gablin had been through the Master
Gardener training at the University of Arizona's Cooperative
Extension Service in Maricopa County. He had worked in the booth at
a sweet-onion festival one year with other master gardeners, who
answered plant and bug questions from the public.
</P>
<P>
   A year and many hours of marketing expertise later, Gablin
became the festival's coordinator and probably the state's premier
expert on the dry-onion crop. The non-profit Grand Canyon Sweet
Onion Corp. was formed to facilitate onion promotion. Gov. Jane Dee
Hull has proclaimed May Grand Canyon Sweet Onion Festival Month.
Like a Johnny Onionseed, Gablin (and the master gardeners) have
given away hundreds of packets of onion seeds and sets at events
and in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who wants free onion seeds, we'll give them to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most people know what a sweet onion is,'' Gablin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, it's an onion sweet enough to bite into like an
apple.
</P>
<P>
   Driving through fields in western Maricopa County planted in
onions, grapes, wheat, corn, roses, artichokes and subdivisions,
Gablin said he envisions a time when onions are grown at all
elevations in the state, so they mature at different times and
extend the spring harvest season of six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is one of the only places you could have sweet onions
from April to October,'' Gablin said.
</P>
<P>
   Dry-onion seeds are planted at desert elevations in October (the
1015 name of Texas sweets refers to their planting date) and
harvested from late April to early June. At higher elevations,
onions are planted as sets and harvested around Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   To get growing, onions are irrigated by sprinklers or
underground tapes in laser-leveled fields. The onion grows in a
curious way: The top of the bulb emerges from the ground as it
swells from the size of a golf ball up to the 4-inch colossal size
sometimes grown for the restaurant blooming onion. When the midline
equator of the onion emerges, the onion is about ready to be
harvested. Irrigation is cut off a couple weeks before harvest
time.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest-crew supervisor Pete Chavez said that when the green
tops of the onions fall over, the onions are ready. Crews flatten
the tops, then flip over the onions, which are left in the field
for five or six days to dry. Chavez supervises 60 to 80 people
clipping onions in a 40-acre field. ``You have to let Mother Nature
take her course,'' Chavez said. ``Take them out too early and
you'll get new growth, and then they'll shrink.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez loves a chopped onion with tomato, cilantro and lemon. He
held up a medium-size union and said, ``This is the best onion for
families. You use it all up in one recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   Onions are graded in the field by size, not sweetness. There is
no sugar standard for sweetness in onions as there is for
cantaloupes and melons in Arizona, said Joe Grencevicz, field
supervisor for citrus fruit and vegetable standardization in the
state's Department of Agriculture. His job is to assure the quality
of produce grown here and coming in from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Grencevicz said, ``as far as the state goes, there is no
standard that says, `This is a sweet onion.' But in Arizona, we do
grow a sweet onion. It's just never been marketed as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now. Grencevicz said he's tasted an Arizona onion next to
a Vidalia onion, ``and you can't tell the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Green onions are grown in Arizona, too, but sweet onions fall
into the category known technically as dry onions. Arizona ranks
fourth nationally in dry spring onion production, after Texas,
California and Georgia, said Lloyd Brown of the state Agriculture
Department Public Information Office.
</P>
<P>
   Grencevicz said, ``Onions always have been a very stable crop in
the state of Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   And the numbers may be going up. In 1997, 2,100 acres of dry
onions were grown here, compared with 1,400 acres in 1993, Brown
said. The crop was worth $9.4 million in 1997, the most recent
statistics available. Like any food crop, the market value each
year can fluctuate due to weather and to yields from other U.S.
onion-producing areas.
</P>
<P>
   From the field, the onions go into 50-pound bags, which for
festival and marketing purposes are broken down into 10-pound bags.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, people come to the onion festival, open their car
trunks, and say ``fill it up,'' Gablin said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most common festival questions Gablin hears is ``What
am I going to do with 10 pounds of onions?'' His wife, Trula,
points out that if you make only an onion pie and French onion
soup, that'll use up the entire bag. Or you can try the recipes we
offer today.
</P>
<P>
   Dry onions store best in a cool, dry area. The best
untraditional way to store sweet onions is to put them in the legs
of old pantyhose, knotted in between each onion. Hang up the hose
legs when they're full, and cut off one onion at a time to use
them. This lets the air circulate and keeps them fresher longer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RECIPES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Onion and Squash Casserole &QL; 
(An Arizona Grown recipe) &QL; 
4 medium yellow squash, cut in 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 medium sweet onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter, divided use
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dry bread crumbs, divided use
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan, combine squash with 1 inch of water. Bring
squash to a boil. Add onion and cook, covered, for 10 minutes or
just until tender. Drain; lightly mash vegetables. Add 1/2
tablespoon butter, 1/2 cup crumbs and remaining ingredients except
cooking spray; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Coat an 8-inch square pan with cooking spray and spoon in squash
mixture. Melt remaining butter and combine with remaining crumbs.
Sprinkle over squash. Bake for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. Approximate values per serving: 96 calories, 3
g fat, 5 mg cholesterol, 15 g carbohydrates, 3 g fiber, 3 g
protein, 208 mg sodium, 27 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Black Bean Salsa(An Arizona Grown recipe) &QL; 
1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large sweet onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 bell peppers, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (15 ounces each) black beans, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in large skillet and saute onion, bell pepper, garlic,
cilantro and salt until vegetables are tender. Add black beans.
Simmer for 20 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings. Approximate values per serving: 255 calories,
1 g fat, 0 cholesterol, 47 g carbohydrates, 12 g fiber, 16 g
protein, 186 mg sodium, 4 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sauteed Onions, Peppers and Corn &QL; 
(An Arizona Grown recipe) &QL; 
1 tablespoon butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sliced sweet onions
</P>
<P>
   1 bell pepper, cut into thin julienne strips
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 large tomato, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces frozen corn, thawed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter in heavy skillet; saute onion, green pepper and
garlic until onion is almost tender, about 10 minutes. Add rest of
ingredients. Cook and stir until hot.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings. Approximate values per serving: 49 calories,
2 g fat, 3 mg cholesterol, 8 g carbohydrates, 1.5 g fiber, 1 g
protein, 62 mg sodium, 33 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Honey Onions &QL; 
(An Arizona Grown recipe) &QL; 
4 medium sweet onions
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tomato juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   Peel onions and cut in half crosswise. Place onion halves, cut
side up, in a 12- by 8- by 2-inch baking dish. Combine remaining
ingredients; stir well. Pour over onions and bake at 350 degrees
for one hour.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. Approximate values per serving: 88 calories, 2
g fat, 5 mg cholesterol, 17 g carbohydrates, 3.8 g fiber, 3 g
protein, 336 mg sodium, 20 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Garlic Salsa Stuffed Sweet Onion &QL; 
(An Arizona Grown Recipe) &QL; 
1 sweet onion
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons salsa
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon non-fat sour cream (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Trim ends of onion, remove outer tough onion skin. Brush onion
top slightly with olive oil. Microwave or bake onion until center
is fork tender, about 3 minutes in microwave. Remove from heat and
cool slightly. While onion cooks and cools, trim, peel and mince
garlic clove. Carefully remove center of cooled onion, leaving an
onion shell at least 2 rings thick. Finely chop the removed onion
center and mix in a bowl with the minced garlic, salsa and Parmesan
cheese. Stuff the mixture into onion shell. Top with additional
salsa, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 325 degrees for 10 to 15 minutes, until heated through.
Serve with non-fat sour cream, if desired. The onions can be
prepared, covered and refrigerated a day before serving up to the
baking time.
</P>
<P>
   Serving is one medium sweet onion per person. Multiply the
ingredients by the number of people you will be serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 serving. Approximate values per serving: 108 calories, 5
g fat, 8 mg cholesterol, 12 g carbohydrates, 4 g fiber, 7 g
protein, 233 mg sodium, 34 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
