<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing Kosovo crisis:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Bielefeld, Germany) _ In a clear sign of the
strains placed on Germany's governing coalition by the Kosovo
conflict, the environmentalist Green party today broke ranks with
its Social Democratic partners and other Western governments by
calling for a ``limited halt'' to the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia.
The Greens, in a stormy and bitterly divisive one-day congress,
rejected a motion calling for an immediate and unconditional
termination of the NATO bombing, a measure that would probably have
brought down the government of the Social Democratic chancellor,
Gerhard Schroeder. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ Acknowledging that Americans were
impatient with the pace of NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia,
President Clinton on Thursday warned against ``refugee fatigue,''
and forcefully retold the stories of Albanians who have been
executed, raped and systematically routed from their homes. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Daily developments on the
military campaign. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-PRESS (Beijing) _ On the role the Chinese media
played in reaction to embassy bombing. Its language was very
reminiscent of old days and many papers printed identical pages of
coverage. But how well and how long and on what issues can this
control really work in a society with access to the Internet and
other communication tools? For instance, at a Foreign Ministry
briefing today, the first question, from a Chinese reporter, was
why officials never mention Serbian ethnic cleansing. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ In an elaborate ceremony at the Great
Hall of the People, China's leaders bestowed the title of
``revolutionary martyr'' today on the three Chinese journalists
killed by NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade last
week. The ceremony conferring one of the Communist Party's highest
honors on the dead appeared intended to bring an emotional close to
the anti-American activity that took over Beijing in recent days, a
rare dovetailing of public sentiment and official purpose. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RIGHTS (Belgrade ) _ Mary Robinson, the U.N. High
Commissioner for Human Rights, was frustrated in her aim to tackle
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on his government's human
rights record, when he refused to see her in Belgrade on Thursday.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
