<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-JAIL-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        FOUR KOSOVO REFUGEES SENT TO PENNSYLVANIA JAILS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 13 -- Four Kosovo refugees have wound up in
Pennsylvania jails, after being charged with using fake identities
to gain entry to the United States, immigration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When the four arrived last week at Fort Dix, N.J., immigration
officials realized their names didn't match identification photos
taken in Macedonia, said Carl Rusnok a spokesman for the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service's Philadelphia regional
office.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, aged 21 and 22 are being held in Carbon County
prison, and a 22-year-old Kosovo woman is in York County prison. A
17-year-old Kosovo girl has been taken to the Berks County youth
center, Rusnok said. Officials will not release their names.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people claimed to be somebody they weren't,'' Rusnok
said. ``Right now we don't know why they used fake identities. I
can't make comments on whether they had criminal records in their
own country or if they were participating in the atrocities in
Kosovo. That's all part of the investigation. We only know they
made it here under false pretenses and the system worked.''
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting immigration hearings to determine if they can
remain in the country, the four refugees have been sent to
``dormitory portions'' of the jail where they are separated from
the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The four refugees were in the second wave of ethnic Albanians
who arrived at McGuire Air Force Base in New Jersey on Friday,
immigration officials said. The U.S. has agreed to take in 20,000
Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, officials announced the adoption of a tightened
screening process to keep participants of the atrocities in Kosovo
from being accepted into the country along with refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, INS officials received special training on how to
identify criminals who may be living among the refugee population.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for The United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees, said the group may provide legal assistance to the four
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy they made it here, escaped the war and
persecution,'' said Panos Moumtzis, a UNHCR spokesman. ``Then they
end up in jail. They have gone through a terrible time and we would
like to see this resolved. But it has been made quite clear that
they were supposed to provide the most complete and accurate
information about their identities. We are still learning details
of the case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
