<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN'S ART IS A FEAST FOR THE SENSES  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Don't visit Virginia Sardi's art exhibition on an
empty stomach. Her work might have you taking a bite out of a
T-shirt or a pair of briefs.
</P>
<P>
   Sardi is a fiber artist whose themes revolve around food. Her
current exhibition at the Barlow &AMP; Straker gallery in Phoenix
simulates a marketplace where bundles of fabric slathered in
barbecue sauce resemble a butcher counter, surgical gauze dyed in
ketchup and wine look like chicken parts, and casings of nylon hose
stuffed with cloth suggest strings of sausages and salamis.
</P>
<P>
   Bring along a yen for unconventional art and a bottle of Tums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food, the subject matter, has been treated at all times in
art,'' says Sardi, a native of Caracas, Venezuela, who has just
earned her master's degree in art from Arizona State University in
Tempe. I use food as a metaphor for many things. It works. It's
connected through emotions. It's a very wide subject that can be
explored from many angles.''
</P>
<P>
   Sardi's master's thesis was an installation titled ``Cravings,''
displayed recently at ASU. The exhibit included the butcher
counter, which sent up waves of barbecue aroma as visitors walked
through the door; Jockey briefs coated with caramelized sugar;
hundreds of rolls of socks dipped in wax to look like bonbons and
cinnamon rolls; the hanging wall of ``sausages''; the chicken
parts; a wall of fabric bundles dipped in caramelized sugar and
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors who signed the exhibit's guest book left tasty
comments:
</P>
<P>
   ``Bravo!!! Stinky Stuff!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty ripe, but I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sensual delight.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sardi's exhibit has been retitled ``Leftovers'' and is
featured at the new Barlow &AMP; Straker gallery.
</P>
<P>
   To purists who crave a Monet or a Rembrandt, Sardi's works will
not be their cup of tea. But food and art are in the eyes of the
beholder. Sardi believes viewers can relate to artwork that evokes
their last meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food can trigger a dream or a memory,'' she says, calling her
exhibit ``an experience of the senses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tactile experience . . . I want them to experience
as if they're in a market, a suggestion of something that can bring
up memories because of the smell.''
</P>
<P>
   In Venezuela, Sardi studied film and theater. Eight years ago,
she took a job at the Venezuelan Embassy in Washington, D.C.,
working as an assistant to the press counselor and cultural
attache.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting Arizona on vacation, she decided to finish her
studies at ASU, impressed with the wide range of the art school's
curriculum, including courses in wood, metal, fibers, photography
and other art media. Sardi initially planned to study photography
and painting. But a class in fiber art taught by Clare Verstegen
persuaded her that textiles were her medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very prone to surfaces and textures,'' Sardi says. ``There
was a place for me to work on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Combining fibers and food seemed a natural: ``I enjoy food. I
love to eat and I love to eat well.''
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan cuisine includes plenty of meat, rice and beans, and
fruits such as plantains. It has been influenced heavily by
Caribbean foods and such European countries as Spain, Italy and
Germany, Sardi says.
</P>
<P>
   When she and her ASU friends get together for a potluck, she
sometimes contributes Chupe, a chicken soup with vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Food is an integral part of culture, Sardi believes. It
celebrates joyful moments and comforts the grieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can give you a lot of pleasure,'' she says. ``It not only
fills a biological necessity. It's not just fuel for survival, but
other necessities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she notes, the act of eating becomes the act of
gluttony. In her artist's statement for the ``Cravings''
exhibition, Sardi says, ``Sugar, creamy, buttery and salty
confections seduce us for immediate pleasure. Sometimes, we cannot
stop devouring until gluttony rises to the level of intoxication.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether her audience sips a little of her exhibit or becomes
intoxicated, Sardi believes her work ``turned out really good.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, it's dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in front of a table stacked with blood-red
representations of meat cuts, she acknowledges that the work can
evoke strong feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could attract you or repel you,'' she says. ``It turns out
to be provocative.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
