<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-APACHE-0514-CO     05-13 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-APACHE-0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARMY PILOTS IN ALBANIA WALK THIN LINE BETWEEN GALLANTRY AND
DEATH DAILY
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: Due to security concerns cited to Cox Newspapers, the
Army would not allow the use of Johnny's last name or military
handle in this story.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0514.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAWK BASE, Albania _ The urgent warning from ``Woot'' cracked
across the intercom, cutting through the thudding sound of the
helicopter blades that had just lifted the 25,000-pound Chinook and
its cargo, thousands of pounds of gasoline, off the ground:
``Suspected fuel leak.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny, the pilot, could smell it, too. He ordered his flight
engineer to quickly check the craft's fittings as the Chinook
hovered only a few feet above the ground. ``Woot'' found a puddle
of liquid on the floor of the chopper. It smelled ``like gas,'' he
said, but he couldn't be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than abort the mission, Johnny rolled the dice. He lifted
the Chinook and its cargo higher into the air and headed out for a
night-time refueling rendezvous with his brothers in arms, the
pilots of Apache gunships, the ``spear point'' for any NATO ground
assault against Serb forces in embattled Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a training mission Wednesday night, but to have
aborted would have been, in Johnny's words, ``a show stopper,'' a
period of down time that would have denied the Apache pilots some
valuable time practicing for a lethal push into threatening terrain
occupied by Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that Johnny's Chinook was able to reach its
destination and his crew roll out hoses from its cargo, the ``Fat
Cow'' bladder of gasoline, just seconds before the Apache gunships
descended vampire-like in the night to suck up the precious fluid
for their continued flight.
</P>
<P>
   The incident at takeoff also underscored how dangerous even
training missions are in this area near the Kosovo frontier -- how
thin the line is between duty and getting blown up. And it
illustrated the many and varied sources of inspiration for the
troops involved in Operation Allied Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision had to be made -- I played the odds on,'' Johnny
said Thursday after having completed the training exercise without
incident or harm to his aircraft and the several dozen paratroopers
riding shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, his craft could have been leaking fuel, but the puddle of
liquid ``Woot'' found could also have been water, he calculated.
``I knew they had just washed the airplane that day, and so I was
hoping it was water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny told the entire crew to stay on the lookout for any fuel
leak as he rumbled across the Albanian terrain to meet up with the
Apaches. If any of them started feeling ``uncomfortable'' with the
circumstances of the mission, he told them, he wanted to know
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll call the mission there,'' he explained. ``But I don't
want to call it when you cannot give me a definite, 'Hey, I got a
fuel leak; I've got my hand in it.' I know what's going on and this
is dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   When soldiers fly with Johnny, ``they have the right to speak
up,'' he explained later. ``That doesn't mean I'm going to listen
to them. That doesn't mean I'm going to take their advice. But if
they are uncomfortable with something, they should damn sure speak
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny -- military censors would only allow the media to use his
first name, say he's in his early 30s and is from Georgia -- has
been flying Chinooks nearly eight years, in Korea and at Hunter
Army Air Field, near Savannah, Ga. He was an instructor pilot with
the ``Big Windy'' Chinook unit in Germany before it was deployed to
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinook, long a U.S. Army fixture, was used for troop
transport in Vietnam, earning the nickname ``Jolly Green.'' But
with NATO reluctant to use ground forces in Kosovo, the Chinook is
helping to keep the Apache gunships flying.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Johnny's job is flying the ``Fat Cow,'' a big heavy metal
bladder that fits in the back of the Chinook. ``If you don't mind
me bragging, it is the biggest, the fastest and the strongest
aircraft the Army has,'' he says of his aircraft. ``And they give
us the mission because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   There's ``a pride thing going'' in the training exercises here,
Johnny admitted. That's one of the reasons he decided against
scrubbing Wednesday night's mission, even after ``Woot,'' the
nickname of his flight engineer, warned of a possible fuel leak.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond pride, there is inspiration, something Johnny found
while growing up in Georgia. ``It was probably from those times
when I used to sneak into the University of Georgia stadium to
watch (football All-American) Herschel(CQ) Walker run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
