<HEADER>
A6090 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-CAMP-0514-COX     05-13 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-CAMP-0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALBANIA'S NEWEST, BIGGEST REFUGEE CAMP IS ALL-AMERICAN
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SENA, Albania _ Two weeks ago, Dave Henrickson surveyed this
south Albanian plain and saw untilled farmland as far as he could
see.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, he saw the beginnings of a village _ just in
time.
</P>
<P>
   As Henrickson's crews scrambled to cut holes in the floors of
rough-hewn outhouses and dump gravel on roads alongside the neat
rows of dark green military tents, the buses came rumbling up.
</P>
<P>
   They carried the first residents of Camp Hope, which is being
built under contract from the U.S. military about 70 miles from the
Albanian capital, Tirana. With an ultimate capacity of 20,000
refugees, it is expected to be the biggest camp in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with the refugee crisis continuing, officials are looking
for land nearby to provide for as many as 60,000 Kosovar Albanians.
More than 400,000 refugees are in Albania, Europe's poorest
country, and government officials fear that number could swell to
more than 700,000.
</P>
<P>
   On the last Saturday in April, Henrickson was mowing his grass
at his home near Cape Canaveral, Fla., when his wife interrupted
him with a phone call. The next day, he was on a plane to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force had selected his company, RMS of Panama City, Fla.
-- a subsidiary of Johnson Controls -- to build the camp on short
order. He declined to give the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The site was on 160 acres of farmland far from the airport in
Tirana and the seaport in Durres. The roads to the site are little
more than joined organized potholes: It takes three kidney bruising
hours to drive the 70 miles from Tirana. It has no electricity or
water. But the site has a rare advantage in Albania: Its ownership
is discernible in a former communist
</P>
<P>
   state in which property issues often frustrate relief
organizations' efforts to assemble large parcels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to call these things 'challenges' rather than
'problems,''' said Henrickson, sitting on the floor of one of the
empty tents, trying to escape the brilliant sunshine for a few
minutes. ``Some of the challenges have been interesting indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the land is rutted for agriculture. Seeking to make
the best of what the land provided, Henrickson's team decided to
put gravel in the ruts to encourage drainage. Unfortunately, in the
first heavy rain, the tents filled with water. The engineers
started over from scratch, raised the camp's surface and are
waiting anxiously for the next heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   The task was also complicated by the marching order that they
use local workers, contractors and materials. Consequently, RMS
engineers went door to door in the nearby town of Fier seeking
anyone who had a bulldozer, truck or knew anything about
construction. In some cases, they had to explain to local
construction companies such capitalistic concepts as competitive
bidding. More than 200 local workers were hired and between 25 and
30
</P>
<P>
   contracts were issued to local firms.
</P>
<P>
   They worked from dawn until dark. ``You know it's pitch black
out here after dark, and someone would have been hurt,'' he said.
When completed, the camp will offer more than 2,000 tents and a
subsistence living. There is a six-month lease on the site -- which
is renewable.
</P>
<P>
   The camp also will face a severe test at the end of this month.
Each spring for decades, this land has been flooded for irrigation.
This year, the flood is scheduled for May 28, but the engineers
hope to divert the water away from the refugees. Even so,
Henrickson said his team will be watching nervously when the
irrigation starts. ``We want to do this right,'' he said, ``or else
we'll have these people living in a mud hole.''
</P>
<P>
   When the buses arrived Thursday morning, the work pace
accelerated from frantic to frenzied. While Camp Hope still
appeared to be more construction site than village, officials said
it was ready enough, given the realities of life for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ready to the degree that it's better than sleeping on the
ground at Kukes,'' said Bob Kobayashi, the Air Force major
overseeing the project.
</P>
<P>
   By the look of the refugees, Camp Hope was a welcome site. One
man from the town of Pec in Kosovo, said his family had been at
Kukes seven days before coming to Fier where he waited three days
before being permitted to come to the camp.
</P>
<P>
   The camp will accept an initial population of 2,500 refugees,
the limit of the daily water supply that can be provided by truck,
said Chris Sykes of Care International, the camp manager. In the
meantime, the engineers are struggling to find another way to
provide the 100,000 gallons a day the refugees will require.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll figure out something,'' said Henrickson, as he rose from
his shady break to get back to village building.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
