<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6094 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TA     05-13 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERNED ABOUT 2000 ELECTION, CLINTON COUNSELS GORE TO ENLIVEN
IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is concerned that Vice President
Al Gore's campaign to succeed him seems to be floundering,
according to several people close to the president. They say
Clinton has personally coached Gore on how to loosen up and appear
less remote and rigid on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   These people emphasized that Clinton, who views the election of
Gore as affirming his own legacy, is by no means alarmed about the
state of the campaign and, like most of the Democratic
establishment, still expects Gore to win his party's nomination.
For its part, the Gore campaign publicly insists that it is on
track, that is has broken fund-raising records and has nailed down
an impressive roster of endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who spoke with Clinton said he has privately
counseled Gore that he would better connect with voters if he tries
to relax _ and even have fun _ on the trail and does not fret that
he might make a mistake. They said he has also suggested that Gore
take a more informal approach by shedding his blue suit more
frequently, plunging into crowds, staying overnight with supporters
in Iowa and New Hampshire and trying to reduce his cumbersome
entourage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is concerned,'' said one person who has spoken to Clinton
about Gore. ``You do not have the feeling that the Gore campaign is
moving in a positive, forceful, determined way to prepare
themselves. But he'll be the first one to tell you that this has a
long way to go and nobody should overreact.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore came closest to publicly acknowledging the troubles by his
abrupt naming this week of Tony Coelho, the former House Democratic
whip, as his campaign chairman. Gore, who had been making many of
the day-to-day political decisions himself _ from his travel
schedule to topics for his speeches _ has relinquished that role to
Coelho.
</P>
<P>
   Another person who spoke directly to Clinton said the president
had urged Gore to turn over control. ``He thinks Gore needs to stop
worrying, he needs to look at the assets he's got, the story he's
got to tell the American people _ and focus on that,'' this person
said. ``He was one of the people who thought he shouldn't be
terribly concerned about who manages the thing on a day-to-day
basis and spend his time instead on what he says to the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who discussed Clinton's concerns for this article included
people who are loyal to Gore and others who support his candidacy
but are not as devoted. The reasons they agreed to interviews _
only on condition of anonymity _ may be multi-faceted: to give a
complete picture of the president's position, to show themselves to
be in the know, and perhaps, to send a public message to the vice
president that he needs to make repairs quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The president has hardly been alone in his worries. A consensus
has emerged among prominent Democrats that the Gore campaign has
had a lackluster start for a variety of reasons: the quick and
unexpected rise of former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey as a
challenger; polls showing that Gore's popularity is not
particularly deep, that he may be damaged by Clinton's scandals and
that he would be easily defeated in a general election by Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas or Elizabeth Dole; a sense that Gore has
deficient campaigning skills and has fumbled with gaffes such as
taking credit for inventing the Internet; a view that he has not
adequately articulated positions, and that he was trying to run his
campaign single-handedly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton monitors Gore's campaign appearances on television and
reads up on the campaign, according to one of the people who spoke
with Clinton. ``He's really into what's going on out there,'' he
said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``He, as well as many
Democrats, is concerned about the polls and that the campaign
seemed to be listless, lacking in enthusiasm. How many times did
you hear people saying there was just no excitement?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Clinton's counsel, James Carville, the strategist
who is close to the president, said, ``I've heard the same thing,
and I think it's good advice.'' Carville added that the president
did not tell him of his conversations with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Gore's aides insist that the campaign is in far better
shape than many people think. They note that Vice President George
Bush had similar problems moving out of President Reagan's shadow
in the 1988 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're the front runner you have everybody, from
virtually every angle and every side taking their shots at you,''
said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman. ``But the bottom line is that
today the vice president is extremely strong. Our fund raising has
been immensely successful. To the extent that you believe in polls,
in the primaries we're exceedingly strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore advisers concede that the vice president had hoped
to keep a low campaign profile throughout the summer but that the
spate of bad notices had led him to try to demonstrate momentum.
For example, the campaign had planned to put off Gore's formal
announcement of candidacy until toward the end of the year, if at
all. But now, Gore's advisers said, they have moved the date to
June or July.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is also pumping resources into an aggressive
behind-the-scenes effort to assure that Gore has a respectable
showing against Bradley in a straw poll being conducted on Saturday
by the Massachusetts Democratic Party. Gore is so mindful of
catering to an important constituency that aides said he overruled
White House and State Department officials and agreed to give an
address to the American-Israel Public Affairs Committee on May 23.
Administration officials had warned that it was risky to give the
speech then because the timing would be awkward after the Israeli
election and just before an expected runoff on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Gore advisers said concerns about his campaign also led Gore
to move fast in hiring Coelho. ``I was shocked when he called me,''
Coelho said of his telephone call from Gore last Wednesday. ``It
was totally out of the blue. But I don't sense any panic or
urgency. What people don't understand is that this is a start-up
business.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting in the vice president's residence on Tuesday, where
Gore introduced Coelho to his top advisers, several participants
said Coelho interrupted the vice president twice and and overruled
him on decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, you're in charge,'' participants quoted Gore as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Sosnik, a top aide to Clinton, said the president
believed that the addition of Coelho ``was a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews, a range of Democratic politicians,
strategists and thinkers cautioned that not everything can be fixed
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gore's closest advisers, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said he was hopeful but not certain that Coelho would
force the vice president to stop micromanaging the campaign. ``The
important thing is not Tony,'' he said. ``The important thing is
that this may signal a willingness on his part to divorce himself
from the mechanics. One of the major problems has been that for
quite some time he has spent too much time being not only the
candidate but being the campaign.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At a closed-door meeting at the Democratic Party headquarters on
Wednesday, Gore's top advisers met with more than 50 House
Democrats to reassure them of the vice president's viability. Craig
Smith, the campaign manager, and others sought to make their case
by distributing polls showing that Gore still holds a sizable lead
over Bradley. But some House members registered a range of
concerns, including their fear that Gore was ignoring key party
constituencies, like minorities and unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would we prefer to be 80 points up right now? Of course,''
said Rep. Bart Gordon of Tennessee, who helped organize the
session. ``But people recognize that the election is a year and a
half away and that we're well positioned and that there's going to
be an ugly Republican primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is well known _ and often ridiculed _ for his uncomfortable
campaign style, but several politicians said the president's advice
sounded appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a natural inclination for a lot of Democrats to say,
`Is there anyone else?''' said Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa, who is
close to Gore. ``And to look for excitement.'' He added, ``Al
Gore's a serious guy, and you've got to show people that you like
what you're doing and you like being out there with them and be
open and have a sense of humor, a sense of proportion. We don't
elect kings in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to the president said he did not believe he should
play an active role in plotting campaign strategy, and that he has
resisted entreaties from some of his aides to involve himself more
directly in the Gore operation.
</P>
<P>
   White House advisers said Hillary Rodham Clinton was also
worried about the Gore campaign, but not as focused on it as the
president. They noted that if Mrs. Clinton runs for Senate from New
York next year, her effort would suffer if Gore runs poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I be happier if Gore were running well ahead of Bush?
The answer is, `Of course I would,''' said Al From, president of
the Democratic Leadership Council, a centrist group. ``I don't
think it's extraordinarily significant but I do think it's an early
warning sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon expressed confidence that once Democrats become realistic
about their expectations they will become more satisfied with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got married last year,'' he said. ``I'm 49 years old, and I
went out with a variety of people. But when you get married, you're
not looking for a rock star. You're looking for, `Who do I want to
spend the rest of my life with?' Sooner or later, he said, ``people
might say, `I'm looking for someone who's dependable, someone who
understands the issues.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
