<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-LAWYER-ART-N     05-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-LAWYER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTREPID LAWYER RISES FOR FIRST KHMER ROUGE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ There is no diploma on the wall of Benson
Samay's law office. But there is something better _ photographs in
which he poses with influential government figures, the best
credential in Cambodia's corrupt and politicized judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   Samay, 56, said he studied law in the United States but did not
earn a degree. He said he graduated from law school here in 1968,
seven years before the Khmer Rouge took power and destroyed
official records like those of universities.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 to 1996, he lived in France and the United States,
where, he said, he worked as a legal assistant, returning here to
take up the practice of law for the first time just three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now Samay, with his pressed court officer's uniform and shock of
black-dyed hair, has become the most prominent lawyer in Cambodia.
He will defend Ta Mok, the first _ and so far the only _ Khmer
Rouge leader to face trial in the deaths of more than a million
people from 1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed that I would take this case, nor did I expect
to be involved in a Khmer Rouge trial,'' Samay said in an interview
in his well-appointed office. ``It was not an easy decision to
make. But I had a professional duty to accept the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ta Mok's hiring of Samay sight unseen raised eyebrows here, and
the selection remains puzzling to several experts. Samay represents
Hun Sen's governing Cambodian People's Party and has been an
adviser to top officials.
</P>
<P>
   His hiring in April was one of the first steps in a process that
has under fire, even before it began, as highly likely to be
professionally inadequate and politically skewed.
</P>
<P>
   The legal system is only beginning to be rebuilt after the
devastation of the Khmer Rouge years, in which virtually all
lawyers were executed. Legal aid groups describe the system as
corrupt and often unfair.
</P>
<P>
   In one telling statistic, 20 of 135 judges have college degrees,
a Justice Ministry official, Seng Syvutha, said recently. In
another indicator, Seng Syvutha said, judges often earn little more
than $10 a month, making them depend on payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   High-profile cases, including recent trials of rivals of Prime
Minister Hun Sen, have been stage managed to produce what legal
experts said were predetermined outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A domestic trial will not be fair, cannot reveal the truth and
does not serve the principles of justice and accountability,''
Amnesty International said in April, supporting a United Nations
call for a trial in an international court.
</P>
<P>
   Even the head of the Cambodian Bar Association, Ang Eng Thong,
commented shortly after Samay's selection, ``A Khmer Rouge trial in
Cambodia cannot be completely impartial, because there is too much
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Samay dismissed the concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had any trouble like this,'' he said. ``Cambodia
should not be prejudiced and stereotyped. And, anyway, this trial
will be different. This will be different, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Samay's account of how Ta Mok chose him drew skepticism
recounted to a top official in the judiciary here. The official
said he believed that someone was ``playing games.'' Underscoring
the politicized nature of judicial affairs, the official insisted
on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   After the two legal aid groups in the country rejected
government requests to supply a defense, arguing that Ta Mok, who
grew rich as a smuggler, did not need their services, the Bar
Association gave the defendant with a member's name.
</P>
<P>
   Ta Mok rejected the name, saying the candidate was too young and
asked instead for Samay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he read about me in the newspapers and he saw my
picture,'' Samay explained. ``Mostly I represent big clients. And
when he saw my name on a list of lawyers, he chose me without ever
meeting me.''
</P>
<P>
   Samay said he was in the process of assembling an international
team of lawyers to defend his client, but appeared to have not yet
reached firm arrangements. He also said it was too early to talk
about what kind of defense he would mount.
</P>
<P>
   Ta Mok, who has a reputation for brutality as a regional leader
and a member of the Khmer Rouge Central Committee, has been charged
so far only with violating a 1994 law against membership in the
radical Communist insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say new statutes must be enacted to allow him to
be prosecuted in Cambodia for international crimes like genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The Documentation Center for Cambodia, which has been assembling
records from the Khmer Rouge era, has turned over 1,000 pages of
documents on Ta Mok to a military prosecutor and Samay.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the center, Youk Chhang, said that Ta Mok's
signature was on many of the documents but that the prosecution
would need to explain the context and the chain of command in order
for this evidence to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome might depend on the defense lawyer,'' Youk Chhang
said. ``Ta Mok had better think carefully about his defense lawyer,
because his life and death might depend on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Samay, along with most of his generation, is a victim of the
Khmer Rouge movement, in which Ta Mok was a leading figure. While
he was in France, the lawyer said, his wife and 12-year-old
daughter returned to Phnom Penh for a visit and were killed by the
Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he could put the personal tragedy aside. Indeed, he
said, he likes his client. ``He likes me,'' Samay said. ``I like
him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Samay hastened to add: ``I don't like him because he is a
killer. I like the way he tells the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   It is another issue that gives Samay pause. ``As you know, this
is a very big case, and in the beginning I didn't know how Ta Mok
would pay me,'' the lawyer said. ``This is the problem. This is the
problem. He said, `I will pay you.' OK. But not yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
