<HEADER>
A6102 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-BOS &LR;      05-13 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ABOUT YELTSIN COMPETENCY   FUEL IMPEACHMENT MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin commands a huge
nuclear arsenal, but sometimes has trouble completing a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He holds sway over the world's largest country, but often
appears confused, childish, and out-of-touch.
</P>
<P>
   He has difficulty walking, but Russia's fate _ as legislators
began an effort to impeach him Thursday _ depends on his next move.
</P>
<P>
   Does Yeltsin know what he is doing?
</P>
<P>
   That was the question on nearly everyone's mind a day after
Yeltsin fired the popular prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov and
replaced him with Sergei Stepashin, a longtime ally who heads of
Russia's police force and interior security army.
</P>
<P>
   The move has outraged lawmakers and set off a government crisis,
sent the ruble plunging and put talks with international lenders on
hold, as well as raising doubts about Moscow's ability to mediate a
settlement between NATO and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Kremlin, which viewed the shakeup as a boost for
economic reform, almost no one sees anything positive coming from
Yeltsin's move. But Kremlin watchers are split in their assessment
of Yeltsin's motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Was Primakov's dismissal a classic power play by a man who
always puts his own political survival above the interests of the
country, a typical move by a president who has repeatedly
undermined his own political and economic reforms with surprise
shakeups, contradictory public statements, and abrupt policy
reversals?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it possible that Yeltsin, an ailing 68 in country where
most men do not live to see 60, may have finally lost it? ``One
theory is that Yeltsin has basically lost touch with reality, and
has begun saying and doing silly things,'' said Alan Rousso, head
of the Carnegie Moscow Center. ``There's enough evidence to sustain
that. But to sleep better at night, I prefer to believe the signs
that he is acting rationally.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens next will depend on the answer. The State Duma, the
lower house of Parliament which heard opening arguments in
impeachment hearings Thursday, will almost certainly vote to
impeach Yeltsin on one of the five charges he faces, that he
illegally waged the 1994-1996 war in Chechnya that killed an
estimated 80,000 Russian citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constitution, that step would deprive Yeltsin of the
right to dissolve the Duma if it rejects his choice to replace
Primakov, as many legislators suggests it will. But the
constitution also says that the president is obliged to disband the
Duma if it rejects his candidate for prime minister three times.
</P>
<P>
   That built-in contradiction raises the possibility of a showdown
outside the law. Russia has a precedent for that _ in 1993, Yeltsin
sent tanks to demolish Parliament after it refused his order to
disband (the Duma Thursday heard arguments over whether to impeach
him for that, too).
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin Thursday said Yeltsin would oppose disbanding the
Duma. But some were unconvinced. If Yeltsin were acting rationally,
why did he not wait for the Duma to vote on impeachment before
sacking Primakov?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dangerous situation, dissolving the Duma would be
deadly for the country, and everything is so unpredictable because
of Yeltsin,'' said Masha Lipman, deputy editor of Itogi magazine,
which recently ran a big expose on the president's poor health.
``It is his health, his body, that is unpredictable. It's not just
that he is an whimsical person _ he never knows when he will be
sick again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks prior to Primakov's dismissal, Yeltsin looked
almost childish during one government meeting when he ordered his
ministers to change seats, an episode that evoked nationwide
ridicule after it was broadcast on television.
</P>
<P>
   Russian viewers never got to see another incident, when Yeltsin
babbled almost incoherently about Yugoslavia during a recent
Kremlin ceremony: His press aides asked local press not to
rebroadcast the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has frequently made public statements his aides have
later rushed to correct. He has confused Scandinavian countries,
mistakenly referred to Japan's nuclear arsenal (it has none), and,
most recently, threatened NATO by suggesting Russia's nuclear
weapons could be re-aimed at Western targets.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, parliamentary leaders said Yeltsin told them
he was proposing another candidate to replace Primakov before a
letter arrived with Stepashin's name on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not know what he said 15 minutes ago,'' remarked
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, who has led the drive to impeach
Yeltsin that resulted in Thursday's hearing and could lead to a
vote as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is again following with fear the unstable gait of
its president,'' the Moscow newspaper Obschaya Gazeta commented.
``Unfortunately, Yeltsin of late is doing worse in handling the
deficiencies of his character.''
</P>
<P>
   Those deficiencies had not mattered so much after Primakov took
office following last summer's economic collapse. As Yeltsin, who
had a quintuple bypass operation in 1996, convalesced with various
ailments, the doughty premier forged an alliance with Parliament
and calmed Russia's restive regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly by avoiding any rash moves, Primakov cooled a financial
meltdown and brought a feeble stability to the economy. Replacing
Yeltsin as the country's day-to-day leader, he earned popularity
that the widely disliked president has not enjoyed since he was
reelected in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov also set in motion corruption investigations that were
closing in on Yeltsin's inner circle, including family members.
Proponents of the theory that the president is acting rationally
say his recent moves make sense _ for Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are rational for the point of view of his vested interest
to preseve power at any price,'' said Yevgeny Volk, head of the
Heritage Foundation's Moscow office. ``He reacts like a cornered
tiger. Unfortunately, he doesn't care about the country, and that's
the tragedy of Russia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
