<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-GATEWAY-BOS </SLUG>
  
 GATEWAY BACKS CMGI with $200 MILLION IN VENTURE CAPITAL  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CMGI Inc., the Andover, Mass. company that invests in Internet
businesses, has $200 million more to work with, thanks to an
investment from personal computer maker Gateway 2000 Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway is buying slightly less than 2 percent of outstanding
CMGI stock as part of a strategic alliance.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego-based Gateway isn't simply looking to hitch a ride on
the soaring value of CMGI stock. Gateway will seek to develop new
Internet-based products and services in cooperation with the dozens
of Internet companies in the CMGI stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gateway is the leading consumer PC manufacturer,'' said CMGI
chairman and CEO David Wetherell. ``The number one reason people
are buying PCs today is to get on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   CMGI holds investments in about 40 companies that provide a
variety of Internet services. Gateway plans to work with those
companies to develop new Internet-based offerings that will help
the company sell more PCs.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reflects a new focus at CMGI on coordinating the
activities of its various Internet investments. ``CMGI is becoming
more and more an operating and a systems integration company for
the Internet,'' said Lior Yahalomi, Gateway's vice president of
business development.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, CMGI can work with its various Internet firms to
create customized products that can be of interest to a variety of
businesses. Gateway is interested in CMGI firms that can further
enhance its existing Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway runs its own Internet service provider for use by owners
of Gateway machines. Yahalomi said that CMGI companies can provide
a number of additional enhancements. For instance, CMGI owns 39
percent of Ancestry.com, which runs a Web site devoted to family
issues. Yahalomi said that Gateway and Ancestry.com may create a
family-friendly service specifically for users of Gateway home
computers.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI owns a majority stake in Navinet, a company that runs a
nationwide dial-up Internet service. Gateway could partner with
Navinet to provide easier Internet access in communities not
directly served by Gateway's own service, said Yahalomi.
</P>
<P>
   With so many CMGI Internet companies, there are many potential
deals to be done. ``We have formed a committee at the highest level
of the company,'' said Yahalomi. ``We are going to meet on a
continuous basis to explore those specific arrangements.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahalomi said the $200 million investment in CMGI will ensure
that Gateway will get first crack at new Internet products and
services developed by CMGI firms.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Mazzucchelli , senior vice president at the investment
firm Gerard Klauer Mattison in New York, said it's no surprise that
Gateway is interested in beefing up its on-line capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gateway specifically has been at the head of the pack at using
the Internet to broaden their product and service offerings,'' he
said. But Mazzucchelli questioned whether the CMGI companies can
actually offer much that would dramatically strengthen Gateway's
position in the market. ``Not a lot of instant solutions leap out
at me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI lost $1 11/16 Thursday and closed at $238 1/16 on the
Nasdaq. Gateway lost $ 9/16 and closed at $67 5/8 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
