<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6112 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CANNOT-DECIDE-     05-13 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CANNOT-DECIDE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO CAN'T DECIDE ON ANYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By JORGE G. CASTANEDA  
 c.1999 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only way to reconcile two terribly contradictory perceptions
about Mexico's current and future prospects circulating today is to
understand how deeply the country has been divided by the process
of change over the past decade and a half.
</P>
<P>
   The cleavages sundering Mexico have created not only two
countries, but two increasingly alienated societies.
</P>
<P>
   A booming export sector, concentrated in and looking to the
north, has taken off. It is competitive, efficient, dynamic and
outward-looking. Its inputs, credit, output and standards are all
U.S.-based.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Mexico _ where more than 80 percent of the nation's
100 million inhabitants live and work _ finds itself sinking into
political fragmentation, economic stagnation and social
dissolution.
</P>
<P>
   The images and assessments arising from these two situations are
both accurate: The aggregate economic numbers, heavily influenced
by the export sector, are improving constantly; the pessimism and
chaos pervading the rest of the country reflect the growing
intractability of Mexico's underlying problems.
</P>
<P>
   The most characteristic and worrisome among them is that it is
virtually impossible for the country to agree on anything. For
decades _ if not for centuries _ Mexico lived under a regime of
consensus: mostly imposed through authoritarian means, on occasion
freely consented. But gridlock, whether it be regional, political
or social impasses, were infrequent, if not totally absent.
Mexicans agreed, or were forced to agree, on most issues facing the
country.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the Carlos Salinas administration, Mexico carried
out dramatic changes in its development plans and policies without
serious dissent, or in any case without experiencing severe
consequences when silencing dissent through governmental nastiness
or heavy-handedness.
</P>
<P>
   This trend, which for better or for worse allowed the country to
experience half a century of political stability, economic growth
and social modernization, has obviously come to an end. As Mexico
enters the first truly uncertain presidential election in its
history, the country seems singularly devoid of any capacity or
inclination to agree on any conceivable question, important or
trivial.
</P>
<P>
   The examples are countless and revealing, and they range from
the truly substantive to the symbolic. Among the latter, the most
symptomatic are perhaps those related to the Power and Light
privatization project submitted by the government to the Congress a
couple of months ago, and the proposal to charge modest tuition
fees at the National University to those students able to pay.
</P>
<P>
   On both counts the proposals are arguable and reasonable;
sensible people can dislike them or find them beneficial for the
country. But instead of arousing a serious debate and negotiation
from which a long-term national consensus would emerge _ in one
direction or another _ the two initiatives have awakened passions
and fanned the flames of social discontent.
</P>
<P>
   This month's Mayday demonstrations were the most
anti-government, intense and well-attended in years. The
possibility of reaching closure and convergence is more remote than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the inability to decide has affected apparently minor
affairs. One involves time zones in the country, and the absurd
debate that took place in late March as to who would adopt daylight
savings time, and who would not, and why.
</P>
<P>
   As of now, some Mexican states adopted the hour change, and
others did not; some are on U.S. Central Time, some on Rocky
Mountain Time and some on Pacific Time, while the one that used to
go by Eastern Time _ Quintana Roo, where Cancun is located, decided
to go back to Central Time, perhaps because the drug traffickers
found it more accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   While Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas wisely desisted from
heeding the calls of his rank-and-file and accepted the federal
government's decision to move clocks forward on April 1, it was
touch and go for several days, in the capital and in Guadalajara,
the country's second largest city. The country cannot even agree,
literally, on the time of day.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can it figure out what to do with the 2 million, or perhaps
even 3 million, imported used cars circulating without valid
license plates, registration cards, insurance or inspection
controls. They were brought in over the years by migrants returning
from the United States, or by border state inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   All of these mostly dilapidated vehicles entered Mexico with
temporary importation permits; they paid no taxes on entry, nor any
property levies like all other cars and trucks pay in Mexico. They
have all outstayed their welcome and their authorization. The local
automobile industry is up in arms over the prospect of regularizing
these imports. The inhabitants of the northern cities where they
are largely concentrated want some sort of amnesty and
after-the-fact legalization.
</P>
<P>
   The government is caught in a vicious cross-fire between
hundreds of thousands of owners who cannot afford the much more
expensive used cars available in Mexico, and others who feel
punished for having purchased their vehicles in Mexico and obeying
the law. The likelihood of any agreement in the near future is
close to nil.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's surprising macro-economic numbers are neither imaginary
nor artificial. But they cannot blot out the collapsing national
consensus on any issue of substance, in a country where, since time
immemorial, centrifugal forces have always threatened Mexican
cohesion. More than lower interest rates, higher exports, or more
foreign investment _ all necessary and desirable, of course _
Mexico today needs to craft the instruments for constructing new
broad agreements on at least basic matters, whether decisive or
inconsequential. Today it disagrees on both.
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
