<HEADER>
A6113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-WEBSITE-COX     05-13 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-WEBSITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Menace' site run by local teacher
 &HT;    By David Thomas
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Star Wars is a hobby for some and an
obsession for others. For Robert Beasley, it's both.
</P>
<P>
   The English teacher at Port St. Lucie High School runs Prequel
Watch, a Web site dedicated to listing every scrap of information
related to the newest installment in the cinematic space saga.
</P>
<P>
   Under the JediNet.com home page, Web surfers can find Beasley's
obsession and love. After abandoning his own Web site, Dunesea.com,
because of server difficulties, Beasley was asked by JediNet's
Webmaster John Benson to help with the Prequel Watch page. Months
later, Beasley has found himself in front of CBS news cameras and
mentioned in countless publications. All awash in search of Phantom
Menace information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I update the site 10 times or more a day,'' Beasley
admitted. Prequel Watch has been getting 25,000 hits a day
regularly, something unheard of for a fan-run site. But what
surprised Beasley the most when he began working on the page was
how much information people actually sent him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my students are really into the movie. They bring me
articles from magazines all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   People send faxes, too. ``The coolest fax came in July of 1997,
and we didn't post it until January. It contained a three-page plot
synopsis, character sketches, character bios. It turned out to be a
30-page fax. I just thought it was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Beasley also got faxes from anonymous Hasbro sources about the
line of toys made in conjunction with the movie. The faxes never
had a return number or name. On the flip side, he also gets e-mail
from disgruntled fans unhappy that they learned more than they
wanted to know on his site. (Beasley says his page warns of such
``spoilers.'')
</P>
<P>
   The cloak and dagger antics are finally coming to a close,
though. Since the novelization of the movie was released last week,
there's no possibility for Prequel Watch to reveal anything new
about Phantom Menace before it opens on Wednesday. But Beasley
still has much to do.
</P>
<P>
   On May 20, he and his partners at Prequel Watch begin counting
down to Episode Two, which comes out in 2002. Beasley has already
confirmed some news on the film. He knows that Lucas will direct
the movie and the primary filming will move from London to
Australia. He and his partners will spend the next three years
searching for even more tidbits.
</P>
<P>
   Has all the insider information spoiled the fan? ``I bought the
book and read it that night. Afterward I was kicking myself,''
Beasley lamented. But he brightened when asked about the most
exciting moment since he began working on Prequel Watch. He
remembers the rush of Nov. 11, when the first coming attractions
trailer hit theaters. ``I knew Star Wars was back!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, on Wednesday, Beasley will be at the theater watching
the full length version of the film. Not clips, not trailers, not
behind-the-scenes footage, but the real deal. ``I'm just going to
watch it, watch it, watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
