<HEADER>
A6115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-NYT &LR;      05-13 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN'S MOVES MAY WORSEN RUSSIA'S ECONOMIC SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin's decision to dismiss his
Cabinet may deepen Russia's economic troubles by jeopardizing a
badly needed loan-refinancing program from the International
Monetary Fund and negotiations with other foreign creditors.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Russia was supposed to repay the IMF about $4 billion
and sovereign lenders and commercial banks about $17 billion. But
after the economy collapsed last summer, Russia effectively
defaulted on much of its foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the Cabinet of the now-ousted prime minister,
Yevgeny Primakov, and the IMF had spent the last few months
developing an economic program and tied it to a critical
refinancing agreement, announced in Washington late last month. The
IMF deal, in turn, gave Russia the credibility to renegotiate its
debts with other creditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has made the IMF program far more uncertain,'' Roland
Nash, chief economist with MFK Renaissance, a brokerage firm here,
said Thursday. ``It looked like the IMF and Primakov had struck
some sort of deal. Even then, the IMF bent over backward to release
the credits.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank has already suspended a $3 billion loan for
Russia that is tied to the IMF agreement. ``We were just about to
try and conclude our arrangements for a $3 billion package,'' the
World Bank's president, James D. Wolfensohn, said in Washington.
``But now we don't have a government to deal with, and, until there
is a new government, clearly there is nothing more we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The political turmoil caused the ruble to fall 3.9 percent
against the dollar in foreign-exchange trading Thursday, its second
consecutive big drop. Russian stock prices rebounded 2.7 percent
after a 16 percent loss on Wednesday, the worst this year.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the uncertainty comes from a set of conditions the IMF
required before proceeding with the loan refinancing. The fund has
faced accusations that it gave money to Russia in the past even
when Moscow failed to make important economic changes tied to the
lending.
</P>
<P>
   Its recent conditions were meant to prove that Russia is getting
its finances in order, and they included changes to the Russian tax
code to increase budget revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Such changes, however, have to be adopted by the Communist-led
lower house of Parliament, where Primakov has enjoyed strong
support.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house is already in a fighting mood: Thursday was the
first day of a long-planned session to impeach Yeltsin. Even if the
impeachment effort fails, it will hardly ease the tension between
Yeltsin and Parliament or smooth the passage of the IMF-linked
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house must approve Yeltsin's nominee to be the next
prime minister, Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin. The process,
even if successful, could take as long as five weeks of political
wrangling, distracting attention from legislation.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a strong chance that the legislators may reject
Stepashin, a presidential loyalist, which would give Yeltsin the
constitutional right to disband Parliament and call for early
elections. Stepashin and the new Cabinet appointees would stay on,
but only as a caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
   If Parliament is dissolved, Nash, the economist, said: ``The IMF
would face the prospect of giving money to a country without a
legislature or a government. In every statement the IMF has made,
it said it expects to have a legislative underpinning to the
economic program.''
</P>
<P>
   Some economists think that dissolving Parliament might not
necessarily hurt the IMF program. Under the constitution, the
President can issue decrees establishing such a program in the
absence of laws.
</P>
<P>
   Others contend that whatever the outcome of the house's vote on
Stepashin, the IMF will have to yield to political pressure to help
Russia from its largest contributors, notably the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason there's an IMF program to begin with isn't because
anyone expects major change,'' said Charles Blitzer, chief
international economist with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``It's
driven by the urgency of the West to remain engaged in Russia.''
And right or wrong, he added, it ``wants to do that through the
IMF.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A way will be found around any problems,'' Blitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   In the current political and economic conditions, any government
can do very little, economists said. Russia faces elections for
Parliament this winter and presidential elections in mid-2000, and
it is becoming apparent, they said, that no one wants to make
painful choices that would be sure to anger some part of the
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems in Russia aren't fiscal, but far deeper
structurally,'' Blitzer said. ``No government is going to be brave
enough or strong enough to even begin to deal with those basic
problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
