<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, May 14. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
AGUA PRIETA-ALIENS (Phoenix) - It's being called the Calcutta of
Mexico, a once quiet, solitary desert town which is now in the
middle of the busiest crossing area to the U.S. by illegal
immigrants. Hundreds are being deported from the U.S. daily and
many become street people. Low-end hotels and cheap taco stands
have proliferated in recent months. The hotel business is so
profitable that three doctors in downtown Agua Prieta have turned
their medical practices into hotels. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
JOGGERS (Gilbert, Ariz.) - This is the story of three avid joggers
who run in Gilbert. When they meet headed in opposite directions,
they don't budge. So one got a court order against the others. They
have to stay 10 feet away while she runs, or can be arrested. She
says the others - a married couple - run side by side and refuse to
move over or go single-file when she approaches so she can get by.
She says she has to move into traffic, and also says elbows and
words _ and possibly spit _ have been involved. A reflection on our
society? By CHRIS FISCUS. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SWEETONIONS-FOOD (Phoenix) - Arizona's onion industry keeps
growing, thanks to a high profile concocted by Mr. Sweet Onion, Ken
Gablin. Story includes five recipes. With SWEETSIDE-FOOD and
PHOTOS. By JUDY WALKER. Stories moved in the ``D`' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOODART (Phoenix) - Don't visit Virginia Sardi's art exhibition on
an empty stomach. Her work might have you taking a bite out of a
T-shirt or a pair of briefs. Sardi is a fiber artist whose themes
revolve around food. With PHOTOS. By BARBARA YOST. Story moved in
the ``D'' and ``E'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICAGO HOPE (Phoenix) - Thanks to David E. Kelley, there's hope
for ``Chicago Hope.'' CBS agreed to resuscitate the sometimes-soapy
hospital series if Kelley, its creator, agreed to write this
season's finale and next season's opener. Kelley also agreed to
take a more active role in its week-to-week production, including
reviewing and punching up scripts, and overseeing casting
decisions. By DAVE WALKER. Story will move in the ``E'' category.
Embargoed for Sunday, May 16. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
