A6119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NATO-HNS &LR;      05-13 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON COMPARES `ETHNIC CLEANSING' TO HOLOCAUST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton compared the Yugoslav ``ethnic
cleansing'' policy to the Holocaust as he sought Thursday to
justify NATO's continued bombing of the Serbs as a moral duty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made another in a series of speeches on Kosovo as the
allied air campaign, fraught with a series of missteps, including
the mistaken bombing of the Chinese Embassy, enters its eighth
week. He acknowledged the frustration Americans may be feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we see these pictures of the refugees on television
every night and most people would like another story, but we must
not get refugee fatigue. We must not forget the real victims of
this tragedy,'' Clinton said in an address to the nation's veterans
at the National Defense University.
</P>
<P>
   He said Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic`s Serb troops
have uprooted almost all of the 1.7 million ethnic Albanians living
in the Serb province of Kosovo, sending them fleeing across the
borders or into the mountains. Another 100,000 are missing,
thousands executed and 500 villages burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though his `ethnic cleansing' is not the same as the ethnic
extermination of the Holocaust, the two are related; both vicious,
premeditated, systematic oppression fueled by religious and ethnic
hatred,'' Clinton said. ``This campaign to drive the Kosovars from
their land and to indeed erase their very identity is an affront to
humanity and an attack not only on a people, but on the dignity of
all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Butch Miller, the American Legion's top official, told The
Associated Press that Clinton's remarks failed to make the case for
continued U.S. operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Committing the sons and daughters of America to armed conflict
overseas requires a clear, compelling statement of the national
interest that hasn't been articulated yet for the Kosovo
operation,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also continued his appeals to Russia to remain
involved in the peace negotiations. Clinton said NATO wants Russian
troops to be a part of the international security force after the
war. He said a Russian presence ``will help to reassure the Serbs
who live in Kosovo and they will need some protection, too, after
all that has occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said NATO forces at times have risked their own
lives in a quest to avoid civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we regret any casualties that are accidental,
including those at the Chinese Embassy,'' he said, referring to the
attack last week that left three Chinese dead and 20 wounded. ``But
let me be clear again. These are accidents; they are inadvertent
tragedies of conflict. We have worked very hard to avoid them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States remained ``committed to building a
long-term strategic partnership'' with China.
</P>
<P>
   The president again explained to Americans why the United States
and its European allies launched the bombing raids that have
pounded Yugoslavia since March 24.
</P>
<P>
   He recounted the emotional horror stories told by refugees: The
farmer who survived a mass execution when other bodies fell on him,
the Serb police robbing the Kosovars of their passports and money,
the stories of rapes by masked Serbs, the murder of four children
whose family had no money for bribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no accident that Mr. Milosevic has not allowed the
international media to see the slaughter and destruction in Kosovo.
There is no picture reflecting the story that one refugee told, of
15 men being tied together and set on fire while they were alive.
No, there are no pictures of that. But we have enough of those
stories to know that there is a systematic effort that has animated
our actions, and we must not forget it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters before his address, Clinton said he
believed Americans ``are probably frustrated that it is not already
over. But I said in the beginning, we have to be prepared to pay
the price of time.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Clinton again reiterated the steps Milosevic must take to
stop the bombing: allow the Kosovar refugees to return, withdraw
Serb forces, allow the Kosovar Albanians self-government and allow
an international security force into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's Operation Allied Force, fraught with missteps, has come
under criticism from many fronts and its bombing raids had little
impact on Milosevic's routing of Kosovar Albanians. Yugoslav forces
this week declared their operation in Kosovo to be successful and
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also noted Milosevic is being investigated for war
crimes and said the responsibility for the atrocities lies with the
government not the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political leaders do this kind of thing. Do you think the
Germans would have perpetrated the Holocaust on their own without
Hitler? Was there something in the history of the German race that
made them do this? No. We have got to get straight about this, this
is something political leaders do. And if people make decisions to
do these kinds of things, other people can make decisions to stop
them ... and that is exactly what we intend to do,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton held out the prospect of economic aid for Serbia,
Yugoslavia's largest republic, should it turn away from the
``ethnic cleansing'' policies. He said the European Union stood
ready to take a lead role in development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand ready, therefore, to embrace Serbia as a part of a
new Europe if the people of Serbia are willing to invest and
embrace that kind of future,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
