</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE CONGRESS RESTORES PRESIDENT'S CUTS TO EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ After a week of student
demonstrations, the Argentine Congress has restored $280 million in
aid to schools and universities that President Carlos Saul Menem
had ordered cut to control a federal budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming vote in both houses of Congress on Wednesday
night came only two days after Menem had himself partly reversed
the cuts. But the united effort by legislators of both the
government party and opposition underscored the president's waning
influence as his second five-year term winds down.
</P>
<P>
   The vote also came less than a week after a gubernatorial
candidate supported by Menem in Buenos Aires province was trounced
by a nearly 3-to-1 margin in a primary held by the governing
Justicialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Menem made the cut in Education Ministry financing last month as
part of a broad $1 billion package of budget cuts to satisfy
International Monetary Fund targets for Argentina's 1999 deficit,
now projected to reach nearly $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts were publicly challenged by Education Minister Susana
Decibe, who resigned last week while endorsing growing student
protests at more than 25 public universities around the country in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand university student blocked major avenues in
Buenos Aires on Monday, causing huge traffic jams. And then on
Tuesday a national school strike paralyzed the public education
system and kept hundreds of thousands of students at home.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the chancellor of the University of Buenos Aires
threatened to close the school in October, leaving politicians with
the prospect of 185,000 students and their parents angry at the
country's leaders during the final weeks of the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the protests, Menem partly reversed the education
cuts on Tuesday, reinstating $150 million of the original $280
million.
</P>
<P>
   But congressional members of the Alianza opposition and
congressional supporters of Gov. Eduardo Duhalde of Buenos Aires
province, a bitter political foe of Menem and the leading
Justicialist candidate for president, joined forces on Wednesday
night to erase the entire education cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strong depreciation of executive power by the
Congress,'' said an opposition congresswoman, Graciela Fernandez
Meijide. She criticized Menem for making the cuts by emergency
decree rather than presenting them to Congress for debate.
</P>
<P>
   The Justicialist legislators managed to protect most of the
government's budget cuts, while the opposition promised to review
other cuts in health, housing and public pensions.
</P>
<P>
   The growing setbacks to the Menem government has led to rising
speculation in the press that Economy Minister Roque Fernandez will
be forced to resign. In interviews Thursday, however, Fernandez
said that he would remain and that ``we are not going to concede
anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the student demonstrators, he added, ``They can
cause trouble with their street demonstrators, but they will not
affect the nation's fundamental economic equilibrium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
