<HEADLINE>
JUST ONE BIG HAPPY WILSON FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you worked in the  &UR; Pete Wilson &LR;  administration _ ah, remember
those heady days of yesteryear? _ you've probably received a letter
from Pete saying how he and  &UR; Gayle &LR;  really want to keep in touch.
``To that end,'' he writes, he's had aides put together a
``world-class alumni organization'' that costs only $50 a year ($85
for two, if you act now) to join.
</P>
<P>
   You and your bunch o' pals can take advantage of an online job
bank, alumni directory, bulletin board _ ``the birth of a new baby,
or just a simple `Hello, I am alive and working in Las Vegas' '' _
and all kinds of ``networking opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Washington was the father of this country,'' writes
patriarch Pete, ``I think I can lay claim to being the grandfather
of the next generation of Republicans!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TACKY, TREACLY, TERRIBLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Billy Philadelphia &LR;  is sick of ``sexy.'' The word ``used to
mean, well, sexy,'' he writes, ``but now it's what's hot, trendy,
exciting, etc. A news story can be sexy. ... I guess I'm getting
old.'' Other nominations to  &UR; George Leonard &LR; 's list of words
overused in critical essays:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tom Turner &LR; 's had it with ``arguably'' and ``flinty'' (the
meaning of the latter is a total mystery, he writes).  &UR; Russell &LR; 
 &UR; Kane &LR;  is sick of `` `riveting.' ... And give `whopping' the ax,''
he says, ``since it is always self-evident.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mike Grandin &LR;  hates ``shaded.'' And ``enigmatic,'' ``tonal,''
``tonality,'' ``multifaceted,'' ``inflected,'' ``shadowed'' and
``overarching.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; T.S. Bolton &LR; , who must be a positive kind of guy, puts nothing
but negative words on his list: ``insipid,'' ``annoying,''
``condescending,'' ``banal,'' ``supercilious,'' ``vexatious'' and
``troglodytic.'' Troglodytic?
</P>
<P>
   Likewise,  &UR; Ronn Robbins &LR;  doesn't like ``moronic'' or
``disgusting.'' And  &UR; Glen Farmer &LR;  is sick and tired of ``Sound and
fury signifying a big advance from a conglomerate of unrelated
companies including one or two that used to be respected
publishers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BONDS PUTS HIS NAME ON CRUNCH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry's MVP Crunch,'' a new frosted flake-like cereal named
after  &UR; Barry Bonds &LR;  _ and featuring his picture on the box _ will
be on the market in a few weeks. This product is the creation of
Famous Fixins, which says it has signed up a ``ton of ballplayers''
nationwide for the right to put their names on cereals and barbecue
sauces to be sold in their teams' towns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cal Ripken Jr. &LR;  cereal will be on the market in Baltimore
shortly;  &UR; Erik Estrada &LR;  Tortilla Chips are to follow. The company
has been selling  &UR; Olympia Dukakis &LR;  Greek salad dressing for about a
year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds says he'll donate a portion of his profits to learning
programs to be established in public schools and to a private
school scholarship program.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In other news of marketing opportunities,  &UR; Rebecca &LR; 
 &UR; Thomson &LR;  is dismayed at Amazon.com's using the death of  &UR; Shel &LR; 
 &UR; Silverstein &LR;  this week as an occasion for a sales pitch. It's true,
the bookseller's home page mentions Silverstein and invites
consumers to ``check out our list'' of Silverstein books and
recordings, but maybe they just wanted to be nice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading a Los Angeles Times profile of Green Party
Assemblywoman  &UR; Audie Bock &LR; ,  &UR; Hank Chapot &LR;  was surprised at
Assemblywoman  &UR; Carole Migden &LR; 's comment. ``With the Greens, you
could get some wacky person with a tie-dyed T-shirt who hasn't had
a haircut in 10 years,'' she said, going on to say how Bock isn't
like the stereotype at all. How would Migden take it, asks Chapot,
if someone said it was surprising that she wasn't a tough-looking
leather-wearing Harley rider?
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bob Visotcky &LR; , general manager of radio station KXPK in
Denver, has apologized to listeners ``if  &UR; Howard Stern &LR;  has
offended you in any way ... during this horrific event.'' Stern was
on the air shortly after the Littleton massacre expressing surprise
that the shooters hadn't tried to ``have sex with any of the
good-looking girls,'' which he said he would have done.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Francis Moonan &LR;  is noticing that multilingual San Francisco
signs _ swimmers' warnings at Ocean Beach and don't feed the
pigeons at the Old Mint, for example _ include Russian.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a diva in development.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Singing star LeAnn Rimes, 18, in Rolling Stone.
</P>
