<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-RELOCATE-COX     05-13 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-RELOCATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jobs, support, hospitality mean a warm welcome
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The same qualities that draw people to Atlanta from
the shores of California and the avenues of New York make the metro
area attractive for resettling refugees from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   A booming economy, moderate living expenses and warm hospitality
are determining factors when resettlement agencies seek a safe
haven for people fleeing war and political persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1981, more than 37,000 refugees have come to Georgia from
Bosnia, Vietnam, the former Soviet Union, Cambodia, Ethiopia, Iraq
and many other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental goal and premise of resettlement is to give
them a second chance,'' said Susan Somach, executive director of
the Newcomers' Network, which provides services to refugees. ``A
big component of that is to rebuild self-sufficiency. One of the
big fundamentals is employment, and Atlanta has a great job
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The metro area's geographic size is another benefit, said Dana
White, professor of urban studies at Atlanta's Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know `sprawl' is a dirty word now, but the spread-out city
works advantageously in that sense,'' he said. ``You can move new
groups in with less danger of putting them up against another
group. In Boston and New York there's tighter space.''
</P>
<P>
   Those factors, taken together, mean that metro Atlanta will soon
become home to several hundred of the 20,000 Kosovar refugees who
will enter the United States in the coming months. Atlanta's first
group is expected to arrive early next week.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 resettlement organizations in America. On
Wednesday, representatives from each of those groups held their
weekly meeting in New York to determine how many cases each agency
could handle, through local affiliates. When local affiliates can
assure the national organizations that they have what they need to
get families off to a good start, the refugees begin arriving in
that area.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday afternoon, two local affiliates had received
their initial family allocations. World Relief will assist an
extended family group consisting of 17 people. And Catholic Social
Services notified the national office that it could resettle 20 to
30 families.
</P>
<P>
   There are at most half a dozen Kosovar families in the Atlanta
area, said Peter Herbert, regional director of the International
Rescue Committeee. So the refugees moving to Atlanta will be people
without any ties to the area.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what makes the metro area's hospitality and community
support such crucial factors when national organizations select
their affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community is extremely supportive here. It's one of the
best I've seen,'' said Herbert, who used to work in IRC's New York
office. ``People here are interested in helping people from other
countries and in their own communities. I'm impressed with how
generous people are.''
</P>
<P>
   The generosity of Atlantans is exemplified by people like Eve
Goldstein and Stephanie Kenney.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein called Jewish Family and Career Services to volunteer
whatever type of assistance a family might need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a docent at the William Bremen Jewish Heritage Museum, and
when I give tours to children, I tell them that during the
Holocaust the major group of people were onlookers,'' Goldstein
said. ``We try to make clear the difference between onlookers and
making the decision to help. You don't want to say this is someone
else's problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney volunteered through World Relief, a major resettlement
organization whose affiliate in Atlanta will ultimately help
perhaps 25 to 30 families. She agreed to sponsor a family _ which
means that she has found housing, furniture, sundries and the
support network necessary to help a Kosovar family start a new
life.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her preparations, Kenney tapped resources at the
schools of her three children, got support from her church and
enlisted the help of friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person I called said they would do whatever to help,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of hers have provided an apartment for two months at
their house. Others donated items necessary to run a household, and
volunteered to cook dinners and provide transportation for the
family. Kenney's husband, who works in real estate, is trying to
find the refugees a permanent home. ``I thought, `What can I do to
help?' '' Kenney said. ``Because they are coming from a terrible
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Christy Oglesby writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
