<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-PRESS-60     05-13 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-PRESS-600(2TAKES)NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY BOMBING INVIGORATES CHINESE PROPAGANDA APPARATUS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ever since NATO bombs hit the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade last Friday, China's state-run media have dished up a
ceaseless stream of banner headlines and jarring photos: of bereft
parents crying over victims' bodies, of President Jiang Zemin in
tears as he greeted families of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers and television programs have uniformly called the
bombing an intentional ``criminal act'' perpetrated by ``U.S.-led
NATO forces.'' The three dead Chinese have been anointed
``martyrs.'' The NATO forces, ``barbarians,'' or worse.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been no mention of the rock-throwing that damaged
the facade of the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, nor have the words
``ethnic cleansing'' ever appeared. It took two days for China's
news media to report President Clinton's initial apology, a delay
that fanned the flame of public outrage.
</P>
<P>
   State-controlled reports have played a crucial link in the cycle
of hatred that has rolled through China this week, reflecting both
genuine public outrage and urging it on with half truths and
inflammatory calls for the ``revenge of blood debts.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's somewhat rusty propaganda apparatus seemed to
spring back to life in response to this extraordinary event.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where newspapers and television programs are
generally quite diverse and distinct, it was startling to watch
China's news media once again speak with one voice. Many Chinese
people were moved by what they heard and saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing the news reports and those pictures, I felt furious
about America's actions,'' said Wei Fang, a 24-year-old auditor at
an American accounting firm in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Luo Zhanggong, a 28-year-old independent businessman who spent
the weekend making protest posters for display near his home, said
he ``simply didn't believe'' Western claims that student
demonstrators had trashed the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, it may be hard to conduct an old-style
propaganda campaign in China, where millions of urban Chinese have
access to foreign Web sites, watch television beamed in by
satellite from Hong Kong, and have friends and relatives overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese people are much more sophisticated than they were 20
years ago,'' said Minxin Pei, a researcher at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There were some signs at least that by week's end the official
version of events was fraying around the edges. At a government
press conference Thursday, a Chinese television reporter boldly
asked the Foreign Ministry spokesman: Why hadn't the government
mentioned Slobodan Milosevic's ethnic cleansing campaign?
</P>
<P>
   On the front page of Thursday's Southern Weekend, a popular
weekly with a liberal bent, editors condemned the NATO bombings,
but also warned against developing xenophobia and ``blind,
fanatical, narrow-minded nationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese media have become far more lively and diverse in the
last decade, partly because, to survive in the country's new market
economy, television programs must survive on advertising and
newspapers need to attract paying readers.
</P>
<P>
   To this end, dozens of newspapers and television programs have
branched into investigative reporting, run editorials on topics
like legal reforms, and cover stories about unemployment, crime and
domestic violence. Today, more than ever, China's media look more
like journalism and less like propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Readers and viewers are more inclined to expect the truth. As
one university student told his American professor this week: ``The
protestors didn't set fire to an American Consulate _ that's a lie.
If it was true it would have been on China Central Television.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the media's core task is still to protect and promote the
government's point of view, and this week they moved back to
basics. Hours after the bombings, Ding Guangen, the head of the
Communist Party's Propaganda Department, called a meeting of
newspaper editors to order up coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, virtually every newspaper _ from the popular Beijing
Youth Daily to the party's mouthpiece, People's Daily _ has devoted
pages and pages to the bombings, all expressing identical views and
often using the same catch phrases. Even specialty papers like
Farmers Daily and Health News joined in. Enterprising television
programs that normally focus on corruption, has bellowed a similar
outrage.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Beijing Youth Daily has devoted at least eight
pages to the bombings every day, a dramatic shift from its usual
lively mix.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the newspaper's banner headline ``Shock _ Outrage _
Protest'' was punctuated with tiny targets, the symbol of Serbian
defiance. Another issue featured ``The Bomb Attack Was
Premeditated.'' Virtually all newspapers have offered up columns by
military experts contending that the bombing was intentional.
</P>
<P>
   The paper did not run a Western apology on Tuesday, two days
after Western leaders first expressed regrets.
</P>
<P>
   Such manipulations left the Chinese people stewing over the
apparent lack of an apology for an extra 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia and smaller countries all over the world are expressing
their condolences, but I haven't seen anything about Western
countries expressing these thoughts,'' said an angry physician who
would give only her surname, Han. ``It doesn't seem like the West
regards all this as important.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Beijingers point out that the vast propaganda campaign was
principally effective because it dovetailed with the public's
initial fury about the bombings, even if careful management fueled
that rage and channeled it into certain directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the disparities between the Chinese media and the
Western press, for us there are two simple facts: That NATO bombed
the Chinese Embassy and that three people died,'' said Luo, who
owns a chemical company. ``Now I'm not a party kind of person, but
this is a matter on which the Chinese people, from the lowest
peasant on up, are extremely unified.''
</P>
<P>
   Luo and others dismissed the notion that in 1999 a propaganda
campaign could ever manipulate Chinese people's thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days China has become quite open and we get news from a
whole variety of sources,'' said Li Pingwei, a 35-year-old who
works in advertising. ``I get it from TV, newspapers, the Internet
and from speaking to my friends and colleagues who are overseas. I
know what the outside world is saying.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Li said he ``had heard'' that the American
Consulate in Chengdu had been burned. He said he debated with his
Chinese friends working in the West about whether the bombing was
intentional or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely have a different understanding of the events
from Chinese people here,'' Li said. ``But they think the American
media are to some extent also controlled. Our media say it was
deliberate, and theirs say it was a mistake. So our opinions
differ.''
</P>
<P>
   But others had more basic reasons why the media blitz here left
them unmoved. ``Of course everyone's furious, three people were
killed,'' said a man surnamed Wang, a shopkeeper. ``Would I
demonstrate? Of course not! You can't make money demonstrating. And
that's what it's all about now, isn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
