<HEADLINE>
FINNERAN, KRAFT APPEAR FRIENDLY AT LUNCHEON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They did not say much publicly, but when House Speaker
Thomas M. Finneran and New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft
smiled, laughed, shook hands, and got touchy-feely in public
Thursday, it created quite a stir.
</P>
<P>
   In front of 250 of Boston's highest-profile business pt
the Boston Harbor Hotel, Massachusetts' consummate Odd Couple
looked more like old buddies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they appeared downright convivial.
</P>
<P>
   Having fought a long war over the appropriate level and use of
public finances for a new stadium for the National Football League
team, the two men have largely been considered enemies in the
public eye. And in a state where revenge sometimes seems to be the
most popular participant sport, who would ever have thought that
Finneran's arm would be seen publicly around Kraft's shoulder, or
that Kraft would grasp the speaker's hand well after shaking it?
And what about all of the laughter?
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable!'' exclaimed the chief executive of one company,
as others literally pointed at the scene and whispered to their
lunch companions in the hotel's Wharf Room.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and Finneran sat at the same table for a luncheon speech
by Ted Turner, the Time Warner vice chairman, to the Boston
Colleges Chief Executives Club. Before the speech, Finneran
approached Kraft who was already seated.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft looked up, smiled, and shook hands with Finneran.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran crouched slightly, put his arm around Kraft's shoulder
and both began a four-and-a-half minute conversation.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Finneran could be heard saying, ``There'll be a
hearing and then a vote Tuesday.'' That is the schedule of action
in the Legislature next week on a bill to spend $70 million in
infrastructure improvements in Foxborough for the proposed new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft nodded a lot, and had a few words of his own for Finneran.
At one point, he laughed and grasped Finneran's forearm, while the
speaker's lips remained at Kraft's ear.
</P>
<P>
   It all was much different from the days when Finneran referred
directly to Kraft as ``a whiny millionaire'' _ before publicly
apologizing for the comment after being taken to task for it by his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hunter, a spokesman for the Boston College group, said
Thursday that seating assignments were made by the college after
consideration was given to who would attend, and their prominence
in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and Finneran were at the head table with Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Reverend J. Donald Monan, the chancellor of BC and member of a
group of six civic leaders who put the Patriots' stadium issue back
on the agenda, had nothing to do with bringing the men together,
Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   But Monan was at an adjacent table, his seat less than 15 feet
away. At the same table with Kraft and Finneran was another member
of the group of six, William F. Connell, a developer and
industrialist. Another member of the civic group, Wayne A. Budd,
group president of Bell Atlantic, was at a second adjacent table.
</P>
<P>
   When the luncheon was over, Kraft apologized for having little
to say about his conversation with Finneran, or the buzz it created
in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to say much about it, now,'' Kraft said,
still smiling broadly.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker both thoughtful and magnanimous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had one disagreement in all of those years: the proper
use of taxpayers' dollars for a football stadium. And on that
issue, we have agreed to disagree. In the course of such
disagreements, sometimes the wrong things are said.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his prominent, public conversation with Kraft was a bit
of a coming out for both men, Finneran grinned broadly and said,
``It was nice to see him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
