</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKRUPTCY (Washington) _ As the number of personal
bankruptcies soars to record highs, Congress is considering
legislation that would make it harder for people earning more than
$50,000 a year to walk away from their debts. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-PROFILES-COX     05-13 2089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-PROFILES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Starting over in Georgia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fleeing warfare or political persecution, more than
37,000 refugees from around the world have found sanctuary in
Georgia since 1981. As metro Atlanta prepares to take in refugees
from the conflict in Kosovo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff
writers Lillian Lee Kim and Jeffry Scott talked to five recent
refugee families to see how they're adjusting to their new lives
here.
</P>
<P>
   From Bosnia:
</P>
<P>
   The Cvijetinovic family
</P>
<P>
   Arrived in Georgia: 1996
</P>
<P>
   Now living in: Clarkston, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   During the war in Bosnia, Slavica Cvijetinovic learned to live
with numbing fear and uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Then she came to Atlanta and learned true heartache.
</P>
<P>
   Four months pregnant when she arrived in December 1996, she
miscarried shortly afterward. A year later, her husband, Srdan, was
diagnosed with a rare form of throat cancer.
</P>
<P>
   And her lack of English rendered her mute at a time when she
most desperately needed to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can fight with life,'' says the 39-year-old former engineer.
``But it's very hard when you can't speak. You want to say
something, but you can't.''
</P>
<P>
   She learned English. She learned how to open a bank account. She
learned how to navigate mega-grocery stores and medical insurance
forms.
</P>
<P>
   She learned how to say ``tonsil'' and ``salivary gland'' and
``radiation therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   She is still Bosnian. But she knows her son is not.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan, 3, was born in Bosnia, but he is now as American as
Play-doh and Pez candy.
</P>
<P>
   Slavica's younger brother, Franjo, laughs at something Ivan says
in Bosnian. She explains that Ivan speaks Bosnian with a terrible
American accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son will grow up to love the United States. He will not
love Bosnia,'' Slavica says, wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that,'' she continues, as though she is
trying to convince herself. ``He loves everything American. He
should be American.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan and Franjo stroll across the street for candy, and return
with a whole cache: Runts, Nerds, Now &AMP; Laters. Slavica sifts
through the pile, muttering, ``Unhealthy, unhealthy,'' but she lets
Ivan eat what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, she recalls, she didn't know if there would be
food the next day. She didn't know if her husband or brothers, all
soldiers in the Bosnian army, would come home.
</P>
<P>
   Now she knows. Srdan's cancer is in remission; the former
graphic designer works in a factory, where he makes enough to
support the family. She is on leave from her job as a translator at
World Relief, a refugee resettlement agency.
</P>
<P>
   That's because there is a brand-new U.S. citizen in the
Cvijetinovic household: 4-week-old Ana, who sleeps peacefully in
the crib beside her parents' bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are my angel,'' Slavica coos to Ana _ in English.
</P>
<P>
   From Somalia:
</P>
<P>
   The Warsame family
</P>
<P>
   Arrived in Georgia: 1999
</P>
<P>
   Now living in: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Ali Mohamed was crushed that he couldn't start school
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   His four older siblings went, but his mother, Markabo, hadn't
been able to get his documents in order by then, explained the
family's caseworker, Mimi Mahmood. So the 10-year-old had to wait
until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to his mother, `You are a bad mother! You are a bad
mother!' '' Mahmood recalls, to the enormous amusement of the rest
of the family. Even Mohamed grins.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of grinning goes on in this tidy two-bedroom apartment,
where Ali Mohamed Warsame, 43, his wife, Markabo, 42, and their
seven children have lived since arriving in the United States a
month and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old Shukri earns laughter when she parades into the
living room wearing an ``abbya,'' the traditional head covering
that Somali women wear. She usually doen't wear it, her mother
says, but lately she has become something of a fashion plate, all 4
feet of her.
</P>
<P>
   You would never guess, from their joyous faces, that the Warsame
family had suffered since fleeing their native Somalia in November
1992. These faces reveal nothing of the seven years they spent in a
succession of Kenyan refugee camps, dodging marauders, scratching
out a living, waiting to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Warsame explains that the family no longer has anything to fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I came here, I'm very happy, I'm content,'' he says in
Somalian. ``I left all my worries behind.''
</P>
<P>
   They left behind almost everything they owned, except for some
clothes. Catholic Social Services, the agency that handled the
family's resettlement, provided new mattresses, bedclothes and
donated furniture. A volunteer secured a TV and VCR, so the
children could begin to learn English.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the little, loving touches that have turned this
shabby apartment into a warm home: the fringed shawl draped over an
end table, the dishes carefully arranged in a glass-fronted
bookcase, the incense scenting the air.
</P>
<P>
   From Cuba: The Feliciano family
</P>
<P>
   Arrived in Georgia: 1999
</P>
<P>
   Now living in: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Like so many refugees, Israel Feliciano, 39, had to make a
terrible choice.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba was no longer safe for his family. He and his wife, Isidra
Fleites, 43, both political activists, had been jailed for speaking
out against Fidel Castro. Even his 8-year-old daughter, Eileen, had
been forced to spend two days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   So he decided to leave. Then he learned that he would not be
able to take his son, Eldisney, with him.
</P>
<P>
   Eldisney was just months shy of 16, the age at which Cuban boys
are pressed into military service. He wouldn't be allowed to leave
the country with the rest of his family.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Feliciano started procedures for getting his son
released from his military obligation. The process is long; no one
knows how long.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Feliciano arrived in Atlanta. Eight days ago,
Fleites and Eileen joined him. They pray Eldisney will not be far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know when he can come,'' Fleites says softly.
</P>
<P>
   Vu family
</P>
<P>
   Country of origin: Vietnam
</P>
<P>
   Arrived in Georgia: 1998
</P>
<P>
   Now living in: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   The nightmares still visit Thang Vu.
</P>
<P>
   He imagines himself back in Vietnam's ``reeducation'' camps,
where he spent seven hellish years as a political prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I wake up, I recognize that now I am in U.S.,'' the
49-year-old Vu says.
</P>
<P>
   He avoids thinking about the past, he says. Instead, all his
energy is focused on building a new life in Atlanta, where Vu, his
wife and two sons arrived in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is the future of my family,'' Vu
repeats again and again. His 18-year-old son, Khoa, nods.
</P>
<P>
   Khoa has plans. Right now he's stuck in the ninth grade, because
all refugee kids at South Atlanta High between 14 and 18
automatically start as freshmen, no matter what their education
level.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of his family's caseworker, however, Khoa has
found a ticket to a better job without fully repeating high school.
He's taking GED classes downtown so he can get his high-school
equivalency diploma and enroll at Atlanta Tech, where he wants to
study computer programming. Six months in the United States, and he
already knows where the money is.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he practices English every chance he gets, by
chatting up other neighborhood kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult thing for me is English,'' Khoa says,
haltingly but intelligibly. ``Nobody understands me.''
</P>
<P>
   At least he's already mastered the American teenager look:
untucked Tommy Hilfiger shirt over baggy khaki pants sized for a
walrus.
</P>
<P>
   Phung Quang Chieu
</P>
<P>
   Country of origin: Vietnam
</P>
<P>
   Arrived in Georgia: 1983
</P>
<P>
   Now lives in: Doraville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Phung Quang Chieu, 63, tell his story, you see the
universal image of political refugees:
</P>
<P>
   Reaching for help, the help often eluding the grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the people who tried to climb the wall of the
U.S. Embassy the day that Saigon fell, trying to get on the
helicopters that were evacuating the embassy, '' says Chieu, who
worked as a translator for the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   North Vietnamese forces were shooting at the Embassy, he says.
``So I climbed back down. People were lying dead all over the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   It was April 30, 1975, and for the next 4 1/2 years Chieu served
time in a Vietnamese concentration camp.
</P>
<P>
   After his release, three times he tried and failed to escape
Vietnam by boat to join his wife and three children, who had fled
just before the fall of Saigon, in America.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Chieu was accepted as a political refugee by Italy, and
in 1983 emigrated to the United States for a short-lived reunion
with his family. Has was divorced in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta and lived for a year with an old friend from Vietnam,
Pham The Truyen, while working in the restaurant cooking, cleaning
and washing dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Later, his background and fluency in English got him a job at
the International Rescue Committee, where he's now deputy director.
</P>
<P>
   He's become the conduit for many Vietnamese resettling in
Atlanta, having helped 600 refugee families find homes here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult thing is the language,'' he says. ``Then
it's finding work, transportation, and understanding the laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``But everybody from South Vietnam wants to get out of Vietnam,
not because of the economy. They cannot live under the communist
regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Still single, Chieu bought a home two months ago, after 10 years
of saving for the downpayment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do that on one income,'' he says. ``But it makes
me feel like I've settled in Atlanta at last.''
</P>
<P>
   Veledar family
</P>
<P>
   Country of origin: Bosnia-Herzegovina
</P>
<P>
   Arrived in Georgia: 1994
</P>
<P>
   Now live in: Gwinnett County, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Emir Veledar, 45, remembers the things he wishes to forget, none
more horrifying than a fellow college professor forced at gunpoint
by Croatian soldiers to walk naked into the streets of Mostar,
Bosnia, where he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``His body lay in the streets for days because his friends and
family were afraid if they moved it, they would be shot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As he and wife, Mila, 44, recall life in Bosnia as Muslims, an
ethnic group targeted for eradication, Veledar shakes his head and
looks flustered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about something else,'' he says, running a hand
through his hair. ``Let's talk about how much I love this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Veledars arrived in Atlanta in March 1994, with their
daughters Sanja and Jasna, with the sponsorship of St. John Neumann
Catholic Church in suburban Atlanta, which paid their first two
months apartment rent.
</P>
<P>
   Both are college-educated. He taught college math. She worked as
a mechanical engineer. But the language barrier limited them to
lower-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   She shampooed hair at a beauty shop. He drove a delivery truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two years I was stuck in the cycle,'' says Mila. ``I
couldn't get a skilled job because of my English, and I couldn't
get a low-level job because I was too educated. But I did learn a
lot of English in the beauty parlor.''
</P>
<P>
   Emir's delivery job had its own frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these people in Atlanta really need,'' he says, laughing,
``is more imagination in naming streets. Peachtree Street,
Peachtree Road, Peachtree Industrial, New Peachtree Road. Very
confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   After living three years in Cherokee Court Apartments _ where
almost all the residents were Bosnian refugees _ two years ago the
Veledars bought a two-story three bedroom home near the suburban
town.
</P>
<P>
   She got a job soldering wireless phones at EMS Technology, and
has since been promoted to quality control.
</P>
<P>
   He works at the Emory University medical school doing
statistical research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now a three-car family,'' says Emir.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Emir visited relatives in Bosnia. But he and his
family have no wish to return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's home, but it's a different one,'' he says. ``There was so
much destruction that people who live in Bosnia know that during
the rest of their life it will never be the same again.''
</P>
<P>
   Their daughters both are honor students. Sanja, a junior in high
school, is talking about attending Georgia Tech. Emir and Mila
marvel at how the family has adjusted and been embraced by the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have one unpleasant experience in America,''
says Emir. ``Of course, when you go to buy a car they try to trick
you. But that's not personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim and Jeffry Scott write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
