<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welfare success story's unhappy twist
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lost in the much-heralded success of the nation's
welfare reform law is the less well-known story of the number of
former recipients who have lost their health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   A study published Thursday by Families USA provides the first
statistical glimpse of how many people may have been affected by
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based health advocacy group found that 675,000
former welfare recipients and their families have lost their
government-funded health insurance as an unintended consequence of
leaving the welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   That means one out of every five people leaving the welfare
system end up among the nation's 43.5 million people who are
uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reward many are receiving for coming off welfare is the
loss of health care coverage,'' said Ron Pollack, executive
director of Families USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the tip of the iceberg. We are only beginning to
see the impact of the welfare reform law,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Congress ordered the overhaul of the
welfare system in 1996, requiring most welfare recipients to work
as a condition of getting financial aid. The new law also imposed a
five-year limit on the benefits, among other restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Since the law took effect, the number of people on welfare
across the country has declined by 4.6 million people, or 38
percent. In Georgia, the rolls have dropped by nearly half.
</P>
<P>
   But the welfare law also required state officials to inform
former welfare recipients of their right to receive Medicaid for up
to one year after leaving the system. And that, say advocates, is
not happening as it should.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on data compiled from the U.S. Census Bureau
and the Health Care Financing Administration, which administers the
government-funded Medicaid program that insures welfare recipients
and low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   While federal officials agree that more should be done to inform
former welfare recipients of their right to stay on Medicaid, they
disagree with the group's statistics.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the mathematical model that the group used, said
Melissa Skolfield, assistant secretary for public affairs at the
Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   The study does not take into consideration that the Medicaid
rolls could have dropped as a result of the robust economy,
Skolfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack says the economy was taken into account, and he noted
that the computations were done by a reputable outside company.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, state officials are concerned that the message is
not getting out to former welfare recipients that they have the
right to remain on Medicaid for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important that they (former welfare recipients)
know they can stay on Medicaid,'' said Joyce Goldberg, a
spokeswoman for the Department of Family and Children Services,
which administers welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid, child care and transportation are the three services
that help those who leave welfare, Goldberg said. Her department is
training caseworkers to tell former recipients about the services
available to them.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Lowe, a Georgia-based consumer health advocate, said the
study confirms what advocates for welfare recipients long have
feared: There's been too little attention focused on informing
families that they can get Medicaid as they make the transition
into the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people, particularly adults, have been lost in the
system,'' Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
