<HEADER>
A6153 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-LIFE15-COX     05-13 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The rose: A beauty full of contradictions
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 16.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In some ways, the rose is like the pansy. Each grows a
gardenful of contradictions; each teaches a lifetime of lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Here in mid-May, pansies still grow strong despite their
reputation as flowers of the cool and cold. Routinely, they'll
perform until midsummer. Pansy is one of the toughest bloomers in
the garden _ even though the word usually disparages; there's
nothing weak about the pansy, known to brightly lift its face out
of snowdrifts that keep supposedly tougher plants on their knees.
With a happy face, the pansy shucks off labels and rises above low
expectations, excelling beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of life lesson you can't learn in school _
especially in these baffling times when concerns about security and
safety threaten to turn teachers and schools into soldiers and
fortresses.
</P>
<P>
   The rose, that deeply loved, highly prized queen of the garden,
has its own contradictions, lessons. It is at once elegant and
prickly, silky and rough, inviting and repelling, bringing those
qualities together like no other flower (prickly pear, with its
fine yellow flower rising from pin-cushion pads, combines similar
characteristics but without the respect the rose enjoys).
</P>
<P>
   Growing, cutting, handling, gazing upon a perfect rose blossom,
surrounded by forbidding thorns, teaches appreciation for life's
myriad contrasts, its sometimes mysterious contradictions. This
royal shrub produces its own kind of yin and yang, a harmony
accentuating both the soft elegance of the bloom and the hard-edged
prickliness of the stem.
</P>
<P>
   Such harmony can be seen in many places. I have appreciated it,
for example, in the ruggedly lovely Rosa rugosa along Atlantic Road
in Gloucester, Mass. This crinkly-leafed shrub with the fragrant
flower and tomatolike hips reflects the mesmerizing beauty of the
ocean, as well as the craggy rocks jutting from the water. During
walks along the road, these three natural wonders _ the sea, the
stony shoreline and the rose _ arrest me every time.
</P>
<P>
   And, in my own less-dramatic space, I grow roses here and there,
integrating them with other plants. Most are nameless. I propagated
my first many Decembers ago by taking several 6-inch cuttings from
a neighbor's bush and pushing them into soft dirt up to the two
sets of leaves I left on.
</P>
<P>
   One cutting made it through the winter and still grows happily.
(Isn't that often the way with propagation _ no matter how many
cuttings you take, one takes.)
</P>
<P>
   I bought two other nameless roses near Meridian, Miss., several
years ago, assured by the nursery people that ``these are the kind
Grandma grew.'' In fact, they said, grandmothers were prominent
sources for their plants. Somehow, it seemed fitting that Big
Mommas, such important figures in so many of our lives, would share
floral joy.
</P>
<P>
   Just as I always loved the rose as the symbol for Mother's Day.
I don't see as many people wearing them as I used to, but years
ago, red roses were worn in great numbers by people whose mothers
were alive, while white roses were for those whose mothers had gone
on. So long ago, when practically everyone I knew wore red.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what color they are, my roses must be
self-sufficient; needy roses have no place in my garden. Which is
why I choose those that have thrived on neglect.
</P>
<P>
   One grows near a little juniper and a short pine, its
red-and-yellow blooms softly contrasting with the conifer needles,
while the rose thorns complement those same sharp needles.
</P>
<P>
   Another, orangy-red, twines along through the wrought-iron
fence, its delicate, fleeting blossoms softening the fence's
permanently rigid lines _ mortality and immortality co-existing, as
they do in our heads when we reconcile our youthful belief that
life is forever with our aging knowledge that it has limits.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of aging, I do love roses more than when I was younger
(just as I more appreciate gardening in general), showing again
that years sometimes bring wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   The years also have brought me roses I did not plant. Two have
sprouted from the ground during the last couple of years _ one
burgundy, one pink, neither close to an established plant. Maybe
there's some scientific reason for these appearances, but I like to
believe roses come because of my growing appreciation. My
understanding of how beauty and charm can thrive in the thorniest
places. How we can be tough and tender at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay(at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
