<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIRCOLOR-MEN16-COX     05-13 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIRCOLOR-MEN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Way beyond gray: Men take to color as fashion statement
 &HT;    EDs: Embaroged for Sunday May 16.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gentlemen still prefer blondes. They also like
dabbling with redheads and brunettes.
</P>
<P>
   Hair dye has become the latest fashion accessory for
style-conscious men who like changing their look as often as some
fellows buy a new pair of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Neuroth, a 21-year-old Georgia Tech student and part-time
bartender at Mumbo Jumbo, recently had his hair dyed Rocket Fire
Red just for the heck of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do lots of different hairstyles, so I like trying different
colors,'' explained Neuroth, whose hair used to be brown.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their older brothers, guys today aren't dyeing just to
cover gray. They're dyeing for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Major hair care manufacturers are catering to the trend by
developing colors with masculine sounding names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can create a very subtle look to a very bold look and
everything in between,'' said Clancey Callaway, head colorist for
Vidal Sassoon in Lenox Square (Atlanta), who's been in the business
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The color craze among males prompted L'Oreal to put men on the
boxes of its Feria brand home coloring kits. Feria's new colors for
men are Bleach Blonding, a light, sun-kissed yellow; Cherry Cola, a
deep burgandy; Camel, a golden blond; and Gothic, black.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just hit the shelves in late April,'' said Carlene Pruitt,
spokeswoman for L'Oreal in New York. ``It seemed very natural to
put men on the boxes. More men are coloring their hair, not only to
cover gray but to make a statement. We choose those shades very
strategically.''
</P>
<P>
   Clairol also has developed a new men's line, called Natural
Instincts for Men, that's scheduled to be on grocery and drugstore
shelves this summer. The 10 new colors will replace Clairol's Men's
Choice, which has been out since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The company developed the new products after research showed
that the use of hair coloring by men between ages 30 and 54 had
grown 8 percent per year for the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although cost is a factor _ a salon will charge at least $60 for
a coloring job, compared with a home kit for as little as $3.99 _
men tend to color their hair more often than women because they
wear it shorter and cut it more frequently. A man typically needs
his dye retouched once a month, whereas women can go for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   While some men prefer subtle shades that merely hide gray or
enhance their natural color, bolder souls go for the bleach.
Platinum and bleached blond shades are the most sought-after colors
this season. Bill Cook is so smitten with his platinum-white hair
that he's had it dyed every four weeks for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very '30s, silver-screen, movie-star look,''
said Cook, who's a natural ash blond. ``It goes real well with my
skin tone, and it's dramatic. People remember you when you have
platinum hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
