<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-POET-BOS &LR;      05-13 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BU PROFESSOR LEADER IN BRITISH POET LAUREATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a battle pitting a literary tradition that goes back
three centuries and Britain's evolving post-imperial identity,
Boston University professor and Nobel poetry prize recipient Derek
Walcott has emerged as the front-runner to become the nation's poet
laureate.
</P>
<P>
   Walcott, who was born a British subject on the Caribbean island
of St. Lucia in 1930, would replace Ted Hughes, who died six months
ago. He would be the nation's 19th poet laureate, filling a
lifetime post once held by figures such as Tennyson and Wordsworth.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Prime Minister Tony Blair Thursday said the
new laureate would be named by the end of the month, but declined
to say whether Walcott is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   In literary circles here, however, Walcott is said to have the
inside track. Walcott, who has just wrapped up teaching the spring
semester at BU, was in Boston Thursday but through BU spokesman
Kevin Carleton declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is aware that he is under consideration,'' said Carleton.
</P>
<P>
   The British government had expected to have named a replacement
by now for Hughes, who Thursday was remembered by many of Britain's
top writers during a memorial service at Westminster Abbey. It had
been hoped that his successor could be at the service.
</P>
<P>
   But filling a job that dates back to the 17th century and which
Hughes had held for nearly two decades has proved to be an
unexpectedly daunting task, mainly because of a tug of war between
those who want the job to stay within its traditional parameters
and those who want it to reflect modern Britain.
</P>
<P>
   While Walcott would be the first black laureate, and would
appeal to Blair's desire to celebrate Britain's diversity, he is
being pushed by some of the staunchest traditionalists because they
see him as a literary heavyweight and because they fear the job may
go to a more populist poet. Among Walcott's supporters is Hughes's
widow Carol, who recently wrote to Blair urging him not to
modernize the post.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much debate within Blair's ``Cool Britannia''
government about making poetry more accessible by installing a less
highbrow ``people's poet.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists, however, have howled at the prospect of
changing a job that since 1692 has offered a yearly stipend of 100
pounds, which was good money 307 years ago but is a considerably
less impressive honorarium today.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the poet laureate's prime responsibility has been
to pen verse to commemorate state events, such as royal weddings.
There is some pressure to have the new laureate in place for next
month's wedding of Prince Edward and Sophie Rhys-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   While Queen Elizabeth II will name the new laureate, she will
effectively be announcing Blair's selection. Under British
parliamentary law, one of the powers specifically invested in the
prime minister is forwarding the laureate's name to the monarch.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish poet and Nobel laureate Seamus Heaney was initially a
government favorite, especially given Blair's efforts to bring
about peace and reconciliation in Northern Ireland. But Heaney took
himself out of the running because while he was born in
British-controlled Northern Ireland, he carries an Irish passport
and could not swear loyalty to a monarch.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's office has floated ideas about giving the
laureate's post a limited term, a change that traditionalists have
also attacked.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Thursday to The Daily Telegraph, the voice of the
British establishment that has campaigned against changing the
laureate's job description, Alan Howarth, the British arts
minister, dismissed suggestions that the government was determined
to create a ``people's poet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The government can see no advantage in anything that would
impair the Poet Laureate's traditional resonance or the respect and
regard in which the office is held by the public,'' said Howarth.
``It is inconceivable that we would wish anything to undermine this
precious literary legacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
