<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6158 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAIKIKI-BEACHBOY-ART-     05-13 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAIKIKI-BEACHBOY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRINCE OF THE OLD WAIKIKI IS BID ALOHA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This story, eliminated earlier, is now restored. We apologize
for the inconvenience.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ As the wind rose and the surf boiled and the last
light leached from the wide sky over Waikiki on Wednesday night,
Charlie Lambert, a prince of old Hawaii, went home to the waves he
loved.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert, who died last month at 73 after battling emphysema and
a bad heart, made his living as a sales and convention manager for
the big waterfront hotels here. But for six years in the early
1950s _ and spiritually for the rest of his life _ he was a Waikiki
beach boy, among the last of a vanishing, century-old breed of
Hawaiian originals, part Sherpa, part big-game guide, part maitre
d' for the wealthy travelers who discovered these islands before
the age of jet travel and made this slender stretch of sand an
international playground.
</P>
<P>
   Charles David Kanaina Lambert, a rakish rogue who in old
photographs looks like a cross between Peter Lawford and William
Holden, could boogie with the best of them. He gave John Wayne a
surfing lesson and paddled an outrigger canoe for Frank Sinatra and
Ava Gardner on their honeymoon, with Sinatra's friend Sam Giancana
in tow. Like his brother beach boys, he put out towels and chairs
and umbrellas for the swells, often with a yellow plumeria blossom
tucked seductively behind his left ear.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that a knot of graying elders, along with some
buffed and tanned successors to the trade, came together at a
slate-gray sunset amid a parade of passing tourists to help
Lambert's family paddle his ashes out to sea _ to the spot the
beach boys call ``first break,'' where the blue Pacific curls up
into foaming white surf in sight of the shore. These funerals are
the most cherished ritual of Waikiki culture and are practiced with
precision, from the long green ti leaves tucked along the gunwales
of the outrigger canoe to the fragrant leis of white ginger
blossoms tossed onto the water with the ashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was so Hawaii for me,'' his daughter Cindy, who now
lives in Los Angeles, told the group of mourners clustered together
against a sudden shower, her voice catching as she struggled to
control her emotions. ``I said, `Dad, when you die, where do I look
for you?' He said, `Put your feet in the water and I'll kiss your
toes.'''
</P>
<P>
   The beach boys were the crack troops that made Waikiki work in
the lazy days before World War II, when there were just two grand
hotels on the beach (the Moana and the Royal Hawaiian), when the
travelers came by steamship and dispensed $100 tips, and when
``Aloha'' was a gracious way of life and not a commercial slogan.
Beginning at the turn of the century, these watermen revived
surfing and canoe racing, the ancient sports of Hawaiian kings that
had been all but stamped out by Calvinist missionaries, who
complained that such pursuits encouraged nudity and gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``A true beach boy's life really revolved around the ocean and
his relationship to it,'' said Grady Timmons, a former sportswriter
for The Honolulu Star-Bulletin, and author of ``Waikiki Beachboy,''
a 1989 coffee table book to which Lambert contributed. ``That is
why the funeral is so significant. You're taking the beach boy back
to the one thing that's a constant. Waikiki has changed a lot over
the years, but the ocean is still there. He's returning to his
friends. Most of them are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert's on-shore friends all attested to his qualities of
grace, and he apparently came by them naturally. Of mixed Hawaiian
and ``haole,'' or Caucasian, heritage, he traced his lineage to the
line of King Lunalilo and was a great-grandson of Queen
Lili'uokalani, the islands' last monarch, who was overthrown by the
United States in 1893. He was friends with all the greats of the
beach, including Duke Kahanamoku, the Jazz Age Olympic swimming
champion who was regarded as the father of international surfing
and was godfather to another of Lambert's three daughters, Lisa, an
antiques dealer in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie was a gentleman, really special, old school,'' said
Claire Heen Cameron, Miss Hawaii of 1953, who with her friend
Sandra Lee-Song held exquisitely scented gardenia blossoms in
tribute to Lambert's practice of handing them out ``to every lady
he saw,'' in his days as a public relations official for the Royal
Hawaiian.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive growth in tourism that brought a new kind of
discount traveler to Waikiki took its toll on the old beach boys'
suave style as a new breed of freelance competitors brought an air
of cutthroat hustle. By 1959, the television host Arthur Godfrey, a
Waikiki regular, branded the beach ``a Coney Island with palm
trees,'' and his outburst led to licensing requirements and tests
for lifesaving and water skills that remain in force today.
</P>
<P>
   Waikiki may no longer be the favored retreat of Hollywood stars
and captains of commerce, and beach boys may no longer strum
ukuleles at sunset, but the tradition continues in its way, in a
place where surf boards are lined up outside the Elks Club.
</P>
<P>
   At Lambert's funeral, Harry S. Robello, at 81 perhaps the dean
of the old school, stood at the edge of the crowd, quietly
appraising the proceedings. But his son, Harry D. Robello, 37, the
owner of Aloha Beach Service, the oldest concession on the beach,
was right in the thick of things, supervising the launching of the
funeral canoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' the younger Robello said of his life, as his
9-year-old son, Ryan, the next generation in training, scampered
around him on the sand. ``You live day to day. You're never going
to make a great living. But you have a great life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
