<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYBRIBES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC papers turn focus to member dossiers
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The release Tuesday of personal notes compiled on his
peers by an embattled International Olympic Committee member from
Australia has focused attention on confidential dossiers produced
by Olympic bid groups.
</P>
<P>
   The practice dates back at least to the late 1980s, when Atlanta
bidders assembled files on the IOC voters, their families and their
preferences among the candidate cities for the 1996 Summer
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The notes made public in Sydney by Michael Knight, the city's
Olympic committee president, include details such as IOC members'
marital problems, personalities, moods and smoking and eating
habits. They were compiled by Phil Coles, who faces possible
expulsion from the IOC for accepting favors from Salt Lake
officials. Coles is suspected of passing the files on to the
successful Salt Lake bid team for the 2002 Winter Games. Coles, a
member of the Sydney group that won the 2000 Summer Olympics,
denied sharing the information with Salt Lake and accused Knight of
trying to run him off. The files were co-authored by Coles'
partner, Patricia Rosenbrock.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta bid team's approach apparently dealt with IOC
members' interests, their children and gifts that would appeal to
them, according to documents contained in the first nine boxes of
Olympic records unsealed at the Atlanta History Center.
</P>
<P>
   On one ``IOC Update,'' dated Nov. 29, 1989, it was noted that
the daughter of IOC member Louis Guirandou-N'Diaye from the Ivory
Coast was getting married and that ``Mayor (Andrew) Young should
give gift.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was noted that Guirandou-N'Diaye ``has recently been in
the hospital while visiting Melbourne.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes on David Sibandze from Swaziland included these:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``His son is interested in attending Georgia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We sent him two Bill Cosby books _ did he receive them?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Billy Payne should ask him about returning to Atlanta in May
after he visits Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibandze's son ended up at the University of Utah, where he
received tuition assistance from Salt Lake officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta dossiers illustrated a strategy of heavy courtship
and multiple invitations to visit the city. One on Jean-Claude
Ganga of the Republic of Congo suggested to ``ask if Danielle &AMP;
Vicki would like to come to Atlanta for another visit, as they are
in school in Canada and cannot go home often.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ganga notes also issued a reminder: ``Need to update him on
equipment that he requested for the School Games to be held Easter
1990.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Maynard Jackson presented crates of sports equipment and
clothing to Ganga, the Congolese minister of sports, apparently for
use at the National Interscholastic Games in March 1990. Jackson
also presented an electronic stadium scoreboard, which was funded
by the Coca-Cola Co., according to a U.S. state department
dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   Sibandze and Ganga are among several members mentioned in the
Atlanta files who either have been expelled by the IOC or resigned
after being accused of taking improper gifts, favors or direct cash
payments from the Salt Lake City bid committee. Guirandou-N'Diaye
received a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Notes on some members were missing from the ``IOC update''
document, which was contained in the files of Nancy Newton, a bid
team member in charge of international relations.
</P>
<P>
   The documents unveiled Tuesday in Sydney portrayed a different
approach. For example, Rosenbrock labeled Greek IOC member Lambis
Nikolaou as being ``very temperamental _ emphasis on mental.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that Lamine Kieta of Mali, who has been expelled, was
``more than prepared to take advantage of any expense allowance.
Not to be trusted I believe _ but said he supports Salt Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles has been reprimanded for benefiting from excessive
hospitality from the Salt Lake bid and is under investigation for
claims he received expensive jewelry from Athens' failed bid for
the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
