<HEADER>
A6165 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FURNITURE-HOLLYWOOD13     05-13 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNITURE-HOLLYWOOD13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Modern styles snatch second looks at High Point furniture market
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ As with fame, most things about Hollywood are
fleeting. Stars rise and fall. Marriages, like hair colors, come
and go.
</P>
<P>
   But remnants of Tinseltown's golden age of glamour endure in
furnishings made popular in the '20s, '30s and '40s _ art deco and
Art Moderne styles that graced silver screens around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the understated elegance of pieces with clean, sleek
lines and more graceful curves than Rita Hayworth have remained so
popular that designers are paying tribute to the period with more
retro-influenced furnishings than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Leather was among a half-dozen manufacturers showing new
interpretations of the era last month at the spring International
Home Furnishings Market in High Point, N.C. Cinema giant
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer licensed the company, which last year
introduced its Titanic collection, to create a line that captures
the glamour, romance and excitement of old Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about taking people into a world of Hollywood that wasn't
superficial but would last,'' said Linda Berman, manager of MGM's
consumer products division. ``Furniture was a serious player in
that world.''
</P>
<P>
   And now it's a serious player as retro rages and furniture
makers close their sketchbooks on a century of design. For fans of
modern, first popularized with elegant French art deco designs at
the 1925 Paris Exposition, its endurance lies in sharp curves,
simple lines and rectilinear shapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retro refers to the most beautiful modern things that we've
done in the past,'' fashion-turned-furniture designer Bob Mackie
said during a panel discussion on trends.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are banking on consumers wanting to cull the best of
modern design for homes they will decorate in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   When MGM approached Classic Leather about designing a line
inspired by Hollywood, ``It was a no-brainer,'' said Ron Freeman,
business development director for the leather manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael Zenie, a former fashion designer, tapped into the
moviemaker's extensive archive of 5,100 films produced over 75
years to design the 32-piece Classic Collection, including a bed,
sofa, dining room table and chairs, upholstered chairs and coffee
tables. But instead of re-creating pieces from particular films,
Zenie went for the overall mood of the period with clean lines and
understated style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to put myself in the shoes of a designer of the
period,'' said Zenie. ``I didn't want it to look all art deco.''
</P>
<P>
   Soft, luxurious fabrics, including velvet, mohair, leather and
Ultrasuede, envelope sofas and chairs in plush elegance, while
maple and black-lacquered finishes make the line versatile enough
to be dressed up or down.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces are practical for today's lifestyles. Zenie designed
a coffee table, for example, in six cubes, each of which can be
pulled out and used as an accent table or stool. End tables feature
shelves. ``I'm obsessed with having space,'' the designer said.
</P>
<P>
   A companion Hollywood collection, On Location, includes 21
pieces designed after furnishings featured in MGM movies filmed in
Africa. Light eucalyptus wood and rustic rattan give the line a
feel of the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Retail prices are expected to range from $250 for a campaign
folding chair in the On Location line to $2,500 for a Manhattan
cocktail table in the Classic Collection.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone in furniture knows glamour, it's Larry Laslo. The
flamboyant New York interior designer, whose creations several
years ago for Directional included pieces named for Marilyn Monroe
and Jean Harlow, introduced a retro line at last fall's market for
Bexley Heath by John Widdicomb. At this market, he expanded the
Moderne Collection to include a dining table and chairs and a
mahogany-based sofa, club chair and ottoman.
</P>
<P>
   Art deco-style woven Jacquard covers the dining chairs, and the
feet on others are boxy, with an Oriental flavor. Subtle fabric
patterns and bleached sycamore give the line a fresh, modern look.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all simple, cleaned up and pared down,'' said Laslo, who
never misses an opportunity to toss a little drama into his sofas
and chairs in the form of a fake fur.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Wolf also expanded his designs of modern-style
furnishings for Carson's. Wolf, one of the country's most published
designers, introduced his 20th Century Collection last year. His
newest pieces include a sectional sofa, which has found a new
following not only because of the retro revolution but because
family rooms have grown. Wolf's sofa is sold in a range of fabrics,
including velvet, chenille and silk.
</P>
<P>
   Designer John Mascheroni unveiled a kidney-shaped sofa, nearly
10 feet long, for Swaim, while Thayer Coggin introduced Jake, a new
lounge chair by Ransom Culler.
</P>
<P>
   Carson's also was ready to ride into the future. In addition to
the Wolf line, the company was showing Harley, a squatty armchair
with bulky arms designed to resemble a bike. Upholstered in a
two-tone suede, the chair is pitched so that it swallows its
occupant in cozy comfort. Talk about a throwback.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds like furniture designs are moving backward instead
of forward as the millennium nears, look at it this way: ``We're
still going to be looking backward, but it's really more a
re-examination of the century, an attempt to put an exclamation
mark on it,'' designer Jena Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best of those designs will continue into the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
