<HEADER>
A6166 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-FURNISHINGS14-CO     05-13 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-FURNISHINGS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Century-end furniture designs draw on simpler French, Asian
influences
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ If you're wondering where furnishings, like
fashions, are headed as the calendar turns to a new century, think
east _ as in France and beyond to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Not French as in ornate, heavily gilded pieces, or Oriental as
in highly lacquered, exotic ones. Think a casual French cottage,
influenced by the garden; and a softer, cleaner and simpler Asian
that carries a contemporary flavor.
</P>
<P>
   And while you're traveling, remember the curvy modern lines of
the 1920s, '30s and '40s, when the glamour of art deco was
prevalent in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense of casual elegance in what's happening, in
that we're turning back to the classic lines of the modern
period,'' designer Vladimir Kagan said during last month's
International Home Furnishings Market.
</P>
<P>
   French casual, modern Asian and retro influences were three of
the major directions furnishings seem to be taking at the world's
largest wholesale trade expo.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz on the streets of High Point, where more than 75,000
manufacturers, retailers, designers and media flock twice a year to
see what's headed to stores, was so thick with French you'd expect
to hear bonjour.
</P>
<P>
   The French they were describing was still elegant but more
relaxed, with the casual look of the provincial countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Among about a dozen manufacturers introducing French-inspired
designs was Highland House, which unveiled its Rue de Provence
collection. The 35 pieces are inspired by regional Provencal
antiques and colorful fabrics of the Mediterranean region. Buyers
could almost smell the rosemary and lavender as they touched the
multilayered stripes, florals and prints of bright red, blue and
yellow toile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a really fun, colorful feel,'' said Robin Tucker, a
company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Woods sported the aged whitewashed and rust finishes that have
become so popular among garden-inspired pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finishes are what's really attracting people to this
look,'' said Suzanne Pruitt, a spokeswoman for Toccoa-based
Habersham, which introduced its Cottage Collection.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-painted pieces draw on the country look, with crackled
and weathered finishes or colorful garden-inspired motifs. Many are
large amoires that make quite a statement as accent pieces that can
be mixed with a variety of other styles.
</P>
<P>
   Bairstow Designs honed in on country French with its new Colors
of Provence collection of hand-painted tables and chairs with woven
grass seats and 10 finishes. ``It's barefoot elegance,'' said Mary
Bairstow, president of the Atlanta company. ``Americans are
learning from Europeans that mixing pieces brings a casualness to
formal furnishings.''
</P>
<P>
   Even major manufacturers such as Stanley and Stickley jumped on
the Provence-bound bandwagon. Stanley showed its Mirabeau bedroom
and dining room line in relaxed warm brown finishes, while Stickley
launched its Directoire Collection of solid cherry and
walnut-accented pieces, featuring clean, simple lines.
</P>
<P>
   That simplicity was present in Asian-inspired furnishings as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Stressed-out Americans are paying homage to Zen principles,
simplifying their surroundings and creating spaces for meditation.
That atmosphere calls for scaled-down, simple designs that make for
a contemporary look.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tranquil, Asian look with exotic Burmese, Indonesian
designs that tie in with the whole globetrotting and collecting
movement going on these days,'' said Mark McMenamin, merchandising
and business editor for the trade journal Home Accents Today.
``It's not difficult to take these designs and make them more
contemporary, so you end up with a more modern Asian flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   As with most contemporary looks, Asian pieces can be mixed with
other styles to create an eclectic interior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asian has really evolved,'' said Paige Smith of PierceMartin,
an Atlanta manufacturer of wicker, rattan and iron furnishings and
importer of antiques from Hong Kong, Thailand and Indonesia.
``We're taking everyday things from Asian life and combining them
with other furnishings.''
</P>
<P>
   Elephant saddles that double as coffee tables. Old tribal drums
refinished as accessories. Lamps made from old pots.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are buying more individual pieces rather than entire
collections, as they do in fashion with sportswear,'' said Jena
Hall, among the designers at the market asked to forecast trends.
</P>
<P>
   And as the millennium approaches, they're turning to the best of
all styles of design, collecting pieces that carry nostalgic
sentiments of special times in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Retro influences were larger than ever at High Point _ and
should grow even larger, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really more a re-examination of the century, an attempt
to put a punctuation on it,'' she said. ``The best of these pieces
will continue into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
