<HEADER>
A6167 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKSHOP-PONDS13-COX     05-13 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKSHOP-PONDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pond makes the back yard a cool splash of relaxation
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    Photos by Jean Shefrin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Creating a pond for your yard is as simple as buying a
fiberglass shell and filling it with water.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it also requires a little digging and a vision of
what you want the finished pond to look like. So all the necessary
landscaping materials should be purchased ahead of time. Perhaps
the most difficult part of the job is finding family or friends to
help with the labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a minimum of two people. The more, the merrier,''
said Dan Wooley, assistant manager at Lowe's Home Improvement
Warehouse in Woodstock (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you'll need:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A preformed plastic or fiberglass shell
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A two-by-four
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A level
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A pond filter and fountain kit in size appropriate for pond
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An extension cord for outdoor use
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A water hose that can extend from water socket to the pond
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sand (enough to pack underneath and around pond)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tools (shovels, rakes, gloves and other digging tools )
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pond decor (rocks, plants, fish, flowers, etc., to landscape
around pond)
</P>
<P>
   Step 1:
</P>
<P>
   1. Place preformed pond shell on the ground, right side up. In
the ground, mark the circumference of the pond shell bottom and, if
the shape of the pond shell angles out, the circumference of its
top. Dig a hole that mimics the silhouette of the shell, angling
out from the inside marks to the outside marks and allowing for 2
inches of fill to be added later around the shell. Dig the hole the
approximate depth of the shell. Using a level, make sure the hole
is flat.
</P>
<P>
   Step 2:
</P>
<P>
   2. When bottom is even, add a 2-inch layer of damp sand. Spread
sand evenly along bottom. Sand will help pond shell fit snugly in
the hole and protect the fiberglass shell.
</P>
<P>
   Step 3:
</P>
<P>
   3. Carefully lower the shell into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Step 4:
</P>
<P>
   4. Lay a two-by-four on its edge across the shell and use a
level to recheck that it lies flat.
</P>
<P>
   Step 5:
</P>
<P>
   5. Slowly fill pond with water. Meanwhile, backfill around the
pond with remaining sand and dirt. Add 4 inches of sand and soil
around the shell, then 4 inches of water to the pond. Check shell
to make sure it is still level. If so, continue to backfill. If
not, remove or add backfill. Check level periodically until water
reaches top. It's important to make sure pond stays level until it
is full.
</P>
<P>
   Step 6:
</P>
<P>
   6. When pond is almost full, plug pond filter into a power
source. Place filter and fountain in the middle of the pond. Turn
on so filter can circulate water.
</P>
<P>
   Step 7:
</P>
<P>
   7. Place rocks, plants, flowers and other landscaping material
around border of the pond to give it a finished look.
</P>
<P>
   Step 8:
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the finished pond.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
