<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tuscan sun is still burning bright for author
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frances Mayes had a hunch her book ``Under the Tuscan Sun''
would do well. But she didn't realize her epicurean travelogue
about restoring a 200-year-old Italian villa would sell 900,000
copies and become a darling of book clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was a real mania for Italy,'' says Mayes, a South
Georgia native who lives in San Francisco but spends her summers in
Tuscany. ``More than 600,000 Americans go to Tuscany every year.
That's one reason the book sold. But readers also tell me they like
the fact that I took a risk in midlife and did something like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayes admits that buying the run-down stone farmhouse in 1985
could have been a disaster. The building was picturesque, but the
wiring and plumbing and almost everything else needed replacing.
Ignoring her friends' advice, Mayes and her partner, San Francisco
poet Ed Kleinschmidt, bought the house and began tearing out walls,
replacing pipes and sweeping out hordes of scorpions and spiders.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring the house and writing the book were just the therapy
she needed, says Mayes, who had just gone through a nasty divorce.
``Part of this whole thing was a quest to re-establish a new
identity. When you change a house, you're changing your own image
of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Mayes has moved to a new home in San Francisco _ one that
needs renovating _ and written ``Bella Tuscany: The Sweet Life in
Italy'' (Broadway, $25), a continuation of her first book. Filled
with recipes from Italy and reminiscences about her childhood in
Fitzgerald, ``Bella Tuscany'' is a celebration of the Italian
people and the ``voluptuousness'' of Italian life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was the first time I was able to live there during
the spring,'' says Mayes, who is on leave for a year from her
teaching post at San Francisco State University to write a novel
set in South Georgia. ``I discovered new tastes for my spring
kitchen such as the fresh fava beans and artichokes. There's a big
emphasis on food in Cortona. That's one thing that reminds me of my
hometown. If we weren't cooking food, we were talking about what we
were going to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayes will sign her book at 7 tonight at Chapter 11 in Peachtree
Battle Shopping Center, 2345-A Peachtree Road N.E., 404-237-7199.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW LIST: We've had the 100 greatest novels and 100 greatest
nonfiction books of the century. Now the Publishing Triangle has
assembled a team of 14 judges, including award-winning author
Dorothy Allison, to select the 100 Best Lesbian and Gay Novels.
This will not be just another list, says Charles Flowers, chairman
of the Publishing Triangle, an association of lesbians and gay men
in publishing. ``We hope this list will provoke debate about how to
define a `gay book' and the implications of such a category.
Consider the recent success of Michael Cunningham's `The Hours,' a
wonderful book which some readers are considering `gay' while
others are considering `crossover.' Where does the line between gay
and straight fall?''
</P>
<P>
   The list will be announced the first week of June, and readers
will be invited to respond to the selections on the Web site www
</P>
<P>
   .publishingtriangle.org to create a readers' choice list.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND OPERA: In 1920, Enrico Caruso was performing in the opera
``Aida'' when a bomb explosion rocked the Teatro Nacional in
Havana. A dazed Caruso was seen wandering the streets after the
incident, and then he disappeared for several days. Drawing on this
mystery, Cuban-born Mayra Montero has written ``The Messenger''
(HarperCollins, $24), a novel that blends African santeria and
Chinese magic with the few known facts to explain the great tenor's
disappearance. In Montero's fictional version of the events, a
beautiful Chinese woman named Aida Cheng rescues Caruso and briefly
becomes his lover, thus fulfilling the prophecy of Aida's
godfather, an Afro-Cuban santero named Jose de Calazan.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a television writer and actor, Montero, 47, is a
former journalist who was a visiting lecturer at Emory University
last semester. She will sign her book at 7 p.m. Tuesday at
Wordsworth Booksellers in Decatur, 2112 N. Decatur Road,
404-633-4275.
</P>
<P>
   HEALING THE WOUNDS: For 45 years, not even neighbors in Phenix
City, Ala., would discuss the night that Alabama Attorney
General-elect Albert Patterson was assassinated. ``That time is
like an open wound,'' says Phenix City Mayor Peggy Martin, who was
a young girl when criminal elements controlled the town and
prostitution and gambling were rampant. Now, Martin says, the wound
is beginning to heal because of Margaret Anne Barnes' book ``The
Tragedy and the Triumph of Phenix City, Alabama'' (Mercer
University Press, $24.95). Barnes' account of the town's struggle
to rid itself of corruption has sparked a needed dialogue, the
mayor says. In honor of the book, the Decatur writer will be given
a key to the city in a 2 p.m. ceremony Sunday at the Buchanan
House, 1040 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
