<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ADVENTURES16-CO     05-13 1500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ADVENTURES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New book list for the summer
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 16.
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two posthumously published novels and a sequel about a
psychopath head the list of new books this summer. Ralph Ellison's
``Juneteenth,'' Ernest Hemingway's ``True at First Light: A
Fictional Memoir'' and Thomas Harris' ``Hannibal'' may be the
season's blockbusters, but there are a lot of other options coming
soon to a bookstore or library near you. Below are some of the
highlights.
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Hannibal. By Thomas Harris. Dell Books. $27.95. Hannibal Lecter,
one of contemporary fiction's most chilling characters, is back,
and he still craves human flesh and a nice Chianti. A decade after
writing ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' the best seller that became
the Oscar-winning movie starring Jodie Foster and Anthony Hopkins,
Harris picks up the story seven years after the cannibalistic
killer's stunning escape from authorities. (June 8)
</P>
<P>
   Juneteenth. By Ralph Ellison. Random House. $25. When Ellison
died in 1994, he left unfinished his follow-up novel to ``Invisible
Man.'' His literary executor, John F. Callahan, edited the huge
manuscript into this novel, about a black jazz musician who becomes
a minister and raises a young boy who grows up to become a
race-baiting senator in New England. (June)
</P>
<P>
   A God in Ruins. By Leon Uris. HarperCollins. $27.50. The
literary lion (``Exodus,'' ``QB VII,'' ``Trinity'') jumps ahead to
2008, when a presidential candidate raised Catholic discovers he
was born Jewish. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Timbuktu. By Paul Auster. Henry Holt. $23. The endlessly
inventive Auster (the screenplay for ``Smoke'' and a memoir, ``Hand
to Mouth'') uses a canine narrator named Mr. Bones to spin a
tragic, comic tale. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Local Girls. By Alice Hoffman. Putnam. $22.95. A collection of
stories about the Samuelsons of Long Island, N.Y., a family torn
apart by tragedy and divorce, from the author of ``Here on Earth''
and ``Practical Magic.'' (June)
</P>
<P>
   The Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing. By Melissa Bank.
Viking. $23.95. In the seven collected stories of this debut
collection, witty and wise Jane navigates her way through love,
sex, relationships and career. (June)
</P>
<P>
   The Fencing Master. By Arturo Perez-Reverte. Harcourt Brace.
$24. The Spanish-born author of ``The Club Dumas'' and ``The
Seville Communion'' sets this elaborate historical mystery in
19th-century Madrid. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Back to the Moon. By Homer H. Hickam Jr. Delacorte. $23.95. The
space shuttle Columbia is hijacked by a renegade group of former
NASA insiders and headed for the moon. Hickam, a former NASA
engineer and author of the acclaimed memoir ``Rocket Boys''
(renamed ``October Sky'' for the big screen), tries his hand at
fiction for the first time. (June)
</P>
<P>
   True at First Light: A Fictional Memoir. By Ernest Hemingway.
Scribner. $26. Thirty-eight years after Hemingway's death by
self-inflicted gunshot, his son Patrick releases an edited account
based on his father's final safari in Africa and his love affair
with a young African woman. (July 6)
</P>
<P>
   Broke Heart Blues. By Joyce Carol Oates. Dutton. $24.95. John
Reddy Heart, a handsome young heartthrob in Willowsville, N.Y., is
implicated in his mother's murder and quickly becomes a celebrity
on the lam. (July)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick hits: Martin Cruz Smith brings back soulful Russian
detective Arkady Renko (``Gorky Park'') in a new thriller, ``Havana
Bay'' (Random House, $25.95, June). . . . Kay Scarpetta is back in
Patricia Cornwell's ``Black Notice'' (Putnam, $25.95, July 5),
taking on a case that begins with the discovery of a decomposed
stowaway on a cargo ship and ultimately careens across
international borders. . . . And former Atlanta Falcon Tim Green
sets another thriller in the world of professional football in
``Double Reverse'' (Warner Books, $24, August).
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHY/
</P>
<P>
   MEMOIR
</P>
<P>
   The View From Alger's Window. By Tony Hiss. Knopf. $24. Hiss
provides a new perspective on his father's life and relates his own
experience as a young boy during his father's trial for perjury in
a controversial espionage case. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Clear Springs. By Bobbie Ann Mason. Random House. $25. Novelist
Mason (``Feather Crowns,'' ``In Country'') recounts her escape from
the family's Kentucky farm and eventual return to country life.
(June)
</P>
<P>
   Encore Provence: New Adventures in the South of France. By Peter
Mayle. Knopf. $23. More Francophile frolics from the author of ``A
Year in Provence'' and ``Toujours Provence.'' (June)
</P>
<P>
   Undressed: The Life and Times of Gianni Versace. By Christopher
Mason. Little, Brown. $25. Mason delves into the complex world of
the late fashion designer, from his early years in Italy to his
murder in front of his palatial Miami home. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Denmark Vesey: The Buried History of America's Largest Slave
Rebellion. By David Robertson. Knopf. $23. Robertson profiles the
leader on a failed early 19th-century slave revolt that ended with
Vesey and five co-conspirators being hanged on July 22, 1822,
outside Charleston, S.C. (July)
</P>
<P>
   George Eliot: The Last Victorian. By Kathryn Hughes. Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux. $30. Hughes investigates the personal dramas that
shaped Eliot's life and work. (July)
</P>
<P>
   House of Steps: Adventures of a Southerner in Kansas. By Amy
Blackmarr. Viking. $22.95. In 1997's ``Going to Ground,'' Blackmarr
told of her Thoreauvian journey from city life to her grandfather's
pond-side cabin in Georgia. In this second book of essays, she
continues her personal odyssey, moving from Georgia to a house on a
northeast Kansas bluff. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Edward Albee: A Singular Journey. By Mel Gussow. Simon &AMP;
Schuster. $30. Gussow takes readers through the lauded playwright's
rocky life and offers insight into his work. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kaufman Revealed! By Bob Zmuda. Little, Brown. $24. Close
friend and producer Zmuda shares his memories of the influential
comedian in anticipation of the fall release of the Kaufman biopic
starring Jim Carrey. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Lady Bird: A Biography of Mrs. Johnson. By Jan Jarboe Russell.
Scribner. $26. An award-winning Texas journalist tells the life
story of a beloved former first lady and wildflower activist.
(August)
</P>
<P>
   I Will Bear Witness: A Diary of the Nazi Years, 1941-1945
(Volume 2). By Victor Klemperer. Random House. $29.95. Klemperer's
first volume, published in English last year, was a mesmerizing
day-by-day account of the horrors and humiliations suffered by
millions of German Jews. Volume 2 includes the Dresden professor's
diary entries through the end of Hitler's war. (August)
</P>
<P>
   NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   Shadow: Five Presidents and the Legacy of Watergate. By Bob
Woodward. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $27.50. Following a paper trail of
confidential memos, meeting notes, diaries and detailed
recollections of participants, Woodward examines how all the
presidential scandals have affected Ford, Reagan, Carter, Bush and
Clinton _ personally and in their ability to govern. (June 18)
</P>
<P>
   The Embrace: A True Vampire Story. By Aphrodite Jones. Pocket
Books. $23. Jones looks at black magic and Satanism among bored,
disenfranchised teenagers. (June)
</P>
<P>
   God's Funeral: The Decline of Faith in Western Civilization. By
A.N. Wilson. Norton. $29.59. Wilson, a formidable critic and
biographer of Tolstoy, C.S. Lewis and Jesus, reveals that doubts
about the existence of God had many sources. (June)
</P>
<P>
   We Were the Land's: The Biography of a Homeplace. By John Head.
Longstreet. $22. Head, a member of The Atlanta Constitution's
editorial board, brings his grandfather's house back to life while
exploring the meaning of family, community and our connection to
the past. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Like a River: The Black Church and Social Reform. By
Andrew Billingsley. Oxford. $25. Billingsley, a professor at the
University of South Carolina, surveys 1,000 black churches across
the country, including the oldest, the First African Baptist Church
in Savannah. (June)
</P>
<P>
   Due South: Dispatches From Down Home. By R. Scott Brunner.
Villard. $19.95. A collection of essays on daily life from a
National Public Radio commentator who grew up in Bessemer, Ala.,
and lives in Brandon, Miss. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Virus. By Luc Montagnier. Norton. $24.95. The co-discoverer of
HIV brings an insider's perspective to the history and science of
AIDS. (July)
</P>
<P>
   Nabokov's Butterflies: Unpublished and Uncollected Writings.
Edited by Brian Boyd and Robert Michael Pyle. Beacon Press. $45.
Newly translated works by Vladimir Nabokov on the twin passions of
his life: literature and lepidopterology. (August)
</P>
<P>
   The Last Survivor: In Search of Martin Zaidenstadt. By Timothy
Ryback. Pantheon. $21. Ryback draws a portrait of the town and
townspeople of Dachau, Germany, and their daily struggle with a
troubling past. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Weaver writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
