<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ALTAR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author's latest novel explores lost chance for racial
reconciliation following Civil War
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 16.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``Cold Mountain'' began rising to the top of best-seller
lists in 1997, Charles Price got a sinking feeling. The North
Carolina author, who has written one critically acclaimed novel
about the Civil War, was nearly finished with his second when
Charles Frazier's book rolled into stores like a Union juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crestfallen,'' says Price, 60, who lives in a mountain
cabin north of Asheville. ``I thought my book would get
overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Price has no illusions that his ``Freedom's Altar''
(John F. Blair, $19.95) will be the phenomenon that ``Cold
Mountain'' was, early reviews have been laudatory.
</P>
<P>
   In Publishers Weekly, the national trade magazine for
booksellers, a critic wrote that Price's novel ``eloquently
addresses questions of race and class and morality, poignantly
exploring whether hope and loyalty can exist in a world where war
has damaged lives irrevocably.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Hodges, a literary columnist for the Durham, N.C.,
Herald-Sun, was equally impressed. ``It was extremely well
written,'' Durham says. ``It was a tighter, shorter `Cold
Mountain.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Frazier's novel chronicles the odysseys of two lovers
separated by the war, Price's book focuses on the aftermath of the
conflict, when former slaves and masters attempt to get along.
</P>
<P>
   As the novel opens, Union Army soldier and former slave Daniel
McFee has returned home to propose a sharecropping venture with his
former master, Judge Madison Curtis. The judge is surprised that
the man he once owned seems to regard him now with less friendship
and respect. Meanwhile, a madman called Nahum Bellamy the Pilot
rides roughshod through the country, whipping freed slaves into a
frenzy and seeking revenge on former Rebel soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Price, whose first novel, ``Hiwassee'' (Academy Chicago
Publishers, $20), dealt with the war itself, decided to examine the
moral question of slavery in this sequel. ``In particular I wanted
to explore what seemed to me a lost opportunity for racial
reconciliation in the South immediately after the war,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When people think of Reconstruction, Price says, they think of
the period after 1867 when Congress imposed Radical Reconstruction.
But immediately after the war, he says, the South could have chosen
its own course in regard to the races.
</P>
<P>
   Both novels are loosely based on Price's family. In the first,
he traces the careers of his great-great-grandfather Oliver Price
and three of his great-great uncles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in there is verified by my research,'' he says. ``I
tried to imagine what it was like on the home front. I did research
on what was happening in North Carolina and North Georgia. I also
wanted to explore the ethical and moral questions of folks who
owned no slaves at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Like some other Southerners, Price's great-great grandfather was
opposed to slavery but still felt duty-bound to fight for the
Confederacy. In ``Freedom's Altar,'' Oliver Price represents the
poor white man who is seeking a place in the newly emancipated
society.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Methodist minister, Price worked as a journalist,
urban planner and lobbyist before retiring to write fiction.
Divorced and childless, he quit his job as a lobbyist about four
years ago and began writing full time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided I was going to do it, although sometimes I wake
up in the middle of the night with cold sweat on my brow.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
