<HEADER>
A6176 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-DREAM14-COX     05-13 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-DREAM14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magic is missing from this `Dream'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A sexy cast, a classic play, the sensuous Tuscan countryside.
How could ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' misfire? Blame it on
director Michael Hoffman, whose picturesque but pedestrian approach
dims the sparkle of William Shakespeare's script.
</P>
<P>
   The movie changes the play's ancient Athens to
turn-of-the-century Italy. In this predecessor of screwball comedy,
Christian Bale, Calista Flockhart, Anna Friel and Dominic West are
the mismatched lovers who, on a long night in the woods, get
romantically mixed and matched by fairy king Oberon (Rupert
Everett) and his goaty henchman Puck (Stanley Tucci). Meanwhile, a
hammy actor named Bottom (Kevin Kline) becomes the donkey-headed
love object of the fairy queen Titania (Michelle Pfeiffer), herself
a victim of Puck's spells.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Kenneth Branagh's updatings of ``Hamlet'' and ``Much Ado
About Nothing,'' the transplants here don't make much organic
sense, starting with the setting of Mount Athens, Italy, to justify
the script's Athenian references. Bicycles play supporting roles,
though there's no big payoff. Hoffman's choices seem arbitrary, an
excuse to doll his mortal actors up in nice Edwardian duds. While
the director's ``Restoration'' was a visual feast, his enchanted
forest is strictly of the kitschy, glitter-and-greasepaint variety.
We get Hammer Horror sets, not-so-special effects and a fairy court
that moons around like an out-of-work circus troupe.
</P>
<P>
   As if some strange spell has been cast on the film itself,
everything seems slightly off kilter. The ``Dream'' of the title
seems too literal; the lines are well-spoken, but there's a sense
of sleepwalking vagueness to the story. The ever-actory Kline is a
perfect choice for the role of that uber-ham, Bottom, but even he
seems subdued in places. And though Hoffman tries to juice things
up with some scenic nudity, the movie isn't especially sexy or
funny. You know you're not dealing with a nuances comic director
when the cat fight between Helena and Hermia climaxes with a round
of mud-wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the end does the movie find a rare grace note, during
the comic coda featuring Bottom and his fellow actors staging a
wonderfully awful version of ``Pyramus and Thisbe.'' Sam Rockwell,
as the sketch's doomed heroine, expertly switches from his
vaudeville drag turn into a performance of unexpected poignancy.
The moment reminds us that even the silliest-seeming love affair
can, in an instant, become heartbreakingly powerful. It's a bit of
acting sleight of hand that delivers ``Dream'' one of its rare bits
of true magic.
</P>
<P>
   Too little, too late. Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``William Shakespeare's
</P>
<P>
   A Midsummer
</P>
<P>
   Night's Dream''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Kline, Michelle
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer, Stanley Tucci, Rupert
</P>
<P>
   Everett and Calista Flockhart. Rated PG-13 for sexuality and
nudity. 1 hour, 55 minutes. At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Sometimes, magic doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
