<HEADER>
A6177 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-TRIPPIN'14-COX     05-13 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-TRIPPIN'14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Trippin' ' stumbles over mixed message
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a student who parties every night but still expects to make
the honor roll, ``Trippin' '' is a movie that wants to have it both
ways. It keeps trippin' up on its own mixed message.
</P>
<P>
   Deon Richmond plays Greg, aka ``G,'' a high school senior whose
plans for college keep getting waylaid by his fantasies of living
the phat life, surrounded by gorgeous women whose sole goal in life
is to show him their breasts.
</P>
<P>
   G's parents try to snap him out of it, sliding college
applications under his nose. But he's too busy hanging with his
pals June (Donald Adeosun Faison) and Fish (Guy Torry) to think
about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Then he falls for Cinny (Maia Campbell), a smart, curvaceous
classmate. She already has a boyfriend, but G starts to win her
over. Their growing romance is something the movie makes us take on
faith; it's hard to buy Cinny falling for G, who's just an
overgrown kid. The idea, of course, is that G learns to grow up
through love, responsibility and respect.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice thought. So is the movie's stress on the importance
of education. But the message gets muddied by the nonstop fantasy
parade of T&AMP;A. ``Trippin' '' has genuine flashes of charm and
heart, but they're undermined by the filmmakers' pandering to the
basic instincts of its target teen audience. One dream scene
features a recruiter from a college called ``Morehoward,'' known as
``Mo Ho'' for short. And we get the spectacle of June turning a
naked woman into a banana split, via whipped cream and chocolate
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   When June calls a woman a ``bitch,'' the movie lets her punch
him out. He also gets his comeuppance from the many girls he's lied
to. Still, it doesn't compensate for the ways ``Trippin' ''
presents most of its women as playthings. Even Cinny never gets to
be more than an idealized dream girl.
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's subplots has June getting pressed into service
by the neighborhood drug dealer. The plot seems to be an excuse to
trot out a ``Termin-ator''-style fantasy for G, an ammo-heavy
revenge scenario that's difficult to enjoy so soon after the
Littleton, Colo., slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and for the record, this is another of the countless recent
teen flicks that climax at a prom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trippin'''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Deon Richmond and Donald Adeosun Faison. Rated R
</P>
<P>
   for sexuality and language. At
</P>
<P>
   metro theaters. 1 hour, 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Trips up on its awkward mix of positive message and
sleazy pandering.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
