<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PLATINUM14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Double' divas make film that's easy on the ears
 &HT;    By Lyle Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The term ``diva'' has been hijacked by every bratty one-hit
wonder with a good agent and bad publicity, but Diana Ross puts
most of them to shame.
</P>
<P>
   After famously dumping the Supremes during Motown's heyday, Ross
has rarely shared a marquee, or her prodigious talent, with other
female vocalists. So it's a surprise to see her co-starring with
teeny-bop sensation Brandy Norwood in the ABC movie, ``Double
Platinum.''
</P>
<P>
   Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   Norwood has a new solo album, and although Ross hasn't had a hit
in years, this movie (which she executive produced) coincides with
the release of her latest album.
</P>
<P>
   Together, their music covers the 18-to-49 demographic TV
networks die for: Ross has a lock on baby boomers who have a copy
of ``Ain't No Mountain High Enough'' on vinyl, while Norwood
appeals to a younger set who grew up watching her UPN sitcom
``Moesha'' and buying her Grammy-winning CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Double Platinum'' is the improbable story of struggling
Atlanta nightclub singer Olivia Harris (Ross) who abandons her
infant daughter Kayla (Norwood) and perpetually ticked-off husband
to land a record deal in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward 18 years later and Ross is star with millions of
fans, including the all grown up, but still unsuspecting Kayla who
(surprise!) wants to be a singer.
</P>
<P>
   They are re-united by a series of embarrassing plot
contrivances, and mom promises to help Kayla get in the recording
business. Kayla's career takes off and she falls for her adorable
handler Ric (Allen Payne), even as her resentment toward Olivia
simmers.
</P>
<P>
   To reveal more would spoil what little ``Double Platinum''
offers. The message is clear enough though: show biz is full of
slimy characters but your mama knows best _ even if she's one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Sure Ross and Norwood can act, but it's not a requirement for
what amounts to a two-hour music video with some annoying dialogue
thrown in. It's when Ross and Norwood sing that the movie briefly
soars.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' voice is as commanding and supple as ever. The rest of her
ain't too shabby either, and as proof there's a gratuitous shot of
her prancing around in her delicate undergarments.
</P>
<P>
   Less flattering aspects of Ross's persona are also intact
including the toothy-but-joyless grin, the unfortunate hairweave,
and the patented move in which she raises her arms triumphantly
after each song, giving us an unobstructed view of her
neatly-manicured pits.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood sings several hits from her own album, and her breathy
alto meshes perfectly with Ross' sexy, slippery soprano during a
closing duet ``Love is All that Matters.''
</P>
<P>
   As a movie, ``Double Platinum'' is not much to look at. But
listening to a bona fide diva like Ross, and a diva-in-the-making
like Norwood makes this one of the better TV movies we've heard in
a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Double Platinum''
</P>
<P>
   Airs Sunday at 9 on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
