<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STEERING TEXAS MEDIA FOCUS AWAY FROM PRESIDENTIAL BID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, who has been trying to
lower state news media attention on his presidential bid,
threatened to walk out of a meeting with Longview civic leaders
this week because a local reporter was there taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really strange behavior,'' Longview News-Journal
Publisher Glenn McCutchen said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McCutchen said Bush was talking about his possible run for the
Republican presidential nomination when he spotted reporter Mike
Elswick. He said Bush demanded three times that Elswick stop taking
notes or the meeting with Longview leaders would be over.
</P>
<P>
   McCutchen was among about 25 Longview civic leaders who met Bush
at the Capitol on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's outburst with the Longview delegation fits a recent
pattern by Bush's staff to keep public focus on his job as governor
rather than his presidential exploratory bid as the state
Legislature enters its final weeks in session.
</P>
<P>
   Many events are being left off Bush's public schedule,
particularly if they have a political tone.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Bush spoke of his presidential aspirations two
weeks ago to about 1,000 members of the Texas Federation of
Republican Women during a luncheon at the Austin Convention Center.
The meeting was open to the public, but no news media covered the
speech because it was not on the governor's public schedule so
reporters didn't know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, his public schedule did not reflect the fund-raising
event Bush hosted last Saturday in Austin for Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. Nor did the schedule list the governor's
receipt of an award Wednesday before students, faculty and parents
of Austin High.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's schedule for this Saturday lists his commencement speech
at Southern Methodist University. However, it doesn't mention
Bush's featured role later that same day at a Texas Right to Life
Committee, $5,000-a-plate fund-raiser at The Mansion on Turtle
Creek. The fund-raiser has been closed to the news media at the
request of his presidential exploratory committee, event organizers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the schedule only reflects
the fact that Bush has some events that are public and some that
are considered private.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put public events on the governor's public schedule, and
some events are private events,'' Hughes said. ``We have tried to
make sure he remains accessible to the media at least once a week,
and we have done so all (this legislative) session.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes noted that Bush was available for news media questions
Tuesday and Thursday this week.
</P>
<P>
   She said the confrontation between Bush and the Longview
reporter occurred because the event was a photo-opportunity, not a
news conference. ``We make it very clear that these are photo
sessions only for pictures with the governor. These are not media
events. These are not news conferences.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCutchen said Bush's staff was given a list of 25 people
who would be meeting with the governor Wednesday, including the
name of the Longview reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're naive in Longview, but it seems odd that you could
go off the record in public,'' McCutchen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can be off the record with a group of 25 people, that's
an interesting proposition,'' the publisher said. ``It's like he's
saying, `I'm standing before you and my lips are moving, but
nothing is coming out.'''
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred as Bush met Wednesday with members of the
Longview Chamber of Commerce and Convention and Visitors Bureau in
the Governor's reception room at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The News-Journal reported Thursday that Bush shot Elswick ``a
laser beam look'' and said the meeting was ``off the record.'' The
governor warned that if Elswick did not stop taking notes, Bush
would leave the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   McCutchen said that even after Elswick complied with Bush's
request, Bush twice questioned the reporter about whether his tape
recorder was turned off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that a third time, as if the reporter was a dishonest
person,'' McCutchen said.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Thursday, Bush responded to a story in
Wednesday's Houston Chronicle that questioned whether he has been
less involved in this Legislature because of his presidential bid.
The Chronicle story was based on a review of Bush's office
calendars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because it's not on the calendar, it doesn't mean I'm not
spending a lot of time meeting with members of the House and the
Senate,'' Bush said. ``It still feels like I'm spending as much
time with members of the House and Senate as I have in previous
sessions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle reported Wednesday that Bush's calendars showed
his scheduled meetings with civic leaders and legislators during
the 1999 session are about half the number he had during the 1997
session.
</P>
<P>
   The records also indicated Bush had spent twice as many hours on
presidential campaign meetings as he had in scheduled meetings with
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
