<HEADLINE>
RILEY, MIAMI TAKING THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Riley's practices can be tests of will, stamina,
and purpose. Thursday's also was something else: a chance for the
game's eminent coaching mind to remind his bruised forces that it
might be their last get-together for quite awhile. Even the players
don't want that.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Heat face elimination Friday at the hands of the
dreaded Knicks, a team Riley likes even less than the Celtics. The
teams have played three games and Miami has been bludgeoned in two
of them. One more slip and the Heat become the first Eastern
Conference No. 1 seed to lose in the first round since the 16-team
format was adopted in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, they were the first _ and only _ Eastern Conference
team to lose as a No. 2 seed in the first round. That happened last
year. The opponent? The Knicks. Only one Eastern Conference team
has ever lost twice in the first round: Atlanta in 1994. Its
opponent? The Heat.
</P>
<P>
   This is obviously not the situation Riley envisioned as the Heat
entered the first Jordan-less postseason in four years with their
eye on the prize. But the Knicks know them and are not fazed by
them; only six games separated the teams in the regular season.
There's a lot of history and enmity at work here. Riley, once
revered in New York, is now the target of numerous ``Riley bleeps''
chants from the enlightened crowd at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one of Miami's top offensive weapons, Tim Hardaway,
is playing like tim hardaway and one of its best defensive players,
Dan Majerle, has a right shoulder with more breaks than a 60-footer
at St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the team that got me here and will get me over the
top,'' Riley said Thursday. ``Or else, we'll all go down
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway is the main concern. He has a sore right knee and
resembles only in name the Miami point guard who delighted in
torching the Knicks in years past. In three games, Hardaway has
made 6 of 32 shots. In Game 3, a 24-point Miami loss, he made one
basket _ a layup.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of scoring is only a small part of the problem.
Hardaway isn't breaking down the defenses. He's not dishing and
penetrating. The crossover dribble is almost nonexistent. This was
one position the Heat felt they had a big advantage, but he's
getting outplayed by Charlie Ward and Chris Childs. He was so
ineffective and frustrated in Game 3 that he earned himself an
ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Is Hardaway hurting to the point where he won't be the same
Hardaway until next season? He wasn't talking Thursday, but Riley
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to ask him,'' the coach said. ``I put five names
on the card. I expect them to play. He took a hit two months ago
(against Detroit) but for the last six weeks, the doctors say he's
OK and he says he's OK. He doesn't want to hear it. That's the way
it is in this league. It's just like Patrick's Achilles'. We don't
want to hear it. He doesn't want to hear it. We have to move
forward as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   This being a time when men are men, no one is cutting anyone any
slack. Ewing is day to day with his Achilles'. Majerle's situation
is a joke. He has bone spurs on his collarbone. There are fractures
in those spurs. He played 18 invisible minutes in Game 3 and has
made two baskets in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Riley hinted he may employ Voshon Lenard more. At least Lenard
can shoot. His problem: he was out all year and he's seen as a
defensive liability. Riley tends to constrict his roster at playoff
time. Lenard and Mark Strickland, an active body, are the
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about those options, Riley interrupted to say, ``the
options are execution and execution.''
</P>
<P>
   We trust he meant running the plays correctly on the floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
