<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-RACESUIT-COX     05-13 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-RACESUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge gives plantiffs in Coke race suit free reign; CEO Ivester
not chastised
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Federal Judge Richard Story said he will give broad
freedom to African-American plaintiffs to talk with Coca-Cola
employees who may want to join a racial discrimination suit against
the company.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Story did not chastise Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer M. Douglas Ivester for discussing the merits of
the suit in e-mails to employees, and said he will not order
Ivester to withdraw his statements.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing in U.S. District Court in Atlanta focused mostly on
the rights of the company and plaintiffs to communicate with
Coca-Cola employees about the case. But the judge also outlined
plans to speed up the process for determining if the issues can go
to trial on a class-action basis.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Story conducted the hearing informally, but said he will
issue a formal order within days, outlining the rules governing
what company officials and attorneys for the plaintiffs can say to
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a judge who generally stands against any prior restraint
to communication,'' Story said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, however, raised several probing questions for Cyrus
Mehri, lead attorney for the plaintiffs, about an Internet site
(www.essential.org/action/spotlight/coke/complaint.html) that
carries the full text of the complaint against Coca-Cola. He
appeared concerned that the site gave an advantage to plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will consider some proposed alterations to that site,'' he
said, though Mehri indicated he did not control the Web site. The
attorney acknowledged that he had made the lawsuit available to the
site, which is run by a Ralph Nader affiliate called The Essential
Information.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, John Richard of the Nader group said
the site was a forum for various interest groups without the means
to publish their own information, including groups against
Microsoft, a boycott Shell organization and groups against the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Richard suggested that the judge, who is newly appointed the
federal bench, could run afoul of free speech rights if he
attempted to restrict the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long has this judge been in office,'' Richard asked. ``Has
he gotten down to the amendments to the Constitution yet?''
</P>
<P>
   Story also repeatedly expressed considerable discomfort with
lawyers talking to the press about the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer to see more talk between the lawyers to get
this case along, and less talk in the media,'' he said. But the
judge stopped short of suggesting a gag order on comments.
</P>
<P>
   Communication policy aside, there had been some speculation that
certification of a class could take years, but Story clearly leaned
toward a decision within months.
</P>
<P>
   He outlined steps for the lawyers that could expedite the
all-important first phase of determining if a class of plaintiffs
exists. The company would be required to open its employee
database, including statistics on pay, promotions and other
potential evidence of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the form of the information supplied by Coca-Cola-Cola
might be a problem, Mehri said, ``as long as it is readable and
workable, we can make use of it.'' He said he would report to the
court if there were problems with the company data.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers for Coca-Cola said they would make a motion
soon to dismiss the case as not being a valid class action
complaint embracing misconduct by the company.
</P>
<P>
   But, in a broad hint, Story indicated it would be hard for him
to dismiss the case before the full process of determining the
class had been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the company, and for the plaintiffs, took some
satisfaction from Story's comments during the Thursday hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very pleased that the judge approved of our broad
right to communicate,'' said Elizabeth Finn Johnson, a company
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Said Mehri, ``we were pleased and impressed with the judge's
diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
