<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS NEED TO GET BACK TO THEIR GAME PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ It's a sales job now. Make 'em believe. Make 'em
want. Make 'em buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a learning process,'' said coach Pat Burns, hoping his
club can pull even in Game 4 of its playoff series here Friday
against the Sabres. ``Some of that is unteachable, but it is
livable _ and they are living it.''
</P>
<P>
   Life's lessons Wednesday night had the Bruins living and
learning the bad. They entered the third period with a 2-1 lead on
the scoreboard, needing only to survive 20 more minutes to take a
more important 2-1 lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, they were 3-2 losers, their game plan not
coming so much unglued as much as it was eroded by a persistent,
tenacious third-period attack by the Sabres. The Bruins veered
slightly off course with their game plan, lost sight of how to
pressure the puck and how to deploy their defensive coverages, and
the win they thought they had in hand quickly was handed over to
the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat can only do so much,'' said Boston netminder Byron Dafoe.
``At this point, really, it comes down to us. It's a matter of who
wants it more. Who will put it all on the line? No more talking.
Now we all have to get it together and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have come this far this season, to Round 2 of the
Stanley Cup playoffs, because of youth. They are now in trouble, in
part, for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   On top of those pockets of immaturity, injuries are now
beginning to take serious bites out of their depth. Don Sweeney
(back injury) won't play. Sergei Samsonov (back spasms) was a
scratch for Game 3. Tim Taylor is a walking voodoo doll, taking
three needles before every game to cope with pain in his shoulder
and ribs. On one hand Burns is trying to coax along a lineup that,
in key places, has yet to prove itself in the postseason. On the
other hand, aches and pains are taking the shoot and pass right out
of his club's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's physical out there,'' said Burns. ``Everyone has to
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the injuries, the Bruins can get back in this series,
but they'll have to rely heavily on the lines centered by Joe
Thornton and Jason Allison. This is nothing new. Headed into this
series, they knew the Allison line _ then with Samsonov and Dmitri
Khristich as wingers _ would have to play much better than in the
previous round against Carolina. Thornton's line, with Steve Heinze
and Anson Carter as the shooters _ would have to carry over its
momentum from Round 1.
</P>
<P>
   Not once in this series, however, have the two lines played well
in the same game. In Game 2, both combinations played poorly, part
of a team-wide letdown. In Game 3, Thornton's line was much
improved _ Burns called Thornton a ``force'' and a ``horse of a
man'' _ but the Allison line again was a huge disappointment. The
talented pivot had Landon Wilson on the left side, filling in for
Samsonov, and Khristich on the right. Wilson showed some of the
flashes that made him look like a budding power forward in the
series vs. the 'Canes. Khristich, once more, looked overwhelmingly
disinterested.
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested here after Game 2 that the Bruins need one of
their young forwards to step up in this series and take charge of
the offense, in the spirit of a Bryan Trottier or Mark Messier.
Thornton, the youngest and perhaps most talented of the bunch, took
a stride toward doing that in Game 4. Even with his learning curve
angled sharply upward of late, he alone can't carry this team.
</P>
<P>
   It very well could be that the Allison-Michael Peca matchup
determines whether the Bruins make a series out of this. Peca has
been the inside-the-shirt and down-the-pants pest that everyone
knew he would be in this series. Allison has been unable to shake
him, in part because neither of his linemates have posed any kind
of surrounding threat.
</P>
<P>
   But rarely are these matchups simply one-on-one,
center-vs.-center affairs. Let's say Allison can outplay Peca,
either by finesse or brute force. Will his wingers make anything
out of his head-to-head victories? Thus far that hasn't been the
case. Allison can get more physical and more confrontational with
Peca _ in fact, if he doesn't the show is over _ but he'll need
much better efforts from his wingers. Don't be surprised if Burns
slaps Ken Belanger on one of those wings, in hopes of implementing
a better forechecking game and getting some improved work in the
corners. The coach keeps sticking with Khristich, in hopes that
he'll start playing one day this spring, but eventually he'll have
no choice but to abandon that goodwill effort.
</P>
<P>
   The salesman in Burns now must keep after the likes of Allison,
Carter, and Thornton on the offense, Hal Gill and even Kyle McLaren
on defense. They are the ones young enough and impressionable
enough to listen, to try, to improve. They still have upsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be easy to blame our youth and our lack of
experience,'' said captain Ray Bourque. ``But we all went through
the last series and we were down in that, 2-1. That wasn't easy,
either, but we responded well. Yeah, sure, we've got a lot of young
guys, but they're young guys who've played well for us, and we
expect they'll do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no options now. Burns must keep coaxing his kids, keep
after those who ultimately must carry the team. He made a point
Thursday after saying that he didn't tell his team anything after
the disappointing loss in Game 3. He held a brief team meeting
Thursday before a light on-ice workout and emphasised how much they
had done correctly. He is dwelling on the positive. This is no time
for a bad cop. He is the good cop, carrying a salesman's briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all maturity,'' said Burns, knowing full well that age is
measured not so much in years as in games played, ``that's all it
is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
