<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FERNANDO-TATIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERNANDO TATIS GIVES THE CARDINALS, AND HIMSELF, MUCH TO SMILE
ABOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Fernando Tatis smiles a lot these days.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals third baseman smiles when he's on the
field, bantering with shortstop Edgar Renteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always making jokes,'' Tatis said. ``I'm the funny guy.
He's kind of serious, and I always say just relax. Be like me.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles in the clubhouse before the game. He smiles about the
day he set a major-league record by hitting two grand slams in one
inning, and about the fact that he _ not record-setting slugger
Mark McGwire _ leads the team in homers and RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy,'' said Tatis, 24. ``I'm having fun right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles even wider when he thinks about becoming the next
Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis probably never will have a season like Sosa did last year,
when he hit 66 homers and drove in 158 runs. But, like Sosa, he can
be good enough to make the Rangers regret trading him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they made a mistake,'' Tatis said.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis wasn't smiling last July 31, when the Rangers dealt him to
the Cardinals. He came up through the Texas farm system, touted as
a top prospect, and was in just his second full season in the
majors. He planned on a long, successful career in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed,'' he said. ``A lot of things went
through my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew why he Darren Oliver and minor-league outfielder Mark
Little were traded for Royce Clayton and Todd Stottlemyre. The
Rangers were trying to win the American League West title. Clayton
provided an upgrade at shortstop, and Stottlemyre improved the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' short-term prospects were more important than
Tatis' long-term potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to be in the playoffs,'' he said. ``They needed
Stottlemyre, so that's why they traded me. But they made a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin has said he would make the
trade again. The team won the West, although they were knocked out
by the New York Yankees in the first round of the playoffs. That's
something that didn't happen when the club traded Sosa and Wilson
Alvarez for Harold Baines.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also made the trade knowing they might be
second-guessed if Tatis matured into the front-line player they
thought he could be. They didn't necessarily think it would happen
this soon, however.
</P>
<P>
   Through Tuesday's games Tatis was tied for third in the National
League with 11 homers _ four more than McGwire _ and was second in
the league with 34 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   He only had 11 homers all of last season, three in 95 games (330
at-bats) with the Rangers and eight in 55 games (202 at-bats) with
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great stroke,'' Cardinals hitting coach Mike Easler
said. ``And he's learning what pitchers are doing to him. You've
got to know No. 1, what you're doing mechanically, and No. 2, what
the pitchers are trying to do to you. He's starting to figure these
things out. He's a good student.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatis showed power potential in the minor leagues. He hit 24
homers at Double-A Tulsa in 1997, and added eight more after being
promoted to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   No one, though, expected him to be among the top sluggers in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   While Tatis' power is helping the Cardinals stay competitive in
the NL Central, McGwire warns his teammate about wanting to be like
Mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hitting home runs, but you can't call him a home-run
hitter,'' McGwire said. ``He's a doubles hitter who's just hitting
home runs. I told him, `That would be the worst thing the media can
do, is start driving into your head that you're a home-run hitter,
because you're not.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worked very, very hard on his swing. He's getting pitches
to hit, and he's driving them out of the ballpark. But it's easy to
fall into that trap. That's why I'm trying to discourage it. Labels
are not good, unless you're an older player and you have a track
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but Tatis has worn the label of ``good hitter'' every
since the trade. He batted .287 with eight homers and 26 runs
batted in during the final two months with the Cardinals last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started doing a lot better,'' he said. ``I started having a
lot of fun over here. There wasn't a lot of pressure, like there
was in Texas. I played a lot more relaxed over here.''
</P>
<P>
   The smiles don't lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun,'' he said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
