<HEADER>
A6197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-WARD-BOS &LR;      05-13 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-WARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARD'S IN THE ZONE AT PLAYOFF TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Each shift is a personnel evaluation, each game
a potential pink slip. For players who inhabit the NHL fringes,
such as Sabres winger Dixon Ward, insecurity is such a staple that
it becomes almost a comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why Ward seems to flourish in hockey's ultimate
crucible, the Stanley Cup playoffs. While his more entrenched
colleagues can find the sudden pressure of postseason survival
suffocating, it's almost a breather to Ward, whose future always
has been on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fighting for my life every time I step out there,'' he
said. ``I'm fighting for my job. I'm fighting for respect. I'm not
the most skilled player in the world. I have to bring something
else to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   What he brings is grit, a relentless determination that
compensates for subpar skating and doesn't acknowledge nerves.
</P>
<P>
   That was epitomized Wednesday night at Marine Midland Arena. In
dire straits after two desultory periods, Buffalo was staring at a
2-1 deficit in the game _ and potentially in the best-of-seven
Eastern Conference semifinals against the Bruins. Ward, who with
Michael Peca and Vaclav Varada had formed the Sabres' only
facsimile of a cohesive line in the first 40 minutes, took them off
the hook.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:38, a little less than three minutes after Rhett Warrener
tied the game, the 30-year-old Ward exploited a couple of Boston
defensive breakdowns and was in perfect position to take a Varada
feed from the goal line and bang home the goal that gave Buffalo a
3-2 victory and the series advantage. It was his third goal of the
playoffs and second game-winner, forming a bookend to his score
that triggered Buffalo's 3-0 win over Ottawa in Game 3 of a
first-round sweep. Coupled with his empty-netter that iced Sunday's
3-1 win in Boston, it gave him a genuine scoring streak and
cemented his reputation for responding imperturably to crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put the word `desperation' under his name,'' said
coach Lindy Ruff, ``because that's the way he plays in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because he has become intimately, if unwillingly,
acquainted with the term during a textbook journeyman's career that
has taken him from Vancouver to Los Angeles to Toronto to the
minors and finally _ he hopes _ to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   He began to get the message that he would never be a fixture
when he came out of the University of North Dakota, scored 22 goals
as a rookie with the Canucks in 1992-93 _ and was dealt to the
Kings midway through his second season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised by that,'' he said. ``I figured after
the rookie year I'd had . . . I think at that stage, Vancouver was
looking for a certain type of player for the lineup, a more
offensive player. I was very tradeable after my rookie year, and I
think (general manager) Pat Quinn wanted to see if he could
resurrect Jimmy Carson.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn couldn't as Carson, the former 50-goal scorer he obtained
from the Kings, proved a flop in Vancouver. But LA was no paradise
for Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization was in turmoil,'' he said. ``I couldn't see
myself staying there. In training camp the next year, I requested a
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was on to Toronto, where he received his rudest awakening.
Joining the Maple Leafs the day before the NHL lockout in 1994,
Ward was a stranger in the lineup when play resumed following the
new year. Used sparingly during the truncated season, he was
released afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burns, who was coaching the Maple Leafs at the time and
watched from behind the Boston bench as Ward beat him Wednesday,
insists that the move wasn't his doing and that he likes Ward,
always has. For his part, Ward says now, ``I never once had bad
words for Pat Burns,'' and credits his former coach for teaching
him how to be emotionally ready for every game.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently, Burns did see some room for improvement. ``The
Dixon Ward of five years ago is not the Dixon Ward of today,'' he
said. ``He (itals)knows(unitals) now. He gets the job done. It's a
matter of maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   Humbling, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the low point in my career,'' said Ward. ``I figured I
had to do something to make myself important.''
</P>
<P>
   Given a second chance in Buffalo, he immediately became the most
important player in the league. The American Hockey League. He
spent the bulk of the 1995-96 season with Rochester, tallying 38
goals and 94 points, then being named playoff MVP as he led the
Americans to the Calder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the best thing that happened to me,'' he said,
``going down and proving I belonged up here.''
</P>
<P>
   He can afford to be philosophical now. He's been a full-time
Sabre for the past three seasons, establishing himself as a willing
grinder and this year getting back to the 20-goal plateau. Having
experienced the descent, he's all the more appreciative of the
resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a short time to lose respect and a long time to get
it back,'' he said. ``Sometimes you have to go through tough times.
Looking back, I learned something from every experience. A little
bit of every place I've been, every coach I've played for, has
stayed with me.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for reminiscence. Players of Ward's pedigree must focus
on the present, in this case Friday's game here, when the Sabres
can effectively end the series or the Bruins can get right back in
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next one,'' said Ward, ``is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like all the others he plays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
