<HEADER>
A6201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARRGUNS-COX     05-13 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRGUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr wants 'level playing field' for disabled students caught
with weapons
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) is shocked that two disabled
Cobb County, Ga. middle school students were not expelled earlier
this year when they brought a semi-automatic gun to school.
</P>
<P>
   If the students had not been protected by the federal
Individuals with Disabilities Education Act they would have been
automatically expelled from the school, Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   So Barr introduced legislation in March that would ``level the
playing field'' by giving local school boards the authority to
expel disabled students who bring firearms to school.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the local school board would not be responsible for
the cost of educating that child at home as it is now required to
do if a student is removed from the school for disciplinary
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do is get the authority back where it ought to
be--away from some federal bureaucrat and in the hands of the local
school board,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone ought to be treated equally,'' Barr said. ``If a
disabled student brings a gun to school they should be treated the
same as other students who bring guns to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the disabled are less than pleased with Barr's
proposal. They point out that when Congress reauthorized the
Disabilities Education Act in 1997, it added a provision that
allowed the removal of a disabled student from school for up to 45
days for bringing a weapon to school.
</P>
<P>
   That suspension can be extended for another 45-day cycle,
indefinitely, said Myrna Mamdlawitz, director of government
relations for the Washington-based National Association of State
Directors of Special Education.
</P>
<P>
   It makes little sense to expell students to solve violent
tendencies, Mamdlawitz said, since kids who are prone to violence
are the kids who need special attention, not more isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Her organization believes if a child is expelled that child
should be educated at home whether or not he or she is disabled.
``Expelling kids to the street is like sending them to a graduate
school of criminology,'' Mamdlawitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Gordon O'Neill, a member of the Cobb County Board
of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The federal law) in its effort to support special education
children has gone beyond common sense,'' O'Neill said. ``There is
no reason why we should not have the authority to expel a child for
putting another child at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia activists for the disabled vow to fight Barr's bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Barr's bill does not take into consideration the disabled
community,'' said Linda Shepard, executive director of Parents
Educating Parents and Professionals,Inc., a non-profit group
charged with representing the rights of the disabled in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's legislation ``makes no sense,'' Shepard said. The law
already makes it clear that disabled students can be removed from
school for bringing a gun to school. ``We will fight against
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.) was just leaving his post as the
president of the Georgia state board of education when the
controversy over the two students arose.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson, who has not read Barr's bill, said that he agrees with
Barr that the first priority should be protecting students from
students who are prone to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my child were in that Cobb County classroom, I would want
the law equally applied,'' said Isakson, referring to the whether
the gun toters were disabled or not. ``Given the tragedies that we
have experienced all over the country, I think schools must have
the authority to remove students who bring weapons to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
