<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6202 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      05-13 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS MOVE CLOSER TO WRAPPING UP KOSOVO SPENDING BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House and Senate negotiations over emergency
funding for the Kosovo war operation degenerated into some serious
name-calling Thursday, as members from both chambers accused each
other of trying to ``pork-up'' the bill with unrelated spending and
provisions to appease special interests.
</P>
<P>
   Still, negotiators hoped to wrap up a final compromise bill late
Thursday that could be sent to President Clinton for his signature
by this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The name-calling started in earnest in the House, where a
bipartisan group of lawmakers passed a resolution instructing its
negotiators to reject all ``pork items'' that senators want to add
to the bill, including provisions that would protect tobacco
settlement money for the states and a $1 billion loan guarantee
program for financially-strapped U.S. steel and other industries
hard-hit by foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution passed 381-46 after a number of lawmakers rose to
speak out against what Rep. Charles Bass, R-N.H., called ``the
porkfest ... going on in the Senate,'' where members ``are trying
to load up ... a military emergency spending bill with their pet
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of House Democrats agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the arrogance of power,'' remarked Rep. Peter
Deutsch, R-Fla., calling the move by both Republican and Democratic
senators to add more spending and other amendments ``absolutely
beyond the pale.''
</P>
<P>
   But senators took a shot of their own at House members, calling
their complaints about added pork ``the height of hypocrisy'' after
the House voted to more than double President Clinton's original
$6.05 billion emergency Kosovo request to $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used this bill as a pack mule for every kind of military
spending. I mean give me a break, it strains credibility,'' an
angry Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to dozens of defense-related construction and
other nonessential spending measures that were added to the House
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to complain about the Senate, I think that is the
height of irresponsibility and hypocrisy,'' said Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Both Daschle and Dorgan have been trying to attach a number of
measures to the Senate version of the Kosovo bill, including a $5.3
billion price support and loan program to help financially
depressed farmers recover from low prices and bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts were rejected by House and Senate negotiators. But
the bargainers representing the two chambers did accept dozens of
other amendments, including one offered by Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, that waives the federal government's claim to a
portion of the $246 billion tobacco settlement with the states.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment would not require states to spend any of the money
gained from settling lawsuits with the tobacco industry on tobacco-
or health-related programs, as the Clinton administration wants
them to do. But Hutchison was offering to change the wording of her
provision to encourage states to spend the settlement money only on
health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has threatened to veto the emergency bill if it reaches
his desk with the tobacco provision attached. But he sounded less
confrontational Wednesday when he told reporters that he thought
House and Senate negotiators were ``actually making progress'' on
reaching an agreement that would be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is some effort to trim down the bill some and to
get it in a position where I can sign it,'' Clinton said, adding
that he is ``pretty encouraged'' that some extraneous amendments
have been rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Kosovo bill has ballooned to about $15 billion as
lawmakers have tried to turn it into what one House member
described as ``a Christmas tree'' of presents for special interests
with ``emergencies of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said Rep. Mike Castle, R-Del., ``the so-called
(Kosovo) emergency spending bill is somewhat of a disaster itself''
for the American taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   By the time House and Senate negotiators are through, the bill
could contain such items as a $26 million loan program for Alaska
fishermen and a provision that would block Interior Department
efforts aimed at preventing the Houston-based Battle Mountain
Company's Crown Jewel Gold Mine from dumping mine tailings in
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent millions fighting a law that governs how
tailings and other wastes are disposed of.
</P>
<P>
   It could also include a bailout program for steel companies that
could be worth as much as $1 billion. Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.,
who is trying to help a financially strapped steel company in his
home state avoid layoffs, has threatened to filibuster if his
bailout provision is axed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also contains an amendment pushed by Hutchison that
would extend the current prohibition on increasing federal
royalties on oil and gas through at least Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, who will lead a seven-senator delegation on a
fact-finding trip to the Balkans this weekend, also hoped to
convince negotiators to attach another amendment she wants that
would provide loan guarantees to small, struggling oil and gas
producers in Texas and other oil patch states.
</P>
<P>
   But while negotiators saw fit to help some favored interests,
they rejected others. American farmers, for example, didn't fare as
well as they had hoped even though they got some $566 million in
loan guarantees. The negotiators also denied additional education
money for hiring more school counselors to help head off the kind
of violence that occurred in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate leaders still hoped to reach a compromise on
the emergency bill late Thursday and get it to the president for
his signature by this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to $11.7 billion for the Kosovo operation and other
military-related items, the final bill is expected to include
nearly $1 billion in relief aid to Central American countries hit
by Hurricane Mitch last fall and as much as $900 million in
disaster aid to the victims of the monster tornadoes that ripped
through Oklahoma and Kansas two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But even if negotiators reach a compromise, there is still no
guarantee that the House and Senate will vote to accept it because
of objections primarily over Byrd's steel provision.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., worked Thursday to get negotiators to take
Byrd's amendment out of the final bill and threatened to hold up a
vote on it if it stays in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard-headedness and caginess don't get you much if you don't
have a bill to deal with,'' Lott warned.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert was able to get two Republicans on the negotiating
conference to reverse themselves and vote against Byrd's amendment.
But it was still unclear late Thursday whether it would remain in
the final bill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
