<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6204 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0514-C     05-13 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. WAGES TWO-PRONGED CAMPAIGN WITH NATO BOMBING, SHUTTLE
DIPLOMACY
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-APACHE-0514; ALBANIA-CAMP-0514.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dismissing a small Serb troop withdrawal from
Kosovo as more propaganda than pullback, NATO pressed its most
intensive attacks to date against Yugoslavia, flying some 760
combat sorties late Thursday and early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On an equally furious diplomatic offensive, U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott met Thursday night in Geneva with
United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan to discuss the search
for an end to the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   That meeting followed a day-long session in Moscow between
Talbott and Russia's envoy to the Balkans, Viktor Chernomyrdin, and
separate meetings between Talbott and Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov. Talks centered on how to craft a U.N. Security Council
resolution aimed at placing Kosovo under international control
policed by a military peacekeeping force with NATO and Russian
participation.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott was scheduled to brief NATO officials on the diplomatic
front at alliance headquarters in Brussels on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diplomacy needs some time to ripen before we can discuss the
substance,'' State Department spokesman James Rubin said in
Washington. ``We're trying to get greater and greater agreement
between NATO's elaborated conditions and the Russian views.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton urged the country to look beyond a week of
diplomatic and political setbacks and focus instead on the core
reason for NATO's air campaign: the bloody Serb repression
targeting ethnic Albanians in the embattled Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not get refugee fatigue,'' Clinton said. ``We must not
forget the real victims of this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Escalating his rhetorical attacks against Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, Clinton likened the repression
in Kosovo -- a campaign of alleged executions, rapes and terror
that has driven an estimated 1.5 million ethnic Albanians from
their homes -- to the Holocaust half a century before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though his ethnic cleansing is not the same as the ethnic
extermination of the Holocaust, the two are related,'' Clinton said
in a speech to U.S. military veterans. ``Both vicious,
premeditated, systematic oppression fueled by religious and ethnic
hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a pointed warning to Milosevic, Clinton laid out more
clearly than ever the direct link between the Serb leader and the
alleged war crimes committed by forces under his command in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now, Mr. Milosevic is being investigated by the
International War Crimes Tribunal for alleged war crimes, including
mass killing and ethnic cleansing,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine of every 10 Kosovar Albanians now has been driven from
their homes, thousands murdered, at least 100,000 missing, many
young men led away in front of their families; over 500 cities,
towns and villages torched,'' Clinton said, adding that it could
not have happened without direct orders from Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not have systematic slaughter in an effort to eradicate
the religion, the culture, the heritage, the very record of
presence of a people in any area unless some politician thinks it
is in his interest to foment that sort of hatred. That is how these
things happen,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political leaders do this kind of thing,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think the Germans would have perpetrated the Holocaust
on their own without Hitler? Was there something in the history of
the German race that made them do this? No,'' Clinton said. ``We've
got to get straight about this: this is something political leaders
do.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, state-run media showed footage of 120 smiling
soldiers leaving Kosovo, evidence, Yugoslav officials said, of a
broader pullback from the province.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials ignored the gesture and pressed forward with an
escalating bombing campaign. U.S. and allied pilots struck at more
than four dozen military targets late Wednesday and early Thursday,
ranging from troop barracks and command and control bunkers to
individual tanks, artillery pieces and troop staging areas arrayed
across Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon contends that there are some 40,000 Serb troops and
police in the war-torn province and that they continued, as
recently as Wednesday, to shell and otherwise attack ethnic
Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see no signs of legitimate withdrawal,'' said Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking out a couple of hundred soldiers here and a couple
hundred soldiers there is not what we consider to be withdrawal,''
Bacon told reporters at the Pentagon. ``We consider that to be
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's air campaign rolled into its eighth week on Thursday,
clear weather and a growing arsenal of warplanes and support craft
helped bolster the sortie rate to its highest levels to date, said
Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance was scheduled to fly more than 900 sorties -- 760
of which were to involved armed combat planes -- from late Thursday
through early Friday, Wald said.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, Wald said, there were 645 U.S. aircraft --
including 272 fighter/bombers plus refueling tankers and
reconnaissance planes -- and 277 planes from other NATO nations
employed in Operation Allied Force.
</P>
<P>
   The United States plans to add 337 fresh planes ``over the next
few weeks,'' said Wald, bringing the U.S. total to 982 and the NATO
total to nearly 1,300 planes.
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO air corps expands, Yugoslavia's continues to shrink.
With another half-dozen of its fighter jets destroyed in attacks
late Wednesday and early Thursday, Milosevic has now lost roughly
100 aircraft since the U.S. and allied strikes began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll end up with nothing at the end of this,'' said Wald,
``if he doesn't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said NATO is reviewing the contours of a possible
peacekeeping force in Kosovo, with an eye toward expanding that
contingent beyond the 28,000 troops -- 4,000 of them Americans --
envisioned earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody now believes that that force is probably too small
and that a larger force will be required to go in as a peacekeeping
force,'' Bacon said. ``We don't know whether it will be twice as
large or three times as large, or 50 percent as large as we
initially planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said news reports of a new plan that would involve up to
16,000 U.S. Marines were premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are far away from that decision right now,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may end up sending all Army people, all Marines, some
combination of the two,'' said Bacon. ``We may end up sending more
than 16,000, less than 16,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by the United States, NATO launched air strikes to counter a
mounting Serb military and police offensive targeting ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, a province in southern Serbia, Yugoslavia's
dominant republic. Belgrade claimed, however, that the offensive
was necessitated by Kosovar Albanian rebels who were committing
terrorist acts against Kosovo's Serb minority.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials insist the campaign will continue until
Milosevic agrees to:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  end the repression;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  withdraw all Serb troops and police from Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  permit a peacekeeping force with NATO at its core to police
the peace in Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  guarantee for the safe return of ethnic Albanian refugees;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and permit political autonomy for ethnic Albanians, who made
up 90 percent of Kosovo's pre-conflict population.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
