<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-BIZMAGS-$ADV16     05-13 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BIZMAGS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING PORTFOLIO CUES FROM A MAGAZINE'S LIST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you get rich investing in the companies that created the
wealth of the Forbes 400? Or in those that Fortune magazine lists
as America's most admired? You may soon be invited to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Cashing in on the popularity of unit investment trusts, which
are similar to mutual funds but hold an unmanaged portfolio of
securities for a set period, John Nuveen &AMP; Co. has bundled into a
UIT the stocks on Fortune's annual list of the 10 most admired
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Prudential Securities expects by this summer
to begin selling a UIT composed of the 40 publicly traded stocks
that are the largest equity holdings of people on Forbes magazine's
list of the 400 wealthiest Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Like many broker-sold UITs, these don't come cheap. The
Nuveen-Fortune America's Most Admired Companies Portfolio has an
up-front sales charge of 1 percent; investors who hold it for its
full two-year duration will have an additional 3.5 percent deducted
over that time as a deferred sales charge, plus annual operating
expenses of 29.25 cents for each $100 invested.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the Forbes 40 Index Trust will pay 1 percent up
front and an additional 1.75 percent deferred sales charge over the
one-year term; those who renew at the end of the year will not have
to pay another up-front fee, but the 1.75 percent will be deducted
every year.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an annual trustee's fee of 19 cents for every
$100, according to Kenneth Swankie, a Prudential senior vice
president. (Sales charges for both trusts are reduced somewhat for
purchases over $50,000; the minimum investment is $1,000 for the
Nuveen-Fortune trust and $250 for Prudential's Forbes UIT.)
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the average United States diversified stock
mutual fund charges 1.42 percent of assets for annual expenses,
excluding sales charges, according to Morningstar Inc., the fund
researchers in Chicago. Fees for unmanaged portfolios, like index
funds, tend to be far lower.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the trusts' fees go to brokers and underwriters, but the
magazines will also get a portion for the use of their names.
Fortune, owned by Time Warner, will receive 10 cents a year for
every $100 invested in the Nuveen trust, said Bill Adams, an
executive vice president at Nuveen. Forbes Inc. said its cut from
Prudential had not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the fees, Adams said UITs are ``a fairly economical
way of being able to purchase a basket of securities that pursue a
particular strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuveen does not offer any back-tested data of the Fortune
portfolio in its prospectus. The Forbes UIT prospectus, however,
says that a hypothetical portfolio of its stocks _ the Forbes 40
index _ would have had an annual average return of 22.5 percent
from January 1989 to December 1998, versus a total return of 19.2
percent for the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the two magazines said they saw no problem with
such use of their proprietary lists, noting out publishers like Dow
Jones have licensed the use of their names with similar investment
products.
</P>
<P>
   Both trusts include many large-cap highfliers, like Wal-Mart
Stores, Microsoft and Dell Computer.
</P>
<P>
   A. Michael Lipper, chairman of Lipper Inc., the research firm,
said such stocks could be among the most susceptible to a broad
market downdraft. But he added that the Forbes trust ``directs
investment into the more entrepreneurial companies, and over a
sustained period that's probably a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fortune UIT, he said, is a ``much more difficult call.''
After all, he said, ``most stocks at their peak are admired by
somebody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0514-C     05-13 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. WAGES TWO-PRONGED CAMPAIGN WITH NATO BOMBING, SHUTTLE
DIPLOMACY
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-APACHE-0514; ALBANIA-CAMP-0514.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
