<HEADLINE>
HOW PUZZLE MAY PLAY OUT IN MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's last constitutional crisis ended badly, with a
violent mutiny led by parliamentary leaders that was put down by
the president with the help of army tanks.
</P>
<P>
   That was in October 1993. By December that year, Russia had a
new constitution, tailor-made to suit President Boris Yeltsin. Six
years later, as Yeltsin heads toward another collision with another
parliament, his constitution turns out to be not much help at all.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in brief, is the predicament caused by the crisis set in
motion Wednesday by Yeltsin's decision to remove Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov, on the day before the parliament began to debate
his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   If the lower house votes to impeach the president, it
automatically triggers a clause in the constitution that forbids
the president from disbanding that chamber.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, the same chamber votes three times to reject Sergei
V. Stepashin, the president's nominee to replace Primakov, the
constitution requires Yeltsin to disband the parliament, and call
early elections.
</P>
<P>
   This open-ended contradiction is now the source of much
puzzlement in Moscow, as the Kremlin and the parliament each look
for ways to score a political victory without a repeat of the 1993
confrontation, which cost more than 140 lives.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the two sides choose to avoid violence, that does
not mean they can avoid deadlock. From the Kremlin's point of view,
a deadlock is not necessarily a bad thing, since it would allow
Yeltsin to keep the Prime Minister of his choice, in an acting
capacity, with or without the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deadlock scenario, the parliament's lower chamber, the
Duma, votes to impeach the president, probably on the charge that
accuses him of waging an illegal war in the breakaway republic of
Chechnya from 1994 to 1996. Within five days, the impeachment is
referred both to the Supreme Court, which must rule on the legal
content of the charges, and to the Constitutional Court, which
judges the constitutionality of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Only then does the impeachment move to the floor of the upper
house, the Council of Federation, where a two-thirds majority is
required to remove a president from office. If the Council has not
acted on the impeachment measure within three months of its
approval by the Duma, then the measure is considered to have
failed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, few expect an impeachment charge involving the Chechen
war to reach the Council of Federation. It will probably die an
early death in the Supreme Court, which is unlikely to overturn a
1995 ruling by the Constitutional Court that upheld the legality of
the war.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the lower house must cast its first vote on the
Stepashin nomination on Wednesday, May 19. If on a third try (after
a process that could stretch out a month), the nomination is
rejected, Yeltsin can simply carry on with his acting prime
minister, and his acting government, for as long as he wants. If
the impeachment process is still going on, he cannot disband the
Duma. If it is over, he must.
</P>
<P>
   With regularly scheduled parliamentary elections just six months
away, either scenario is fine by the Kremlin, according to a top
Yeltsin lieutenant interviewed Thursday by the Russian news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Vladimir Putin, chief of the Russian Federal
Security Service, even suggested that the preferred option would be
an acting government, together with a sitting lower house, which he
said would give the government greater legitimacy both at home and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   There are more options. The impeachment vote could have strong
support but fall short of the required 300 votes in the 450-seat
Duma, delivering Yeltsin a blow that would be painful, but not
crippling. And the parliament could approve Stepashin on its first
vote. ``He just might suit quite a few people of various political
views,'' said Putin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
