<HEADLINE>
IMPERSONATING THE INSIDERS: YES, ITS PAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of Insiders, a newsletter that picks stocks by
insider buying activity is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16)  
 (af)  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do they or don't they? Do corporate insiders _ like company
directors and officers _ know so much more than we do about their
company's prospects that we can beat the market simply by imitating
their purchases and sales?
</P>
<P>
   Opinion varies widely on this question, partly because
researchers themselves have changed their minds. The initial
answers came more than 30 years ago, in several academic studies
that found that investors could beat the market simply by buying
the stocks that insiders were buying.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly compelling was the fact that unlike some other
strategies, this one was so easy to practice. The Securities and
Exchange Commission requires insiders to report their purchases and
sales, and several investment newsletters translate that data into
investor-friendly formats.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was the conventional wisdom for many years. But
serious doubts were raised in the 1980s, when researchers found
that the insiders of small-capitalization companies were more
likely to buy their companies' shares than were the insiders of
larger companies. And they found that insiders of value-oriented
companies _ defined as those trading at the lowest price-to-book
ratios _ were more likely to buy than those of growth-oriented
companies.
</P>
<P>
   That research placed the earlier studies in a very different
light. It meant that those landmark studies from the 1960s might
have discovered little more than the long-term tendency for
small-cap stocks to outperform large-cap stocks, and for value
stocks to outperform growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of the newer research was that if your portfolio was
already concentrated in small-cap value stocks, you gained no
advantage from paying attention to insiders.
</P>
<P>
   That new consensus also lasted for some years. But it, too, has
come under fire, as a number of researchers have looked into
whether the patterns have endured.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they have found several wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   One study, circulating as a working paper, was conducted by
Leslie Jeng, an associate professor of finance and economics at
Boston University, and Andrew Metrick and Richard Zeckhauser, an
associate professor of economics and a professor of political
economy, respectively, at Harvard. In effect, they have found that
the studies from the 1960s were on to something after all. Though
the impact of insider buying and selling is strongest among
small-cap value stocks, they found, it nonetheless exists among
large-cap growth stocks, too.
</P>
<P>
   The professors reached their conclusion by examining every stock
insiders bought from 1975 to 1996. A hypothetical portfolio that
held each of these stocks for one year, and in the amounts bought
by the insiders, would have outperformed the market by 7.4
percentage points annually, before transaction costs.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that only one-third of this outperformance could
be explained by the disproportionate propensity of insiders at
small-cap and value-oriented companies to buy their companies'
stocks. That means that even investors in large-cap growth stocks
can bolster returns by following the insiders' lead, though not as
much as with small-cap value stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, you don't even have to react immediately upon
learning of an insider's buying. True, such a stock most likely
will have already risen by the time the insider's purchase is
reported publicly.
</P>
<P>
   But the professors, looking at the amount by which such a stock
beat the market over the next year, found that two-thirds of the
outperformance came after the first month. In other words, you
needn't be a day trader to benefit from the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the professors found that stocks sold by insiders
performed no better or worse, on average, than the overall market.
That makes sense, because insiders have many reasons for raising
cash. But there is just one primary reason insiders buy their
company's stock: They think it will go up.
</P>
<P>
   More companies have been lending money to insiders to buy their
shares, prompting suggestions that the insider-imitation strategy
could become less profitable. But these loan programs have gained
steam only in the last two years, after the period in the study, so
their effect is not yet known. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
