u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      05-13 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS DOCTOR ADMITS SUSPICION OF SERIOUS HEART PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Even though he announced at a press conference six
years ago that Celtics star Reggie Lewis did not have a
life-threatening heart condition, Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr.
acknowledged Thursday that he believed he might.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying for the first time in the malpractice trial stemming
from Lewis's death, Mudge also acknowledged that he ignored the
advice of a colleague who disagreed with his diagnosis and wanted
more testing.
</P>
<P>
   And he testified that Lewis's heart was electrically monitored
only twice -- for one 23-hour period and one 17-minute period -- in
the 11 weeks prior to his death on July 27, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis collapsed and died of a heart attack while casually
shooting baskets at Brandeis University. He was 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctor, your contention is that you had not reached a
definitive diagnosis of neurocardiogenic syncope (the benign
fainting disorder that Mudge announced Lewis had),is that
correct?'' asked Robert Harley, who represents Lewis's widow, Donna
Harris-Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is correct,'' said Mudge, who took over Lewis's care
after he left New England Baptist Hospital against medical advice
and transferred to Brigham and Women's Hospital in early May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your contention is that you were still considering the
life-threatening arrhythmia, is that correct?'' asked Harley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were considering the arrhythmia as a potential cause,
yes,'' Mudge said.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled by Harley, Mudge insisted that he had not said anything
inaccurate at the press conference, ``but what I did say was very
limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Mudge, ``We had two diagnoses, two potential diagnoses.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, during a televised press conference on May 10, 1993 --
which was replayed for jurors Thursday -- Mudge announced without
hesitation a single, apparently definitive diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge said that Lewis had nothing more than a ``poorly
understood'' neurological disorder that caused him to faint during
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``After extensive testing, evaluation and review of all data, I
believe that Mr. Lewis has a normal athlete's heart with normal
functions. Our testing showed no evidence of cardiomyopathy or
abnormal life-threatening arrhythmias. ...I am optimistic that
under medical supervision Mr. Reggie Lewis will be able to return
to professional basketball without limitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's testimony, which came on the ninth day of a trial
estimated to last four to six weeks, echoed testimony earlier this
week from Dr. Peter L. Friedman, a Brigham cardiologist also named
in the medical malpractice lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   During a full day of direct examination Thursday by Harley,
Mudge was alternately passive and feisty.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by Harley about a team of four cardiologists in
California who evaluated Lewis to provide a third medical opinion,
Mudge acknowledged that one of the doctors was under consideration
for a job at the Brigham at the time.
</P>
<P>
   That doctor, William Stevenson, who backed Mudge's findings, is
now co-director, with Friedman, of Brigham's electrophysiology
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had been on not only local, but national, television with
your diagnosis,'' noted Harley.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, to ask a doctor who plans to come to your institution that
all that stuff or some of that stuff on television is wrong is
asking a lot, do you agree with me?'' asked Harley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with you at all,'' said Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   Harley suggested that the lure of the limelight had influenced
Mudge's medical judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this press conference, you were going to be able to stand
up before Boston and the world and say that all these doctors at
the Baptist were wrong and Reggie Lewis will be able to play
basketball again,'' said Harley.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's lawyers objected to the question and Mudge was not
allowed to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge also testified that he told Brigham nurses Lewis had to be
monitored if he engaged in ``any form of vigorous physical
exercise,'' but conceded that Lewis's discharge form indicated no
restrictions on his physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge also testified that he had not spoken with the Lewises
about an anti-arrhythmia drug on the couple's first day at the
hospital, contradicting a statement he'd given during a deposition
in which he said he'd spoken with them about the drug ``in detail''
that day.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge acknowledged that he did not act on suggestions from Dr.
Roman W. DeSanctis -- who consulted on Lewis's case both during his
hospitalization at the Baptist and at the Brigham -- that
additional tests be performed. DeSanctis, director emeritus of
clinical cardiology at Massachusetts General Hospital, testified
last week that he had a letter hand-delivered to Mudge outlining
his misgivings about Mudge's diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   While agreeing with Harley's suggestion that it would have been
desirable to monitor Lewis as much as possible, given that he had
not ruled out a heart condition, Mudge conceded that he
discontinued electrical monitoring of Lewis's heart two days he
left the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before court recessed for the day, jurors were shown a
videotape of the May 1993 press conference at which Mudge said
Lewis suffered from neurocardiogenic syncope, a condition that
causes heart rate to fall during physical exertion.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, after Mudge announced his diagnosis, Lewis took the
microphone and said, in part, ``I'm just glad it's finally come to
an end, but with the help of Dr. Mudge, we'll still be taking
things slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   As she watched from the seat in the front row, Harris-Lewis
wept. Mudge often averted his eyes from the television monitor as
the tape was played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicine is not a precise science,'' he said on the videotape.
``In the end, it is a judgment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
