<HEADLINE>
NOW, BEFORE YOU GO CRUISING YOU MUST DO SOME CHOOSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16)  
 (af)  
 By JIM McCRAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just five years ago, if you wanted a cruiser motorcycle you
bought a Harley. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before cruisers became an American phenomenon. Come
summer, highways and parking lots from coast to coast will be
buzzing with these machines designed for relaxed long-distance
travel and characterized by their roomy saddles and upright,
relaxed riding positions.
</P>
<P>
   Cruisers now represent 55 percent of the American motorcycle
market, according to Don Brown of DJB Associates, a consulting firm
in Irvine, Calif., up from 10 percent in 1991. He estimates that
cruiser sales grew 17 percent last year, to 154,000. Next year, he
expects sales to top 180,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cruiser motorcycles offer their buyers _ many of them baby
boomers _ freedom from their cars along with individuality,
adventure and fellowship with other riders. Beneficiaries of
increased disposable income in a booming economy, cruisers offer an
alternative to adult toys like sports cars or boats. They are more
maneuverable than heavy touring bikes and more comfortable than
agile sport bikes.
</P>
<P>
   There are more cruisers for sale this spring than ever before.
Not only is Harley-Davidson working on new models _ it already has
24 on the market _ but all four Japanese manufacturers have
invested heavily in cruisers and the Europeans aren't far behind.
There are also two new American manufacturers, Excelsior-Henderson
and Polaris.
</P>
<P>
   Harley-Davidson's share of the American cruiser market may have
slipped _ to about 55 percent from 100 percent in half a decade _
but it still sets the tone for all cruisers. Harleys have an
imposing presence _ visually and aurally _ with their big V-twin
engines, big torque, big fenders, big tanks, big saddles for two,
small mufflers (the better to keep the noise level high), low seat
height (accommodating male or female riders), lustrous paint and
chrome and lots of accessories for customization.
</P>
<P>
   Harley-Davidson may have had this market to itself for decades,
but its tremendous success _ customers routinely have to wait six
months for delivery _ convinced other motorcycle companies to jump
into the cruiser segment. Here are eight of the leading cruisers on
the market this summer: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BMW R1200C The giant German auto and motorcycle maker introduced
its first cruiser last year after going 75 years without one, and
it quickly became the company's best-selling motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   The R1200C uses BMW's traditional horizontally opposed
1,170-cubic-centimeter fuel-injected engine _ the company's
largest, most powerful ever. The smallest engine in the senior
cruiser group, it produces more than 70 foot-pounds of torque with
a five-speed transmission and BMW's time-tested shaft-drive system.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is unlike most cruisers', with the company's
patented Telelever front and Monolever rear suspension instead of
conventional forks and swing arms. The R1200C is the most
radical-looking cruiser, with its pulled-back handlebars _ nearly
chopper style _ a solo saddle with a pillion pad behind it, a
simple bar-mounted gauge cluster and more chrome than you'll find
on any other BMW. Options include saddle bags, a tank bag and _
unique among cruisers _ anti-lock brakes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: The flashiest cruiser. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXCELSIOR-HENDERSON SUPER X A combination of two classic
American motorcycle brands that went out of production decades ago,
the Excelsior-Henderson is built by the Hanlon family and their
staff in a new factory in Belle Plaine, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   The Super X has a 1,386cc 50-degree V-twin engine with overhead
cams, four valves per cylinder and electronic fuel injection. There
is an exposed coil spring leading-link front suspension; the forks
go right through the fenders, just like those on the 1931
Excelsior. The fenders are fully valanced _ they cover the tread,
and much of the sidewall, of the tires _ another nostalgic touch.
The Super X has quiet belt drive instead of chain or shaft drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Super X is pricey _ $18,000 for solid black, more for
two-tone versions.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Lots of power and excellent brakes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HARLEY-DAVIDSON ROAD KING Of Harley's 24 models, the Road King
is the prototypical cruiser. This year, it features the all-new
Twin Cam 88, a 45-degree V-twin engine of 88 cubic inches that
produces 82 foot-pounds of torque. The engine is mounted indirectly
to minimize vibration and is linked to a five-speed transmission
and a quiet, reinforced rubber-belt drive system.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Harleys, the Road King makes few concessions to weight
reduction; while the Japanese and German bikes are using aluminum,
the Harley packs a lot of iron and steel under its paint. The
result is a weight of 699 pounds on a short 63.5-inch wheelbase.
</P>
<P>
   The Road King can be dressed out with hundreds of
Harley-Davidson accessories from windshields and extra driving
lamps to saddle bags and chrome dress-up items. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: The best all-round Harley. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
