<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sobieski hitching her star to a saint
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's one of Hollywood's It Kids: a 16-year-old actress whose
star is on the rise. Her fair, entrancingly plain looks have
prompted comparisons to a young Helen Hunt, but Leelee Sobieski
already is carving out her own identity.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski stars as the teenage saint in ``Joan of Arc,'' CBS's
$25 million miniseries that airs at 9 p.m. Sunday and Tuesday.
She's also in the upcoming ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' the much-anticipated
movie directed by the late Stanley Kubrick and starring Nicole
Kidman and Tom Cruise. Other credits: The current Drew Barrymore
comedy, ``Never Been Kissed,'' and TV movies ``Reunion'' and ``A
Horse for Danny.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski calls her acting career ``an accident.'' She was found
by a casting agent in her New York private school cafeteria. When
not working, she still goes to high school there, living at home
with her father (a painter), mother (a writer) and brother (a
10-year-old).
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no clue what acting was,'' she says. ``I was horrible.
Then I thought, `Maybe I should figure out how to play this game.'
Things started happening. My parents said, `As long as you stay
grounded, we'll support you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what else Sobieski had to say before the ``Joan'' debut:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On being an actress and a high school sophomore: When I'm
working, I have one life, and when I go back to school, I have a
whole other life. I call my friends for the local gossip, figure
out what's going on. Things like, ``I sort of have a boyfriend
now,'' or ``I don't want any boyfriends,'' or ``I'm mad at her
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On people thinking she resembles a young Helen Hunt: I think
it's a nice thing. She's a very nice actress. But I don't see any
resemblance at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On strong roles for teenage girls: For a while (Hollywood)
thought only young men or teenage boys could lead a film. Now there
are a lot of female teenage roles _ though often they're played by
24-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On not letting fame go to her head: I'm very close to my
family, and my mother, father and little brother keep me grounded.
I tell my parents everything _ they're my best friends in the
world. They know me better than I know myself.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On religion: I'm not sure of my religion. I was taught when I
was little I could go to any religious ceremony I wanted to. It was
left up to me. I always celebrated Christmas _ all little kids love
presents. But I haven't decided yet if there's a religion I'd like
to have. I like the idea of a religion, it's great guidance. But I
don't feel I have to seek that guidence (right now). My parents are
behind me 100 percent, so I'm not seeking that yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On experiencing the power of Joan of Arc: Charging (on a
horse) in front of an army with 200 people behind you, charging
toward this fortress, you do feel powerful. You do feel a lot of
the things she was going through. Then they yell, ``Cut!'' and none
of the men are following you anymore.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On watching previous film portrayals of Joan of Arc, by Ingrid
Bergman (1948) and Jean Seberg (1957): In the Seberg
virgin,version, I didn't see any spark in her. She seemed so
monotone. In the Bergman version, she was actually sleeping with
the director at the time, so I was wondering how she portrayed a
virgin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On what surprised her in researching this role: I don't know
if it's a fact or not, but when (Joan) was burned at the stake, her
heart didn't burn, which I think is so cool.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
