</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-MOTORCYCLES-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: round Harley.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONDA VALKYRIE Instead of a V-twin engine, Honda uses the
``flat,'' or horizontally opposed, 1,520cc six-cylinder engine from
the huge Gold Wing touring bike, only with more power and torque.
The Valkyrie is the quickest and fastest cruiser you can buy.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, Honda offers the basic Valkyrie, the dressed-up
Valkyrie Tourer and the full-dress Valkyrie Interstate, all using
the flat six with six carburetors and more than 100 horsepower.
They all have five-speed transmissions, shaft drive and triple-disk
brakes.
</P>
<P>
   The dry, or unloaded, weight is 682 pounds. The 66.5-inch
wheelbase and a relatively tall seat height of 29.1 inches. The
Valkyrie family runs from $12,799 to $15,999, depending on the
model and paint. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Tops in power. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KAWASAKI DRIFTER 1500 The new Drifter is a cruiser designed to
look like the venerable Indian Chief last produced in 1953. Its
designers chose black paint instead of chrome for its frame, forks,
headlamp housing, fender braces and bag mounts _ a decidedly retro
thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Drifter's 1500cc V-twin engine has four valves and two spark
plugs per cylinder and uses digital electronic fuel injection.
There is a counterbalancing shaft and rubber engine mounts for
smoothness. The five-speed transmission automatically helps the
rider to find neutral and uses shaft drive to transmit power to the
rear wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The Drifter weighs 668 pounds, rides on a 65.2-inch wheelbase
and has a 29.1-inch seat height. Prices start at $11,499; a lot of
accessories are available, including two saddles, a tank trim panel
and accessory headlamps. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Long on torque and nostalgia. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POLARIS VICTORY V92C This is the first motorcycle from Polaris,
a company famous for its snowmobiles and personal watercraft. Built
along very traditional but very clean lines, the deep-fendered
Victory uses a 1,507cc V-twin engine with the cylinders splayed at
a 50-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
   It is a single-overhead-cam engine with oil cooling, four valves
per cylinder and electronic fuel injection that produces a lot of
torque. The Victory uses a five-speed transmission and belt drive,
as well as cast aluminum wheels. Unlike most cruisers, the
Victory's engine is used as a part of the frame to give the chassis
added strength.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: An excellent first effort. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUZUKI VL1500 INTRUDER Suzuki builds V-twin cruisers with the
most radical designs, featuring very tall engine cylinders with a
narrow V-angle, chopper-style gas tanks and alloy front and rear
wheels.
</P>
<P>
   The VL1500 Intruder has a 45-degree V-twin engine like the
Harley, liquid-cooled and tuned for peak torque at very low engine
speeds. The engine uses dual-downdraft 36-millimeter carburetors
and hydraulic valve adjusters for minimal maintenance. There is
also a digital electronic ignition system, a five-speed
transmission and maintenenace-free shaft drive. The suggested
retail price is $9,899. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: The four-digit pricing is attractive. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YAMAHA ROAD STAR This is the most Harley-like of all the
Japanese cruisers, and its mechanical formula is simplicity itself.
It uses a 1,602cc 48-degree overhead-valve V-twin engine, the
largest in the industry. It has one cam, four valves and two spark
plugs per cylinder, and the most torque _ 99 foot-pounds. The
single-carburetor engine puts power through a five-speed
transmission and Yamaha's first belt-drive system.
</P>
<P>
   The Road Star features a retro instrument cluster with Art Deco
graphics, lots of chrome trim and more than 100 accessories from
lights to luggage. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Awesome torque, Harley looks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
