<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio Senator heads to Balkans on fact-finding mission
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. George Voinovich, who has been critical of the
air war against Yugoslavia, expects to leave today for a three-day
trip through the Balkans ``to add to my understanding,'' of the
situation, he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While talking with reporters about the trip, the Republican from
Cleveland, Ohio remained opposed to the NATO bombing policy and
spoke again of the need to find an immediate diplomatic solution to
the fight over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back to my statements,'' Voinovich said, ``what I
expected to happen is what has happened. The longer we go the more
unglued the situation becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich is of Serbian and Slovenian ancestry and early in the
conflict he drew upon his sense of history about the region to warn
that bombs alone wouldn't deter Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic from reclaiming Kosovo. He also said that Yugoslavians,
who have not been supportive of Milosevic's presidency, were likely
to rally behind him when Belgrade came under attack.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich plans to travel with seven other senators to make a
diplomatic and fact-finding visit to the region. First they plan to
meet with officials in Hungary and then Bulgaria, two countries
that border Yugoslavia, to plumb their views of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Later, they hope to visit a refugee camp in Albania before being
briefed at the Aviano Air Base in Italy and the NATO Headquarters
in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to try to add to my understanding... ``
Voinovich said, ``by getting into what the actual facts are.''
</P>
<P>
   But the trip could be postponed for a looming vote on the $11.9
billion emergency spending bill written to cover costs of the
Kosovo operation. The final bill, still being fine-tuned by House
and Senate negotiators late last night, nearly doubled the amount
of money President Clinton had proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich said Thursday he hadn't decided how he'd vote on the
spending bill because it contained a variety of provisions and he
had not yet seen it.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``If we're there, we've got to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cost of fighting over Kosovo is another factor that
drives Voinovich to want peace as quickly as possible. He doesn't
think NATO or the U.S. realizes how difficult and costly it would
be to expel Serbian military forces from Kosovo if the bombing
campaign never brings about a retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some real budgetary decisions to be made on this by
congress,'' Voinovich said. ``Nobody's going to want to cut
domestic spending to pay for this, and nobody's going to want to
use the surplus and nobody's going to want to raise taxes. But
those are the choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very, very serious stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
