A6216 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JOANOFARC14-COX     05-13 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JOANOFARC14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New `Joan' has historical sweep, plenty of heart
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leelee Sobieski glows. Even when she's not being burned at the
stake as Joan of Arc, even in the midst of a battle scene bogged
down in mud, the 16-year-old actress (who strongly resembles a
young Helen Hunt) is so radiant, so utterly convinced and
convincing, that you'll want to follow her into battle just like
legions of mud-spattered Frenchmen do repeatedly in ``Joan of
Arc.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Joan unified a divided and dispirited France in the 15th
century, Sobieski is the charismatic center that holds this
four-hour miniseries together. Despite a rocky start and too many
slo-mo war scenes, ``Joan'' ultimately is a pretty dang good stab
at finding the human being in the saint and legend.
</P>
<P>
   And compared with the other historical biggies of May sweeps _
NBC's laughable ``Noah's Ark'' and ABC's upcoming cheeseball
``Cleopatra'' _ ``Joan'' shines like polished armor.
</P>
<P>
   Most American viewers are probably familiar only with the
broadest outline of who Joan was and what she did, despite frequent
retellings of her legend, including George Bernard Shaw's famous
play ``Saint Joan.'' CBS' version, premiering on the anniversary of
Joan's canonization by the Roman Catholic Church as a saint (May
16, 1920), gets a lot of the history right without ever forgetting
the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Born to peasants (Powers Boothe, Jacqueline Bisset) in Domremy,
France, in 1412, Jeanne begins to see visions and hear the voices
of saints speaking to her as a young girl. At 16, she leaves her
family on a mission to unify France, which is in the middle of the
Hundred Years' War, fighting both the English and the Burgundians
(now part of France).
</P>
<P>
   Her first stop is the palace of Charles the Dauphin (Neil
Patrick Harris), a weak prince who's supposed to be king but can't
get his royal act together. She inspires Charles, perhaps a little
too much; in Part 2, finally a king, he'll turn on her and prove to
be as manipulative as he once was weak. She also has her first
run-in with Bishop Cauchon (Peter O'Toole), a composite character
who signifies how the church of the day first used Joan, then
turned against her.
</P>
<P>
   Believing her to be a warrior of legend, the Maid of Lorraine,
the French rally to Joan and win a series of battles. But she's no
match for the plotting of Charles and Cauchon and is eventually
tried for heresy, both for claiming to hear directly from saints
and for wearing men's clothing. She was burned at the stake in 1431
at the age of 19, although the verdict against her was soon
annulled _ just not soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski, who starred in ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries''
and had a generic teen-girl role in ``Deep Impact,'' has a
career-making role here, while O'Toole has a career-capping one. As
Cauchon accuses Joan, his words are harsh and unequivocal, but his
face is filled with ambivalence and even envy for this illiterate
child. Her faith is so pure, and his so complicated. ``Joan of
Arc'' is both _ pure and complicated.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Joan of Arc''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday (5784) and 9 p.m. Tuesday (1596)
</P>
<P>
   on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
