<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A KIND OF HUSH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., S.C.)   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can be as romantic as you please about love,'' George
Bernard Shaw wrote, ``but you mustn't be romantic about money.'' He
wasn't wrong. Money _ the making of it and the spending of it _ is
the No. 1 source of argument for couples.
</P>
<P>
   During courtship, however, the discussion of money can be a
major taboo. After just two drinks, many people are more than happy
to spill their sexual beans. But ask about their net worth and _
boom! _ you're branded as rude, or, worse, as a gold digger.
</P>
<P>
   The direct approach _ ``What's your salary?'' _ is socially
unacceptable. Even the slightly more subtle ``So, did the IRS hit
you hard this year?'' can seem too prying. Sure, you can make
intelligent assessments by considering where a person lives, or the
kind of car she drives. But what if you're from Manhattan, where
few people own cars and the size of one's apartment doesn't
necessarily reflect your bank account?
</P>
<P>
   In the past, gauging a potential partner's financial status was
easy: Your parents did it for you. Your beloved would be invited to
meet the folks, who would engage in polite, if serious, grilling.
All parties knew this was more of a job interview than friendly
chitchat over chicken Marsala; they were digging for a Future, or
the size of a dowry.
</P>
<P>
   Now the task of talking about money is generally left to the
couple. And many couples don't know how to approach it, or when.
``On a first date it's completely inappropriate to talk about
money,'' said Randall Lane, editor of P.O.V., a men's magazine.
``On the 2nd or 10th it is, too. No one wants to feel like they're
going to be a meal ticket; they want to be loved for who they are.
Eventually, in a long-term relationship, finances will come out,
but in the nascent days it's bad form, a big red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Fishman, 25, a publicist with JP Communications in New
York, would agree. Ms. Fishman and her boyfriend for three years,
Randy Weinberger, didn't have the Conversation until they had been
dating for eight months and were starting to get serious. ``My
expectations are high and I wanted to know where he was going with
his career,'' Ms. Fishman said.
</P>
<P>
   So they sat down and discussed their futures and what they
wanted from their life together. Ms. Fishman explained that she
wasn't looking for, say, a Bill Gates, but that she did have
certain needs and expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him there are things I want my kids to have, and if in
five years he's making his current salary, we won't even be able to
have kids,'' she said. ``I've seen too many of my friends' parents
split up because of money problems, and I want to pre-empt that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberger, also 25, has similar concerns, though he
acknowledged that the discussion was not the most pleasant.
``Initially, I felt she was being superficial, but as we went on I
saw things more her way,'' said Weinberger, vice president of
operations at Sakon, a company in North Bergen, N.J., that provides
international telecommunications and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unrealistic to think you can go through life with money
issues and be happy,'' he said. ``It breaks down to, `Do I want to
spend my life with you, and do I want to struggle all my life?' She
said that to me, and at first it makes you question yourself. But
when you think about it, it makes sense. It's something that should
be directly discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   What can happen when it's not discussed early on? One woman, a
hospital administrator in South Carolina in her late 20s, says she
never talked about money with her husband until after they were
married. ``I thought love was enough,'' she said. But eventually,
she saw that her financial ambitions were much higher than his.
</P>
<P>
   They are now separated, with money differences a major reason.
``I can't be with someone who isn't driven,'' the woman explained.
``I don't need to be with an oil baron, or a guy with excessive
tastes, but I want to be with someone who can hold his own and also
has similar values.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does she discuss money with prospective boyfriends? ``I
hint,'' she said with a laugh. ``I talk about the lottery and how
I'd like to open a children's center if I win. Or I say: `Oh, I'd
like to make six figures one day. What are your dreams?'''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``It's a good tactic for females to use to determine
the net worth of a guy.''
</P>
<P>
   A practical view _ and a Shavian one, if not particularly
romantic. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Ellin is a Manhattan writer. Her column on starting out in
the world of money appears the third Sunday of each month. E-mail:
preludes(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
