</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-PORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO AND TORNADO RELIEF COMES AT A PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK with TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On the face of it, the seven-year battle over a mining
company's petition to blow a 900-foot hole in a mountain in
northern Washington state and extract the gold inside would seem to
have nothing to do with an emergency bill in Congress to aid war
refugees in Kosovo and victims of the recent Midwest tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   But that is only on the face of it. In fact, negotiations on the
spending bill, which lurched slowly toward conclusion on Thursday
night, were bogged down by the efforts of lawmakers to add pet
projects, anti-environmental riders and other provisions that were
driving the cost of the measure to $14.6 billion, more than twice
the amount President Clinton had sought for war and disaster
relief.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Buckhorn Mountain, in the Okanogan Highlands of
north-central Washington, comes in. So far, Washington's senior
senator, Slade Gorton, a Republican who is running for re-election
next year, has attached language to the spending bill that
effectively overturns a Clinton administration decision to deny a
permit for the mine. The administration says that mining would
leave far too much cyanide-treated waste rock on federal land at
the mountain, near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-mining measure, or rider, is just one that members of
Congress from all over the nation are trying to attach to the
spending bill. Also being hashed over are hundreds of millions of
dollars in farm aid, loan programs for the steel, oil and gas
industries and a host of other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., has been fighting for language to
force the White House to keep the Alabama sturgeon off the
endangered species amendment. Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, has added
$3 million for commercial reindeer herders.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation, of course, is often made in ways that are not
pretty, and riders have been around almost since the dawn of the
Republic. But many involved in the fight in the Capitol say they
find something particularly distasteful about the way that this
bill, also intended to provide help for victims of last year's
Central American hurricanes, has been sidetracked by matters
affecting so many other people whose interests are, to say the
least, less urgent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is about as low as it goes,'' said Marty Haden,
director of policy and legislation for the Earthjustice Legal
Defense Fund, an environmental group that opposes the Buckhorn
Mountain mining project. ``The supporters of these efforts are
cynically taking advantage of a very real human tragedy, by
including this provision and others like it in a bill meant to aid
victims of natural disaster and war.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the provisions are equally resentful. Gorton,
for instance, who was huddling with a mining lobbyist late
Wednesday night outside a Capitol basement conference room
reviewing proposed language, said that including the rider in a
bill that is unlikely to be vetoed was a perfectly acceptable way
of overturning the administration's decision to block the mine.
</P>
<P>
   The mining company, Battle Mountain Gold of Houston, and a
partner, Crown Resources Corp. of Denver, have spent years and
estimated $80 million on the permit process, and have obtained
permits from lower agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just immoral,'' Gorton said of the recent decision,
which was made by the Interior Department and is part of a debate
over a century-old mining law that has allowed companies to extract
billions of dollars of minerals from federal land and pay no
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   The senator added, ``This is not how an honest government deals
with its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill was described as a mess early on Thursday by
Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee, and negotiators were meeting in the
Capitol again on Thursday evening to try to reach a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the president is pressing for speedy passage of any
package that will allow the United States and its NATO allies to
fight the war in Yugoslavia and aid refugees, a White House
spokeswoman held out the possibility of a veto and blamed Congress
for ``trying to take advantage of emergency needs in Kosovo and
Central America by loading up this bill with everybody's pet
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has strongly defended the project as an economic boon for
a depressed area of Washington, Okanogan County, which has an
unemployment rate of about 11 percent, more than twice the state
average.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of the area are enthusiastic about Gorton's
support of the mine project, which could employ 140 people for
about 10 years and yield as much as half a billion dollars of gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had several bad years in a row in the apples market; the
timber industry is down,'' said Jimmie Dale Walker, the mayor of
Oroville, a town of 1,500 people near Buckhorn Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including the Confederated Tribes of the Colville Indian
Reservation, whose members live near five streams with headwaters
on Buckhorn Mountain, are bitterly opposed. Many of the critics say
the mine threatens the spectacular qualities that have made tourism
an important part of the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have this kind of star in their eyes that they're
going to get rich on the gold mine, instead of looking at the
natural beauty all around them and working with that,'' said Dave
Kliegman, executive director of the Okanogan Highlands Alliance, a
local environment group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
