<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MELLENCAMP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MELLOWER JOHN MELLENCAMP MUSES ABOUT MUSIC TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ John Mellencamp, the feisty Indiana rocker who gave us
hits like ``Hurts So Bad,'' ``Pink Houses'' and ``Jack and Diane,''
knows rock 'n' roll isn't the cultural force it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to realize that what a lot of us grew up
listening to is just another music form today,'' Mellencamp, 47,
said recently in a phone interview from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to look at the situation today in the same way
that Frank Sinatra looked at things when Elvis Presley and the
Beatles showed up. It's like, `Hey, who are these guys? We kind of
had it our own way for a while. Why are they messin' up our gig?'
''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it isn't rock that dominates the record charts, but
hip-hop, R&AMP;B, Latin and mainstream pop. (Mellencamp recently
authorized rewrites of his 1981 hit, ``Jack and Diane,'' by rappers
Jay-Z and Puff Daddy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you listen to the radio, it'll tell you that,''
Mellencamp said. ``And when you turn on MTV, it'll tell you that
rock music is not the most important music anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   As he nears 50, Mellencamp has mixed feelings about rock's
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saddened by it in one sense and encouraged in another,''
he said. ``It's sad when the soundtrack of your life starts to fade
into the background. But people my age don't need music to tell us
who we are _ or to express our feelings for us. We're capable of
doing that on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp, who began his recording career in the '70s as Johnny
Cougar, realized that popular music was changing when he saw rapper
Snoop Doggy Dogg on the cover of Time magazine a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like the Rolling Stones,'' Mellencamp said. ``It was
the same kind of rebellion for a new generation that the Rolling
Stones were for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp is on tour right now, with a stop in Washington
state's The Gorge on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp's new album, ``John Mellencamp,'' is one of the most
reflective of his career. It's filled with songs of struggle and
growth, such as ``Your Life Is Now,'' written with longtime
collaborator George Green, and ``I'm Not Running Anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp, who suffered a heart attack in 1994 at age 42,
describes ``Your Life Is Now'' as ``a kind of Post-It note'' to
Green about living for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 30s, I was too busy worrying about what was going to
happen next to enjoy the moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the early '90s, I was getting terribly bitter about my job
and my career.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been doing it for 20 years, and for 15 years I'd been on the
road every day, day in and day out. I just got tired of it. I only
did it because I had to.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I decided that I was really wasting an opportunity
and that I needed to refocus my life. My wife had a lot to do with
changing my outlook. It was like when somebody looks at you and
they say, `You know, you're an idiot for thinking like that.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Not Running Anymore'' is an upbeat song about fatherhood
and faded youth. One of the verses is about Mellencamp's sons _
Hud, 6, and Speck, 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see them acting like Johnny Cougar _ always in a hurry,
spittin' and cussin' _ I tell them, `Hey, guys, slow down a little
bit. We don't have to do it this way.' And that's how that verse
came about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp, who is now with Columbia Records after 20 years with
Mercury Records, recorded his new album with his longtime band.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a vast wealth of experience,'' Mellencamp said. ``So
before we started making the record, I said, `Look, we've been
doing this for a long time. Let's pool all our knowledge and all
our experience and all our musical ability.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp also encouraged them to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `Music has changed quite a bit, so it doesn't
matter what kind of record we make. It's probably not going to be
on the radio like our records used to be. It's probably not going
to sell like our records used to. So really all we have to do is
entertain ourselves and make a record that people are going to
love.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp, who still lives in his hometown of Belmont, Ind.,
named his current ``Rural Electrification Tour'' after a U.S.
government program in the 1930s that brought electricity to rural
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to this journalist friend of mine and we were
talking about what a concert is supposed to do for people. And he
said that it should give them power over the evening, power over
their day-to-day lives,'' Mellencamp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what rural electrification did during the Depression.
It gave people in the country power over the evening. And I mean
power in terms of light and music and eventually television. It
gave them a way to communicate with the cities and it gave them the
music of Woody Guthrie and Hank Williams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
