u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS &LR;      05-13 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVERBULLETDAY OUT OF PREAKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE - Silverbulletday, the sensational filly listed as the
7-2 second choice, was withdrawn Thursday from Saturday's Preakness
at Pimlico. Vicar was all but removed from the race, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The connections of both horses were deeply disappointed that
they wound up with the two outside posts for the Preakness,
Silverbulletday in No. 14, and Vicar in No. 13, leading to the
defection of one, and near defection of the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out,'' said Silverbulletday's owner, Mike Pegram.
``Silverbulletday will run (Friday) in the Black-Eyed Susan. We
came up here intending to run in the Preakness, we didn't even know
how long the Black-Eyed Susan was until we looked it up in the book
(Thursday) morning. The Belmont (June 5) is not in the plans. We'll
go in the Black-Eyed Susan, and see what fate has to deal us from
there. It hurts, but it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicar, a colt, is listed at 30-1 for the Preakness, but he was
only 8-1 in the May 1 Kentucky Derby, and is still considered a
threat. However, owner James Tafel and trainer Carl Nafzger were so
horrified by Vicar's six-wide trip in the Derby, which led to an
18th place finish, that they almost didn't bring Vicar to Pimlico.
At Friday's draw, their worst fear was realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not run from No. 13,'' said Nafzger Thursday. ``I have
enough sense not to predict an unpredictable game, so we will wait
until (Saturday) morning. But we will not run out of 13, for sure.
After that, if there is a scratch, Mr. Tafel and I will make a
management decision. But I'm not saying we'll run from No. 12,
either. In racing, you don't guess it, you just go with it. I'm
definitely not scratching until the parties are over. I'm not
wishing anybody bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   If Nafzger scratches Vicar, winner of the Fountain of Youth and
Florida Derby, it will be because he doesn't have enough confidence
that his charge, whose style is to press the early pace, can win
from the outside. But nobody lacks confidence in Silverbulletday,
winner of 10 of 11 starts and over $2 million in purses. It's just
that Pegram and trainer Bob Baffert don't want her beaten up by
bigger, stronger males in a roughly run race.
</P>
<P>
   Only four fillies have won the Preakness in 123 runnings, the
last being Nellie Morse in 1924. The others were: Flocarline in
1903; Whimsical, '06, and and Rhine Maiden, '15.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put a filly in a large field, you have to be careful,
especailly if you have a filly with a future,'' said Baffert, who
trains Silverbulletday and another outstanding filly, the more
robust Excellent Meeting, who ran fifth in the Derby and will run
in the Preakness as the 5-1 third pick in the morning line. ``It
takes an exceptional filly to run with colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent Meeting showed in the Derby that she can do it. She
was beaten just a little over two lengths, and she easily lost
seven or eight lengths to trouble. She could easily have won the
Derby. Excellent Meeting is a great filly, and she came out of the
Derby great. Both of my fillies are seasoned, they've got the
credentials. But, even in the Black-Eyed Susan, Sillvebulletday is
going to need luck. This game is all about racing luck. She's got
them over a barrel, but you need the trip in any race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to take care of Silverbulletday. This was a hard
decision. If this had happened to Excellent Meeting, we wouldn't
have run her, either. In this game, you expect the worst and hope
for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three fillies have won the Derby in 125 runnings, and D.
Wayne Lukas, Baffert's main rival, trained one of them, Winning
Colors in 1988 (the others were: Regret in 1915, and Genuine Risk,
'80). Winning Colors, who went wire-to-wire in the Derby, was
belted around in the Preakness, finshing third; then finished a
badly beaten sixth in the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing with fillies, and this is me talking, not
Baffert, is that when your training horses, time is your ally, and
the Derby to the Preakness is the shortest time between races,''
said Lukas. ``Bob knows his fillies. The question is: Can they come
back to their form or not? We all agree that they're good enough. I
don't know how Excellent Meeting will come out of the Derby. When
Winning Colors won the Derby, she had a relatively easy race. But,
the way the Preakness was run, she could not win. Our whole concern
with Winning Colors was getting her energy back up after the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any trainer who rolls the dice with a filly in the Derby,
well, that's their problem. It's awfully tough to come back to the
Preakness and do it again with a filly. Excellent Meeting had a
very tough trip in the Derby. That would compromise any horse's
chances in the Preakness, let alone a filly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteen head here at Pimlico are as bad as 20 at Churchill. I
hope a traffic jam doesn't happen. I hope everybody gets a clean
trip, but when you run 14 horses, the race is not going to be
trouble free.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Silverbulletday, and, most likely, Vicar, won't
contest the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The immediate beneficiary of the withdrawal of Silvebulletday
was trainer Nick Zito, who obtained the considerable services of
jockey Gary Stevens aboard Stephen Got Even for the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Chris McCarron, the regular rider of Stephen Got Even, injured
his foot while working a horse at Hollywood Park Monday morning,
but Zito was patient, realizing that Baffert had cross-entered both
of his fillies in the Black-Eyed Susan, and the Silvebulletday
situation worked out in Zito's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this colt is very deserving,'' said Zito. ``He's a
wonderful horse. He had a big excuse in the Derby (wiped out on the
first turn). We'll find out Saturday. I'm very grateful that we
were able to get Gary. I'll buy Mr. Pegram anything he'd like. Do
you think he'd like a new suit?''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the regular rider of Silverbulletday, will ride her in
the $200,000 Black-Eyed Susan, in which she will break from post
No. 1 against eight rivals. Excellent Meeting will be scratched
from the Black-Eyed Susan, and will be ridden by Kent Desormeaux in
the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Elliott Walden schooled 5-2 Preakness favorite Menifee
in the area of the Pimlico turf course where the horses will be
saddled for the Preaknes. Menifee was established the choice off a
fast-closing second to Derby winner Charismatic, who is trained by
Lukas and is 6-1. ``I think he'll probably be up closer than he was
in the Derby,'' said Walden. ``He got shuffled back early, but we
got a good draw for this race (No. 5), and Pat (Day) should be able
to place him where he wants. He's an extremely good horse. He ran a
great race to get past all those horses in the Derby. It does seem
like this group is void of true speed. Everybody wants to be a
stalker. The field did not spread out well in Kentucky.'' . . . Tom
Albertrani, assistant trainer for the Godolphin Stable of Dubai,
expects a better race out of Worldly Manner, who faded to seventh
in the Derby after running a strong nine furlongs in the 10-furlong
event. ``He ran a credible race,'' said Albertrani. ``He was
pulling a little bit too much for his own good, and it wore him
out. He'll be a little more relaxed for the Preakness. He came out
of the Derby in great shape, and we're pretty confident. The Derby
tunned him up, but we have no regrets about the way we handled him
(Worldly Manner did not have an official prep race.) Maybe, next
time, we'll take a different approach. He will improve from the
Derby to the Preakness, more mentally than physically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
