<HEADLINE>
SAPOLU REFLECTS ON FRIEND TUINEI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesse Sapolu is on the line from Hawaii, and he is reflecting on
the death of his longtime friend, Mark Tuinei.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in a state of shock ... absolutely stunned,'' said
Sapolu, who attended Tuinei's funeral Thursday afternoon at Central
Union Church in Honolulu. ``To be honest you, I've taken this even
harder than when my mom passed away six months ago. At least my mom
lived a long and full life, and I expected it. But what happened to
Mark is just so stunning. He had so much more life to live. I still
don't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Drugs including heroin have been determined as the cause of
Tuinei's death that has sent shock waves through the athletic
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea that Mark was doing any of that stuff,'' said
Sapolu. ``I don't know, maybe Mark needed another challenge to
replace the high of playing football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really understands what a football player goes through
after retirement. It's a terrible adjustment. It's a complete
cultural shock. I remember last July was the first time since 1983
I wasn't at an NFL training camp, and there were some days when my
body started to sweat even though I wasn't practicing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to suddenly put down your weapon when you've
been playing football for so much of your life. You have to find
other things to do, and you have to stay away from the team. I
heard Mark still worked out at the Dallas Cowboy training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapolu and Tuinei played together at the University of Hawaii
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just two kids from Hawaii who didn't draw much
interest from the NFL,'' said Sapolu, who now lives in the Park
Estates area of Long Beach with wife Lisa and four children. ``I
was an 11th round pick from the San Francisco 49ers and Mark signed
as a free agent with the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   But both offensive linemen would wind up flourishing in the NFL
for 15 years with the same team, with Sapolu appearing on four
victorious 49er Super Bowl teams and Tuinei on three victorious
ones with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Saleamua (NFL defensive lineman) and I were playing golf
the last time I talked to Mark Tuinei,'' related Sapolu. ``He
called me on my cell phone and kidded me about how bad a golf
player I was. That was on a Saturday. The following Thursday I was
up in San Francisco doing some business when a friend of mine from
Hawaii told me he had just heard of Mark's death on ESPN radio. I
thought it was some kind of joke. But, sadly, it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapolu these days serves as the Hawaiian coordinator for Pre
Paid Legal Services Inc., flying once a month to his native state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made it a point to keep myself busy,'' he said. ``You
just have to. You can't sit around, and think about football
because that's gone forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I still can't believe that Mark is gone forever. He kept
in good shape. And he was a great guy, one of my best friends. I
think back to all the great times we had together, and it has to
end like this. It's just all so sad and tragic'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State will announce today that its longtime men's
volleyball coach, Ray Ratelle, will retire after next season and
will be replaced by Alan Knipe, his assistant the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Knipe, a former 49er All American who played on Ratelle's 1991
NCAA team, also will have a new title next season associate head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Ratelle, whose 49ers will return all six starters from the team
that lost to BYU in the NCAA title game Saturday, has been a
popular and successful fixture at Long Beach State for the past 18
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to remain involved with the program on an
emeritus basis for at least two years after Knipe assumes control.
...
</P>
<P>
   Every time Pedro Martinez pitches a masterpiece, which is about
every time he pitches, I wince for my old pal Fred Claire. You
might recall it was the former Dodger general manager who traded
Martinez to the Montreal Expos for the immortal second baseman
Delino DeShields, with a nodding assent from Tom Lasorda. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento King Vlade Divac who exchanged elbows with the
likes of Karl Malone and played with a busted up eye Wednesday
night against the Utah Jazz isn't the same Los Angeles Laker Vlade
Divac whose timidity used to infuriate Magic Johnson. ...
</P>
<P>
   Yippee, I see where John Elway wants to get involved in the Los
Angeles NFL expansion group. That really has me excited! Now we
just have to get Y.A. Tittle and Terry Bradshaw involved, too, and
I'll know the kindly NFL owners will bless us professional football
challenged Southern California souls with a team. I just can't
wait. ...
</P>
<P>
   I still think the Dodgers will win the N.L. West Division by a
comfortable margin, even with a catcher, Todd Hundley, who can't
throw out base runners, and a shortstop, Mark Grudzielanek, who
can't field or hit. ...
</P>
<P>
   I hear both the Mandalay Bay and the MGM Grand are in bidding
competition to hold the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis rematch
Nov.6, with the site fees eventually expected to reach the $10
million vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   Mandalay Bay, with its state-of-the-art 12,000-seat, is becoming
a serious player in boxing, as it also would host the proposed
Sept. 18 match between Oscar De La Hoya and Felix Trinidad. This is
the one fistic purists long have been yearning. ...
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most attractive boxer in the world, Ms. Mia St.
John, has a $100,000 offer to take off her trunks for Playboy
Magazine. Her hard-nosed manager, Debbie (Daughter of Bozo) Caplan,
is holding out for $150,000 for St. John, a former Playboy model
who brings new meaning to the term sweet science.
</P>
</TEXT>
