<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$807 MILLION MORE AVAILABLE TO TEXAS LAWMAKERS, SAYS COMPTOLLER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Just when lawmakers appeared to be gridlocked
over fiscal issues, state revenue estimators Thursday said there
will be $807 million more than expected for the next two years,
increasing the likelihood of significant teacher pay raises and
widespread tax cuts, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and key lawmakers said the rosy income
projection from Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander should make it
easier for the Legislature to reach agreements on tax relief and
spending issues before the biennial session ends in 18 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident we can meet the basic priorities of Texas, fully
fund our schools and have a meaningful tax cut,'' Bush said,
defining that as ``a tax cut people can feel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be property tax cuts, sales tax cuts and there will
be business tax cuts. I'm in the process of discussing that with
the appropriate people right now,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers negotiating the budget and tax relief bills said they
have a long way to go in deciding how to allot the new sum among
many competing needs. And with the official confirmation that there
is more money available to spend, some discarded proposals were
suddenly back in play _ including suggestions to eliminate taxes on
Internet access and to give businesses a tax credit for research
and development.
</P>
<P>
   Even a sales tax rate cut is being discussed, Bush said. ``This
money makes it easier to do all.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Rylander predicted the state would have $5.6 billion
more available than in the two-year budget cycle for 1998-1999. She
upped the figure to $6.4 billion, giving lawmakers the largest
available surplus in state history, though some of the amount was
earmarked to pay for natural growth of schools and state programs
that serve the public.
</P>
<P>
   With lawmakers bound by the Texas Constitution to pay as they go
_ meaning no deficit spending _ they have anxiously awaited
Rylander's announcement to see how much they could devote to Bush's
tax-relief proposals along with other big-ticket items such as the
teacher pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half our leading economic indicators have turned up,''
Rylander said Thursday. ``The oil industry has not completely
recovered but prices have rebounded. The state's economy will
remain robust, but we may not see the extraordinary growth of the
last two years when the economy expanded at an unusually high
rate.''
</P>
<P>
   A proposed two-year budget of $97 billion is nearly complete and
in the hands of a House-Senate negotiating committee that plans to
issue a final document next week. The negotiators set aside $3
billion. In recent weeks, the House and Senate have approved
tax-relief packages of about $500 million _ a total that could rise
in coming days. But no agreement has been reached on how to
implement the property tax cuts that Bush promised in his 1998
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the property tax cut is ... there is nothing
more difficult to do ... because it's assessed by the local school
board,'' said House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, D-San
Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mechanics of how that's going to be done is something we
worked a whole session on (in 1997),'' he said. ``It has not worked
out because we can't control those local school districts from
turning around and raising taxes again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from both parties had been saying Bush's goal of $2
billion in tax relief was unattainable, and so far they have not
agreed whether all or some teachers should get a raise. Also in
dispute is whether all or some state employees would get more pay.
Now, all options are being re-evaluated, according to key
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hopeful that this new revenue estimate will help us reach
agreements on the major fiscal issues that remain in this
session,'' said House Speaker Pete Laney.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Rene Oliveira,
D-Brownsville, said a top priority will be to arrange a $3,000
annual pay raise for every teacher, which would cost up to $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident the state employees will get a pay raise also,''
Oliveira added, emphasizing that teacher pay is the top objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we will see what's left, if any, for tax cuts,'' he said.
``This certainly gives us an opportunity to look at the governor's
whole tax package. Whether we can accomplish it or not, we don't
know yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, who presides over the Senate, said
``the new revenue estimate means we can have record increases in
public school funding, significant teacher pay raises and historic
tax cuts. We can now get to $2 billion in tax cuts this session.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Perry's political party, the GOP, wants the bulk of the
surplus devoted to tax cuts, its leader said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The additional funds ... should go directly toward tax cuts,''
said Republican Party chairman Susan Weddington. ``The people of
Texas recognize the fact that a budget surplus means that state
government has too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   But a nonpartisan group that analyzes state budgets discouraged
that plan. Center for Public Policy Priorities director Dianne
Stewart said ``massive tax cuts ... will drain state coffers,
divert funding from crucial state services, jeopardize the state's
future fiscal soundness and yet hardly be felt by the average
household.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
