<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-PROJECT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas regents approve $90M in new projects
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas officials got the go-ahead
Thursday to pursue a hotel/conference center and won approval for
nearly $90 million in building projects, including its first
dormitory in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   UT System regents, meeting at UT-Pan American in Edinburg, also
agreed to let UT-Austin increase room charges for students living
at Jester Center by $100 a year. The increase will cover $6 million
in fire and safety improvements, also approved Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin campus is in the midst of a building boom, with these
new projects coming on top of $167 million in construction already
under way. The previously approved projects include a track and
soccer stadium; academic buildings; and a parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, these projects do not involve state-appropriated
money,'' said Charles Franklin, UT's vice president for business
affairs. ``They are primarily financed with revenue bonds that will
be paid back by the users,'' those who park in the garage, live in
a dorm or use a particular building.
</P>
<P>
   Donations also help finance various projects, Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
   UT President Larry Faulkner asked the Board of Regents to
endorse the hotel/conference center to bring more people to campus
and provide accommodations to executives and others who attend UT's
short courses or professional development classes.
</P>
<P>
   With the board's blessing, UT will commission a study to see
whether the project is attractive to investors. If the feedback is
favorable, UT will seek bids, possibly in the fall, for a private
company to build and operate the 250-room hotel and conference
center, said UT Vice President Patricia Ohlendorf. The facility
would be on the Thompson Conference Center parking lot at Dean
Keeton and Red River streets.
</P>
<P>
   The winning bidder would build a garage to replace the parking
lot and would assume all costs associated with the project. The
contractor would get all of the profits but would pay UT for a
long-term lease.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, UT considered remodeling the campus-area Villa
Capri motel, but ``it would have cost more to renovate than it
would to build a whole new facility and you still wouldn't have
what you wanted,'' said Tom Hatfield, director of the Thompson
center and dean of continuing education and extension. UT bought
the land, tore down the Villa Capri and installed athletic practice
fields instead.
</P>
<P>
   If UT solicits bids for the new project, it probably would be
another two years before it would open, Ohlendorf said.
</P>
<P>
   The new projects are:
</P>
<P>
   _ $52.4 million for a dormitory that would add 850 badly needed
beds to the 5,300 beds on campus. About half of the beds are
expected to be ready when the dorm is scheduled to open, by fall
2000, said Sheila Ochner, associate director of the Division of
Housing and Food Service. A committee of the Texas High Education
Coordinating Board is expected to give final approval to the dorm
today.
</P>
<P>
   _ $21.6 million for a parking garage and office building near
the intersection of 27th Street and Speedway. The office building
would sit between two parking garages _ one of which already is
under construction.
</P>
<P>
   _ $6 million in fire safety improvements at the 30-year-old
Jester Center dorm. The cost of a standard double room, which is
$2,243 this year, will rise to $2,521 next fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ $3.1 million to expand laboratory space at the Pickle Research
Campus, 10000 Burnet Road.
</P>
<P>
   _ $6 million for scientific and computational engineering
equipment at a main campus building being expanded by Dallas donor
Peter O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
