<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUZZME-LOGAN14-COX     05-13 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUZZME-LOGAN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Logan's run: New label, big changes
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Never accuse the music business of anything
approaching logic. Jack Logan won't, and he's a happier man for it.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Winder-based songwriter seemed poised to move
to the next level in his unusual career. Though virtually unknown
outside Athens _ where he was part of a laid-back local scene that
included inspired, offbeat personalities such as Vic Chesnutt and
various indefatigable garage-rock bands _ Logan had built a strong
critical reputation with two solo albums. ``Bulk'' (1994) and
``Mood Elevator'' (1996) were stuffed with shambling, lo-fi
vignettes and skewed character studies, recorded on the cheap and
released by the independent Restless label. The songs had the feel
of short, Southern Gothic fictions, pumped up by musicians who came
of age chugging beers to the Rolling Stones and Neil Young.
</P>
<P>
   Because Logan also was a mechanic who had penned some 600 tunes
years before releasing any of them, he also made great copy.
Unfortunately, by the time he finished recording his third album in
1997, his label had lost interest. And ``Buzz Me In,''
paradoxically Logan's effort to make a slicker recording, sat in
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a mess of changes,'' says Logan, 40, who can finally
celebrate Saturday with a show at Smith's Olde Bar. Atlanta-based
Capricorn Records, which recently signed Logan to a two-album deal,
releases ``Buzz Me In'' on Tuesday, making it the prolific
songwriter's third album in a year. (Ill content to sit around
waiting for someone to notice him, Logan completed ``Little Private
Angel,'' a collaboration with songwriter pal Bob Kimball, and
``Tinker,'' on his home-grown Backburner label.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you would have told me it would have worked out like this
two years ago, I would have felt a lot better about the whole
thing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Logan's period of transition included his departure from
Doraville Electric Motor Service and the dissolution of his backing
band, the Liquor Cabinet. His brief promotional tour will feature
Kimball and members of the Athens (Ga.) rock band the
Possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll always be guitars and beating on boxes for me,'' says
Logan, who nonetheless presents a more polished version of himself
on ``Buzz Me In.'' Produced by former Clash associate Kosmo Vinyl
at Clay Harper's Casino Studios in Little Five Points, the album
flaunts a surprising palette of instrumental hues. ``It's
Technicolor as opposed to painted cels,'' says Logan, who is also a
gifted cartoonist. ``Clay knew everybody in town, so if you needed
a sitar, he'd run to an Indian restaurant and bring back some guy
with a sitar.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta guitarist Jeff Calder, who visited some of the sessions,
recalls: ``The way Kosmo and (engineer) Phil Hadaway went about it
was in contrast to Jack's more insouciant nature. I remember Jack
was a smoker, and I think they got him to stop. They wanted to get
good vocals on Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan admits that all the knob-twiddling made him nervous, but
he enjoyed the opportunity to break from his home-recording
aesthetic. ``If you have a chance to step up and do something a
little more exotic, you need to gather yourself up and go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   If the focused production trades off some immediacy, it also
emphasizes the casual soulfulness of Logan's voice and helps to
buoy a jukebox classic or two. The mellowed-out, honky-tonk lament
``Melancholy Girl'' is a prime example.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind the strings, the vibes, the bongos. Logan is no
sonic visionary. He just likes to play guitar with his friends and
tell these odd, and oddly touching, little stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of those guys trying to capture the sound in his
head. That's not my deal. I ain't Brian Wilson,'' he says. ``That's
one of those statements they come up with halfway into those VH1
specials, right before the guy overdoses on heroin.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Logan
</P>
<P>
   With Beth Wood and the Possibilities. 8 p.m. Saturday. $8
advance; $10 at the door. Smith's Olde Bar, 1580 Piedmont Ave. N.E.
404-875-1522.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
