<HEADER>
A6238 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GERMANY-2TAKES     05-13 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GERMANY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN GREENS BACK `LIMITED HALT' IN KOSOVO AIRSTRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIELEFELD, Germany _ In a clear sign of the strains placed on
Germany's government by the Kosovo conflict, the environmentalist
Green party Thursday broke ranks with its coalition partners and
other Western governments by calling for a ``limited halt'' to the
NATO bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens, in a stormy and bitterly divisive one-day party
congress, rejected a motion calling for an immediate and
unconditional termination of the NATO bombing. That measure would
probably have brought down the government of the Social Democratic
chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, which was built on a fragile
alliance with the Green party.
</P>
<P>
   But the motion that was adopted by 444 votes to 318 still marked
the growing unease of the once pacifist Green party with the NATO
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to strengthen the chances of diplomacy,'' it said,
``NATO should declare a limited halt to the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote, a breach in the unity that NATO has been at pains to
preserve, illustrated how the airstrikes are putting growing
pressure on some European governments. Just how long the policy of
bombing Yugoslavia until NATO's demands are met can continue
without precipitating a full political crisis in Germany is now
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer appeared relieved at the
outcome, embracing fellow Green party ministers. Earlier Thursday,
he had come close to putting his job _ and the government's future
_ on the line by saying that the motion rejecting NATO policies
outright, which ultimately was defeated, would have made his
position as minister untenable.
</P>
<P>
   His day was tumultuous, beginning in the worst way when a
protester hurled a bag of red paint at his face from point-blank
range. As Foreign Ministry security guards wrestled the assailant
to the floor, Fischer stood stunned on the podium, his right cheek
and gray jacket covered in paint.
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders, also sprayed in red, held their heads in their
hands, dismayed that the congress of a party still viscerally
opposed to force had descended so quickly into violence.
</P>
<P>
   The grim ministry security guards wearing suits and standing
next to the casually dressed delegates seemed to sum up the party's
uneasy adaptation to the responsibilities of power.
</P>
<P>
   As Fischer moved to the microphone to speak about half-an-hour
later, chants of ``Warmonger! Warmonger! Warmonger!'' rose from the
crowd. Referring to the Yugoslav president, Fischer shot back,
``Yes, I'm a warmonger, and I suppose Slobodan Milosevic should be
awarded the Nobel Prize for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to make an impassioned speech, recounting his
unstinting efforts to find a settlement before the bombing began,
asking how the party could oppose neo-Nazism in Germany while
turning a blind eye to fascism elsewhere in Europe, listing the
more than 70 U.N. resolutions that have failed to bring peace to
the Balkans, and placing blame for the violence squarely with
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plead with you to help me and give me your support _ and not
cut me off at the knees _ so I can emerge from this congress
strengthened and can continue our policy!'' Fischer shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a thinly veiled threat to resign if the motion calling
for an immediate and final end to the bombing passed, he said, ``If
we send the wrong signal to Milosevic today, I will not be able to
carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Fischer was taken to a hospital to have his
right ear examined, apparently because it was filled with paint.
But he returned in time to see the motion that averted an immediate
government crisis pass with a 58 percent majority.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a vociferous and large minority revealed how deep the
party's divisions have grown by voting in favor of a proposal put
forward by a leading Green party member, Christian Strobele, that
called for ``an immediate end to the NATO bombing that alone would
make negotiations possible.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an speech almost as impassioned as that of the foreign
minister, Strobele argued that the NATO campaign had been a
disaster. ``We have achieved the opposite of our avowed aim, which
is the protection of human rights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens, born in the late 1970s as a pacifist movement that
rejected the stifling rigidity of the immediate postwar generation,
have suffered the extraordinary fate of finding themselves in
government for the first time and then, just a few months later,
backing Germany's return to war as part of the NATO forces bombing
Yugoslavia today.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear Thursday that this series of events has torn the
party's always fragile unity to shreds.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted suddenly by two opposing but strongly espoused
principles _ ``Never again war'' and ``Never again Auschwitz'' _ it
has narrowly chosen to support the use of military force in the
face of what many of its members see as policies of ethnic,
religious and racial persecution in Yugoslavia that recall the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   In his defeated motion, Strobele warned against such parallels.
``We are against drawing comparisons between the murderous
Milosevic regime and the Holocaust,'' he said. ``Doing so would
mean an unacceptable diminishment of the horror of Nazi fascism and
the genocide against European Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ludger Volmer, a deputy foreign minister and ally of
Fischer, drew rousing applause as he described Milosevic's planning
and execution of a policy of destruction of the ethnic Albanian
population of Kosovo and declared, ``My friends, there is only word
for this, and that word is fascism.''
</P>
<P>
   Such statements, and a clear desire to preserve the life of the
country's first ``Red-Green'' coalition, ultimately carried the
day. But the message to Schroeder was unmistakable: a resolution of
the conflict must be urgently found if the coalition is not to risk
irreparable damage.
</P>
<P>
   The motion passed did not say how long the ``limited halt'' to
the NATO bombing should last, but said it should enable Milosevic
to withdraw his forces from Kosovo. If this happened, and the
expulsion of ethnic Albanians stopped, then ``the cease-fire could
be extended.''
</P>
<P>
   Those proposals for what would amount to a unilateral pause in
the NATO bombing marked a clear break from the German government's
peace plan advanced last month and an even clearer break from the
position of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer proposed on April 14 that if Yugoslavia began a troop
withdrawal, NATO should suspend airstrikes for 24 hours. But the
Clinton administration did not endorse the idea and has insisted
that five conditions _ including a withdrawal of Yugoslav forces
and acceptance of the deployment an international NATO-dominated
force in Kosovo _ be fully met by Milosevic before there is any
stop to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a highly emotional day, several Green delegates
appeared shattered by the outcome, betrayed by the party's
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greens are nothing if they are not a party of peace,''
said Bertram Schneeweiss, a 34-year-old doctor from Bavaria.
``NATO's actions have only made things worse, and Fischer has not
represented the party from which he came.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Cohn-Bendit, a student leader known for his anti-war
activities in 1968 and now a Green Party member close to Fischer,
said: ``We have to be coherent. We cannot say we are still against
war and remain in this government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
