<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS IN BOMBING OF CHINESE EMBASSY HONORED IN BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In an elaborate ceremony at the Great Hall of the
People, China's leaders bestowed the title of ``revolutionary
martyr'' Thursday on the three Chinese journalists killed by NATO's
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade last week.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony conferring one of the Communist Party's highest
honors on the dead appeared intended to bring an emotional close to
the anti-American activity that took over Beijing in recent days, a
rare dovetailing of public sentiment and official purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing is widely seen here as a deliberate attack and not
the mistake that NATO maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Student-led demonstrations coordinated by the government have
now stopped. And street traffic returned to normal Thursday in the
diplomatic quarter, which was besieged by raucous rock-throwing
demonstrators after the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if China's leaders want to cool mass displays of
emotion, President Jiang Zemin warned at Thursday's ceremony that
China would not consider the matter closed until the United States
and NATO make a full accounting of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise the Chinese people will never let the matter go,''
Jiang said in a speech.
</P>
<P>
   On state television's evening news, Jiang and five of China's
most senior leaders were shown going from one hospital room to
another to visit some of the Chinese citizens who were injured in
the bombing and returned to Beijing on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are all heroes,'' Jiang said to one of the wounded.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of what is likely to be many state-sponsored
commemorations of the journalists, The Guangming Daily Press said
it would publish a book next week honoring Xu Xinghu and his wife,
Zhu Ying.
</P>
<P>
   The swell of anti-American and nationalist sentiment is likely
to have far-reaching if not entirely predictable consequences on
China's political, economic and social environment in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Zhu Bangzao, a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry,
said Thursday that the atmosphere of negotiations over China's
entry into the World Trade Organization would inevitably be
affected by the changed political climate.
</P>
<P>
   Although Zhu reiterated Beijing's wish to seek entry to the
trade group by the end of the year, his remarks reflect a consensus
here that the intensely strained political mood will further
stiffen the negotiating position of Chinese officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
