</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JOAN-OF-ARC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEELEE SOBIESKI BRINGS TO `JOAN OF ARC' A DIGNITY, QUIET
INTENSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Unifying a country is never easy, especially when the
country is France in the early 15th century. Several decades into
the Hundred Years War, the English control Paris, a good chunk of
France would rather be English, and the heir to the French throne
is afraid to wear the crown.
</P>
<P>
   Into this roiling ratatouille rides Jeanne la Pucelle _ Joan the
Maid _ and out of it CBS ladles a tasty four-hour miniseries that
respects the material and its audience. What luck! Had it been an
NBC production in the manner of the recent ``Noah's Ark at the
Improv,'' Meg Ryan would be starring in something called ``You've
Got Chain Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   But CBS hews as close to the revered story of St. Joan as a TV
dramatization allows. And Leelee Sobieski, if not the next Natalie
Portman then certainly the former Helen Hunt (they could be
sisters), brings to Joan a dignity and quiet intensity that may
have millions of American males scouring their garages for
trash-can armor and pledging loyalty to la belle France.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen playing a teen, the 16-year-old Sobieski (``A
Soldier's Daughter Never Cries,'' ``Deep Impact'') is startlingly
appropriate in the role. (Ingrid Bergman was in her 30s when she
played Joan in the 1948 Victor Fleming film; Milla Jovovich,
starring in a Luc Besson theatrical release due this fall, is 23;
Mira Sorvino, linked to another possible ``Joan'' project, is 30.)
None can match the open honesty in Sobieski's unlined, youthful
face. Her Joan is naive and unsure, but at the same time plucky and
brave.
</P>
<P>
   It is an understated performance that will disappoint anyone
looking for a passionate zealot leading men into sword-clanging
battle. But Sobieski's approach, under the guidance of director
Christian Duguay, makes perfect sense. How many men would risk
death behind a ranting 16-year-old girl rushing the battlements?
Instead, Sobieski's calm and clever Joan demonstrates a rational
progression from an uncertain adolescent to a gifted woman who
slowly gains the realization that she's a born leader.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski gets plenty of help in this two-night epic from two
guys named Peter, neither of them saints. As the not-so-venerable
Bishop Cauchon, Joan's one-time supporter but eventual inquisitor,
the venerable Peter O'Toole is imperious, bombastic and tormented.
As a seasoned army captain named La Hire, miniseries veteran Peter
Strauss is a courageous mercenary leery of taking orders from a
girl who dresses as a man.
</P>
<P>
   Like any high-profile sweeps-month project, ``Joan of Arc'' has
enough celebrities to screw in a light bulb on the overtaxed
marquee. Powers Boothe and Jacqueline Bisset blandly play Joan's
peasant parents _ with remarkably good teeth _ in the colorless
village of Domremy. Robert Loggia nods compassionately as a country
priest in shaved-dome tonsure. Shirley MacLaine is an extraneous
Burgundian noblewoman bidding Joan to fight for the other side. And
Olympia Dukakis gamely keeps Joan company as a kind nun drawn to
the maid's mission.
</P>
<P>
   Each role could have gone to lesser-known players, but the
loading up on big names isn't the distraction it might have been.
Even Neil Patrick Harris, as Joan's duplicitous benefactor, Charles
VII, is amusing and slippery, even if one can't help but think of
him as King Doogie, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful scenery (courtesy of the Czech Republic), beautiful
photography (by Pierre Gill) and beautiful costuming (by John Hay)
complement the appealing lushness of ``Joan of Arc.'' One could
quibble with the film's confusing presentation of historical
material. And, since everyone is speaking theatrical English, it's
sometimes hard to tell the good Frenchmen from the bad Frenchmen,
let alone the Englishmen. Still, Sobieski's portrayal of a simple
farm girl who hears the voices of the saints makes this ``Joan'' a
graceful survey of devotion and deceit, inspiration and intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   The film, airing Sunday and Tuesday nights, is violent in
places, but Joan's many battles in the cause of awakening a French
national conscience are condensed to a handful of scenes.
Blood-spilling is minimal, and even Joan's unhappy demise at the
hands of the British is not a tasteless special-effects pyro-orgy,
proving that sad tales aren't bad tales when they're told this
well.
</P>
<P>
   Joan of Arc. Four-hour miniseries about the teenager who helped
unite France in the 15th century. Starring Leelee Sobieski, Peter
O'Toole, Neil Patrick Harris and Peter Strauss. Sunday and Tuesday
on CBS. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
