<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMERS-NOMINATION-NY     05-13 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERS-NOMINATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY APPROVAL IS PREDICTED FOR SUMMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's nominee for Treasury secretary,
Lawrence Summers, appears to be facing relatively little opposition
in the Senate, even from Republican critics of the administration's
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Summers and Robert Rubin, the current secretary who on Wednesday
announced his intention to resign, spent part of the day on Capitol
Hill, dropping in on key members of the Senate. Summers, now the
deputy secretary, left Thursday evening for Malaysia, for a
long-scheduled meeting of Asian finance ministers. But he is to
return by Monday and is expected to say little in public while
preparing for his confirmation hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings for any appointee toward the end of an administration
are always a bit unpredictable, and it is always possible that
Summers' nomination could become a political football. White House
aides said they suspected that Rubin tried to time his departure to
maximize Summers' chances of confirmation. ``The closer you get to
the presidential election,'' one White House official said, ``the
more risks you run.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Senate majority Leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
who in recent weeks has cast himself in opposition to several
administration economic initiatives, said Thursday morning that he
saw no problems with Summers' nomination. Later in the day, he met
with Summers, as did Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the
Senate Finance Committee, which will consider the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said Thursday that his committee had ``a good working
relationship'' with Summers, suggesting that he saw no large
hurdles to confirmation. His committee might have felt differently
a few years ago, when Summers clashed with the panel over the $12
billion bailout of Mexico. To raise the money, the administration
circumvented Congress and drew on the Exchange Stabilization Fund,
which is under the Treasury's control.
</P>
<P>
   Summers himself was uncharacteristically quiet Thursday, and
aides said he would keep public comments to a minimum while his
nomination was under consideration. That is hardly unusual for any
nominee. But it is considered a particularly important strategy for
the sometimes blunt-speaking Summers, who went out of his way this
week to repeatedly use the phrase ``subject to the will of the
Senate'' when referring to his appointment.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Rubin devoted the entirety of a short
commencement speech at New York University to talk about
decision-making _ spelling out how he approached problems on Wall
Street and at the treasury by weighing probabilities and focusing
more on how a decision was reached than whether its outcome was
successful.
</P>
<P>
   It was a subject he often discussed during the Asian financial
crisis, when he was often faced with the question of whether
propping up a country _ or its currency _ would help promote reform
or, in the alternative, take the pressure off politicians to change
the country's economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those bets went bad. More than $4 billion committed
to Russia was essentially lost, with no reforms. But the bailouts
of Thailand and South Korea went hand in hand with at least some
modest changes in banking systems and regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin recalled facing the decision in June 1998 about whether to
prop up the Japanese yen, whose value had been falling sharply _
threatening to trigger devaluations elsewhere in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, to say the least, a very complicated situation,''
Rubin said. The discussion could have gone on indefinitely, he
said, not adding that in the Clinton White House, discussions
usually do go on at great length. ``But we didn't have that luxury:
Markets wait for no one.''
</P>
<P>
   That bet worked out, and the yen's decline was halted. But Rubin
argued, as he did last year during several failed attempts to prop
up Russia and Indonesia, that ``judging solely on results is a
serious deterrent to taking the risk that may be necessary to
making the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, the way decisions are evaluated affects the way
decisions are made,'' Rubin said. ``I believe the public would be
better served, and their elected officials and others in Washington
would do a more effective job, if judgments were based on the
quality of decision-making instead of focusing solely on
outcomes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
