<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWYERS-MARKETPLACE-N     05-13 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYERS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: LAWYERS PROPOSE AN INNOVATIVE WAY TO BE PAID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the first, the litigation triggered by the collapse of
Cendant Corp.'s stock price in April 1998 has provided provocative
entertainment to anyone lucky enough to have avoided being caught
in the financial wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the magnitude of investors' losses _ estimated at
$14 billion _ made the case potentially the most lucrative
class-action lawsuit the securities litigation community had ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the scramble among lawyers for a dominant role in the case
produced accusations of political favoritism, after which the judge
decided to adopt a form of competitive bidding for awarding the
legal work.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at a court hearing scheduled for Tuesday before federal
Judge William Walls in Newark, N.J., there will be another
interesting fight over a novel fee arrangement proposed by lawyers
who have negotiated a settlement with Cendant on behalf of the
holders of one of its derivative securities, called Prides.
</P>
<P>
   Those lawyers, led by the Manhattan firm of Kirby McInerney &AMP;
Squire, have agreed that their fee will be paid in the same
``currency'' that their clients are getting _ namely, a new
security to be issued by Cendant. Thus, if the security that
investors are getting in settlement of their claims does not retain
its anticipated value, the lawyers will find that their fee, too,
has withered away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting our fees where our mouths are,'' the Kirby firm
explained in documents filed with the court.
</P>
<P>
   That unusual arrangement is being challenged by a persistent
gadfly in the case, who argues that the legal fees being sought,
regardless of how they are paid, greatly exceed the bid the Kirby
firm submitted in the competition conducted last year.
</P>
<P>
   The gadfly, Howard Sirota, is part of a team of lawyers that
originally pressed for the competitive bidding arrangement, a role
for which they are also seeking a fee. Sirota's team was also an
unsuccessful bidder in the fight to be lead counsel in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The current litigation started April 16, 1998, when Cendant's
stock plummeted 46 percent after the company disclosed serious
accounting irregularities. Those irregularities are still being
investigated by federal prosecutors and the Securities and Exchange
Commission, with Cendant's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of private class-action lawsuits were filed against the
company in the days after the stock collapsed, and Walls had the
job of designating which of the various plaintiffs would oversee
the legal work and hire the ``lead'' lawyers _ who would reap the
biggest fees in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Public pension funds in New York state, overseen by state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall, were named lead plaintiffs among the
common stockholders; Connecticut's pension fund was chosen to lead
the litigation on behalf of the Prides investors.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Sirota officially complained that the selection of
lead counsel might have been influenced by campaign contributions
made to McCall by the lawyers he hired. Without endorsing Sirota's
view, Walls still established a confidential competitive bidding
procedure for lawyers who wanted to work on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Kirby firm emerged from that process as lead counsel for the
holders of the Cendant Prides, a derivative security issued by
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and ultimately convertible into new shares of
Cendant common stock.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the firm announced a complex settlement with
Cendant that experts say is worth between $340 million and $350
million. The plan calls for Cendant to give the Prides holders new
certificates, called rights, that can be traded or held to maturity
in 2001, when they can be converted into new Cendant stock. When
combined with the existing Prides, the rights also entitle
investors to new Prides securities, convertible into a larger
number of Cendant shares than the old ones.
</P>
<P>
   If the valuation experts are right, the settlement adds up to a
full recovery for the Prides investors.
</P>
<P>
   As its fee for negotiating this deal _ which lawyer Roger Kirby
modestly called ``a settlement of monumental, possibly unmatchable,
significance in this field'' _ the plaintiffs' lawyers are seeking
a fee that, they say, links their interests directly with those of
their clients. Specifically, they want to receive 2,916,147 new
Cendant rights as their fee.
</P>
<P>
   But Sirota calculates the value of that compensation would be
$34 million, and argues it would thus be about 10 percent of the
total settlement fund _ a percentage he contends greatly exceeds
the confidential bid that the Kirby firm submitted to the court
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive bidding is still a controversial approach for
awarding legal work on big cases like this one, though a few
federal judges rely on it routinely. But Sirota, a staunch advocate
of the bidding process, said its advantages to investors evaporate
if the winning lawyers can come back later and seek fees in excess
of their original bid.
</P>
<P>
   He also argues that this plan, which calls for the lawyers to be
paid primarily with rights that have gone unclaimed by eligible
investors, creates an unhealthy incentive that could reduce the
aggressiveness with which claimants are encouraged to apply for a
share of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Kirby firm vehemently disagrees. The search for eligible
members of the class has been very aggressive, they insist, and
besides, any unclaimed rights would otherwise revert to Cendant,
not to the original Prides investors.
</P>
<P>
   Walls will make the final call, of course, and his decision
could lead to more cases in which legal fees are paid in the same
currency as the settlements _ or alternatively, to more cases in
which legal fees are firmly set by competitive bid at the start of
the case. Thus, regardless of who loses, shareholders in future
cases could win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
