<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AU PAIR'S PARENTS REPORTEDLY ARRESTED IN FUNDS FRAUD PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN AND PEGGY HERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The parents of Louise Woodward were allegedly arrested
last week by British investigators who believe they fraudently
drained their daughter's defense fund of as much as $280,000.
</P>
<P>
   The money was donated by worldwide sympathizers of the British
au pair convicted of killing a baby in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Cheshire, England released a statement Thursday
confirming two people were arrested May 4 in connection with
allegations that the suspects misused the money in the Louise
Woodward Family Trust. The pair were brought to the police station,
where they were told to return July 1, when prosecutors will meet
with them.
</P>
<P>
   A source in Woodward's hometown of Elton, who is familiar with
the case, said Thursday that Woodward's mother Susan was one of
those arrested. At the same time, leading British news sources,
including the British Broadcasting Corp., identified Woodward's
father, Gary, as also having been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued through her lawyer Thursday, Susan
Woodward denied any misdeeds. Her husband could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodwards, familiar faces to those who followed their
daughter's sensational trial, separated following Louise Woodward's
Oct. 30, 1997 conviction for killing 8-month-old Matthew Eappen of
Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Sky News reported that the police are looking into
allegations that approximately $283,000 was transferred out of the
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, including the FBI, who have been following a
trail of paper evidence in this country and abroad, refused to
identify the two people arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The pair, police said, were released on what the British call
``police bail'' pending a decision by crown prosecutors on whether
to formally file charges.
</P>
<P>
   Former family friend Elaine Whitfield Sharp, a lawyer who hosted
Susan Woodward at Sharp's Marblehead, Mass. home during Louise
Woodward's legal troubles, said Thursday she felt sorry, but not
surprised, by the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very sad that it's come to this,'' said Sharp, a one-time
ally of the Woodwards who severed any allegiance to them when she
alleged last year that Susan Woodward had forged Sharp's signature
on a $15,000 invoice drawn on the fund. Susan Woodward alleged that
Sharp charged her rent during Louise Woodward's sensational trial
near Boston in the fall of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a personal vindication,'' said Sharp, speaking
at a press conference Thursday. ``I never charged them a penny, and
I never lied about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was an intentional draining of the fund,'' said
Sharp, recalling that she grew suspicious when Woodward's parents
made public appeals for more money, when there was enough to
finance a new trial available.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said she believed the money was taken from the account so
the Matthew Eappen family would not be able to collect any funds in
a wrongful death lawsuit against Louise Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens' attorney declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the statement from Susan Woodward's attorney accused
Sharp of making false allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan Woodward took the opportunity to give the police her
side of the story and an insight into the motives of Elaine
Whitfield-Sharp in making false allegations against her and her
family,'' the statement read..
</P>
<P>
   Sharp had fallen from favor of the Woodwards in May of 1998,
when she was arrested for drunk driving, and allegedly told a
Massachusetts state trooper she was suffering, and drinking,
because she had to live with the knowledge that the young au pair
was guilty. Sharp denies making the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The defense funds were allegedly solicited to pay for a second
trial to clear the teenager's name.
</P>
<P>
   EF AuPair, the agency which recruited Woodward, paid the costs
of the initial trial, including the high-profile defense team of
Harvey Silverglate, Barry Scheck and Andrew Good.
</P>
<P>
   A Middlesex (Mass.) Superior Court jury convicted the au pair in
the second-degree murder of Matthew Eappen, who died of a fractured
skull in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, now 21 and studying law, was alone with the boy when
he was rushed to the hospital, his brain bleeding. A jury listened
to 17 days of testimony and convicted her of second-degree murder,
but Judge Hiller Zobel reduced the verdict to involuntary
manslaughter and set Woodward free on time served -- 279 days.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision was upheld by the state Supreme Judicial
Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
