<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP OFFERS REVAMPED GUN-CONTROL MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fearing political fallout from angry voters, Senate
Republicans reversed course Thursday, introducing a package of
gun-control restrictions and embracing a measure they had rejected
only 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Senate Thursday adopted a ban on high-capacity
ammunition clips, a provision that had been defeated a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Senators are scheduled to vote Friday on the GOP package, which
some Democrats called a ``sham,'' as part of the a bill that would
toughen prosecution of juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the shootings at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., the measure has become a forum for debating gun
control, with the Clinton administration proposals such mesures as
raising the legal age for gun ownership to 21 from 18 and holding
parents criminally liable for giving their children access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Thursday night whether Thursday's Republican
proposals represent a strategic retreat that will enable the GOP to
claim progress on gun-control while forestalling broader changes,
or whether public pressure will carry other Clinton-backed measures
to passage.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the Republican reversal was an indication
that the Colorado shootings have for the moment galvanized public
opinion, shifted the political debate in favor of tighter
restrictions on firearms, and created concerns about how potent an
issue gun control may become in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   It also may signal a weakening of the powerful gun lobby, the
National Rifle Association, which launched an intensive lobbying
effort this weak to counter gun-control groups, whicgh also were
out in force on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders decided to reverse course after a group of
senators indicated they were unhappy with a measure approved
Wednesday, which established a system of voluntary background
checks on firearms sales by private dealers at gun shows. Such
checks are mandatory on sales by licensed firearms dealers, and
Democrats had proposed closing this so-called loophole to include
gun show sales between private persons. Two guns used by the
Columbine students during their shooting spree were bought at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary system was proposed by Senator Larry Craig, an
Idaho Republican and NRA board member, and also would change how
the background-check rules apply to pawn shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just woke up unhappy at what we had done,'' said Senator
Gordon Smith, Republican of Oregon, who said he would try to change
his vote. ``I had been under the impression, perhaps mistaken, that
we would have an amendment that closed the gun show loophole.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans who made their concerns known to Craig and to
party leaders included moderate Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan
Collins, both of Maine. It also included Arizona Senator John
McCain, a presidential candidate who, Democrats speculated, might
be worried about the political potency of the issue as the election
year approaches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
