<DOCNO> NYT19990513.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS &LR;      05-13 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GOP LEADERSHIP RETREATS ON GUN CONTROL MEASURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional ending) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with stinging criticism from the White House
and some of its own members, the Senate GOP leadership Thursday
abruptly reversed course and threw its support behind mandatory
instant background checks for buyers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to endorse such gun show checks came a day after
the GOP majority narrowly defeated a similar measure proposed by
Senate Democrats and instead opted for voluntary checks. The Senate
is to vote Friday on the amendment to juvenile justice legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker who led the effort against mandatory gun show
checks, Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, said he changed his mind after
meeting with several Republicans who complained they were misled
about his voluntary approach.
</P>
<P>
   One of those GOP lawmakers, Sen. Gordon Smith of Oregon, who had
voted against mandatory checks and for the voluntary option,
threatened to have his voted changed unless the leadership
revisited the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I defend the Second Amendment for law-abiding citizens but not
for nuts and crooks,'' Smith said. ``If a gun is transacted at a
gun show, there should be a background check _ that is not a huge
imposition on the Second Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The reversal was a major embarrassment to the GOP leadership and
the National Rifle Association, which has lobbied heavily for the
defeat of new gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The gun show checks have emerged as a flash point in the
Senate's debate on juvenile crime in part because the issue is
related to the recent high school killings in Colorado. Some of the
weapons used by the student killers at Columbine High School in
suburban Littleton were purchased at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Currently the criminal background checks that are required for
gun purchases under the Brady Law can be avoided at gun shows,
where unlicensed dealers do not have to conduct such checks.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately pounced on the about-face by their
Republican colleagues as evidence that they had been overly
influenced by the gun lobby and were out of touch with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the gang that can't shoot straight,'' said Sen.
Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer and other Democrats remained wary of the mandatory
gun-show check proposal advanced by Republicans, arguing that
gaping loopholes remained.
</P>
<P>
   They claimed the GOP provision would exempt certain gun shows,
such as those with 10 tables or less, from forcing sellers to
conduct background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, they said the Republican version would exempt
pawnbrokers from doing such checks on people who bought back guns
they had turned over temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said such checks were unnecessary because pawn shops
already had to report to law-enforcement authorities any guns
turned into them.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over gun shows overshadowed the fact that the Senate
overwhelmingly approved a provision that would bar juveniles under
the age of 18 from purchasing semiautomatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The gun debate began early in the day as President Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno took time out to blast the Senate
Republicans for the previous day's vote to defeat mandatory
gun-show checks.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Senate defeated the mandatory checks 51-47 and
approved voluntary checks 53-41.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the life of me I can't figure out how they did it,''
Clinton said. He said that there was ``simply no excuse for letting
criminals get arms at gun shows they can't get at gun stores.''
</P>
<P>
   At her weekly news conference, Reno said ``I am stunned that
less than one month after the worst school shooting in our nation's
history the Senate has decided to make it easier for felons,
fugitives and other prohibited purchasers to buy guns,.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were quick to note the influence of the gun lobby and
pointed out that Sen. Craig is a board member of the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA was on the floor of the Senate working the well,''
said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., the chief Democratic sponsor of
the gun show checks.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Center for Responsive Politics study, the NRA and
other gun rights groups have given nearly $9 million to candidates
and political parties between 1991 and 1998. Republicans have
received 74 percent of those donations.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that those senators who voted against the
mandatory gun show checks Wednesday received an average of $10,478
from gun groups while those who voted in favor of it received an
average of $297.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Texas Republican Kay Bailey Hutchison led
lawmakers in contributions from gun groups, receiving $23,900
between 1993 and 1998, according to the Center for Responsive
Politics analysis. The state's senior senator, Republican Phil
Gramm, ranked fourth having received $18,550 from gun rights groups
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gramm and Hutchison voted initially against the mandatory
gun show checks and for the voluntary approach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
