<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-AD-COLUMN-AR     05-13 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-AD-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FOURTH `STAR WARS' FILM PREPARES TO OPEN, THE SALES FORCE IS
WITH US 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coming soon, a film with marketing more choreographed than a
Fred Astaire version of ``Saturday Night Fever!'' More skillfully
planned than the mission to save Matt Damon! A campaign more
orchestrated than all of Bernard Herrmann's scores for Alfred
Hitchcock! Yes, a movie even more unsinkable than Titanic!
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise what we're talking about. Only those overheated
trailers at the Bijous and Orpheums of the 1940s and '50s can
approximate the frenzied peddling of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace.'' Though the movie does not open until Wednesday,
merchandise is flooding toy stores, Web sites, fast-food
restaurants, computer stores, music stores, supermarkets,
bookstores and newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   Fed by legions of enthusiasts who have waited years for this
moment _ at some theaters, they camped out for weeks to get advance
tickets that went on sale this Wednesday afternoon _ the fourth
``Star Wars'' film has taken on a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's genuine passion here; no one is telling those people
to line up,'' said Dawn Hudson, senior vice president for strategy
and marketing at the Pepsi-Cola Co. unit of Pepsico Inc. in
Purchase, N.Y., which is spending $2 billion to sponsor ``The
Phantom Menace'' and sequels to be released in 2002 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The new installment, the first ``prequel'' to the original
trinity, is largely selling itself _ thanks in no small part to the
eager involvement of licensees, merchandisers, retailers and, of
course, the news media, churning out programs and articles like
this one.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the groundswell of excitement, though, is a well-tended
machine, cranking out the biggest marketing blitz ever for a mere
movie. That effort is being supervised down to the teensiest detail
by George Lucas, the zillionaire writer-producer-director who
created the ``Star Wars'' juggernaut and whose Lucasfilm Ltd. has
been working on the next chapter since the last film was released
in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketing of an entertainment property is becoming the
story instead of the property itself,'' said Michael Schau,
executive editor of the Entertainment Marketing Letter newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to college,'' he said, ``we didn't ask each
other, `What do you suppose the top-grossing movie was this
weekend?' Now we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since ``Gone With the Wind'' has there been so much
spontaneous anticipation so far in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something there that touches their hearts,'' said
Howard Roffman, vice president for licensing at Lucasfilm in San
Rafael, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any hype at all, it comes from the media,'' he
added. ``They see this as an important story that will get viewers
and sell newspapers and magazines. It has resulted in a level of
attention we frankly are not seeking ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two major newspapers are printing daily ``countdown''
features. Magazines with cover articles include Entertainment
Weekly, GQ, Newsweek, Premiere, Time, Vanity Fair, Wired _ even
Popular Mechanics (``The Machines of `Star Wars'''), Vogue (```Star
Wars' Couture'') and TV Guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't plan on becoming a cultural phenomenon,'' said
Roffman, who joined Lucasfilm in 1980, or as he dates it, ``a
couple weeks before `The Empire Strikes Back' was released.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like people sat down in 1975 and said, `Let's create
a space mythology that'll last for generations,''' he added. ``It
all stems from demand from the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   That was underscored in November, when thousands of ``Star
Wars'' fans bought tickets for clunky films like ``Meet Joe Black''
just to catch the 130-second trailer for ``The Phantom Menace.'' It
was further verified this week by the telephone and Internet
traffic jams that occurred on buying sites around the country after
tickets went on sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' has become a consumer brand, promising quality and
performance the way brand-name cars, candy and clothing do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great brands create a relationship between a company and a
consumer that secures future earnings,'' said John Grace, an
executive director at Interbrand, a consulting company in New York
owned by Omnicom Group. `` `Star Wars' has all the characteristics
of a great brand of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Just look at Hasbro Inc., the toy company whose licensing deal
with Lucasfilm dates to the first film in 1977. One Hasbro
executive, Tim Hall, has a title that says it all: vice president
for ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   To renew its agreement with Lucas, Hasbro is guaranteeing an
estimated $500 million in royalties from ``Phantom Menace''
products that range from Darth Maul With Lightsaber to the Anakin
Skywalker Podracer to the Hidden Majesty Queen Amidala.
</P>
<P>
   Behind it all stands Lucas. ``I've got to hand it to George,''
said Jack Trout, president at Trout &AMP; Partners, marketing
consultants in Greenwich, Conn. ``He's turning an 800-pound gorilla
into King Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's brilliant the way he has carefully nurtured this property
over many years,'' Trout said. ``Eat your heart out, Walt Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   The usually reclusive Lucas, who oversees Lucasfilm and other
companies like Lucasarts Entertainment, has granted a score of
interviews to help stoke the bonfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to admire Lucas for his long-term approach,'' said
Peter Waller, president and chief concept officer at Taco Bell in
Irvine, Calif., one of three chains owned by Tricon Global
Restaurants that are the fast-food marketing partners for the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about a great summer movie,'' Waller asserted.
``It's about building `Star Wars' in a real brand sense as an
experience people want to keep re-entering.''
</P>
<P>
   There are predictions that ``The Phantom Menace,'' which will be
distributed by the 20th Century Fox unit of the News Corp., could
set records by taking in as much as $100 million in its first five
days. Topping ``Titanic,'' which garnered worldwide grosses of more
than $1.8 billion, would be ``a tall order,'' said Paul
Dergarabedian, president at the Exhibitor Relations Co. in Los
Angeles, which tracks box-office performance. Even so, he added,
``if any film has the chance to do it, it would be this one.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
