<HEADER>
A6261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-AD-COLUMN-2N     05-13 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-AD-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: be this one.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still, ``any high-profile film that gets lots of interest and
attention can fall victim to the double-edged sword,''
Dergarabedian warned, adding that it is particularly true for a
film that ``has had such a high profile for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   There are already signs of trouble. Both Time and Newsweek
dubbed the new film ``The Phantom Movie,'' and there have been
harshly negative advance reviews as well as derogatory columns by
critics like Jack Mathews of The Daily News in New York. He mocked
the selling of the film with such lines as ``May the Sales Force be
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   To help cool the overheated expectations, the advertising budget
for ``The Phantom Menace'' is less than $20 million, not much for a
film with a budget of $115 million competing in the blockbuster
sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to overdo it,'' said Roffman at Lucasfilm.
``The worst thing you can do is to create a plan based on your
needs instead of the consumers'.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas recognizes the potential pitfalls, said Jill Wilfert,
senior brand manager at Lego Systems in Enfield, Conn., a unit of
Lego Group, who met with him as part of planning for her company's
``Phantom Menace'' line _ its first licensed merchandise ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants people to have a good experience with the movie and
not see it as being overly commercialized,'' Ms. Wilfert said,
``because he doesn't want them to be sick of it after a few
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the movie will benefit from spillover from its
partners' own marketing campaigns, which will include glitzy
commercials by the BBDO New York and TBWA/Chiat/Day units of
Omnicom for Pepsico and Tricon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this to be one of our most successful promotions''
across ``our entire peak summer selling season,'' said Ms. Hudson
at Pepsi-Cola, which hopes to sell millions of cans of five
soft-drink brands that feature ``Phantom Menace'' characters.
Consumers who find cans bearing the venerable visage of Yoda can
redeem them for `` `Star Wars' checks'' worth $20.
</P>
<P>
   At Tricon, which owns Pizza Hut and KFC in addition to Taco
Bell, the campaign marks the first time the three brands have
united under a single promotional theme. ``It's all in the
never-been-done-before league,'' Waller said.
</P>
<P>
   Each chain will be identified with one of three planets in the
movie, Coruscant, Naboo and Tatooine, selling toys and drink-cup
tops with names like Opee Sea Creature Chaser, Jar Jar Binks
Squishy and Hovering Watto.
</P>
<P>
   For true fans, though, even too much commercialization may not
be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans are so into `Star Wars' that the advertising is almost
entertainment to them, part of the cultural impact the film is
making,'' said Tim Doyle, a copywriter at Leo Burnett Interactive
in Toronto, part of the Leo Burnett Co. Doyle and two fellow fans
in Australia and Los Angeles have on their own put up a ``Phantom
Menace'' Web site (www.starwars.countingdown.com).
</P>
<P>
   So how will ``The Phantom Menace'' do?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the box office, total merchandise sales may reach $2
billion this year _ almost half what the ``Star Wars'' franchise
has sold since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   In theaters, ``America is ready to climb back into fantasy land
and see the good guys beat the bad guys,'' Trout predicted. ``Wait
till it opens and the lines are wrapped around the block. Wait till
you see the press for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The final word goes to Dergarabedian at Exhibitor Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make money whether there is good word of mouth or bad
word of mouth,'' he said, ``but what will keep it playing is
terrific word of mouth. There's no better marketing than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
