<HEADLINE>
`MIDSUMMER'S NIGHT DREAM' SUFFERS FROM AN AVALANCHE OF STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a recent interview, British actor Jeremy Northam groaned over
the popular consensus about William Shakespeare's best-known
comedy, ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do people persist in thinking it's a twee little play?''
he wondered. ``It's all about sex!''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, every character in the enchanted comedy lusts for
someone; Oberon, the fairy king, for his queen, Titania; Theseus
for Hippolyta; Lysander for Hermia; and Helena for Demetrius; even
Nick, the weaver, eyeballs every woman who walks by.
</P>
<P>
   Lust is certainly hinted at in director/writer Michael Hoffman's
long-delayed version, which he has reset in Tuscany at the end of
the 19th century. So why doesn't it have an ounce of oomph or sex
appeal?
</P>
<P>
   The cast is attractive enough: Michelle Pfeiffer is Titania.
Rupert Everett stars as Oberon. Stanley Tucci plays the impish
fairy Puck, who casts spells over a quartet of lost lovers one warm
summer's night. The lovers are played by Christian Bale, Anna
Friel, Dominic West and Calista Flockhart. And Kevin Kline is
onboard as Nick Bottom, the weaver who is turned into an ass by one
of Oberon and Puck's more mean-spirited spells.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Will's tale: Hermia (Friel) is being married off to
Demetrius (Bale). But she really loves Lysander (West). Her best
friend Helena (Flockhart) adores Demetrius, who looks upon her with
disdain. Hermia and Lysander plan to run away and elope but Helena
tells Demetrius, who pursues the couple deep into the woods. They
crash into the secluded kingdom of the fairy king, Oberon, his
queen Titania and his prankster imp Puck. Spells are cast, chaos
ensues and by dawn, true love prevails.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the course of true love never did flow smooth,'' wrote
Shakespeare, and indeed it's not the only thing that stops and
starts in this ragged version. Hoffman, who did the adaptation
himself, cuts and pastes portions of the play into his movie with a
clunky hand. And the avalanche of star power nearly sinks the ship.
Certainly Hoffman is prepared to handle a big cast; his films
``Promised Land'' and ``Restoration'' were full of talent and he
directed both movies stylishly. But he's also the guy who made the
stagnant romantic comedy ``One Fine Day,'' which starred Pfeiffer
as well.
</P>
<P>
   She's one of the biggest problems with this film too. Titania
should sparkle and glow with earthiness. When that happens,
Oberon's demands and trickery make sense. Pfeiffer is too ethereal
to make us believe that the king's libido would rise because of
her.
</P>
<P>
   Of the lovers, Friel and West fare best. They have an ease with
the text and momentarily spark the film to life. Flockhart gives a
valiant effort, but it's too apparent she's ``acting.'' And Kline
throws the film off-kilter entirely with his overblown, hammy
portrayal. By the time he musters the pathos Nick needs, the
credits are about to roll.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the problem is less theirs than the script's. Hoffman stuffs
his film with shots of Tuscany that are as overripe as an olive. He
makes a mess of his marketplace scenes by throwing in everything
but the kitchen sink and his enchanted forest looks like the set
was carved out of plastic. Shakespeare's comical, all-too-human
tale of lust, foreplay and wordplay is buried beneath bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   A Midsummer Night's Dream. Directed and adapted by Michael
Hoffman from Shakespeare's play. Cast: Kevin Kline, Michelle
Pfeiffer, Rupert Everett, Stanley Tucci, Calista Flockhart. Fox
Searchlight. 115 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
