</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JOAN-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STIRRING `JOAN OF ARC' FROM CBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The viewing public might have restrained enthusiasm for whether
a 15th century peasant could break up the Burgundian alliance with
the English and revive the Valois dynasty in France.
</P>
<P>
   No, the 15th century is so ancient and musty that it seems
almost as long ago as 1969.
</P>
<P>
   But French history aside, the story of Joan of Arc is timeless,
and the CBS miniseries ``Joan of Arc'' (airing Sunday and Tuesday)
is an honest effort to tell it. Sometimes even a grand effort.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a conscious effort, along with NBC's ``Noah's Ark''
and ABC's ``Cleopatra'' this month, to keep alive the flickering
tradition of spectacle in sweeps-month miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joan of Arc'' is frustratingly uneven, and some of the stars
in its cast are twinkling in the wrong firmament. But it's head,
shoulders and coat of armor above CBS' junky ``Last Don''
centerpieces of the past two May sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly incongruous cast includes Jacqueline Bisset, Peter
O'Toole, Neil Patrick Harris, Robert Loggia, Shirley MacLaine,
Olympia Dukakis, Powers Boothe, Maximilian Schell and Peter
Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old Leelee Sobieski (``Never Been Kissed'') is cast
as Joan, a star-making role that led famously to Marshalltown,
Iowa, and the discovery of Jean Seberg for Otto Preminger's 1957
film ``Saint Joan.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski proves to be an acquired taste. It's no big deal that
her face is so startlingly reminiscent of Helen Hunt's. The initial
problem is one of those cinematic mysteries. The eyes, the mouth,
the demeanor, the delivery all smack of United States 1999, not
provincial France nearly 600 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Joan of Arc'' unleashes a little miracle of its own.
Sobieski grows into the role. If she never quite propels Joan into
the ethereal realm, she at least achieves dignity and depth, a girl
fearful of her terrible fate _ to be convicted of heresy and burned
at the stake _ but ultimately secure in her faith.
</P>
<P>
   Booth is seriously miscast as Joan's father. Same for Loggia as
the wig-domed priest in Joan's native village, Domremy. And Strauss
as a battle-hardened French warrior? Uh, no.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is a pleasant surprise as the French king, Charles VII.
You might expect him to be more Doogie than dauphin, but he
performs confidently and believably as a cunning ruler who exploits
Joan's magnetism.
</P>
<P>
   MacLaine grabs a few scenes as Madame de Beaurevoir, a
Burgundian noblewoman who briefly protects the captured Joan.
O'Toole dresses up the production as Bishop Cauchon, the king's
spiritual adviser and later one of Joan's inquisitors.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a restrained O'Toole, venturing no closer to over
the top than a whiff of jaded wistfulness. He seems to respect the
material, even when he ties the ribbon on this deliberately goofy
line:
</P>
<P>
   ``As his majesty's church-appointed spiritual adviser, I advise
his majesty not to take lightly the advice of his church-appointed
spiritual adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   The line is doubly instructive because it suggests that the
screenwriters, Ronald Parker and Michael Miller, can bat the
language around with more skill than is routinely apparent in
network movies. The script is erratic, but it hits peaks far above
the TV norm.
</P>
<P>
   (Incidentally, one of the actual charges against Joan was that
the saints Catherine, Margaret and Michael spoke to her in French
rather than in English. That's not mentioned in the miniseries.
Maybe there's no point in riling Canadian viewers.)
</P>
<P>
   Fluidly directed by Christian Duguay, ``Joan of Arc'' was filmed
in the Czech Republic, where dozens of battlements and hundreds of
extras provide a balance between taste and gore in the medieval
battle scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Few viewers will succeed in deciphering the historical details
of ``Joan of Arc.'' But there's nothing stale about the conflict
between gnarled intrigue and innocence, or between cunning and
character.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Joan of Arc,'' CBS takes the highest aim of the '98-99
television season. This is a miniseries that wants to stir the
soul. It creates a rustle, at least.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
