<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS14-COX     05-13 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS LOAD UP EMERGENCY KOSOVO BILL
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An emergency measure that began with a $6 billion
request for the air war in Yugoslavia swelled Thursday into a $14
billion package that includes relief for interests ranging from the
oil and gas industry to Alaska crab fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   As House and Senate negotiators continued to wrangle over the
spending bill Thursday night, they received reassurance from
President Clinton that he might sign it, despite earlier hints of a
veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the funds now, and we need the demonstration of
support for the Kosovar refugees and for Macedonia and Albania
now,'' Clinton said in a speech to veterans groups, adding that he
was ``pretty encouraged'' by reports that the bill would be scaled
back.
</P>
<P>
   However, the only add-on that was deleted Thursday was $1
billion in loan guarantees to bail out the steel industry, which
has been buffeted by a flood of cheap Asian imports. Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., had pushed for the provision and bitterly protested
when the House-Senate conference narrowly dropped his amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see here is a steamroller,'' Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, support by other senators raised the prospect
that Byrd's amendment might be resurrected. In addition, Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, was trying to revive a measure killed
earlier that would aid the oil and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill almost doubles the $6 billion that Clinton
sought for the conflict over Kosovo. The joint congressional
conference has agreed to spend $11.7 billion related to the crisis,
most of it for the military, and the rest for aid to the Kosovar
refugees and the Balkan nations which are harboring them.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the bill is nearly $1 billion that Clinton proposed to
help Honduras and other Central American countries hit last year by
the devastation of Hurricane Mitch. The conferees added $566
million in aid to U.S. farmers hit by a drastic drop in commodity
prices.
</P>
<P>
   With a bill that seemed almost certain of passage before them,
many lawmakers were not about to miss an opportunity to attach
special-interest provisions. Outside the Capitol basement meeting
room, lobbyists waited in the hallways and dialed cell phones to
report updates.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pet issues that made their way onto the bill:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hutchison won approval of a plan to forbid the federal
government from sharing _ or even telling states how to spend _ the
$246 billion won in their lawsuits against the tobacco industry.
Hutchison had been allied with Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., in the
effort to keep the federal government from funneling a share of the
money into Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   _ A second Hutchison provision would give more help to the
energy industry, delaying until at least next October any change in
the way the Interior Deparment calculates royalties for oil and gas
drilled on federal lands. The department has said the royalties are
not based on the actual market value of the oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Ala., won provisions to aid crab fishermen
in Glacier Bay, Alaska, and also tucked a provision for $3 million
for reindeer ranchers, which he touted as ``my Santa Claus
provision.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., inserted a provision overruling an
Interior Department action that had stalled a mining company,
Battle Mountain Gold of Houston, which has been attempting to
establish a mine on Buckhorn Mountain in his state.
Environmentalists' efforts to head off the Gorton amendment failed.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gorton decried the packaging of so much
spending in the guise of an emergency. ``I am very dubious about
the entire bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another critic of the bill, Rep. Dave Obey, D-Wis., said
Thursday that since the emergency bill would provide so much basic
funding for military operations and maintenance, ammunition,
aircraft and a pay raise, lawmakers would be able to include much
more spending for pet local projects in the annual defense
appropriations bill next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the snow plow that clears the way for the snow job,''
Obey said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Kosovo bill and its amendments are considered
``emergency'' spending, the funds are exempt from spending caps
that limit how much Congress can include in annual appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who has lambasted Congress for using
defense spending bills as a vehicle for pet programs, offered a
similar view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so disillusioning because, also as a Republican, you
know we promised when we came to power in 1994 we wouldn't do those
things anymore,'' he said Wednesday on the ``Midweek With Mary
Matalin'' show on the America's Voice Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I have to tell you we do them just as much as the
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
