<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SARAZEN-APPRECIATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARAZEN AN ENDURING HERO OF GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was best known for one incredible golf shot, but the
greatness of Gene Sarazen should be measured by his many triumphs
and unmatched dignity.
</P>
<P>
   If there were a collective conscience in the game, flags on all
pins throughout the land today would be lowered, for the sport must
bid farewell to one of its enduring heroes. Sarazen, 97, died
Thursday in Naples, Fla., from complications of pneumonia and in
all corners of the golf world, the pain is felt. ``You hate to lose
people like him, because you lose such a part of the game,'' said
course architect Rees Jones. ``And the game just ain't the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he is right. But if those of us who never had the
pleasure of meeting Sarazen are saddened, imagine the heartache
felt by those who knew The Squire not as the ceremonial starter of
the Masters, dressed in his trademark knickers, but as a consummate
gentleman with a stern, competitive spirit. ``It is sad news,''
said Herbert Warren Wind, whose eloquent prose about this great
game appeared for years in The New Yorker and has never been
equaled. ``He was a great friend. Gene had a sense of standards. I
really think the best way to present Gene is to say he had brains
and enough insight to know to stay in shape and pick really fine
people as friends and model himself after them.''
</P>
<P>
   We study history as children, then toss it aside as we grow up
and chase a string of tomorrows. So perhaps we need to be reminded
that the men of hickory and Gutta-percha were skilled athletes,
too, that golfers were not invented by television or nurtured by
irrigation systems. Gene Sarazen played the game long before money
soiled it and his achievements are a testament to his
determination.
</P>
<P>
   If he were a rare athlete to whom success came early _ Sarazen
won both the US Open and PGA Championship in 1922 when he was 20
and earned another PGA title in 1923 _ so, too, was this
5-foot-5-inch son of a carpenter a patient soul who never quit. For
a period of nearly eight years, Sarazen played poorly in the
majors &UR;  &LR; or made bad mistakes when he did challenge, the cause being
a nasty hook he could not solve. When he finally did, he was 30
years old and in the next five years he would win a second US Open,
a third PGA, the British Open, and that monumental event at Augusta
National in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   It was called the ``Annual Invitation Tournament'' back then,
but Sarazen's second shot to the par-5 15th in the final round went
a long way in turning it into The Masters. The 4-wood from 220
yards rolled into the cup, a double-eagle, and became the most
famous shot in the sport's history thanks in part to the playoff he
got into and won over Craig Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a spectacular shot,'' Sarazen would always say, ``but
it was just a piece of luck. They forget the championships I won.''
</P>
<P>
   Only if they are ignorant; for Sarazen is one of four golfers
(Ben Hogan, Jack Nicklaus, and Gary Player being the others) to win
all four of the majors. And, in this year of the Ryder Cup, let us
pause to recall that Sarazen was the last living member of that
1927 inaugural event in Worcester, Mass. Nor should we overlook
another remarkable aspect of Sarazen's golf career, that being the
polished play he exhibited as he aged so gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, for instance, he was 38 and semiretired when he lost a
US Open playoff to Lawson Little at Canterbury GC in Cleveland.
Seven years later, Sarazen beat Sam Snead, then the game's dominant
player, in a second-round match of the PGA Championship. The next
year in that event, Sarazen lost to Ben Hogan on the 36th hole in
the third round. At age 56, he finished in a tie for 16th at the
British Open and in 1963, the 61-year-old Sarazen made the cut at
the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was the 1973 British Open at Royal Troon
in western Scotland. Sarazen, then 71, had been extended a special
invitation by the Royal &AMP; Ancient and their wisdom paid off with a
priceless golf memory _ he aced the infamous Postage Stamp par-3
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   It was a perfect stroke of great fortune for a man who was
brought into this world with not a lick of it.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Italian immigrants, Eugenio Saraceni was born in 1902
in Harrison, N.Y., and raised during a time of great hardship, the
likes of which few of us can fathom. ``He was from such an ordinary
family, but he was such a classy man,'' said Wind. ``He was one of
the only players I knew to come from such a family of immigrants.''
</P>
<P>
   To help support the family, Sarazen worked numerous odd jobs,
but one of them turned his life around. He was toting golf bags at
the Apawamis Club in Rye, N.Y., in 1913 when a former caddie from
Brookline, Mass. named Francis Ouimet shocked the golf world by
winning the US Open. ``If he can win it, so can I,'' thought
Sarazen, and he immediately changed his grip to the interlocking
style favored by Ouimet.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Sarazen and Ouimet would become close friends and if
they were separated by nearly 20 years, they were brought together
by their love of golf and a common decency that is found in only
the rarest of those special people. ``Please write that,'' said
Wind, ``for they were great friends and great, great men.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen was a true treasure, an athlete who captured a nation's
attention when Ruth was king and still gripped our sporting spirit
every April when he would unleash that classic swing to start the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was doing his autobiography (in the 1940s),'' said
Wind, ``I spent six or seven weeks with him at his farm in
Germantown, N.Y. He always had his feet on the ground. He told me,
`If my game ever disappears, I will have this farm still going for
me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His game did fade away, though fortunately for us, he didn't. At
least not for a long, delightful, and very rewarding time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
