</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-DECISION-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.) 
WAL-MART DECIDES AGAINST SELLING EMERGENCY CONTRACEPTIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. has decided not to sell an emergency
contraceptive approved last year for sale in the United States and
widely available in drugstores nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The company stated in a letter to Planned Parenthood that it had
made a ``business decision'' not to fill prescriptions for Preven,
which stops ovulation and may prevent fertilized eggs from becoming
implanted in the uterus. The drug, manufactured by Gynetics Inc. of
Somerville, N.J., is recommended for use up to 72 hours after
unprotected sex and is sometimes called a ``morning after'' pill.
</P>
<P>
   Though Wal-Mart declined repeated requests for more information
about its decision, Planned Parenthood said it suspected the policy
might have stemmed from pressure from people who say life begins
the moment an egg is fertilized. Anti-abortion groups have not,
however, singled out Preven for attack, as they did with RU-486, an
abortion pill that is illegal in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart is the nation's fifth-largest distributor of
pharmaceuticals, with a strong presence in the South, and has
pharmacies in more than 2,428 of its 2,450 stores.
</P>
<P>
   According to a two-sentence statement: ``At this time Wal-Mart
has made the business decision not to sell Preven. However, in the
interest of serving and meeting the needs of our customers, our
pharmacists will refer any request for this product to a pharmacy
that does carry it.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug is being sold in other major retail chains and discount
stores, including Walgreens, Rite Aid and Kmart. Sales are
relatively small, estimated at $10 million this year, though
Gynetics, a private company, declined to release figures.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the decision represents little lost business for
Wal-Mart. But Planned Parenthood worries that in some markets,
particularly small towns where Wal-Mart has little competition,
women may have difficulty getting the drug elsewhere quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Preven, which costs about $20 for four pills that are taken two
at a time over 12 hours, is a high-dose birth control medication.
The drug, which the manufacturer says is 98 percent effective,
usually has only mild side effects, which include nausea, dizziness
and vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   For decades doctors have instructed women to take high doses of
regular birth control pills as emergency contraception. But Preven
is the first birth control medication to be marketed specifically
for that use.
</P>
<P>
   It is not to be confused with RU-486, which can be used within
49 days of unprotected sex to induce an abortion and is legal in
Europe and in China. RU-486 requires repeat visits to a doctor and
has been associated with some serious side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike RU-486, Preven does not work if a fertilized egg has
already been implanted in the uterus. Even so, Pro-Life America,
Protestants Against Birth Control and Pharmacists for Life
International say they oppose Preven because they consider it to
work by prompting an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike RU-486, however, Preven was not the target of widespread
opposition, and some anti-abortion groups, including the Right To
Life Committee, do not take a stance on it at all. But as the drug
has hit store shelves, some groups have issued statements opposing
it.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacies for Life International, for instance, says it had
expressed its concerns about the drug to Wal-Mart and applauded the
chain for not selling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concur with Wal-Mart on that decision,'' said Lloyd J.
DuPlantis Jr., president of the group, which said it has 1,500
member pharmacists, though he said his group was not the catalyst
for the Wal-Mart ban.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Wal-Mart's reasoning, the policy has confused the
drug's manufacturer and angered women's health advocates.
</P>
<P>
   The Planned Parenthood Federation of America expressed outrage
over the decision by Wal-Mart, saying the company ``deserts women
faced with reproductive health emergencies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood's New York affiliate has been one of the most
outspoken critics and has alerted women through newsletters about
Wal-Mart's policy. It has also asked Aetna/US Healthcare, which
provides insurance to Planned Parenthood's employees, to find
another prescription-by-mail service, now provided by Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is unacceptable from a women's health point of
view'' for Wal-Mart pharmacies not to carry the drug,'' said
Alexander C. Sanger, president of Planned Parenthood of New York
City. ``Wal-Mart pharmacies are licensed by the states in which
they operate and are thereby part of the public health system, and
we believe it is incumbent upon them to have available this
time-sensitive medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Wal-Mart refuses to sell other prescription
medications, Jessica Moser, a company spokeswoman, said that she
could not discuss specific products, but ``it is not practical
given the sheer volume to carry every one of them.'' The company
does carry birth control pills.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer, is a leading pharmacy
chain, trailing only CVS, Walgreen, Eckerd and Rite Aid, according
to Drug Store News. As such, the retailer has an obligation not to
withhold drugs that doctors have decided its customers need, said
Marie Griffin, editor of the trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should not get involved in the sacred relationship
between a physician and patient,'' Ms. Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists for Life International disagrees, saying there are
times when pharmacies should not dispense medication. ``First of
all, our position is that in general a pharmacist has a right to
refuse to fill a prescription,'' said DuPlantis, the group's
president. ``Regarding Preven, based on the way we feel that life
begins at fertilization, it's an abortifacient mechanism.''
Therefore, Wal-Mart, he said, should not sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Gynetics said that Preven does not cause abortions but simply
prevents pregnancy. Roderick Mackenzie, the company's chairman,
said that the product had been better received by major drugstore
and discount chains than initially expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have every piece of business available in the
world,'' Mackenzie said, ``but I'm realistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
