<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LED BY IBM, DOW AND S&AMP;P SET NEW RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices mostly advanced Thursday, buoyed by
economic reports that pushed down long-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But while two of the main gauges, the Dow Jones industrial
average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, reached new
highs, the bulk of their gains came from a spectacular 20{-point
leap in IBM shares after the company's chairman said the computer
giant was getting about one-quarter of its revenue from
Internet-related business.
</P>
<P>
   Big Blue finished at a record of 246 and accounted for 87
percent of the Dow's rise of 106.82 points and nearly two-thirds of
the 3.56-point rise in the S&AMP;P 500. The stock has now soared 43
percent since announcing April 21 that first-quarter earnings far
surpassed expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow finished up 1 percent, to 11,107.19, while the S&AMP;P 500
rose 0.3 percent, to 1,367.56.
</P>
<P>
   A second outsized winner was J.P. Morgan, which jumped 7|, to
146} after traders began recirculating a month-old report by a
Dillon Read analyst suggesting that the bank, which until recently
has been bedeviled by weak earnings, was vulnerable to a takeover
and might be bought during the next year. But people close to
Morgan's senior management said a sale was highly unlikely because
the bank's board wanted to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an afternoon sell-off in Internet and other
high-technology stocks left the NASDAQ composite index with a loss
of 24.54 points, or 0.9 percent, to 2,582.00. The index, breaking a
string of four straight gains, now stands 70 points below its
record close of 2,652.05 on April 26. Analysts said the market was
relieved that a government report showed inflation still well in
check, with little sign that an upturn in oil prices was rippling
through the economy. With further encouragement from slower growth
of retail sales in April, interest rates retreated by as much as
one-tenth of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing was the extremely favorable data as far as
inflation was concerned,'' said Charles Pradilla, chief investment
strategist at S.G. Cowen Securities. ``Bonds were very oversold.''
</P>
<P>
   The government is scheduled to report Friday on inflation at the
consumer level. Barring a significant surprise, the Federal Reserve
is expected to leave interest rates alone at its meeting on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the central bank are keeping a close eye on the
stock and bond markets, with Fed Vice Chairman Alice Rivlin, saying
that ``someone's being very optimistic about earnings to want to
pay those prices'' in reference to blue-chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dow's big gain Thursday, achieved despite 15 of its 30
components being down, the blue-chip average has advanced 21
percent so far this year compared with 11.25 percent for the S&AMP;P
500 and 17.8 percent for NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most sessions, neither growth stocks nor those sensitive
to the business cycle stood out as a group. Yet the violent
rotation into cyclicals this spring has clearly wound down, with
many analysts contending that stocks like Alcoa and Minnesota
Mining &AMP; Manufacturing, which have enjoyed huge run-ups, have
little further potential.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Mining was the Dow's biggest loser Thursday, shedding
2 15/16, to 90 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs was one of the solid sectors Thursday, with Lilly up 2
7/16, to 78~; Pfizer up 2 1/16, to 117 13/16, and Merck up 1 7/16,
to 73. Some bank stocks besides Morgan also rose.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were mostly weak, with Amazon.com down 6
15/16, to 136. Ebay fell 6\, to 192{; Intel dropped 2 7/16, to 60
1/16; America Online sank 5 13/16, to 132|, and EMC fell 5 5/16, to
105 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   In an initial offering, Copper Mountain Networks, a company in
Palo Alto, Calif., whose products provide access to the Internet
over telephone lines, posted the 10th-biggest first-day gain on
record. It offered 4 million shares at 21, with trading starting at
63 and ending at 68 7/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
