<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6273 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-13 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Become A Telecommuter
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'm 66, with arthritis and hearing loss. I'd like to get
a job that involves working at home on my computer but that doesn't
require any telephone work. I assume there are a lot of clerical
opportunities that would fit this bill. However, I'm having trouble
finding lists of big national companies that employ telecommuters
like me. Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Telecommuting may sound like a perfect solution but,
frankly, it's going to be hard to find the kind of job you're
seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Most of today's telecommuters are people who started out in an
office and over time persuaded their boss that they were dependable
enough to telecommute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rare for companies to hire telecommuters from
outside: They're almost always selected from the current
workforce,'' said Gil Gordon, a New Jersey telecommuting consultant
with a helpful Web site at  &LR; www.gilgordon.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   There also aren't any good lists of companies that employ
at-home clerical workers. In fact, you should think twice before
joining up with some firms that actively advertise for home-based
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases, they're just disguised PC sales operations,''
Gordon said. ``They require you to buy a computer from them before
getting any work. Any venture that requires you to lay out money _
to buy a PC, for instance, or a business kit _ is probably a
scam.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of looking for big national employers, try thinking
locally.
</P>
<P>
   Check the Yellow Pages for local companies that provide services
such as data processing or transcription. Also check the
help-wanted ads in your local newspaper for firms seeking data
entry workers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these firms may be willing to let you work at home. But
you'll improve your chances if you're a little flexible about where
you work. For instance, employers may want you to spend your first
few weeks working out of their main office. Or they may want you to
come into the office once a week for meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is starting your own business. You can market
your clerical services to small businesses that have more
data-entry work than their current office staff can handle. The
drawback is that running a business takes constant marketing and
hustle, as well as a lot of record-keeping _ perhaps more effort
than you're willing to put in at this point in your life.
</P>
<P>
   Legal Red Flags
</P>
<P>
   Q: I work at a health care facility, where we insert credit
card-style time cards into a clock each morning. The clock
automatically deducts a half hour for lunch each day, even though
we often have no break due to short staffing. We're not given any
written record of our hours, and when we get our checks, they are
always short a few hours. Is this legal?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: No, it's not legal. In fact, your situation raises a
number of legal red flags:
</P>
<P>
   _Federal and state laws require employees to be paid for all the
hours they actually work. By not paying you for those lunch hours
that you spend working, this company is breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
   _California employers are required to give workers a meal break
after five hours of work. In some circumstances employees can waive
their right to a meal break _ but they must do so in writing. It
sounds like your employer is violating the state labor code by
having people work through lunch on a routine basis.
</P>
<P>
   _California also requires employers to indicate total hours
worked on the paycheck stubs of hourly workers. If your firm isn't
tallying your hours on your pay stub, that's another violation.
</P>
<P>
   You should politely inform management of these potential legal
problems. Not only is the company treating you badly, it's putting
itself in serious financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The California Labor Commissioner could do an audit of the
past three years, and this company could end up having to pay a lot
of back wages and penalties,'' warned Ralph Yanello, CEO of Lexcom,
an employment law advisory service in Walnut Creek.
</P>
<P>
   If management refuses to retool its pay practices and give you
the back wages you are owed, call the labor commissioner's office
at (415) 557-7878. Or call the Employment Law Center, which offers
free legal advice to low-income workers at (415) 864-8208.
</P>
<P>
   Buyout Game
</P>
<P>
   Q: The company my wife works for is being bought out. Some
employees including my wife will be rehired by the new company.
They've been told that their 401(k) plan will be frozen for 60
days, with no additions or withdrawals allowed. At the end of those
60 days, my wife can roll over her proceeds into the new company's
401(k) plan or an IRA. Is this standard procedure? Just what are
the rules in buyouts when both companies have 401(k) plans?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: This sounds pretty typical. Companies facing a merger
have two options for their 401(k) plans, according to David Peckman
of 401k CQ  &LR; Forum, an investment advisory service in San Francisco.
They can:
</P>
<P>
   _Terminate one of the plans and allow employees the option of
moving their funds into the other plan. (It sounds like this is
what your wife's firm is doing.)
</P>
<P>
   _Integrate the two plans. One plan ends and employee funds are
moved automatically into similar investments in the other plan _
from one small-cap mutual fund to another, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, it's not unusual to have a blackout period
ranging from 30 days to three months when employees can't touch
their 401(k) money. That's to give the plan administrators time to
handle all the paperwork involved with the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 60-day freeze is very common when moving over to a new
(401(k) management) company,'' said Cari Kaye, a spokeswoman for
Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   After the blackout period, your wife should be able to choose to
move her funds into the new firm's 401(k) or into an IRA, without
any tax penalty. She can also take the money out in cash _ but
would face stiff tax penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Want more info on 401(k) procedures? Some useful Web sites are
the one run by 401k Forum at  &LR; www.401kafe.com &LR;  and the one run by
Fidelity at  &LR; www.fidelityatwork.com/401k &LR;   &LR; /about/about.htm. &LR;  Or
check out the Web site of the Profit Sharing/ 401(k) Council of
America at  &LR; www.psca.org/particip.html. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
