<SLUG> BC-FILM-TEA-WITH-MUSSOLINI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEA WITH MUSSOLINI' A STORY OF DIVERSE CHARACTERS IN DIFFICULT
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to throw stones at the historical accuracy of a
private memoir when it's transferred to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Think back to Fred Zinnemann's 1977 ``Julia,'' adapted from
Lillian Hellman's memoir, ``Pentimento.'' Literary critics scoffed
at the truthfulness of Hellman's ``selective memory.'' ``Julia''
told of Hellman's beloved childhood friend, a rich, brilliant woman
who became a resistance fighter during World War II. The tale told
of a courageous plan that Hellman undertook at Julia's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea With Mussolini'' is much in that same vein. Its
76-year-old
</P>
<P>
   director, Franco Zeffirelli (``La Traviata,'' ``Romeo and
Juliet''), creates a lovely, perfectly composed and lyrical look at
life under Mussolini's black-shirted fascist regime. But despite
danger on every corner in Italy, there is a tinge of rose-colored
sentiment that blurs the events yet lends to the making of an
affecting dramatic period piece.
</P>
<P>
   Florence in 1935 was a place of great culture. It was a magnet
for English and American expatriates eager to soak up its art,
architecture and rural beauty. For the ``Scorpioni,'' a group of
colorful ladies, Italy is also home. It is here they have settled,
having tea sharply at four, and working for Italian employers
desiring the ``English experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Luca, abandoned by his father and orphaned by his mother,
is taken under their collective wing. They give him an education in
manners _ until Mussolini aligns with Hitler and the women become
the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   A ritualistic act of bravery must take place in order for Luca
to realize how courageous and unique are the women _ played by
Cher, Joan Plowright, Maggie Smith, Judi Dench and Lily Tomlin.
</P>
<P>
   Zeffirelli uses Luca as his third eye and his character is the
least developed and motivated. He's used as an observer and
narrator of the action. Consequently, we're sometimes left on the
outside with Luca as well. Recent Oscar winner Dench is demure and
low-key and Plowright and Smith are wonderfully brittle and
self-deluded. They both make an interior journey that adds
dimension and resonance to their roles. Cher is Elsa, the pivotal
object of desire, who is instrumental in Luca's self-education, and
Tomlin is the comic relief _ an outrageously butch archaeologist.
</P>
<P>
   The diverse characters and the beauty of the landscape combine
to make a movie that veers away from cloying preciousness. Nor does
Zeffirelli get high-handed or pass judgment about political
wrongdoing. He wisely allows his story to unfold without letting us
forget that this is, above all, not a chronicle of Italy's war
crimes but a loving, gorgeous recollection of women who existed in
an extreme time and in a place where the line between life and
death was very thin.
</P>
<P>
   Tea With Mussolini. Directed by Franco Zeffirelli. Written by
John Mortimer, Zeffirelli. Cast: Cher, Judi Dench, Joan Plowright,
Maggie Smith, Lily Tomlin. MGM. 116 minutes. Rated PG for sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
