<HEADER>
A6276 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      05-13 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Fund Manager Tells Why It May Be Time to Move Into Small Caps
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Given that the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index set yet another record
high yesterday, maybe now is the time to shift some S&AMP;P 500 assets
into index funds that track bigger universes of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, S&AMP;P 500 index funds have been world-beaters the past
few years. Just ask any active portfolio manager who has been
eating the S&AMP;P 500's dust.
</P>
<P>
   But history tells us that no sector can dominate a rally
forever, and eventually, some other group of stocks is likely to
take the lead if this bull run is going to continue into the next
millennium. That's why it might be wise to rebalance your portfolio
to include some other index funds that mirror the broader stock
market, says Dick Shelton, president of the California Investment
Trust Fund Group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   With so many investors placing most of their eggs in the S&AMP;P 500
basket, ``they are bound to be underinvested'' in the broader
market, says Shelton, whose fund complex runs nine no-load mutual
funds, including one that mirrors the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the stock market may continue to go up, but
there is no guarantee that every investor will benefit from the
rise because they could be too narrowly focused on the S&AMP;P 500 and
not adequately invested in smaller stocks and foreign markets,
Shelton says.
</P>
<P>
   Only the top 50 stocks or so in the S&AMP;P 500 account for nearly
half of the entire index's weighted value, which means that many of
these stocks could be overvalued and may run out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are hundreds of cheap small- and mid-cap stocks
that have been racking up consistent earnings, but their stock
prices continue to sit idle, Shelton says.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, Wall Street will start buying these stocks, and
the average investor may miss the train out of the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnings estimates for small and midsize companies are far
better than those for the S&AMP;P 500 and other large-cap stocks.
(Plus), the actual earnings are coming in much stronger than
earlier anticipated,'' Shelton says.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a look at the numbers. The S&AMP;P 500 index is
expensive, trading at 24.3 times forward-looking earnings estimates
for 1999, according to IBES International, a New York research firm
that tallies earnings estimates by financial analysts.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; By comparison, the S&AMP;P MidCap 400 index _ a basket of 400
midsize stocks _ is considerably cheaper, with a price-earnings
ratio of 18.3. And the S&AMP;P SmallCap 600 index _ a basket of 600
smaller stocks _ is an even better bargain, trading at 17.9.
</P>
<P>
   This trend is likely to continue. Earnings for S&AMP;P MidCap 400
companies are expected to grow 22.8 percent a year over the next
five years, and S&AMP;P SmallCap 600 stocks are estimated to rack up
about 18.2 percent in annual earnings growth during the same
period, according to IBES.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with the S&AMP;P 500 companies _ whose earnings are
projected to rise just 12.8 percent a year _ and the littler guys
are starting to look pretty darn attractive, Shelton argues.
</P>
<P>
   With the small-cap indexes, ``you get an earnings double in less
than four years. That's pretty strong stuff,'' Shelton says.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, small- and mid-cap stocks have been left on the
sidelines during the past four or five years. One of the primary
arguments as to why is the fact that many of these smaller
companies have equally small floats _ meaning that they don't have
a lot of shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   That can make their stocks illiquid, making it difficult for
institutional money managers to amass big stakes and find buyers
for their shares when they are ready to unload them.
</P>
<P>
   However, with such rosy earnings projections, Shelton contends,
the big guns on Wall Street can't ignore smaller stocks forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fundamental. You're going to find some buyers,'' Shelton
says. Of course, in addition to an S&AMP;P 500 fund, California
Investment Trust manages an S&AMP;P SmallCap 600 index fund and an S&AMP;P
MidCap 400 Index. So here is Shelton's pitch: By owning all three
funds, an investor would own approximately 88 percent of of the
entire U.S. stock market on a market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if stock pickers finally rotate out of big-caps into the
littler guys, investors in all three funds should not miss the next
stage of the bull rally &LR;   &LR; _ &LR;   &LR; presuming there will be one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time, value will win out. Over the course of history, it
always has,'' Shelton says.
</P>
<P>
   The fund group president presents a compelling case. Perhaps
investors can't afford not to heed his words.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SEE YA: &LR;  This is my last column for The Chronicle before I leave to
become the technology columnist for Barron's. I just want to thank
the owners, publisher and editors of the paper for giving me the
opportunity to write Street Smarts. As I said before, it has been a
privilege to write in this space about money and the people who
help us make, manage and lose it. I can honestly say I've never had
more fun in journalism. It's been a blast.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely have I enjoyed so much interaction with everyday readers
of the paper. Although some of you did not always agree with my
thinking or even like me, seldom was there a dull moment. You kept
me honest, and for that I am grateful.
</P>
<P>
   My predecessor, Herb Greenberg (who like me is a Crain's Chicago
Business alum, by the way), helped put The Chronicle's business
section on the national map with his must-read column. I hope that
during my short time here I was able to build on that success. May
the tradition continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
