<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Gap Reports Record Profits, But Stock Dips
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Shares of Gap Inc. dipped yesterday despite record earnings that
exceeded analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Gap announced that earnings for the first
quarter of 1999, which ended May 1, hit a record $202 million, a 49
percent jump against the same quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per share tallied 34 cents, compared to a consensus
estimate of 31 cents among analysts polled by Zacks Investment
Research. But Gap's stock edged down 19 cents to close at $62.06.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly revenues rose 32 percent to $2.28 billion while sales
at stores open at least a year, known as same-store sales, rose a
healthy 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Postol, an analyst with A.G. Edwards, said investors
became nervous after Gap's April sales came in lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year this company couldn't do anything wrong and now
everybody is hanging on every little negative thing,'' said Postol.
``This is the first concern that has popped up in this company in
quite some time, and the markets don't like uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Gap's shares fell 7.4 percent last Thursday after it said
same-store sales in April rose 1 percent, its smallest gain in
almost two years. Analysts had forecast a gain of as much as 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer was hurt by the Gap chain, where same-store sales
declined about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For all of last quarter, same-store sales rose approximately 5
percent at the Gap chain. They fell about 2 percent at GapKids, and
rose about 21 percent at Old Navy and 13 percent at Banana
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Same-store sales were hurt by a comparison against April 28,
when they jumped 29 percent. Also, most Easter shopping occurred in
March, rather than April, this year, said Postol.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Gap was forced to mark down some prices in April,
something it rarely had to do last year, its markdown levels were
typical of most retailers, said Postol.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for Gap stock's failure to rise on the good news
is that its shares are considered pricey. It has the third highest
market capitalization among U.S. retailers, exceeded only by
Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Home Depot Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Postol expects Gap to generate profits this year of $1 billion
on sales of more than $11 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
