<HEADER>
A6278 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AREACODE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-13 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AREACODE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Assemblyman Wants First Phone Overlay Put on Hold
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
State Assemblyman Wally Knox asked California regulators yesterday
to halt the state's first area code ``overlay'' in the 310 region
of West Los Angeles, saying phone companies have not proven it's
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The overlay _ designed to address a shortage of phone numbers in
the region _ went into effect in the 310 region on April 17,
forcing all residents in that area to dial 1 plus the area code and
phone number for every call. After July 17, new phone customers in
the 310 region will get 424 as their area code.
</P>
<P>
   The state Public Utilities Commission approved the overlay at
the request of the telecommunications industry, which said it was
running out of available phone numbers in the region. Phone
companies also complained of a similar number shortage in the Bay
Area and overlays are now planned for the 408, 415, 510 and 650
area codes. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But Knox, D-Los Angeles, told the PUC yesterday that he doesn't
believe there is actually an area code crunch. He said there are
more than 145 million telephone numbers in the state that have been
assigned to phone companies but are not being used.
</P>
<P>
   While Knox's frustrated constituents may dislike the overlay,
industry experts said there's little chance that the plan could be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're at 11:57 here,'' said Natalie Billingsley, a
telecommunications expert at the PUC. ``It's not the absolute last
second, but it's pretty close to being too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers in West Los Angeles have been dialing 11 digits for
almost a month and companies have reprogrammed their switches to
recognize the 424 area code when it goes into effect. Changing all
that would be costly and confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Billingsley said halting the overlay may also violate FCC rules.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the FCC ruled that state commissions may not delay
area code changes just because they are unpopular with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you yank the overlay back now, you may run afoul of the FCC
rules,'' Billingsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Knox told the PUC that telephone companies should be forced to
disclose how many phone numbers they have and how many are in use
before consumers are inconvenienced with an overlay.
</P>
<P>
   He has a bill pending in the Assembly that would force the phone
companies to provide the PUC with this information _ something they
currently are not legally required to disclose.
</P>
<P>
   Once the state knows how many phone numbers are actually in use,
the PUC could force phone companies to return any unused numbers so
they could be given to other phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Until phone companies supply that data, Knox said, the state
should refuse to allow an overlay.
</P>
<P>
   His bill would also change the way phone numbers are assigned so
that unused numbers could be doled out.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, phone numbers are assigned in blocks of 10,000,
regardless of how many customers a company has. So even if a phone
company has only 300 customers, it still must request 10,000
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 150 phone companies operating in California and
requesting new phone numbers, the supply of available numbers in
each area code has dwindled quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Knox's bill would require that numbers be assigned in blocks of
1,000 instead of 10,000. Several groups, including the Federal
Communications Commission and a state coalition, are looking into
better ways to assign phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an arcane regulatory structure that hasn't kept up
with reality and it wreaks havoc on the lives of the rest of us,''
Knox said. ``I'm creating as much pressure as I can to have the
system changed as fast as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   While his bill would not specifically ban overlays, it would
lead to fewer area code changes in the future because the supply of
available phone numbers would not be exhausted as quickly. Since
his bill would force phone companies to pool their unused numbers
and return them, there would be more phone numbers to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Only one overlay has ever been halted. In 1995, state regulators
stopped an overlay in Houston several months after it began because
they felt it was too disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   However, the rules on area codes were different at that time and
state regulators were not responsible for approving area code
changes. Instead, the local phone company, SBC Communications,
implemented the overlay.
</P>
<P>
   The state then implemented an area code split, but six months
later, it reimplemented the overlay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very long, protracted, contested proceeding,'' said
Linda Hymans, a utility analyst with the Texas public utilities
commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
