<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOGAMES-700&AMP;ADD-NY     05-13 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAMES-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO GAME INDUSTRY DEFENDS BLOOD-SPLATTERING ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Calif., Ky.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The video game industry opened its annual trade
show here Thursday in a mood part defiant and part defensive about
accusations that violent video games contributed to the high school
shootings last month in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment industry has no reason to run and hide,''
said Douglas Lowenstein, president of the Interactive Digital
Software Association, the trade group that runs the show and
represents most of the major game manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference at which every question was related to
video game violence, Lowenstein said: ``The evidence does not exist
to support a link between playing violent video games and community
mass murder. Video games don't teach people to hate. Video games
don't teach people to become Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding up a joystick, he added, ``And if you get good at using
one of these controllers, it doesn't make you a marksman.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lowenstein and other executives, while saying they had a
free-speech right to make violent games, said they would make
greater efforts to inform parents about the industry's rating
system for games and to make sure retailers enforce the ratings and
do not sell inappropriate games to minors. Executives also said
they would tone down some advertisements, which reach children even
if the games themselves are rated as not appropriate for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the word `kill' comes out of the vocabulary,'' said
Phillip G. Adam, vice president for business development at
Interplay Productions.
</P>
<P>
   Interplay Productions, based in Irvine, Calif., makes the game
Carmaggedon, in which virtual motorists rack up points by running
down pedestrians, a pursuit that a company ad said was ``as easy as
killing babies with axes.'' An advertisement for its new game
Kingpin, Life of Crime notes that players can ``target specific
body parts and see the damage done _ including exit wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   For the video game industry, the timing of this year's
Electronic Entertainment Exposition is perhaps unfortunate, though
not as unfortunate as that of the National Rifle Association, whose
annual convention took place recently in Denver, less than two
weeks after and only miles away from the Littleton shootings, which
ended in the death of 15 people, including the two teen-age gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Because the gunmen were said to have been avid players of the
shooting video game Doom, the video industry is under attack from
all sides, like a player in one of its games. On Wednesday, the
Senate voted to authorize studies of the effects of violent video
games and of whether the entertainment industry is marketing
violence to youngsters. Several states are considering legislation
to ban or regulate violent games.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the families of three girls killed in a 1997 school
shooting in Paducah, Ky., filed suit against numerous video game
and other entertainment companies, asserting that violent media
influenced the killer, a high school freshman named Michael
Carneal. Similar suits are possible from Colorado, raising the
possibility that the industry will face litigation similar to that
faced by cigarette and gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the rifle association's convention, which was cut short
and drew thousands of protesters, the video game expo has not drawn
demonstrators and will run its full three days. There seemed to be
plenty of violent games among the 1,900 new ones being shown here.
The Los Angeles Convention Center was a huge cacophony of on-screen
kung-fu fights, fearsome gun battles, blaring explosions and car
crashes. Signs outside said that ``absolutely no one under 18''
would be admitted to the show, which is not open to the public in
any case.
</P>
<P>
   Many exhibitors said that although they are sensitive to
concerns arising from the Colorado shootings, they did not change
their planned exhibits, or their long-term strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we haven't taken guns out of any games,'' said
Mike McGarvey, chief operating officer of Eidos Interactive, a
British game maker whose booth had a big sign with the slogan ``Go
to War.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many visitors tried out Quake III Arena, the latest game from
the Id Software, the company that made Doom. Like Doom, Quake III
is what the industry calls a first-person shooter, in which there
is no character on the screen representing the player. Only the
player's gun is visible, at the bottom of the screen. As the
shooter fires, bodies splatter into pieces in a sea of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Todd S. Hollenshead, Id's chief executive, said there was no
reason to alter the company's display. ``I don't think pretending
it's Tickle Me Elmo is going to fool anyone for very long,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hollenshead, 30, said that just because Doom was not responsible
for the Littleton shooting just because the gunmen might have
played it. ``There's probably 20 million other people who love Doom
as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was some caution. Activision, a leading game
company, did not display its Soldier of Fortune game on the show
floor, although it was said to be available in a back room. One
chief executive of a game company has begun consulting
psychologists to inform himself about the research linking games
and violent behavior. Many executives would not comment on the
issue, citing the lawsuit against them.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Lincoln, chairman of Nintendo of America, said the video
game industry was being attacked by politicians because it was a
new industry without strong political connections. ``The gun lobby
is pretty powerful so politicians are not going to attack guns,''
Lincoln added, noting that on Wednesday the Senate rejected new gun
control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that there have been few studies so far done on
whether video games contribute to violent behavior and that the
answer is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein, the trade association official, said more than half
of frequent video game players are adults and 90 percent of the
games are purchased by adults. He also said 70 percent of the games
rated over the last five years are rated suitable for children.
Only two of the top selling games last year were rated M for
mature, meaning for those 17 and above. said, ``first-person
shooters'' accounted for only 6 percent of the market last year.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some movement away from gratuitous violence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, eschewing violence can be risky. Nintendo several years
ago came out with a tame version of Mortal Kombat while Sega
continued to sell the original, ultra-gory version. ``We got
creamed in the marketplace and got letters from parents saying we
were censors,''' Lincoln of Nintendo said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Tapscott, a consultant and author who was the keynote
speaker, said video games were being made a scapegoat for more
complex ills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can ban video games, I suppose,'' Tapscott said, ``though
doing something about poverty is a little more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But after defending games, he called on the industry to turn its
attention to educational software and to ``shape the industry for
the common good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
