<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC REFUSES TO SEE TOP U.N. RIGHTS OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Mary Robinson, the U.N. high commissioner
for human rights, was frustrated in her aim to ask Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic about his government's human rights
record when he refused to see her here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Robinson, the former president of Ireland and the United
Nations' high-profile campaigner for human rights since 1997, met
Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic and went to Nis to inspect
damage to a residential area that NATO bombs caused.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Robinson denounced all civilian casualties in the war, but
reserved her strongest language for the ``devastating pattern of
ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo. She placed the responsibility
squarely on Milosevic and the Yugoslav authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she also voiced her concern about NATO's using cluster bombs
near civilian areas and the resulting civilian casualties. The NATO
campaign, Ms. Robinson added, should attack only military targets.
</P>
<P>
   After a tour that included surrounding countries, Ms. Robinson
was in no doubt where the main guilt lay. ``People in uniform are
driving people from their homes and from Kosovo,'' she said at a
news conference. ``That is a responsibility of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not officers were under orders, she added, the
failure to stop them meant that the government was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav federal government must end immediately the
vicious human rights violations its army, police and paramilitary
forces are accused of in Kosovo and commit itself to an
unconditional and safe return of internally displaced persons,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ms. Robinson questioned the need for NATO to
attack sites in civilian areas and public works.
</P>
<P>
   In her visit, Ms. Robinson was trying to tread a fine line
between the two sides in the conflict, but received little thanks.
Her visit and her intention to meet Milosevic, had already been
attack by other rights organizations, which said the trip would
send the wrong signal to a government that was acting against the
Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Robinson replied that after having visited Albania,
Macedonia and Montenegro and heard the accounts from refugees and
human rights teams, it was important to bring the cases to the
attention of those responsible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
