<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LANDON WILSON, DECISION TO PLAY HURT WAS EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ On Wednesday, many hours before the teams
dropped the puck for Game 3 against the Sabres, Bruins' coach Pat
Burns sat down with injured wing Landon Wilson and picked the
player's brain.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had been absent because of a separated shoulder suffered
in Game 4 against Carolina and he was close to returning. Burns let
Wilson know that with the absence of Sergei Samsonov due to an
injury and the prospect of having to struggle on offense even more
than they already had to, which was difficult for even the coach to
fathom, the Bruins needed him.
</P>
<P>
   Could he go, the coach wanted to know?
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, Burns is the type of coach to tell the player to
sit down another few days rather than risk losing him in the first
shift or any time in the first period and having a hole on the
bench the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson was needed. He said he felt that urgency from the
coach and answered the bell. Burns responded by installing Wilson
in Samsonov's spot with center Jason Allison and right wing Dmitri
Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   He played 20 shifts for a total of 16 minutes, 52 seconds and
performed well, even getting a painful test on the shoulder at
16:50 of the first period that knocked him out for a couple of
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Willie and I had a long talk at the hotel and he said he felt
fine in the practices and I said there was going to be a certain
amount of pain involved no matter what,'' said Burns, recounting
his meeting with Wilson. ``Willie is different (than Samsonov). He
can bring something else to the table. He's a banger, he's a
crasher, he's a big man along the boards. He came over to the bench
one time and he was really wincing. Then I said, `(Trainer Donny
Del Negro), work on him,' and he rubbed it down and he finished the
game and (Thursday) he was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson showed tremendous flair in the first three-plus games of
the Carolina series, playing the best hockey of his young career.
Then he was injured and it wasn't known how he would respond when
he was able to come back. Burns said he was pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he brought something to that line, a physical
part,'' the coach said. ``He played through a little bit of hurt
and saw that it wasn't that bad. He was the guy on that line who
pressured the puck the most and that's what you have to do. When we
don't pressure the puck, we end up by backing up and then we lose
assignments. He's got a great shot. When he comes in on that
off-wing, he snaps it pretty good. He's physical and he has people
looking at him when he comes because he's a big man.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson potted the Bruins' first shot of the game, a nice wrister
from the right circle at 7:19 of the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard shot,'' said Wilson. ``It almost went between
(goalie Dominik) Hasek's legs. He even had trouble handling it. I
tried to stop for the rebound and poke it in. I didn't know Ally
was right beside me, otherwise I would've maybe thought of
passing.''
</P>
<P>
   He made some room for Khristich and Allison and though he had no
points to show for it, he played a strong game. It was his shot at
the end, with goalie Byron Dafoe pulled for an extra attacker late
in Game 3, that came the closest to tying it up before the Bruins
fell, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was deflected,'' he said. ``I had a good shot and somehow
it went into the corner. It hit something.''
</P>
<P>
   As well as Wilson thought he performed, he said he also felt
like the goat on Buffalo's third and winning goal, scored by Dixon
Ward at 9:38 of the third. Vaclav Varada was behind the Bruins'
net. It was his pass to a charging Ward that resulted in the
one-timer that beat Dafoe. Ward was Wilson's assignment and he
missed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Varada) came from the other side,'' said Wilson. ``I didn't
want to chase him behind the net because then (Ray Bourque) would
be put in an awkward situation where he would have to go for him or
go for the high guy (Ward). I couldn't go behind the net so I tried
to go in front of the net and when I saw (Varada) come out, I tried
to go in front of the net and that's when I saw Dixon Ward coming
in. It all happened like that. It was my responsibility for that
high guy. Varada made a very nice pass. I had to go get the high
guy and I was a little late reacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said if he had it to do over again, he wouldn't have
hesitated to go after Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go out and meet Dixon instead of going across and trying
to beat him,'' he said. ``I would've angled differently. I didn't
want to make a tough decision for Ray. I went across instead of
coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   For the young Bruins' team, this series is about learning
lessons and Wilson is one of those who's learning all of them, good
and bad. He learned about decision making in Game 3 and, with a lot
of support from his coach, he also learned about playing hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be sore now; you just have to play through it,''
he said. ``I wanted to play. It was up to really myself, I guess.
Donny didn't think it was a good idea for me to come back so early
but I wanted to help out the team any way I could. I talked to
coach and it made me realize I do want to play and I'm going to get
the opportunity to play. I decided it was the right decision for
myself as well as the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said part of what made his decision easy was that he knew
he'd be put in a prime position -- playing with Allison and
Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat wanted me to get involved, be physical and hopefully
create some room for our skilled guys,'' Wilson said. ``It was just
an opportunity for myself to play with those two that really helped
me decide whether to play or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
