</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE SHIFTING POLITICS OF GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mich., Wash., Minn., Ariz., Mo.)  (See also CONGRESS-GUNS) 
(mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five years ago, when the Democrats lost their
majority in Congress, they felt they had paid dearly for backing a
ban on many kinds of assault weapons. But that was before a series
of school shootings culminated in the massacre at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo. And on Thursday there were strong signs
that both parties sense that the politics of guns and violence are
shifting.
</P>
<P>
   So as the Senate debated gun control for a second day, the
Republicans did an about-face and offered their own proposal to
require background checks for sales at gun shows, just a day after
killing a similar but tougher measure. The Democrats, in contrast,
remained determinedly on the offensive, unexpectedly forcing
through a ban on imported high-capacity ammunition clips for
automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who heads the Senate Democratic
re-election effort, vowed that Republicans would be held
accountable for their vote on Wednesday. ``No force on earth can
stop this now from becoming a central issue in the 2000 elections
debate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to name some of the Republicans who are up for
re-election and are considered vulnerable. ``It will be very hard
for Spence Abraham to explain to the people of Michigan, Slade
Gorton to the people of Washington, Rod Grams to the people of
Minnesota, that after Littleton, they couldn't require background
checks at gun shows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps another sign of the growing potency of the issue,
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., one of the candidates for the Republican
presidential nomination, was among the Republican senators who
demanded Thursday that their party change its stance on gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Recent opinion surveys show that the American public is changing
its views on guns, though it is still conflicted. An Associated
Press poll found that in the week after the Colorado high school
shootings, the percentage of Americans who thought that tougher gun
control laws would be more effective than tighter enforcement of
current law was up nine percentage points to 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of split might not seem overwhelming enough to explain
the Democrats' determination to control guns. But there are other
factors bolstering President Clinton and his party.
</P>
<P>
   Since the days in the early 1990s when they were voting to
impose a waiting period for handgun sales and to ban 19 types of
assault weapons, the Democrats have recast many of their gun
control measures as ones designed to keep weapons out of the hands
of teen-agers. ``This is not about the broader population,''
Torricelli said. ``It is about guns and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposals calling for trigger locks on guns and raising the
minimum age for weapons possession draw overwhelming support from
the public. So the Republicans put up no fight against the
president's proposal to ban sales of semiautomatic assault weapons
to children under 18. The amendment was sponsored by another
Republican up for re-election in 2000, John Ashcroft of Missouri.
It passed 96-2.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, gun control is a regional issue that resonates
differently in the cities than it does in rural and western areas.
But as violence has spread to suburban schools, one place it has
become particularly popular is in the suburbs. And the suburbs have
become the swing areas in both the presidential and congressional
elections. Gun control also appeals overwhelmingly to
college-educated women, who have been considered key to the
Democrats' inroads this decade into the once solidly Republican
suburban vote.
</P>
<P>
   That has not been lost on Elizabeth Dole, who has been seeking
to capitalize on her appeal to women. In contrast to her husband,
Bob Dole, she has attacked the National Rifle Association as a
``special interest group'' and endorsed the assault weapons ban,
trigger locks on handguns and a ban on armor-piercing bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, despite the financial support they receive from
Hollywood, Democrats have learned not to be as dismissive as they
once were of cultural concerns about the entertainment industry's
effect on the national psyche. Clinton made the V-chip to block
objectionable television programs a key point in the family-values
agenda he put forth before his 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority leader, reflected
the Democrats' new way of talking about issues of violence when he
told reporters at a breakfast Thursday that in searching for a
response to the violence in Colorado, ``I don't want this to become
just a discussion of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, the gun control issue has become more difficult
as American sentiment has shifted. Their core conservative
supporters include many people who feel strongly about the Second
Amendment's guarantee of the right to bear arms. And the NRA was
one of the advocacy groups that House Republicans credited with
helping them win the majority in 1994. It is also a major donor to
Republicans. In 1998, for example, the NRA's political action
committee donated $1.35 million to Republican congressional
candidates and $283,000 to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   That means that, particularly in the House, where the two
parties are fighting for control in 2000, Republicans must carry
out a difficult balancing act, doing nothing to offend these
conservatives while not imperiling the moderate Republicans from
the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert has said little about the gun issue
beyond calling for a national dialogue on Littleton. An aide said
he was amenable to an appeal by Gephardt that the two men try to
explore some kind of bipartisan approach to the violence issue.
</P>
<P>
   But one House Republican aide said Thursday that the best course
for his party might be to try to sidestep the gun control debate
entirely, despite the votes this week in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either put off the soccer moms or you put off the gun
owners,'' he said. ``So you try to avoid gun votes, period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
