<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISS-TESTIMONY-ART-NY     05-13 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISS-TESTIMONY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS RELEASE OF TESTIMONY FROM ALGER HISS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a potentially groundbreaking ruling that could
help resolve some of the enduring mysteries of the Cold War, a
federal judge in Manhattan on Thursday ordered the government to
unseal thousands of pages of secret grand jury testimony from the
investigation of Alger Hiss and the underground communist movement
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which came over the strong objections of the
government, could lead to the release of grand jury testimony in
1947 and 1948 by Hiss and dozens of other witnesses, including his
chief accuser, Whittaker Chambers, and Richard M. Nixon, then a
California congressman, whose role in the Hiss case thrust him into
the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Hiss was ultimately indicted on perjury charges in an espionage
case that raised fears about communist infiltration of the federal
government and eventually became one of the most divisive issues of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Historians and legal scholars said that the ruling by Judge
Peter Leisure could lead to more attempts to examine records of
grand juries in other historically significant cases, such as the
attempts to indict Aaron Burr after he was vice president, or more
recently, the espionage case against Julius and Ethel Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   In ordering the papers released, Leisure cited the longstanding
debate about the case, which he said fits a narrow exception to
grand jury secrecy in matters of compelling historical importance,
an assertion disputed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Leisure noted the continuing questions about Nixon's role and
whether he had sought to lobby the grand jury to indict Hiss, the
extent of Soviet espionage activity in the United States during and
after World War II, and whether there were improprieties in the
grand jury investigation itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is confident that disclosure will fill in important
gaps,'' Leisure wrote, adding that releasing the documents would
lead to new debate and new historical works, ``all to the immense
benefit of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The materials should languish on archival shelves, behind
locked doors, no longer,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   David Vladeck, a lawyer for a coalition of scholars and
historical associations that had petitioned for the release of the
papers, said the decision was the ``first major ruling establishing
the proposition that grand jury records should not be locked away
forever where there's a historical need for them to be made
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladeck, of the Public Citizen Litigation Group, said: ``It
says, in a sense, that once the traditional justification for grand
jury secrecy erodes, there will be cases _ extraordinary cases _
but there will be cases, where the public has a right to see its
own history.'' Vladeck's group was founded by Ralph Nader and has
been involved in other cases seeking access to government records.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Manhattan, who had fought the papers'
release, said Thursday that they were still considering whether to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, said her office
opposed disclosure of the records based on grand jury secrecy
rules: ``There is no exception for historical interest in the
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White added that the rules ``safeguard the grand jury
process, the integrity of investigations, and the reputations and
privacy of both innocent subjects and witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   She said there was a ``vast amount of material already in the
public record about this subject _ much of it released by the
government itself,'' and those seeking the papers had failed to
meet ``their extraordinarily heavy burden'' of establishing a legal
basis for access to the materials.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White's office argued, for example, that scholars had long
ago concluded that Nixon had attempted to persuade the grand jury
to indict Hiss rather than Chambers, and those seeking the records
had not shown a ``genuine gap in the historical record.''
</P>
<P>
   But Leisure concluded that ``the public has a significant
interest in disclosure of Nixon's testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand jury testimony by a congressional official allegedly
attempting to influence a grand jury's charging decision,'' he
wrote, ``is of inherent and substantial historical importance.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Confirmation of what was actually said by Nixon will
significantly enrich the debate about the propriety of that
testimony and its importance to the grand jury's decision to
indict.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge did rule that a small portion of the records may
involve privacy interests, and allowed the government additional
time to argue against their release. But Vladeck said those
portions represented a ``trivial'' part of documents that were
being sought.
</P>
</TEXT>
