<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREAKNESS SHOULD ANSWER QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 -LADN-(SLANG) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Race to Watch if You Watch Only One Race
All Year, take two.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical season the Kentucky Derby is the definitive event
for young thoroughbreds and the Preakness merely crosses the T's
and dots the I's in the history books.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, the Derby was inconclusive because (a) more
than half of the 19 horses suffered traffic trouble, (b) there was
no standout going into the race, and (c) I didn't pick the winner.
</P>
<P>
   So now it's up to Saturday's Preakness, at Pimlico Race Course
in Baltimore, to answer a long list of remaining questions about
America's (and Dubai's) 3-year-olds (and 3-year-old fillies).
</P>
<P>
   The Preakness result will be scrutinized for meaning the way the
Derby result usually is. But why wait for the race to be run?
Here's what it'll mean if. . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Charismatic wins: Then he and D. Wayne Lukas deserve
credit they haven't received since winning the Derby _ as a
supposedly overmatched horse who had the audacity to blossom at the
right time and a supposedly inflexible trainer who figured out what
made this one tick. . . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Excellent Meeting wins: Then maybe she was best in the
Derby when she rallied from 18th to fourth; the best fillies are
the equals of the best colts this year, and the best colts are
mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some will conclude Silverbulletday, ostensibly the
better filly in trainer Bob Baffert's barn, would have won if she'd
run. (She skipped the Derby to beat fillies in the Kentucky Oaks
and will skip the Preakness to face fillies in today's Black-Eyed
Susan.)
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe the Silverbulletday hype _ until Baffert and owner
Mike Pegram follow through on their boasts and take on males, she's
only been beating no-name fillies, and her 10-for-11 record is a
testament to careful management. If they thought they had the best
3-year-old, they'd be in the Preakness despite drawing post
position 14. . . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Vicar wins: Then trainer Carl Nafzger will earn
congratulations for realizing you CAN win from an outside post _
but it seems more likely the epidemic of post-position hysteria has
infected Nafzger and he'll scratch. . . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Worldly Manner wins: Then it's a rare case in which
America's best 2-year-old goes on to be its best 3-year-old, and we
can conclude he might have held on to win the Derby if his
Dubai-based owners had prepped him in a more traditional manner. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Cat Thief wins: Then Lukas has taken back the King of the
Triple Crown title from Baffert by winning the Derby and Preakness
with different horses for the second time. That's reassuring for
fundamental handicappers shaken by Charismatic. . . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Menifee wins: Then _ and maybe only then _ there's reason
to be excited about this crop of 3-year-olds, because the Blue
Grass winner and troubled Derby runnerup would be a deserving
Preakness winner. . . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Stephen Got Even wins: Then the first-turn Derby bumping
was as costly as it looked, if the 14th-place finisher can bounce
back to win the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   That also would complete a Triple Crown season to forget for
Chris McCarron, who lost the mount on Santa Anita Derby winner
General Challenge to Gary Stevens, and now has a foot fracture that
will leave Stephen Got Even to Stevens. . . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Valhol wins Then a year after Pimlico's Preakness-day
power failure, the electricity would definitely be back on. . . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Kimberlite Pipe or Adonis wins: Then this is the craziest,
not to say the absolute worst, bunch of 3-year-olds ever. . . .
</P>
<P>
   !bold!Patience Game, Badge or Torrid Sand wins: Then it's a rare
victory for the Preakness ``fresh horse'' angle and the Derby
horses should hang their heads in shame.
</P>
<P>
   All in all it's one of the more intriguing Preaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll win? Charismatic is good enough to win again, but it
might be too much to expect racing luck to go his way twice in a
row. At the morning-line odds _ which will come down because
Silverbulletday (7-2) is out, Menifee (5-2) is too popular and Cat
Thief (8-1) and Worldly Manner (12-1) look like better values.
</P>
<P>
   My picks: 1. Cat Thief (Mike Smith), 2. Worldly Manner (Jerry
Bailey), 3. Menifee (Pat Day).
</P>
<P>
   __ At Hollywood Park: Gates will open at 10 a.m. on Preakness
day and Hollywood Park's first live race will be at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The first of five simulcasts from Pimlico will be at 11 a.m. and
the Preakness is set for 2:27 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Preakness lacks the local drawing power of the Kentucky
Derby. Last year 12,477 went to Hollywood Park on Preakness day
after 21,949 showed up on Derby day.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Black-Eyed Susan is scheduled for 2:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gold Cup is leaking: On Thursday, a week after Strub Stakes
winner Event of the Year was sidelined by a knee problem, Santa
Anita Handicap winner Free House was declared out for at least 90
days.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Paco Gonzalez said a nuclear scan showed Free House came
out of his second to Real Quiet in last Saturday's Pimlico Special
with a tear in the ligament connecting the left hip to the spine.
The 5-year-old will recuperate at owners Trudy McCaffery and John
Toffan's ranch in Bradbury.
</P>
<P>
   The injury means Free House will miss the June 27 Hollywood Gold
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   So could 1998 Big 'Cap winner Malek, who has stiffness in his
back and will miss the May 29 Massachusetts Handicap, trainer
Richard Mandella said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
