<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LBJ-SYMPOSIUM-COX     05-13 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LBJ-SYMPOSIUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Symposium keys in on interpretation gap, civil rights
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In Thursday's keynote speech for the ``Legacy of
the Sixties'' symposium at the LBJ Library, historian Arthur
Schlesinger Jr. invoked ``the tranquilizing perspective of time.''
</P>
<P>
   As the subsequent panels made plain, however, the passage of
time hasn't exactly prove-- tranquil or resolved what Schlesinger
termed ``a chaos of conflicting interpretations.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a chasm of imposing perspectives divides those who hail
the decade's idealists and those who condemn its anarchists and
hedonists. The two points on which most participants agreed are
that one of the legacies of the '60s is that we have yet to stop
talking about the legacy of the '60s, and that the significance of
that tumultuous era is in the mind of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   A Pulitzer Prize-winning scholar and a special assistant to John
F. Kennedy, Schlesinger proceeded to fire the first shots. He
dismissed New Left activists as ``neo-Stalinists'' (only less
tolerant and cultured than the originals), whose ``scorn for
history was exceeded only by their ignorance of it.'' Whatever
credit the movement claimed for civil-rights advances and an end to
the war in Vietnam, Schlesinger said that the politics of the
street only ``marginally accelerated changes that were already
under way,'' and that their major effect was to strengthen the
conservative movement that would elect Richard Nixon and Ronald
Reagan to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The panel that followed Schlesinger's speech was titled ``The
Counter-Culture Movement _ Its Effect on American Life Today.'' It
largely reinforced his contention that '60s radicalism was a
marginal aberration, a noisy distraction, before business as usual
reasserted itself. ``In my opinion, the dominant culture won,''
said Rice University history professor Allen Matusow, who cited
``the unchallenged position and power of the large corporations''
in contemporary society. As the anti-materialist hippies became
conspicuously consuming yuppies, commodification (as one wag put
it) transformed the counterculture into the over-the-counter
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon session on ``Civil Rights _ The Situation Now''
touched a strikingly different chord. Moderator Julian Bond, the
national director of the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People, proclaimed that ``the movement for civil rights
made public policy,'' putting pressure on a government that
preferred change at a more deliberate pace, if at all. Addressing
Schlesinger's dismissal of youthful rebellion even more directly,
panelist Vincent Harding celebrated the '60s as an era in which
young people felt ``empowered to work for change for good in their
society. That's a legacy that needs to be nurtured and developed.''
He also suggested that the morning's panel, made up of five white
males, could hardly be reflective of the counterculture of the
times.
</P>
<P>
   What Bond termed the after- noon's ``rainbow panel'' of Latino-
American, Asian-American and African-American activists hailed
President Johnson's domestic policies of the '60s, while charging
that there has been considerable backsliding in the decades since.
Panelist John Maguire, in rhetoric that had a '60s ring to it,
decried the ever-growing gulf between ``the obscenely rich''
(overwhelmingly white) and ``the desperately poor''
(disproportionately of color).
</P>
<P>
   Whatever dialogue might have bridged the cultural chasms was
made more difficult by the framework of the panels, which were
presented as a series of monologues, followed by questions from the
audience. Instead of talking with each other, participants found
themselves talking at each other, or past each other.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium concludes today with sessions on foreign policy (9
a.m.), space exploration (9:30 a.m.), the Great Society (1:30 p.m.)
and LBJ in retrospect (6 p.m.). All events take place at the LBJ
Library's LBJ Auditorium and are free and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Don McLeese writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
