u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSTON-MEXICO-HNS &LR;      05-13 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO MAY WARN ITS CITIZENS ABOUT HOUSTON POLICE SHOOTINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Moves in ``a'' and ``i'' categories) 
 
By JENALIA MORENO 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Mexican government is considering warning its
citizens to avoid traveling to Houston because of recent fatal
shootings of Mexicans by police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is very concerned with this situation,'' said Rodulfo
Figueroa, Consul General of Mexico in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa said the Mexican federal government has considered
issuing a travel warning for the past three months because of the
shootings by Houston police of Pedro Oregon Navarro in July and
Uvaldo Garcia Armendariz in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon was shot 12 times, nine in the back, July 12 by Houston
police in an aborted drug bust turned sour. Garcia was shot by
police when responding to a domestic disturbance call.
</P>
<P>
   Those threats increased following last month's police shooting
death of robbery suspect Eulogio Perez in southwest Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that all three men lived in Houston and were not
some of the more than 1 million tourists that reportedly visit
Houston annually.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Mexican Consulate General's office and
Houston Police Department have already met at least once to discuss
the shootings and plan to meet again next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what their problem is internally,'' Figueroa
said. ``They have to clean up their house.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Mayor Lee Brown said, in a statement released Thursday,
that it is not necessary to issue such a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of Mexico who travel to Houston and choose to
live in our city can feel safe because they are protected by one of
the finest law enforcement organizations in the world,'' Brown
said. ``Houston has one of the lowest crime rates for any large
city in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials say its government rarely, if at all, issues
travel warnings for its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised (about Mexico's advisory). The United States
is always issuing advisories not to go to Chiapas or Guerrero or
other places of unrest in Mexico, so now it's their turn,'' said
Cristobal Hinojosa, a Houston Hispanic activist.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa, who has protested against the Pedro Oregon shooting
and is a member of Mothers and Families United, said he views the
the advisory as political payback.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa and other government officials contacted Thursday said
a decision about a travel warning may not come for some time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Mexico is the leading generator of international tourism
for Houston, officials here are taking the threat seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Houston, as much as it's trying to generate
business and tourism business, it's not something that we can
afford at all,'' said Richard Torres, president and chief executive
officer of the Houston Hispanic Chamber of Commerce. ``We need to
look at the problem, but I don't think that by having a travel
alert if that's going to solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican tourists have not mentioned any fears of traveling to
Houston and have reported no harassment by police, said Yolanda
Londono, director of the Houston Image Group and the tourism
director of the Greater Houston Convention and Visitors bureau.
</P>
<P>
   She said most Mexican tourists stay 10 days and spend $130 a day
in Houston. Most come to Houston to shop, she said. She said June
through September is a popular time for tourists to come to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interestingly, they feel safe and secure _ 90 percent said
that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
