<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6310 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-ANTLEY-PREAKNESS-     05-13 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ANTLEY-PREAKNESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIS ANTLEY BACK IN CONTENTION AS A TOP JOCKEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Charismatic didn't have to face much adversity two
weeks ago in the Kentucky Derby, so he isn't getting as much
respect for tomorrow's Preakness Stakes as a Derby winner might
deserve.
</P>
<P>
   But his jockey, Chris Antley, has endured enough hard times for
both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Antley has battled substance abuse. He has been to dieting hell
and back again. But when trainer D. Wayne Lukas was searching for a
Derby jockey for Charismatic, he ignored those personal problems
and instead focused on the 8-year-old trophy perched on Antley's
living room shelf, commemorating a winning ride on Strike the Gold
in the 1991 Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd won the Derby,'' Lukas explained, ``so it wasn't like we
were going with a guy that would break down in the post parade.''
</P>
<P>
   No, if Antley was going to break down, it would have happened
when he tested positive for cocaine at age 22 and was temporarily
suspended from the sport. Or months before the Derby, at home in
Columbia, S.C., when his weight ballooned to 147 pounds and his
career appeared doomed. Or when he was riding in New York two years
and starving himself to get down to 113 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Weight is an albatross to the careers of many riders. To Antley,
it nearly was an anchor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through it all trying to lose weight,'' he said. ``But
I continued to get bigger and bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley once was a star rider on the New York circuit, where in
1989 he rode at least one winner for 64 consecutive racing days.
Once he won nine races in one day, five at an afternoon track and
four at night.
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately left New York in 1993 because of two pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most riders did 113 \Rpounds\S or less in New York. If you did
114 it was kind of unheard of,'' Antley said. ``I came to
California because you were considered light if you `tacked' 115.
\RLaffit\S Pincay and a couple of others tacked 117.''
</P>
<P>
   He rode well in California, too, but the constant stress of
reducing his weight finally took its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of riders are Lasix users,'' Antley said.
</P>
<P>
   Lasix is a diuretic also commonly used on racehorses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of riders are bulimic. Everybody has their
personal way,'' Antley said. ``Some don't eat or eat a tiny, tiny
bit. Some sit in a hotbox for five hours, or take Lasix or diet
pills. Myself, I went from cycle to cycle. If anybody ever did a
medical report on riders, it might be ... . I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Antley believes, it came down to self-control. And
that had never been one of his strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I didn't have the commitment like a Laffit Pincay
would,'' he said, referring to the legendary Hall of Fame rider who
has made dietary nutrition an art form. ``I fault myself on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Physically weak from battling the scales, Antley returned home
to South Carolina in fall 1997 and temporarily let himself go. When
he decided he wanted to ride again, he needed the resolve of a
Marine. He found it within himself, running 25 miles a day and
earning the nickname Forrest Gump from neighborhood merchants along
his daily route.
</P>
<P>
   But Antley made it back this year at age 33, both to the
occupation he loves and to the Kentucky Derby winner's circle with
Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   His experience plus his newfound drive caught Lukas' eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hungry,'' Lukas said, ``and he has a passion to get back
to the higher echelon of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a warm feeling coming to the wire,'' Antley said of his
second Derby victory. ``It wasn't a jump-up-and-down feeling. I
felt a warm feeling like things were coming together.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
