<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-NELSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS LEADS SCORING ONSLAUGHT AT NELSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Nick Price teased with a course record yesterday
at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic. But he still finished last in his
threesome.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who tied the tournament scoring mark with an
opening 61, failed to earn tee-box honors with a front-nine 29
because playing partner Paul Goydos took birdies on seven of his
first 11 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Such was life in the Woods-Goydos-Price group, which provided
the perfect microcosm for the most prolific scoring day in
tournament history. Of yesterday's 156 starters, 103 broke even-par
70 at the Four Seasons Resort and Club, the most in any round at
any Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Woods did the most damage, going 9 under par on the Cottonwood
Valley Golf Course and pacing a threesome that finished a combined
24-under. But he never grabbed the solo lead until Goydos (8 under)
misfired on his approach shot to the 18th green, setting up a
closing bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Woods leads Goydos, Steve Lowery and Sergio Garcia by one stroke
heading into today's second round, with Price among a five-player
group at 7-under that includes Corey Pavin and Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have shot lower,'' said Woods, who missed only two
putts inside eight feet during a nine-birdie, no-bogey round. ``I
went out and attacked the pins and put myself in a lot of birdie
positions. And from there, I made a lot of putts. It's always fun
when you really get it going like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, Goydos and Garcia all got it going well enough that they
admitted to fleeting thoughts of reaching 59, the PGA Tour scoring
record, during the closing holes. By finishing at 61, Woods tied
both the Nelson tournament record and the Cottonwood Valley course
record on a postcard-perfect day with benign winds and
rain-softened greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best day to play golf out here that I've ever
seen,'' Nelson said. ``If you can't play out there today, you can't
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were so pristine, said Goydos, that players in his
group ``weren't even thinking about bogeys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone got going, and we fed off each other,'' said Goydos,
who had a 28 on the front nine. ``We were all in the same rhythm.
I'd never shot in the 20s on nine holes before. That's a mythical
number. It still seems ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Woods-Goydos-Price group combined for 25 birdies
and a bogey. Fans became so jaded, Goydos joked, that Price ``shot
63, and no one asked for his autograph.''
</P>
<P>
   But plenty of fans hovered around Woods, who averaged 311 yards
per drive and one-putted 13 greens. Of his nine birdie putts, only
a 30-footer at No. 12 traveled more than 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   With his 61, Woods matched Billy Mayfair (1993), Ernie Els
(1995) and Charlie Rymer (1996) for the lowest score in tournament
history. Els, like Woods, made his mark at Cottonwood Valley.
Mayfair and Rymer blistered the TPC at Las Colinas, which proved to
be a stroke more difficult in the opening round than the Cottonwood
layout.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors averaged 69.1 strokes per round yesterday at TPC,
with a low of 62 by Lowery. Scoring average at Cottonwood was 68.2,
with Woods leading a birdie barrage that saw 140 players shoot 72
or better in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was his lowest score of the season on the PGA Tour,
Woods said he played better during a third-round 62 at the Buick
Invitational in La Jolla, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more rewarding when it takes more effort,'' Woods said.
``People have shot 61s out here before. So it's not as rewarding,
but I'm not saying it doesn't feel good.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
