<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFER LOWERY TRIES TO REBUILD HOME, CAREER FROM ASHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Steve Lowery's million-dollar home went up in
flames three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He's determined not to let his golf career go with it.
</P>
<P>
   The date _ Feb. 28 _ is scorched into Lowery's memory, in so
many ways. He had just come off the 18th green after the final
round of the Tucson Open, a tournament he had once been in position
to win, when tour official Mark Russell approached and said he had
some grim news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your family is all right, but there's been a fire,'' Russell
informed Lowery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that maybe it was like a kitchen fire,'' Lowery, 38,
said, picking up the narrative yesterday after his opening-round 62
at the Byron Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured there would be just a little damage, maybe a few
rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, Lowery said, he was on a plane headed home to
Orlando, Fla. He turned his street corner around 1 a.m. The fire
engines were still busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was like ... nothing,'' he said. ``We went out to the
house and it was, like, gone. It wasn't there any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The home had been located on the fourth fairway of the Bay Hill
Club in Orlando. It had five bedrooms and measured 5,500 square
feet. The Lowerys, Steve and his wife, Kathryn, had spent a year
remodeling the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our dream house,'' Steve said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn and the three children were at the kitchen table, doing
homework, when 7-year-old Kristen noticed the flames. The family
evacuated swiftly and safely, and firefighters arrived in four
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But fire officials estimated that the fire had begun around 2
p.m. and had already been burning for an hour. The
million-dollar-plus home was quickly engulfed in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn and the children didn't carry anything with them when
they escaped from the burning house.
</P>
<P>
   As Steve said, ``You think, well, the men are going to put out
the fire, and everything inside is still going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the Lowerys, nothing was spared. Gone were the family
mementos, the wedding pictures, everything.
</P>
<P>
   Lost was a $12,000 gold and silver bowl awarded to Lowery for
winning the 1994 Sprint Invitational, his only tour victory. Gone
were every trophy, cup and ribbon from every golf tournament that
Lowery ever won, along with prized memorabilia from the Masters and
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I had,'' Lowery said, wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurance people give you money for it. But there are
things you just can't replace. Like, I went to the University of
Alabama, and I had some personalized letters from Bear Bryant. How
can you replace that?''
</P>
<P>
   Ten weeks later, investigators still aren't certain what caused
the blaze. Suspicions point to the electrical wiring in the attic.
Not that it matters now, Lowery said.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it could easily have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk to somebody like Stuart Appleby, who lost his wife,
and you start to realize how lucky you are,'' Lowery said. ``We got
everyone out of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire, however, left more than ashes. After a couple of
weeks, Lowery had to refocus his mind on golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wears on you,'' he said. ``Guys who are doing things like
going through a divorce, building a house _ you just don't have the
energy to focus for four days.''
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, three weeks after the blaze the golf tour
arrived for its annual stop at the Bay Hill Club. Lowery opened
with what was then his best round of the year, a 67, one stroke off
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys in the press interview room, `Here's your
chance. The headline should be `Lowery on fire at Bay Hill,' '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowery was finding that he was finally able to joke about it.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with Colin Montgomerie, they were on the third hole at
Bay Hill when Monty asked, ``Don't you live around here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a great house,'' Lowery shot back. ``I can let you
have it for about $400,000 below appraisal. Five bedrooms.
Fifty-five hundred square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the fireplace has only had one fire in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery finished in a tie for 37th in that tournament. His best
since then has been a $26,000 check for finishing 23rd at the
Greater Greensboro Open.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowery's 62 yesterday on the TPC course _ six birdies and an
eagle on the par-5 16th _ has him solidly in the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The family will build another dream home elsewhere, maybe in
Birmingham, Ala., where Steve grew up.
</P>
<P>
   His golf game will rise from the ashes, too, Lowery said.
There's going to be a new trophy case to fill.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
