<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6314 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-W     05-13 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERNED ABOUT 2000 ELECTION, CLINTON COUNSELS GORE TO ENLIVEN
IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Rewrites throughout; new top adds Clinton interview) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton acknowledged Thursday night that
he had been concerned that Vice President Al Gore's presidential
campaign was off to a sluggish start. He said he had personally
coached Gore on how to loosen up and appear less remote and rigid
on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, in a telephone interview with The New York Times,
insisted that he was by no means alarmed by the state of the
campaign and that, like most of the Democratic establishment, he
still expected Gore to win his party's nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he was much less worried than he had
been several weeks ago and that he was particularly heartened that
Gore earlier this week named Tony Coelho, the former House
Democratic whip, as his campaign chairman. Coelho has been charged
with whipping the Gore operation into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that I have urged him to go out there and enjoy
this,'' Clinton said. ``I have told him to go out and have a good
time. I want people to know him the way I know him. I want people
to see him the way I see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is regarded as unrivaled for his skills on the
stump, said the campaign ``is in a lot better shape now than it was
eight weeks ago _ and I think the appointment of Tony Coelho was a
very good move, because he's a strong man and an experienced person
and he'll really take a lot of the burdens off the vice
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The president telephoned The Times tonight after learning that
the newspaper intended to publish an article citing his worries _
described in interviews by several people close to Clinton _ that
the Gore campaign was floundering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not have the feeling that the Gore campaign is moving
in a positive, forceful, determined way to prepare themselves,''
said one person, recounting his conversations with Clinton about
Gore. ``But he'll be the first one to tell you that this has a long
way to go and nobody should overreact.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who views the election of Gore as affirming his own
legacy, has hardly been alone in his worries. A consensus has
emerged among prominent Democrats that the Gore campaign has had a
lackluster start.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats point to the quick and unanticipated rise of
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey as a challenger; polls
showing that Gore's popularity is not particularly deep, that he
may be damaged by Clinton's scandals and that he would be easily
defeated in a general election by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas or
Elizabeth Dole; a sense that Gore has deficient campaigning skills
and has fumbled, making gaffes like taking credit for inventing the
Internet; a view that he has not adequately articulated positions,
and that he was trying to run his own campaign single-handedly.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Gore campaign publicly insists that it is on
track, noting that it has broken fund-raising records and nailed
down an impressive roster of endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   In his advice to Gore, associates said, Clinton suggested that
the vice president take a more informal approach by shedding his
blue suit more frequently, plunging into crowds, staying overnight
with supporters in Iowa and New Hampshire and striking out on his
own from his his cumbersome entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore came closest to publicly acknowledging the troubles by his
abrupt naming this week Coelho. Gore, who had been making many of
the day-to-day political decisions himself _ from his travel
schedule to topics for his speeches _ has now relinquished that
role to Coelho.
</P>
<P>
   Another person who spoke with Clinton said the president had
urged Gore to turn over control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks Gore needs to stop worrying, he needs to look at the
assets he's got, the story he's got to tell the American people _
and focus on that,'' this person said. ``He was one of the people
who thought he shouldn't be terribly concerned about who manages
the thing on a day-to-day basis and spend his time instead on what
he says to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who discussed Clinton's concerns for this article did not
volunteer the information but spoke only reluctantly. They included
people who are loyal to Gore and others who are personally closer
to Clinton but support Gore's candidacy. The reasons they agreed to
interviews _ only on condition of anonymity _ may be multi-faceted:
to give a complete picture of the President's position, to show
themselves in the know, or perhaps, to send a public message to the
vice president that he needs to make repairs quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton monitors his vice president's campaign appearances on
television and reads up on the campaign, according to one of the
people who spoke with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really into what's going on out there,'' he said. ``He,
as well as many Democrats, is concerned about the polls and that
the campaign seemed to be listless, lacking in enthusiasm. How many
times did you hear people saying there was just no excitement?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Clinton's counsel, James Carville, the strategist
who is close to the President, said, ``I think it's good advice.''
Carville added that the president had not told him about his
conversations with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Gore's aides insist that the campaign is in far better
shape than many people think. They note that Vice President George
Bush had similar problems moving out of President Reagan's shadow
in the 1988 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're the front runner you have everybody, from
virtually every angle and every side taking their shots at you,''
said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman. ``But the bottom line is that
today the vice president is extremely strong. Our fund raising has
been immensely successful. To the extent that you believe in polls,
in the primaries we're exceedingly strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore advisers concede that the vice president had hoped
to keep a low campaign profile throughout the summer, but that the
spate of bad notices had led him to take several steps to try to
demonstrate momentum.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the campaign had planned to put off Gore's formal
announcement of his candidacy until toward the end of the year, if
at all. (Clinton sought to seem above politics during the 1996
campaign by never officially announcing his candidacy.) But now,
Gore's advisers said, they have moved the date to June or July.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is also pumping resources into an aggressive
behind-the-scenes effort to assure that Gore has a respectable
showing against Bradley in a straw poll being conducted on Saturday
by the Massachusetts Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is so mindful of catering to an important constituency that
aides said he had overruled White House and State Department
officials and agreed to give an address to the American-Israel
Public Affairs Committee on May 23.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had warned that it was risky to give
the speech then because the timing would be awkward: it falls days
after the Israeli election and just before an expected runoff vote
on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore advisers said concerns about his campaign had also led
Gore to move fast in hiring Coelho. ``I was shocked when he called
me,'' Coelho said of his telephone call from Gore last Wednesday.
``It was totally out of the blue. But I don't sense any panic or
urgency. What people don't understand is that this is a start-up
business.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting on Tuesday in the Vice President's residence, where
Gore introduced Coelho to his top advisers, Coelho interrupted the
Vice President twice and and overruled him on decisions, several
participants said.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, you're in charge,'' they quoted the vice president as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews, a range of Democratic politicians,
strategists and thinkers cautioned that not everything can be fixed
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gore's closest advisers, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said he was hopeful but not certain that Coelho would
force the vice president to stop micromanaging the campaign. ``The
important thing is not Tony,'' he said. ``The important thing is
that this may signal a willingness on his part to divorce himself
from the mechanics. One of the major problems has been that for
quite some time he has spent too much time being not only the
candidate but being the campaign.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At a closed-door meeting at the Democratic Party headquarters on
Wednesday, a day after Coelho's hiring was announced, Gore's top
advisers met with more than 50 House Democrats to reassure them of
the vice president's viability. Craig Smith, the campaign manager,
and others sought to make their case by distributing polls showing
that Gore still holds a sizable lead over Bradley. But some House
members registered a range of concerns, including their fear that
Gore was ignoring key party constituencies, like minorities and
unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would we prefer to be 80 points up right now? Of course,''
said Rep. Bart Gordon of Tennessee, who helped organize the
session. ``But people recognize that the election is a year and a
half away, and that we're well positioned and that there's going to
be an ugly Republican primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is well known _ and often ridiculed _ for his uncomfortable
campaign style, but several politicians said the president's advice
sounded appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a natural inclination for a lot of Democrats to say,
`Is there anyone else?' and to look for excitement,'' said Sen. Tom
Harkin of Iowa, who is close to Gore. `He added, ``Al Gore's a
serious guy, and you've got to show people that you like what
you're doing and you like being out there with them and be open and
have a sense of humor, a sense of proportion. We don't elect kings
in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to the president said that he did not believe he
should play an active role in plotting campaign strategy and that
he has resisted entreaties from some of his aides to involve
himself more directly in the Gore operation.
</P>
<P>
   White House advisers said Hillary Rodham Clinton was also
worried about the Gore campaign, but was not as focused on it as
the president. They noted that if Mrs. Clinton ran for Senate from
New York next year, her effort would suffer if Gore ran poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I be happier if Gore were running well ahead of Bush?
The answer is, `Of course I would,''' said Al From, president of
the Democratic Leadership Council, a centrist group. ``I don't
think it's extraordinarily significant, but I do think it's an
early warning sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon expressed confidence that once Democrats become realistic
about their expectations they will become more satisfied with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got married last year,'' he said. ``I'm 49 years old, and I
went out with a variety of people. But when you get married you're
not looking for a rock star. You're looking for, `Who do I want to
spend the rest of my life with?''' Sooner or later, he said,
``People might say, `I'm looking for someone who's dependable,
someone who understands the issues.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
