</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BOSTON -- May 13, 1999 -- HOME-GIBSON-BOS, 5-13 -- The
red room/library in Gibson House, opened to the public in 1957. The
home is attracting some long-overdue attention and is undergoing
needed restoration work. (Janet Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SAUGUS, Mass. -- May 13, 1999 -- FASHION-PROM-BOS, 5-13
-- Jody Abrams, owner of Bodacious Babes Ltd., helps Robin Carney
with her prom dress. While many high school girls are tanning and
cruising malls to prepare for one of the most anticipated events of
the teenage years, plenty of plus-size girls are sitting at home in
tears. ``It's really affirming when a customer comes in your store
and starts screaming,'' says Ms. Abrams. (Dominic Chavez/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) PHNOM PENH, Cambodia -- May 13, 1999 -- CAMBODIA-LAWYER,
5-13 --Benson Samay, shown in his office, has become the most
prominent lawyer in Cambodia. He will defend Ta Mok, the first -
and so far the only - Khmer Rouge leader to face trial in the
deaths of more than a million people from 1975 to 1979. ``I never
dreamed that I would take this case, nor did I expect to be
involved in a Khmer Rouge trial,'' says Samay, 56, who claims he
studied law in the United States but did not earn a degree. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LOS ANGELES -- May 13, 1999 -- VIDEO-GAMES, 5-13 --
Young men play GT Interactive's Duke Nukon Zero Hour game at the
Electronic Entertainment Exposition at the Loa Angeles Convention
Center. The video game industry opened its annual trade show on
Thursday in a mood part defiant and part defensive about charges
that violent video games contributed to the high school shooting
last month in Littleton, Colo. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WAIKIKI, Hawaii -- May 13, 1999 -- WAIKIKI-BEACHBOY-2,
5-13 -- Pauline Buckley, third from left, greets well wishers at a
ceremony honoring her brother, Charles Lambert, a Waikiki beach boy
for over 30 years, on Wednesday near a table with his portraits.
Lambert's ashes were scattered off Waikiki Beach in an area called
by fellow beach boys as ``First Break,'' where the Pacific curls up
into foaming white surf in sight of the shore. (David Scull/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LAS CHIMALAPAS, Mexico -- May 13, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 16 -- MEXICO-FIRES-2-COX, 5-13 -- New growth is starting to
appear among the scorched pine victims of the devastating fires
that swept through Mexico last year and sent plumes of choking
smoke thousands of miles north into the United States. Forestry
experts say parts of the Chimalapas wildnerness in Oaxaca state -
which includes Mexico's last virgin rainforest - won't recover from
the blazes within our lifetime. (Sergio Dorantes/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LAS CHIMALAPAS, Mexico -- May 13, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 16 -- MEXICO-FIRES-1-COX, 5-13 -- Domingo Jimenez stands on a
scorched mountainside, site of one of the devastating fires that
swept through Mexico last year. Jimenez, a local Zoque Indian, is
trying to save the extraordinary biodiversity of the forest by
converting his fellow peasants to completely organic cultivation
methods that avoid the use of chemicals and slash-and-burn clearing
techniques. (Sergio Dorantes/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WAIKIKI, Hawaii -- May 13, 1999 -- WAIKIKI-BEACHBOY,
5-13 -- Ann Lambert, the former wife of the late Charles Lambert, a
Waikiki beach boy for over 30 years, passes a gardenia to Lambert's
daughter Cindy Tiare Lambert while his other daughter Lisa Lambert
holds his ashes as they head out off Waikiki Beach. The boat was
paddled to the spot beach boys call ``First Break,'' where the
Pacific curls up into foaming white surf in sight of the shore,
where Lambert's ashes were scattered. (David Scull/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzogovina -- May 13, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., MAY 16 -- BOSNIA-CHILDREN-2-COX, 5-13 -- This eight-year-old
seems happy enough, but a counselor working with him is worried:
When drawing a self-portrait, he scribbles out his own face.
Outwardly, they still act like children, but three years after the
bloody civil war ended here, many of Bosnia's youngest victims are
still reeling from the horrors they lived through. (Susannah
Nesmith/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzogovina -- May 13, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., MAY 16 -- BOSNIA-CHILDREN-1-COX, 5-13 -- From left, Ilda
Mujezinovic, 10, Majda Topalovic, 11, and Azra Terzic, 12, want to
dance like the Spice Girls. Outwardly, they still act like
children, but three years after the bloody civil war ended here,
many of Bosnia's youngest victims are still reeling from the
horrors they lived through. (Susannah Nesmith/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) RINAS AIRBASE, Albania -- May 13, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PILOT-COX, 5-12 -- Matt, an Apache pilot, waits to enter his
helicopter at the Rinas Airbase in Albania on Tuesday. Matt
(military censors would not allow him to be identified any further)
is from the West Point class of 1996, husky, single, of medium
build, easy-going and for the last 15 months the ``driver,'' as he
calls it, of one of America's most lethal killing machines - the
AH-65 Apache attack helicopter. (Darko Bandic/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- May 13, 1999 -- JUVENILE-CRIME, 5-13 --
Sens. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.Y., and Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., during
a news conference on Thursday. Under pressure from the White House
and some wavering Republicans, Senate GOP leaders today moved to
reverse an earlier vote and require background checks for all
private firearm sales at gun shows. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 13, 1999 -- AMERICAN-BALLET-MEN, 5-13 --
Maxim Belotserkovsky in ``Don Quixote.'' Attention must be paid
this season to the male dancers at American Ballet Theater. Rarely
has so much dance talent at the top come together at one time: like
planets converging in the night sky to symbolize an auspicious
future, this cluster of men, with their virtuosity and diversity of
style, has changed the look of the company. (Ozier Muhammad/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MARCO ISLAND, Fla. -- May 13, 1999 -- GLF-OBIT-SARAZEN,
5-13 -- Gene Sarazen, the first golfer to win all four of the
sport's major championships, at the Island Club in 1989. Sarazen
died on Thursday at the age of 97. (Courtesy of the Gene and Mary
Sarazen Foundation/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PHOENIX -- May 13, 1999 -- YMCA-RENTER-AZR, 5-12 -- Frank
Mazza has rented a room at the Valley of the Sun YMCA in downtown
Phoenix since 1967. The rates have gone up more than 800 percent
and his room number has changed at least five times, but this has
been his mailing address for almost 32 years. ``It's just a
sleeping room,'' he says, volunteering to conduct a guided tour.
``Small, but it's all right.'' (Randy Reid/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- May 13, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CLINTON, 5-13 --
President Clinton addresses veterans at the Military College on
Thursday about the U.S. miliatry involvement in Kosovo. A spokesman
with the National Security Council said Clinton's speech was ``an
opportunity to give a larger explanation to the American people
about the U.S. interest in Kosovo.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- May 13, 1999 -- OBIT-STEINBERG-3-B&AMP;W, 5-12 --
Saul Steinberg's most famous image, New York as the center of the
world. Steinberg, the metaphysically minded artist and cartoonist
and brooding doodler whose drawings appeared in The New Yorker for
more than half a century, elevating comic illustration into fine
art, died Wednesday at his home in Manhattan. He was 84. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- May 13, 1999 -- OBIT-STEINBERG-2-B&AMP;W, 5-12 --
