<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-ART-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BLAMES MILOSEVIC, NOT FATE, FOR BLOODSHED
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday that he had misread
Balkan history and he apologized for any past suggestions that
there is ``some Balkan disease'' that condemns all sides in
Yugoslavia to an endless cycle of ethnic blood feuds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that for centuries these people have lived
together in the Balkans and southeastern Europe with greater or
lesser degrees of tension, but often without anything approaching
the intolerable conditions and conflicts that exist today,'' he
said in a speech here to combat veterans of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Of the notion that the Yugoslavs are locked in implacable
hatreds, he said: ``I, myself, have been guilty of saying that on
an occasion or two, and I regret it now more than I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's 35-minute rumination on Kosovo came as the
fighting grinds into its eighth week, persisting longer than the
war in the Persian Gulf. The president acknowledged that Americans
are impatient with the pace of NATO's air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, Clinton
warned against ``refugee fatigue'' and forcefully retold the
stories of Albanians who have been executed, raped and routed from
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we see these pictures of the refugees on television
every night, and most people would like another story,'' Clinton
said. ``But we must not get refugee fatigue. We must not forget the
real victims of this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was voicing a concern that Blair raised on Wednesday: that
without the ability to show pictures of the atrocities being
committed inside Kosovo, the news media would tire of repetitious
footage of fleeing refugees, and that reduced exposure to such
scenes could then weaken public support for the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said the Serbs benefited by barring reporters from Kosovo,
because that factor, along with editorial boredom with the
refugees, was leading the media to highlight NATO mistakes like
last week's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, coverage
that cost NATO an edge in the propaganda war.
</P>
<P>
   Taking that argument to heart, Clinton tried to paint a
compelling portrait of the atrocities inside Kosovo, evoking images
of Hitler's slaughter of the Jews and detailing eyewitness accounts
of mass executions, rapes and people being set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though his ethnic cleansing is not the same as the ethnic
extermination of the Holocaust,'' Clinton said, ``the two are
related _ both vicious, premeditated, systematic oppression fueled
by religious and ethnic hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Nine of every 10 Kosovar Albanians now has been
driven from their homes, thousands murdered, at least 100,000
missing, many young men led away in front of their families, over
500 cities, towns and villages burned.''
</P>
<P>
   The president uttered no new policy in his speech, but seemed
determined to clarify, again, the moral imperative for American
participation in a war in Europe that began March 24 and shows
little sign of ending.
</P>
<P>
   He called the campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' being carried out
in Kosovo by the forces of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, ``an affront to humanity and an attack not only on a
people but on the dignity of all people.''
</P>
<P>
   In saying he was mistaken to portray Balkan infighting as
inevitable, he said that Milosevic, like Hitler in Germany, had
been the catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think the Germans would have perpetrated the Holocaust on
their own without Hitler?'' Clinton asked. ``Was there something in
the history of the German race that made them do this? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Brushing aside any half-measures _ like the partial withdrawal
of Milosevic's troops from Kosovo that was staged Thursday for
cameras that his forces controlled _ Clinton said that NATO would
continue its bombing campaign until Milosevic met the allies'
demands in full.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central imperative is this,'' Clinton said in his speech,
delivered at Fort McNair. ``The Kosovars must be able to return
home and live in safety. For this to happen, the Serb forces must
leave; partial withdrawals can only mean continued civil wars with
the Kosovar insurgence.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the same time, the administration played down any effect that
the internal political turmoil in Russia might have on diplomatic
efforts to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said that Strobe
Talbott, the deputy secretary of state, was continuing to work
``constructively'' with the Russians and that he had detected no
setbacks despite President Boris Yeltsin's firing of Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott was in Moscow for two days and had been expected to work
with the Russians on plans for the composition of an international
security force that would be stationed in Kosovo. He was headed to
Brussels for meetings at NATO offices and was also expected to meet
Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary-general, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As he left Moscow, Talbott offered no new details, but said,
``There are many problems here, but there is reason for hope and we
must continue our diplomatic efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   The harshest words of the day came from China, where fury still
raged at the United States for the embassy bombing, which killed
three Chinese. President Jiang Zemin said the United States was
using its economic and technological superiority to aggressively
expand its influence, pursue ``power politics and wantonly
interfere in the internal affairs of other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that despite Jiang's fiery public
comments, tensions with China appeared to be easing. David Leavy, a
spokesman for the National Security Council, said that in a visit
Thursday with the Chinese ambassador, Clinton said that the United
States would carry out a full investigation of the bombing and
would inform the Chinese people of its results.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the ambassador told Clinton that Jiang was now
ready to speak with him by telephone _ an overture that the Chinese
had rebuffed since the bombing. Leavy said that Jiang was trying to
reach Clinton and that the two leaders might talk as early as
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton signed a book of condolences for the
deaths, writing next to his signature: ``With profound grief and
sincere condolences to the victims, their families and the people
of China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
