<HEADLINE>
BUSH BACKS COMPROMISE ON PARENT NOTIFICATION BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A delicate compromise on parental notification
fell apart Thursday, at least temporarily, amid sniping at
Republican Gov. George W. Bush by anti-abortion activists.
</P>
<P>
   Bush remained steadfast, however, in his support of a compromise
bill to notify parents when minors seek abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, the result of weeks of haggling between House
Republicans and a few key Democrats, is a substitute for Senate
Bill 30 by Republican Sen. Florence Shapiro of Plano. The agreement
would waive a waiting period for a girl whose parents bring her for
an abortion. In return, only a judge could decide if there is
justification for a girl not to tell her parents. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Even though the negotiated compromise was signed by various
parties, most of whom are conservative Republicans, an expected
favorable vote from the House State Affairs Committee was called
off late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, anti-abortion activists railed against the
compromise for allowing doctors stronger legal defenses against
criminal misdemeanor charges, which carried a punishment of a
possible one-year jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot support this legislation, and we would consider a
vote in favor of this language to be a pro-abortion vote,'' the
Texas Coalition for Parents' Rights said in a statement signed by
members of eight socially conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respectfully disagree,'' Bush said at a press conference on
various legislative matters. ``I believe the bill we have discussed
would have accomplished the objective of reducing abortions in
Texas by having a strong parental notification bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important for us to pass a good parental
notification bill. This is a good opportunity to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Price, president of Texans United for Life, said he had
lost trust in Bush, whom he accused of not showing enough interest
in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the governor has to gain by alienating
members of the pro-life movement,'' Price said. ``It's going to
have to be negotiated by the governor. The governor's going to have
to come out of the mansion and engage himself in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Price also threatened that the anti-abortion movement would seek
to kill parental legislation this year if it contains the
protections for doctors against criminal charges now contained in
the compromise bill Bush said he supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have drawn the line in the sand,'' he said of the doctor
issue. Earlier, the anti-abortion forces had drawn the line over
allowing only a judge to bypass the parents, which the compromise
grants.
</P>
<P>
   Price added that he would rather believe the attorney for the
National Right to Life Committee in Washington, D.C., that the
compromise is an ``abortion doctor protection bill'' than he would
``a candidate running for president who wants desperately to pass a
piece of legislation to catch up with his little brother (Gov. Jeb
Bush of Florida).''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he understands that some people are casting the
dispute as one of presidential politics but insisted he's
attempting to do what's best for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the compromise deal could well be on again, after a
key Republican player in the controversial negotiations said she
had misunderstood the intentions of Rep. Patricia Gray,
D-Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Gray and Rep. Dianne Delisi, R-Temple, have backed parental
notice legislation this year, but Delisi is the House sponsor of SB
30, which passed that chamber in March.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats, including Houston Reps. Kevin Bailey and
Debra Danburg, thought Delisi killed the compromise she had agreed
to under pressure from angry anti-abortion activists.
</P>
<P>
   Delisi, however, said Thursday evening that the real explanation
is a misunderstanding between her and Gray, for which Delisi takes
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House Republican Caucus leader Ken Marchant of
Coppell said he had been asked to accept a ``code of silence'' on
the issue. He said that talks are now going on between Delisi and
Democrat Steve Wolens, chairman of the key committee and the
credited author of the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Wolens was not available for comment Thursday, but Delisi
indicated the confusion, at most, has stalled the compromise from
passing committee by just one more day. She said she signed an
agreement to support it, and she will honor that agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation down here is that politics at this particular
time (in the last days of the session) is compromise,'' she said.
``I have always held to my agreement. The only reason for a delay
in time is I thought the door was open again for future
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
