<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE BLACKED OUT AS NATO PLANES CONTINUE ASSAULT
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Parts of Belgrade sustained a blackout Thursday
night as NATO warplanes struck at least one of the city's power
plants in the heaviest strike in the capital since the Chinese
Embassy bombing nearly a week ago, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavian television reported that NATO bombers also dropped
short-circuiting graphite bombs against power plants in the cities
of Novi Sad and Nis, causing widespread power blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by surprisingly good weather, NATO scheduled 900 air
sorties over Yugoslavia Thursday. The number of sorties will
``continue to grow as the weather gets good and the aircraft
continue to arrive,'' said Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also announced its decision to send the last 176
airplanes requested by NATO to Europe over the next few weeks,
bringing the total fleet for this war to 1,259.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday onight's flights over Belgrade were the most intense
since three missiles were mistakenly dropped on the Chinese Embassy
last Friday, and NATO and the Pentagon insisted they will continue
striking targets in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman, said Thursday that
President Slobodan Milosevic had miscalculated if he believed there
would be a letup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he believed that NATO would hit Belgrade hard,
night after night,'' Bacon said. ``It has, and it will continue to
do so,'' he added. ``I don't believe he felt that we would fly low
enough and often enough to have a big impact on his forces on the
ground in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO airstrikes focused again on Serbian ground troops in
Kosovo, striking at tanks, barracks and troop formations in the
forests.
</P>
<P>
   Wald announced that the 24 Apache attack helicopters that
arrived in Albania more than three weeks ago were now ready for
combat. There were delays in sending the Apaches to the country,
and once there two crashed in training accidents. In one crash, two
Air Force pilots died.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, NATO's secretary general, Javier Solana, said the
Apaches would be used ``very soon.'' However, Gen. Wesley Clark,
NATO's supreme commander, has yet to request permission to deploy
the Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials dismissed claims by Yugoslavia that
it was withdrawing troops from Kosovo, scoffing at footage that was
released Thursday showing 120 troops leaving Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see no signs of a legitimate withdrawal,'' said Bacon,
dismissing the television footage as a ``staged withdrawal, handful
of troops in starchy uniforms getting onto a shiny bus, smiling at
each other and driving away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also said the State Department's announcement on Monday
that the United States would begin airdrops to the displaced
Albanians in Kosovo was premature. The Pentagon is trying to find
some way to deliver food to the more than half a million stranded
Kosovars, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
