<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DUKE-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE RESEARCHERS ARE TAKEN ABACK BY HALT IN STUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ As an expert on the effects of stress on health,
Dr. Redford Williams Jr. does not want to say he is hopping mad
about the abrupt shutdown this week of his and other federally
financed research at Duke University Medical Center. But he is
decidedly passionate about it.
</P>
<P>
   Four of his experiments were shut down on Tuesday, involving
$1.2 million in research costs and some 150 patients, including
some who were being taught ways to reduce their stress after heart
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not just a bunch of adults playing in the sandbox
here,'' Williams said. ``Day to day we are working to save lives.
If we can reduce stress in patients, we believe we can prevent some
deaths. And now we have a halt to our research. As best I can tell,
the halt does not come because patients are being harmed, but
because there are administrative problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he added, ``we need to think about the harm that may
come from halting work.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators on Monday evening temporarily decertified
Duke University Medical Center as an institution eligible to do
research with federal financing. The investigators, from the Office
of Protection From Research Risks, found a number of apparent
violations of safety and ethics rules, and the university failed to
correct them for several months, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The violations cited by the government were chiefly failures at
Duke's Institutional Review Board, the body that reviews each
proposed human experiment. The board must follow federal rules in
determining which experiments are permitted, and what risks
patients may be subjected to. Twenty violations were found, ranging
from informed consent documents that may have given patients
incomplete information about what they were undertaking, to the
board's approval of experiments without complete review.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Duke officials met in Maryland with officials of
the agency charged with overseeing the safety of patients in human
experiments around the nation. After presenting a plan to correct
the deficiencies cited, the Duke officials characterized the
meeting as ``both collegial and productive'' and said they hoped to
get the research license reinstated soon.
</P>
<P>
   All over the sprawling medical center, doctors grappled with the
shutdown. Some patients who had traveled from other parts of the
nation to get blood tests or X-rays as they took part in
experiments had to be sent home without getting the work done, they
said. Researchers getting grant requests ready for June 1 deadlines
were delayed from finishing studies and analyzing the data they
will need to persuade grantors of the worth of their work.
</P>
<P>
   Specially trained nurses who work on experiments like the
testing of new drugs either now or soon may be on the payroll but
unable to do the work. The cost in his area, said Dr. Christopher
Granger, a cardiologist who runs a number of experiments that have
been stopped from bringing in new patients, could amount to a few
hundred to a few thousand dollars per patient if the delay lasts
more than a few days. Several dozen patients are included in his
studies, and the costs will begin to mount after a few days of no
new patient enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   The behavioral studies being conducted by Williams, who heads
the Behavioral Medicine Research Center, involve $1.2 million in
mostly federal money. Williams calculated that roughly $3,260 a day
would be lost if the decision remained in effect past a few days.
Asked if he would have to come up with new money to replace it, he
replied: ``No, I hope not. We will work much harder to try to make
up lost time.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a point in a couple of weeks, researchers suggest, past
which time and money cannot be made up, and studies will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. K. Ranga Krishnan, chairman of the department of psychiatry
at Duke, said some 150 studies in his department had been
completely closed down. Asked his view of the federal investigators
and what they did, he replied: ``They are right. In this kind of
work they always must be right. After all, they are not doing this
to be mean. It is their job.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is a positive side, he said, explaining, ``We are
certainly educating researchers about the importance of federal
oversight and evaluating risks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
