r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHNIC-CLEANSING:GIAG     05-13 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHNIC-CLEANSING:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUPHEMISMS COVER UGLY TRUTH: `ETHNIC CLEANSING' MEANS GENOCIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is CEO of book publishers Lakota
Times Publishing, Inc., located in Sioux Falls, S.D. His Indian
name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I've always liked the word ``euphemism.'' There are just some
words that sort of roll around on the tongue and are fun to say.
This word is one of them. But it can be used in the wrong way.
 &HT;    A professor of English I had many years ago had his own special
words for euphemisms. He called them ``Nice-Nellyisms.'' One
example he gave was in a story about Winston Churchill. It seems
the British prime minister was invited to a state dinner in
Washington. The lady known as ``The Hostess with the Mostess,''
Perle Mesta, arranged the seating so that she could be next to the
prime minister. When Churchill asked for the breast of the chicken,
Ms. Mesta whispered in his ear, ``In America we are very discreet
and we refer to the breast of the chicken as the white meat.''
Churchill nodded and continued with his meal.
 &HT;    A few years later Churchill had the duty of awarding medals to
several Americans, Ms. Mesta among them. As he approached Perle
with medal in hand he whispered in her ear, ``Pardon me, while I
pin this medal on your white meat.''
 &HT;    That is what my professor referred to as ``Nice-Nellyisms.''
 &HT;    Laid to rest, gone to the great beyond, met his maker, journeyed
to the spirit world, pushing up daisies, or has gone to a better
place, are just a few of the euphemisms to describe death.
 &HT;    For deaf people we now have hearing impaired. For bald people
some now say follicle impaired. Children once referred to as
retarded are now children with a learning disability. Some would
say these are politically correct expressions rather than
euphemisms.
 &HT;    When it comes to gender distinction we have created an entirely
new vocabulary. Instead of the stewardess on airplanes we now have
flight attendants. Our old reliable mailman is now a mailperson.
Chairman of the board is now chairperson. And on and on.
 &HT;    I thought about these things when the words ``ethnic cleansing''
kept bouncing around the airwaves. It put me in mind of the
euphemisms used by the Nazis during World War II. When they first
started to move Jews from their homes to concentration camps they
called it ``relocation.'' When they got real serious about
exterminating the Jewish population of Europe, they called it ``the
final solution.''
 &HT;    Ethnic cleansing is genocide pure and simple. Creating a
``Nice-Nellyism'' to soften its meaning does not change the end
result. It is still genocide.
 &HT;    In early America, Manifest Destiny meant that God had chosen a
race of people to occupy a land. To the American Indians the words
still meant genocide.
 &HT;    If an errant bomb or missile strikes a civilian neighborhood
killing and maiming many people, the carnage is known as
``collateral damage.'' If an attack by artillery or bombers strikes
its own forces by mistake and incur casualties, this is known as
being killed by ``friendly fire.''
 &HT;    In the Lakota language, a very ancient language, it would be
very difficult to create euphemisms. There are many words nearly
impossible to translate into English. In fact, there were no words
in Lakota for key, jail or prison because these objects or
facilities did not exist in the pre-colonization land of the
Lakota.
 &HT;    When euphemisms are used to dilute or soften the meaning of
words because they are offensive or cruel, perhaps this carries
things too far into dishonesty. Ethnic cleansing is genocide and it
should be referred to as such. Because Nazis used the phrase ``The
Final Solution'' to describe the murder of millions of Jews, it did
not make it easier on those being murdered.
 &HT;    To me, euphemisms are amusing only when they are not used to
cover or disguise an evil deed. Winston Churchill could have told
you that.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) &QL;
</P>
