<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6353 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIOUS-LABOR-LOSS:CO     05-13 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIOUS-LABOR-LOSS:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR SHORTAGES THREATEN U.S. ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Premise No. 1 among those working to strangle immigration _
legal and illegal _ into the United States, is that we don't need
newcomers because there are plenty of Americans to do the work in
the largest economy in the world. WRONG!
 &HT;    Welfare and unemployed people, they maintain, can fill all the
jobs. WRONG!
 &HT;    Raise wages and better working conditions and people will flock
to the fields to earn $10 an hour or more, they claim. WRONG!
 &HT;    During harvest season in California's San Joaquin Valley,
perhaps the greatest agricultural complex in world history, a
quarter of a million workers are needed to harvest dozens of crops.
The 1998 work force was shy 80,000 workers. That's more people than
hundreds of cities in the country. Is this for real? Yes, according
to Manuel Cunha, president of the Nisei Farmers League of Fresno,
California.
 &HT;    Oregon and Washington labor contractors were raiding California
fields for workers by paying $75 bounties and free transportation.
``Contractors were pulling workers off the fields,'' Cunha told the
Los Angeles Times.
 &HT;    There was such a worker shortage in the Fresno area that the
raisin harvest was lengthened by a month. Nevertheless, grapes were
still lost.
 &HT;    There are people who don't believe the farmers. They are people
like the ultra-liberal Farm Worker's Union, and ultra-conservatives
like Pat Buchanan, David Duke, and the Federation of Americans for
Immigration Reform (FAIR). Anti-immigrant advocates (they call
themselves `immigration reformers') would like fewer immigrants
altogether, but would select immigrants who are preferably white,
Protestant and Northern European. As usual, however, the facts
prove them wrong. Why?
 &HT;    A lack of farm labor is just one shortage caused by
anti-immigrant restrictions forced on the American economy in
recent years. Other examples are the hospitals that are having to
cut services because of workers shortages. St. Bernard's Hospital
in the Chicago suburb of Englewood threatened to shut down because
of a lack of nurses. Into the breach stepped Democratic Rep. Bobby
Rush, formerly of the Black Panthers, with an emergency bill to
allow 500 foreign nurses into the country to staff hospitals like
St. Bernard's.
 &HT;    California's St. John's Regional Medical Center in Oxnard has
announced that it will close acute-care wings and drop some
elective surgeries _ for lack of nurses.
 &HT;    Foreign nurses ``work mostly evenings, nights, weekends and in
areas where majority (white) nurses will not work,'' states Barbara
Nichols, head of the Commission on Graduates of Foreign Nursing
Schools. She points out that; ``foreign-educated nurses have been
used to fill the gaps.''
 &HT;    Not enough nurses, not enough farm workers, and this is merely
the beginning. Hi-tech industries in Silicon Valley, San Diego and
Boston are suffering from labor shortages. There are 300,000 empty
hi-tech job billets. And, hi-tech is the one field in which
Congress has loosened the curbs and doubled the number of foreign
workers permitted. These are high-pay jobs going begging. It will
get worse.
 &HT;    In the fields, Fresno farmers raised wages 20 percent last
summer and asked the state for welfare and unemployed people and
were sent 1 percent of their required workers.
 &HT;    The shortage of workers is fueled by something else, too,
besides the unwillingness of Americans to work in the fields or in
inner-city hospitals, and that is the hammer of tighter immigrant
control at the border and in the hinterland. On the one hand, the
Border Patrol has been beefed up with several thousand new agents
and they have clamped the border down at all the usual places where
illegals used to cross with impunity.
 &HT;    Recently, the Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS)
announced that it was going to comb the personnel records of
Midwestern meat-packing plants to weed out and run out of their
jobs any immigrants they suspected of using forged or false
documents in applying for jobs. Such was the case recently in the
Yakima Valley of the State of Washington where the INS forced
employers to fire over 500 workers whom the INS suspected of
circumventing regulations by giving employers false documents.
 &HT;    A crisis is building throughout the country and it is a direct
result of anti-immigrant hysteria and people who are uncomfortable
with the race, religion and ethnicity of America today. But in
their success there is danger.
 &HT;    ``We've lost asparagus, cauliflower. Broccoli, peaches, grapes.
These are things I know for a fact. It's statewide and it's
nationwide.'' So says Steve Scaroni, president of the Imperial
Valley Vegetable Growers Association.
 &HT;    And so say I. The situation will get worse. Our booming economy
will slow because there aren't enough workers. Laying the blame for
the end of the booming '90s will be easy this time.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
