A6355 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EQUALITY:COLBERT-NEWA     05-13 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUALITY:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EQUALITY AND CIVIL LIBERTIES FOR ALL
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By CHUCK COLBERT 
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert is a founder of the Gay and Lesbian Alumni of
Notre Dame/St. Mary's College, and serves on the board of directors
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Are civil rights _ that is, the fight for equality and civil
liberties for African Americans _ and gay rights really a common
struggle?
 &HT;    All three panelists from left and right of the political
spectrum _ State Rep. Jarrett Barrios, the Rev. Peter Gomes, and
Patricia Ireland _ answered with a resounding ``yes'' at a recent
forum held at the John F. Kennedy School of Government.
 &HT;    Sponsored by the Kennedy School's gay student group, the Women
and Public Policy Program, and the student advisory committee of
the Institute of Politics, the event drew more than 200 people _
standing room only.
 &HT;    Gomes, Harvard's Plummer Professor of Christian Morals and
minister in the university's Memorial Church, provided a
comparative perspective. Gomes, who is gay, African American, and
Republican, said that from the time of the Civil War onward the
term ``civil rights'' applied almost universally _ much like a
copyright _ to the rights of African Americans.
 &HT;    Then came the issue of gays in the military.
 &HT;    ``When I tried to promulgate the parity and equity question
between gays in the military and the integration of the armed
services by President Truman at the end of the Second World, a
great howl was raised, frankly on the part of African Americans,
who felt that their copyright on the struggle was somehow being
infringed, that there somehow was a moral distinction to be made
between civil rights, capital C, capital R, and whatever it was
that gay people seemed to feel the country owed them,'' Gomes said.
 &HT;    Continuing, ``This revealed a tremendous fissure in our moral
and our legal universe in this country, part of the divisioning ...
by which no rights get accorded to everybody because everybody with
a few rights defends his or her territory absolutely and feels that
sharing of rights in some respect makes vulnerable the rights
heretofore won and compromises the integrity of the enterprise,''
he said.
 &HT;    But for those who lack the moral imagination and civic courage
to see that gay rights are not special rights _ rather civil
liberties entitled to everybody _ Patricia Ireland, president of
the National Organization for Women, makes the necessary
connections.
 &HT;    ``We support lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgendered issues
for the same reason we support ending racism or bias on ethnicity _
nobody should be discriminated against because of an accident of
birth,'' she said.
 &HT;    ``We support lesbian and gay issues for the same reason we
support non-discrimination based on religion: if it's something you
choose _ and most of us, even those of us who are born into a
particular religion, choose our religion as adults _ you shouldn't
face discrimination,'' Ireland said.
 &HT;    ``We support lesbian and gay civil rights for the same reason we
support abortion rights because in the very intimate area of our
lives, sexuality or reproduction, we don't think that we should
have interference with our privacy,'' she said.
 &HT;    ``As a matter of a pragmatic political position, there is no
question that lesbian and gay rights are part of the feminist
agenda,'' Ireland said. ``It's also a principled position.''
 &HT;    Barrios _ the first openly gay man elected to the Massachusetts
legislature and one of three Latino representatives _ also said
that gay rights and civil rights were similar. They ``are not
something that can be divorced. Both are the legally and morally
distinguishable part within us that motivates us to be imaginative
and indignant about issues, about how we are going to overcome
them. It's clear from that part of you that wants to change the
world whether you are gay or Latino,'' he said.
 &HT;    Gay rights and civil rights are one in the same _ no matter
what's considered: fair housing, employment, or even civil
marriage, Barrios said.
 &HT;    All three panelists agreed that the right to same-sex civil
marriage is the current hot button issue; and as Gomes said, the
``blessing of same-sex ceremonies, not a substitute for marriage,
even that raises cultural hackles.''
 &HT;    Gomes went on to say that the ``secular order will drive the
religious order to do the right thing. If one had waited for
churches to lead the civil rights movement, we'd all be at the back
of the bus ... for better or worse the culture has to have this
debate.''
 &HT;    Continuing, ``as a Christian minister it scandalizes and
embarrasses me to say that in so many movements for the liberation
of the spirit, the religious community is on the sidelines, waiting
to see how it turns out,'' he said.
 &HT;    That's truly a shame since so much opposition to civil rights
and equality for gay people stems from organized religion and
misinterpretation of the Bible.
 &HT;    Ecclesiastical courage, coupled with moral imagination and civic
valor, could go a long way in the common struggle for equality and
civil liberties for all _ gay and straight.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Chuck Colbert 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
