<HEADLINE>
MOST LOYAL SECRETARY; LUCKIER BOSS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By KIRSTEN CHAPMAN 
 &HT;    (Kirsten Chapman writes a weekly column for the Columbus
Dispatch in Columbus, Ohio, and is the author of three books,
including recently published ``The Way Home.'') 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In 1948, Dinah Shore filled the air with ``Buttons and Bows,''
Citation became the eighth horse in racing history to win the
Triple Crown and Harry. S. Truman was re-elected president of the
United States.
 &HT;    That spring, 36-year-old Thelma Lien boarded a bus in her
Wisconsin hometown of Beloit and headed for Kenosha 2 1/2 hours
away.
 &HT;    ``A friend had mentioned that somebody needed a
bookkeeping-machine operator, so I took a chance,'' she recalled
recently.
 &HT;    The job had fallen through, though, but then she learned that a
Kenosha doctor needed a secretary. Fortunately, she knew shorthand.
 &HT;    ``I was scared stiff,'' she said, remembering the day she
climbed the white marble steps of the old Kenosha Clinic for her
interview.
 &HT;    Yet she found my father, 41 at the time, ``congenial and easy to
talk to. The next thing I knew, I was hired,'' she said.
 &HT;    ``I was a jack-of-all-trades; anything that concerned the
office, I took care of.''
 &HT;    She not only filled the role of the receptionist but also
balanced the books, did the banking and kept the files. She was
known to even wash the windows and scrub the floors.
 &HT;    One time, during dictation, the building janitor appeared
suddenly, so scared he was stuttering. After calming him down, Dad
and Thelma discovered what had frightened him: An arm from the
clinic skeleton had dropped from the rafters onto his shoulder
while he was cleaning the basement.
 &HT;    They thought they'd have to conduct a funeral to dispose of the
deteriorating bones. ``But Dr. Swift, who taught radiology classes
at the hospital, took it off our hands.''
 &HT;    Thelma, who doesn't drive, lived close enough to walk to work.
Conveniently, she had an apartment overlooking Library Park _ for,
as she said, ``My nose is always in a book.''
 &HT;    Sometimes she had us kids over for dinner. On one occasion she
served orange-juice ``cocktails'' and lobster tails to make us feel
grown up.
 &HT;    And she and my mother shared a mutual admiration, each one
helping the other.
 &HT;    Thelma first baby-sat for us right after my brother, the fourth
and youngest, was born. When she stayed a week or two, she asked in
the morning what we wanted for dinner.
 &HT;    Excitement waited to happen until she came to visit: Once, the
water heater broke and flooded the basement.
 &HT;    Another time, down in the basement, my toddler brother looked up
and asked, ``Why is that man coming through the window?''
 &HT;    Thelma, unintimidated, scared him off. The police found only his
tools.
 &HT;    Many years later, the 85-year-old woman who served my father for
more than three decades continues to be a fountain of information.
 &HT;    ``Whatever happened to that old x-ray machine that Dad used to
have in his office?'' I wondered..
 &HT;    ``He sold it to Dr. Schmick for a dollar.''
 &HT;    ``Why did he keep anise candy in his top right desk drawer?''
 &HT;    ``Frank Christiansen knew he liked it; he always brought him
some whenever he had an appointment.''
 &HT;    Of her 32-years with Dad, she said: ``The time went so fast, it
seemed as though it stood still. My job was enjoyable. I was a
member of your family. It was a perfect way.''
 &HT;    For Thelma, he was never Leif, always ``Dr. Lokvam.''
 &HT;    ``No one could ever say anything against Dr. Lokvam in front of
me.''
 &HT;    After a national day to honor secretaries was initiated in 1952,
Dad (``when he wasn't in surgery'') would take her to lunch.
 &HT;    ``We might just go and get a hamburger, but it was
entertainment,'' she said.
 &HT;    In her apartment, Thelma still displays a picture of my father,
a photograph taken in his prime, when together they saved the
world.
 &HT;    ``He was like a brother to me,'' she said.
 &HT;    Although he has been gone for seven years, she still sees him
every day.
 &HT;    I can't imagine a more loyal secretary. Or a luckier boss.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Kirsten Chapman 
