<HEADER>
A6360 &Cx1f; tab-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYT     05-13 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (These ``separate buy'' articles from this week's New America News
Service moved today.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish a NEWAM article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicatees
Executive DEBORAH WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISRAEL, THE LAND OF DRIVING ADVENTURE. Nothing, not reading, not
watching documentaries, not talking to those who have driven there,
prepares your mind and nerves for driving in Israel, writes
columnist Bill Maxwell, on assignment in the Middle East. ``After a
week of executing life-and-death maneuvers on the highways of the
Holy Land, I am beginning to question my sanity,'' he admits. But
more importantly he wonders about the sanity of Israelis. Former
Jerusalem Mayor Teddy Kolleck was once quoted as explaining: ``When
you have to fight a war once every 10 years, safe driving becomes
the farthest thing from your mind.'' Not much comfort to the
intrepid reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-HOLY-HIGHWAY-COWBOYS:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary, ``i'' international and ``t'' travel files.
</P>
<P>
   EUPHEMISMS COVER UGLY TRUTH: `ETHNIC CLEANSING' MEANS GENOCIDE.
Thinking about the many euphemisms used today often to disguise
truth, the words ``ethnic cleansing'' put columnist Tim Giago in
mind of the expressions ``relocation'' and ``the final solution''
used by the Nazis during World War II. ``In early America,
`Manifest Destiny' meant that God had chosen a race of people to
occupy a land,'' he writes. ``To the American Indians those words
meant genocide ... for, in the Lakota language, a very ancient
language, it would be very difficult to create such euphemisms.''
Ethnic cleansing is genocide pure and simple, he declares.
``Creating a euphemism to soften its meaning does not change the
end result. It is still genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-ETHNIC-CLEANSING:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR SHORTAGES THREATEN U.S. ECONOMY. The premises that America
doesn't need immigration because there are plenty of U.S. citizens
to do the work in the largest economy in the world, or that welfare
and unemployed people can fill all the jobs, or that by raising
wages and better working conditions people will flock to the fields
to earn $10 an hour or more, are all WRONG! states columnist Raoul
Lowery Contreras. The realities of strict immigration and migration
controls are severe shortages of farm laborers, meat packers,
hospital nurses and hi-tech workers, to name just a few of the
industries suffering serious losses. ``This could dramatically slow
down our booming economy,'' Contreras notes somberly.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-SERIOUS-LABOR-LOSS:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   EQUALITY AND CIVIL LIBERTIES FOR ALL. Are civil rights _ the
fight for equality and civil liberties for African Americans _ and
gay rights really a common struggle? All three panelists from left
and right of the political spectrum, attending a recent forum held
at the John F. Kennedy School of Government, answered with a
resounding ``yes,'' reports columnist Chuck Colbert. Panelist
Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization for Women,
made it clearer: ``We support lesbian, gay, bisexual, and
transgendered issues for the same reason we support ending racism
or bias on ethnicity _ nobody should be discriminated against
because of an accident of birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-EQUALITY:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   MOST LOYAL SECRETARY; LUCKIER BOSS. Her father's secretary
Thelma has become an enduring piece of her family history, writes
columnist Kirsten Chapman. The woman, now 85, who served her father
for 32 years, recalls every detail of those years beginning in
1948: ``I was a jack-of-all-trades,'' she says, ``anything that
concerned the office, I took care of.'' She not only filled the
role of the receptionist but also balanced the books, did the
banking and kept the files, and was known to even wash the windows
and scrub the floors on occasion. ``The time went so fast,'' she
tells Chapman now, ``it seemed as though it stood still. My job was
enjoyable. I was a member of your family. It was a perfect way.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-DAD'S-SECRETARY:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
