<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP-CONTROLLED HOUSE PANEL SEEKS TO CUT NASA PROJECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-controlled House Science Committee
wants to scrap NASA's Triana project, a camera-equipped satellite
pushed by Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The panel voted 21-18 along party lines Thursday to prohibit the
space agency from spending money on the project, which would
broadcast live, round-the-clock video images of Earth over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members also decided against spending any more
taxpayer money on an inflatable habitat for the international space
station, a project called TransHab being developed at Johnson Space
Center.
</P>
<P>
   An effort to pull the plug on U.S. involvement in the
international space station was rejected by the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The prohibitions were written into so-called ``authorization''
legislation outlining NASA spending priorities over the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The measure envisions the agency receiving $41.2 billion as part
of the federal budget through 2002, slightly more than requested by
the Clinton administration. The bill now goes to the full House.
</P>
<P>
   NASA this year will spend about $35 million on the Triana
project, which Gore convinced the agency to tackle in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Named for Rodrigo de Triana, the sailor who first spotted the
New World on Christopher Columbus' voyage in 1492, the satellite is
scheduled for launch aboard a space shuttle in December 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Once released by the shuttle, the satellite would be guided to
its permanent station about halfway between Earth and the sun. The
new spacecraft would carry a small telescope and a high-definition
camera.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being available to Internet users, images of the
sun-splashed Earth would be used by scientists to study weather
patterns, cloud formations, oceans and the planet's vegetation
canopy.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the project ``a multimillion-dollar screen saver,'' Rep.
Dave Weldon, R-Fla., led the effort to shift $35 million requested
for Triana into cancer and microbiology research overseen by the
space agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has ``cut NASA's budget year after
year, and then turns around and proposes tripe science like
Triana,'' Weldon complained. ``Maybe NASA can't stand up to the
White House, but the U.S. Congress certainly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bart Gordon, D-Tenn., accused Republicans of trying to kill
the enterprise in ``a misguided partisan effort'' to harm Gore's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a tremendous education tool that all schools
would have access to and be a treasure chest of resources'' for
scientists and weather forecasters, Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   If the authorization bill clears both the House and Senate
without the Triana project, NASA administrator Dan Goldin has told
lawmakers, he will urge President Clinton to veto the measure.
</P>
<P>
   For the past six years, NASA has operated under guidance
Congress has provided in annual ppropriations legislation and an
authorization bill passed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   While congressional budget-writers will have the final say on
how much will be allocated for 2000, House Science Committee
members recommended fully funding NASA's request for the space
station and space shuttle programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA's streamlining and reform efforts over the past few years
have strongly improved our space operations,'' said Rep. Dana
Rohrabacher, R-Calif. and chairman of the House space subcommittee.
``This legislation builds on this by both increasing NASA's budget
and pushing NASA to continue on the reform path.''
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of Science Committee Chairman James
Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., the bill prohibits any funding for TransHab,
which NASA is developing to provide space explorers more room on
long missions.
</P>
<P>
   Set for launch in 2004 as one of the final components of the
space station, TransHab would provide crews a three-level habitat.
One level would be sleeping quarters, another a gymnasium and the
third, a large galley. Its estimated cost is $80 million more than
the crew quarters in the current design.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Texas, had planned to push for removal of
the TransHab spending restriction, but faced opposition from
Sensenbrenner and his Republican allies. Lampson said he might try
to amend the authorization bill when it reaches the House floor,
possibly next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tie the hands of NASA scientists to keep them from finding
better, safer, more efficient ways to improve the living space of
astronauts is unbelievable,'' said Lampson, whose district includes
the Johnson Space Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner said he is not opposed to the concept, merely to
the idea of redrawing space station components five years after the
U.S. and its international partners adopted the current design.
``We're sticking to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space station almost got killed (in 1993) because we had
eight years of perpetual redesigning,'' Sensenbrenner said. ``I
don't want to get back on that track.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the committee approved the NASA authorization bill, a
provision pushed by Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, was added to
include minority facilities in the agency's academic programs.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee's proposal would ensure that almost half the $387.8
million spent by NASA on academic programs over the next three
years would go into minority education and research programs. In
addition, just over $100 million of that amount would be spent at
historically black colleges and universities under her proposal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
