<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-ATOMIC-TRAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC EDITS `NUCLEAR WASTE' FROM MINISERIES, AND OUTSIDE PRESSURE IS
CHARGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Idaho, Nev.)  (rk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What began as a generic disaster movie about a runaway train has
turned into an unusual damage-control exercise for NBC, which went
to great lengths to redub ``Atomic Train,'' a two-part miniseries
to be broadcast on Sunday and Monday nights, to delete all
references to nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. senator, in a speech Thursday, accused NBC of bowing to
pressure from the nuclear power industry. But NBC executives say
the only pressure came from the network's own chief censor, who
stepped in after the entertainment division's promotions department
had put out news releases that wrongly portrayed the miniseries as
a fact-based docudrama.
</P>
<P>
   The miniseries' plot involves a train traveling from Idaho to
Colorado carrying nuclear waste _ now being redubbed as ``hazardous
material'' _ as well as a Russian-made nuclear bomb secretly tucked
on board by the bad guys. When the train's brakes fail as it
hurtles toward Denver, the hero (played by Rob Lowe) must try to
stop it. When the train crashes, the ``hazardous material'' catches
fire, and the nuclear bomb explodes.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Atomic Train'' is fictional, the issue of safety in
transporting nuclear waste is a real concern, especially to Sen.
Richard H. Bryan, a D-Nev., whose state is the site of proposed
nuclear waste repositories still being haggled over in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in a speech on the Senate floor, Bryan questioned
whether NBC had redubbed ``Atomic Train'' in deference to the
nuclear power industry, since NBC's parent company, General
Electric, has a nuclear energy unit. While admitting he had no
proof, the senator said it seemed ``extraordinary'' that the
network would go to such lengths to change a movie a week before it
was scheduled to be broadcast, and after releasing reams of
promotional material on it.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC argues the flip side of that coin, saying it would not
have gone to the cost (estimated by industry sources as tens of
thousands of dollars) and trouble of redubbing unless it believed
it had a responsibility to viewers not to mislead them. The network
says it could simply have put disclaimers on the miniseries to
remind viewers that it was fictional.
</P>
<P>
   NBC revised its account from Wednesday to Thursday. At first,
NBC executives said nuclear waste was not typically carried by
train, making the miniseries grossly inaccurate. Later they said
that nuclear products might be carried by train, but would not be
carried in boxcars, as the miniseries depicted. Ultimately, they
said the problem was that the drama was being promoted as
fact-based and had never been ``vetted'' for factual accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives say part of the problem is that the network's
publicists were eager to whip up audience interest in the drama,
which will appear during a ``sweeps'' month when Nielsen ratings
are used to calculate future advertising rates. The publicists had
sent out news packages that vividly connected ``Atomic Train'' to
real life.
</P>
<P>
   It ``may sound like total fiction _ but it isn't,'' one release
read, going on to provide excerpts from newspaper articles and
technical studies about the possibilities of accidents from the
transport of nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   Another included a map of train and highway routes, and directed
television editors to ``look at the enclosed map and you will see
that your city is currently on a truck or train route for nuclear
waste transportation.'' That one concluded: ``If you want to
explore the timeliness of this miniseries, please contact me. I can
put you in touch with authorities who will give you great quotes.''
</P>
<P>
   Such releases came to the attention of Rosalyn Weinman, NBC's
executive vice president for content policy, only when the
publicity department, she said, proposed screening the drama for
someone in a government agency or special-interest group; such a
publicity move requires Weinman's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Weinman said that when she saw the extent to which the
miniseries was being promoted as factual, she felt she had to take
two steps _ making sure it had a prominent disclaimer on the
broadcast itself, emphasizing that it is fiction, and redubbing the
words ``nuclear waste'' to ``hazardous material.'' The nuclear bomb
is still part of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our own promotional positioning led people to perceive it
as nonfiction,'' Weinman said Thursday, ``then I think our level of
responsibility includes not only putting a disclaimer out but also
to taking that next step. There's a lot of science here, and a lot
of regulatory and transportation issues, and we didn't have the
time to vet it properly. The conservative broadcasterly thing to do
was to make those changes.''
</P>
<P>
   She said it would have been different had the drama been
promoted strictly as a ``straight-out roller coaster action
thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the hubbub about whether the frightening scenario
could be interpreted as fact-based, NBC had to deal with another
difficult scenario. The network had considered changing the
miniseries' setting from Denver to another city because of a
real-life disaster that had afflicted the Denver area _ the
Littleton, Colo., school shootings. But those changes would have
been prohibitively costly, NBC said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
