<HEADER>
A6393 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-1STLD-W     05-13 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: gun shows. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican Senators, in addition to Smith of Oregon, who
expressed concern to Craig about Wednesday's votes included John
McCain of Arizona, Olympia Snowe of Maine and Susan Collins of
Maine. McCain and Collins both rose to speak on the Senate floor
Thursday in favor of background checks.
</P>
<P>
   In comments Thursday morning, President Clinton urged lawmakers
to amend what he saw as Wednesday's mistake. ``For the life of
me,'' Clinton said, ``I can't figure out how they did it or why
they passed up this chance to save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are watching this debate,'' the President
added. ``They care very much about the result.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the result was that the Senate passed, by an
overwhelming majority, 96 to 2, the amendment on semiautomatic
assault weapons, which was sponsored by Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   It not only made sales of those weapons to those under 18
illegal, but also make possession of such weapons by children
without parental consent a crime. That merely brings the federal
law on assault weapons into line with the law on handguns, which,
curiously, was more severe.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's amendment included exemptions for assault weapons
used by hunters, ranchers or sportsmen.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising, senators also approved, 59-39, an amendment by
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., to ban the import of ammunition
clips that enabled assault weapons to fire more than 10 rounds at
once. The manufacture of such clips in America is already illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty Republicans joined 39 Democrats in favor of the
amendment, while only four Democrats joined 35 Republicans in
opposition. Two Democrats were absent.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein attributed the outcome to ``a realization that the
American people want some regulation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
