<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-TEXACO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TEXACO DEAL, CHEVRON WANTS CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chevron Corp. and Texaco Inc. will continue merger talks next
week, but they remain divided principally over Chevron's insistence
that it control the combined company, said executives close to the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron has been talking to potential partners, the executives
said, since the $42.8 billion takeover of Amoco Corp. by British
Petroleum last August, forming BP Amoco PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron chairman and chief executive Kenneth Derr had sought to
buy Atlantic Richfield Co. earlier this year but lost out to BP
Amoco, which reached agreement to buy ARCO in March for $26.8
billion. Derr had also discussed a possible combination with Amoco
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Derr and other Chevron executives now face several major
stumbling blocks in the company's effort to acquire Texaco, which
is still in a preliminary stage.
</P>
<P>
   Still unresolved is what role Texaco chairman and chief
executive Peter Bijur would play in a combined company, the
executives and industry analysts said. Other issues include an
appropriate price for Texaco and possible antitrust issues deriving
from the dominant position that the combined companies would have
in refining, particularly in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Bijur, who ascended to Texaco's top job in 1996, stressed in an
interview in December that while he was open to a merger he had
positioned his company to go it alone. He began last year to cut a
further $650 million in costs on top of deep reductions already in
place. Texaco, like other oil companies, has had to cope with a
plunge in crude oil prices that has only been reversed in recent
months. Crude oil that averaged about $14 a barrel last year has
recovered to $18 a barrel, and some analysts think it may go higher
than $20.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of analysts, this has eased the pressure on Bijur to
agree to a takeover by Chevron, which is about the same size at
Texaco in terms of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco stock closed Thursday at $69.125 in trading on the New
York Stock Exchange. Chevron closed at $94.4375. An analyst said
that a $75-or-lower share price for Texaco was more likely than the
$80 price that had earlier been floated by bankers to see what the
reaction of Wall Street and stockholders would be.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Sieminski, an oil analyst with BT Alex. Brown, said that if
Chevron made a good offer Bijur would have a simple decision to
make: ``Do you fight hard to keep slots open for Texaco management,
or should you take the money and run?''
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, however, is determined to absorb Texaco on its own
terms, according to an Chevron executive close to the talks.
``We've told them if we go through with this, we will run it _
period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps unsurprisingly, Texaco is not comfortable with this
position. `` Bijur does not perceive Texaco as a company desperate
to be taken over,'' particularly at a time of rebounding crude oil
prices, said John D. Hervey, an analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette who is based in London.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in recent major takeovers in the industry, one executive and
company have emerged as clearly dominant. BP Amoco chief executive
Sir John Browne assumed such a role in carrying out the Amoco and
ARCO deals.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly in the $80 billion agreement by Exxon to take over
Mobil, Lee R. Raymond, the chairman and chief executive of Exxon,
added the title of president and has emerged dominant.
</P>
<P>
   A further complication in the Chevron attempt with Texaco is
that Chevron vice chairman David O'Reilly is viewed as a likely
successor to Derr, and would therefore find it hard to allow Bijur
a turn to run a combined company.
</P>
<P>
   A hint of the strategic reasons why Chevron is pursuing Texaco
was given by Martin Klitten, the vice president and chief financial
officer of Chevron, in a meeting with some analysts in New York on
Tuesday, a participant in the session said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what gaps Chevron was seeking to fill, Klitten,
without specifically discussing the talks with Texaco, said that
the company wanted to add to its domestic production of oil and
natural gas to generate the cash to finance its exploration in
other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco is a large producer of both oil and natural gas in the
United States. Unlike most oil companies, whose domestic production
is declining, Texaco increased its production of crude oil last
year to 433,000 barrels a day from 396,000 barrels in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The growth came largely through the acquisition in 1997 of
Monterey Resources, which has fields of heavy oil that Texaco has
expertise in producing.
</P>
<P>
   By applying new methods, Texaco has been able to revive
production of heavy oil at one if its oldest fields, at Kern River
in Bakersfield, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Klitten also said that Chevron was looking to become a major
refiner and marketer of gasoline in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco owns a large refinery in Britain and 35 percent of
another in the Netherlands, and Chevron has tried to buy these
refineries. Texaco also has more than 3,000 gasoline stations and
other retail outlets in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Although smaller in Europe than some major competitors like BP
Amoco and Shell Oil, a deal would give Chevron a base to build a
major European refining operation.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for a prospective merger is an existing alliance
between Texaco and the Shell, the U.S. subsidiary of Royal
Dutch/Shell Group. In refining, the alliance now controls about 15
percent of the U.S. market, and is particularly strong on the West
Coast. This could set off antitrust concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
