<SLUG> BC-SOVIET-ATOMSPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR DENIES THAT MIT PROFESSOR WAS THE RUSSIAN SPY, KNOWN AS
PERSEUS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Russia)  By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeremy J. Stone, having accused a prominent American physicist
of spying for Moscow while involved in the making of the first
atomic bomb half a century ago, has now written him to accept his
denial that he was the Soviet atom spy whom the Russians called
Perseus.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, president of the Federation of American Scientists, a
private group in Washington, laid out his suspicions in a chapter
of his new memoir, ``Every Man Should Try: Adventures of a Public
Interest Activist'' (Public Affairs, 1999). The book referred to
the physicist only as a ``Dr. X,'' but Stone, after initially
refusing to identify him, did so once the physicist identified
himself to a reporter as the object of Stone's suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   The physicist, Dr. Philip Morrison of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, was accused by Stone of being a Soviet spy
whose code name, disclosed by the Russians at the end of the Cold
War, was Perseus.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter to Stone on Monday, Morrison listed ways he
differed from the spy's profile, as outlined in Stone's book and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the light of these facts, which I certainly cannot
contradict,'' Stone wrote in response on Tuesday, ``I can only
accept your denial that you are Perseus.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, however, Stone refused to discuss his letter or
whether he believed Morrison might have spied under another code
name, or none. ``I feel my letter speaks for itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone added that he hoped his book would help locate a Perseus
suspect who more closely fit the relevant facts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
