<SLUG> BC-NRA-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN AWARDED $4.4 MILLION IN NRA SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal jury in Philadelphia awarded $4.4 million Thursday to
an Iowa man who said he was assaulted last year by a security guard
for the National Rifle Association at a session of the group's
annual convention there.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also found the association liable for ``false light
publicity,'' a form of defamation, for a suggestion by the NRA
president, Charlton Heston, that the man had staged the incident at
the behest of opponents of the NRA leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we've been vindicated,'' said the plaintiff, Ken
Brodbeck, 40, an agricultural engineer from West Des Moines, who
was attacked for videotaping his wife, Sally, an NRA board member
at the time, as she spoke at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the rifle association said it would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA fought vigorously to defend itself from false
accusations,'' said the spokeswoman, Debbie Nauser.
</P>
<P>
   Such jury awards are frequently lowered on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred on June 8, the day Heston was elected the
association's 56th president.
</P>
<P>
   After the incident, in which Brodbeck and several witnesses said
a guard grabbed him by the throat and threw him down, Heston said,
``As an actor and director, I can tell you it was very bad
acting.''
</P>
<P>
   Guards had told Brodbeck that the taping violated NRA laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
