<HEADER>
A6408 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-DRUGS-CRIME-N     05-13 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-DRUGS-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY COMPARES U.S. AND ENGLISH DRUG CRIMES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, Chile, Netherlands, Scotland and South Africa)   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Illegal drugs drive crime in England just as they do in the
United States, says a two-nation survey that challenges assumptions
that addicted criminals are a particularly American problem.
</P>
<P>
   The report, being released Friday, found that among suspects
arrested in England, 55 percent said they had used a psychoactive
drug in the prior three days. That is slightly more than in
America, where just under half a comparable sampling said the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The type of crime and of drug use differs between the countries.
``We don't have the problem with gun-related violence,'' Dr.
Malcolm Ramsay, principal research officer for the Research
Development and Statistics Directorate of the British Home Office,
said in a telephone interview from London.
</P>
<P>
   In England, Ramsay said, ``robbery and burglary are rare as a
means of financing the purchase of drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoplifting accounted for one-third of the arrests of the
English heroin users sampled, Ramsay said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said 35 percent of the Americans arrested were
charged with personal crimes of violence like robbery compared to
16 percent of the English. The Americans were also more likely to
be arrested for drug or alcohol offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Suspects arrested in England use heroin and amphetamines at a
higher rate than people arrested in the United States, but cocaine
is more popular in the United States, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   A sample of 839 people arrested in England showed that they
appeared twice as likely as their American counterparts to have
used heroin and amphetamines. But more than 40 percent of 4,470
people arrested in five American cities tested positive for crack
or powder cocaine, compared with 9 percent of the English.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-page report is the first under a program that began last
year. The National Institute of Justice, the research arm of the
United States Justice Department, has used such statistics since
1987 to try to measure links between crime and drugs in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the institute, Jeremy Travis, said adopting the
same research methodology made possible a true comparison between
patterns of arrests in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a window into the world of offender behavior so we can
understand drug use, public health issues and socioeconomic factors
related to crime,'' Travis said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the high cocaine use, 68 percent of the suspected
criminals sampled in the United States were found using an illicit
drug, compared with 59 percent of the English sample. But the
English admitted using more kinds of drugs than the Americans. The
findings were based on urine tests, as well as the suspects'
statements.
</P>
<P>
   The preference for heroin among English offenders may stem from
England's position on trade routes of opium-producing countries
like Myanmar, Pakistan and Iran, the report said. Similarly,
Americans may use more cocaine because it comes from Colombia and
other Andean countries close to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Australia and Chile are collecting data to join the program, and
the Netherlands, Scotland and South Africa also plan to
participate, Travis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
