<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      05-13 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER'S TESTIMONY ATTACKED IN TORTURE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers defending two police officers in the Abner
Louima brutality case Thursday attacked the credibility of another
officer who testified against them, suggesting that he was
motivated by self-interest and had offered an initially shifting
account.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers questioned the witness, Detective Eric Turetzky,
sharply about what they termed inconsistencies between his
testimony at the trial Wednesday and his original account to
investigators days after prosecutors say Louima was tortured in the
restroom of a Brooklyn station house.
</P>
<P>
   And they sought to convince the jury that rather than being a
hero who came forward out of a sense of duty, Turetzky was acting
out of fear that he might be accused of wrongdoing himself.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky, who was a patrol officer in the 70th Precinct when
prosecutors say Louima was attacked in August 1997, testified
Wednesday that he had seen one of the accused officers, Justin
Volpe _ in an agitated state and with a stick in his hand _ escort
Louima from the restroom area to a holding cell.
</P>
<P>
   He told the jury in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn that
Louima's pants were around his ankles and that after placing Louima
in the cell, Volpe began swinging the stick ``like it was a sword
and hitting it against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that Volpe, in the restroom, had rammed a
stick into Louima's rectum and then his mouth, inflicting severe
internal injuries, while another officer, Charles Schwarz, held him
down. And the prosecutors charge that these two officers, and two
others also on trial, had earlier beaten Louima, a 32-year-old
Haitian immigrant, in a police car after his arrest in a melee
outside a nightclub in Flatbush.
</P>
<P>
   In cross-examining Turetzky on Thursday, Volpe's lawyer sought
to contrast the brisk and smooth account he had given Wednesday
with the uncertain and confused version he had originally given
investigators in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, cited Turetzky's interview with
police investigators on Aug. 15, 1997, six days after the reported
attack on Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a transcript, Kornberg showed that Turetzky had
admitted confusion, saying at one point that he was ``not clear''
on who took Louima to his cell, then saying, ``I think it's Officer
Volpe,'' and finally expressing certainty that it was Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky expressed no doubt that he had seen Volpe standing with
a stick near the restroom at the time. But Kornberg appeared to be
suggesting that the detective's initial uncertainty over who
escorted Louima from the restroom to the cell called into question
his entire testimony implicating Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   In his cross-examination of Turetzky, Schwarz's lawyer, Stephen
Worth, sought to puncture whatever image jurors might have
developed of a selfless whistle-blower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you consider yourself a hero cop who broke the blue wall of
silence?'' the lawyer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' the detective, 28, replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you acting out of self-interest?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you come forward?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth then pointed out that by the time Turetzky came forward,
two days had already passed since news reports of the alleged
attack had provoked public shock, denunciations from the mayor and
an intensive investigation. Volpe, in fact, had already been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Turetzky, who was still a patrol officer at the
time, had helped arrest Louima in the street melee, Worth said that
Turetzky knew he was soon to be questioned by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer suggested that fear of being accused of involvement
in the alleged assaults drove Turetzky to cooperate and called into
question his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it true, Detective Turetzky, that you were scared to
death what would happen to you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' the detective responded. But a moment later, he
said, ``I was concerned with my welfare, but not what was going to
happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Turetzky became the first officer to aid investigators in
the Louima case, police officials praised his cooperation as a sign
that the ``blue wall'' would not protect rogue officers.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir told reporters Thursday that
Turetzky ``is doing what all police officers should do, but it
takes a great deal of courage to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Officer Turetzky has shown a great deal of courage
right from the beginning,'' Safir said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
