<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NO. 8 TEAM LEADS NO. 1: VERY STRANGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I start laughing every time I think of the Monty
Python reunion last year, when they kicked over poor Graham
Chapman's ashes. Right on cue, out come the vacuum cleaners and the
brooms, and the lads start sweeping up their fallen comrade.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me started, or I won't be able to type.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny in the comics when the urchins knock off the rich
man's top hat with a snowball. Chris Rock is funny. It's funny when
Groucho lurches around with the cigar held behind his back. Who
walks that way in real life?
</P>
<P>
   It's also funny that the Knicks are leading the Heat, two games
to one. I am not rooting here for the New York team. In fact, the
Knicks disrupt my springtime big time if they do something bold
Friday night or Sunday. It's just funny, that's all.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, No. 8 is leading No. 1. Bugs Bunny is popping up
behind Elmer Fudd and asking, ``Anybody here seen any Winners
Within lately?'' Or maybe it's Elmer Fudd harassing Bugs Bunny. Man
bites rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody in the Knicks' camp is talking up such
nonsense. They're professionals. They know better. They know Tim
Hardaway must be hurting or he'd be able to shoot the ball. They
know how tenacious Pat Riley and Alonzo Mourning will be with the
season in peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are down, 2-1, and they're coming out with all
their warfare,'' the Knicks' Larry Johnson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That's not funny. That's an honest sports cliche. However, we _
the press, the civilians, the fans, with imagination, our human
taste for the bizarre _ we can see the banana peel lying out there
on the sidewalk. We can imagine the first-place team flopping
around in midair in the middle of a pratfall. Nothing personal, but
upsets are funny.
</P>
<P>
   The chattering teeth in the glass on the old Ernie Kovacs show
were funny. It's funny when David Letterman envisions his grubby
lonely loser weekends in Connecticut. (Maybe it's guy humor, but
it's funny to me.)
</P>
<P>
   It was funny Thursday when Jeff Van Gundy came out for his daily
news briefing and discovered somebody had moved the table out of
the glare of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a habit of creature,'' Van Gundy said, moving back to his
normal spot.
</P>
<P>
   Don't know if he reversed the words on purpose, or not. He gave
a shrug, and commenced his news conference.
</P>
<P>
   It was kind of funny when Jeff mimicked the rabid New York news
media for its mood swings about his team. ``They build 'em up after
Game 1, they crush 'em after Game 2,'' he said in a pretty good
singsong. And he was right. It's a goofy dance. It could go on for
a while.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is not funny over in New Jersey, where Ernie
Grunfeld watches the team he assembled, watches Latrell Sprewell
and Marcus Camby run through the suddenly porous Riley defense.
</P>
<P>
   However, I bet it looks and sounds funny in the corporate
headquarters of whoever owns the Knicks this quarter. I bet they
are doing Marx Brothers conniptions over this strange little turn
of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez, what if we get into the second round? What do we do
about the coach? How much money do we make if we get into the
Eastern finals? Who gets the celebrity seats if we get into the
finals? How much is the franchise worth at the moment? Is this for
real?''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows how to approach this business of a No. 8 team leading
a No. 1 team. If this were a normal season, there would be more of
a track record, but this is a 50-game aberration. The Knicks are
just getting to know one another's names.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing says it is difficult to think of the Knicks as a
mere No. 8 team ``given the way we finished the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the history of the NBA has a No. 8 team knocked off
a No. 1 team in the playoffs. That was in the spring of 1994 when
Denver (42-40) won a fifth game in Seattle (63-19).
</P>
<P>
   In this weird little season they have foisted upon us, there was
only a six-game difference between the Heat (33-17) and the Knicks
(27-23).
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is,'' Johnson said Thursday, ``Miami is a No. 1
and we are a No. 8. You can't dwell on it, but we are up, 2-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people will say none of this matters, in a weird season
with the Chicago Bulls having been dismantled. Any way you look at
it, No. 8 is home Friday night, in position to befuddle No. 1.
Funny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
