<SLUG> BC-BOEING-JOBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO ELIMINATE AS MANY AS 7,000 JOBS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (rk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After losing a key order for its F-15 Eagle jet fighter two
weeks ago, the Boeing Co. said Thursday that it planned to cut as
many as 7,000 jobs at its manufacturing plant in St. Louis by the
middle of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts, two-thirds of which will be white-collar jobs, will
reduce Boeing's total work force in St. Louis by one-third from the
current 20,000. The company also plans to consolidate its real
estate and take other steps to cuts its expenses there.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said that the cuts would be included in its previously
announced plan to reduce employment over the next two years. The
company, which is engaged in a long-term campaign to raise its
flagging profits, has said that it intends to cut as many as 46,000
jobs by 2001. The company now employs about 219,000, down from
231,000 at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement, while not unexpected, still surprised
some analysts because Boeing is awaiting a decision from Israel
about whether it will order more F-15s. ``Are they signaling
something?'' Byron K. Callan, an aerospace industry analyst at
Merrill Lynch, asked Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Downey, a Boeing spokesman, insisted that the company was
competing aggressively for the order from Israel, which is also
considering buying the F-16 fighter made by the Lockheed Martin
Corp. But after Greece passed over Boeing on April 30 in favor of
the F-16, Downey said that it became clear that Boeing would at the
very least have to suspend production of the F-15 next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this says is that because of the lead time related to the
order from Israel, we will have a gap in the line,'' he said. If
the order comes through, the gap might be as short as 12 months,
meaning that employment could rise again. But if it does not come
through, the cuts would last longer.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is also winding down the current generation of the F/A-18
Hornet, another aircraft made in St. Louis, creating another gap
before production of the new so-called Super Hornet begins.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is said to be considering buying 12 to 25 of the
twin-engine F-15s, which cost about $50 million each. The
single-engine F-16 is about half the price. Moshe Arens, the
Israeli defense minister, visited both Boeing and Lockheed earlier
this month. A decision is expected soon, but Arens did not say
when, and next week's election in Israel may delay an announcement.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,500 F-15s have been built in St. Louis since the
plane was introduced in 1972. The fighter is flown by air forces in
Israel, Saudi Arabia, Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's adequate now, but there are other planes on the horizon
that are as expensive but may be more modern,'' Callan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the job reductions should not alarm investors. ``I
wouldn't put this in the same catalog of woes as some of the things
that went on last year,'' he said, referring to production turmoil
at Boeing's flagship commercial airplane division.
</P>
<P>
   But the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers, whose members account for about one-third of the jobs to
be cut in St. Louis, may see things differently. The union and
Boeing are scheduled to begin new contract negotiations this
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
