</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF SERIES PAST MODERATE THE KNICKS' GIDDINESS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The New York Knicks streamed through the
corridor clapping their hands and letting out a whoop or two as
they crossed the threshold of a locker room that had a fraternity
house feel to it. Then there was the buzz killer.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson and Chris Childs lifted their voices to throw a
bucket of cold reality on the afterglow of the Knicks' Game 3
victory on Wednesday night, an unfathomable 97-73 dismantling of
the Miami Heat that gave them a 2-1 edge in the three-of-five-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   After riding a preposterous 32-2 run, the Knicks are on the
verge of becoming only the second eighth-seeded in 15 years to
advance past a No. 1 seed. (The Denver Nuggets eliminated the
Seattle SuperSonics in 1994.) They are one home victory away, with
Game 4 at Madison Square Garden on Friday night. The possibility of
achieving the feat at their rival's expense makes it that much more
tantalizing.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson and Childs remember what wicked turns can snarl a
path that seems so clear. Two years ago, they were part of a Knicks
team that seemed so unselfish, dominant and unlimited in its
playoff potential. Two years ago, the Knicks had clicked together
like Legos to form a team that was unstoppable in sweeping
Charlotte, and the Knicks were one home victory away from
eliminating the Heat and advancing to the conference final.
</P>
<P>
   Then Charlie Ward boxed out P.J. Brown with 1 minute 53 seconds
left in Game 5. Brown responded by flipping Ward over like a
flapjack onto the Heat's court, and the Knicks mindlessly left the
bench only to receive suspensions that were handed out like
leaflets. Two short-handed playoff games later, the Knicks were
left devastated by their bitter elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry and Chris talked briefly, and basically said that we
don't want to go back to Miami,'' Marcus Camby said Thursday after
the team practiced at SUNY-Purchase. ``We have to go out and close
it out. We don't want to be in a Game 5 situation, where everything
is on the line. And especially not in a Knick-Heat series because
anything can happen down there in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything is possible. With that, the cautionary tales were being
told in every corner of the Knicks' practice facility, like
campfire stories. There were cameras and microphones circling every
player who could point to a moment this year when the enigmatic
Knicks let their complacency get the best of them. Like Game 2 of
this series, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let down, we sure did,'' Johnson said. ``The third game was
an excellent game for us. That said, if anyone was coming in here
today with their shoulders up and their heads held high over what a
great game we played, the tape showed different.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the jostling and physical nature of this rivalry have
not ignited the kind of series-altering moments that have occurred
in a past the Knicks are not likely to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, they outplayed us badly down there in Game 5,
and then we know what happened after that,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy
said. ``We just have to be committed to winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning would leave the once dysfunctional Knicks with an
invitation to the second round. ``When you have an opportunity to
do something like this,'' Childs said, ``you want to take advantage
of it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
