</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS GORE IS `SMART' NOT TO MENTION HIM ON CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE-CAMPAIGN) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his most extensive comments thus far on how the
2000 presidential race is unfolding, President Clinton on Thursday
night discussed his campaign tips for Vice President Al Gore and
said it was perfectly understandable that the vice president rarely
uttered his name on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a telephone interview, said he had advised Gore that
it was unrealistic for him to be steeped in the details of running
a campaign while also serving as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no person on the face of the earth who can be both
the most active vice president in history and an active candidate
for president,'' he explained, suggesting that Gore step back from
the day-to-day campaign minutiae.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he told Gore not to retreat from boasting about his
accomplishments _ and to mix more with voters. ``He's got a lot to
be proud of in his record,'' he said. ``I told him to go out and
have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was hurt that Gore, in his campaign appearances,
usually did not mention him, the president said, ``Oh, goodness no.
I think he should be very proud of what we accomplished together
because he played a big role in a lot of the economic progress we
made and on a whole range of issues. We should be proud of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he continued, ``people need to look at him when he's
out there campaigning as the person who would be the next
president. I would advise him to spend most of his time on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked again if Gore's failure to mention him was appropriate,
the president said, ``I think it's smart. And I really agree with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hesitated when asked about the strength of Gore's sole
rival for the nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
``I don't know,'' he said. ``We've not talked about that very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for his observations about Bradley, whose candidacy has
recently been taken far more seriously by leading Democrats,
Clinton said: ``I don't know because I've been so covered up in
Kosovo. He's an intelligent man. He's an interesting man. But I
have always believed that the vice president would win the whole
thing. Not just the nomination. That's what I've always believed.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he was not unnerved by early polls
showing that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas would defeat Gore by more
than 20 points in a general election matchup or by polls showing
that Elizabeth Dole would also defeat Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm less concerned about that than nearly everybody else,''
Clinton said. ``I bet if you go back and look at the polls in 1959
or look at President Bush's polls in 1987, I bet you whoever the
best-known Democrat was in 1959 was running way ahead of Richard
Nixon. So I'm just not concerned about that.'' In fact, the 1960
Democratic nominee, John F. Kennedy, narrowly defeated Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this thing will shake out. My view is that he is doing
well, that he is addressing the issues in an appropriate way. He
has now addressed the issue of his campaign structure in an
appropriate way. I just want him to get out and have a good time,
talk about what he would do in the next four years, just enjoy
himself and let people see him the way I see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has worked for years behind the scenes to help Gore,
with whom he is close personally. ``I will do whatever I can and
however I can best be helpful,'' he said of his role. ``I've got a
job, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his exact involvement should be, he said, ``He's got
to make that decision and that call. I'll do whatever I can. He's
going to win this on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he sympathizes with the run of tough publicity that
Gore has had to endure. ``You know as well as I do that every
presidential campaign is part joy and part agony,'' he said. ``I
took my licks in 1992. He's the front-runner, so he's the
convenient target for everyone. I expect him to do very well the
whole way, and I feel very good about where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton kept returning to the value of Gore's true
personality. ``I think it's very important to recognize that as
smart as he is and as energetic as he is, he's a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   The president added of the politician who has been by his side
(if not behind him) since 1992: ``I care a lot about him. I know
him as few people in America do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
