</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RILEY AT THE CROSSROADS AS THE UNTHINKABLE LOOMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Riley left New York in 1995 for power, money and
sun. Packing his vision of a championship team, he arrived in Miami
and found a franchise center, an improvisational point guard, role
players with high pain thresholds and the ability to discern
between being ``a'' winner and being ``the'' winner.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Riley, the coach with the highest winning
percentage in the National Basketball Association, cannot shake the
Knicks. Game 4 is Friday night at Madison Square Garden against the
Knicks, and the unthinkable looms: being eliminated again in the
first round by his former team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we've worked for, everything we've talked about is
on the line,'' Riley said the after the Heat were run off the
Garden floor in a 97-73 loss. ``We have an mvp candidate, veteran
warriors on this team, one of the greatest clutch players in the
history of the NBA with Tim Hardaway, role players that help us win
games on a regular basis. We have a great defensive foundation. We
are a winning team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the team that got me here. This is the team that will
get me over the top, or we're all going to go down together.''
</P>
<P>
   The house that Riley built in South Florida has been pounded
mercilessly by the Knicks. Its confidence shaken and its point
guard hurting, the Heat has been exposed as a structurally flawed
team. Facing elimination, the Heat players walked glumly into
Madison Square Garden Thursday for perhaps their last practice of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, with his bruised knee, is having a miserable series.
An aging Dan &QC; Majerle staggers around like a woozy prizefighter with
a bad shoulder, refusing to drop from a barrage of overhand rights.
No Heat player can throttle Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell for
more than one game, and Jamal Mashburn cannot make an important
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' said P.J. Brown. ``It's just
amazing to see how well they shoot, how well they play against us.
You would think they're the No. 1 seed and we're the No. 8 seed.
We're kind of back on our heels. They have an amazing high level of
confidence when they play the Miami Heat. And it's been like that
almost every game. I don't know what it is, but they get the job
done when they play us.''
</P>
<P>
   If the bunker is empty, Riley's players were not admitting it.
Alonzo Mourning as much as predicted victory, saying his team was
using Game 4 as a potential steppingstone for a deciding Game 5 on
Sunday at Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two more games to play,'' Mourning said. ``We are
going to start out with the one on Friday and finish with the one
on Sunday. That's the way we're looking at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the influence of Sprewell (19 points a game) in the
series, Mourning said: ``It's the same team. Nothing has changed.
They run the same plays. Sprewell has had some good ball games. We
haven't done anything to alter it. The second game we came out a
little more aggressive defensively to alter his play and Allan
Houston's play.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as a Sprewell factor, to tell you the truth, we're
shooting ourselves in the foot. We know what we have to and we're
not doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Miami is eliminated Friday night, it may be the last time
several players on the roster wear a Heat uniform. Other than
Mourning, who has carried the team on his huge shoulders for three
games, expect Riley to keep almost no one safe from the trading
block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching other games,'' Riley said, ``watching Sacramento beat
the Jazz last night, watching Portland beat Phoenix, watching
Milwaukee go down to the wire against Indiana _ I mean, the Lakers
with a new, refound identity and enthusiasm. There's a different
freshness. There's a new kid on the block. And the new kid on the
block is hunger, excitement, enthusiasm and a chance to perform on
a platform they've never been on before.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I see that being the difference from some of the teams
that have been there before, that are sort of used to the routine
and getting into the playoffs and having good regular-season
records. Those teams are running into some ferocious energy on the
part of teams that may have been out of it, and all of a sudden the
hunger and enthusiasm is rising above the talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, who doubles as the team president, stubbornly believed in
his veterans, enough so that he did not give Riley, the coach, a
bona fide third offensive option in the off season. He thought
Golden State asked too much for Sprewell and left the bidding to
the Knicks. He made overtures to the Lakers about Eddie Jones and
Elden Campbell and explored several other deals, but he never
pulled the trigger to upgrade his team offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're into building a team,'' he said. ``We went through the
season with this basketball team because we wanted to see it whole
in the playoffs, and if this is what I've seen in the playoffs,
then we got a lot of work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a winning team. We're a good program. We're building
something good down there. But this isn't good at all. It doesn't
mean anything to win three Atlantic Division titles if we lose in
the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Dilapidated, leaky and losing value every day, this is the house
that Pat built. Yet it was built with integrity and character, and
until it becomes unlivable Riley cannot tear it down, for that
would be to admit that his way was the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if another loss to the Knicks would be the season's
enduring image.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's going to happen,'' Riley said. ``But it's up to
us to objectively evaluate exactly what happened and why it
happened and then go from there. We're still in a building process
of championship dreams. And right now those dreams are getting a
little bit cloudy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
