<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAGIC-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
76ERS BEAT THE MAGIC WITH SPEED AND STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The coach owns two NBA championship rings. The
starting power forward owns three. Two of their leading scorers
have finals experience, and the Orlando Magic is far more seasoned
than its upstart opponents, the Philadelphia 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Magic's maturity was nowhere to be found Thursday night
at the First Union Center. Whatever savvy Orlando brought to
Philadelphia crumbled beneath the pressure of a smothering 76ers
assault that was sparked by quickness and enforced by strength.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting Orlando's call to brawl, the youthful 76ers pummeled
their guests by 97-85 to take a 2-1 lead in this best-of-5-game
series. Game 4 is here Saturday afternoon, and if the third-seeded
Magic want to avoid elimination, they had better bring more mettle
to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway, who along with teammate Nick Anderson helped
Orlando reach the NBA finals in 1995, had fear in his eyes. Horace
Grant, who won three titles with Michael Jordan, was no enforcer on
this night, and Chuck Daly, the celebrated coach of Detroit's Bad
Boys, could not come up with a scheme to solve Philadelphia's
abrasive defense.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Allen Iverson, the league-leading scorer who was bumped
and jostled into an erratic 13-point performance in Orlando's Game
2 victory, dominated.
</P>
<P>
   Redeeming himself with a vengeance, he scored 33 points and used
his breathtaking quickness to put expressions of fright on the
Magic players' faces and generally take them out of their offense.
</P>
<P>
   Swarming the passing lanes, Iverson set an NBA playoff record
for steals, with 10. His ninth theft, which set the mark, came less
than five minutes into the third quarter and ended with a
fashionable two-handed dunk that gave the 76ers a 56-39 lead. Two
more slams in the next two minutes buried the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Dogged by the defensive pressure of the faster 76ers, Hardaway
committed seven turnovers, including four of the Magic's 20 in the
first half. Orlando finished with 27 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia made 14 steals to break the game open by halftime,
taking leads of 23-15 after one quarter and 46-31 after two. As
careless as Hardaway was with the ball, his backcourt mate, Darrell
Armstrong, was worse, committing nine turnovers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
