<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYERS ARE SELECTIVE AT CHRISTIE'S MODERN ART SALE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A sophisticated group of collectors came to
Christie's sale of 20th-century art Thursday night prepared to buy,
but only if the price was right. While clearly the market is hungry
for modern art, bidders for the most part were a controlled group,
willing to stretch their budgets but only so far. The sale totaled
$62.6 million, below the sale's low $64 million estimate. Of the 62
works offered, 10 failed to find buyers.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes were glued to the bidding for Jasper Johns' ``Two
Flags,'' a 1973 painting made of two sets of three canvas panels
each that depicts two vertical flags in red, white and blue. The
work _ the most expensive sale of the evening _ came with a past
auction history. In 1989, at the height of the auction market,
Sotheby's in New York sold it for $11 million. Before the sale,
some experts said they thought the $7 million to $10 million
estimate was too high. Two bidders tried to buy the painting which
sold to Larry Gagosian, the Manhattan dealer, for $7.1 million,
making it the evening's most expensive picture.
</P>
<P>
   The evening got off to a brisk start because Christie's shrewdly
began with a cohesive collection of modern art put together over
the last 20 years by a Detroit couple, Maurice and Margo Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've seen this week is the way people pay a premium for
works of art coming from special collections,'' said Franck Giraud,
head of Christie's 19th- and 20th-century art departments.
</P>
<P>
   Three bidders tried to buy one of the Cohens' best paintings,
Leger's ``Three Women with a Bouquet,'' (1922) which combines an
elongated nude figure with two clothed women. Estimated to sell for
$5 million to $7 million, it sold to an unidentified telephone
buyer for less, making $4.4 million. Experts had thought it would
bring a higher price because of its similarity to ``The Big
Breakfast'' which was painted a year earlier and which hangs in the
permanent collection of the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   The Cohens collected the work of several artists in depth, among
them Miro, Calder and Dubuffet. Miro's ``The Hope,'' which the
artist painted in 1946 as an expression of joy at the end of World
War II, was estimated to bring $2 million to $3 million. It became
one of the evening's top sellers, bringing $4.5 million to another
unidentified telephone bidder. Five people wanted to take home
``Woman being Stabbed by the Sun,'' a 1939 gouache that relates to
a painting on view at the Peggy Guggenheim Museum in Venice. After
a serious bidding war it finally sold to a telephone bidder for
$1.4 million, twice its $700,000 low estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Four bidders also wanted ``Painting (The Circus Horse)'' (1927)
a Surrealist painting on a brilliant blue background that was
estimated at $1.8 million to $2.5 million. Eventually the hammer
fell at $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Cohens also owned a number of works by Calder. Among the
best was a standing mobile, ``Red Post, Black Leaves,'' which was
estimated to fetch $600,000 to $800,000. Abigail Asher, a Manhattan
dealer, bought the sculpture for $937,500. Another standing mobile
sold for way above its estimate. ``Hanging Apricot,'' (1950) was
thought to sell for $500,000 to $700,000. William Acquavella,
another Manhattan dealer, was willing to pay $992,500.
</P>
<P>
   Dubuffets made up a large group of the Cohens holdings. ``Secret
Dances of the Beard'' is a small ink collage of a standing man with
a beard from a series the artist executed in 1959. Four bidders
made a serious effort to buy the collage which finally sold for
$173,000, nearly three times its high estimate of $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also from 1959, ``The Vase of Beard,'' in which a beard is
juxtaposed with a vase _ an improbable fusion between two disparate
elements _ was thought to sell for $1.2 million to $1.6 million,
Marc Blondeau, a Parisian dealer, bought it for $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade earlier, in 1948, Dubuffet painted ``Sahara''
from a trip he made to North Africa. It was estimated to sell for
$900,000 to $1.2 million, and was bought by a telephone bidder for
$1.9 million. An early gouache, pen and ink, ``The Nude Cyclist''
inspired by a bicycle trip that the artist took in 1943 through the
South of France, was thought to sell for $100,000 to $150,000. It
sold for twice its high estimate. A telephone buyer, bidding
through Giraud, paid $332,500.
</P>
<P>
   The Cohen collection was by far the evening's success story,
making $22.1 million, above its $16.5 low estimate. The rest of the
evening, however, was touch and go.
</P>
<P>
   Matisse has been a particularly popular artist recently. His
``The Safrano Roses (Still Life in Front of an Open Window, Nice,
Place Charles-Felix)'' from 1925, one of a group of sun-filled
still lifes the artist painted in Nice, was estimated to bring $3
million to $4 million. There were many interested takers and the
painting sold for $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 plus 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   One record price was set last night. It was for Henry Moore's
``Reclining Figure (1969-1970.) Robert Mnuchin, a Manhattan dealer,
bought it for $4 million, $1 million above its high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I contributed to one of the strongest prices of the evening,''
said Mnuchin after the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Mitchell-Innes, another Manhattan dealer said that ``even
mediocre pictures did well.'' But, she added, ``The biggest problem
these days is that good property changes hands so fast it is
distressing. It means works aren't reaching the auction rooms and
for dealers, it's hard to keep any inventory.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
