<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TEAM PRICES SOARING, INDIANS GO UP FOR SALE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ohio)   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tantalized by escalating franchise prices, Richard Jacobs put
his Cleveland Indians up for sale Thursday, less than a year after
taking the team public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say this,'' said Jacobs, a 73-year-old real estate
developer. ``Somebody said Steinbrenner said his team is worth $1
billion and he had a buyer. And I said, `If that buyer has a
brother, give him my number.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The news that Jacobs may sell drove Indians stock up by 63.5
percent, to close at $16.25. Since going public last June at $15 a
share, the stock has underperformed the market, sinking to a low of
$5.375 a share. Based on Thursday's closing price, the team is
worth about $224 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll go for more than that,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dolan, a Cleveland lawyer whose brother, Charles, is the
chairman of Cablevision, said the plan to sell the Indians came as
a ``real surprise.'' In a statement, he said, ``It is premature to
say whether or not I am a prospective buyer.'' Recently, Larry
Dolan unsuccessfully bid for the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said he was not selling for estate-planning reasons. In
fact, he had tried to diversify the company by adding real estate
properties like hotels or television and radio stations, which
might have made the stock more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he felt the easiest way to boost the stock was to sell
the team,'' said Jeffrey Phillips, a vice president at Houlihan
Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin, a Chicago-based investment banking firm that
specializes in sports.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs was motivated to consider selling by the prices paid
last year for other Major League Baseball teams, like the Los
Angeles Dodgers, at $311 million, and the Texas Rangers, at $250
million. Earlier this year, the Yankees were valued at $600 million
for their merger with the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs watched as the National Football League sold the
expansion Cleveland Browns for $530 million _ Jacobs was an early
candidate in the team's auction _ and kept an eye on the pending
$800 million sale of the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Abe Pollin, 75, sold the Washington Capitals and a
small stake in the Washington Wizards and the MCI Center for about
$200 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any interest in disposing of the franchise until
recently,'' Jacobs said. ``But there's a market for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins' sale by the Jack Kent Cooke estate has been a
rancorous affair that has featured the withdrawal of one contracted
buyer, Howard Milstein, and the entrance of Daniel Snyder, one of
his partners, as the likely purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs said he wanted to control the process and keep the
Indians in Cleveland. If he is unhappy with the prices offered or
the suitors, he said, he will yank the team off the market. But
Jacobs has hired two investment banking firms, Goldman Sachs Group
and McDonald Investments, to identify buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the price, Jacobs will profit handsomely. He and his
late brother, David, acquired the once-moribund team in 1986 for
$36 million. When the team went public, Jacobs collected $60
million from selling four million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jacobs was paid a $467,424 salary. General Manager
John Hart earned $600,000 and received a bonus of $195,692.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine a future owner wanting to flee
Cleveland or lose the financial foundation of revenues that flow
from the publicly owned Jacobs Field. The five-year-old stadium has
sold out 308 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the team earned operating income of $12.7 million on
revenues of $144.5 million, which included $55.8 million for
tickets, $16.2 million for concessions, $9.4 million for luxury
suite and club seat rentals and $9.8 million for advertising.
Playoff revenues totaled $8.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Indians have maximized most existing revenues,
Jacobs said the team expected to benefit greatly when baseball's
national television contracts expire after the 2000 season and from
selling naming rights to the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do better than they've been doing,'' said Andy
Zimbalist, an economics professor at Smith College. ``They have
excess demands for all tickets, and they've thought of merging with
the Cavaliers into a holding company that would present a united
front to sell TV rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Since moving into Jacobs Field, the Indians' record is 464-310,
a winning percentage of .599. The team lost the 1995 and 1997 World
Series and the American League Championship Series to the Yankees
last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
