<HEADER>
A6423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CONGRESS-GUNS-NY     05-13 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONGRESS-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SENATE AND THE NRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, May 14:
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's first instinct in responding to April's high school
massacre in Littleton, Colo., was to obey the gun lobby by ducking
any crackdown on weapons and, incredibly, even relaxing existing
gun controls. Fortunately, this action was so perverse, so out of
touch with the tides of public concern, that it triggered a
backlash that has forced a partial retreat.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the Republican-led Senate, jumping as high as the
National Rifle Association demanded, killed a proposal to close the
egregious loophole in the Brady law that allows criminals and
juveniles to purchase firearms at gun shows without any background
check. Then it approved an amendment offered by Sen. Larry Craig,
R-Idaho, an NRA board member, that would significantly weaken
existing gun control laws by opening big new loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Coming just three weeks after the tragic events at Columbine
High School, where all four weapons used in the massacre were
bought at gun shows, this outcome was an insult to all Americans
concerned about the ease with which troubled youngsters can now
obtain weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, under pressure from President Clinton and
Republican colleagues who had second thoughts, like Sens. John
McCain of Arizona, Susan Collins of Maine and Gordon Smith of
Oregon, Craig reversed course on gun shows by introducing a
amendment _ itself shot through with loopholes _ to require
background checks for firearms sales at such shows.
</P>
<P>
   But this ``fix'' would not rescind other gifts to the NRA
designed to ease gun access that are buried in his original
measure. These include a new pawnshop loophole that will allow
convicted felons to get their guns out of hock without any
background check, and a provision that will allow licensed gun
dealers to sell their wares at gun shows outside their home states,
making it harder to effectively police shady gun dealers.
</P>
<P>
   This fight is not yet over. Taking advantage of the backlash
against gun-lobby politics, gun control advocates Thursday
successfully added some important provisions to a broader juvenile
crime bill, including a ban on juvenile purchase and possession of
assault rifles and large-capacity ammunition magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott is no friend of gun control.
But given the embarrassing events of the past two days, and the
public's strong interest in seeing Congress seriously address the
problem of youth and guns, he should allow an extensive
freestanding debate, and recorded votes, on all the items in the
Democratic package.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
