<HEADLINE>
CRIME DOWN IN NEW YORK CITY SUBWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While the subway system may be a long way from
shedding its image as a symbol of urban menace, new police
statistics show that underground crime has dropped precipitously in
the first four months of the year, continuing an eight-year decline
that has been steeper than the city's overall drop in crime.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such high-profile crimes as the shoving of two riders to
the tracks in that period, crime experts say the most telling
measures of crime in the subways are different from those elsewhere
in the city, in part because murder and rape have always been rare
in the subway system. The new figures show that the most common
types of subway crime, like pickpocketing and common assault, have
dropped the most sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with New York City Transit and transit watchdogs
attribute the drop in part to improved police work and in part to
the impact of a major increase in subway ridership. They say that a
new-found safety in numbers, and perhaps a renewed sense of
civility, may be reinforcing the downward trend, in which six
categories of felonies dropped 15 percent in the first third of
1999 compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police are doing a better job, and people are looking out
for each other,'' said Michael T. Doyle, a transportation planner
for the New York City Transit Riders Council, a state-funded
watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also the sheer factor of numbers,'' he added. ``With
so many people riding the subways, its is hard for the criminals
not to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The police figures released Thursday showed that in a system
serving 3.4 million riders daily, there were were 547 robberies
reported, or 4.6 a day, during the first four months of the year, a
drop of 17 percent from the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Grand larceny, a category that includes the theft of wallets,
credit cards, jewelry and other property worth over $1,000, was
more commonplace, the police said, with six such crimes reported
each day, but dropped 12 percent over last year. The other of the
most common subway crimes, assaults, was least prevalent, with and
average of 1.1 reported to the police each day, a drop of 18
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
