<SLUG> BC-SMITH-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `REAL' SIDE OF SPEAKERS IS WHAT BUSINESS AUDIENCES WANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the idea of giving speeches gives you quaky knees and
nightmares, Geoffrey Lane has some reassuring thoughts for you.
</P>
<P>
   Think Roberto Benigni, the effusive Italian actor, at the
Academy Awards. Just be yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The highly polished presentation speech is rapidly becoming
obsolete in an era when audiences demand more interaction with
their speakers, Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, making presentations is a growing part of many
people's jobs. People present their ideas to staff, customers,
regulators, community members and a host of other audiences, often
on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to effectively present an idea and connect with an
audience is a critical skill in today's work environment, said
Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, whose NuMethod Education Inc. training business is based
in Vancouver, B.C., has spent more than two decades talking for a
living. Now he's teaching others new ways of approaching public
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ironic twist for Lane, whose speaking career nearly
tanked after his first time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shook and I sweated,'' he said. ``I died that awful social
death everybody fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he got off the stage, though, he was fine presenting his
ideas on a one-to-one basis with audience members.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered that if he applied the same relaxed, informal
style of speaking he used in those face-to-face conversations when
he got back up in front of groups, the response of the audience was
much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience wants to know who you are, and what you care
about,'' he said. ``So don't waste your time trying to be
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Most audiences are sophisticated. They're experts at getting
information quickly. What they want from a speaker is something
they can't get off the Web _ a sense of personal connection and a
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of ``public speaking,'' which connotes standing up
before a vast auditorium of people, has changed, he said. Most
speaking is done to groups of 30 or fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   That demands a more intimate, ``real'' presentation style.
</P>
<P>
   People are put off when speakers are so formal that their
natural style doesn't show through, he said. The best-remembered
Oscar speeches, for example, are those when the true personality of
the speaker shines. Benigni made an indelible impression with his
infectious enthusiasm. Gwyneth Paltrow made an equally strong one
by revealing her personal ties to her family, something that
mattered deeply to her.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers make those personal connections with the audience by
letting their guard down, showing people who they really are, and
sharing relevant personal stories, Lane said. Most people are the
most persuasive when they're being themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   People can also improve their presentations by knowing their
audiences. ``You have to understand their demographics, their
psychology, how they listen and what their intention is in
listening to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will come to get educated. Some will come to get a
few pointers to support what they already know, and some come so
they can criticize you later.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing at the outset helps you tailor your message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every speaker should have a purpose and objective,'' he said.
``The reason you do research about the audience is so you can craft
the message so it will be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   An engineer presenting the environmental impact of a project,
for example, would present the information differently to a panel
of regulators than to a meeting of community members. The
information may be the same, but the presentations will take into
account the different needs of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   And there are some other tricks Lane has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Today's audiences want to be informed and entertained, he said.
There's nothing duller than someone who stands in one place and
lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Moving around, making eye contact with the audience, laughing
and using humor where appropriate will help people connect with
what you're telling them. Involving the audience helps as well.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell jokes. Most people aren't that good at telling them,
he said. Bob Hope once admitted he sometimes practices his
one-liners for years to get them right.
</P>
<P>
   And one more thing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   End on a strong note.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
