<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-AMERICAN-AIRLINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT SUES AMERICAN AIRLINES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
and LAURA GOLDBERG 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Justice Department on Thursday accused
American Airlines of engaging in predatory practices to drive three
small airlines away from its hub at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Justice officials contend American, the nation's second-largest
carrier, saturated markets with flights and slashed fares in a
systematic attempt to snuff out competition from start-up carriers
Vanguard Airlines, SunJet International and Western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``American crossed a fundamental line,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Joel Klein. ``It operated at a loss for one reason only _
to kill off a competitor so that it could then more-than-recoup
those short-term losses through monopoly pricing.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials said they were ``bewildered and
disappointed'' by the Justice Department action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than enforcing established legal standards in an
appropriate case, the government has chosen to overreach and
improperly attempt to extend the law to punish actions that have
consistently been found by the courts to be lawful and beneficial
to consumers,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth, Texas--based carrier argued the Justice
Department was attempting to enforce a standard that would ``take
away from consumers the ability to choose between two
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Small, start-up carriers have been complaining for years about
the major airlines' tactics at their ``fortress hub'' airports.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department suit, filed Thursday in U.S. District
Court in Wichita, Kan., represents the first time antitrust
enforcers have gone to court over an airline's behavior at a hub
airport since the industry was first deregulated 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shot across the bow, warning all airlines not to
overreact when a small guy enters the market,'' Ray Neidl, an
airline analyst with ING Barings Furman Selz, said of the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Justice officials are known to have been investigating at least
three other carriers _ United Airlines, Delta Air Lines and
Northwest Airlines. Klein confirmed Thursday that investigations of
other airlines are continuing, but he declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   American is far-and-away the largest carrier operating at DFW,
the nation's third-busiest airport. American offers more than 700
flights from DFW daily, serving 70 percent of the nonstop
passengers flying between that airport and other cities, the
Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   In their suit _ the product of an 18-month investigation _
Justice officials say American executives first became concerned
about competition from low-cost carriers back in 1993. Airline
managers feared these new entrant, low-cost carriers could threaten
nearly $1.5 billion in revenues annually, the government alleges.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1995, Kansas City, Mo.-based Vanguard launched air
service between DFW and Kansas City, with three round-trip flights
daily. American operated eight round-trip flights _ controlling 65
percent of the market _ while Delta offered six.
</P>
<P>
   By April, American had matched Vanguard's fares, dropping its
prices from an average $108 each way to $80 each way. Vanguard cut
back its service to one round trip a day, and in May, Delta dropped
all of its service between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
   American then beefed up its service, adding six new round-trip
flights daily. Company documents indicate American's plan was ``to
drive (Vanguard) from the market,'' the Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Vanguard withdrew from that market. American began
reducing service, dropping from 14 flights daily to 10 a day by
July 1996, the suit notes.
</P>
<P>
   American also kicked up its fares, with prices for a one-way
ticket ranging from $112 to $147. The route was transformed from
one of the carrier's worst performers to ``best in the West,''
Justice officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in September 1996, Vanguard announced plans to expand its
DFW service once again, with nonstop flights to Kansas City,
Phoenix and Cincinnati. The carrier was already flying to Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   American responded by expanding service to Kansas City and
Wichita, accelerating plans for new service to Phoenix and resuming
previously abandoned service to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard dropped the plan, and American again raised its fares,
some to Cincinnati by as much as 80 percent, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   When Smyrna, Ga.-based SunJet, a public charter operator, and
Western Pacific also tried to expand at DFW, American likewise
added service in effort to force them from the market, the Justice
Department contends.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard hailed the suit as vindication of a position it has
argued for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a move that will preserve open competition throughout
the industry and help consumers and new entrant airlines alike,''
Robert ``Rocky'' Spane, Vanguard's chief executive officer, said in
a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard plans to begin service between Chicago and Buffalo,
N.Y., a market American serves, with four flights daily. Vanguard
officials said they will be watching closely for any behavior they
would consider predatory.
</P>
<P>
   SunJet said it was pleased the Justice Department took into
account the harm it had suffered. Western Pacific is believed to be
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit comes as the airline industry is already under
scrutiny for its customer service. At least four so-called
passenger rights bill have been introduced in Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater called the suit ``good
for consumers'' and ``consistent with this department's efforts to
prevent major carriers from using anti-competitive tactics to drive
low-fare carriers from their hub markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials are currently readying new guidelines
on airline competition, proposals they plan to send up to Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Trippler, a consumer advocate for the on-line travel
service 1travel.com, said ``The entire hub set-up could really come
under attack if this thing succeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers themselves must accept some responsibility for the
fate of new carriers, Trippler said. If passengers want new
carriers to stay in business, they must fly them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
