<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PRESSURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS COACH UNFAZED BY HIGH EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Ken Hitchcock leaned back in his chair and
laughed a loud ``Hah!''_ the kind of laugh that clears the throat,
the kind of laugh that clears the soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure? Is this pressure?'' the Stars coach said, answering
a question with a question. ``I guess you could call it pressure,
but the playoffs are always pressure. This is no different than any
year of my career. I've been through this at every level. Yeah,
there's pressure, but you have to be able to thrive on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off consecutive overtime losses and heading into a
crucial Game 5 of their best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals
series with the St. Louis Blues tomorrow night at Reunion Arena,
the Stars have earned the pressure of the playoffs. It can be read
in newspapers, heard on radio talk shows and seen on national
television, where even hockey's greatest experts are starting to
dissect the Stars to find out if there's something to accusations
that the team can't step up its play from the regular season _
where it twice has won the Presidents' Trophy _ to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the series is tied at 2-2 and the Stars still hold the
home-ice advantage, experts and fans are asking the Stars for a
sign _ pondering whether the Stars need to beat the Blues
convincingly to prove themselves a worthy contender for the Stanley
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if it goes to seven games, just so long as we
win,'' Hitchcock said. Nobody's talking about what will happen if
the Blues don't advance past the second round _ they don't have any
expectations to make it to the Western Conference finals. If the
Stars' lose, however, people in North Texas will want answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just life,'' Stars winger Mike Keane said. ``That's
life outside the rink and outside the room. And that's life we
can't worry about right now. Our life is on the ice, and on the ice
it's a dogfight between two teams who expect to win.'']
</P>
<P>
   But should the Stars worry themselves about what others think?
Certainly, North Texas will be putting even more pressure on the
Stars' _ the one shining chance at a championship for local teams.
As Game 5 approaches, the Stars' collective city will get even more
tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the city's problem, not mine,'' Hitchcock said. ``My
problem is to get every ounce of potential out of every player,
that's my goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will win this series, I have that confidence,''
Hitchcock said. ``But if we don't, what are you going to do? You
can't go worrying about what's going to happen if you lose, then
you already have one foot in the grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he can't understand why people continue to paint
the Blues as such an underdog. They allowed the fewest shots on
goal of any NHL team (23.5) per game, they had the second-best
penalty-killing unit and the third- best power play. They also were
able to post a 37-32-13 record despite using five goaltenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good team, this has been a good team for years and
it's a team that gives us a lot of problems,'' Hitchcock said.
``Can't people see that?''
</P>
<P>
   What people see is the Stars had 114 points during the regular
season and the Blues had 87. What people see is that they've never
heard of Pavol Demitra, Michal Handzus and Jochen Hecht, no matter
how good they are. What people see is that a team with Mike Modano
and Joe Nieuwendyk and Brett Hull and Pat Verbeek should be able to
score, should be able to run a decent power play, should be able to
advance past the blue-collar Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every team is going to win, and first seeds get knocked
off all the time in hockey,'' Keane said. ``Look at New Jersey,
look at Ottawa, look at Philadelphia. I mean, this is a sport where
it's not always the top teams that win, and you obviously are aware
of that as a player. But at the same time, do you want to be the
team that might have a chance to pull an upset or do you want to be
the team that is supposed to win, that carries the expectations of
winning?''
</P>
<P>
   Keane said the Stars don't mind the pressure. Several of the
players carried it every day when they used to play for the
Montreal Canadiens. Keane, a former Canadiens captain, said it was
no different than when he helped the Colorado Avalanche win the
Stanley Cup in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we got \Rgoalie\S Patrick \RRoy\S, it was `All
right, go out and win the thing,'' Keane said. ``That was the
expectation, and we were able to meet that expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   But in doing so, a team has to answer key challenges, and Game 5
will provide just that. of the final three games at home.] To hold
their home-ice advantage, they need to assert themselves tomorrow
night. A win at Reunion Arena, where the Stars are 4-0 in the
playoffs and where they went 29-8-4 during the regular season _ the
best home record in the league _ puts the pressure squarely back on
the Blues. A loss by the Stars means they'll have to win at Kiel
Center, where they are 0-5-1 in their past six visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is on the home team in Game 5,'' Hitchcock said.
``It should be a helluva a game, and it shouldn't be any different
than any other game in this series. They thought they should have
won some games, we thought we should have won some games. I see the
series is exactly where it should be.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
