<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-GARCIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN SPANIARD SPINS HIS BEST TIGER TALE, TRAILS WOODS BY 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ He packs a yo-yo and a video game into his
suitcase on long trips. He is still studying for his June high
school graduation. And if everything falls right, he'll have
completed requirements for his first driver's license next week.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia, 19, might have a lot of growing up to do. But the
native of Borriol, Spain, is already grown up on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, hailed in his homeland as the European Tiger Woods for
his boyish charm and killer golf game, fired an 8-under-par 62
yesterday at Cottonwood Valley Course during the first round of the
GTE Byron Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   With his scoring forged by nine birdies and only one bogey,
Garcia is in a three-way tie for second place. Interestingly,
Garcia sits one stroke behind the very player to whom his career is
being compared, Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just like to be myself,'' Garcia said, ``but if they
compare you with a good player, I guess that means you have
something in your game.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia has plenty of game. His father, Victor, is a golf pro and
serves as Sergio's swing coach. The work with dad has paid off. At
15, Garcia was the European Amateur champ. He has won Spanish and
French amateur championships and is the reigning British Amateur
champion. Last month, he finished as the low amateur in the
Masters. And his Miami-based agent, Jose Marquina, said Garcia has
won more than 70 amateur tournaments in 15 different countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got every part of the game that you need to be
successful,'' said Jerry Higginbotham, who served as caddie for
Mark O'Meara's 1998 Masters championship and is now the caddie for
Garcia. ``He is very aggressive. He attacks the golf course. He is
very accomplished. He'll be a force for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia began yesterday with a 29 on the front nine, scoring five
birdies in his first eight holes. He was briefly tied with Woods
for the lead after a birdie on the par-3 17th. But his tee shot on
18 hit a tree and then he two-putted after he left his 8-iron
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-two is OK,'' Garcia deadpanned to a laughing media
audience. ``I finished bad. ... You need to have luck. You need to
play well. Maybe some days I shoot 75 and some days I shoot 62.
I'll just try to keep playing my game and see if it goes well.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
