<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMED-TO-THE-TEETH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEETH AREN'T A WEAPON IN AN ATTACK, COURT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York state's highest court decided Thursday to take the
teeth out of the state's laws on assault.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a vigorous dissent invoking the infamous Evander
Holyfield-Mike Tyson fight, the state Court of Appeals ruled that a
former Brooklyn resident, Maxwell Owusu, could not be charged with
using his teeth as a ``dangerous instrument'' in a fight with his
estranged wife's boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The teeth were part of Owusu's body and not some portable device
he picked up to cause more serious injuries, the court decided,
noting that ``Owusu's teeth came with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-1 decision stemmed from a February 1996 incident in which
Owusu entered his former apartment on Caton Avenue in the
Kensington section and started fighting with Michael Samuel. After
punching him in the face and knocking him to the floor, court
papers contend, Owusu bit Samuel's left index finger to the bone,
severing nerves and causing serious permanent injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Owusu, a Nigerian native who is now a U.S. citizen, was charged
with first-degree burglary and first-degree assault, both felonies
involving a dangerous instrument. The top charge carried a possible
sentence of 12 1/2 to 25 years in jail, said Joyce Slevin, the
assistant district attorney handling the case in state Supreme
Court, noting that domestic violence cases often involve teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't come up with strangers, it doesn't come up with
robberies, but in domestic abuse cases it does,'' said Ms. Slevin,
who compared teeth to weapons like a baseball bat. ``We are saying,
why should anyone be treated differently for using his teeth?''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ruling, the charges against Owusu will have to be
reduced to second-degree burglary and second-degree assault, with
the top charge carrying a maximum sentence of 7 1/2 to 15 years.
The case has never been tried and no trial date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate division of state Supreme Court had upheld the
original charges, citing an earlier case in which a man's foot was
deemed a dangerous instrument. But in that case the foot had been
encased in a boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you add something to a body part, then it would be a
dangerous instrument,'' said Edward Friedman, Owusu's
court-appointed lawyer, in praising Thursday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution argued that molars can be menacing depending on
how they are used and noted the strong dissent to Thursday's ruling
by Judge Joseph Bellacosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander Holyfield,'' the justice wrote, ``might then
legitimately wonder about the implied extrapolation from this case
holding that Tyson's (or anyone else's) `choppers' could never be
deemed or used as an `instrument' of dangerous propensities.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that previous rulings had found that even a sidewalk
could be a dangerous instrument if someone was seriously injured by
having his head beaten against it, Bellacosa said the jury should
decide in each case what constitutes a dangerous instrument.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded that the court's decision might produce absurd
cases in the future. Someone with dentures biting someone else, for
instance, might be found liable of using a dangerous instrument
because they are not attached to the assailant's mouth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
