<HEADER>
A6559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SCURRY-PROFILE-72     05-13 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SCURRY-PROFILE-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SCURRY, IT'S WORLD CUP OR NOTHING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Minn.)  (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ It was a harmless victory ritual by the Norwegian
soccer players, crawling on the ground, linked hand-to-ankle like
human boxcars, but the memory of the celebration has been as
indelible for Briana Scurry as the tattoo of a panther on her
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The match occurred in the semifinals of the 1995 Women's World
Cup, and Scurry allowed the lone goal in a 1-0 defeat for the
United States, which disconsolately settled for third place after
winning the initial women's world championship in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Norway's victory came on a ball headed past Scurry, the American
goalkeeper, on a corner kick. She tried vainly to muscle through a
wall of opponents, and the ball whistled past her, inside the near
post, seemingly no more than an inch beyond her fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, the Norwegians fell to the ground, linked up and
began choo-chooing around the field in a routine called the Train.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was harmless but humiliating,'' Scurry said as the
Americans prepared for an exhibition match here Thursday night
against the Netherlands in a tuneup for next month's 1999 Women's
World Cup. ``I burned it into my head so I wouldn't forget it
later. I felt I wasn't strong enough to get to the ball, so I hit
the weight room hard. I was determined to knock a few Norwegians
around.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the two teams met again in the semifinals of the
1996 Summer Olympics. Scurry had put on 15 pounds, weighing about
150, and she stood her ground as the Americans prevailed, 2-1, in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, the Americans won the inaugural Olympic
tournament over China and, keeping a promise, Scurry streaked down
a secluded street in Athens, Ga., wearing nothing but her gold
medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was such a release of anxiety from the year before,''
Scurry said. ``I did not cry a tear until we beat them in the
Olympics. That's when I cried.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 10, in the Rose Bowl, the United States could face
Norway yet again in the final of the 1999 World Cup, and there is a
redemptive need among the Americans to defeat the defending world
champions and to derail the Train once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics was a great payback, but that was separate,''
Scurry said. ``To be the Olympic champion and world champion at the
same time would be the be-all and end-all. We took that game hard
in 1995. We expect to win, and when we don't it's devastation. We
won third, but it was like `Who cares?' We felt like they had taken
something that was ours. We need to take it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry grew up in Anoka, Minn., a suburb of Minneapolis that is
the supposed inspiration for Garrison Keillor's Lake Wobegon, where
``all the women are strong, all the men are good looking and all
the children are above average.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first love was football, not soccer. In fourth and fifth
grades, she played cornerback and wide receiver in a youth league,
loving that she could ``hit people and it being legal and you would
not get into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother would not let her play in a heavier weight division,
so Scurry turned to soccer in the sixth grade. Then, as now, soccer
remains a suburban sport in the United States, unlike the rest of
the world, where it is a city game.
</P>
<P>
   Scurry is the only African-American in the starting lineup for
the United States. The American players feel an almost missionary
zeal as role models for young girls, and for Scurry there is a
particular urgency in her purpose. She hopes that black boys and
girls will see her in person, or on television, this summer and
decide to give soccer a try.
</P>
<P>
   When she gives clinics, Scurry encourages kids to approach
soccer as if it were licorice _ you may not like it, but just taste
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer's not a sport that's in the inner city at all,'' said
Scurry, who is 27 and holds a degree in political science from the
University of Massachusetts. ``For one thing, there's no place to
play. You go in the inner city and what do you see? Tar. And what
do you play on tar? Basketball. Minneapolis has one soccer field in
the entire inner-city area. It's just not something that kids are
exposed to. It's like ice hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans do well and dominate every sport _ football,
basketball, baseball,'' she said. ``Why not soccer? There's no
reason we can't get more African-Americans playing soccer. It's all
about exposure.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When France won the 1998 men's World Cup, galvanizing an entire
country with an exquisitely multiethnic team, American soccer
officials conceded that they had not cast a sufficiently wide net
in seeking talent to build the men's team to respectability and to
keep the women's team atop the sport's summit.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, that is changing. A foundation to develop the sport in
this country has been created by the U.S. Soccer Federation with a
$60 million surplus from the 1994 men's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has awarded more than $8 million in grants and
intends to build 500 soccer fields nationwide in the next five
years. About 25 percent of the $2 million in grant money to be
dispensed in the year beginning July 1 has been earmarked for
underprivileged neighborhoods, according to Alan Rothenberg, former
president of the soccer federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we continue to develop soccer in this country, there are
two minority groups we have to do a better job with,'' said
Rothenberg, who is chairman of the 1999 Women's World Cup
organizing committee. ``Hispanics are out there playing, but
largely not in federation leagues, so we have to scout outside our
customary locations. And we have to sell African-Americans on the
sport. There are not enough African-Americans playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-8-inch Scurry was an all-state basketball forward in
high school who also went to the Minnesota state high school track
championships as a sprinter and long jumper.
</P>
<P>
   She has now built herself into one of the world's top
goalkeepers. Once primarily a shot blocker, relying on her
anticipation and reflexes, she has matured into a goalie who spends
more time organizing the defense and less time having to make
spectacular saves.
</P>
<P>
   In the World Cup, coach Tony DiCicco is counting on Scurry to be
more assertive away from the goal line and to be a reliable
pressure valve when the ball is played back to her by the American
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need her to be the best she's ever been,'' DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   Her love of the game, Scurry said, comes from knowing that she
controls the outcome. If the other team cannot score on her, it
cannot win.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, there will be no nakedly enthusiastic
celebration this summer as at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't top it,'' Scurry said, laughing. ``Maybe bungee
jumping naked, but I don't think that's going to happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
