<SLUG> BC-NY-FISH-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY IS SAID TO WEIGH MOVING FISH MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city is considering a multimillion-dollar plan to
modernize and move the Fulton Fish Market from the storied but
gritty site it has occupied for 166 years in lower Manhattan, a top
Giuliani administration official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to act because of more stringent federal requirements
regarding the refrigeration of fish, the administration plans to
decide by this summer whether to renovate the existing market or
build a new center for wholesale fish and shellfish companies
elsewhere in the city, Deputy Mayor Rudy Washington said in an
interview. Either alternative would cost $30 million to $55
million, Washington said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to identify what sections of the city were being
considered as possible sites for the market, the nation's largest
wholesale seafood distribution point, with annual sales of $800
million to $1 billion. But as fishmongers and workers toiled
Thursday in the early morning mists, many said they believed that
City Hall was reviving previous proposals to transfer them to a
spot near the Hunts Point Produce Market in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Some merchants and employees also said that the administration
was bent on razing the two main buildings of the market, a remnant
of 19th-century New York that has figured in the works of the
writings of Joseph Mitchell and others. Moving the market, people
who work there say, could clear the way for development of valuable
city-owned land near the South Street Seaport and alongside the
East River.
</P>
<P>
   Washington acknowledged that the city could profit from the sale
of a three-block area for commercial and residential use if the
market is moved. Real estate developers and brokers estimated the
property could be sold for $40 million to $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Washington said the city was being forced to act because of
stricter federal regulations for the handling and refrigeration of
perishable seafood. Much of the seafood brought to the market daily
by refrigerated trucks is kept for hours in containers packed with
ice but not refrigerated before it is sold to fish stores and
restaurants, Washington said.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that there were no health dangers or sanitary
violations in the current system. But he said that new rules from
the federal Food and Drug Administration would eventually require
more refrigeration, especially in the summer, and other food-safety
protection programs that cannot be easily accommodated in the
market's antiquated electrical system and scruffy buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come into compliance with the new regulations,'' Washington
said, ``we must come up with the most economical plan for the city:
to retrofit the old buildings or relocate and build another
structure.''
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials want the city to produce a compliance schedule by
this summer, he added, and that is the deadline for a decision on
the market's future.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who is deputy mayor for community development and
business services, said that food safety was not the only reason to
revamp the market. ``The wholesale merchants understand as well as
we do that something has to happen,'' he said. ``The market was
built with technology from the turn of the century, not the
millennium we are about to enter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
