<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CLURMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIRLEY CLURMAN, 74, EDITOR AND PRODUCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shirley Potash Clurman, a retired magazine editor and
television producer, died Thursday at St. Rose's Home in Manhattan.
She was 74 and lived on Manhattan's Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clurman, a native of Los Angeles, began her career in the
publicity department of 20th Century Fox before moving to New York
to work as an assistant to Richard Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein
II.
</P>
<P>
   She did public relations work for Time Inc. and, until the early
1960s, for the Rockefeller family, then worked as an editor at
People magazine. When she retired, she was working for ABC News as
an associate producer of the news magazine program ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clurman was the widow of Richard M. Clurman, a longtime
leader in New York City's cultural life and former chief of
correspondents and head of Time-Life News Service. He died three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by their son, Michael, of Manhattan; two
stepdaughters, Susan Emma Clurman of Manhattan and Carol Mae Duning
of Alexandria, Va., and a sister, Ellen Schwartz of Waco, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
