u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORACLE-STOCK-NYT &LR;      05-13 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE SHARES TUMBLE 9 PERCENT OVER WARNING ON EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares of Oracle Corp. dropped 9 percent
Thursday after several analysts suggested that the company might
not meet earnings estimates for its fourth quarter, which ends May
31, because of a slowdown in sales of software that manages
corporate information systems.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle, which was the most active stock Thursday, with 57.3
million shares changing hands, fell $2.3125, to $23 a share, in
NASDAQ trading. Oracle shares are down 20 percent this year even as
other technology companies reach new highs. Much of the drop came
March 12 after Oracle reported third-quarter earnings that
essentially matched analysts' expectations, but database and
application revenue fell short. Oracle said at the time that
several large sales had slid into the fourth quarter, traditionally
its strongest, so any weakness in this quarter did not bode well
for the future, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, who met with Oracle executives Thursday at the
company's headquarters in Redwood Shores, Calif., predicted weaker
revenue and profit. If sales and earnings do fall short this
quarter, one likely cause will be the general weakness in the
so-called enterprise resource-planning software market. Companies
are delaying purchases of these software packages, which manage
critical tasks like human resources and manufacturing, because of
the Year 2000 problem. Companies that sell such software, including
Peoplesoft Inc., Baan Co. and SAP AG, have all experienced a
slowdown in sales.
</P>
<P>
   William Epifanio II, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said that
Oracle was directly affected because about one-fourth of its sales
come from enterprise resource software and indirectly because about
one-third of the rest of its sales is database software used with
other companies' enterprise resource applications. ``Given that
that market is in such bad shape, with no sign of improvement until
the middle of 2000, I am concerned as to where they will find these
revenues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Oracle's sales pattern, it's heavily weighted
to this quarter,'' he added, noting that customers hold off
purchases to get end-of-the-year discounts. ``Weakness now portends
at least another quarter or more of the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think that Oracle's traditional database business
is getting squeezed by IBM's DB2 product at the high end and by
Microsoft Corp.'s SQL Server at the low end. Oracle looked first to
the enterprise resource applications to stimulate new growth, but
that market is stalled, and the company is now promoting a new
suite of customer-relationship management programs to compete with
companies like Siebel Systems Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2320EDT &QL; 
