<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS' 61 LEADS GARCIA BY ONLY ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It was a record-tying day for Tiger Woods, and
an attention-getting day for 19-year-old Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Woods opened the GTE Byron Nelson Classic on Thursday with a
nine-under- par 61, his first 61 as a professional, which tied the
Cottonwood Valley Course record set by Ernie Els in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But while Woods left Thursday's first-round with a one-stroke
lead, it was Garcia who left people wondering if they had just
witnessed a coming-out party for the game's next young star.
Shooting a 62 in his first PGA Tour professional round, and showing
why the comparisons between Woods and Garcia are bound to continue,
Garcia was tied for second place with Paul Goydos and Steve Lowery
as Woods and Garcia positioned themselves for perhaps their first
head-to-head weekend tournament battle.
</P>
<P>
   Woods set a blistering pace on a birdie-filled day, shooting a
29 on the front nine, and returning from his three-week hiatus
looking fresh, confident and determined. It was his best round
since his 10-under-par 62 in February en route to winning the Buick
Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove in a lot of fairways and the greens were very soft, so
I attacked,'' said Woods, who shot a 29 on the front nine. ``It's
always fun when you can get it going like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia, who teed off almost three hours after Woods, was
hardly intimidated. Garcia made his pro debut in Spain, after
winning low amateur at last month's Masters, and after dominating
the amateur ranks in Europe much the way Woods dominated in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of 70 amateur tournaments, including last year's British
Amateur championship, Garcia is a long-hitting, aggressive player,
with an intuitive short-game touch, an maturity beyond his years.
</P>
<P>
   Tutored by both Seve Ballesteros and the reigning Masters
champion, Jose Maria Olazabal, Garcia hopes to follow in their
footsteps to become Spain's next great player. And as Thursday
indicated, Garcia has special gifts.
</P>
<P>
   He made a 30-foot putt for birdie at No. 14, holed a bunker shot
for birdie at No. 15, and he reached No. 18 tied with Woods at nine
under par, before making a bogey on the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good putter, he's very aggressive, and he's got every
part of the game,'' said Jerry Higginbotham, Garcia's caddie this
week and Mark O'Meara's caddie for five years. ``He's not your
average 19 year-old kid. Once every 10 years, somebody comes along
like this. He's the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia plans to play at least four more tour events this year _
The Memorial, the FedEx St. Jude Classic, the Sprint International
and the Westin Open. Asked what his goals were coming into this
week, Garcia said, ``To make the cut and play well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I have a chance to win, I'll go for it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how Garcia will fare over 72 holes,
because he was just one of many players who turned Thursday's round
into a birdie barrage. Goydos, playing with Woods for the first
time, shot a 28 on the front nine, one better than Woods. Goydos
was so hot that Woods never teed off first on the front nine. Nick
Price, the third player in the Woods-Goydos threesome, shot a 63.
How often is a 63 the worst score in a threesome?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said I wasn't excited about playing with
Tiger and Nick Price,'' said Goydos, whose only tour victory came
at the 1996 Bay Hill Invitational. ``I might have been a little
more focused. You don't want to embarrass yourself. I'm used to
playing in front of my wife and the other player's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery's 62 may have been the most impressive, because it was
the lowest score at the TPC of Las Colinas, the tougher of the two
courses on which the tournament is played. It has been an eventful
year for Lowery, whose home burned to the ground in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to play better,'' said Lowery, who is thankful
that his wife and three children escaped injury in the fire. ``It's
to the point now where the insurance is handling it. They have to
hire a builder and reconstruct the house. I've been able to focus
back on golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was focused Thursday, in a round that included nine
birdies and no bogeys. When Woods putts as well as he did Thursday,
he is usually in contention.
</P>
<P>
   Woods made four consecutive birdies, starting at No. 5, and his
most spectacular birdie came at No. 12, where he made a 30-foot
putt. But while Woods set the pace, he was joined on the
leaderboard by another talented young player, four years his
junior.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Garcia have become friends, they have practiced
together numerous times, and nobody has to tell Woods how good
Garcia is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give him advice if he asks me,'' said Woods, when asked
about Garcia on Wednesday. ``But he'll find his own way of doing
things to be successful. And believe me, he's going to be
successful.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
