<SLUG> BC-OBIT-THOMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEON THOMAS, JAZZ SINGER KNOWN FOR `YODEL,' DIES AT 61  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Tenn., Mo.)   By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leon Thomas, a jazz singer known for his bellowing
glottal-stop style in free jazz of the 1970s, died on Saturday at
Lincoln Hospital in the Bronx. He was 61 and lived in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure as a result of leukemia, Karen
Dagneau, his tour manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who was born in East St. Louis, Ill., and studied music
at Tennessee State University, moved to New York in 1958. With his
stout tenor voice, he worked as a straight blues-jazz singer,
performing with Count Basie and Mary Lou Williams in the mid-'60s.
But by then he had also begun to spend time with young jazz
musicians, like Randy Weston and Pharoah Sanders, who were looking
to Africa, the East and meditation for musical material.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage with Sanders in the late 60s Thomas developed his
ululating singing style, which has been compared to African pygmy
and American Indian singing techniques, and which he later called
``soularphone.'' He believed that his ancestors had given him his
elastic throat articulation, he said, and henceforth always used
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This voice is not me,'' he explained in a 1995 interview. ``My
voice is ancient. This person you see before you is controlled by
ego, but my voice is egoless.''
</P>
<P>
   The best-known Pharoah Sanders tracks on which Thomas performed
were ``The Creator Has a Master Plan'' from 1969 and
``Hum-Allah-Hum-Allah-Hum Allah'' from 1970, both full of Thomas'
wordless yodeling over band vamps. In recent years Thomas' profile
rose a bit as this kind of spiritual African-tinged soul-jazz has
become known by record connoisseurs and club D.J.'s as
``kosmigroov.''
</P>
<P>
   After working with Sanders and making some of his own albums for
the Flying Dutchman label, Thomas spent two years as a member of
Santana, performing on the albums ``Welcome'' and ``Lotus.'' He
also appeared on recordings by Johnny Hodges, Oliver Nelson, Hank
Crawford and Jamaaladeen Tacuma. In the last few years Thomas often
sang at the Lenox Lounge in Harlem, backed by the Donald Smith
trio. He had just come home from performing at the Up Over Cafe in
Park Slope, Brooklyn, when he died.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a son, Amos, of the Bronx, and a brother,
Curtis of St. Louis, Mo..
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
