<SLUG> BC-STARTIX-SCALPING-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: and sell two over eBay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to make back some of what I paid,'' said Hazen, a
veteran of buying and selling DVDs and movie posters on eBay. ``The
closer it is to the opening, the higher the price will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Caltech student Victor Huang is less certain that he'll cash in
on the eight tickets he has for sale. He waited between 4 p.m. and
9 p.m. Wednesday at the Chinese and had to settle for tickets to a
May 21 showing at 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had to buy something after standing in the cold
for that long, but it turns out that we have a real glut of tickets
from Caltech students so I don't really need them,'' Huang said.
``I may just wind up getting my money back.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherak had no concrete sales figures because exhibitors have
said they are too busy handling advance tickets, but said sales had
gone ``very well.'' As for MovieFone, the nation's largest
movie-ticket service, it announced Thursday that it had received
more than 4 million inquiries in the first 24 hours of sales with
95 percent of those for ``Phantom Menace'' tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the sales went very well although we know that not
everyone was going to be able to get through,'' said spokeswoman
Christine Facundiny. ``It may have taken some people a couple of
hours to get through, but I think they expected it to be busy.
There's been a gradual tapering off, but it's still very busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox plans to book ``Phantom Menace'' into about 2,950 theaters,
which will mean showings in about 5,000 auditoriums. That's well
short of the record 3,306 theaters used a year ago for the launch
of ``Godzilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry trackers expect ``Phantom Menace'' is likely to top the
domestic records held by ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' for
biggest opening, including $26.1 million gross in the first day and
$104.9 million gross for the first week. With early reviews mixed,
it could have a hard time matching the final $601million in gross
ticket receipts sold domestically set by ``Titanic.''
</P>
