<HEADLINE>
SCALPERS OFFER `STAR WARS' OPENING DAY TICKETS ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let the scalping begin.
</P>
<P>
   In what some might say is the dark side of next week's opening
of ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace,'' thousands of
people who bought tickets to next Wednesday's debut turned around
and offered some of those tickets for sale Thursday via newspaper
advertisements, ticket brokers or online at places like eBay.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear indication of the unprecedented anticipation over
George Lucas' prequel, there were 124 different ``Star Wars''
ticket packages on sale at eBay, the leading Internet auction site,
less than 24 hours after ticket sales began. More tickets are
available through newspaper ads and at ticket brokers that usually
deal only with sporting events and music concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be selling tickets for prime shows at places like Mann
Chinese in Hollywood at prices from $25 to $65,'' said Richard
Shelter with Applause Tickets of Los Angeles. ``The 12:01 a.m.
showing is the most desired.''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Evans of Yorba Linda is asking $525 for four opening-night
tickets at the Edwards Anaheim in Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who bought 44 tickets for opening-day showings at four
different theaters, plans to sell them all through eBay and
believes he might clean up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invested $308, so I'm thinking I could clear a lot on
this,'' said Evans, a 20-year-old who lost his job last month as an
event coordinator. ``I'm anticipating selling them all because
these kinds of tickets are going to be pretty scarce by next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, a veteran of selling jewelry and computer equipment on
eBay, won't go to ``Phantom Menace'' for several weeks. ``I'm not a
fan at all and that was making some of the people in the lines
pretty upset,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although ticket scalping is a fact of life for concerts, plays
and sporting events, it is virtually unheard of for movies. As a
result, many sellers said Thursday that it is hard to predict
exactly where prices will head for ``Phantom Menace'' tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers agreed, however, that location and timing are the
critical factors to pricing tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting to get about $35 or $40 for a pair of
opening-night tickets at the Winnetka 20 because there's no way
people will pay more than that for a showing in the San Fernando
Valley,'' said real estate agent Asher Sarkis, who is selling two
dozen tickets online. ``I could see tickets for the Chinese going
for $50 or $100 each for the 12:01 a.m. show. It's like going to a
concert.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Mills, a broker with the Good Times agency, said the agency
had no tickets available for the first showing at the Chinese. He
added that he probably would pay $30 per ticket _ nearly four times
the $8.50 face value _ if they were offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that most of the people who stood in line
want to go, but I would imagine there will be some available in the
next few days,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's likely to be a premium for tickets even if they
aren't at flagship theaters. Gina, a mortgage company employee who
elected not to give her last name, already had received a $30 bid
for two tickets for the first show at the Edwards Grand Palace in
Calabasas she had received from a co-worker. And she's hopeful the
excitement over the film will spark a bidding war.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get a good bid, I'll stand outside and sell them,''
she said. ``I know that sometimes these online auctions roll out of
control because for some people it gets to be a matter of pride to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas and 20th Century Fox warned of the scalping scenario a
month ago when they sought to convince theater owners that advance
sales should be banned. When they relented a few weeks later, they
imposed a 12-ticket-per-customer limit in order to limit scalping.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that we're not surprised by the
scalping,'' said Tom Sherak, chairman of 20th Century Fox's
domestic film group. ``We weren't born yesterday. We are
disappointed but that's how people are.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherak advised those seeking tickets for first-day shows to
avoid scalpers. ``There's still plenty of theaters with tickets for
the shows, although maybe not at the Chinese and the Mann Village
(in Westwood),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fans began forming lines at those two theaters more than a month
ago. Since the seats at each show are taken on a first-come,
first-served basis, many of the hard core were in new lines
Thursday to be the first to get into the theaters next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they've been there for a month, what's another week,''
said Mann executive Sandy Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hazen, who works as an assistant to a literary agent, stood
in line for 18 hours to get a dozen seats for the first show at the
Glendale Exchange. The 24-year-old plans to attend with nine
friends and sell two over eBay.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
