<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVERBULLETDAY IS WITHDRAWN FROM THE PREAKNESS FOR THE `SUSAN'
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ ``I have to take care of her,'' Bob Baffert said
Thursday morning, and so he withdrew his prize filly,
Silverbulletday, from the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer from California, dejected because he had drawn the
No. 14 post position on the far outside for Silverbulletday,
followed through on his earlier warning and said that he would
scratch her from the Preakness on Saturday and run her instead in
the Black-Eyed Susan Stakes for fillies on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And the flight from the Preakness seemed to be widening when
Carl Nafzger insisted that he would not start his colt Vicar from
the No. 13 post.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the good ones, you've got to be careful,'' Baffert said.
``This was a hard decision. We even discussed it with the groom and
with the jockey's agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she had won the Kentucky Derby, we might take a shot from
Post 14. If this had happened to my other filly, Excellent Meeting,
we wouldn't have run her, either. In this game, you expect the
worst and hope for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday has given one smashing performance after another
as she raced to the top of the filly class in racing. She won 10 of
her 11 starts, extended her winning streak to seven and raised her
career earnings past $2 million when she won the Kentucky Oaks two
weeks ago on the day before the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But when Baffert drew the No. 14 post position for the
Preakness, he lost interest in running her against colts, even
though she was second choice for the Preakness, behind Menifee, in
the morning-line odds.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer said he and Mike Pegram, the filly's owner, had
reached their decision after a long evening of mulling the
short-term opportunity against the long-range danger to the filly's
career. Pegram said that he was deeply disappointed that they were
going to scratch Silverbulletday but that he agreed with the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts,'' Pegram said, outside the stakes barn at Pimlico
Race Course, ``but it was the right thing to do. We had to look at
the book to see how far the Black-Eyed Susan was. She was entered
in it, but I never thought of anything but the Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Black-Eyed Susan will be run at a 1 1/8 miles; the
Preakness, at 1 3/16 miles. But the race for fillies carries a
purse of only $200,000; the Preakness, $1 million. Silverbulletday
already drew the No. 1 post position on the inside for the
Black-Eyed Susan, and she will be the overwhelming favorite in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Another horse with a shining record, Vicar, seemed ready to
follow Silverbulletday out of the Preakness because he drew No. 13
after drawing No. 17 for the Kentucky Derby and finishing 18th. The
colt came out of Florida last winter with consecutive victories in
the Fountain of Youth Stakes and the Florida Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will just not run from No. 13,'' Nafzger said. ``I learned
a long time ago never to try to predict the unpredictable. If we
scratch, it won't be until Saturday morning.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked about the custom of scratching by noon Friday in
order to make the advance betting on the Preakness more realistic,
and he replied: ``I can scratch whenever I want to. I can scratch
45 minutes before post time, or I can scratch with a veterinarian
20 minutes before post time.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the defections, a revised list of early odds was
presented by Clem Florio, the linemaker for Pimlico, although
Menifee stood as the 5-2 favorite. With Silverbulletday taken off
the list as the 7-2 second choice, Florio moved up Excellent
Meeting to that role at 9-2. The Kentucky Derby winner,
Charismatic, now was third choice at 5-1 with Kimberlite Pipe next
at 6-1 and Stephen Got Even at 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   The defections proved a boon to Nick Zito, who lost his jockey
on Stephen Got Even when Chris McCarron fell from a horse during a
workout at Hollywood Park on Tuesday and broke a bone in his foot.
Because Silverbulletday was being withdrawn, Gary Stevens was now
excused as her jockey in the Preakness. And Zito promptly signed
him to ride Stephen Got Even.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had luck with Gary in the past,'' Zito said. ``He rode
Halory Hunter for us to win the Blue Grass last year. We've got
Adonis in the No. 9 post and Stephen in No. 11, and they're not
ideal, but I can't do anything about that now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
