r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VANGUARD-AIRLINE-KAN &LR;      05-13 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANGUARD-AIRLINE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT LAWSUIT ACCUSES AMERICAN AIRLINES OF PREDATORY PRICING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The U.S. Justice Department sued American
Airlines for alleged antitrust violations Thursday, accusing the
carrier of using illegal pricing tactics to drive out Vanguard
Airlines and other small competitors from its Dallas hub.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard, a low-cost carrier based in Mission, Kan., is one of
three airlines cited in the Justice Department's lawsuit as a
victim of American's alleged monopolistic practices. The Justice
Department said Sun Jet and Western Pacific also faced predatory
pricing moves by American, the nation's second-largest carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit culminates more than two years of investigation by
the federal government into complaints of predatory pricing
practices by American and other major carriers. It is the first
predatory pricing case brought in the industry since airline
deregulation in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Several industry analysts said many airlines use questionable
pricing tactics to attract business. However, one analyst said the
government's case against American was weak.
</P>
<P>
   The department's civil lawsuit, filed in federal court in
Wichita, said a megacarrier such as American must be prohibited
from future predatory pricing practices when facing competition
from smaller, discount airlines at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, the nation's third-largest airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without competition, hub carriers will charge high fares on
routes they dominate,'' said Joel I. Klein, assistant attorney
general in charge of the Justice Department's antitrust division.
``Hub carriers cannot be permitted to use predatory tactics to keep
new entrants out of their markets.''
</P>
<P>
   American issued a statement vowing to fight the lawsuit, saying
the Justice Department's action goes ``against the very essence of
free market competition.''
</P>
<P>
   American said it was confident its actions in Dallas//Fort Worth
``will prove to be nothing more than those of any tough competitor
in a highly competitive industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard, which has struggled financially since its inception in
December 1994, said its position had been vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the actions that American Airlines took to
eliminate Vanguard Airlines from the Dallas-Fort Worth marketplace
were unlawful and violated antitrust laws,'' said Robert J. Spane,
Vanguard's president and chief executive officer. ``This is a move
that will help preserve open competition throughout the industry
and help consumers and new entrant airlines alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the lawsuit focuses on Vanguard's attempts to move into
the Dallas market and the subsequent response by American. In
January 1995, when Vanguard was starting up, the carrier began
operating three daily, nonstop round-trip flights between Kansas
City and Dallas at discount prices.
</P>
<P>
   American immediately matched Vanguard's fares and then added
several more Kansas City-Dallas flights later that year. By the end
of the year, Vanguard withdrew its Kansas City-Dallas nonstop
service, and American raised its fares in early 1996, according to
the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, American, in documents, vowed that its
additional Kansas City-Dallas flights were intended ``to drive
(Vanguard) out of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard again tried to enter the Dallas market in September
1996, with new nonstop service from Dallas to Kansas City, Phoenix
and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, according to the lawsuit, American announced
plans to expand service from Dallas to Kansas City, Cincinnati,
Phoenix and Wichita. American also matched Vanguard's fares on
selected flights.
</P>
<P>
   One month later, Vanguard withdrew its Cincinnati and Phoenix
service from Dallas and reduced its Kansas City-Dallas schedule.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said Thursday that the actions it took in the
face of competition from Vanguard and other discount carriers did
not violate antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply matched their fares,'' said American spokesman Chris
Chiames. ``At no point did we undercut fares. Vanguard set the
fares, and we matched them.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that with the lawsuit, the federal
government essentially is telling American it cannot compete with
new-entrant carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the lawsuit is potentially anti-consumer and would
have a chilling effect not just on airlines but on other businesses
as well,'' Chiames said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Gillman, Vanguard's general counsel, disagreed. Vanguard
has been cooperating with the Justice Department since 1997 on the
inquiry. The airline supplied additional pricing information to the
government last month, which had fueled speculation that the
Justice Department was close to taking action.
</P>
<P>
   One aviation industry analyst said he was surprised by the
Justice Department's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard was a new and financially troubled carrier with
operational problems during the period the Justice Department
focuses on, said Michael Boyd, president of the Boyd Group, a
consulting firm in Evergreen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (the federal government) wanted American to do is not
match their competitors' fares,'' Boyd said. ``Is there predatory
pricing out there? Yes. But is American guilty in this case? I
don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst said that although American and other major
airlines use questionable pricing tactics, customers need to fly on
high-quality discount carriers that are competing head-to-head with
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lawsuit may get the major carriers to step back and say,
`They're watching us,' '' said Terry Trippler, a consumer affairs
expert with 1travel.com, a discount travel Web site. ``But a lot of
the blame for this behavior lies with the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Vanguard comes to town and offers a low fare that
American matches, people choose to fly American. People want
Vanguard prices, but they want to fly American. Consumers have to
make wise decisions and support the discount carrier to maintain
that low fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard has begun posting operating profits in the past year.
The company has about 780 full- and part-time employees in the
Kansas City area. Vanguard and American now offer nonstop flights
to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time American has faced antitrust
allegations. In 1983, the Justice Department charged Robert L.
Crandall, American's ex-president, with conspiring with Braniff's
top executive to raise fares. American eventually agreed in a court
order not to engage in such activity in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
