<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MARKETS ARE IGNORING CONVENTIONAL WISDOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An incredible happening occurred this week. Just about the same
time the government reported a substantial first-quarter gain in
productivity, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to its
highest level in almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   This seemed to defy conventional economic wisdom, because rising
productivity restrains wage inflation and thus implies continued
price stability. Labor costs represent the biggest chunk of
overhead for most businesses and thus have the most effect on
pricing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the bellwether bond's interest rate spike all the
more remarkable was a companion report showing only a small gain
for unit labor costs in the January-March period.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity for nonfarm businesses rose at a 4 percent annual
rate. The year-over-year gain of 2.8 percent is the best in three
years. Unit labor costs inched up only 0.3 percent from last year's
fourth quarter, which brought the year-over-year gain to a
relatively piddling 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in long-term interest rates over the last few weeks is
not only a puzzle, but also a big disappointment for investors
expecting good inflation news to translate into rising values for
their bond holdings. Instead they've been losing money because bond
prices and yields move in opposite directions, which means bond
prices decline as interest rates rise.
</P>
<P>
   Smart money would bet that economic conditions normally
promising price stability would be a boon rather than a bane for
the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   Although the April reading of the Consumer Price Index due out
this morning is expected to show a higher-than-usual rise, the
retail inflation gauge through March was up only 1.7 percent during
the previous 12 months. While Thursday's Producer Price Index
report showed wholesale prices up 0.5 percent, the core rate that
excludes the volatile food and energy components was up only 0.1
percent. The same core-rate showing is expected of the CPI if its
overall increase is comparable to the PPI's gain.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of alarming inflation developments makes recent
interest rate jumps curious, because interest rates are normally
driven by inflationary expectations. They also are also driven by
anticipation of Federal Reserve policy, of course, which is also
guided by its policy-makers' inflationary expectations. The Fed's
Open Market Committee, which decides monetary policy, will hold one
of its regular meetings next week to review the situation, but Wall
Street isn't expecting the committee to boost rates.
</P>
<P>
   So, if inflation isn't a discernible near-term threat and the
Fed is expected to hew to the status quo for the time being, what
is spooking the bond market into bidding up yields?
</P>
<P>
   A consensus is beginning to emerge among analysts that even if
the Fed doesn't tighten monetary policy with a rate increase next
week, a boost is inevitable later this year if the economy
continues its strong growth.
</P>
<P>
   Another contrarian wild card, meantime, is the stock market's
ability to continue defying gravity. Conventional wisdom again
would dictate a weakening stock market in the face of rising
interest rates, but it hasn't happened. This is as incredible as
interest rates soaring in the absence of any immediate inflationary
threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
