</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGUA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MEXICO'S KOSOVO': THOUSANDS IN TRANSIT TO U.S. SWAMP BORDER CITY 
</HEADLINE>
 PRIETA-ALIENS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGUA PRIETA, Sonora _ It was last month that Mayor Vicente Teran
really realized how much this dusty border city has become what he
calls ``Mexico's Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others in this, the border's most popular crossing point
for illegal immigrants, already had watched the number of strangers
wandering daily around downtown grow to 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   They'd seen the new, low-end hotels springing up, lured by a
demand so lucrative that even three doctors turned their offices
into lodging for people heading north.
</P>
<P>
   They'd heard of the 100 immigrant-smuggling organizations
supposedly operating within a 10-minute walk of the border
checkpoint to neighboring Douglas, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   But what really drove home the point, Teran said, was the
``waiting line to get in the cemetery'' during one week last month
when 27 people met a violent end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coyotes'' _ immigrant smugglers _ were killing other coyotes
in the turf war over human bounty, he said. Border bandits were
killing helpless immigrants for their meager possessions. A
prisoner from another part of Mexico slipped his restraints and
murdered two local police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a giant mafia controlling this city,'' said Paula
Lopez Martinez, who operates a jewelry store on bustling Fourth
Avenue downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not the drug smugglers like in the past. It's the
people smugglers.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, a half-dozen hotels served this city of 120,000.
Agua Prieta, located in arid, isolated northeastern Sonora, had
never been on anyone's map of likely destinations.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed when U.S. immigration officials started
clamping down on traditional immigrant-smuggling routes _ first El
Paso, then San Diego and later, Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Agua Prieta boasts 16 hotels and more than 500 rooms. At
least, that's the official version of the hospitality industry.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, dozens of other smaller hotels also have opened in
the city, many in abandoned storefronts. Many homeowners have
converted vacant rooms and sheds into lodging.
</P>
<P>
   Eight blocks from the border, a developer is nearing completion
of a large multilevel dormitory with cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church also is getting in on the act,
building a shelter for 50 people with beds and eating facilities
about two miles from the border.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Human smuggling is against the law in Mexico, and several
`coyotes' have been arrested in Agua Prieta. Still, local
entrepreneurs say they aren't going to turn their back on such
inviting money-making opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The demand is so great that smugglers stuff as many as 20 people
in one hotel room; some hotels rent out space on hall floors for
immigrants to sleep on.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Mayor Ray Borane, who's lobbying the U.S. government to
do something about the relentless waves of immigrants, said he has
met resistance from Agua Prieta businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep saying, `Hey, stay out of this. Business has never
been better and we want to keep it that way,' '' Borane said.
</P>
<P>
   But some Agua Prieta businessmen, like hardware-store owner
David de la Torre, said the problem of the ``floating refugees'' is
ruining legitimate businesses and respectable townspeople.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious problem when you have 3,000 people just hanging
around your downtown area, and buses full of more of them coming
here every day,'' de la Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom has had to close her curio shop because of the
increased violence and the fact that tourists just don't come here
any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Efrain Martinez, who hosts an Agua Prieta radio talk show, put
the problem this way: fewer gringos with money and more Mexicans
from the interior without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also are angry about all the crime, how you can't find a
taxi any more because they are all moving immigrants around to
cross the border,'' Martinez said, ``and how the used-car lots
don't seem to have anything but vans for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people on the streets have been caught numerous
times by U.S. Border Patrol agents and are left penniless in the
Mexican city.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, more than 20,000 Mexicans a month have been
returned to their country at Agua Prieta. The Border Patrol drew
the ire of city leaders in February when it was learned that, in
addition to those being caught in the Douglas area, immigrants
caught in the Nogales area also were pushed back south at Agua
Prieta.
</P>
<P>
   But the Border Patrol, in an attempt to disrupt smuggling
operations, then started deporting people caught in the Nogales
area in Agua Prieta and those in the Douglas area in Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   Teran, the Agua Prieta mayor, said the immigrants have taxed his
city's services to the max. Many of those who have been repeatedly
captured by the Border Patrol have formed neighborhoods of
cardboard and scrap-wood shacks on the city's far-south side.
</P>
<P>
   They typically live hand-to-mouth or pick up the worst jobs that
the city's maquila industries have to offer, Teran said.
</P>
<P>
   '`In the past five years, our population has doubled to 120,000,
and this is where a large part of that growth has come from,`'
Teran said.
</P>
<P>
   Teran said city officials talked one bus company into offering
half-price fares to take those people back home who wanted to go,
but he didn't know how successful the special fare had been.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, the jewelry-store owner, gets a big chuckle out of that
one.
</P>
<P>
   She said she recently took a bus trip to her native state of
Guanajuato on a virtually empty bus. On the way north, however, she
could find only one seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was full of people from southern Mexico and Guatemala with
a `coyote' who controlled the movements of the bus,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driver stopped whenever the `coyote' wanted him to, and we
stayed a lot of time at the checkpoints wherever there were federal
police because he was paying bribes to all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez glanced down the street to the half block of buildings she
bought with her husband three years ago, when they were empty. Now
they house her jewelry store, a flourishing law practice and a
restaurant kept busy by lines of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   She smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we bought at the right time,'' she said. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
