r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHWAYS-BRIDGES-KAN &LR;      05-13 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAYS-BRIDGES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL RULING THREATENS HIGHWAY PROJECTS, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Among the Kansas City area highway projects
threatened by an unexpected federal ruling is the $30 million new
Chouteau Bridge, state highway officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And the ruling may affect more than federal projects, officials
said. It could also delay some projects that local governments are
paying to complete, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling set off a flurry of activity in Washington, Topeka
and Jefferson City on Thursday, as officials scrambled to interpret
its impact and decide how to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation ruled that the area's
transportation plans failed to conform with federal clean-air
requirements. As a result, the agency this week began to withhold
approval for area highway projects that widen roads or add lanes.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also could stop some projects that have started,
because several contracts are usually required to complete an
expansion project, said Bill Ahrens, urban planning manager for the
Kansas Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've finished design and you're ready to go to
right-of-way acquisition, you can't do it,'' Ahrens said. ``If you
finished right-of-way and you're ready to go to construction, you
can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri highway officials on Thursday listed four major
projects that may be affected. The projects and their anticipated
costs:
</P>
<P>
   - Missouri 7, between Moreland School Road and Wyatt Road,
$700,000.
</P>
<P>
   - Missouri 291, paving of the new bridge over the Missouri
River, $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   - The Chouteau Bridge, two contracts, $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   - Missouri 78, east of Missouri 291, $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Those projects were to begin as early as September, said Linda
Clark, the Missouri Department of Transportation's planning manager
for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get this problem worked out soon, nothing will happen to
those projects,'' Clark said. ``And when I say `soon,' I mean in
the next month.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas highway officials were working Thursday to assemble a
list of threatened projects.
</P>
<P>
   The list may be available as soon as today, when state and local
officials plan to meet in Kansas City with representatives of the
U.S. Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Kit Bond, a Missouri Republican, said he hoped to
introduce a bill soon that would prevent the kind of roadblock to
local highway funds facing the Kansas City region.
</P>
<P>
   His measure would turn into law an Environmental Protection
Agency rule that would allow ``grandfathering'' of previously
approved transportation projects into conformity with current clean
air rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can pass it, that would solve the problem for the Kansas
City metro area,'' he said. He added that other cities face similar
tensions between highway money and clean-air rules.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials think the federal agencies are taking a hard
line on the Kansas City issue because of recent federal court
rulings involving long-range transportation plans in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   There, a federal judge ordered federal officials to stop
allowing highway projects to proceed when area transportation plans
didn't conform to federal clean-air requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In Jefferson City, Gov. Mel Carnahan's staff planned to meet
late Thursday with the state's environment and highway officials to
assess what to do about the situation, said Chris Sifford, a
spokesman for Carnahan.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Kansas Gov. Bill Graves said he is awaiting
official notice of the ruling from federal highway officials before
considering what action to take.
</P>
<P>
   One quick way for the area to comply with federal clean-air
requirements would be for the governors of Kansas and Missouri to
formally ask that reformulated gasoline be brought to area pumps
next year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the governors have decided to wait until an
early June ``fuels summit'' with refiners, regulators and other
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, officials involved in this issue thought that
waiting until June would present no problem.
</P>
<P>
   Regional planning officials had thought the U.S. Department of
Transportation wouldn't place the area's transportation plans in
noncompliance until next year at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   But early this week, federal transportation officials informed
the Mid-America Regional Council that it had also placed the area's
current plan in noncompliance and had begun to halt new approvals
of highway expansion projects.
</P>
<P>
   Only projects that add to a highway's capacity are affected, but
such projects are usually among the most expensive. In 1998,
expansion projects amounted to half of the area's $400 million
transportation program, federal highway officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal clean-air laws require that long-range transportation
plans conform to the area's clean-air plans. In Kansas City, the
latest plan involves bringing reformulated gas to area pumps as
early as next year.
</P>
<P>
   That can't happen until the two governors ask for the gas to be
brought to Kansas City. Until that happens, the Environmental
Protection Agency said in an April 6 letter, it couldn't recommend
approval of the area's transportation plans.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation ratified the agency's
position this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-99 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
