<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT &LR;      05-13 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCY SPENDING BILL HITS $15 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (The following story, eliminated earlier from N.Y. Times News
Service budget, is now restored.)  (See related CONGRESS-PORK) 
(rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After three days and nights of haggling, House and
Senate negotiators on Thursday night wrapped up an emergency
spending package that ballooned to almost $15 billion, more that
twice what the White House had sought, to pay for wars and
disasters around the word.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers included more than $5 billion in military programs
that the Pentagon had never asked for, as well as some deeply
disputed legislation that would aid the mining, steel, fishing and
energy industries. They proposed Thursday night to pay for most of
it with surplus money from Social Security and food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Wearily emerging from bargaining sessions in the basement of the
Capitol and their personal suites, the conferees had accomplished
two things: They had added more than $8 billion, mostly in military
funds, to the package, and they had earned the anger and
disappointment from some fellow members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of both parties who saw the bill as politically and
financially undisciplined vowed to oppose it when it comes to a
final vote next week. Veteran staff members said the House-Senate
conference sessions had been chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   The final cost of the bill grew almost by the hour, and remained
in doubt at the close.
</P>
<P>
   To reach an agreement, the negotiators had to remove from the
spending bill measures offered by Sens. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
and Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., intended to help the steel, oil and
gas industries. Domenici's amendment would have spent $125 million
to back half a billion dollars in loans for oil and gas companies.
Byrd's measure would have spent $145 million or more to create $1
billion in loan guarantees for steel companies, including one in
his home state.
</P>
<P>
   The House-Senate appropriations conference first accepted the
package shortly before 1 a.m. Thursday. Then, under pressure from
Republican leaders, two House conferees switched their votes late
Thursday afternoon, defeating it on a vote of 12 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate stood firm for the package, creating an impasse
with long speeches by Byrd citing the Bible, Roman history and
congressional lore.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, late Thursday night, the conferees agreed to place the
steel, oil and gas measures in a separate emergency package for
future consideration by the House and Senate. With that maneuver,
the conferees had wrapped up a $14.7 billion bill.
</P>
<P>
   They took President Clinton's $6 billion request for the bombing
of Yugoslavia and Iraq and the care and feeding of refugees from
Kosovo, and added $2.25 million for military operations, $1.84
billion for a military pay increase, $475 million for military
construction, $300 million for aircraft, $250 million for weapons
and $200 million for the Coast Guard. They also increased money for
assisting refugees to $919 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money in the emergency bill would come from surplus
Social Security money, infuriating fiscal conservatives. The
members of the House Appropriations Committee in the conference
committee proposed Thursday night to offset some of those costs by
eliminating $1.25 billion in money for food stamps, which they said
was surplus and would go unspent this year, $350 million in
programs for low-income housing and $50 million for foreign
operations.
</P>
<P>
   That decision prompted an angry reaction from Rep. Marcy Kaptur,
D-Ohio. ``I cannot believe we're going to take funds from the most
vulnerable people in this country and give it away, most of it to
defense,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaptur's colleagues said most of the food-stamp money was
technically being used to offset costs of disaster aid to Central
American victims of Hurricane Mitch in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They included $687 million for the hurricane victims, with an
additional $216 million for the Defense Department's initial relief
efforts for them; $570 million for assistance to American farmers
stung by low commodity prices, and $80 million to deter illegal
immigration from Central America and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The conference also included $900 million for the Federal
Emergency Management Agency, mostly to help tornado and storm
victims in the Midwest, and $100 million to shore up Jordan's role
in the Mideast peace process. And it gave the Census Bureau $45
million to finance its operations through the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
