<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIG-TRIAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO COMPANY WINS JURY VERDICT IN KC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. had no
responsibility for the 1995 lung cancer death of 56-year-old
Charles Steele, a Kansas City federal jury ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters and with Brown &AMP; Williamson's lawyers
after the verdict, jury foreman Gary White, himself a smoker, said
deliberations quickly focused on testimony that Steele, of
Vandalia, Mo., apparently understood the risks of smoking and
consciously chose to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were convinced he knew cigarettes had a danger,'' White
said. ``His final decision was that the pleasure outweighed the
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's third-largest tobacco manufacturer hopes the
victory, combined with a win in a Tennessee courtroom earlier this
week, represents a return to the way juries traditionally have
viewed smoking cases and the way the industry defends its products.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Kansas City case, as well as the trials in Memphis, was
about personal responsibility and choice,'' said Steven McCormick,
a lawyer representing Brown and Williamson. ``Those juries'
verdicts are consistent with an overwhelming majority of American
citizens who believe plaintiffs should not be awarded money for
actions in which they exercised their own personal
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry has consistently prevailed over complaints
brought by sick smokers over the years. But two recent losses by
Philip Morris in California and Oregon dented the industry's armor
and helped drive down stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analyst Gary Black, with Sanford C. Bernstein, said
Brown &AMP; Williamson's wins in Kansas City and Memphis show investors
the industry still can manage its legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking-related lawsuits filed against tobacco companies rose
from about 150 in 1996 to about 800 in 1998, and about 180,000 new
cases of lung cancer are diagnosed every year, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry needed to win this case and the case in Memphis
to show plaintiffs' attorneys that these cases are not easy to
win,'' Black said. ``They needed to show they were in control.''
</P>
<P>
   And with victory, the markets responded.
</P>
<P>
   American depositary receipts for British American Tobacco, Brown
&AMP; Williamson's parent company, rose 1 to 19 by the end of trading
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Other tobacco stocks also showed improvements. Philip Morris
climbed 1 to 39. RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp., which plans to spin
off its R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. unit, gained to 29.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Steele, Charles Steele's daughter, said she was not
surprised by the verdict. She said she and her brother, Charles
Steele Jr., brought the case at the request of their mother, who
died a year after their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into this with an open mind,'' Michelle Steele said.
``This was our mother's decision. When she died we decided to
continue it. We knew from the beginning it would be a hard case.''
</P>
<P>
   Their lawyer, J. Michael Cronan of Independence, said he did not
plan to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had a fair shot at this,'' Cronan said. ``The jury
took it seriously, and we accept their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit, the Steeles contended that Brown &AMP;
Williamson's Kool Filter Kings were defective, ``unreasonably''
dangerous and directly responsible for his lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses for the defense, including company Chairman Nicholas
Brookes, acknowledged that smoking was risky but argued that Brown
&AMP; Williamson has helped fund about $300 million in independent
health research on smoking since the 1950s and helped to disclose
its hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments are emerging as a potent tobacco industry
defense, McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know jurors come to these cases with a very negative view
of the industry from what they've read in the papers,'' McCormick
said. ``Absolutely telling the story of Brown &AMP; Williamson will be
central to our defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the nine jurors in the Steele case were smokers or
ex-smokers. But White said they didn't consider that in their
decision.
</P>
<P>
   It did factor into their deliberations, however.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the case about 11:45 a.m. Wednesday, jurors
asked court officials a question that is never far from a smoker's
mind:
</P>
<P>
   Would they be able to take cigarette breaks? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
