<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORE-DIGITS-KAN &LR;      05-14 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORE-DIGITS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 KC area soon will have more digits to dial  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Denverite Jenni Pieratt has words of solace
for the communication junkies who are going to panic when they hear
the cold hard truth.
</P>
<P>
   True, Kansas City is going to 10-digit local dialing. But it's
``no big deal,'' Pieratt says.
</P>
<P>
   The area is running out of seven-digit telephone numbers for all
of those computer lines, fax machines, cell phones and home phones
that people are buying. On Dec. 4, callers are going to have to use
area codes when making local calls across the state line.
</P>
<P>
   Calling from Overland Park to Lee's Summit, for example, will
require dialing 816 and then the number. A call from Kansas City,
Mo., to Kansas City, Kan., will start with a 913. These calls still
will be local, won't require a 1 before the area code and won't be
charged as long distance. They simply will require the 10 digits of
the area code and the number.
</P>
<P>
   Denver went to a similar system in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty basic,'' said Pieratt, spokeswoman for Janus,
the Denver-based mutual fund company that is owned by Kansas City
Southern Industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do have to go through the issue of programming your speed
dials. When you have a cell phone and a work phone and a home
phone, that can take a bit of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The most nettlesome thing Pieratt faced was figuring out that
she needed to reprogram her home computer so she could connect to
her Internet provider.
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, the issues are more complex. In addition to
reprogramming phone equipment, they will have to change such things
as van signs, company phone lists and client lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 25,000 accounts in the metro area,'' said Kent Rowland,
service manager for ADT Security Services, which has its monitoring
offices in Missouri. ``It could mean we will have to go out to all
of our customers in Kansas and reprogram their systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Although regulators know it will be inconvenient, they said
there was no other choice. And no one local telephone company is
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no hidden agenda behind this. It is a mathematical
thing,'' said Rosemary Foreman, spokeswoman for the Kansas
Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Kansas City area has had the convenience of local
calling, even though there are separate long-distance exchanges for
each side of the state line, said Bill Adair of Southwestern Bell,
who serves the area as the local codes administrator. He is the
industry go-between who handles requests for new telephone numbers
on behalf of all area telecommunication providers.
</P>
<P>
   The area's local calling system meant that the same prefix and
phone number couldn't be used in Kansas and Missouri, even though
residents lived in different area codes. As a result, a big pool of
potential numbers couldn't be used in one state or the other. But
by December, he said, the area will run out of seven-digit numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became clear this past summer that we had gone as far as we
could,'' Adair said. ``Yet we had a big pool of numbers just
sitting there doing nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Adair and others said the two factors exhausting numbers are
technology and competition. People use much more telephone
technology and many more telephone companies are selling those
services. Those companies have to have a supply of telephone
numbers to be able to sell their services.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decade ago the only people with cell phones were doctors and
lawyers,'' Adair said. ``I have two cell phones and a pager. I have
six telephone numbers personally, counting fax, phone and computer.
When you go to the mall, just about every kid has a pager on their
belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kelly, spokesman for the Missouri Public Service
Commission, which regulates telephone service in the state, said
that a few years ago only Southwestern Bell and Sprint Corp.'s
United Telephone Co. provided local telephone service in the Kansas
City area. Now that local phone competition is permissible, 39
telephone companies have been approved in the state since 1997.
Most of those have made Kansas City a target and need phone
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   With available numbers slipping away, a study group of
telecommunications companies and regulators in both states devised
the 10-digit plan. It mimics plans in place in Houston, Dallas,
Atlanta, St. Louis, Denver and the entire state of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   To make the process easier, the group decided to leave
seven-digit dialing in place within each area code. In other words,
nothing changes for a local call within an area code, although the
call will go through if the caller dials the area code first.
</P>
<P>
   It was also decided to have a lengthy ``permissive period,''
starting June 5, when customers can use 10-digit dialing but don't
have to. That way they can prepare for the change in December.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Bosshardt, administrator of external communications at
Sprint, said the company knew 10-digit calling was coming and has
been preparing employees, fielding questions and urging them to
begin using 10 digits this summer to become comfortable with the
extra numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting question Bosshardt received was whether a
wireless phone with an 816 exchange but being used while traveling
in the 913 area would have to use 10 digits while calling a 913
number. The answer is yes. It is the exchange, not the location,
that makes that determination.
</P>
<P>
   Adair said he knows people will find it an inconvenience at
first, but he expects them to adjust quickly. Eventually technology
might make 10-digit dialing unnecessary, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say people will like it,'' he said. ``I would rather
dial seven numbers. I would rather do two or even one. But this is
where a lot of areas are moving to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
